quran[6236]{c,v,t}:
  1,1,"In the name of Allah, the All-Merciful, the Bestower of mercy."
  1,2,"All praise be to Allah, Lord of all realms,"
  1,3,"the All-Merciful, the Bestower of mercy,"
  1,4,"<span class="h">Master<sup foot_note="364880">1</sup></span> of the Day of Recompense.",footnotes:345343:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf in one of his narrations read it as: “King of the Day of Recompense.”</span>
  1,5,"It is You we worship, and it is You we call for help."
  1,6,"Guide us to the straight path:"
  1,7,"the path of those You have blessed, not those who have incurred <small>(Your)</small> wrath, nor those who have gone astray."
  2,1,"Alif Lām Mīm."
  2,2,"That is the Scripture; there is no doubt about it—a guidance for the mindful <small>(of God)</small>,<sup foot_note="364881">1</sup>",footnotes:345344:This portion can be read differently in Arabic by pausing after 'doubt', and in this case it means: 'That is the Scripture, no doubt. In it there is guidance for the mindful (of God).’
  2,3,"who believe in the <small>(existence of)</small> hidden realms and establish the prayers and spend out of what We have provided them,"
  2,4,"and those who believe in what has been sent down to you<sup>sg</sup> and what has been sent down before you, and regarding the Hereafter they are certain."
  2,5,"Those are upon guidance from their Lord, and those are the successful."
  2,6,"Indeed, it is the same for those who have denied: whether you<sup>sg</sup> have warned them or have not warned them, they do not believe."
  2,7,"Allah has set a seal on their hearts and on their hearing, and over their sight<small>(s)</small><sup foot_note="364882">1</sup> is a veil; for for them is a great punishment.",footnotes:345345:Mentioned in plural form in Arabic, denoted by (s) in English for grammatical reasons.
  2,8,"And of mankind are those who say, “We have attained faith in Allah and in the Last Day,” but they are not believers."
  2,9,"They try to deceive Allah and those who have attained faith, yet they <span class="h">deceive<sup foot_note="364883">1</sup></span> none but themselves, but they are unaware.",footnotes:345346:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “…yet they try to deceive none but…”</span>
  2,10,"In their hearts is sickness, so Allah increased their sickness, and for them is a painful punishment on account of how they used to <span class="h">lie<sup foot_note="364884">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:345347:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…they used to disbelieve.”</span>
  2,11,"And when it is said to them, “Do not spread corruption in the land,” they say, “Indeed, we are only reformers.”"
  2,12,"Undoubtedly, it is they who are indeed the corrupters, but they are unaware."
  2,13,"And when it is said to them, “Believe as the people have believed,” they say, “Shall we believe as the fools have believed?” Undoubtedly, it is they who are indeed the fools, but they do not know."
  2,14,"And when they encounter those who have attained faith, they say, “We have attained faith.” But when they are alone with their Satans, they say, “We are indeed with you; we are only ridiculing.”"
  2,15,"Allah ridicules them and gives them free rein to exceed all limits, wandering blindly."
  2,16,"Those are the ones who have purchased utter misguidance in exchange for guidance, so in no way has their bargain made any profit, and in no way have they been rightly guided."
  2,17,"Their likeness is that of a person who kindled a fire, but when it illuminated all around him, Allah took away their<sup foot_note="364885">1</sup> light and left them in darkness<small>(es)</small><sup foot_note="364886">2</sup>, unable to see.",footnotes:345348:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.|345349:Mentioned in plural form in Arabic, denoted by (es) in English for grammatical reasons.
  2,18,"Deaf, mute, blind, so they are not returning."
  2,19,"Or like a cloudburst from the sky in which are darkness<small>(es)</small> and thunder and lightning. They put their fingers into their ears against the thunderbolts, in fear of death. Yet Allah is All-Encompassing of the deniers."
  2,20,"The lightning almost snatches their sight<small>(s)</small> away; whenever it illuminates for them, they walk in it. But when it darkens over them, they stand <small>(still)</small>. And had Allah willed, He could have done away with their hearing and their sight<small>(s)</small>. Indeed, Allah is All-Powerful over everything."
  2,21,"O mankind, worship your Lord Who created you and those before you, that you may become mindful <small>(of Him)</small>:"
  2,22,"the One Who has made the land a habitat for you and the sky a structure, and has sent water down from the sky and has brought out products thereby as provision for you. So do not assign rivals to Allah while you know."
  2,23,"And if you<sup>pl</sup> are in doubt about what We have bestowed upon Our servant from on high, then bring a single surah<sup foot_note="364887">1</sup> of its like, and call your witnesses apart from Allah if you are truthful.",footnotes:345350:Each portion of the Qur'an is called a ‘surah’, which is sometimes translated as ‘chapter’.
  2,24,"But if you<sup>pl</sup> do not—and you will not—then be mindful of the Fire<sup foot_note="364888">1</sup> whose fuel is people and stones; it has been prepared for the deniers.",footnotes:345351:Literally 'protect yourselves against the Fire'.
  2,25,"And give<sup>sg</sup> glad tidings to those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds: that for them are Gardens beneath which rivers flow. Whenever they are provided with any produce therefrom as provision, they say, “This is what we were provided with before,” and they are brought <small>(them)</small> in <small>(perfect)</small> resemblance. And for them are cleansed spouses therein, and therein they abide."
  2,26,"Indeed, Allah does not shy away from setting forth any parable, even of a gnat or anything above it. So as for those who have attained faith—they know that it is the truth from their Lord. But as for those who have denied—they say, “What did Allah want <small>(to say)</small> by this parable?” He misguides many thereby and He guides many thereby, but He does not misguide thereby except the defiantly disobedient"
  2,27,"who violate Allah’s covenant after it has been pledged and sever what Allah has commanded to be joined and spread corruption in the earth—those are the losers."
  2,28,"How can you<sup>pl</sup> deny Allah when you were lifeless and He gave you life, then He puts you to death, then He brings you to life, then to Him you are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="364889">1</sup></span>?",footnotes:345352:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…to Him you return?”</span>
  2,29,"It is He Who created for you<sup>pl</sup> what is on earth, all together, then turned to the heaven and formed them<sup foot_note="364890">1</sup> into seven heavens. And He is All-Knowing of everything.",footnotes:345353:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  2,30,"And recall when your<sup>sg</sup> Lord said to the angels, “I am appointing a viceroy in the earth.” They said, “Will You appoint in it someone who causes corruption in it and sheds blood, while we highly exalt You with praise and proclaim Your holiness?” He said, “Indeed, I know what you do not know.”"
  2,31,"And He taught Adam the names, all of them; then He presented them to the angels and said, “Inform Me of the names of these, if you are truthful.”"
  2,32,"They said, “Highly Exalted be You! We have no knowledge except what You have taught us. Indeed, it is You Who are the All-Knowing, the All-Wise.”"
  2,33,"He said, “O Adam, inform them of their names.” So when he informed them of their names, He said, “Did I not tell you<sup>pl</sup> that I know <small>(all about)</small> the hidden realm of the heavens and the earth, and that I know what you disclose and what you have been concealing?”"
  2,34,"And recall when We said to the angels, “Prostrate yourselves to Adam", so they prostrated themselves—but not Iblis<sup foot_note="364891">1</sup> . He refused and acted arrogantly and became of the deniers.",footnotes:345354:Iblis is another name of Satan or <i>Shaytan</i>.
  2,35,"Thereafter, We said, “O Adam, settle in the Garden, you and your spouse, and eat<sup>dl</sup> from it freely as you both will; but do not approach<sup>dl</sup> this tree, lest you<sup>dl</sup> become of the unjust.”"
  2,36,"Yet Satan made them <span class="h">slip<sup foot_note="364892">1</sup></span> therefrom, so he brought them out of what they were in. Then We said, “Descend<sup>pl</sup>, as enemies to one another, for in the earth you<sup>pl</sup> have a place of settlement and enjoyment for a while.”",footnotes:345355:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “Yet Satan removed them therefrom,”</span>
  2,37,"Thereupon Adam received <span class="h">words<sup foot_note="364893">1</sup></span> from his Lord. Thus, He granted him repentance and accepted it from him. Indeed, it is He Who is the Superb Granter and Accepter of repentance, the Bestower of mercy.",footnotes:345356:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “Thereupon Adam was received by words from His Lord…”</span>
  2,38,"We said, “Descend from it, all together. Then whenever any guidance comes to you from Me, then whoever follows My guidance—then no <span class="h">fear<sup foot_note="364894">1</sup></span> shall be upon them<sup foot_note="364895">2</sup> nor shall they grieve.",footnotes:345357:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…then no fear shall ever be upon them nor shall they grieve.”</span>|345358:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  2,39,"But those who have denied and disbelieved in Our signs—those are the fellows of the Fire; therein they abide.”"
  2,40,"O Children of Israel, "Remember My blessing which I blessed you with and fulfill your <small>(part of the)</small> covenant so that I fulfill My <small>(part of the)</small> covenant, and fear Me alone."
  2,41,"And believe<sup>pl</sup> in what I have sent down, confirming what is with you<sup>pl</sup>. And do not be the first denier<sup foot_note="364896">1</sup> of it, and do not purchase, in exchange for My revelations, a small price, and be mindful of Me alone.",footnotes:345359:A grammatical shift from plural to singular.
  2,42,"And do not mix truth with falsehood, and do not conceal the truth while you<sup>pl</sup> know."
  2,43,"And establish the prayer, and bring<sup foot_note="364897">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="364898">2</sup>, and bow down with the ones bowing down.",footnotes:345360:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|345361:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  2,44,"Do you<sup>pl</sup> command mankind to virtue and forget yourselves, even though you read the Scripture? Do you not reason?"
  2,45,"And seek<sup>pl</sup> help through patience and prayer, and it is indeed a great burden except for the reverent"
  2,46,"who are certain that they shall meet their Lord and that to Him they will return."
  2,47,"O Children of Israel, remember My blessing with which I blessed you, and that I favored you over all communities."
  2,48,"And be mindful of a day<sup foot_note="364899">1</sup> when no self avails another in anything, nor is any intercession accepted on its behalf, nor is any ransom taken from it, nor are they<sup foot_note="364900">2</sup> supported.",footnotes:345362:Literally 'protect yourselves against a day'.|345363:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  2,49,"And recall how We delivered you<sup>pl</sup> from Pharaoh's folk— <small>(those)</small> inflicting<sup foot_note="364901">1</sup> upon you an evil punishment, slaying your sons and keeping your women alive <small>(in bondage)</small>. For therein is a great test from your Lord.",footnotes:345364:A grammatical shift describing past events in present tense, serving to create a vivid portrait of events.
  2,50,"And recall how We parted the sea for you<sup>pl</sup> and <small>(thus)</small> We saved you, and We drowned Pharaoh's folk while you were beholding."
  2,51,"And recall when We appointed <span class="h">with<sup foot_note="364902">1</sup></span> Moses forty nights. Then you<sup>pl</sup> took the calf <small>(for worship)</small> after him, while you were unjust.",footnotes:345365:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…appointed for Moses…”</span>
  2,52,"Then We pardoned you after that, that you may give thanks."
  2,53,"And recall when We gave Moses the Scripture and the Criterion, that you<sup>pl</sup> may be guided."
  2,54,"And recall when Moses said to his people, “O my people, you have done injustice to yourselves by taking the calf <small>(for worship)</small>. So repent to your Maker and kill yourselves<sup foot_note="364903">1</sup> . That would be better for you with your Maker.” So He granted you repentance and accepted it from you; indeed it is He who is the Superb Granter and Accepter of repentance, the Bestower of mercy.",footnotes:345366:By mortifying it.
  2,55,"And recall when you<sup>pl</sup> said, “O Moses, we will not believe in you unless we see Allah plainly.” Thereupon the thunderbolt struck you while you were beholding."
  2,56,"Then We revived you<sup>pl</sup> after your death, that you may give thanks."
  2,57,"And We shaded you<sup>pl</sup> with mists, and We sent down manna and quails upon you: “Eat of the good things We have provided for you.” And in no way did they do injustice to Us, but they used to do injustice to themselves."
  2,58,"And recall when We said, “Enter this town and eat from it freely wherever you<sup>pl</sup> will, but enter the gate bowing down and say, 'disburden <small>(us)</small>'. We <small>(will)</small> forgive you your <span class="h">offenses<sup foot_note="364904">1</sup></span>, and We will give more to those who excel in doing good.”",footnotes:345367:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “Your offenses will be forgiven for you,”</span>
  2,59,"Then the ones who did injustice exchanged <small>(it for a )</small> a saying other than that which had been said to them, so We sent down upon the ones who did injustice a torment from heaven on account of how they used to defiantly disobey."
  2,60,"And recall how Moses prayed for water for his people, so We said, “Strike the rock with your<sup>sg</sup> staff.” Thereupon twelve springs gushed out from it; each group of people certainly knew its drinking-place. “Eat<sup>pl</sup> and drink from Allah’s provision, and do not go wickedly about the land, corrupting <small>(it)</small>.”"
  2,61,"And recall when you<sup>pl</sup> said, “O Moses, we shall not endure one kind of food, so call upon your Lord to bring out for us of what the earth germinates: of its herbs and its cucumbers and its garlic and its lentils and its onions.” He said, “Would you<sup>pl</sup> exchange what is better for what is less? Go down to Egypt where you will have what you asked for.” And they<sup foot_note="364905">1</sup> were struck with humiliation and destituteness, and they incurred wrath from Allah. That was because they used to deny Allah’s signs<sup foot_note="364906">2</sup> and unjustifiably kill the prophets. That was because they disobeyed and used to transgress.",footnotes:345368:A grammatical shift from 2<sup><small>nd</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.|345369:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  2,62,"Indeed, those who have attained faith and those who have Judaized and the Christians and the Sabians—whoever has attained faith in Allah and the Last Day and has acted righteously—then their<sup foot_note="364907">1</sup> reward is with their Lord, and no <span class="h">fear<sup foot_note="364908">2</sup></span> shall be upon them nor shall they grieve.",footnotes:345370:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.|345371:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…and no fear shall ever be upon them nor shall they grieve.”</span>
  2,63,"And recall when We took a pledge from you<sup>pl</sup> and raised Mount Tûr above you: “Take what We have given you firmly and remember what is in it, that you may become mindful <small>(of God)</small>.”"
  2,64,"But after that you<sup>pl</sup> turned away. So were it not for Allah’s grace and mercy towards you, you would have been of the losers."
  2,65,"And you surely knew those of you who transgressed the Sabbath, so We said to them, “Be despicable apes!”"
  2,66,"Thus We made it a deterrent for their generation and for subsequent generations, and a lesson for the mindful<sup>pl</sup> <small>(of God)</small>."
  2,67,"And recall when Moses said to his people, “Indeed, Allah commands you to slaughter a cow.” They said, “Do you make a mockery of us?” He said, “I seek refuge with Allah from being one of the ignorant.”"
  2,68,"They said, “Call upon your Lord to make evident to us what (sort of cow) it is.” He said, “He says it is a cow neither too old nor too young—of median age between that, so do what you are commanded.”"
  2,69,"They said, “Call upon your Lord to make evident to us what its color is.” He said, “Indeed, He says that it is surely a yellow cow, bright in color, pleasing to the beholders.”"
  2,70,"They said, “Call upon your Lord to make evident to us what <small>(sort of)</small> cow it is; surely all cows look alike to us and—if Allah wills— we shall most surely be guided.”"
  2,71,"He said, “He says it is a cow neither yoked to plow the earth nor to irrigate the field, sound without blemish.” They said, “Now you have come with the truth.” So they slaughtered it, though they almost did not."
  2,72,"And recall when you<sup>pl</sup> killed a self then shifted responsibility for it onto each other, but Allah was to bring out <small>(to the open)</small> what you were concealing."
  2,73,"So We said, “Strike him with part of it.” Thus Allah brings the dead to life, and He shows you<sup>pl</sup> His signs, that you may reason."
  2,74,"Then after that your hearts hardened, so that they were as rocks or even harder. For surely from some rocks rivers gush out, and surely some others splinter so that water comes out from them, and surely some others sink in awe of Allah. And Allah is never oblivious of what <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="364909">1</sup></span> do.",footnotes:345372:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “…of what they do.”</span>
  2,75,"Do you<sup>pl</sup> ardently hope that they will believe you, when a group of them used to hear the Speech of Allah and then distort it after they had reasoned, knowingly?"
  2,76,"And when they encounter those who have attained faith, they say, “We have attained faith.” But when they come together privately, they say, “Do you<sup>pl</sup> inform them of what Allah has disclosed to you so that they might debate you concerning it before your Lord?” Do you not reason?"
  2,77,"Do they not know that Allah knows whatever they keep secret and whatever they make public?"
  2,78,"And among them<sup foot_note="364910">1</sup> are illiterates who do not know the Scripture, other than fancies, and they only speculate.",footnotes:345373:The Jews.
  2,79,"So woe to those who scribe the Scripture with their own hands and then say, “This is from Allah,” that they may purchase, in exchange for it, a small price. Woe to them on account of what their hands have written, and woe to them on account of what they earn<sup foot_note="364911">1</sup> .",footnotes:345374:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense.
  2,80,"And they said, “The Fire will not touch us except for a few days.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Have you<sup>pl</sup> taken a covenant from Allah—so Allah will never break His covenant—or are you saying about Allah what you do not know?”"
  2,81,"Yes indeed, whoever has earned an evil deed and whose offense <span class="h">has<sup foot_note="364912">1</sup></span> surrounded him—then those are the fellows of the Fire; therein they abide.",footnotes:345375:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…whose offenses have surrounded…”</span>
  2,82,"But those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—those are the fellows of the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small>; therein they abide."
  2,83,"And recall when We took a pledge from the Children of Israel: <span class="h">“You<sup foot_note="364913">1</sup></span> shall worship none but Allah, and excel in showing kindness to the parents and the relative and orphans and the destitute<sup>pl</sup>, and say kind words to mankind and establish the prayers and bring<sup foot_note="364914">2</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="364915">3</sup> .” Then you<sup foot_note="364916">4</sup> turned away in disregard, except for a few of you.",footnotes:345376:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Hamza and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “They shall worship…”</span>|345377:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|345378:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.|345379:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 2<sup><small>nd</small></sup> person.
  2,84,"And recall when We took a pledge from you<sup>pl</sup>: “You shall not shed your blood nor evict yourselves from your homes.” Then you consented while you were witnessing."
  2,85,"Then here you are, killing yourselves and evicting a group of your own from their homes—backing each other against them in sin and hostility. And if they come to you as captives, you do <span class="h">ransom<sup foot_note="364917">1</sup></span> them, while their eviction is forbidden to you. Is it that you believe in part of the Scripture and deny part? So what is the repayment for those of you who do that but disgrace in the Earlier Life, and <small>(that)</small> on the Day of Resurrection they are turned back to the most severe punishment? For Allah is never oblivious of what <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="364918">2</sup></span> do.",footnotes:345380:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Asem, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…you ransom them,”</span>|345381:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Shu’bah, Ya’qub and Khalaf in his preferred narration read it as: “…what they do.”</span>
  2,86,"Those are the ones who purchased the Earlier Life in exchange for the Hereafter, so the punishment is not lightened for them nor are they to be supported."
  2,87,"And most surely, We brought Moses the Scripture and sent a succession of messengers after him. And We brought Jesus, son of Mary, the evident proofs, and We aided him with the Holy Spirit. Is it that every time a messenger came to you with anything your <small>(inner)</small> selves do not desire, you acted arrogantly, so one group you disbelieved, and another group you kill<sup foot_note="364919">1</sup> ?",footnotes:345382:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense; using present tense for an old practice emphasizes that it was a tradition frequently practiced.
  2,88,"And they said, “Our hearts are enfolded.” Rather, Allah has cursed them for their denial, so little do they believe."
  2,89,"For when a scripture came to them from Allah, confirming what they had—although previously they were seeking a conquest against those who denied—but when there came to them what they recognized, they denied it. So may Allah’s curse be upon the deniers."
  2,90,"Miserable is what they have purchased in exchange for their <small>(very)</small> selves—that they deny what Allah has bestowed from on <span class="h">high<sup foot_note="364920">1</sup></span>, out of resentment that Allah would send down His grace upon whomever He wills of His servants. Thus they incurred wrath upon wrath, for for the deniers is a demeaning punishment.",footnotes:345383:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…what Allah has sent down,”</span>
  2,91,"And when it is said to them, “Believe in what Allah has sent down,” they say, “We believe in what was sent down to us,” and they deny anything beyond that, although it is the truth which confirms what they have. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Why <small>(then)</small> do you kill<sup foot_note="364921">1</sup> Allah’s prophets—earlier—if you are believers?”",footnotes:345384:Using present tense for an old practice emphasizes that it was a tradition frequently practiced.
  2,92,"And very truly Moses came to you<sup>pl</sup> with the evident proofs, then you took the calf <small>(for worship)</small> after him while you were unjust."
  2,93,"And recall when We took a pledge from you<sup>pl</sup> and raised Mount Tûr above you: “Take what We have given you firmly and hear.” They said, “We have heard and disobeyed.” And, on account of their denial, in their hearts they were soaked in <small>(the worship of)</small> the calf. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “How miserable is that which your<sup>pl</sup> faith commands you to do, if you are believers.”"
  2,94,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “If the Home of the Hereafter with Allah is for you<sup>pl</sup> alone apart from all mankind, then wish for death if you are truthful.”"
  2,95,"But they will never wish for it, on account of what their hands have put forth. For Allah is All-Knowing of the unjust."
  2,96,"And you<sup>sg</sup> will most surely find them the most adhering of mankind to life, and more so than those who associated <small>(others with God)</small>. Every one of them would love to have his life extended a thousand years, but being granted a long life does not nudge him from the punishment, for Allah is All-Seeing of what <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="364922">1</sup></span> do.",footnotes:345385:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…of what you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> do.”</span>
  2,97,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Whoever is an enemy to Gabriel…<sup foot_note="364923">1</sup> —for indeed, it is he who has bestowed it upon your<sup>sg</sup> heart from on high by Allah’s leave, confirming what preceded it, and guidance and glad tidings for the believers.”",footnotes:345386:This sentence is left open-ended; according to some exegetes its predicate is “then woe to him.”
  2,98,"Whoever is an enemy to Allah and His angels and His messengers and Gabriel and Michael—then surely Allah is an enemy to the deniers."
  2,99,"And We have indeed sent down to you<sup>sg</sup> evident signs, and none denies them except the defiantly disobedient."
  2,100,"Is it not that whenever they make a covenant, a group of them throws it away? In fact, most of them do not believe."
  2,101,"For when a messenger from Allah came to them confirming what they had, a group of those who were given the Scripture threw the Scripture of Allah behind their backs as if they did not know,"
  2,102,"and they followed what the devils read<sup foot_note="364924">1</sup> during the reign of Solomon. But never did Solomon deny<sup foot_note="364925">2</sup> ; rather it was the Satans who denied, teaching people sorcery and what was sent down in Babylon to the two angels Harut and Marut. And they do not teach anybody until they say, “We are but a means of trial, so do not deny <small>(faith)</small>.” Even so, they learn from them the means to cause separation between a man and his spouse—but never could they harm anyone except by Allah's leave. And they learn what would harm them and not benefit them. Yet they did know that whoever purchased it<sup foot_note="364926">3</sup> would have no share in the Hereafter. So indeed, how miserable is what they sold themselves for, if they only knew!",footnotes:345387:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense; using present tense for an old practice emphasizes that it was a tradition frequently practiced.|345388:Blaspheme.|345389:Sorcery.
  2,103,"And had they attained faith and been mindful <small>(of God)</small>, then surely a requital from Allah would have been better, if they only knew."
  2,104,"O you who have attained faith, do not say ‘Ra'ina,’<sup foot_note="364927">1</sup> but say, ‘Unthurna,’<sup foot_note="364928">2</sup> and listen, for for the deniers is a painful punishment.",footnotes:345390:This word means ‘Pay heed to us’ but sounds similar to a Hebrew word that means ‘the most evil of us’.|345391:Grant us consideration.
  2,105,"Neither the deniers from among the People of the Scripture nor the polytheists would love that any good be sent down upon <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="364929">1</sup></span> from yourpl Lord. Yet Allah specifies for His mercy whomever He wills, for Allah is the Possessor of great grace.",footnotes:345392:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…be bestowed upon you from on high by your<sup><small>pl</small></sup> Lord.”</span>
  2,106,"Never do We <span class="h">abrogate<sup foot_note="364930">1</sup></span> any sign<sup foot_note="364931">2</sup> nor cause it to be <span class="h">forgotten<sup foot_note="364932">3</sup></span> unless We bring one better than it or similar to it. Have yousg not come to know that Allah is All-Powerful over everything?",footnotes:345393:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “Never do we command the abrogation of any...”</span>|345394:The Arabic word used is<i> ayah</i>. <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.|345395:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “…nor postpone it unless We…”</span>
  2,107,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not come to know that to Allah belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth? For apart from Allah you<sup>pl</sup> have neither ally nor supporter."
  2,108,"Or do you<sup>pl</sup> want to question your Messenger as Moses was questioned earlier? For whoever substitutes denial for faith, then he has certainly strayed from the right way."
  2,109,"Many of the People of the Scripture would love to turn you<sup>pl</sup> back into deniers after you have attained faith, out of envy in their <small>(inner)</small> selves, after the truth has become evident to them. So pardon and overlook until Allah brings about His command. Indeed, Allah is All-Powerful over everything."
  2,110,"And establish the prayer and bring<sup foot_note="364933">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="364934">2</sup>, for whatever good you forward for yourselves, you will find it with Allah. Indeed, Allah is All-Seeing of what you do.",footnotes:345396:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|345397:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  2,111,"And they said, “None will enter the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> unless he has been a Jew or a Christian.” These are their fancies. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Produce your proof, if you are truthful.”"
  2,112,"Yes indeed, whoever submits his face <small>(in worship)</small> to Allah while excelling in doing good, then he has his reward with his Lord, and no <span class="h">fear<sup foot_note="364935">1</sup></span> shall be upon them<sup foot_note="364936">2</sup> nor shall they grieve.",footnotes:345398:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…, and no fear shall ever be upon them nor shall they grieve.”</span>|345399:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  2,113,"Nevertheless, the Jews said, “Christians have no ground whatsoever to stand on,” while the Christians said, “Jews have no ground whatsoever to stand on.” Yet they read the Scripture. Similarly, the ones who do not know said the like of their saying. Thus Allah judges between them on the Day of Resurrection regarding whatever they differed over."
  2,114,"And who is more unjust than one who prevented <small>(praying in)</small> the mosques of Allah so that His Name be not mentioned in them, and pursued their ruin? Those—never was it for them to enter them except in fear. For them is disgrace in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small>, and for them in the Hereafter is a great punishment."
  2,115,"And to Allah belong the East and the West, so wherever you<sup>pl</sup> turn, then that is where Allah’s Countenance is. Indeed, Allah is All-Embracing, All-Knowing."
  2,116,"And <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="364937">1</sup></span> said, “Allah has taken <small>(for Himself)</small> offspring.” Highly Exalted is He. Rather, to Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth; all are devout towards Him—",footnotes:345400:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “They said,”</span>
  2,117,"the Innovator of the heavens and the earth, and whenever He decrees a matter, He only says to it, “Be,” and so it <span class="h">is<sup foot_note="364938">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:345401:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “He only says to it, ‘Be,’ so it is.”</span>
  2,118,"And those who do not know said, “If only Allah would speak to us, or a sign would come to us.” Thus said those who were before them—just what they said. Their hearts are alike. We have certainly made the signs evident for people who are certain."
  2,119,"We have indeed sent you with the truth as a herald of glad tidings and as a warner, for you will not be <span class="h">asked<sup foot_note="364939">1</sup></span> about the fellows of purgatory.",footnotes:345402:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Ya’qub read it as: “…as a warner, so do not ask about the fellows of purgatory.”</span>
  2,120,"And never will the Jews or the Christians be pleased with you<sup>sg</sup> until you follow their creed. Say, “Surely, Allah’s guidance is the Guidance.” And should you<sup>sg</sup> follow their whims after the knowledge that has come to you, you would have against Allah neither ally nor supporter."
  2,121,"Those to whom We have brought the Scripture read it as it ought to be read; those ones believe in it. But whoever denies it—then those<sup foot_note="364940">1</sup> are the losers.",footnotes:345403:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  2,122,"O Children of Israel, remember My blessing with which I have blessed you and that I have favored you over all communities."
  2,123,"And be<sup>pl</sup> mindful of a day<sup foot_note="364941">1</sup> when no self avails any other self in anything, nor is any ransom accepted from it, nor does any intercession benefit it, nor are they<sup foot_note="364942">2</sup> supported.",footnotes:345404:Literally 'protect yourselves against a day'.|345405:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  2,124,"And recall when <span class="h">Abraham<sup foot_note="364943">1</sup></span> was tried by his Lord with certain words and he fulfilled them. He said, “I am appointing you as a leader for mankind.” He said, “And of my offspring?” He said, “My covenant does not include the unjust<sup>pl</sup>.”",footnotes:345406:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as <i>Ibrahim</i>, Hisham and Ibn Zekwan in one of his narrations read it as: “Abraham”.</span>
  2,125,"And recall when We made the House a resort for mankind, and a sanctuary. <span class="h">And<sup foot_note="364944">1</sup></span> take<sup>pl</sup> from <span class="h">Abraham's<sup foot_note="364945">2</sup></span> standing place a place of prayer. And We covenanted with Abraham and Ishmael, “Cleanse My House for circumambulators and consecrators and those bowing down and prostrating themselves.”",footnotes:345407:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Ibn Amer read it as: “And they took from Abraham's…”</span>|345408:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as <i>Ibrahim</i>, Hisham and Ibn Zekwan in one of his narrations read it as: “Abraham”.</span>
  2,126,"And recall when Abraham said, "Lord! Make this a secure land and provide its people with products—whoever of them has attained faith in Allah and the Last Day.” He said, “And whoever denies—I will give him a little enjoyment, then compel him to the punishment of the Fire, and what a miserable destiny!”"
  2,127,"And recall <span class="h">Abraham<sup foot_note="364946">1</sup></span> raising the foundations of the House together with Ishmael, “Our Lord, accept <small>(it)</small> from us; indeed, it is You, You <small>(alone),</small> who are the All-Hearing, the All-Knowing.",footnotes:345409:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as <i>Ibrahim</i>, Hisham and Ibn Zekwan in one of his narrations read it as: “Abraham”.</span>
  2,128,"Our Lord, and make us both Muslim<sup foot_note="364947">1</sup> to You, and from our offspring a Muslim community <small>(submitting)</small> to You. And show us our rites, and grant us repentance and accept it from us; indeed, it is You, You <small>(alone)</small> who are the Superb Granter and Accepter of repentance, the Bestower of mercy.",footnotes:345410:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  2,129,"Our Lord, and send forth among them a messenger from themselves to read to them Your signs<sup foot_note="364948">1</sup> and teach them the Scripture and the wisdom and purify them. Indeed, it is you, You <small>(alone)</small>, who are the Almighty, the All-Wise.”",footnotes:345411:The Arabic word used is a<i>yat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  2,130,"And who would forsake the creed of <span class="h">Abraham<sup foot_note="364949">1</sup></span> except he who fools himself? And We have indeed chosen him in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small>, and in the Hereafter he is most surely one of the righteous.",footnotes:345412:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as <i>Ibrahim</i>, Hisham and Ibn Zekwan in one of his narrations read it as: “Abraham”.</span>
  2,131,"Recall when his Lord said to him, “Submit!” He said, “I have submitted to the Lord of all realms.”"
  2,132,"And with this <span class="h">Abraham<sup foot_note="364950">1</sup></span> frequently <span class="h">enjoined<sup foot_note="364951">2</sup></span> his children, and <small>(so did)</small> Jacob, “O my children, Allah has indeed chosen the religion for you, so do not die except as Muslims<sup foot_note="364952">3</sup> .”",footnotes:345413:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as <i>Ibrahim</i>, Hisham and Ibn Zekwan in one of his narrations read it as: “Abraham”.</span>|345414:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “And with this Abraham enjoined…”</span>|345415:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  2,133,"Or were you witnesses when death approached Jacob, and he said to his children, “What will you worship after me?” They said, “We will worship your God and the God of your fathers, <span class="h">Abraham<sup foot_note="364953">1</sup></span>, Ishmael and Isaac: One God, and to Him we are Muslims<sup foot_note="364954">2</sup> .”",footnotes:345416:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as <i>Ibrahim</i>, Hisham and Ibn Zekwan in one of his narrations read it as: “Abraham”.</span>|345417:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  2,134,"That is a nation that has passed. For them is what they have earned, and for you is what you<sup>pl</sup> have earned, and you will not be questioned about what they used to do."
  2,135,"And they said, “Be Jews or Christians and you will be guided.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Rather, the creed of Abraham who turned away from all that is false, for never was he of the polytheists.”"
  2,136,"Say<sup>pl</sup>, “We have attained faith in Allah and in what was sent down to us, and in what was sent down to <span class="h">Abraham<sup foot_note="364955">1</sup></span> and Ishmael and Isaac and Jacob and the Grandsons, and in what was brought to Moses and Jesus, and in what was brought to the prophets by their Lord. We make no distinction between any of them, for to Him we are Muslims<sup foot_note="364956">2</sup> .”",footnotes:345418:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as <i>Ibrahim</i>, Hisham and Ibn Zekwan in one of his narrations read it as: “Abraham”.</span>|345419:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  2,137,"So if they believe in the same as you<sup>pl</sup> have believed in, then they have been guided. But if they turn away, then they are in discord. And Allah will protect you against them, for He is the All-Hearing, the All-Knowing."
  2,138,"<small>(It is) </small>Allah’s hue. And who gives a better hue than Allah? “And of Him we are worshipers.”"
  2,139,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Do you debate with us about Allah, when He is our Lord and your Lord, and when for us are our deeds and for you are your deeds, and to Him we are sincere?”"
  2,140,"Or do <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="364957">1</sup></span> say<sup>pl</sup> that <span class="h">Abraham<sup foot_note="364958">2</sup></span> and Ishmael and Isaac and Jacob and the Grandsons<sup foot_note="364959">3</sup> were Jews or Christians? Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Do you know better or Allah?” And who is more unjust than one who conceals a testimony he has from Allah? For Allah is not oblivious of what you<sup>pl</sup> do.",footnotes:345420:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Abu Ja’far, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Shu’ba and Rouh read it as: “Or do they say…”</span>|345421:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as <i>Ibrahim</i>, Hisham and Ibn Zekwan in one of his narrations read it as: “Abraham”.</span>|345422:The different prophets of the Israelites.
  2,141,"That is a community that has passed away. For them is what they have earned and for you<sup>pl</sup> is what you have earned, for you will not be questioned about what they used to do."
  2,142,"The fools among mankind will say, “What has turned them away from the direction of prayer that they used to follow?” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “To Allah belong the East and the West. He guides whom He wills to a straight path.”"
  2,143,"And thus have We made you a middle community, that you may be witnesses over humanity and that the Messenger may be a witness over you. Thus We only assigned the direction of prayer, which you formerly followed, that We may distinguish the one who follows the Messenger from the one who turns on his heels. And it was indeed difficult, except for those whom Allah has guided. But never would Allah let your faith<sup foot_note="364960">1</sup> go to waste; indeed, towards mankind, Allah has always been truly Compassionate, Bestowing of mercy.",footnotes:345423:It means ‘your prayers performed towards the former direction’.
  2,144,"We have surely seen the turning about of your<sup>sg</sup> face towards the heaven. So We will turn you towards a direction that pleases you. So turn your face towards the Inviolable Mosque. And wherever you<sup>pl</sup> may be, turn your faces<sup foot_note="364961">1</sup> towards it. Indeed, those who were brought the Scripture know that it is the truth from their Lord. And Allah is not oblivious of what <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="364962">2</sup></span> do.",footnotes:345424:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.|345425:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Abu Ja’far and Rouh read it as: “…of what you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> do.”</span>
  2,145,"And indeed, even if you<sup>sg</sup> were to come with every sign to those whom the Scripture was brought to, they would not follow your direction of prayer, nor are you to follow their direction of prayer, nor do they follow the direction of prayer of one another. For if you were to follow their whims after the knowledge that has come to you, you would most surely be, in that case, one of the unjust."
  2,146,"Those whom We have brought the Scripture recognize him<sup foot_note="364963">1</sup> as they recognize their own children. But indeed a group of them do conceal the truth while they know.",footnotes:345426:A grammatical shift from 2<sup><small>nd</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.
  2,147,"The truth is from your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, so never be of the skeptics."
  2,148,"Thus for each is a direction towards which he <span class="h">turns<sup foot_note="364964">1</sup></span>, so race<sup>pl</sup> towards good works. Wherever you may be, Allah will bring you all together. Allah is indeed Powerful over everything.",footnotes:345427:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “…towards which he is turned.”</span>
  2,149,"And from wherever you<sup>sg</sup> set out, turn your face towards the Inviolable Mosque, for this is indeed the truth from your Lord. And Allah is not oblivious of what <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="364965">1</sup></span> do<sup>pl</sup>.",footnotes:345428:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “…of what they do.”</span>
  2,150,"And from wherever you<sup>sg</sup> set out, turn your face towards the Inviolable Mosque. And wherever you<sup>pl</sup> may be, turn your faces towards it so that people may not have any argument against you—except those of them who have been unjust. So do not fear them, but fear Me—and so that I may perfect My blessing upon you<sup>pl</sup>, and that you may be guided."
  2,151,"Just as We sent among you a messenger from yourselves, reading Our signs<sup foot_note="364966">1</sup> to you, and purifying you, and teaching you the Scripture and wisdom, and teaching you what you did not know.",footnotes:345429:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  2,152,"So remember Me <small>(and)</small> I will remember you<sup>pl</sup>. And thank Me, and do not deny Me."
  2,153,"O you who have attained faith, seek help through patience and prayers. Indeed, Allah is with the patient ones."
  2,154,"And do not say<sup>pl</sup> of anyone who is killed in the way of Allah, “<small>(They are) </small>dead<sup foot_note="364967">1</sup> .” Rather, <small>(they are)</small> alive, but you are unaware.",footnotes:345430:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  2,155,"And We will certainly test you<sup>pl</sup> with some fear and hunger and shortage of wealths and lives and products. Thus give<sup>sg</sup> glad tidings to the patient ones:"
  2,156,"those who, when a calamity afflicts them, say, “To Allah we belong, and indeed to Him we are returning.”"
  2,157,"Upon those are pardons and mercy from their Lord, and those are the rightly guided."
  2,158,"Indeed, Al-Safa and Al-Marwa are among the rites of Allah, so whoever performs Pilgrimage<sup foot_note="364968">1</sup> to the House or performs Minor Pilgrimage<sup foot_note="364969">2</sup>, then no sin is committed by him if he circumambulates them. And whoever volunteers a good act—then Allah is indeed Thankful, All-Knowing.",footnotes:345431:Hajj.|345432:Umrah.
  2,159,"Indeed, those who conceal what We have sent down of evident proofs and guidance after We had made it evident for mankind in the Scripture—those—Allah curses them and the cursers curse them,"
  2,160,"except those who have repented and reformed and made <small>(the truth)</small> evident. For those—I grant them repentance and accept it from them, for I am the Superb Granter and Accepter of repentance, the Bestower of mercy."
  2,161,"Indeed, those who have denied and have died as deniers—those—upon them is the curse of Allah and of the angels and of all mankind,"
  2,162,"abiding therein; never is the punishment lightened for them, nor are they given respite."
  2,163,"For your<sup>pl</sup> God is One God. There is no God but He, the All-Merciful, the Bestower of mercy."
  2,164,"Indeed, in the creation of the heavens and the earth, and the alternation of the night and the day, and the ships that sail the sea with what benefits mankind, and the water that Allah sent down from the sky— with which He revived the earth after it had died and scattered in it all kinds of treading creatures, and the shifting of the <span class="h">winds<sup foot_note="364970">1</sup></span>, and the clouds disposed between the sky and the earth are surely signs for people who reason.",footnotes:345433:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “wind”.</span>
  2,165,"Yet of mankind is one who takes <small>(others)</small> apart from Allah as rivals to Him. They<sup foot_note="364971">1</sup> love them with a love like that due to Allah, yet those who have attained faith are stronger in love for Allah. And if only those who have done injustice could <span class="h">see<sup foot_note="364972">2</sup></span>, when they <span class="h">see<sup foot_note="364973">3</sup></span> the punishment, <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="364974">4</sup></span> all power belongs to Allah and that Allah is severe in punishment.",footnotes:345434:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.|345435:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “And if only you<sup><small>sg</small></sup> could see those who have done injustice,”</span>|345436:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “...when they are made to see the punishment,”</span>|345437:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “...could see, when they see the punishment: indeed all power belongs to Allah and indeed Allah is…”</span>
  2,166,"Recall when those who were followed disowned<sup foot_note="364975">1</sup> those who had followed <small>(them),</small> and they saw the punishment and ties between them were severed.",footnotes:345438:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  2,167,"And those who followed said, “If only we could have another chance so we could disown them as they disowned us.” Thus Allah shows<sup foot_note="364976">1</sup> them their deeds as regrets to them, and never will they come out of the Fire.",footnotes:345439:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense.
  2,168,"O mankind, eat of what is lawful and good on earth, and do not follow the footsteps of Satan; indeed, he is to you an evident enemy."
  2,169,"He only commands you<sup>pl</sup> to evil and obscenity, and to say about Allah what you do not know."
  2,170,"And when it is said to them, “Follow what Allah has sent down,” they say, “Rather, we follow what we found our forefathers following. What if their forefathers used not to reason anything nor to seek guidance?"
  2,171,"The parable of those who have denied is that of one<sup foot_note="364977">1</sup> who hollers out to things that hear nothing but mere calls and cries. Deaf, dumb, <small>(and)</small> blind, so they do not reason.",footnotes:345440:A shepherd.
  2,172,"O you who have attained faith, eat of the good things We have provided you, and give thanks to Allah<sup foot_note="364978">1</sup> if it is He that you worship.",footnotes:345441:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.
  2,173,"He has only forbidden youpl carrion and blood and the flesh of swine and what was dedicated to other than Allah. But if anyone is compelled without seeking <small>(it)</small> or exceeding <small>(the limits)</small>, he commits no sin. Indeed, Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  2,174,"Indeed, those who conceal what Allah has sent down of the Scripture and purchase, in exchange for it, a small price—those devour nothing into their bellies but fire. And Allah does not speak to them on the Day of Resurrection, nor does He purify them, for for them is a painful punishment."
  2,175,"Those are the ones who have purchased utter misguidance in exchange for guidance, and punishment in exchange for forgiveness. So how patient are they in the face of the Fire!"
  2,176,"That is because Allah has bestowed the Scripture from on high with the truth. And most surely, those who differed over the Scripture are in profound discord."
  2,177,"Virtue is not <small>(attained)</small> by turning your<sup>pl</sup> faces towards the East and the West. Rather, virtue is <small>(exemplified) </small>in one who has attained faith in Allah and the Last Day and the angels and the Scripture and the prophets, and has brought money—despite his love of it—to relatives and orphans and the destitute<sup>pl</sup> and the traveler in need and the askers and for <small>(the freeing of)</small> slaves<sup foot_note="364979">1</sup>, and has established the prayer and brought<sup foot_note="364980">2</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="364981">3</sup> ; and <small>(it is exemplified) </small>in those<sup foot_note="364982">4</sup> who fulfill their covenant when they have covenanted, and those who are patient in <small>(the face of)</small> misery and adversity and at the time of battle. Those are the ones who were truthful, and it is those who are the mindful <small>(of God)</small>.",footnotes:345442:Literally ‘necks’.|345443:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|345444:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.|345445:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  2,178,"O you who have attained faith, fair retribution for the murdered<sup>pl</sup> has been prescribed upon you: the free for the free, and the bondman for the bondman, and the female for the female. Yet whoever is somewhat pardoned by his brother <small>(in faith)</small>, then this shall be adhered to in accordance with what is fair, and the payment back to him should be in a good way. That is lightening from your Lord and mercy. But whoever transgresses after that—then for him is a painful punishment."
  2,179,"Thus there is life for you in fair retribution, O people of understanding, that you may be mindful <small>(of God)</small>."
  2,180,"It has been prescribed upon you: when death comes to one of you, if he is leaving wealth, <small>(to bequeath)</small> a bequest in favor of the parents and kinsfolk in accordance with what is fair—a duty upon the mindful<sup>pl</sup> <small>(of God)</small>."
  2,181,"But whoever changes it<sup foot_note="364983">1</sup> after he has heard it, then surely its sin is upon those who change it. Indeed, Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing.",footnotes:345446:The will.
  2,182,"Yet whoever fears unfairness or sin from a bequether, so he reconciles between them, then he commits no sin. Indeed, Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  2,183,"O you who have attained faith, fasting has been prescribed upon you as it was prescribed upon those before you, that you may become mindful <small>(of God)</small>."
  2,184,"<small>(This fasting is for)</small> a limited number of days. But should any one of you be sick or on a journey, then <small>(he should fast)</small> a period of other days. Yet for those who can fast with difficulty<sup foot_note="364984">1</sup>, a compensation <small>(is allowed instead)</small>—food for a destitute <span class="h">person<sup foot_note="364985">2</sup></span>. But whoever volunteers a good act, it is better for him. Yet to fast is better for you<sup>pl</sup>, if you only knew.",footnotes:345447:This sign was revealed at a time when fasting was not yet obligatory, then it was abrogated by sign 185.|345448:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hisham read it as: “a compensation (is allowed instead)—food for destitute people.” Nafie’, Ibn Zekwan and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…a compensation of food for destitute persons (is allowed instead.)”</span>
  2,185,"<small>(It was)</small> the month of Ramadan in which the Recital<sup foot_note="364986">1</sup> was sent down as guidance for mankind, and as evident explanations of the guidance and the criterion. So whoever of you witnesses the month, then he shall fast it. But whoever is sick or on a journey, then <small>(he must fast)</small> a period of other days. Allah wants ease for you and does not want hardship for you, and that you should complete the period, and that you should glorify Allah for having guided you, and so that you may give thanks.",footnotes:345449:The Arabic word used is Qur’an which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  2,186,"And when My servants ask you<sup>sg</sup> about Me—indeed, I am near; I respond to the call of the caller when he calls upon Me. So let them respond to Me and let them have faith in Me, that they may become prudent."
  2,187,"Permitted for you<sup>pl</sup> is intercourse with your women on the night of the fast; they are a garment for you and you are a garment for them. Allah has known that you used to betray yourselves, but He granted you repentance and accepted it from you and pardoned you. So approach them now and seek what Allah has prescribed for you, and eat and drink until the white thread becomes evident to you from the black thread at dawn, then complete the fast to the night. But do not approach them while you are consecrating yourselves in the mosques. These are the limits of Allah, so do not come near them. Allah thus clarifies His signs to mankind, that they may become mindful <small>(of Him)</small>."
  2,188,"And do not devour your wealths among yourselves by false means, nor throw it <small>(as bribes) </small>to the judges in order to devour part<sup foot_note="364987">1</sup> of other people’s wealth illicitly, while you know.",footnotes:345450:Literally ‘a group’.
  2,189,"They ask you<sup>sg</sup> about the crescents. Say, “They are time-marks for mankind and for the Pilgrimage<sup foot_note="364988">1</sup> .” And virtue is not <small>(attained)</small> by approaching houses from their backs; rather, virtue is <small>(exemplified) </small>in one who has been mindful <small>(of God)</small>. So approach houses from their doors<sup foot_note="364989">2</sup> and be mindful of Allah, that you<sup>pl</sup> may succeed.",footnotes:345451:Hajj.|345452:Before Islam, Arabs used to enter their houses through the backyards once they had donned their Hajj garments, thinking that entering through the door would invalidate their state of consecration for pilgrimage.
  2,190,"And combat in the way of Allah those who combat you<sup>pl</sup>, but do not start hostilities; indeed, Allah does not love the hostile ones."
  2,191,"And kill them wherever you<sup>pl</sup> encounter them, and evict them from where they have evicted you, for religious persecution is more severe than killing. But do not <span class="h">combat<sup foot_note="364990">1</sup></span> them at the Inviolable Mosque unless they <span class="h">combat<sup foot_note="364991">2</sup></span> you about it. So if they <span class="h">combat<sup foot_note="364992">3</sup></span> you<sup>pl</sup>, then kill them. Such is the repayment of the deniers.",footnotes:345453:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “But do not kill them at the Inviolable Mosque unless they kill you about it. So if they kill you<sup><small>pl</small></sup>, then kill them.”</span>|345454:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “But do not kill them at the Inviolable Mosque unless they kill you about it. So if they kill you<sup><small>pl</small></sup>, then kill them.”</span>|345455:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “But do not kill them at the Inviolable Mosque unless they kill you about it. So if they kill you<sup><small>pl</small></sup>, then kill them.”</span>
  2,192,"But if they cease, then Allah is indeed Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  2,193,"And combat<sup>pl</sup> them until there is no more religious persecution and religion becomes for Allah. But if they cease, then let there be no hostility except against the unjust<sup>pl</sup>."
  2,194,"An inviolable month for an inviolable month, and inviolable rites call for fair retribution. So whoever starts hostilities against you<sup>pl</sup>, be hostile to him in the same measure as he has been hostile to you. And be mindful of Allah, and know that Allah is with the mindfulpl <small>(of Him)</small>."
  2,195,"And spend in the way of Allah and do not cast your<sup>pl</sup> own hands into annihilation, and excel in doing good. Indeed, Allah loves those who excel in doing good."
  2,196,"And complete the Pilgrimage<sup foot_note="364993">1</sup> and the Minor Pilgrimage<sup foot_note="364994">2</sup> for Allah. But if you<sup>pl</sup> are detained, then <small>(offer)</small> whatever is feasible of offerings. And do not shave your heads until the offering has reached its destination. But whoever of you is sick or has some affliction of his head, then the due redemption is fasting or a donation or a sacrifice. Then when you are secure: whoever enjoys a break between the Minor Pilgrimage and the Pilgrimage, then <small>(he must offer)</small> whatever is feasible of offering. But whoever cannot find the means, then fasting for three days during the Pilgrimage, and seven when you<sup>pl</sup> have<sup foot_note="364995">3</sup> returned; that is ten in total. That is for the one whose family is not present at the Inviolable Mosque<sup foot_note="364996">4</sup> . And be<sup>pl</sup> mindful of Allah, and know that Allah is stern in retribution.",footnotes:345456:Hajj.|345457:Umrah.|345458:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.|345459:Lives outside Makkah.
  2,197,"Pilgrimage is during specific months. So whoever decides to perform Pilgrimage, then there shall never be intercourse nor ungodliness nor <span class="h">disputation<sup foot_note="364997">1</sup></span> during the Pilgrimage. And whatever good you<sup>pl</sup> do, Allah knows it. And take provisions, but the best provision is indeed mindfulness <small>(of God)</small>. And be mindful of Me<sup foot_note="364998">2</sup>, O people of understanding.",footnotes:345460:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…then there shall be no intercourse nor ungodliness nor disputation during the Pilgrimage.” Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…then there shall be no intercourse nor ungodliness, and no disputation, ever, during the Pilgrimage</span>|345461:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.
  2,198,"You<sup>pl</sup> commit no sin<sup foot_note="364999">1</sup> by seeking grace from your Lord<sup foot_note="365000">2</sup> . So when you<sup>pl</sup> pour forth from Arafat, remember Allah at the Sacred Landmark. And remember Him as He has guided you<sup>pl</sup>, although before that, you were indeed of those astray.",footnotes:345462:During Pilgrimage.|345463:Through commerce.
  2,199,"Then pour<sup>pl</sup> forth from where the people have poured forth and ask Allah for forgiveness. Indeed, Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  2,200,"Then when you<sup>pl</sup> have completed your rites, remember<sup foot_note="365001">1</sup> Allah as you remember your forefathers or with even greater remembrance. And of mankind is one who says, “Our Lord, bring to us in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small>,” yet he has no share in the Hereafter.",footnotes:345464:During Pilgrimage.
  2,201,"And of them is one who says, “Our Lord, bring to us goodness in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> and goodness in the Hereafter and protect us from the punishment of the Fire.”"
  2,202,"Those shall have a share of what they have earned, for Allah is Swift in reckoning."
  2,203,"And remember<sup>pl</sup> Allah<sup foot_note="365002">1</sup> during a limited number of days. But whoever hurries on <small>(to leave Mena)</small> after two days commits no sin, and whoever stays on commits no sin—provided he maintains mindfulness <small>(of God)</small>. And be<sup>pl</sup> mindful of Allah, and know that to Him you will be herded.",footnotes:345465:In the valley of Mena.
  2,204,"And of mankind is one whose speech about the Earlier Life impresses you<sup>sg</sup>, and he calls upon Allah to bear witness as to what is in his heart, while he is the most hostile of adversaries."
  2,205,"For when he turns away <small>(from you)</small>, he rushes about in the land in order to spread corruption on earth and destroy both field and progeny. But Allah does not love corruption."
  2,206,"And when he is told, “Be mindful of Allah,” the might of the sin takes over him. So Hell is sufficient for him, and indeed, what a miserable resting place!"
  2,207,"And of mankind is one who sells his <small>(inner)</small> self, seeking Allah’s pleasure. And Allah is Compassionate towards the servants."
  2,208,"O you who have attained faith, enter into peacefulness and submission collectively, and do not follow the footsteps of Satan; indeed, to you he is an evident enemy."
  2,209,"So if you<sup>pl</sup> slip after the evident proofs have come to you, then know that Allah is Almighty, All-Wise."
  2,210,"Are they waiting for anything except for <small>(the command of)</small> Allah to come to them in shades of mists, and the angels <span class="h"><small>(too)</small><sup foot_note="365003">1</sup></span>? And <small>(thus)</small> the matter was<sup foot_note="365004">2</sup> settled, for to Allah all things are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365005">3</sup></span>.",footnotes:345466:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…in shades of mists and angels?”</span>|345467:A grammatical shift from present tense to past tense.|345468:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Asem and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…all things return.”</span>
  2,211,"Ask the Children of Israel how many an evident sign We brought them. Yet whoever changes the blessing of Allah after it has come to him, then Allah is indeed stern in retribution."
  2,212,"The Earlier Life has been adorned for those who have denied, and they ridicule those who have attained faith. But those who are mindful <small>(of God)</small> are above them on the Day of Resurrection, for Allah provides to whomever He wills without measure."
  2,213,"Mankind used to be one community, then Allah sent the prophets as bearers of glad tidings and as forewarners. And He sent down with them the Scripture with the truth to <span class="h">judge<sup foot_note="365006">1</sup></span> between mankind regarding whatever they differed over. But none differed over it<sup foot_note="365007">2</sup> except those who were given it—after evident proofs had come to them—out of mutual envy between them. Then Allah guided those who attained faith to the truth they had disputed, by His knowledge<sup foot_note="365008">3</sup> . For Allah guides whom He wills to a straight path.",footnotes:345469:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…so that it may be judged between mankind…”</span>|345470:The Scripture.|345471:Literally ‘by His leave’.
  2,214,"Or did you<sup>pl</sup> expect to enter the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> before the like of <small>(the trials that befell)</small> those who passed on before you had befallen you? Misery and adversity afflicted them, and they were shaken as with an earthquake, <span class="h">until<sup foot_note="365009">1</sup></span> the Messenger and those who believed with him would say, “When is Allah’s support <small>(coming)</small>?” Undoubtedly, Allah’s support is indeed near.",footnotes:345472:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ read it as: “…and they were shaken as with an earthquake, such that the Messenger and those…”</span>
  2,215,"They ask you<sup>sg</sup> what they should spend. Say, “Whatever good <small>(offering)</small> you spend is for the parents and the kinsfolk and the orphans and the destitute<sup>pl</sup> and the traveler in need. For whatever good you<sup>pl</sup> do, Allah is All-Knowing of it."
  2,216,"Combat has been prescribed upon you<sup>pl</sup>, even though you dislike it. But it may be that you<sup>pl</sup> dislike something while it is good for you, and it may be that you like something while it is bad for you. For Allah knows, and you<sup>pl</sup> know not."
  2,217,"They ask you<sup>sg</sup> about the inviolable month—<small>(about)</small> combat during it. Say, “Combat during it is <small>(a)</small> grave <small>(offense)</small>, yet barring bar <small>(others)</small> from the way of Allah and denying Him and <small>(preventing access to)</small> the Inviolable Mosque as well as evicting its people from it are graver to Allah, for religious persecution is <small>(a)</small> graver <small>(offense)</small> than killing. And they will keep combating you<sup>pl</sup> to turn you back from your religion, if they can. And whoever of you turns back from his religion and dies as a denier—those<sup foot_note="365010">1</sup> are the ones whose deeds were nullified in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> and the Hereafter, for those are the fellows of the Fire; therein they abide.",footnotes:345473:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  2,218,"Indeed, those who have attained faith and those who have migrated and have striven in the way of Allah—those expect Allah’s mercy, for Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  2,219,"They ask yousg about wine and gambling. Say, “There is grave <span class="h">sin<sup foot_note="365011">1</sup></span> in them and some benefits for people, but the sin in them<sup foot_note="365012">2</sup> is greater than their benefit.” And they ask you about what they should spend. Say, “The surplus.” Thus Allah makes the sign evident to you<sup>pl</sup>, that you may reflect",footnotes:345474:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “There is much sin in them…”</span>|345475:Literally ‘their sin’.
  2,220,"about the Earlier <small>(Life) </small>and the Hereafter. And they ask you<sup>sg</sup> about <small>(looking after)</small> orphans. Say, “Reforming their affairs is best. And if you intermix with them, then they are your brethren.” And Allah knows the corrupter from the reformer. For had Allah willed, He could have overburdened you<sup>pl</sup>. Indeed, Allah is Almighty, All-Wise."
  2,221,"Moreover, do<sup>pl</sup> not marry polytheistic women until they believe, for a believing bondwoman is surely better than a polytheistic woman, even if she impresses you<sup>pl</sup>. And do not marry your women to polytheistic men until they believe, for a believing bondman is surely better than a polytheistic man, even if he impresses you<sup>pl</sup>. Those call to the Fire, while Allah calls to the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> and to forgiveness by His leave, for He makes clear His signs to mankind, that they may remember."
  2,222,"And they ask you<sup>sg</sup> about menstruation. Say, “It is <small>(a cause of)</small> harm, so keep<sup>pl</sup> away from <small>(sexual intercourse with)</small> women during menstruation, and do not approach them until they are <span class="h">clean<sup foot_note="365013">1</sup></span>. But once they have cleansed themselves, then approach them from where Allah has commanded you.” Indeed, Allah loves those who frequently repent, and He loves those who cleanse themselves.”",footnotes:345476:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…until they are <b>cleansed.”</b></span>
  2,223,"Your<sup>pl</sup> women are a field for you, so approach your fields whichever way you like, but do some <small>(good)</small> act for yourselves beforehand. And be mindful of Allah and know that you<sup>pl</sup> are bound to meet Him. And give<sup>sg</sup> glad tidings to the believers."
  2,224,"And do not make your oaths in Allah's name an excuse to hinder you<sup>pl</sup> from virtue and mindfulness <small>(of God)</small> and reconciling between people, for Allah is All-Listening, All-Knowing."
  2,225,"Allah does not hold you<sup>pl</sup> accountable for idle talk involving your <small>(unintended)</small> oaths, but He holds you accountable for what your hearts have earned, for Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Forbearing."
  2,226,"For those who vow abstinence from their wives is a wait of four months. But if they retract, then Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of Mercy."
  2,227,"But if they resolve to divorce—then Allah is indeed All-Hearing, All-Knowing."
  2,228,"Moreover, divorced women shall keep themselves in wait for three periods, and it is not lawful for them to conceal what Allah has created in their wombs if they believe in Allah and the Last Day, for their husbands have the right to restore them back if they want reconciliation. And women have rights equal to their obligations in accordance with what is fair. But men have a degree over them, for Allah is Almighty, All-Wise."
  2,229,"Divorce is <small>(allowed)</small> twice, then either retention in accordance with what is fair, or setting free kindly. And it is not lawful for you<sup>pl</sup> to take back anything you have given them<sup foot_note="365014">1</sup>, unless they<sup foot_note="365015">2</sup> both <span class="h">fear<sup foot_note="365016">3</sup></span> that they may not maintain Allah's limits. So if you<sup>pl</sup> fear that they may not maintain Allah’s limits, then there is no sin committed by either of them if she pays, as a compensation for her release<sup foot_note="365017">4</sup> . These are Allah’s limits, so do<sup>pl</sup> not transgress them, for those who transgress Allah’s limits are the unjust.",footnotes:345477:“Them” is feminine, denoting that the discourse is addressing men regarding their wives.|345478:A grammatical shift from 2<sup><small>nd</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.|345479:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…unless it is feared that they both may not maintain…”</span>|345480:Literally ‘ransoms herself’.
  2,230,"But if he divorces her, she shall not be lawful for him again until she has married another spouse. Then if he<sup foot_note="365018">1</sup> divorces her, then no sin is committed by them both<sup foot_note="365019">2</sup> if they reunite, provided they think they can maintain Allah's limits. Thus these are Allah’s limits; He makes them evident to people who know.",footnotes:345481:The latter.|345482:She and the first husband.
  2,231,"Thus if youpl divorce women and they have reached their term<sup foot_note="365020">1</sup>, then either retain them in accordance with what is fair or release them in accordance with what is fair. But do not retain them in order to transgress against them, for whoever performs that, then he has surely been unjust to himself. And do not take Allah’s signs for mockery. And remember Allah's blessing upon you<sup>pl</sup> and what He has sent down to you of the Scripture and the Wisdom to admonish you. And be<sup>pl</sup> mindful of Allah, and know that Allah is All-Aware of everything.",footnotes:345483:The waiting period.
  2,232,"Thus if you<sup>pl</sup> divorce women and they have reached their term<sup foot_note="365021">1</sup>, then do not prevent them from marrying their spouses <small>(again)</small>, provided they agree with each other in accordance with what is fair. That is an admonition for whoever of you believes in Allah and the Last Day. That is more purifying for you<sup>pl</sup> and cleaner, for Allah knows, and you know not.",footnotes:345484:The waiting period.
  2,233,"And mothers shall nurse their children for two whole years<sup foot_note="365022">1</sup> —for whoever wants to complete the nursing period. And it is the duty of the father of the infant to provide for them<sup foot_note="365023">2</sup> and clothe them in accordance with what is fair. No self shall be tasked beyond its capacity. No mother should <span class="h">be<sup foot_note="365024">3</sup></span> harmed on account of her child, nor any father of an infant on account of his child. And the same duty rests upon the heir. And if they both want weaning, by mutual consent and consultation, then no sin is committed by them. And if you<sup>pl</sup> want<sup foot_note="365025">4</sup> to seek nursing for your children, then no sin is committed by you as long as you give <small>(them)</small> what you have <span class="h">brought<sup foot_note="365026">5</sup></span> in accordance with what is fair. And be mindful of Allah, and know that Allah is indeed All-Seeing of what you do.",footnotes:345485:Literally ‘two rounds’.|345486:The mothers.|345487:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “No mother is (supposed to be) harmed on account of her child,”</span>|345488:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 2<sup><small>nd</small></sup> person.|345489:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “…what you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> have come up with…”</span>
  2,234,"And those of you who are taken at death and leave spouses behind, they<sup foot_note="365027">1</sup> shall keep themselves in wait for four months and ten days. Then when they have reached their term, then no sin is committed by you<sup>pl</sup> regarding what they might do with themselves in accordance with what is fair. For Allah is All-Aware of what you do.",footnotes:345490:The pronoun is plural feminine, denoting that it means ‘the widows’.
  2,235,"And no sin is committed by you<sup>pl</sup> if you give a hint about engagement to <small>(the widowed) </small>women or if you keep it within yourselves. Allah already knew that you would consider <small>(marrying)</small> them<sup foot_note="365028">1</sup> . But do not meet them secretly unless you have something to say in accordance with what is fair. And do not confirm the marriage tie until the term prescribed is fulfilled. And know that Allah knows what is in your <small>(inner)</small> selves, so beware of Him. And know that Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Forbearing.",footnotes:345491:Literally ‘mention them’.
  2,236,"No sin is committed by you<sup>pl</sup> if you divorce women before having touched<sup foot_note="365029">1</sup> <span class="h">them<sup foot_note="365030">2</sup></span> nor appointed to them any marriage obligation<sup foot_note="365031">3</sup> . And compensate them: the wealthy according to his means, and the poor according to his means—a compensation in accordance with what is fair, a duty upon those who excel in doing good.",footnotes:345492:In sexual intercourse.|345493:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa'i and Khalaf read it as: "...before having touched each other..."</span>|345494:Dowry.
  2,237,"But if you<sup>pl</sup> divorce them before having touched them and you have already appointed them an appointed sum, then <small>(give them)</small> half of what you have appointed—unless they waive it or the one in whose hand is the marriage contract waives it. But to waive it is nearer to mindfulness <small>(of God)</small>. And do not forget grace among yourselves. Indeed, Allah is All-Seeing of what you do."
  2,238,"Preserve<sup>pl</sup> the prayers and the middle prayer, and stand devout before Allah."
  2,239,"But if you<sup>pl</sup> are in fear, then <small>(pray)</small> on foot or while riding. Then when you feel secure, remember Allah as He has taught you what you did not know."
  2,240,"Moreover, those of you <small>(men)</small> who are taken at death and leave spouses behind—<small>(let them bequeath) </small>a <span class="h">bequest<sup foot_note="365032">1</sup></span> for their spouses with compensation for a year without eviction <small>(from the husband's residence)</small>. But if they depart, then no sin is committed by you<sup>pl</sup> regarding what they have done with themselves in accordance with what is fair. For Allah is Almighty, All-Wise.",footnotes:345495:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Abu Amr, Ibn Amer, Hafs and Hamza read it as: “…and leave spouses behind—a bequest (is ordained upon them) for their spouses with compensation…”</span>
  2,241,"And for divorced women there is a compensation in accordance with what is fair—a duty upon the mindful<sup>pl</sup>."
  2,242,"Allah thus makes His signs evident to you<sup>pl</sup>, that you may reason."
  2,243,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen those who departed their homes by the thousands, for fear of death? So Allah said to them, “Die,” then He revived them. Most surely, Allah is Gracious towards mankind, but most of mankind do not thank."
  2,244,"And combat<sup>pl</sup> in the way of Allah, and know that Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing."
  2,245,"Who is it that will lend Allah a good loan? <small>(So)</small> that He may multiply it for him <span class="h">manifold<sup foot_note="365033">1</sup></span>, for Allah withholds and extends, and to Him you<sup>pl</sup> are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365034">2</sup></span>.",footnotes:345496:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “Who is it that will lend Allah a good loan (so) that He may multiply it for him manifold? For Allah withholds and extends,”</span>|345497:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> return.”</span>
  2,246,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen the chiefs of the Children of Israel after Moses, when they said to a prophet of theirs, “Appoint a king for us, and we will combat in the way of Allah.”? He said, “Would you perhaps, in case combat is prescribed upon you, not combat?” They said, “Why would we not combat in the way of Allah when we were evicted from our homes along with our children?” But when combat was prescribed upon them, they turned away, except for a few of them. For Allah is All-Knowing of the unjust<sup>pl</sup>."
  2,247,"Thus their prophet said to them, “Indeed, Allah has sent you Talut<sup foot_note="365035">1</sup> as a king.” They said, “How can he have authority over us when we are more worthy of authority than he, for he was not brought abundance of wealth?” He said, “Allah has chosen him over you and has increased him in knowledge and build.” Thus Allah brings His authority to whomever He wills, for Allah is All-Embracing, All-Knowing.",footnotes:345498:Saul.
  2,248,"And their prophet said to them, “Indeed, the sign of his authority is that the ark<sup foot_note="365036">1</sup> shall come to you with tranquility from your Lord, and relics left by Moses's folk and Aaron's folk. <small>(It shall be)</small> carried by the angels. In that is a sign for you, if you have been believers.”",footnotes:345499:Of the covenant.
  2,249,"So when Talut<sup foot_note="365037">1</sup> set out with the troops, he said, “Allah will indeed be testing you with a river. So whoever drinks from it does not belong with me, but whoever does not taste it does belong with me—except for whoever scoops up a <span class="h">scoopful<sup foot_note="365038">2</sup></span> with his hand.” Yet they drank from it, except for a few of them. Then when he had crossed it together with those who had attained faith with him, they said, “We have no strength to face Galut<sup foot_note="365039">3</sup> and his troops today.” Those expecting to meet Allah said, “How many a small battalion has overcome a large battalion by Allah’s leave, for Allah is with the patient ones.”",footnotes:345500:Saul.|345501:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…scoops up a (single) scoop with his hand.”</span>|345502:Goliath.
  2,250,"And when they confronted Galut<sup foot_note="365040">1</sup> and his troops, they said, “Our Lord, pour down patience upon us and strengthen our foothold and support us against the denying people.”",footnotes:345503:Goliath.
  2,251,"So they defeated them by Allah’s leave when David killed Galut<sup foot_note="365041">1</sup>, and Allah brought him authority and wisdom and taught him as He willed. And were it not for Allah <span class="h">repelling<sup foot_note="365042">2</sup></span> some people by means of others, the earth would indeed become corrupted, but Allah is Gracious to all realms.",footnotes:345504:Goliath.|345505:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “And were it not for Allah strongly repelling some people…”</span>
  2,252,"Those are Allah’s signs<sup foot_note="365043">1</sup> which We read to you in truth, for you are most surely one of the emissaries.",footnotes:345506:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  2,253,"Those messengers—we favored some of them over others of them: to some of them Allah spoke <small>(directly)</small>,<small> </small>and some of them He elevated by degrees. And We<sup foot_note="365044">1</sup> brought Jesus, son of Mary, the evident proofs, and We aided him with the Holy Spirit. And had Allah willed, those who succeeded them would not have fought one another after the evident proofs had come to them, but they disputed—for some of them attained faith and some of them denied. For had Allah willed, they would not have fought one another, but Allah does what He wants.",footnotes:345507:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.
  2,254,"O you who have attained faith, spend from what We have provided for you before there comes a day in which there is neither trading nor close friendship nor intercession for the deniers are the unjust."
  2,255,"Allah—there is no god but He, the Living, the All-Sustaining. Neither slumber overtakes Him nor sleep. To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth. Who is it who can intercede with Him except by His leave? He knows what is before them and what is behind them, and they do not encompass any of His knowledge except according to what He wills. His<small> </small>knowledge<sup foot_note="365045">1</sup> has embraced the heavens and the earth, and their preservation does not fatigue Him, for He is the All-High, the Great.",footnotes:345508:Literally ‘His seat’.
  2,256,"<small>(There shall be) </small>no compulsion in religion; prudence has henceforth become distinct from delusion. So whoever denies false masters and attains faith in Allah, then he has truly grasped the firmest handhold which never fractures. For Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing."
  2,257,"Allah is the Ultimate Guardian of those who have attained faith; He brings them out of the darkness<small>(es)</small> into the light, while those who have denied—their guardians are the false masters; they bring them out of the light into the darkness<small>(es)</small>. Those are the fellows of the Fire; therein they abide."
  2,258,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen the one who debated <span class="h">Abraham<sup foot_note="365046">1</sup></span> about his Lord—that Allah had given him authority? Recall when <span class="h">Abraham<sup foot_note="365047">2</sup></span> said, “My Lord is the One Who gives life and causes death.” He said, “I give life and cause death.” <span class="h">Abraham<sup foot_note="365048">3</sup></span> said, “But surely, Allah brings the sun from the East, so you bring it from the West.” Thus the denier was confounded, for Allah does not guide the unjust<sup>pl</sup>.",footnotes:345509:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as <i>Ibrahim</i>, Hisham and Ibn Zekwan in one of his narrations read it as: “Abraham”.</span>|345510:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as <i>Ibrahim</i>, Hisham and Ibn Zekwan in one of his narrations read it as: “Abraham”.</span>|345511:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as <i>Ibrahim</i>, Hisham and Ibn Zekwan in one of his narrations read it as: “Abraham”.</span>
  2,259,"Or like the one who passed by a town and it was completely devastated upon its trellises. He said, “How can Allah revive this after its death?” Thereupon Allah caused him to die for a hundred years and then resurrected him. He said, “For how long have you tarried?” He said, “I have tarried for a day or part of a day.” He said, “Rather, you have tarried for a hundred years. And look at your food and your drink—it has not spoiled—and look at your donkey. And We will make you a sign for mankind. And look at the bones—how We <span class="h">assemble<sup foot_note="365049">1</sup></span> them, then clothe them with flesh.” So when it became evident to him, he said, “I <span class="h">know<sup foot_note="365050">2</sup></span> that Allah is All-Powerful over everything.”",footnotes:345512:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…how We revivify them,”</span>|345513:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “So when it became evident to him, He said, “Know that…”</span>
  2,260,"And recall when <span class="h">Abraham<sup foot_note="365051">1</sup></span> said, “My Lord, show me how You revive the dead<sup>pl</sup>.” He said, “Have you not attained faith?” He said, “Yes indeed, but that my heart may become serene.” He said, “So take four birds and bend them towards you<sup foot_note="365052">2</sup>, then place on every mountain a part of them, then call them and they will come to you, running. And know that Allah is Almighty, All-Wise.”",footnotes:345514:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as <i>Ibrahim</i>, Hisham and Ibn Zekwan in one of his narrations read it as: “Abraham”.</span>|345515:According to some exegetes, ‘bend them’ is a metaphor for ‘cut them’.
  2,261,"The parable of those who spend their wealths in the way of Allah is that of a grain that has germinated seven ears; in each ear are a hundred grains. For Allah multiplies for whom He wills. And Allah is All-Embracing, All-Knowing."
  2,262,"Those who spend their wealths in the way of Allah and then do not follow up what they have spent with any reminder<sup foot_note="365053">1</sup> or any harm—their reward is with their Lord, and no <span class="h">fear<sup foot_note="365054">2</sup></span> shall be upon them nor shall they grieve.",footnotes:345516:Of their generosity.|345517:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…and no fear shall ever be upon them nor shall they grieve.”</span>
  2,263,"A kind word and forgiveness are better than a donation followed by hurtfulness. For Allah is Self-Sufficient, Forbearing."
  2,264,"O you who have attained faith, do not nullify your donations with reminders and hurtfulness, like one who spends his wealth for show in front of people and does not believe in Allah and the Last Day. His likeness is that of a smooth rock with dust upon it, then a heavy rain struck it and left it bare. They<sup foot_note="365055">1</sup> have no power to retain anything of what they have earned. For Allah does not guide the denying people.",footnotes:345518:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  2,265,"And the parable of those who spend their wealths seeking Allah’s pleasure and the affirmation of their <small>(inner)</small> selves is that of a garden on a hilltop struck by heavy rain, so it brought forth its crops twofold. And even if no heavy rain strikes it, then light rain <small>(is sufficient)</small>. For Allah is All-Seeing of what you do."
  2,266,"Would anyone of you like to have a garden of palms and grapevines under which rivers flow, wherein he has of all kinds of products, but he is afflicted with old age and he has weak offspring—then it was struck with a fiery tornado and was thus burnt? Thus Allah makes the signs evident for you<sup>pl</sup>, that you may reflect."
  2,267,"O you who have attained faith, spend of the good things you have earned and from what We have brought out for you from the earth, and do not pick the nasty of it to give away, whereas you yourselves would not take it unless your eyes were closed to it. And know that Allah is Self-Sufficient, Praiseworthy."
  2,268,"Satan promises you<sup>pl</sup> poverty and commands you to obscenity, while Allah promises you forgiveness from Himself, and grace. For Allah is All-Embracing, All-Knowing."
  2,269,"He brings wisdom to whomever He wills, and whoever is <span class="h">brought<sup foot_note="365056">1</sup></span> wisdom, then he has most surely been brought much good. But none constantly remembers except those of understanding.",footnotes:345519:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…and whoever He brings wisdom, then he has most surely been brought much good.</span>
  2,270,"Thus whatever expenditure youpl have spent or vow you vow, then indeed Allah knows it. And the unjust have no supporters."
  2,271,"If you<sup>pl</sup> disclose donations, then that is excellent. But if you<sup>pl</sup> hide them and bring them to the needy, then that is better for you. and it will <span class="h">remit<sup foot_note="365057">1</sup></span> your evil deeds for you. For Allah is All-Aware of what you do.",footnotes:345520:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Abu Ja’far and Khalaf read it as: “…then that is better for you, and We will (also) remit your evil deeds for you.” Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Shu’ba and Ya’qub read it as: “then that is better for you. And We will remit your evil deeds for you.”</span>
  2,272,"Their guidance is not your<sup>sg</sup> responsibility, but Allah guides whomever He wills. And whatever good you<sup>pl</sup> spend is to your own benefit. And whatever good you spend shall be to seek Allah's Countenance. And whatever good you<sup>pl</sup> spend will be repaid to you in full, for you will not be done injustice."
  2,273,"<small>(Donations are)</small> for the poor—those who are detained <small>(for striving)</small> in the way of Allah, unable to travel in the land <small>(for livelihood)</small>. Anyone ignorant <small>(of their condition)</small> would think them rich due to their self-restraint. You<sup>sg</sup> recognize them by their mark <small>(of poverty)</small>—they do not ask from people insistently. And whatever good you<sup>pl</sup> spend—Allah is indeed All-Knowing of it."
  2,274,"Those who spend their wealths by night and day, secretly and publicly—their reward is with their Lord, and no <span class="h">fear<sup foot_note="365058">1</sup></span> shall be upon them nor shall they grieve.",footnotes:345521:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…and no fear shall ever be upon them nor shall they grieve.”</span>
  2,275,"Those who devour usury cannot stand<sup foot_note="365059">1</sup> except as does one who is being beaten by Satan into insanity. That is because they said, “Trade and usury are certainly the same.” But Allah has permitted trade and has forbidden usury. Thus, to whomsoever an admonition came from his Lord, so he refrained <small>(from usury)</small>—then his past earnings belong to him and his matter rests with Allah. Yet whoever reverts—then those<sup foot_note="365060">2</sup> are the fellows of the Fire; therein they abide.",footnotes:345522:On the Day of Resurrection.|345523:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  2,276,"Allah eliminates usury and He makes donations grow, for Allah does not love every sinning relentless denier."
  2,277,"Indeed, those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds and have established the prayer and have brought<sup foot_note="365061">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="365062">2</sup> —their reward is with their Lord, and no <span class="h">fear<sup foot_note="365063">3</sup></span> shall be upon them nor shall they grieve.",footnotes:345524:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|345525:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.|345526:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…and no fear shall ever be upon them nor shall they grieve.”</span>
  2,278,"O you who have attained faith, be mindful of Allah and leave aside what has remained of usury, if you are believers."
  2,279,"But if you<sup>pl</sup> do not, then be <span class="h">informed<sup foot_note="365064">1</sup></span> of a war from Allah and His Messenger. Yet if you repent, then your capitals belong to you—<small>(thus) </small>you do no injustice, and you are not done injustice.",footnotes:345527:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba and Hamza read it as: “…then inform (everyone) of a war…”</span>
  2,280,"But if he<sup foot_note="365065">1</sup> has hardship, then deferment until a time of ease<small>.</small> But to donate<sup foot_note="365066">2</sup> it is better for you<sup>pl</sup>, if you only knew.",footnotes:345528:The debtor.|345529:To waive it as charity.
  2,281,"And be mindful of a day<sup foot_note="365067">1</sup> when you<sup>pl</sup> are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365068">2</sup></span> to Allah, then the earnings of every single self are rendered in full to it, for they<sup foot_note="365069">3</sup> are not done injustice.",footnotes:345530:Literally ‘guard yourselves against a day’.|345531:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…when you return to Allah,”</span>|345532:A grammatical shift from 2<sup><small>nd</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.
  2,282,"O you who have attained faith, when you transact a debt for a stated term, write it down. And have a scribe write between you, in fairness. And let no scribe refuse to write as Allah has taught him. So let him write, and let the one upon whom is the duty of payment<sup foot_note="365070">1</sup> dictate. And let him be mindful of Allah, his Lord, and defraud nothing of it. But if the one upon whom is the duty of payment is mentally deficient or weak or unable to dictate, then let his guardian dictate with fairness. And call to witness two of your men, but if the two are not men, then one man and two women from those whom you<sup>pl</sup> approve of as witnesses—so that if one of them should <span class="h">err<sup foot_note="365071">2</sup></span>, the other can remind her. And witnesses must not abstain when called upon. And be not averse to writing it down, whether small or large <small>(in value)</small>, including its term. That is more just with Allah<sup foot_note="365072">3</sup> and more upright for testimony and more likely to make you not doubt—except in the case of an immediate bargain you conduct among yourselves—for <small>(then)</small> you commit no sin if you do not write it down. But <small>(otherwise)</small> let there be witnesses whenever you trade with one another. And let no harm befall any scribe or witness, for if you ever do so, it shall be ungodliness on your part. And be mindful of Allah, and Allah teaches you, for Allah is All-Knowing of everything.",footnotes:345533:The debtor.|345534:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: "…so that in case one of them errs, the other reminds her."</span>|345535:That is more just than oral agreements.
  2,283,"But if you<sup>pl</sup> are on a journey and cannot find a scribe, then a security should be handed over. But if you trust one another, let the one who was trusted fulfill his trust, and let him be mindful of Allah, his Lord. And do not conceal testimony, for whoever conceals it—indeed, he has a sinful heart. And Allah is All-Knowing of what you do."
  2,284,"To Allah belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth. Hence, whether you<sup>pl</sup> disclose what is within your selves or hide it, Allah calls you to account for it; He then forgives whomever He wills and He punishes whomever He wills, for Allah is All-Powerful over everything."
  2,285,"The Messenger has attained faith in what was sent down to him from his Lord, as have the believers. They have all attained faith in Allah and His angels and His <span class="h">scriptures<sup foot_note="365073">1</sup></span> and His messengers: “We <span class="h">make<sup foot_note="365074">2</sup></span> no distinction between any of His messengers.” And they said, “We have heard and obeyed. <small>(Grant us)</small> Your forgiveness, our Lord, for to You is the destiny.”",footnotes:345536:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “scripture”</span>|345537:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “He makes no distinction…”</span>
  2,286,"Allah does not task any self beyond its capacity. To its credit is what it has earned, and against it is what it has committed. “Our Lord, do not take us to task if we forget or make a mistake. Our Lord, and do not burden us with a heavy load as You burdened those before us. Our Lord, and do not overburden us with what we have no capability for, and pardon us and forgive us and have mercy upon us. You are our Patron, so support us against the denying people.”"
  3,1,"Alif Lām Mīm."
  3,2,"Allah—there is no god but He, the Living, the All-Sustaining."
  3,3,"He bestowed upon you<sup>sg</sup> the Scripture from on high with the truth, confirming what preceded it. And He sent down the Torah and the Gospel"
  3,4,"previously, as guidance for mankind, and He sent down the Criterion. Indeed, for those who have denied Allah’s signs is a severe punishment, for Allah is Almighty, Capable of vengeance."
  3,5,"Indeed, nothing in the earth or in the heaven is hidden from Allah."
  3,6,"It is He Who designs you<sup>pl</sup> in the wombs as He wills. There is no god except He, the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  3,7,"It is He Who sent down upon you<sup>sg</sup> the Scripture. Some of its signs are explicit; they are the foundation<sup foot_note="365075">1</sup> of the Scripture, while others are equivocal. So as for those whose hearts swerve, they follow whatever is equivocal of it, seeking tribulation and seeking its interpretation. But none knows its interpretation except Allah. Thus, those firmly rooted in knowledge say, “We have attained faith in it; all is from our Lord.” But none constantly remembers except those with understanding.",footnotes:345538:Literally ‘the mother of the Scripture’.
  3,8,"“Our Lord, do not cause our hearts to swerve after You have guided us, and bestow upon us mercy from You; indeed, You are the Superb Bestower."
  3,9,"“Our Lord, You will certainly gather mankind for a day about which there is no doubt.” Indeed, Allah<sup foot_note="365076">1</sup> never breaks a promise.",footnotes:345539:A grammatical shift from 2<sup><small>nd</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.
  3,10,"Those who have denied—certainly, neither their wealth nor their children will avail them anything against Allah, and those are the fuel for the Fire."
  3,11,"Like the behavior of Pharaoh’s folk and those before them: they disbelieved in Our signs, so Allah<sup foot_note="365077">1</sup> seized them on account of their misdeeds. For Allah is Stern in retribution.",footnotes:345540:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.
  3,12,"Say<sup>sg</sup> to those who have denied, <span class="h">“You<sup foot_note="365078">1</sup></span> shall be overcome and herded to Hell, so what a miserable resting place!”",footnotes:345541:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Say<sup>sg</sup> to those who have denied that they shall be overcome and herded to Hell, so what a miserable resting place!” to those who have denied that they shall be overcome and herded to Hell, so what a miserable resting place!”</span>
  3,13,"Surely, there was a sign for you<sup>pl</sup> in two battalions that met: one battalion combating in the way of Allah and another denying, <span class="h">seeing<sup foot_note="365079">1</sup></span> them<sup foot_note="365080">2</sup> —as the eye sees—twice their number. For Allah aids with His support whomever He wills. In that is indeed a lesson for those endowed with sight<small>(s)</small>.",footnotes:345542:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ya’qub and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…and another denying. You<sup><small>pl</small></sup> see them—as the eye sees—twice their number.”</span>|345543:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  3,14,"Adorned for mankind is the love of desires, such as women and children and piles upon piles of gold and silver and branded horses and livestock and fields. That is the enjoyment of the Earlier Life, but with Allah lies the most excellent resort."
  3,15,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Shall I inform you<sup>pl</sup> of something better than that? For those who are mindful <small>(of God)</small>, with their Lord are Gardens beneath which rivers flow, abiding therein, and cleansed spouses and good pleasure from Allah.” For Allah is All Seeing of the servants"
  3,16,"who say, “Our Lord, we have indeed attained faith, so forgive us our misdeeds and guard us from the punishment of the Fire.”"
  3,17,"The patient and the truthful and the devout and the spenders <small>(in the way of God)</small> and the seekers of forgiveness before dawn."
  3,18,"Allah has borne witness that indeed, there is no god but He, as have the angels and those endowed with knowledge—upholding justice. There is no god but He, the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  3,19,"<span class="h">Indeed<sup foot_note="365081">1</sup></span>, religion with Allah is Islam. Yet those who were brought the Scripture did not differ with each other except after knowledge had come to them, thereby oppressing one another. So whoever denies the signs of Allah—then Allah is indeed Swift in reckoning.",footnotes:345544:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al Kesa’i read it as: “(And) that religion with Allah is Islam.”</span>
  3,20,"So if they debate with you<sup>sg</sup>, then say, “I have submitted my countenance to Allah, and <small>(so have)</small> those who have followed me.” And say to those who were brought the Scripture and to the gentiles<sup foot_note="365082">1</sup>, “Have you submitted?” Thus, if they have submitted, then they have been guided. But if they turn away, then your <small>(only)</small> duty is proclamation, for Allah is All-Seeing of the servants.",footnotes:345545:Literally ‘the unlettered’.
  3,21,"Indeed, those who deny Allah’s signs<sup foot_note="365083">1</sup> and unjustifiably kill the prophets and <span class="h">kill<sup foot_note="365084">2</sup></span> those of mankind who command to justice—give them glad tidings<sup foot_note="365085">3</sup> of a painful punishment.",footnotes:345546:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.|345547:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “…and combat those of mankind…”</span>|345548:<big>This is said in sarcasm.</big>
  3,22,"Those are the ones whose deeds were nullified in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> and the Hereafter, for they have no helpers."
  3,23,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen those who were brought a share of the Scripture, being called to the Scripture of Allah to <span class="h">judge<sup foot_note="365086">1</sup></span> between them, then a group of them turn away in disregard?",footnotes:345549:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…being called to the Scripture of Allah so that it may be judged between them,”</span>
  3,24,"That is because they said, “The Fire will not touch us except for a limited number of days.” But they have been deceived in their religion by whatever they fabricated."
  3,25,"So how about when We gather them for a day about which there is no doubt, and every single self is paid in full for what it has earned, and they<sup foot_note="365087">1</sup> are not dealt with unjustly?",footnotes:345550:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  3,26,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “O Allah, Master of the dominion, You grant dominion to whomever You will and You strip dominion from whomever you will, and You honor whomever you will and You humiliate whomever you will; in Your hand is all goodness. You are indeed All-Powerful over everything."
  3,27,"You cause the night to penetrate the day and cause the day to penetrate the night, and you bring the living out of the dead and You bring the dead out of the living, and You provide for whomever You will without measure.”"
  3,28,"Let not the believers take the deniers for allies apart from the believers, for whoever does that has nothing to do with Allah—unless it is to protect your<sup>pl</sup> own selves against them in some manner of self-protection. And Allah cautions you<sup>pl</sup> Himself, for to Allah is the destiny."
  3,29,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Whether you<sup>pl</sup> hide what is within your chests or disclose it, Allah knows it.” For He knows whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth, for Allah is All-Powerful over everything."
  3,30,"On a day when every self finds whatever good it had done presented, while whatever evil it had done—it will wish there were a great distance between itself and it. And Allah Himself cautions you<sup>pl</sup>, for Allah is Compassionate towards the servants."
  3,31,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “If you love Allah, then follow me—Allah will love you and forgive you your misdeeds, for Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy.”"
  3,32,"Say, “Obey Allah and the Messenger.” But if they turn away, then Allah does not love the deniers."
  3,33,"Indeed, Allah has selected Adam and Noah and Abraham's folk and Imran's folk over all communities:"
  3,34,"offspring of one another, for Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing."
  3,35,"Recall when Imran's wife said, “My Lord, I have indeed vowed <small>(to dedicate)</small> to You what is in my belly, dedicated <small>(solely to You)</small>, so accept from me; indeed, You are the All-Hearing, the All-Knowing.”"
  3,36,"So when she gave birth to her, she said, “My Lord, I have indeed given birth to her, a female,” and Allah knows better what she has <span class="h">delivered<sup foot_note="365088">1</sup></span>, “and the male is not like the female, and I have indeed named her Mary, and I do seek refuge with You for her and her offspring from Satan, the outcast.”",footnotes:345551:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer, Shu’ba and Ya’qub read it as: “…a female, and Allah knows better what I have delivered, and the male is not…”</span>
  3,37,"So her Lord accepted her with good acceptance and brought her up a good upbringing and entrusted her to the sponsorship of <span class="h">Zechariah<sup foot_note="365089">1</sup></span>. Whenever Zechariah entered upon her in the sanctuary, he found with her provision<sup foot_note="365090">2</sup> . He said, “O Mary, how did you get this?” She said, “It is from Allah; indeed, Allah provides whomever He wills without measure.”",footnotes:345552:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…and Zechariah sponsored her.”</span>|345553:Food.
  3,38,"Thereupon Zechariah called upon his Lord. He said, “My Lord, grant me from Your bounty good offspring; You are indeed the Hearer of supplication.”"
  3,39,"So the angels <span class="h">called<sup foot_note="365091">1</sup></span> out to him as he stood praying in the sanctuary that: “Allah <span class="h">gives<sup foot_note="365092">2</sup></span> you glad tidings of John, confirming a Word from Allah, and honorable, and abstinent from women, and a prophet from among the righteous.”",footnotes:345554:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “So (one of) the angels called out to him…”</span>|345555:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Hamza read it as: “…sanctuary: “Indeed, Allah gives you…”</span>
  3,40,"He said, “My Lord, how will I have a son when old age has overtaken me and my wife is barren?” He said, “So shall it be! Allah does whatever He wills.”"
  3,41,"He said, “My Lord, set for me a sign.” He said, “Your sign is that you shall not speak to people for three days except by gesture. And remember your Lord much, and exalt <small>(Him)</small> in the evening and the morning.”"
  3,42,"And recall when the angels said, “O Mary, Allah has indeed selected you and cleansed you and He has selected you over the women of all communities."
  3,43,"“O Mary, be devout to your Lord and prostrate yourself and bow down with those who bow down.”"
  3,44,"That is of the stories of the hidden realm which We reveal to you<sup>sg</sup>, for you were not with them when they cast their pens as to which of them would sponsor Mary, nor were you with them when they were disputing."
  3,45,"Recall when the angels said, “O Mary, Allah indeed gives you glad tidings of a Word from Him. His name is the Messiah, Jesus, son of Mary, well-esteemed in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> and the Hereafter, and one of those brought near."
  3,46,"And he will speak to people in the cradle and in adulthood and will be one of the righteous.”"
  3,47,"She said, “My Lord, how can I have a child when no human being has touched me?” He said, “So shall it be! Allah creates whatever He wills. Whenever He decrees a matter, He only says to it, 'Be,' and so it <span class="h">is<sup foot_note="365093">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:345556:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “He only says to it, ‘Be,’ so it is.”</span>
  3,48,"And <span class="h">He<sup foot_note="365094">1</sup></span> will teach him scribing<sup foot_note="365095">2</sup> and wisdom and the Torah and the Gospel.",footnotes:345557:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Asem, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “And We will teach him…”</span>|345558:The Arabic word used is <i>al-kitab</i> which may mean 'scribing' or 'scripture'.
  3,49,"And <small>(He will appoint him as)</small> a messenger to the Children of Israel <small>(to proclaim)</small>: 'I have come to you<sup>pl</sup> with a sign from your Lord: that <span class="h">I<sup foot_note="365096">1</sup></span> create for you out of clay the shape of a bird, then I breathe into it so it becomes a bird by Allah’s leave; and I heal the born-blind and the leper; and I revive the dead by Allah’s leave; and I inform you concerning what you eat and what you store in your houses. Indeed, in that is a sign for you, if you are believers.",footnotes:345559:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…from your Lord: I truly create…”</span>
  3,50,"And I am to confirm what preceded me of the Torah and to make lawful to you<sup>pl</sup> some of what was prohibited for you. And I have come to you with a sign from your Lord, so be mindful of Allah and obey me."
  3,51,"Indeed, Allah is my Lord and your Lord, so worship Him. That is a straight path.'”"
  3,52,"So when Jesus sensed denial on their part, he said, “Who are my supporters towards Allah?” The disciples said, “We are Allah’s supporters; we have attained faith in Allah, so bear witness that we are indeed Muslims<sup foot_note="365097">1</sup> .",footnotes:345560:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimoon</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  3,53,"Our Lord, we have attained faith in what You have sent down and we have followed the Messenger, so inscribe us among those who bear witness.”"
  3,54,"And they<sup foot_note="365098">1</sup> schemed and Allah schemed, but Allah is the best of schemers.",footnotes:345561:The disbelievers.
  3,55,"As Allah said, “O Jesus, I am taking you back and raising you to Me and cleansing you of those who denied, and I am making those who follow you superior to those who denied until the Day of Resurrection. Then to Me is your<sup>pl</sup> return, then I will judge between you regarding whatever you used to differ over."
  3,56,"So as for those who have denied—I will punish them with a severe punishment in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> and the Hereafter, and for them there are no helpers."
  3,57,"And as for those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—He<sup foot_note="365099">1</sup> will <span class="h">render<sup foot_note="365100">2</sup></span> to them their rewards in full, for Allah does not love the unjust.”",footnotes:345562:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.|345563:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs and Roways read it as: “We will render to them…” (In this case there is no grammatical shift).</span>
  3,58,"This is what We read to you<sup>sg</sup> of the signs<sup foot_note="365101">1</sup> and the Wise Reminder.",footnotes:345564:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular a<i>yah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  3,59,"Indeed, the likeness of Jesus with Allah<sup foot_note="365102">1</sup> is as the likeness of Adam: He created him from dust, then said to him, “Be,” and so he is.",footnotes:345565:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.
  3,60,"The truth is from your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, so do not be of those who doubt."
  3,61,"And if anyone debates with you<sup>sg</sup> about him after what has come to you of knowledge, then say, “Come, let us call our sons and your sons, and our women and your women, and ourselves and yourselves, and let us supplicate to make Allah’s curse befall the liars.”"
  3,62,"Indeed, this is the true narrative, for there is no god but Allah, and Allah is indeed the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  3,63,"But if they turn away—Allah is indeed All-Knowing of the corrupters."
  3,64,"Say, “O People of the Scripture, come to a common word between us and you: that we worship none but Allah, and that we associate nothing with Him, and that we do not take one another as lords apart from Allah.” And if they turn away, then say<sup>pl</sup>, “Bear witness that we are Muslims<sup foot_note="365103">1</sup> .”",footnotes:345566:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimoon</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  3,65,"O People of the Scripture, why do you debate about Abraham, when the Torah and the Gospel were not sent down except after him? Do you not reason?"
  3,66,"Here you<sup>pl</sup> are—you have debated about things you have knowledge about, so why do you debate about things you have no knowledge about? For Allah knows and you know not."
  3,67,"Abraham was neither a Jew nor a Christian; rather, he was a Muslim who turned away from all that is false, and never was he of the polytheists."
  3,68,"Surely, those of mankind who are most deserving of Abraham <small>(as an ally)</small> are those who followed him, and this prophet, and those who have attained faith. And Allah is the Ally of the believers."
  3,69,"A faction of the People of the Scripture would love to lead you<sup>pl</sup> astray, but they lead none astray except themselves, but they are unaware."
  3,70,"O People of the Scripture, why do you deny the signs of Allah, though you witness?"
  3,71,"O People of the Scripture, why do you confound the truth with falsehood and conceal the truth, though you know?"
  3,72,"And a faction of the People of the Scripture said, “Believe<sup>pl</sup> in what was sent down to those who attained faith at the beginning of the day, then deny <small>(it)</small> at its end, that perhaps they may return."
  3,73,"But trust none except whoever has followed your<sup>pl</sup> religion.” Say<sup>sg</sup> “Indeed, <small>(true)</small> guidance is <small>(only)</small> Allah’s <span class="h">guidance—that<sup foot_note="365104">1</sup></span> anyone can be brought the like of what you<sup>pl</sup> were brought, or they<sup foot_note="365105">2</sup> may debate with you before your Lord." Say, “All grace is in Allah’s hand; He gives it to whomever He wills.” For Allah is All-Embracing, All-Knowing.",footnotes:345567:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “…Allah’s guidance. Can anyone be brought the like of what you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> were brought, or can they debate with you before your Lord?”</span>|345568:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  3,74,"He specifies His mercy for whomever He wills, for Allah is the Possessor of great grace."
  3,75,"And of the People of the Scripture is one who, if you<sup>sg</sup> entrust him with a heap <small>(of gold)</small>, will pay it back to you. And of them is one who, if you entrust him with a <small>(single)</small> dinar, will not pay it back to you unless you are constantly standing over him. That is because they have said, “We are under no obligation towards the gentiles<sup foot_note="365106">1</sup> .” And they tell lies against Allah, though they know.",footnotes:345569:Literally ‘the unlettered’.
  3,76,"Yes<sup foot_note="365107">1</sup>, whoever fulfills his covenant and is mindful <small>(of God)</small>—then indeed, Allah loves mindful people.",footnotes:345570:Answering their claim that they are under no obligation towards the gentiles.
  3,77,"Indeed, those who purchase, in exchange for Allah's covenant and their oaths, a small price, those—there is no share for them in the Hereafter, nor will Allah speak to them, nor will He look at them on the Day of Resurrection, nor will He purify them, and for them is a painful punishment."
  3,78,"And indeed, of them is a group who twist their tongues with the Scripture, that you<sup>pl</sup> may think it from the Scripture while it is not from the Scripture. And they say, “It is from Allah,” while it is not from Allah. And they tell lies against Allah, though they know."
  3,79,"No person to whom Allah has given the Scripture and wise judgment and prophethood would ever say to mankind, “Be my servants apart from Allah.” Rather, “Be godly<sup foot_note="365108">1</sup> on account of the Scripture which you<sup>pl</sup> used to <span class="h">teach<sup foot_note="365109">2</sup></span> and on account of what you used to learn.”",footnotes:345571:Literally ‘Lordly’.|345572:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Amer, Asem, Hamza, Al Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…used to know and…”</span>
  3,80,"Nor would he command you to take the angels and the prophets as lords. Would he command you to denial after you became Muslims<sup foot_note="365110">1</sup> ?",footnotes:345573:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimoon</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  3,81,"And recall when Allah took the pledge of the <small>(followers of the)</small> prophets, “Inasmuch as <span class="h">I<sup foot_note="365111">1</sup></span> have given you<sup>pl</sup> of scripture and wisdom, should a messenger come to you confirming what you have, you shall certainly believe in him and you shall certainly support him.” He said, “Have you consented and taken up that heavy load towards Me upon yourselves?” They said, “We have consented.” He said, “Then bear witness, and I am with you among the witnesses.”",footnotes:345574:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “Inasmuch as We have given you…” Hamza read it as: “Because of what I have given you of scripture and wisdom, then a messenger has come to you...”</span>
  3,82,"So whoever turns away after that—those are the defiantly disobedient."
  3,83,"Do <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="365112">1</sup></span> seek other than the religion of Allah, when to Him has submitted whoever is in the heavens and the earth, willingly and reluctantly, and to Him they will be <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365113">2</sup></span>?",footnotes:345575:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Abu Amr, Hafs and Ya’qub read it as: “Do you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> seek…”</span>|345576:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “and to Him they return.” All except for Hafs and Ya’qub read it as: “and to Him you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> return.”</span>
  3,84,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “We have attained faith in Allah, and in what was sent down upon us, and in what was sent down upon Abraham and Ishmael and Isaac and Jacob and the Grandsons<sup foot_note="365114">1</sup>, and in what was brought to Moses and Jesus and the prophets from their Lord. We make no distinction between any of them, and to Him we are Muslims<sup foot_note="365115">2</sup> .”",footnotes:345577:The different prophets of the Israelites.|345578:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimoon</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  3,85,"And whoever seeks other than Islam as a religion—it will not be accepted from him, and in the Hereafter he is one of the losers."
  3,86,"How will Allah guide a people who denied after their attainment of faith and <small>(after) </small>having witnessed that the Messenger is true and <small>(after)</small> evident explanations had come to them, when Allah does not guide the unjust people?"
  3,87,"Those—their repayment is that upon them falls the curse of Allah and of the angels and of all mankind,"
  3,88,"abiding therein; never will the punishment be lightened for them, nor are they given respite—"
  3,89,"except those who repented afterwards and reformed, for Allah is indeed Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  3,90,"Indeed, those who denied after their belief then increased in denial—their repentance will not be accepted, for those are the ones who have gone astray."
  3,91,"Indeed, those who denied and died as deniers—not even as much as the earth full of gold would be accepted from any of them, were he to offer it for ransom. Those—for them is a painful punishment, and for them there are no helpers."
  3,92,"You<sup>pl</sup> will not attain virtue until you spend of what you love, for whatever you spend of anything, Allah is indeed All-Knowing of it."
  3,93,"All food was permissible to the Children of Israel except what Israel forbade for himself before the Torah was bestowed from on <span class="h">high<sup foot_note="365116">1</sup></span>. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Bring the Torah and read it, if you<sup>pl</sup> are truthful.”",footnotes:345579:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…before the Torah was sent down.”</span>
  3,94,"Then whoever fabricates lies about Allah after that—then those are the unjust."
  3,95,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Allah has spoken the truth. So follow<sup>pl</sup> the creed of Abraham who turned away from all that is false—and never was he one of the polytheists.”"
  3,96,"Indeed, the first House established for mankind is surely the one at Bakkah, blessed, and a guidance for <small>(all creatures in)</small> all realms."
  3,97,"In it are evident signs: the standing place of Abraham, and <small>(that)</small> whoever enters it becomes secure. Thus, pilgrimage to the House is a duty to Allah upon mankind—whoever can make a way to it. Yet whoever has denied, then Allah is indeed Self-Sufficient <small>(without need for any of the creatures)</small> of all realms."
  3,98,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “O People of the Scripture, why do you deny the signs of Allah, when Allah witnesses whatever you do?”"
  3,99,"Say, “O People of the Scripture, why do you bar from the way of Allah whoever has attained faith, seeking to make it crooked, even though you are witnesses? And Allah is not oblivious of what you do.”"
  3,100,"O you who have attained faith, if you obey a group of those who were given the Scripture, they turn you after having attained faith into deniers."
  3,101,"And how could you deny when Allah’s signs<sup foot_note="365117">1</sup> are being read to you and among you is His Messenger? And whoever holds fast to Allah has surely been guided to a straight path.",footnotes:345580:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  3,102,"O you who have attained faith, be mindful of Allah as is His due, and do not die except as Muslims."
  3,103,"And hold fast to the lifeline of Allah, all together, and do not become disunited. And remember Allah’s blessing upon you: how you were enemies, then He reconciled between your hearts, and by His blessing you became brethren. And you were on the brink of a pit of fire, then He rescued you from it. Allah thus clarifies His signs for you<sup>pl</sup>, that you may be guided."
  3,104,"And let there be a community from among you who call to goodness and command to what is fair and forbid what is deplorable, for those are the successful."
  3,105,"And be not like those who became disunited and disputed after the evident explanations had come to them, for for those is a great punishment—"
  3,106,"on a day when some faces are whitened and some faces are blackened. So as for those whose faces were<sup foot_note="365118">1</sup> blackened: “Did you deny after having attained faith?” Then taste the punishment on account of what you used to deny.",footnotes:345581:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  3,107,"And as for those whose faces were whitened— <small>(they are)</small> in Allah’s mercy; therein they abide."
  3,108,"Those are the signs of Allah; We read them to you<sup>sg</sup> in truth. And Allah wants no injustice for <small>(all creatures)</small> of all realms."
  3,109,"Thus, to Allah belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth, and to Allah all matters are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365119">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:345582:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer, Hamza, Al Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “…and to Allah all matters return.”</span>
  3,110,"You have been the best community that was ever brought forth for mankind: you command to what is fair and forbid what is deplorable and believe in Allah. For had the People of the Scripture believed, it would have been better for them. Some of them are believers, but most of them are defiantly disobedient."
  3,111,"They do not harm you<sup>pl</sup> beyond hurtfulness. And if they combat you they will turn around and flee, then they will not be supported."
  3,112,"They have been stricken with humiliation wherever they are caught, except through a lifeline from Allah and a lifeline from the people. And they have incurred wrath from Allah and have been stricken with destituteness. That is because they used to deny Allah’s signs and unjustifiably kill the prophets. That is because they disobeyed and used to transgress."
  3,113,"They are not alike: of the People of the Scripture is a community that is upright—they read Allah’s signs<sup foot_note="365120">1</sup> throughout the night while prostrating themselves.",footnotes:345583:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  3,114,"They believe in Allah and the Last Day and command to what is fair and forbid what is deplorable and hasten towards good works, for those are of the righteous."
  3,115,"And whatever good <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="365121">1</sup></span> do, they will not be denied it, for Allah is All-Knowing of those who are mindful <small>(of Him)</small>.",footnotes:345584:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Hafs, Hamza, Al Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “And whatever good you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> do, you will not be denied it, ….”</span>
  3,116,"Those who have denied—surely, neither their wealths nor their children will avail them anything against Allah, for those are the fellows of the Fire; therein they abide."
  3,117,"The parable of what they spend in this Earlier Life is that of a frosty wind that struck the field of a people who had been unjust to themselves and annihilated it. And Allah was not unjust to them; rather, they are unjust to themselves."
  3,118,"O you who have attained faith, do not take outsiders for confidants: they never cease to cause you confusion. They have <small>(always)</small> loved to see you suffer. Hatred has already appeared from their mouths, but what their chests hide is bigger. We have already made the messages evident for you, if you have been reasoning."
  3,119,"There you<sup>pl</sup> are, loving them whereas they do not love you, and you believe in the entire Scripture. And when they encounter you, they say, “We have attained faith,” but when they are alone, they bite their fingers in rage at you. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Die<sup>pl</sup> in your rage. Indeed, Allah is All-Knowing of what lies within the chests.”"
  3,120,"If any good touches you<sup>pl</sup>, it upsets them. But if anything evil befalls you, they rejoice at it. Yet if you persevere patiently and become mindful <small>(of God)</small>, their plots will not harm you at all. Indeed, Allah is All-Encompassing of what they do."
  3,121,"And recall when you<sup>sg</sup> left your household in the morning, assigning battle-positions for the believers. For Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing."
  3,122,"Recall when two factions of you<sup>pl</sup> almost faltered, but Allah was their Ultimate Guardian. So in Allah let the believers place their trust."
  3,123,"And Allah had very truly given you<sup>pl</sup> support at Badr when you were humble<sup foot_note="365122">1</sup> . So be mindful of Allah, that you may give thanks.",footnotes:345585:They were lesser in number and in weaponry.
  3,124,"Recall saying<sup>sg</sup> to the believers, “Shall it not suffice you that your Lord should help you with three thousand angels sent <span class="h">down<sup foot_note="365123">1</sup></span>?”",footnotes:345586:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “…three thousand angels bestowed from on high?”</span>
  3,125,"Yes indeed, <small>(but)</small> if you<sup>pl</sup> persevere patiently and become mindful <small>(of God)</small> and they attack you suddenly, your Lord will aid you with five thousand angels having <span class="h">marks<sup foot_note="365124">1</sup></span><small>(of distinction)</small>.",footnotes:345587:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Asem and Ya’qub read it as: “…five thousand marked angels.”</span>
  3,126,"And Allah did not make it except as glad tidings for you and so that your hearts should find comfort thereby. For support comes not except from Allah the Almighty, the All-Wise—"
  3,127,"in order to cut off a fringe of those who denied or repress them so that they may return as losers."
  3,128,"You<sup>sg</sup> have nothing <small>(to say)</small> regarding this matter: whether He accepts their repentance or punishes them, for they are certainly unjust."
  3,129,"Thus to Allah belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth. He forgives whom He wills and He punishes whom He wills, for Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  3,130,"O you who have attained faith, do not devour usury, multiplied <small>(and)</small> re-multiplied, and be mindful of Allah, that you may be successful."
  3,131,"And guard yourselves against the Fire that has been prepared for the deniers."
  3,132,"And obey Allah and the Messenger, that you may obtain mercy."
  3,133,"<span class="h">And<sup foot_note="365125">1</sup></span> hasten towards forgiveness from your<sup>pl</sup> Lord and a Garden as wide as the heavens and the earth, prepared for the mindful <small>(of God)</small>:",footnotes:345588:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “Hasten towards…”</span>
  3,134,"those who spend in prosperity and adversity, and those who restrain <small>(their)</small> rage, and those who forgive mankind—for Allah loves those who excel in doing good,"
  3,135,"and those who, when they commit an indecency or wrong themselves, remember Allah then ask forgiveness for their misdeeds—for who forgives misdeeds except Allah? And they do not persist in their wrongdoing while they know."
  3,136,"Those—their repayment is forgiveness from their Lord and Gardens beneath which rivers flow, abiding therein, and how excellent is the reward of the workers!"
  3,137,"Many rules <small>(God set)</small> for those before you<sup>pl</sup> have passed away, so journey through the earth and look what the outcome was for the disbelievers."
  3,138,"This is a proclamation to mankind, and guidance and an admonition for people who are mindful <small>(of God)</small>."
  3,139,"And do not waver nor grieve, for you are the highest as long as you are believers."
  3,140,"If a blow touches you, a similar blow has surely touched the <small>(other)</small> people. For such days We alternate between mankind, and so that Allah<sup foot_note="365126">1</sup> may know those who have attained faith and take witnesses<sup foot_note="365127">2</sup> from among you. For Allah does not love the unjust.",footnotes:345589:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.|345590:The Arabic word used is <i>shuhada’</i>, which literally means ‘witnesses’ and is usually used to describe martyrs.
  3,141,"And so that Allah may purge those who have attained faith and eliminate the deniers."
  3,142,"Or did you think that you would enter the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> when Allah has not yet known those of you who have striven and known the patient ones?"
  3,143,"And most surely you<sup>pl</sup> used to wish for death before you had encountered it, but now you have surely seen it as you were beholding."
  3,144,"Thus Muhammad is no more than a messenger before whom messengers have passed on. Then will it be that if he dies or gets killed you<sup>pl</sup> will turn on your heels? For whoever turns on his heels—he will not harm Allah in any way. And Allah will repay the thankful ones."
  3,145,"For never was it for anyone to die except by Allah’s leave at a predetermined time. So whoever wants the recompense of the Earlier <small>(Life)</small>, We<sup foot_note="365128">1</sup> bring him of it. And whoever wants the recompense of the Hereafter, We bring him of it. And We will repay the thankful ones.",footnotes:345591:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.
  3,146,"And how many a prophet has had numerous godly<sup foot_note="365129">1</sup> people <span class="h">combating<sup foot_note="365130">2</sup></span> alongside him? And they did not waver regardless of that which afflicted them in the way of Allah, nor did they weaken, nor did they give in. And Allah loves the patient ones.",footnotes:345592:Literally ‘Lordly’.|345593:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…numerous godly people killed alongside him?”</span>
  3,147,"And their only words were, “Our Lord, forgive us our misdeeds and our extremism in <small>(dealing with)</small> our matters, and strengthen our foothold and support us against the denying people.”"
  3,148,"So Allah brought them the recompense of the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> and the most excellent recompense of the Hereafter, for Allah loves those who excel in doing good."
  3,149,"O you who have attained faith, if you obey those who have denied, they will turn you back on your heels and you will end up losers."
  3,150,"Indeed, Allah is your Patron, and He is the Best of Helpers."
  3,151,"We will throw terror into the hearts of those who have denied because they associated with Allah<sup foot_note="365131">1</sup> <small>(partners)</small> for which He bestowed from on <span class="h">high<sup foot_note="365132">2</sup></span> no authority. And their shelter is the Fire, and how miserable is the dwelling of the unjust!",footnotes:345594:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.|345595:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…for which He sent down no authority.”</span>
  3,152,"And very truly Allah fulfilled His promise to you as you decimated them by His leave, until when you faltered and disagreed with each other about the matter and disobeyed after He had shown you what you love: of you is one who wants the Earlier <small>(Life)</small>, and of you is one who wants the Hereafter. Then He turned you away from them to test you. But very truly He has pardoned you, for Allah is Gracious towards the believers."
  3,153,"Recall climbing<sup>pl</sup> and not looking back for anyone, with the Messenger calling you from your rear<sup foot_note="365133">1</sup> . Then He repaid you with sorrow on account of the sorrow <small>(you caused the prophet)</small> so that you would not grieve over what you missed or for what befell you. For Allah is All-Aware of what you do.",footnotes:345596:At the battle of Uhud, the Muslims fled the battlefield upon their defeat and the Prophet (peace be upon him) stood calling them to come back and fight.
  3,154,"Then after the stress He sent down upon you<sup>pl</sup> security <small>(in the form of)</small> drowsiness <span class="h">overcoming<sup foot_note="365134">1</sup></span> a faction of you, while a faction cared only for themselves, assuming about Allah contrary to the truth—assumptions of the era of ignorance<sup foot_note="365135">2</sup> —saying, “Is anything up to us?” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Everything is up to Allah.” They hide within themselves what they do not disclose to you. They say, “If it were up to us, none of us would have been killed here.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Even if you had stayed in your houses, those destined to be killed would have emerged to their death beds.” And so that Allah may test what is in your chests and so that He may purge what is in your hearts, for Allah is All-Knowing of what lies within the chests.",footnotes:345597:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “He sent down upon you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> security overcoming a faction of you (in the form of) a nap, while a faction…”</span>|345598:The Arabic word used is <i>jahiliyah</i> which is derived from <i>jahl</i>, meaning ‘ignorance’, and refers to the pre-Islamic phase of paganism.
  3,155,"Indeed, those of you who turned away on the day when the two armies met—it was Satan who caused them to backslide on account of some of what they had earned. But Allah has most surely pardoned them, for Allah is indeed Oft-Forgiving, Forbearing."
  3,156,"O you who have attained faith, do not be like those who denied and said of their brethren who traveled in the land or were on an expedition, “Had they stayed with us, they would not have died or got killed.” So that Allah may make it a cause of regret in their hearts. For Allah gives life and causes death, and Allah is All-Seeing of what you<sup>pl</sup> <span class="h">do<sup foot_note="365136">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:345599:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Hamza, Al Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…and Allah is All-Seeing of what they do.”</span>
  3,157,"Thus if you<sup>pl</sup> get killed in the way of Allah or die—surely, forgiveness and mercy from Allah are better than what <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="365137">1</sup></span> hoard.",footnotes:345600:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as: “…better than what you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> hoard.”</span>
  3,158,"For if you<sup>pl</sup> die or get killed, then surely to Allah you will be herded."
  3,159,"So it is by mercy from Allah that you<sup>sg</sup> were gentle with them. And had you been harsh, hard-hearted, they would have dispersed from around you. So pardon<sup>sg</sup> them and ask forgiveness for them and consult them in the conduct of affairs. And when you are resolved, place your trust in Allah; indeed, Allah loves those who place their trust <small>(in Him)</small>."
  3,160,"If Allah supports you<sup>sg</sup>, then there is none who can overcome you. But if He forsakes you, then who is it who will support you after Him? So in Allah let the believers place their trust."
  3,161,"And never was it for a prophet to <span class="h">defraud<sup foot_note="365138">1</sup></span>, for whoever defrauds brings whatever he has defrauded on the Day of Resurrection. Then every single self is paid in full for what it has earned, and they are not dealt with unjustly.",footnotes:345601:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Asem read it as: “And never was it for a prophet to be defrauded,”</span>
  3,162,"Is someone who has pursued Allah's good pleasure the same as someone who has incurred Allah's anger and whose shelter is Hell? And what a miserable destiny!"
  3,163,"They are of <small>(different)</small> degrees <small>(of rank)</small> with Allah. And Allah is All-Seeing of what they do."
  3,164,"Most surely, Allah has conferred favor upon the believers, having sent them a messenger from among themselves, reading to them His signs and purifying them and teaching them the Scripture and wisdom, for surely they were previously in evident misguidance."
  3,165,"Is it that when a calamity befell you<sup>pl</sup>, even after you had inflicted twice as much, you said, “How is this?” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “It is from your own selves.” Allah is indeed All-Powerful over everything."
  3,166,"For what befell you<sup>pl</sup> on the day the two armies met was with Allah’s leave, and that He may know the believers,"
  3,167,"and that He may know those who acted hypocritically when it was said to them, “Come, combat in the way of Allah, or at least defend <small>(the community).”</small>They said, “If we knew there was going to be combat, we would follow you<sup>pl</sup>.” On that day they were closer to denial than they were to faith. They say with their mouths what is not in their hearts. But Allah knows better what they conceal."
  3,168,"Those who said of their brethren, as they stayed behind, “Had they obeyed us, they would not have been <span class="h">killed<sup foot_note="365139">1</sup></span>.” Say, “Then avert death from yourselves, if you are truthful.”",footnotes:345602:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hisham read it as: “…they would not have been relentlessly killed.”</span>
  3,169,"And <span class="h">never<sup foot_note="365140">1</sup></span> think<sup>sg</sup> of those <span class="h">killed<sup foot_note="365141">2</sup></span> in the way of Allah as dead. Rather, <small>(they are)</small> alive, with their Lord, being provided for,",footnotes:345603:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hisham—in one of his recitations—read it as: “And never should he think of those killed in the…”</span>|345604:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “And never think<sup><small>sg</small></sup> of those relentlessly killed in the way of Allah as dead.”</span>
  3,170,"exulting over what Allah has brought them out of His grace and glad for those behind them who have not yet joined them: that no <span class="h">fear<sup foot_note="365142">1</sup></span> shall be upon them nor shall they grieve.",footnotes:345605:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…that no fear shall ever be upon them nor shall they grieve.”</span>
  3,171,"Glad because of a blessing from Allah, and grace, and because Allah does not waste the reward of the believers"
  3,172,"who responded to Allah and the Messenger after the blow had befallen them. For those of them who excelled in doing good and were mindful <small>(of God)</small> is a great reward."
  3,173,"Those to whom the people said, “The people have assembled against you, so fear them.” But this only increased them in faith, and they said, “Allah is sufficient for us, and what an excellent Trustee.”"
  3,174,"So they came back with a blessing from Allah, and grace, no harm having touched them. And they pursued Allah’s good pleasure, for Allah is the Possessor of a great grace."
  3,175,"That is only Satan frightening his allies. So do not fear them, but fear Me if you are believers."
  3,176,"And do<sup>sg</sup> not be saddened by those who hasten towards denial. They will not harm Allah in the least. Indeed, Allah wants to give them no share in the Hereafter, for for them is a great punishment."
  3,177,"Indeed, those who have purchased denial in exchange for faith will not harm Allah in the least, for for them is a painful punishment."
  3,178,"And never should those who have denied <span class="h">think<sup foot_note="365143">1</sup></span> that We respite them for their own good. In fact, We only respite them so that they may increase in sin, for for them is a demeaning punishment.",footnotes:345606:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “And never think<sup><small>sg</small></sup>—regarding those who have denied—that We respite them…”</span>
  3,179,"Never would Allah leave the believers in the state which you<sup>pl</sup> are in until He distinguishes the nasty from the good. Nor would Allah make you view the hidden realm. In fact, Allah elects of His messengers whom He wills. So believe in Allah and His messengers, for if you<sup>pl</sup> believe and remain mindful <small>(of God)</small>, you will have a great reward."
  3,180,"And never should those who are miserly with what Allah has given them of His grace <span class="h">think<sup foot_note="365144">1</sup></span> that it is good for them. Rather, it is an evil thing for them. They will be encircled by whatever they were miserly with on the Day of Resurrection, for to Allah belongs the inheritance of the heavens and the earth. And Allah is All-Aware of whatever you<sup>pl</sup> <span class="h">do<sup foot_note="365145">2</sup></span>.",footnotes:345607:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “And never think<sup><small>sg</small></sup>—regarding those who are miserly with what Allah has given them of His grace— that it is good for them.”</span>|345608:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “… of whatever they do.”</span>
  3,181,"Allah has most surely heard the statement of those who said, “Indeed, Allah is poor while we are rich.” We<sup foot_note="365146">1</sup> <span class="h">will<sup foot_note="365147">2</sup></span> write down what they said and their unjustified killing of the prophets, and We will say, “Taste the punishment of the burning.",footnotes:345609:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.|345610:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “What they said and their unjustified killing of the prophets will be written down, and He will say . . .” (In this case there is no grammatical shift.)</span>
  3,182,"That is on account of what your<sup>pl</sup> hands have put forth, and because Allah is not a tyrant unto the servants.”"
  3,183,"Those who said, “Allah has made a covenant with us: that we shall not believe in any messenger unless he brings us an offering to be devoured by the fire.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Certainly, messengers have come to you before me with evident proofs and with that which you said. So why did you kill them, if you are truthful?”"
  3,184,"So if they disbelieve you<sup>sg</sup>, messengers before you were disbelieved. They came with clear proofs and Books and the illuminating <span class="h">Scripture<sup foot_note="365148">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:345611:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hisham read it as: “…and with Books and with the illuminating Scripture.” Ibn Zekwan read it as: “…and with Books and the illuminating Scripture.”</span>
  3,185,"Each self is bound to have a taste of death. And you<sup>pl</sup> will be rendered your rewards in full only on the Day of Resurrection. So whoever is swayed from the Fire and is entered into the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> has triumphed, for the Earlier Life is nothing but a deceptive enjoyment."
  3,186,"You<sup>pl</sup> will surely be tested through your wealths and yourselves, and you will hear from those who received the Scripture before you and from those who associated <small>(others with God)</small> many hurtful things. But if you<sup>pl</sup> persevere patiently and become mindful <small>(of God)</small>—that is indeed a mark of firm resolve."
  3,187,"And as Allah took a pledge from those who were brought the Scripture: “Most surely <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="365149">1</sup></span> shall make it evident to mankind and not conceal it.” But they tossed it behind their backs and purchased, in exchange for it, a small price, so how miserable is what they purchase!",footnotes:345612:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Shu’ba read it as: “Most surely they shall make it evident…”</span>
  3,188,"<span class="h">Never<sup foot_note="365150">1</sup></span> think<sup>sg</sup> of those who exult over what they have come up with and love to be praised for what they have not done—never think<sup>sg</sup> of them as in a place safe from the punishment, for for them is a painful punishment.",footnotes:345613:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “Never should they think—those who exult over what they have come up with and love to be praised for what they have not done, never should they think of them(selves) as in a place safe from the punishment,”Nafie’ read it as: “Never should they think—those who exult over what they have come up with and love to be praised for what they have not done, never think<sup><small>sg</small></sup> of them as in a place safe from the punishment,”</span>
  3,189,"And to Allah belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth, and Allah is Powerful over everything."
  3,190,"Most surely, in the creation of the heavens and the earth and in the alternation of night and day are signs for people of understanding:"
  3,191,"those who remember Allah while standing and sitting and on their sides, and reflect upon the creation of the heavens and the earth: “Our Lord, You did not create this in vain. Highly Exalted are You, so protect us from the punishment of the Fire."
  3,192,"Our Lord, whomever You enter into the Fire, then You have truly disgraced him, for the unjust ones have no supporters."
  3,193,"Our Lord, we have indeed heard a caller calling to the faith: ‘Attain faith in your Lord,' so we have attained faith. So, Our Lord, forgive us our misdeeds and remit our evil deeds and take us at death with the virtuous."
  3,194,"Our Lord, and bring us what You have promised us through Your messengers and do not disgrace us on the Day of Resurrection. Surely, You never break <small>(the promise of)</small> the appointed time.”"
  3,195,"So their Lord responded to them: “I do not waste the work of any worker of you, whether male or female—you are of one another. So those who emigrated and were evicted from their homes and were hurt in my way and <small>(who)</small> combated and were <span class="h">killed<sup foot_note="365151">1</sup></span>—I will most surely remit for them their evil deeds and will most surely admit them into Gardens beneath which rivers flow—a recompense from Allah, for with Allah is the excellent recompense."",footnotes:345614:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…and were killed and (who) combated…” Ibn Kathir and Ibn Amer read it as: “…and (who) combated and were relentlessly killed..…”</span>
  3,196,"Never be<sup>sg</sup> deceived by the movement of those who denied in the land."
  3,197,"A brief enjoyment, then their shelter is Hell, and what a miserable resting place!"
  3,198,"But those who were mindful of their Lord—for them are Gardens beneath which rivers flow, abiding therein, a hospitality from Allah. And what Allah possesses is better for the truly virtuous."
  3,199,"And indeed, of the People of the Scripture are those who believe in Allah and in what was sent down to you and in what was sent down to them. They are reverent towards Allah and do not purchase, in exchange for Allah’s signs<sup foot_note="365152">1</sup>, a small price. Those have their reward with their Lord. Indeed, Allah is Swift in reckoning.",footnotes:345615:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  3,200,"O you who have attained faith, be patient and have outlasting patience and be ever at the ready and be mindful of Allah, that you may succeed."
  4,1,"O mankind, be mindful of your Lord, Who created you from a single self and created from it its spouse, and from them both spread many men and women. Thus be mindful of Allah—in Whose name you ask one another—and of <span class="h">the<sup foot_note="365153">1</sup></span> wombs<sup foot_note="365154">2</sup> . Indeed, Allah has always been Watchful over you.",footnotes:345616:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “Thus be mindful of Allah, in Whose name, and the name of the wombs, you ask one another.”</span>|345617:The term ‘wombs’ is usually used in the Qur’an as a metaphor for blood relatives, meaning: honor the ties of kinship.
  4,2,"And bring orphans their wealths, and do not replace <small>(their)</small> good things with nasty ones, and do not devour their wealths by combining them with your<sup>pl</sup> wealths; indeed, it has always been a gravely serious sin."
  4,3,"And if you<sup>pl</sup> fear you cannot be just towards the orphans, then marry the women you like—two or three or four—but if you fear you will not be equitable, then <small>(only)</small> <span class="h">one<sup foot_note="365155">1</sup></span> or <small>(consider)</small> those whom you rightfully possess. That is more likely to make you avoid bias.",footnotes:345618:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…then (only) one (is enough) or consider…”</span>
  4,4,"Moreover, bring women their dowries graciously. But if they willingly forgo some of it for you<sup>pl</sup>, then devour it with satisfaction, with ease."
  4,5,"But do not bring the foolish ones your<sup>pl</sup> money which Allah has assigned to you for support, yet provide for them from it and clothe them and say to them a fair word."
  4,6,"And test the orphans until they reach the age of marriage. So if you<sup>pl</sup> recognize in them prudence, then hand over their wealths to them and do not devour it extravagantly or hastily before they grow up. For the rich <small>(guardian)</small> should modestly abstain <small>(from charging any wage)</small>, but whoever (of the guardians) is poor may charge<sup foot_note="365156">1</sup> in accordance with what is fair. Then when you hand over their wealths to them, call witnesses in. Yet sufficient is Allah as a Reckoner.",footnotes:345619:Literally ‘devour’.
  4,7,"For men is a share of what parents and kinsfolk have left, and for women is a share of what parents and relatives have left, be it little or much—an ordained share."
  4,8,"And if the distribution is attended by the close relatives and the orphans and the destitute<sup>pl</sup>, then give them something out of it and say to them a fair word."
  4,9,"And let those who, were they to leave behind them weak offspring would be afraid for them, fear <small>(God's punishment).</small> So let them be mindful of Allah and let them speak for justice."
  4,10,"Indeed, those who devour the wealths of orphans illicitly devour only fire into their bellies; and they will <span class="h">roast<sup foot_note="365157">1</sup></span> in a blaze.",footnotes:345620:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Shu’bah read it as: “…and they will be roasted in the blaze.”</span>
  4,11,"Allah enjoins you<sup>pl</sup> regarding your children: for the male is the equivalent of the share of two females. But if they are women above two, they get two-thirds of what he has left; and if she be one, then to her is the half. And for his parents—each gets one-sixth of what he has left if he has children. Yet if he has no children and his parents inherit <small>(solely)</small> from him, then his mother gets one-third. But if he has siblings, then his mother gets one-sixth, after <small>(fulfilling) </small>any bequest he may <span class="h">bequeath<sup foot_note="365158">1</sup></span> and <small>(paying off)</small> any debt. Your parents<sup foot_note="365159">2</sup> and your children—you do not know which are more beneficial to you. <small>(This is)</small> an ordinance from Allah. Indeed, Allah has always been All-Knowing All-Wise.",footnotes:345621:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Ibn Amer and Shu’ba read it as: “…after (fulfilling) any bequest that is bequeathed…”</span>|345622:Literally ‘your fathers’.
  4,12,"And you<sup>pl</sup> get one-half of what your spouses have left if they<sup foot_note="365160">1</sup> have no children. Yet if they have children, then you get one-fourth of what they have left, after <small>(fulfilling)</small> any bequest they may bequeath and <small>(paying off)</small> any debt. And they get one-fourth of what you have left if you have no children. Yet if you have children, then they get one-eighth of what you have left, after <small>(fulfilling)</small> any bequest you may bequeath and <small>(paying off) </small>any debt. And if a man or a woman is to be inherited by a non-lineal heir while having a brother or sister<sup foot_note="365161">2</sup>, then each of them gets one-sixth. But if they are more than that, then they share one-third, after <small>(fulfilling)</small> any bequest that may be <span class="h">bequeathed<sup foot_note="365162">3</sup></span> and <small>(paying off)</small> any debt, without any harm <small>(to anyone).</small> <small>(This is)</small> an injunction from Allah, for Allah is All-Knowing, Clement.",footnotes:345623:The pronoun is in feminine form, denoting that they are female spouses.|345624:According to the majority of exegetes, this means the brother and the sister are from the deceased’s maternal side.|345625:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Kathir, Ibn Amer and Asem read it as: “…after (fulfilling) any bequest that he may bequeath…”</span>
  4,13,"These are the limits of Allah. And whoever obeys Allah and His Messenger—He <span class="h">enters<sup foot_note="365163">1</sup></span> him into Gardens beneath which rivers flow, abiding therein, and that is the great triumph.",footnotes:345626:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…We enter him into…”</span>
  4,14,"But whoever disobeys Allah and His Messenger and oversteps His limits—He <span class="h">enters<sup foot_note="365164">1</sup></span> him into a fire wherein he abides, and for him is a demeaning punishment.",footnotes:345627:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…We enter him into…”</span>
  4,15,"And those of your<sup>pl</sup> women who commit obscenity—call four of you to witness against them; then if they testify, confine them to the houses until death takes them up or Allah makes a way for them."
  4,16,"And those two of you who commit it, then punish them both. Yet if they repent and reform, then disregard them both. Indeed, Allah has always been Granting and Accepting of repentance, Bestowing of mercy."
  4,17,"Indeed, <small>(granting</small> <small>of) </small>repentance is <small>(incumbent)</small> upon Allah<small> </small>for those who do evil out of ignorance then repent soon after, for those—Allah accepts their repentance. And Allah has always been All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  4,18,"But <small>(granting</small> <small>of)</small> repentance is not for those who <small>(continue to)</small> do evil until, when death arrives to one of them, he says, “Indeed, I have now repented,” nor for those who die as deniers. Those—We have prepared for them a painful punishment."
  4,19,"O you who have attained faith, it is not lawful for you to inherit women forcefully, and do not coerce them in order to go away with some of what you have brought them, unless they commit an <span class="h">evident<sup foot_note="365165">1</sup></span> obscenity. And let your<sup>pl</sup> relationship with them be in accordance with what is fair. And if you dislike them, it may be that you dislike something in which Allah has placed much good.",footnotes:345628:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Shu’ba read it as: “…unless they commit an evidenced obscenity.”</span>
  4,20,"And if you<sup>pl</sup> want to replace one spouse with another spouse and you have given one of them a fortune, then take nothing back of it. Would you take it back <small>(by committing) </small>perjury and evident sin?"
  4,21,"And how can you take it back when you have been intimate with one another and they have taken from you a solid pledge?"
  4,22,"And do not marry women whom your fathers had married, except what has already passed. Indeed, that has been an obscenity and loathsome and an evil way."
  4,23,"Prohibited for you are your mothers and your daughters and your sisters and your paternal aunts and your maternal aunts and your brother's daughters and your sister's daughters and your <small>(foster) </small>mothers who nursed you and your sisters through nursing and your wives' mothers and your stepdaughters who are in your guardianship—born of wives with whom you have consummated marriage, but if you have not consummated marriage with them, then no sin is committed by you—and the lawful consorts of your begotten sons and to combine two sisters <small>(in marriage, simultaneously)</small>, except what has already passed. Indeed, Allah has always been Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  4,24,"And <small>(also prohibited are)</small> women in wedlock, except those whom you<sup>pl</sup> rightfully possess<sup foot_note="365166">1</sup> . <small>(This is)</small> Allah’s decree, binding upon you. But anything beyond these limits has been made lawful for <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="365167">2</sup></span>, provided you seek them in wedlock, not in fornication, with <small>(dowries from)</small> your own wealths. So if you wish to enjoy them, then bring them their rewards—<small>(as) </small>an obligation. And no sin is committed by you if you agree to any change to the dowry after establishing the obligation. Indeed, Allah has always been All-Knowing, All-Wise.",footnotes:345629:Men were not allowed to have intimate relationships with their bondwomen who were taken captive in war—a worldwide ancient common practice—unless they menstruated at least once, to verify that they were not pregnant from their previous husbands before bondage.|345630:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al Kesa’i, Abu Ja’far and Khalaf read it as: “But He has made anything beyond these limits lawful for you.”</span>
  4,25,"But if one of you lacks the means to marry free believing women, then of those whom you rightfully possess from among your believing maidens. And Allah knows better of your faith. You are of one another<sup foot_note="365168">1</sup>, so marry them with the permission of their families<sup foot_note="365169">2</sup> and bring them their rewards in accordance with what is fair, in wedlock, not in fornication nor as mistresses. Then when they are married, if they commit an obscenity<sup foot_note="365170">3</sup>, then their punishment is half that of free women. That is for those of you who want to avoid distress <small>(by falling in sin).</small> But to be patient is better for you. And Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy.",footnotes:345631:Equal.|345632:The guardians were called families.|345633:Adultery.
  4,26,"Allah wants to make things evident to you<sup>pl</sup> and to guide you by the rules <small>(He set)</small> for those before you and to grant you repentance and accept it from you. And Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  4,27,"And Allah wants to grant you repentance and accept it from you, while those who follow desires want you to deviate <small>(with) </small>a great deviation."
  4,28,"Allah wants to lighten <small>(your burden)</small> for you, for man was created weak."
  4,29,"O you who have attained faith, do not devour each other’s wealths illicitly; rather (lawfully), if it should be a <span class="h">bargain<sup foot_note="365171">1</sup></span> by your mutual consent. And do not kill yourselves; indeed, Allah has always been Bestowing of mercy upon you.",footnotes:345634:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…rather (it is lawful) in case there is a bargain by your mutual consent.”</span>
  4,30,"And whoever does that out of hostility and unjustly—We will roast him in a fire, and that has always been easy for Allah<sup foot_note="365172">1</sup> .",footnotes:345635:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.
  4,31,"If you<sup>pl</sup> avoid the major deeds of what you have been forbidden, We remit your <small>(lesser)</small> evil deeds and make you enter in a noble <span class="h">way<sup foot_note="365173">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:345636:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…and enter you into a noble entrance.”</span>
  4,32,"And do not covet whatever Allah has favored some of you with over others. For men is a share of what they have earned, and for women is a share of what they have earned. And ask Allah of his grace. Indeed, Allah has always been All-Knowing of everything."
  4,33,"Thus to everyone We have assigned heirs<sup foot_note="365174">1</sup> for what parents and kinsfolk have left. And those with whom you<sup>pl</sup> have a bond of sworn fidelity—bring them their share. Indeed, Allah has always been Witness over everything.",footnotes:345637:Literally ‘protégés’.
  4,34,"Men should be constant caretakers of women with what Allah has favored one over the other and with what they spend <small>(for support)</small> from their wealths. So righteous women are devout, preservers of <small>(virtue, even regarding)</small> hidden matters, as <span class="h">Allah<sup foot_note="365175">1</sup></span><small>(commanded matters to be) </small>preserved. But those women from whom you<sup>pl</sup> fear disloyalty—admonish them and abandon them in beds and strike them<sup foot_note="365176">2</sup> . But if they obey you, then do not seek any way against them. Indeed, Allah has always been All-High, Supreme.",footnotes:345638:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…as (the religion of) Allah has been preserved.”</span>|345639:Hitting lightly after two phases of non-physical interaction is a sign of seriousness about ending the marriage.
  4,35,"And if you<sup>pl</sup> fear discord between them<sup>dl</sup>, then send a judge from his family and a judge from her family; if they<sup>dl</sup> want reconciliation, Allah will bring about harmony between them. Indeed, Allah has always been All-Knowing, All-Aware."
  4,36,"And worship Allah and do not associate anything with Him, and be good to both parents and to the relative and the orphans and the destitute<sup>pl</sup>, and the neighbor who is a relative and the neighbor who is a stranger, and the companion at your side<sup foot_note="365177">1</sup> and the traveler in need and to those whom you rightfully possess. Indeed, Allah does not love whoever has been a self-admiring boaster:",footnotes:345640:The fellow-traveler.
  4,37,"those<sup foot_note="365178">1</sup> who are miserly and command mankind to miserliness and conceal what Allah has brought them of His grace—and We have prepared for the deniers a demeaning punishment,",footnotes:345641:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  4,38,"and those who spend their wealths for show in front of people and believe neither in Allah nor in the Last Day. And whoever has Satan as a comrade, then how evil is such a comrade!"
  4,39,"And what harm would it have done them, had they believed in Allah and the Last Day and spent out of what Allah had provided them? And Allah has always been All-Knowing about them."
  4,40,"Indeed, Allah does not do an atom's weight of injustice. And if it is a <span class="h">good<sup foot_note="365179">1</sup></span> deed, He multiplies it and gives from Himself a great reward.",footnotes:345642:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…atom's weight of injustice. And if there is a good deed…”</span>
  4,41,"So how will it be when We bring forth a witness from every community and We bring you<sup>sg</sup> forth as a witness over all these?"
  4,42,"On that day, those who denied and disobeyed the Messenger wish that the earth would be leveled with them, for they conceal nothing from Allah."
  4,43,"O you who have attained faith, do not approach prayer while you are drunk so that you may know what you say, nor while you are in a state of major impurity<sup foot_note="365180">1</sup> —unless you are traveling—until you have bathed. And if you are sick or traveling or one of you returns from relieving oneself or you have touched women <small>(in intercourse) </small>and cannot find water, then find clean soil and wipe your faces and your hands with it. Indeed, Allah has always been Pardoning, Oft-Forgiving.",footnotes:345643:A state of major impurity after sexual discharge, requiring a full body wash.
  4,44,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen those who were given a share of the Scripture? They purchase utter misguidance and want you<sup>pl</sup> to stray from the way."
  4,45,"Yet Allah knows better of your<sup>pl</sup> enemies, and sufficient is Allah as an Ally, and sufficient is Allah as a Supporter."
  4,46,"Some of those who have Judaized distort words from their context and say, “We have heard and disobeyed,” and “Listen; may you<sup>sg</sup> not hear,” and "Ra'ina<sup foot_note="365181">1</sup> ”, twisting it with their tongues and thereby slandering the religion. But had they said, “We have heard and obeyed,” and “Listen,” and “Give us your<sup>sg</sup> attention,” it would have been better for them and more upright. But Allah has cursed them for their denial, so they do not believe except for a few.",footnotes:345644:This word means ‘Pay heed to us’ but sounds similar to a Hebrew word that means 'the most evil of us'.
  4,47,"O you who have been brought the Scripture, believe in what We have bestowed from on high, confirming what you have, before We obliterate faces and turn them around upon their backs, or curse them as We cursed the fellows of the Sabbath<sup foot_note="365182">1</sup> . And the command of Allah is bound to be performed.",footnotes:345645:The breakers of the Sabbath.
  4,48,"Indeed, Allah does not forgive associating <small>(any partners)</small> with Him, yet He forgives anything less than that for whomever He wills. And whoever associates anything with Allah has very truly fabricated a great sin."
  4,49,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen those who claim purity for themselves? Rather, Allah purifies whom He wills, and they will not be dealt with unjustly by as much as the thread upon a date-stone."
  4,50,"See<sup>sg</sup> how they fabricate lies against Allah, and that alone suffices as an evident sin."
  4,51,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen those who were given a share of the Scripture? They believe in superstition<sup foot_note="365183">1</sup> and false masters, and say of those who have denied, “These are better guided on the way than the ones who have believed.”",footnotes:345646:The Arabic word is <i>Gypt</i> which may also mean the Gyptana, a book written by ancient Egyptian monks.
  4,52,"Those are the ones whom Allah has cursed; and whomever Allah curses, you will find no supporter for him."
  4,53,"Or do they own a share of the dominion? Then they do not bring to mankind by as much as a groove in a date-stone."
  4,54,"Or do they envy mankind for whatever Allah has brought them of His grace? For surely, We brought Abraham's folk the Scripture and wisdom, and We gave them a great dominion."
  4,55,"Then, of them there were those who attained faith in him, and of them were those who barred from him. And sufficient is Hell as a blaze."
  4,56,"Indeed, those who have denied Our signs—We will roast them in a fire. Every time their skins are roasted through, We will replace them with other skins so that they may <small>(continue to)</small> taste the punishment. Indeed, Allah<sup foot_note="365184">1</sup> has always been Almighty, All-Wise.",footnotes:345647:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.
  4,57,"But those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—We will enter them into Gardens beneath which rivers flow, abiding therein forever; for them in it are cleansed spouses, and We will admit them into an ever-shading shade."
  4,58,"Indeed, Allah commands you<sup>pl</sup> to return trusts back to their owners, and that when you judge between mankind, you judge with justice; indeed, Allah admonishes you with what is excellent. Indeed, Allah has always been All-Hearing, All-Seeing."
  4,59,"O you who have attained faith, obey Allah and obey the Messenger and those in command among you. And if you disagree over anything, refer it to Allah and the Messenger, if you believe in Allah and the Last Day. That is better and fairer in interpretation."
  4,60,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen those who claim that they have believed in what was sent down to you and what was sent down before you, yet they want the judgment of false masters in spite of being commanded to deny it? For Satan wants to make them stray into extreme misguidance."
  4,61,"And when it is said to them, “Come to what Allah has sent down, and to the Messenger,” you see the hypocrites barring<small> (themselves and others) </small>from you<sup>sg</sup> completely."
  4,62,"So how will it be when a calamity befalls them because of what their hands have put forth, then they come to you<sup>sg</sup> swearing by Allah: “We only wanted excelling in doing good and bringing about harmony”?"
  4,63,"Those are the ones whom Allah knows whatever is in their hearts, so disregard them, yet admonish them and say to them words far-reaching to their <small>(inner)</small> selves."
  4,64,"And never did We send any messenger but to be obeyed by Allah’s leave<sup foot_note="365185">1</sup> . And had they—after being unjust to themselves—come to you<sup>sg</sup> and sought Allah's forgiveness, and had the Messenger<sup foot_note="365186">2</sup> prayed for their forgiveness, they would have found Allah Granting and Accepting of repentance, Bestowing of mercy.",footnotes:345648:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.|345649:A grammatical shift from 2<sup><small>nd</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.
  4,65,"But no, by your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, they will never attain faith until they make you judge in their disputes, then find within themselves no discomfort<sup foot_note="365187">1</sup> from whatever you have decreed and submit completely.",footnotes:345650:Literally ‘blame’.
  4,66,"And had We decreed for them: “Kill yourselves,” or “Depart your homes,” they would not have done it, except for a few of them. But had they done what they were admonished, it would have been better for them and a firmer confirmation."
  4,67,"And We would then have brought them from Us a great reward,"
  4,68,"and We would have guided them to a straight path."
  4,69,"And whoever obeys Allah and the Messenger—then those<sup foot_note="365188">1</sup> are with the ones whom Allah has blessed of the prophets and the unwavering believers and the witnesses<sup foot_note="365189">2</sup> and the righteous, and excellent are those as company!",footnotes:345651:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.|345652:The Arabic word used is <i>shuhada’</i>, which literally means ‘witnesses’ and is usually used to describe martyrs.
  4,70,"That is the grace from Allah, and sufficient is Allah as All-Knowing."
  4,71,"O you who have attained faith, take your precautions, then mobilize in groups or mobilize all together."
  4,72,"And indeed, there is among you one who would certainly tarry behind; then, if a calamity befalls you, he would say, “Allah has truly favored me as I was not a witness<sup foot_note="365190">1</sup> with them.”",footnotes:345653:The Arabic word <i>shaheed</i> may mean 'a witness', ‘a martyr’ or ‘present’.
  4,73,"But if some grace from Allah befalls you<sup>pl</sup>, he would say—as if no love existed between you and him—“If only I had been with them, I could have triumphed a great triumph.”"
  4,74,"Let those who sell the Earlier Life in exchange for the Hereafter combat in the cause of Allah. For whoever combats in the way of Allah, then is killed or overcomes, We will bring him a great reward."
  4,75,"And what is the matter with you<sup>pl</sup> that you do not combat in the way of Allah and for the ones deemed weak and oppressed among men and women and children—those who say, “Our Lord, get us out from this town whose people are unjust, and appoint for us from You a guardian, and appoint for us from You a supporter!”?"
  4,76,"Those who have attained faith combat in the way of Allah, while those who have denied combat in the way of false masters. So combat<sup>pl</sup> the allies of Satan; indeed, the plotting of Satan has always been weak."
  4,77,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen those who were told, “Restrain your hands and establish the prayer and bring<sup foot_note="365191">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="365192">2</sup> ”? But when combat was prescribed for them, a group of them feared mankind as only Allah ought to be feared, or even more. And they said, “Our Lord, why did You prescribe combat for us? If only You would delay it for us for a short while.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “The enjoyment of the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> is little, while the Hereafter is better for whoever is mindful <small>(of God)</small>; and <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="365193">3</sup></span> will not be dealt with unjustly by as much as the thread upon a date-stone.”",footnotes:345654:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|345655:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.|345656:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Hamza, Al Kesa’i, Abu Ja’far, Khalaf and Rouh read it as: “…and they will not be dealt with unjustly….”</span>
  4,78,"Wherever you<sup>pl</sup> may be, death will overtake you, even if you were in lofty towers. And if any good befalls them, they say, “This is from Allah.” But when any evil befalls them, they say, “This is from you.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “All is from Allah.” So what is wrong with these people, that they hardly comprehend any discourse?"
  4,79,"Whatever good has befallen you<sup>sg</sup> is from Allah, and whatever evil has befallen you is from your own <small>(inner) </small>self. And We sent you to mankind as a messenger, and sufficient is Allah as a Witness."
  4,80,"Whoever obeys the Messenger has surely obeyed Allah, but whoever turns away—then We have not sent you to be a constant preserver over them."
  4,81,"And they say <small>"(We pledge) </small>obedience," but when they leave your presence, a faction of them conspire<sup foot_note="365194">1</sup> something contrary to what you say, yet Allah records what they conspire. So disregard them and place your trust in Allah, for sufficient is Allah as a Trustee.",footnotes:345657:Literally ‘plan by night’.
  4,82,"Do they not ponder the Recital<sup foot_note="365195">1</sup> ? For had it been from any other than Allah, they would have found in it much discrepancy.",footnotes:345658:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  4,83,"And when a matter of security or fear comes to them, they publicize it. But had they referred it to the Messenger and to those in command among them, those who can draw conclusions from it would have learned it. And were it not for Allah’s blessing and mercy upon you<sup>pl</sup>, you<sup foot_note="365196">1</sup> would have followed Satan, except for a few.",footnotes:345659:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 2<sup><small>nd</small></sup> person.
  4,84,"So combat<sup>sg</sup> in the way of Allah; you are not responsible except for yourself. And urge the believers. Hopefully Allah will restrain the force of those who have denied, and Allah is of more intense force and more tormenting."
  4,85,"Whoever intercedes for a good cause shall have a portion of it, and whoever intercedes for an evil cause shall have a share of it. And Allah has always been a Sustainer for everything."
  4,86,"And if you<sup>pl</sup> are greeted with a greeting, then respond with a better one or <small>(at least)</small> return it. Indeed, Allah has always been a Reckoner of everything."
  4,87,"Allah—there is no god except He. He will surely gather you<sup>pl</sup> to the Day of Resurrection about which there is no doubt. And who is truer in discourse than Allah?"
  4,88,"So what is the matter with you, that you are divided into two groups regarding the hypocrites, when Allah Himself has caused them to regress on account of what they have earned? Do you want to guide those whom Allah has misguided? For whomever Allah misguides, you<sup>sg</sup> will never find for him any way<sup foot_note="365197">1</sup> .",footnotes:345660:God misguides kinds of people like the treacherous, the evildoers, the oppressors, etc.
  4,89,"They would love to see you<sup>pl</sup> deny just as they themselves have denied, so that you would become equal. So take no allies from them until they emigrate in the way of Allah. But if they turn away, then seize them and kill them wherever you may find them, and do not take from among them any ally or supporter."
  4,90,"Except those who are related to a people between you<sup>pl</sup> and whom is a pledge, or those who come to you with their hearts constrained from combating you or combating their own people. And had Allah willed, He would have given them authority over you and they would surely have combated you. So if they withdraw from you<sup>pl</sup> and combat not against you and offer you peace, then Allah has opened no way for you against them."
  4,91,"You<sup>pl</sup> will find others who want to be secure from you and secure from their own people—whenever they are turned back to temptation, they are made to regress in it. So if they do not withdraw from you and offer you peace and restrain their hands, then seize them and kill them wherever you find them. And those ones—We have given you, regarding them, an evident authorization."
  4,92,"But never should a believer kill another believer, unless accidentally. Yet anyone who accidentally kills a believer, then the <small>(atonement is the)</small> emancipation of a believing slave<sup foot_note="365198">1</sup> and a compensation submitted to his family, unless they donate<sup foot_note="365199">2</sup> <small>(it)</small>. But if he was from a people who are an enemy to you<sup>pl</sup>, yet he is a believer, then the emancipation of a believing slave<sup foot_note="365200">3</sup> . And if he was from a people between you and whom there is a pledge, then a compensation submitted to his family and the emancipation of a believing slave<sup foot_note="365201">4</sup> . And <small>(for) </small>anyone who lacks the means—then the fasting of two consecutive months as a repentance to Allah. And Allah has always been All-Knowing, All-Wise.",footnotes:345661:Literally 'a neck'.|345662:Unless they waive it as charity.|345663:Literally ‘a neck’.|345664:Literally ‘a neck’.
  4,93,"But whoever kills a believer intentionally—then his repayment is Hell, abiding therein, and upon him is Allah’s wrath and He has cursed him and has prepared for him a great punishment."
  4,94,"O you who have attained faith, when you travel <small>(to strive) </small>in the way of Allah, then you shall <span class="h">investigate<sup foot_note="365202">1</sup></span><small>.</small> And do not say to anyone who offers you<sup foot_note="365203">2</sup> <span class="h">peace<sup foot_note="365204">3</sup></span>, “You are not a <span class="h">believer<sup foot_note="365205">4</sup></span>,” aspiring for the goods of the Earlier Life, for with Allah is a multitude of gains<sup foot_note="365206">5</sup> . You yourselves were like this before, then Allah bestowed favor upon you, so ascertain <small>(the truth).</small> Indeed, Allah has always been All-Aware of what you do.",footnotes:345665:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…then you shall ascertain (the truth).”</span>|345666:This means greeting with the salutation of peace by saying: ‘Peace be upon you.’”|345667:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer, Hamza, Abu Ja’far and Khalaf read it as: “And do not say to anyone who offers to surrender to you, “You are not…”</span>|345668:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Wardan read it as: “You are not granted security,”</span>|345669:The same word, <i>maghanem,</i> is used for ‘spoils of war’.
  4,95,"Those of the believers who, though <span class="h">not<sup foot_note="365207">1</sup></span> disabled, stay behind, are not equal to those who strive in the way of Allah with their wealths and their lives<sup foot_note="365208">2</sup> . Allah has favored those who strive with their wealths and their lives above those who stay behind with a degree<small> (of rank)</small>. But Allah has promised goodness to both. Yet Allah has favored those who strive over those who stay behind with a great reward:",footnotes:345670:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Asem, Hamza and Ya’qub read it as: “Those of the believers—except for the disabled—who stay behind are…”</span>|345671:Literally ‘selves’.
  4,96,"<small>)high(</small> degrees <small>(of rank)</small> from Him, and forgiveness and mercy, for Allah has always been Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  4,97,"Indeed, <small>(regarding)</small> those whom the angels took up at death while they were unjust to themselves, they<sup foot_note="365209">1</sup> said, “What was the matter with you?” They said, “We were deemed weak and oppressed in the land.” They said, “Was Allah’s earth not vast enough for you to emigrate therein?” So those—their shelter is Hell, and what an evil destiny!",footnotes:345672:The angels.
  4,98,"Except for those deemed weak and oppressed among men and women and children who cannot devise any plan and are not guided to any way,"
  4,99,"for those—hopefully Allah will pardon them, for Allah has always been Pardoning, Oft-Forgiving."
  4,100,"Thus anyone who emigrates in the way of Allah will find on earth many places of refuge and abundance. And anyone who sets out from his house, emigrating to Allah and His Messenger, and is then overtaken by death, then his reward is incumbent on Allah. And Allah has always been Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  4,101,"And when you<sup>pl</sup> travel in the land, you commit no sin by shortening the prayers if you fear that the deniers may harm you; indeed, the deniers have always been an evident enemy to you."
  4,102,"And when you<sup>sg</sup> are among them and you call them to prayer, let a faction of them stand with you and let them hold their weapons. Then when they have done their prostrations, let them be behind you<sup>pl</sup> and let another faction that has not prayed yet come forward and pray with you<sup>sg</sup>, and let them take their precautions and their weapons. Those who denied would love that youpl become oblivious to your weapons and your belongings so they can assault you in a single assault. And no sin is committed by you—if you are hurt by rain or are sick—by putting down your weapons, but take precautions. Indeed, Allah has prepared for the deniers a demeaning punishment."
  4,103,"So when you<sup>pl</sup> have concluded the prayer, then remember Allah, standing and sitting and on your sides. Thereafter, when you feel secure, establish the prayer. Indeed, the prayer has been prescribed upon believers at specific times."
  4,104,"And do not waver<sup>pl</sup> in the pursuit of the people<sup foot_note="365210">1</sup> ; if you suffer pain, they suffer pain as you suffer pain, but you expect from Allah what they do not expect. And Allah has always been All-Knowing, All-Wise.",footnotes:345673:The enemy.
  4,105,"Indeed, We have sent down to you<sup>sg</sup> the Scripture with the truth, to judge between mankind in accordance with what Allah has shown you. And do not be an advocate for the treacherous."
  4,106,"And ask<sup>sg</sup> Allah for forgiveness; indeed, Allah has always been Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  4,107,"And do<sup>sg</sup> not argue on behalf of those who betray themselves. Indeed, Allah does not love whoever has been consistently treacherous, sinful."
  4,108,"They seek to hide from mankind, but they do not seek to hide from Allah<sup foot_note="365211">1</sup>, and He is with them when they conspire<sup foot_note="365212">2</sup>, <small>(using) </small>what He does not accept of speech. And Allah has always been All-Encompassing of what they do.",footnotes:345674:They feel ashamed so they seek to hide their sins from people, but they do not feel ashamed in front of Allah.|345675:Literally ‘plan by night’.
  4,109,"There you<sup>pl</sup> are, having argued on their behalf in the Earlier Life, but who will argue with Allah on their behalf on the Day of Resurrection? Or who will be their trustee?"
  4,110,"Yet whoever commits evil or does injustice to himself then asks Allah for forgiveness will find Allah Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  4,111,"And whoever earns a sin—he only earns it to his own detriment, for Allah has always been All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  4,112,"And whoever earns an offense or a sin then blames it on an innocent person, then he has surely burdened himself with perjury and evident sin."
  4,113,"And were it not for Allah’s grace towards you<sup>sg</sup>, and His mercy, a faction of them would have sought to lead you astray. But they lead no one astray except themselves, and they cannot harm you in any way. And Allah has sent down to you the Scripture and wisdom, and has taught you what you did not know. And Allah’s grace towards you has always been great."
  4,114,"There is no good in much of their private conversations, except for one who commands to <small>(even a single) </small>donation or to what is fair or to reconciliation between people. And whoever does that, seeking Allah’s pleasure, then We<sup foot_note="365213">1</sup> will <span class="h">bring<sup foot_note="365214">2</sup></span> him a great reward.",footnotes:345676:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.|345677:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr, Hamza and Khalaf read it as: “…then He will bring him…” (In this case there is no grammatical shift.)</span>
  4,115,"But whoever opposes the Messenger after guidance has become evident to him and follows other than the way of the believers, We will turn him towards what he has turned to and roast him in Hell—and what an evil destiny!"
  4,116,"Indeed, Allah does not forgive associating <small>(any partners)</small> with Him, yet He forgives anything less than that for whomever He wills. And whoever associates<small> (others) </small>with Allah, then he has surely strayed into extreme misguidance."
  4,117,"They call upon, instead of Him, only females. <small>(In fact)</small> they call upon nothing but a defiant Satan—"
  4,118,"Allah has cursed him. And he said, “I will most surely take to myself a due share of Your servants.”"
  4,119,"“And I will most surely lead them astray and fill them with fancies, and I will most surely command them so they will most surely slit the ears of cattle, and most surely I will command them so they will most surely alter the creation of Allah.” Thus, whoever takes Satan for a guardian apart from Allah has truly lost an evident loss."
  4,120,"He promises them and fills them with fancies, but Satan promises them nothing but a deception."
  4,121,"Those—their shelter is Hell, and they find no escape from it."
  4,122,"But those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—We will enter them into Gardens beneath which rivers flow, abiding therein forever; the promise of Allah<sup foot_note="365215">1</sup> is true, and whose word is more truthful than Allah?",footnotes:345678:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.
  4,123,"It is not according to your fancies, nor to the fancies of the People of the Scripture. Whoever does evil will be repaid for it and will not find for himself apart from Allah any ally or supporter."
  4,124,"But whoever does of righteous deeds, whether male or female, and is a believer—those<sup foot_note="365216">1</sup> will <span class="h">enter<sup foot_note="365217">2</sup></span> the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> and will not be dealt with unjustly by as much as the dint on a date-stone.",footnotes:345679:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.|345680:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Shu’ba, Abu Ja’far and Rouh read it as: “…those will be entered into the Garden…”</span>
  4,125,"And who could be better in religion than one who submitted his countenance to Allah, while excelling in doing good, and followed the creed of Abraham who turned away from all that is false. For Allah took Abraham for a close friend."
  4,126,"And to Allah belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth, and Allah has always been All-Encompassing of everything."
  4,127,"They ask you for a ruling about women. Say, “Allah gives you a ruling about them, and <small>(so does)</small> what is read to you in the Scripture about orphan women<sup foot_note="365218">1</sup> to whom you do not bring what is prescribed for them, yet you wish to marry them, and <small>(about) </small>those deemed weak and oppressed from among children and that you should treat orphans justly. And whatever good you do—indeed, Allah has always been All-Knowing of it.”",footnotes:345681:It may also mean women who have orphaned children.
  4,128,"And if a woman fears disloyalty or disregard from her husband, then no sin is committed by them if they <span class="h">reform<sup foot_note="365219">1</sup></span> what is between themselves<sup foot_note="365220">2</sup>, for reconciliation is better. Yet stinginess has been brought to the <small>(inner)</small> selves. But if you<sup>pl</sup> excel in doing good and become mindful <small>(of God)</small>—indeed, Allah has always been All-Aware of what you do.",footnotes:345682:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…if they reconcile between themselves…”</span>|345683:Literally, 'if they reconcile a reconciliation'.
  4,129,"Furthermore, you<sup>pl</sup> will not be able to be equitable between the women<sup foot_note="365221">1</sup> no matter how keen you are, so do not be so biased as to leave her suspended. Rather, if you reform and become mindful <small>(of God)</small>—indeed, Allah has always been Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy.",footnotes:345684:Wives.
  4,130,"Yet if they both separate, Allah will enrich each from His vast means<sup foot_note="365222">1</sup>, for Allah has always been All-Embracing, All-Wise.",footnotes:345685:Literally ‘embracement’.
  4,131,"And to Allah belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth. And very truly We have admonished those who were brought the Scripture before you, as well as yourselves, “Be mindful of Allah<sup foot_note="365223">1</sup> . But if you deny—then to Allah belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth, and Allah has always been Self-Sufficient, Praiseworthy.”",footnotes:345686:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.
  4,132,"And to Allah belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth. And sufficient is Allah as a Trustee."
  4,133,"If He wills, He can do away with you, O mankind, and bring others. For Allah has always been All-Able to do that."
  4,134,"Whoever wants the recompense of the Earlier <small>(Life)</small>—with Allah is the recompense of the Earlier <small>(Life) </small>and the Hereafter. And Allah has always been All-Hearing, All-Seeing."
  4,135,"O you who have attained faith, always stand for justice, as witnesses for the sake of Allah, even if against yourselves or your parents or your close relatives. Whether a person is rich or poor, Allah is worthier as a patron of both. So do not follow prejudice<sup foot_note="365224">1</sup> so as to do justice. But if you twist<small> (your <span class="h">testimony)</span></small><sup foot_note="365225">2</sup> or disregard <small>(giving it)</small>—then indeed Allah has always been All-Aware of what you do.",footnotes:345687:Literally, ‘whim’.|345688:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Hamza read it as: “But whether you go forward (by testifying) or disregard…”</span>
  4,136,"O you who have attained faith, have faith in Allah and His Messenger and the Scripture which He <span class="h">bestowed<sup foot_note="365226">1</sup></span> upon His Messenger from on high and the Scripture He sent down before. And whoever denies Allah and His angels and His books and His messengers and the Last Day, then he has surely strayed into extreme misguidance.",footnotes:345689:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ibn Amer read it as: “…and the Scripture which was bestowed upon…”</span>
  4,137,"Indeed, those who attained faith then denied, then attained faith then denied, then increased in denial—never is Allah to forgive them nor guide them to a way."
  4,138,"Give<sup>sg</sup> glad tidings<sup foot_note="365227">1</sup> to the hypocrites that they will have a painful punishment—",footnotes:345690:This is said in sarcasm.
  4,139,"those who take the deniers as allies apart from the believers. Do they seek might from them? For indeed, all might belongs to Allah."
  4,140,"For He has surely <span class="h">bestowed<sup foot_note="365228">1</sup></span> upon you<sup>pl</sup> from on high, in the Scripture, that when you hear Allah’s signs being denied or ridiculed, then do not sit with them until they engage in some other discourse; you would then be like them. Indeed, Allah will gather the hypocrites and the deniers in Hell, all together—",footnotes:345691:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem and Ya’qub read it as: “For it has surely been bestowed upon you….”</span>
  4,141,"those who lie in wait for you<sup>pl</sup>, so if there is a conquest for you from Allah, they say, “Were we not with you?” While if the deniers have any measure <small>(of success)</small>, they say, “Did we not have privilege over you and defend you from the believers?” Then Allah will judge between you on the Day of Resurrection. And Allah will never grant any way for the deniers against the believers."
  4,142,"Indeed, the hypocrites try to deceive Allah, while He deceives them. And when they rise for prayer they rise lazily, for show in front of mankind. And they do not remember Allah except a little,"
  4,143,"wavering in between, neither with these nor with these. For whomever Allah leads astray—then you<sup>sg</sup> will not find any way for him."
  4,144,"O you who have attained faith, do not take the deniers as allies apart from the believers. Do you want to give Allah evident proof against you?"
  4,145,"Indeed, the hypocrites are in the lowest level of the Fire, and you<sup>sg</sup> will not find any supporter for them—"
  4,146,"except those who repented and reformed and held fast to Allah and dedicated their religion faithfully to Allah, for those are with the believers, and Allah will bring the believers a great reward."
  4,147,"What would Allah do with your<sup>pl</sup> punishment if you have given thanks and have attained faith, when Allah has always been Thankful, All-Knowing?"
  4,148,"Allah does not like the public uttering of offensive words unless someone has been dealt with unjustly, for Allah has always been All-Hearing, All-Knowing."
  4,149,"Whether you<sup>pl</sup> disclose something good or hide it or pardon something bad—Allah has always been Pardoning, All-Able."
  4,150,"Indeed, those who deny Allah and His messengers, and want to make a distinction between Allah and His messengers, and say, “We believe in some and deny some,” and want to take a way in between—"
  4,151,"it is those who are truly the deniers, and We have prepared for the deniers a demeaning punishment."
  4,152,"But those who have attained faith in Allah and His messengers and have made no distinction between any of them—those, <span class="h">He<sup foot_note="365229">1</sup></span> will bring them their rewards. For Allah has always been Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy.",footnotes:345692:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as: “We will bring them…”</span>
  4,153,"The People of the Scripture ask you<sup>sg</sup> to <span class="h">bestow<sup foot_note="365230">1</sup></span> upon them a scripture from heaven. For truly, they had asked Moses for something even greater than that, for they said, “Show us Allah openly.” So the thunderbolt took them on account of their injustice. Then they took the calf for worship after the evident proofs had come to them, yet We pardoned that, and We brought Moses evident authority.",footnotes:345693:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…to send down upon them…”</span>
  4,154,"And We raised Mount Tûr above them in accordance with their pledge, and We said to them, “Enter the gate prostrating,” and We said to them, “Do not transgress the Sabbath”, and We took from them a solid pledge."
  4,155,"But for their violation of their pledge, and their denial of Allah’s signs, and their unjustified killing of the prophets, and their saying, “Our hearts are wrapped,”…<sup foot_note="365231">1</sup> Rather, Allah put a seal upon them on account of their denial, so they do not believe, except for a few.",footnotes:345694:<big>This sentence is left open-ended; according to some exegetes its predicate is “We forbade them good things that used to be lawful for them.” in sign 160.</big>
  4,156,"And on account of their denial and their saying against Mary a great slander,"
  4,157,"and their saying, “We have surely killed the Messiah, Jesus, son of Mary, the Messenger of Allah.”… In fact, they did not kill him, nor did they crucify him, but it appeared to them as if they had. And indeed, those who differed over him are in doubt about it. They have no knowledge of it—just following assumptions. And certainly, they did not kill him."
  4,158,"Rather, Allah raised him up to Himself, for Allah has always been Almighty, All-Wise."
  4,159,"Surely, there is none from the People of the Scripture but will believe in him<sup foot_note="365232">1</sup> before his death, and on the Day of Resurrection he will be a witness against them.",footnotes:345695:Jesus.
  4,160,"So on account of the injustice on the part of the ones who have Judaized We forbade them good things that used to be lawful for them, and on account of barring a lot from the way of Allah,"
  4,161,"and their taking of usury—though they were forbidden it—and their devouring of people's wealths illicitly. And We have prepared for the deniers among them a painful punishment."
  4,162,"But those of them who are firmly rooted in knowledge, and the believers, believe in what was sent down to you<sup>sg</sup> and in what was sent down before you. And those who establish the prayers, and those who bring<sup foot_note="365233">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="365234">2</sup>, and the believers in Allah and the Last Day—those, <span class="h">We<sup foot_note="365235">3</sup></span> will bring them a great reward.",footnotes:345696:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|345697:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.|345698:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Khalaf read it as: “He will bring them a great reward.”</span>
  4,163,"Indeed, We have revealed to you as We revealed to Noah and the prophets after him. And We revealed to Abraham and Ishmael and Isaac and Jacob and the Grandsons<sup foot_note="365236">1</sup> and Jesus and Job and Jonah and Aaron and Solomon, and We brought David a Book.",footnotes:345699:The different prophets of the Israelites.
  4,164,"And messengers <small>(the stories of)</small> whom We have already narrated to you<sup>sg</sup> and messengers <small>(the stories of)</small> whom We have not narrated to you. And Allah spoke to Moses with <small>(direct)</small> speech."
  4,165,"Messengers—bearing glad tidings and forewarning, that mankind may have no excuse before Allah after the <small>(coming of the) </small>messengers, for Allah has always been Almighty, All-Wise."
  4,166,"But Allah bears witness to what He sent down to you; He sent it down with His knowledge, and the angels bear witness, though Allah suffices as a witness."
  4,167,"Surely those who have denied and barred from the way of Allah have truly strayed into extreme misguidance."
  4,168,"Surely those who have denied and have done injustice—indeed, Allah is not to forgive them, nor is He to guide them to any road"
  4,169,"except the road to Hell, abiding therein forever. And that has always been easy for Allah."
  4,170,"O mankind, the Messenger has truly come to you with the truth from your Lord, so believe—that is better for you. But if you deny, then to Allah belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth, for Allah has always been All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  4,171,"O People of the Scripture, do not exaggerate in your religion, and do not say about Allah except the truth. The Messiah, Jesus, son of Mary, is indeed nothing but Allah's Messenger and His Word that He cast to Mary, and a Spirit from Him. So believe in Allah and His messengers, and do not say, “Three.” Refrain—<small>(that is) </small>better for you. Indeed, Allah is only one God; Highly Exalted is He—that He should have a son! To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth. And Allah suffices as a Trustee."
  4,172,"Never shall the Messiah disdain to be a servant of Allah, nor shall the angels who are brought near. And whoever disdains His worship and acts arrogantly—He will herd them to Himself, all together."
  4,173,"But as for those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds, He will render them their rewards in full and increase His grace for them. But as for those who were disdainful and acted arrogantly, He will punish them with a painful punishment, and they will find for themselves, apart from Allah, neither ally nor supporter."
  4,174,"O mankind, a proof has come to you from your Lord, and We<sup foot_note="365237">1</sup> have sent down to you an evident light.",footnotes:345700:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup>person.
  4,175,"So as for those who have attained faith in Allah and have held fast to Him, He will enter them into mercy from Him, and grace, and will guide them to Himself on a straight path."
  4,176,"They ask you<sup>sg</sup> for a ruling. Say, “Allah gives you a ruling concerning the person who has non-lineal heirs.” If a man dies and leaves no children and he has a sister, then for her is one-half of what he has left. And he inherits from her if she has no children. But if they are two <small>(sisters)</small>, then for them are two-thirds of what he has left. Yet if the siblings are men and women, then for the male is the share of two females.” Allah makes things evident for you, lest you<sup>pl</sup> go astray. For Allah is All-Knowing of everything."
  5,1,"O you who have attained faith, fulfil your contracts. Livestock animals have been made lawful to you except whatever is recited to you, provided that you do not make game-hunting lawful while you are consecrating yourselves to pilgrimage. Indeed, Allah decrees whatever He wants."
  5,2,"O you who have attained faith, do not violate Allah’s rites, nor the inviolable month, nor the offerings, nor the garlanded, nor those heading for the Inviolable House seeking grace and good pleasure from their Lord. And when you have left the pilgrim sanctity, then hunt. And let not the <span class="h">hatred<sup foot_note="366151">1</sup></span> of any people incite you to transgress because they <span class="h">barred<sup foot_note="366152">2</sup></span> you from the Inviolable Mosque. And cooperate with one another in showing virtue and mindfulness <small>(of God)</small>, and do not cooperate with one another in sin and hostility. And be mindful of Allah; indeed, Allah is stern in retribution.",footnotes:346614:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer, Shu’ba and Abu Ja’far read it as: “And let not any hating people incite…”</span>|346615:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “…to transgress if they bar you from the Inviolable Mosque.”</span>
  5,3,"Prohibited for you<sup>pl</sup> are carrion and blood and the flesh of swine, and what was dedicated to other than Allah, and the strangled and the beaten <small>(to death)</small> and the toppled <small>(to death)</small> and the gored <small>(to death)</small> and the <small>(partly)</small> eaten by a wild animal—except what you <small>(are able to)</small> slaughter <small>(before its death)</small>—and what was sacrificed on altars, and that you determine shares through divination. All that is grave disobedience. Today, those who have denied have despaired of your religion, so do not fear them but fear Me. Today I have perfected your religion for you and have completed My blessings upon you, and I have approved Islam as a religion for you. But whoever is compelled by starvation, with no intent to sin, then indeed, Allah is Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  5,4,"They ask you<sup>sg</sup> what is made lawful for them. Say, “All good things have been made lawful for you<sup>pl</sup>, and such hunting creatures as you teach, training them as hounds.” You train them according to what Allah has taught you, so eat from what they have caught for you and pronounce Allah’s name over it, and be mindful of Allah; indeed, Allah is Swift in reckoning."
  5,5,"Today all good things have been made lawful for you<sup>pl</sup> and the food of the People of the Scripture is lawful for you and your food is lawful for them. And <small>(lawful are)</small> believing women whose chastity is guarded, and women from the people who were brought the Scripture before you whose chastity is guarded—provided you give them their rewards in wedlock, not in fornication nor as mistresses. For whoever denies faith, then surely his work has been nullified, and in the Hereafter he is one of the losers."
  5,6,"O you who have attained faith, when you rise for prayer, wash your faces and your hands up to the elbows, and wipe your heads <span class="h">and<sup foot_note="366153">1</sup></span><small>(wash)</small> your feet to the ankles. But if you are in a state of major impurity<sup foot_note="366154">2</sup>, then cleanse yourselves. But if you are ill or traveling or one of you returns from relieving himself or you have touched women <small>(in intercourse)</small> and cannot find water, then seek clean soil and wipe over your faces and hands with it. Allah does not want to cause you discomfort; rather He wants to cleanse you and to complete His blessing upon you, that you may give thanks.",footnotes:346616:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Amer, Hafs, Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “…wash your faces and your hands up to the elbows, and wipe your heads and your feet to the ankles.”</span>|346617:A state of impurity after sexual discharge, requiring full body wash.
  5,7,"And remember Allah’s blessing upon you<sup>pl</sup> and His pledge which He pledged you with, when you said, “We have heard and obeyed.” And be mindful of Allah; indeed, Allah is All-Knowing of what lies within the chests."
  5,8,"O you who have attained faith, stand firmly for Allah <small>(as)</small> just witnesses, and let not the <span class="h">hatred<sup foot_note="366155">1</sup></span> of any people provoke you to be unjust. Be just—that is nearer to mindfulness <small>(of God)</small>. And be mindful of Allah; indeed, Allah is All-Aware of all that you do.",footnotes:346618:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer, Shu’ba and Abu Ja’far read it as: “… and let not any hating people…”</span>
  5,9,"Allah has promised those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds: for them is forgiveness and a great reward."
  5,10,"And those who have denied and disbelieved in Our signs—those are the fellows of purgatory."
  5,11,"O you who have attained faith, recall Allah's blessing upon you when some people advanced to extend their hands against you, so He restrained their hands from you. So be mindful of Allah. And in Allah let the believers place their trust."
  5,12,"And most surely Allah took the pledge of the Children of Israel, and We<sup foot_note="366156">1</sup> delegated from among them twelve leaders. And Allah said, “I am indeed with you; if you establish the prayer and bring<sup foot_note="366157">2</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="366158">3</sup> and believe in My messengers and rally to them and lend Allah a good loan, I will most surely remit your evil deeds and most surely enter you into Gardens beneath which rivers flow. But whoever of you denies afterwards, then he has certainly strayed from the right way.”",footnotes:346619:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 1 person to 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.|346620:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|346621:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  5,13,"So on account of their violation of their covenant We cursed them and made their hearts <span class="h">hard<sup foot_note="366159">1</sup></span>, <small>(for)</small> twisting the words out of their contexts, and they forgot some of what they were reminded of. And you<sup>sg</sup> will continue to view treachery on their part except for a few of them, so pardon them and overlook. Indeed, Allah loves those who excel in doing good.",footnotes:346622:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…their hearts fake,” or “…their hearts very hard,” as the way they pronounced the Arabic word <i>qaseyah</i> may mean “very hard” or “fake”.</span>
  5,14,"And from those who have said, “We are Christians,” We took their pledge. But they forgot some of what they were reminded of, so We provoked enmity and hatred among them until the Day of Resurrection, when Allah<sup foot_note="366160">1</sup> will inform them of what they used to do.",footnotes:346623:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  5,15,"O People of the Scripture, Our Messenger has come to you, clarifying for you much of what you kept hidden of the Scripture and overlooking much. A light from Allah<sup foot_note="366161">1</sup> has surely come to you, and an Evident Scripture",footnotes:346624:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  5,16,"with which Allah guides whoever has followed—<small>(for)</small> His good pleasure—<small>(to)</small> the ways of peace, and brings them out of darkness<small>(es)</small> into light, by His permission, and guides them to a straight path."
  5,17,"Most surely, those who said, "Allah is the Christ, son of Mary," have denied <small>(faith)</small>. Say<sup>sg</sup>, "So who could have prevented Allah, had He wanted to annihilate the Christ, son of Mary, and his mother and everyone on earth?” For to Allah belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth and whatever is between them. He creates whatever He wills, for Allah is All-Powerful over everything."
  5,18,"Moreover, the Jews and the Christians said, “We are the children of Allah and are His beloved.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Why then does He punish you for your misdeeds?” Rather, you are but human beings from among those He created. He forgives whom He wills, and He punishes whom He wills, for to Allah belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth and what lies between them, and to Him is the destiny."
  5,19,"O People of the Scripture, Our Messenger has surely come to you, making things clear to you—after a cessation of sending messengers—so that you cannot say, “Neither a herald of glad tidings nor a warner has come to us.” In fact, a herald of glad tidings and a warner has come to you, for Allah is All-Powerful over everything."
  5,20,"And recall when Moses said to his people, “O my people, remember Allah’s blessing upon you when He made among you prophets and made you kings and brought you what He never brought anyone <small>(else)</small> in all communities.”"
  5,21,"“O my people, enter the Holy Land which Allah has prescribed for you, and do not turn on your heels lest you return as losers.”"
  5,22,"They said, “O Moses, there are certainly tyrannical people in it, and we will certainly not enter it until they depart it. So if they depart it, we will then surely enter.”"
  5,23,"Two men of those who fear <small>(God)</small>—on whom Allah had bestowed His blessings—said, “Enter upon them by the gate, for as soon as you have entered it, you are then indeed overcomers. And place your trust in Allah if you are believers.”"
  5,24,"They said, “O Moses, we will certainly not enter it, ever, as long as they are in it. So go ahead, you and your Lord, and combat. We are surely staying behind right here.”"
  5,25,"He said, “My Lord, I have control only over myself and my brother, so separate between us and the defiantly disobedient people.”"
  5,26,"He said, “Then surely, it is forbidden for them for forty years as they wander through the land, so do not grieve over the defiantly disobedient people.”"
  5,27,"And read<sup>sg</sup> to them the true story of Adam's two sons: when they offered an offering, so it was accepted from one of them but was not accepted from the other. He said, “Most surely I will kill you.” He said, “Indeed, Allah accepts only from the ones who are mindful <small>(of Him)</small>."
  5,28,"If you do stretch your hand towards me to kill me, never will I stretch my hand towards you to kill you; indeed, I fear Allah, Lord of all realms."
  5,29,"Indeed, I want you to bear my sin and your sin and thus become one of the fellows of the Fire, for such is the repayment for the unjust.”"
  5,30,"Then His <small>(inner)</small> self prompted him to kill his brother, so he killed him and <small>(thus)</small> became one of the losers."
  5,31,"Then Allah sent a raven scratching up the ground to show him how to cover his brother's corpse. He said, “Woe to me! Was I incapable of being like this raven and burying my brother's corpse?” And he became of the regretful."
  5,32,"Because of that We prescribed for the Children of Israel that whoever kills a <small>(human)</small> self—unless it is for <small>(murder of)</small> another self or corruption in the land—it is as if he has killed mankind, all together. And whoever gives life to it, it is as if he has given life to mankind, all together. And most surely Our messengers came to them with evident proofs, but very truly after that, many of them are<sup foot_note="366162">1</sup> extremists.",footnotes:346625:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense.
  5,33,"Indeed, the punishment for those who fight Allah and His Messenger and rush about in the land spreading corruption is that they be relentlessly killed or crucified or have their hands and feet cut off on opposite sides or be banished from the land. That is a disgrace for them in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small>, and for them in the Hereafter is a great punishment—"
  5,34,"except for those who have repented before you<sup>pl</sup> apprehend them. So know that Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  5,35,"O you who have attained faith, be mindful of Allah and seek the means of approach to Him and strive in His way, that you may succeed."
  5,36,"As for those who have denied—even if they own whatever is in the earth, all of it, and the like of it with it to ransom themselves with it from the punishment of the Day of Resurrection, it would not be accepted from them, and for them is a painful punishment."
  5,37,"They want<sup foot_note="366163">1</sup> to depart the Fire, but in no way are they to depart it, and for them is a perpetual punishment.",footnotes:346626:A grammatical shift to present tense, which serves to create a vivid portrait of future events.
  5,38,"And the male thief and the female thief: cut<sup>pl</sup> their hands as a repayment for what they have earned—a deterrent from Allah, for Allah is Almighty, All-Wise."
  5,39,"But whoever has repented after his injustice and has reformed, then indeed, Allah accepts his repentance. Indeed, Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  5,40,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not come to know that to Allah belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth? He punishes whom He wills, and He forgives whom He wills, for Allah is All-Powerful over everything."
  5,41,"O Messenger, do not be saddened by those who hasten towards denial from among those who said with their mouths, “We believe," but whose hearts have not attained faith, and of the ones who have Judaized—they are constant listeners to lies; they are constant listeners to other people who have not come to you; they distort the words out of their context, saying, “If you<sup>pl</sup> are given this, then take it; but if you are not given it, then beware.” And whomever Allah wants to put to trial, you<sup>sg</sup> will be powerless against Allah on his behalf. Those are the ones whose hearts Allah did not want to cleanse. For them is disgrace in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small>, and for them is a great punishment in the Hereafter."
  5,42,"They are constant listeners to lies; they are constant devourers of illicit earnings. So if they come to you<sup>sg</sup>, then judge between them or disregard them. And if you disregard them, then they will not harm you in any way. Yet if you judge, then judge between them justly. Indeed, Allah loves the just<sup>pl</sup>."
  5,43,"But how do they come to you<sup>sg</sup> for judgment when they have the Torah, in which is Allah’s judgment? Yet they turn away after that. And in no way are those believers."
  5,44,"Indeed, We sent down the Torah, wherein is guidance and light by which the prophets who submitted<sup foot_note="366164">1</sup> themselves <small>(to God)</small> judged those who Judaized, and <small>(so did)</small> the Godly<sup foot_note="366165">2</sup> <small>(scholars)</small> and the rabbis, as they were required to preserve Allah’s Scripture and were witnesses to it. So do<sup>pl</sup> not fear mankind, but fear Me. And do not purchase, in exchange for My signs, a small price. And whoever does not judge according to what Allah has sent down, then those<sup foot_note="366166">3</sup> are the deniers.",footnotes:346627:Literally 'became Muslims'.|346628:Literally ‘Lordly’.|346629:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  5,45,"And We prescribed for them therein: that the life<sup foot_note="366167">1</sup> is for the life, and <small>(that)</small> the eye is for the eye, and <small>(that)</small> the nose is for the nose, and <small>(that)</small> the ear is for the ear, and <small>(that)</small> the tooth is for the tooth, and <small>(that)</small> for wounds is fair <span class="h">retribution<sup foot_note="366168">2</sup></span>. But whoever donates<sup foot_note="366169">3</sup> it, then it is an atonement for him. And whoever does not judge according to what Allah has sent down, then those<sup foot_note="366170">4</sup> are the unjust.",footnotes:346630:The Arabic word used is <i>nafs,</i> which means “self”, referring to the human life.|346631:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Kesa’i read it as: “...therein: that the life is for the life, and the eye for the eye, and the nose for the nose, and the ear for the ear, and the tooth for the tooth, and for wounds fair retribution.” All except for Nafie’, Asem, Hamza, Khalaf, Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “...and for wounds fair retribution.”</span>|346632:Whoever waives it as charity.|346633:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  5,46,"And in their<sup foot_note="366171">1</sup> footsteps We sent Jesus, son of Mary, confirming what preceded him of the Torah. And We brought him the Gospel, wherein is guidance and light, and confirming the Torah that preceded him, and a guidance and an admonition to the ones who are mindful <small>(of God)</small>.",footnotes:346634:The prophets of the Israelites.
  5,47,"So <span class="h">let<sup foot_note="366172">1</sup></span> the people of the Gospel judge according to what Allah has sent down in it. And whoever does not judge according to what Allah has sent down, then those<sup foot_note="366173">2</sup> are the defiantly disobedient.",footnotes:346635:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “And so that the people of the Gospel may judge according…”</span>|346636:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  5,48,"And We sent down to you<sup>sg</sup> the Scripture with truth, confirming whatever scripture that preceded it and an overseer over it. So judge between them according to what Allah has sent down, and do not follow their whims instead of the truth that has come to you. For each of you<sup>pl</sup> We have assigned a legislation and a method. And had Allah willed, He could have made you a single community, but in order to test you through what He has brought you; so race towards good works. To Allah is your return, all of you, then He will inform you regarding whatever you used to differ over."
  5,49,"So judge<sup>sg</sup> between them according to what Allah has sent down, and do not follow their whims. And beware of them lest they lure you away from some of what Allah has sent down to you. But if they turn away, then know that Allah wants to afflict them for some of their misdeeds. And most surely, many people are defiantly disobedient."
  5,50,"Is it the judgment of <small>(the era of)</small> pagan ignorance that <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="366174">1</sup></span> desire? And who is better than Allah in judgment for people of firm faith?",footnotes:346637:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “…that you<sup>pl</sup> desire?” desire?”</span>
  5,51,"O you who have attained faith, do not take the Jews and the Christians as allies; some of them are allies of one another. And whoever of you allies himself with them is indeed one of them. Indeed, Allah does not guide the unjust people."
  5,52,"So you<sup>sg</sup> see those in whose hearts is sickness hastening towards them. They say, “We fear that the wheel of fate may turn against us.” But hopefully Allah will bring about the conquest or something else from Himself, whereupon they will regret what they concealed within themselves."
  5,53,"And <span class="h">those<sup foot_note="366175">1</sup></span> who have attained faith <span class="h">say<sup foot_note="366176">2</sup></span>, “Are these the ones who swore by Allah their most solemn oaths that they are very truly with you<sup>pl</sup>?” Their deeds have been nullified, so they became losers.",footnotes:346638:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ Ibn Kathir, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “Those who have …”</span>|346639:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “And (hopefully) those who have attained faith will say…”</span>
  5,54,"O you who have attained faith, whoever of you turns back from his religion—then Allah will bring a people whom He loves and who love Him, humble<sup>pl</sup> towards the believers, mighty towards the deniers. They strive in the way of Allah and do not fear the blame of any blamer. That is Allah’s grace; He brings it to whomever He wills, for Allah is All-Embracing, All-Knowing."
  5,55,"Indeed, your<sup>pl</sup> ultimate guardian is Allah and His Messenger and those who have attained faith—those who establish the prayer and bring<sup foot_note="366177">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="366178">2</sup> while they bow down.",footnotes:346640:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|346641:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  5,56,"And whoever allies himself with Allah and His Messenger and those who have attained faith—then surely the party of Allah are the overcomers."
  5,57,"O you who have attained faith, do not take as allies those who take your religion for mockery and a game from among those who were given the Scripture before you or the <span class="h">deniers<sup foot_note="366179">1</sup></span>. And be mindful of Allah if you have <small>(really)</small> attained faith.",footnotes:346642:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr, Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “…or from among the deniers.”</span>
  5,58,"And when you<sup>pl</sup> call to the prayer, they take it for mockery and a game. That is because they are people who do not reason."
  5,59,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “O People of the Scripture, do you resent us only because we have attained faith in Allah and in what was sent down to us and in what was sent down previously, while most of you are defiantly disobedient?”"
  5,60,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Shall I inform you of worse than that as requital from Allah? <small>(It is the retribution of)</small> the one whom Allah has cursed and upon whom is His wrath, and <small>(those)</small> whom<sup foot_note="366180">1</sup> He made into apes and pigs, and the worshipers of false <span class="h">masters<sup foot_note="366181">2</sup></span>. Those are in a worse position and further astray from the right way.",footnotes:346643:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.|346644:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “…and the servants of false masters.”</span>
  5,61,"And when they come to you<sup>pl</sup>, they say, 'We have attained faith,' though they have entered with denial, and they have departed with it. But Allah knows better what they have been concealing.”"
  5,62,"And you<sup>sg</sup> see many of them hastening towards sin and hostility and their devouring of illicit gains. Truly miserable is what they have been making!"
  5,63,"If only the Godly<sup foot_note="366182">1</sup> scholars and the rabbis would forbid them from speaking sinfully and devouring illicit gains! Truly miserable is what they have been practicing!",footnotes:346645:Literally ‘Lordly’.
  5,64,"And the Jews said, “Allah’s hand is shackled." Shackled are their hands, and they were cursed for what they said! Rather, both His hands are outstretched; He spends as He wills. And most surely, what was sent down to you<sup>sg</sup> from your Lord will increase many of them in exceeding all limits and in denial. And We cast between them enmity and hatred until the Day of Resurrection. Whenever they kindle a fire of war, Allah extinguishes it. And they rush about in the land spreading corruption, and Allah does not love corrupters."
  5,65,"And had the People of the Scripture attained faith and been mindful <small>(of God)</small>, We would surely have remitted their evil deeds and entered them into the Gardens of Bliss."
  5,66,"And had they established the Torah and the Gospel and what was sent down to them from their Lord, they would surely have eaten from above them and from beneath their feet<sup foot_note="366183">1</sup> . Among them is a moderate community, but <small>(regarding)</small> many of them—evil is what they do.",footnotes:346646:Literally ‘legs’.
  5,67,"O Messenger, proclaim what was sent down to you from your Lord; but if you do not, then you will not have proclaimed His <span class="h">message<sup foot_note="366184">1</sup></span>, for Allah safeguards you from mankind. Indeed, Allah does not guide the denying people.",footnotes:346647:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie, Ibn Amer, Shu’ba and Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…His messages,”</span>
  5,68,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “O People of the Scripture, you have no basis until you establish the Torah and the Gospel and what was sent down to you from your Lord.” But most surely what was sent down to you<sup>sg</sup> from your Lord will increase many of them in exceeding all limits and in denial, so do not be sorry for the denying people."
  5,69,"Indeed, those who have attained faith and those who have Judaized and the Sabians and the Christians—whoever has attained faith in Allah and the Last Day and has acted righteously—then no <span class="h">fear<sup foot_note="366185">1</sup></span> shall be upon them<sup foot_note="366186">2</sup>, nor shall they grieve.",footnotes:346648:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…then no fear shall ever be upon them, nor shall they grieve.”</span>|346649:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  5,70,"We very truly took a pledge from the Children of Israel and We sent to them messengers; whenever a messenger came to them with what their <small>(inner)</small> selves did not desire, one group they disbelieved, and another group they kill<sup foot_note="366187">1</sup> .",footnotes:346650:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense. Using present tense for an old practice emphasizes that it was a tradition frequently practiced.
  5,71,"And they thought that there would be no trial, so they turned blind and deaf. Then Allah granted them repentance and accepted it from them; then <small>(again)</small> many of them turned blind and deaf. But Allah is All-Seeing of whatever they do."
  5,72,"Most surely, those who said, "Allah is the Christ, son of Mary," have denied <small>(faith),</small> for the Messiah <small>(himself)</small> said, “O Children of Israel, worship Allah, my Lord and your Lord; indeed, whoever associates <small>(others)</small> with Allah, then surely for him Allah has forbidden the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small>, and his shelter is the Fire. And for the unjust there are no supporters.”"
  5,73,"Most surely, those who said, "Indeed, Allah is the third of three,” have denied <small>(faith)</small>, for there is no god except one God. And if they do not refrain from what they say, a painful punishment will very truly befall those of them who have denied."
  5,74,"Will they not repent to Allah and ask His forgiveness? For Allah is Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  5,75,"The Messiah, son of Mary, is no more than a messenger before whom other messengers had passed away, and his mother was an unwavering believer; they both used to eat food. Look how We make the signs evident for them, then look how they are <small>(still)</small> averted <small>(from the truth)</small>."
  5,76,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Do you worship apart from Allah what possesses for you neither harm nor benefit, while Allah is the One Who is the All-Hearing, the All-Knowing?”"
  5,77,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “O People of the Scripture, do not exaggerate in your religion beyond the truth, and do not follow the whims of people who have already gone astray before and have led many astray and have <small>(themselves)</small> strayed off the right way.”"
  5,78,"Cursed were those who denied from among the Children of Israel by the very tongue of David and Jesus, son of Mary. That is because they disobeyed and used to transgress."
  5,79,"They used not to forbid one another from any deplorable thing they did. Truly miserable is what they have been doing!"
  5,80,"You<sup>sg</sup> see many of them taking those who deny as allies. Truly miserable is what their <small>(inner)</small> selves have put forth for them, that Allah's anger fell upon them and in the punishment they abide."
  5,81,"And had they believed in Allah and the Prophet and in what was sent down to him, they would not have taken them as allies. But many of them are defiantly disobedient."
  5,82,"You<sup>sg</sup> will definitely find that the most severe of mankind in enmity towards those who have attained faith are the Jews and those who have associated <small>(others with God)</small>, and you will find that the nearest of them in <small>(genuine)</small> love towards those who have attained faith are those who said, “We are indeed Christians.” That is because among them are priests and monks, and because they never act arrogantly."
  5,83,"And when they hear what was sent down to the Messenger, you<sup>sg</sup> see their eyes overflowing with tears for what they recognize of the truth; they say, “Our Lord, we have attained faith, so write us down with those who bear witness."
  5,84,"And how should we not believe in Allah and what has come to us of the truth, and<small> </small>we ardently hope that our Lord will enter us along with the righteous people <small>(into Paradise)</small>?”"
  5,85,"So Allah rewarded them for what they said—Gardens beneath which rivers flow, abiding therein; and that is the repayment of those who excel in doing good."
  5,86,"But those who denied and disbelieved in Our signs—those are the fellows of purgatory."
  5,87,"O you who have attained faith, do not prohibit the good things Allah has made lawful for you, and do not transgress; indeed, Allah does not love the transgressors."
  5,88,"And eat of the lawful, good things Allah has provided for you, and be mindful of Allah in whom you are believers."
  5,89,"Allah does not hold you<sup>pl</sup> accountable for idle talk involving your oaths<sup foot_note="366188">1</sup>, but He holds you accountable for your firm binding of <span class="h">oaths<sup foot_note="366189">2</sup></span>; so its atonement is by feeding ten destitute people from the best of what you feed your families, or by clothing them, or by freeing a slave<sup foot_note="366190">3</sup> . But if anyone does not find <small>(the means)</small>, then fasting for three days. That is the atonement for <small>(breaking)</small> your oaths when you have sworn them. So keep<sup foot_note="366191">4</sup> your oaths. Allah thus clarifies His signs for you, that you may give thanks.",footnotes:346651:Unintended oaths.|346652:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…for your binding of oaths;” Ibn Zekwan read it as: “…for your sustained binding of oaths;”</span>|346653:Literally ‘a neck’.|346654:Literally ‘preserve'.
  5,90,"O you who have attained faith, surely intoxicants and gambling and idolatry and divination are an abomination of Satan’s work, so avoid it, that you may be successful."
  5,91,"Indeed, Satan only wants to induce enmity and hatred among you through intoxicants and gambling, and to bar you from the Reminder of Allah and from the prayer; so will you desist?"
  5,92,"And obey Allah and obey the Messenger and be cautious, for if you<sup>pl</sup> turn away, then know that the only duty of Our<sup foot_note="366192">1</sup> Messenger is evident proclamation.",footnotes:346655:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 1 person to 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.
  5,93,"No sin is committed by those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds regarding what they may have eaten, provided they become mindful <small>(of God)</small> and attain faith and do righteous deeds, then maintain being mindful <small>(of God)</small> and being faithful, then remain mindful <small>(of God)</small> and excel in doing good, for Allah loves those who excel in doing good."
  5,94,"O you who have attained faith, Allah will most surely test you with something of the game that your hands and spears reach, that Allah may know who fears Him, though unseen; so whoever transgresses after that—then for him is a painful punishment."
  5,95,"O you who have attained faith, do not kill game while you are consecrating yourselves to pilgrimage. And whoever of you kills any intentionally, then a <span class="h">penalty:<sup foot_note="366193">1</sup></span> the like of what he has killed of domestic animals, as determined by two reliable persons from among you—an offering delivered to the Ka'bah<sup foot_note="366194">2</sup> —or an atonement: <span class="h">food<sup foot_note="366195">3</sup></span> for <small>(some)</small> destitute people or by fasting an equivalent number of days, so that he may taste the grievous consequences of his conduct. Allah has pardoned what has passed, but whoever reverts, then Allah will take vengeance on him, for Allah is Almighty, Capable of vengeance.",footnotes:346656:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Yaqoub and Khalaf read it as: “…intentionally, then the like of what he has killed of domestic animals (shall do for a penalty),”</span>|346657:For the poor.|346658:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…or an atonement of food for (some) destitute people or by fasting…”</span>
  5,96,"The game of the sea and its food have been made lawful for you<sup>pl</sup> as an enjoyment for you and for travelers, while the game of the land has been forbidden for you as long as you are consecrating yourselves to pilgrimage. And be mindful of Allah to whom you are herded."
  5,97,"Allah has appointed the Ka’bah—the Inviolable House—a leverage for mankind, as well as every inviolable month and the offerings and the garlanded; all this so that you may know that Allah knows whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth, and that Allah is All-Knowing of everything."
  5,98,"Know<sup>pl</sup> that Allah is Stern in retribution, and that Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  5,99,"The Messenger’s only responsibility is proclamation, while Allah knows what you disclose and what you conceal."
  5,100,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “The nasty and the good are not equal, even though the multitude of the nasty may impress you<sup>sg</sup>. So be mindful of Allah, O you people of understanding, that you may succeed.”"
  5,101,"O you who have attained faith, do not ask about things that would trouble you if disclosed to you. But if you<sup>pl</sup> ask about them while the Recital<sup foot_note="366196">1</sup> is being bestowed from on <span class="h">high<sup foot_note="366197">2</sup></span>, they will be disclosed to you; Allah has pardoned that, for Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Clement.",footnotes:346659:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.|346660:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…while the Recital is being sent down,”</span>
  5,102,"Surely, some people before you asked <small>(about)</small> them, then of them they became deniers."
  5,103,"Never did Allah institute <small>(the superstitions of)</small>: the ear-slit she-camel or the free-grazing she-camel or the successive female-bearing cattle or the protected ten-sire camel. But those who denied fabricate lies against Allah, and most of them do not reason."
  5,104,"Thus when it is said to them, “Come to what Allah has sent down and to the Messenger,” they say, “Sufficient for us is what we found our forefathers upon.” What if their forefathers knew nothing and were not guided?"
  5,105,"O you who have attained faith, you are responsible for your <small>(inner)</small> selves; he who has strayed cannot harm you if you are guided. To Allah is your return, all of you, so He may inform you of what you used to do."
  5,106,"O you who have attained faith, when death approaches one of you, let two reliable persons from among you act as witnesses to the making of the bequest, or two persons from another people if you are traveling in the land and the calamity of death afflicts you. Summon<sup>pl</sup> them after the prayer so that they swear by Allah—if you have doubts—<small>(saying)</small>: “We will not purchase, in exchange for it<sup foot_note="366198">1</sup>, any price, even if it were a relative, and we never conceal Allah’s testimony; we would then most surely be of the sinners.”",footnotes:346661:Our testimony.
  5,107,"So if it is discovered that both of them are guilty <small>(of perjury)</small>, then two others deserve to take their place from among those <span class="h">responsible<sup foot_note="366199">1</sup></span> for the claim—the two most concerned—and have them swear by Allah, “Our testimony is more truthful than their testimony, and we have not transgressed; we would then most surely be of the unjust.”",footnotes:346662:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as: “…from among those who were given the responsibility of the claim—the two…”</span>
  5,108,"That makes it more likely that they give the right testimony, or else have fear that their oaths might be contradicted by subsequent oaths. So be mindful of Allah and listen. For Allah does not guide the defiantly disobedient people."
  5,109,"On the day when Allah gathers the messengers, then says, “What response were you given?” They said<sup foot_note="366200">1</sup>, “We have no knowledge; indeed, it is You Who are the Superb Knower of the hidden realms.”",footnotes:346663:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  5,110,"When Allah said, “O Jesus, son of Mary, recall My blessing upon you and upon your mother when I aided you with the holy spirit, <small>(making)</small> you speak to people while in the cradle and in the prime of manhood; and when I taught you the Scripture and wisdom and the Torah and the Gospel; and when you create<sup foot_note="366201">1</sup> from clay the shape of <span class="h">birds<sup foot_note="366202">2</sup></span>, by My leave, then breathe into it so it becomes <span class="h">birds<sup foot_note="366203">3</sup></span>, by My leave; and when you heal the born-blind and the leper, by My leave; and when you bring out the dead, by My leave; and when I restrained the Children of Israel from you when you brought them the evident proofs. But those who denied among them said, `This is nothing but evident <span class="h">sorcery<sup foot_note="366204">4</sup></span>.'"",footnotes:346664:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense.|346665:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…the shape of a bird,”</span>|346666:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…so it becomes a bird,”</span>|346667:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…an evident sorcerer.”</span>
  5,111,"And recall when I revealed to the disciples: "Believe in Me and in My Messenger." They said, "We have attained faith, so bear witness that We are certainly Muslims<sup foot_note="366205">1</sup> ."",footnotes:346668:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimoon</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  5,112,"And recall when the disciples said, "O Jesus, son of Mary, <span class="h">can<sup foot_note="366206">1</sup></span> your Lord bestow upon us from on <span class="h">high<sup foot_note="366207">2</sup></span> a table spread <small>(with food)</small> from heaven?" He said, "Be mindful of Allah, if you are believers."",footnotes:346669:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…can you (ask) your to Lord…”</span>|346670:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “… can your Lord send down to us…”</span>
  5,113,"They said, “We want to eat from it, and so that our hearts are serene, and to know that you have told us the truth, and to be of its witnesses.”"
  5,114,"Jesus, son of Mary, said, “O Allah, our Lord, send down for us a table spread <small>(with food)</small> from heaven to be a feast for us, for the first of us and the last of us, and a sign from You. And provide for us, for You are the Best of providers.”"
  5,115,"Allah said, “Indeed, I shall <span class="h">bestow<sup foot_note="366208">1</sup></span> it upon you<sup>pl</sup> from on high, but whoever of you denies thereafter, then I shall indeed punish him with a punishment the like of which I never punish anyone of <small>(My creation in)</small> all realms.”",footnotes:346671:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “Indeed, I shall send it down to you, but whoever…”</span>
  5,116,"And recall when Allah said, “O Jesus, son of Mary, did you say to mankind, ‘Take me and my mother as two gods apart from Allah?'” He said, “Highly Exalted are You! It is not for me to say what I have no right to. Had I said it, You would have known it. You know whatever is within my <small>(inner)</small> self, and I do not know whatever is within Your Self. You are indeed the Superb Knower of the hidden realms."
  5,117,"Never did I tell them except what You commanded me: that you shall worship Allah, my Lord and your Lord. And I was a witness over them as long as I was among them, but when You took me up, You became the Watcher over them, and You are Witness over everything."
  5,118,"If You punish them, they are Your servants; but if You forgive them, You are the Almighty, the All-Wise.”"
  5,119,"Allah said, “This is the <span class="h">day<sup foot_note="366209">1</sup></span> when the truthful benefit from their truthfulness.” For them are Gardens beneath which rivers flow, abiding therein forever. Allah became well pleased with them, and they became well pleased with Him. That is the great triumph.",footnotes:346672:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ read it as: “Allah said, “This is on the day when the truthful…”</span>
  5,120,"To Allah belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth and whatever lies in them, and He is All-Powerful over everything."
  6,1,"All praise be to Allah, Who created the heavens and the earth and made the darkness<small>(es)</small> and the light; thereafter those who have denied equate <small>(others)</small> with their Lord."
  6,2,"It is He Who created you<sup>pl</sup> from clay, then decreed a term, and a term stated by him, yet you are in doubt."
  6,3,"And He is Allah in the heavens and in the earth; He knows your<sup>pl</sup> secret and whatever you say aloud, and He knows whatever you earn."
  6,4,"And not one of their<sup foot_note="366210">1</sup> Lord’s signs comes to them but they disregard it.",footnotes:346673:A grammatical shift from 2<sup>nd</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  6,5,"For surely they disbelieved in the truth when it came to them, but soon there will reach them the news of what they used to ridicule."
  6,6,"Have they not seen how many generations We annihilated before them? We had established them in the earth more firmly than We established you, and We sent the sky upon them plentifully and We made rivers flow beneath them. But We annihilated them for their misdeeds and raised other generations after them."
  6,7,"And had We bestowed upon you<sup>sg</sup> a scripture from on high on parchment and they had touched it with their hands, those who have denied would have said, “This is nothing but evident sorcery.”"
  6,8,"And they said, “If only an angel had been sent down on him.” But had We sent down an angel, the matter would have been settled, then they would not have been given respite."
  6,9,"And had We made him an angel, We would have made him a man, and We would have confounded them regarding what they are already confounding."
  6,10,"And most surely <small>(other)</small> messengers before you were ridiculed, but those who mocked them were surrounded by what they used to ridicule."
  6,11,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Journey<sup>pl</sup> through the earth, then look what the outcome was for the disbelievers.”"
  6,12,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “To whom belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth?” Say, “To Allah.” He has prescribed for Himself mercifulness. He will surely gather you to the Day of Resurrection about which there is no doubt. Those who have lost themselves do not believe."
  6,13,"And to Him belongs whatever rests in the night and the day. And He is the All-Hearing, the All-Knowing."
  6,14,"Say, “Shall I take for myself a guardian other than Allah, the Originator of the heavens and the earth, He Who feeds and is not fed?” Say, “I have been commanded to be the first of those who become Muslims<sup foot_note="366211">1</sup>,” and do not ever be of the polytheists.",footnotes:346674:The Arabic word used is <i>aslam</i> which means to become <i>Muslim</i> by submitting to God.
  6,15,"Say, “I fear, should I disobey my Lord, the punishment of a great day.”"
  6,16,"Whoever is <span class="h">spared<sup foot_note="366212">1</sup></span> on that day—then He has surely had mercy on him, and that is the evident triumph.",footnotes:346675:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “Whoever He spares on that day—then He has surely had mercy on him,”</span>
  6,17,"And if Allah touches you<sup>sg</sup> with any harm, then none can remove it except He. And if He touches you with good—He is All-Powerful over everything."
  6,18,"And He is the Subjugator over His servants. And He is the All-Wise, the All-Aware."
  6,19,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “What thing is more solemn in testimony?” Say, “Allah is Witness between you<sup>pl</sup> and me. And this Recital<sup foot_note="366213">1</sup> was revealed to me, that I may warn you with it, and whomever it may reach. Do you indeed testify that there are other gods with Allah?” Say, “I myself do not testify.” Say, “He is but One God, and I am indeed innocent of whatever you associate <small>(with Him)</small>.”",footnotes:346676:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  6,20,"Those to whom We have brought the Scripture recognize him<sup foot_note="366214">1</sup> as they recognize their own children; <small>(those are)</small> the ones who have lost themselves, so they do not believe.",footnotes:346677:The 3<sup>rd</sup> person pronoun used in Arabic can be translated to 'him' for the Prophet (peace be upon him) or 'it' for the Qur’an. person pronoun used in Arabic can be translated to 'him' for the Prophet (peace be upon him) or 'it' for the Qur’an.
  6,21,"And who is more unjust than someone who has fabricated lies against Allah or has disbelieved in His signs? Indeed, the unjust never succeed."
  6,22,"And on the day when We <span class="h">herd<sup foot_note="366215">1</sup></span> them all together, then say to those who associated <small>(other gods with God)</small>, “Where are your associates whom you used to claim?”",footnotes:346678:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “And on the day when He herds them…”</span>
  6,23,"Then their only turmoil <span class="h">was<sup foot_note="366216">1</sup></span> when they said<sup foot_note="366217">2</sup>, “By Allah, <span class="h">our<sup foot_note="366218">3</sup></span> Lord, we were not polytheists.”",footnotes:346679:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Abu Amr, Shu’ba, Abu Ja’far and Khalaf read it as: “Then their saying, ‘By Allah, our Lord, we were not polytheists’ was their only turmoil.”All except for Ibn Kathir, Ibn Amer, Hafs, Nafie’, Abu Amr, Shu’ba, Abu Ja’far and Khalaf read it as: “Then their only (excuse during their) turmoil was that they said…”</span>|346680:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.|346681:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “By Allah! O our Lord, we were</span>
  6,24,"Look how they lied to themselves, and whatever they used to fabricate strayed away from them."
  6,25,"And of them are those who listen to you. But We have placed veils over their hearts, preventing them from comprehending it, and heaviness in their ears. Even if they see every sign, they will not believe in it. Until, when they come to you to argue with you, those who deny say, “This is nothing but legends of the ancients.”"
  6,26,"They forbid <small>(others)</small> from it and avoid it themselves, yet they annihilate none except themselves, but they are unaware."
  6,27,"And if only you<sup>sg</sup> could see when they were<sup foot_note="366219">1</sup> made to stand by the Fire and they said, “If only we could be sent back and <span class="h">not<sup foot_note="366220">2</sup></span> disbelieve in the signs of our Lord and be of the believers!”",footnotes:346682:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.|346683:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza and Ya’qub read it as: “If only we could be sent back—for we do not disbelieve in the signs of our Lord—and be of the believers!”</span>
  6,28,"Rather, what they previously used to hide was disclosed to them. And even if they were to be returned back they would revert to what they had been forbidden from, for they are indeed liars."
  6,29,"And they said, “There is nothing but our Earlier Life, and never shall we be resurrected.”"
  6,30,"And if only you<sup>sg</sup> could see when they were<sup foot_note="366221">1</sup> made to stand before their Lord. He said, “Is this not the truth?” They said, “Yes indeed, by our Lord.” He said, “Then taste the punishment on account of what you used to deny.”",footnotes:346684:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  6,31,"Lost indeed are those who disbelieved in the meeting with Allah until, when the Hour comes upon them suddenly, they will say, “Alas for us for whatever we have neglected in it,” while carrying their burdens on their backs. Undoubtedly, evil is what they bear."
  6,32,"And the Earlier Life is nothing but a game and a distraction, but the Home of the Hereafter is definitely <span class="h">better<sup foot_note="366222">1</sup></span> for those who are mindful <small>(of God)</small>. Do you<sup>pl</sup> <span class="h">not<sup foot_note="366223">2</sup></span> reason?",footnotes:346685:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Amer, Hafs, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “Do they not reason?”</span>|346686:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “…but the Home of the Hereafter is better for…”</span>
  6,33,"Indeed, We know that very truly what they say grieves you, but it is not really you whom they disbelieve; rather, it is the signs of Allah that the unjust repudiate."
  6,34,"And very truly, other messengers before you were disbelieved, but they patiently endured being disbelieved and hurt until Our support came to them, for none can change His words. And indeed there has already come to you<sup>sg</sup> some of the emissaries' stories."
  6,35,"And if you find their disregard hard to bear, then if you can, seek a tunnel into the earth or a stairway into the heaven so as to bring them a sign. And had Allah willed, He could have united them on guidance. So do not be<sup>sg</sup> of the ignorant."
  6,36,"Indeed, those who respond are those who hear. But the dead—Allah resurrects them, then to Him they are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="366224">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346687:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…, then to Him they return.”</span>
  6,37,"And they said, “If only a sign had been <span class="h">bestowed<sup foot_note="366225">1</sup></span> upon him from on high by his Lord.” Say, “Indeed, Allah is Able to send down a sign, but most of them do not know.”",footnotes:346688:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “If only a sign had been sent down upon him…”</span>
  6,38,"And there is no treading creature on land, nor a bird flying with its wings, but are communities like you. We have neglected nothing in the Scripture. Then to their Lord they are herded."
  6,39,"Those who disbelieved in Our signs are deaf and dumb, in darkness<small>(es)</small>. Whomever Allah wills, He misguides. And whomever He wills, He sets on a straight path."
  6,40,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Have you seen yourselves? If Allah's punishment came upon you or the Hour came upon you, would you call upon any other than Allah, if you are sincere?"
  6,41,"Rather, it is only Him that you would call upon, then He removes whatever made you call on Him if He so wills, and you would forget what you associated <small>(with Him)</small>.”"
  6,42,"And most surely We sent to communities before you<sup>sg</sup>, and We seized them with misery and adversity, that they may supplicate <small>(Us)</small>."
  6,43,"If only, when Our affliction came upon them they had supplicated <small>(Us)</small>. But their hearts hardened, and Satan adorned for them whatever they used to do."
  6,44,"Then, when they forgot<sup foot_note="366226">1</sup> what they had been reminded of, We <span class="h">opened<sup foot_note="366227">2</sup></span> for them the gates of everything until, when they delighted in what they were given, We seized them suddenly, and they were instantly in despair.",footnotes:346689:Disregarded.|346690:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Roways read it as: “… We widely opened for them…”</span>
  6,45,"Thus the last remnant of those who were unjust was cut off. And praise be to Allah, Lord of all realms."
  6,46,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Have you<sup>pl</sup> seen? If Allah took away your hearing and your sight<small>(s)</small> and set a seal on your hearts, which god other than Allah would restore them to you?” Look how We<sup foot_note="366228">1</sup> diversify the signs, yet they keep turning away.",footnotes:346691:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 1 person to 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.
  6,47,"Say, “Have you seen yourselves? If Allah's punishment came upon you suddenly or openly, would any be annihilated except the unjust people?”"
  6,48,"And We do not send the emissaries except as bearers of glad tidings and as forewarners, so whoever has attained faith and reformed—no fear shall be upon them<sup foot_note="366229">1</sup>, nor shall they grieve.",footnotes:346692:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  6,49,"But those who disbelieved in Our signs—punishment will touch them on account of their defiant disobedience."
  6,50,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “I do not say to youpl the treasuries of Allah are with me, nor do I know what is hidden, nor do I say to you I am an angel. I only follow what is revealed to me.” Say, “Are the blind and the seeing equal? Do you<sup>pl</sup> not reflect?”"
  6,51,"And warn with it those who fear to be herded to their Lord—they do not have, apart from Him, any guardian or intercessor—that they may become mindful <small>(of Him)</small>."
  6,52,"And do<sup>sg</sup> not expel those who call upon their Lord morning and evening, seeking His Countenance; you are not responsible for their reckoning in any way, nor are they responsible for your reckoning in any way. So were you to expel them, you would be of the unjust."
  6,53,"And thus We have tried some of them by means of others, that they may say, “Are these the ones whom Allah has favored from among us?” Does not Allah know better of those who are thankful?"
  6,54,"And when those who believe in Our signs come to you<sup>sg</sup>, say, “Peace be upon you; your Lord has prescribed for Himself mercifulness: <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="366230">1</sup></span> whoever among you does evil out of ignorance then repents afterwards and reforms—that He is then Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy.”",footnotes:346693:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “...mercifulness: that whoever among you does evil out of ignorance then repents afterwards and reforms—indeed, He is then Oft-Forgiving…” All except for Nafie’, Abu Ja’far, Ibn Amer, Asem and Ya’qub read it as: “…mercifulness: indeed, whoever among you does evil out of ignorance then repents afterwards and reforms—indeed, he is then…”</span>
  6,55,"And thus We detail the signs, and so that the way of the criminals can become <span class="h">evident<sup foot_note="366231">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346694:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “… and so that you<sup>sg</sup> can realize the way of the criminals.” can realize the way of the criminals.”</span>
  6,56,"Say, “I have been forbidden from worshiping those you call upon apart from Allah.” Say, “I do not follow your whims, for then I would have surely gone astray and would not be of those guided.”"
  6,57,"Say, “I rely on evident proof from my Lord, while you have disbelieved in Him. I do not possess what you ask to be hastened; judgment belongs to none but Allah; He<sup foot_note="366232">1</sup> <span class="h">states<sup foot_note="366233">2</sup></span> the truth and He is the Best of judges.”",footnotes:346695:The Arabic word used is <i>yaqusu</i> which also means “follows”, implying that the judgement of God follows the truth.|346696:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Asem and Abu Ja’far read it as: “He decrees the truth…”</span>
  6,58,"Say, “If what you ask to be hastened was with me, the matter between me and you would have been settled, for Allah knows better of the unjust<sup>pl</sup>.”"
  6,59,"And with Him are the keys of the hidden realm; none knows them except He. And He knows whatever is on land and sea, and not a leaf falls but He knows it, nor a single grain in the darkness<small>(es)</small> of earth, nor is there anything wet or dry but is in an evident record<sup foot_note="366234">1</sup> .",footnotes:346697:Literally ‘scripture’.
  6,60,"And it is He Who takes you<sup>pl</sup> by night and He knows what you have committed by day, then He raises you up in it, that a stated term may be fulfilled; then to Him is your return, then He will inform you of what you used to do."
  6,61,"And He is the Subjugator over His servants, and He sends preservers over you<sup foot_note="366235">1</sup> until, when death has come to one of you, Our messengers take him away, and they never neglect <small>(their tasks)</small>.",footnotes:346698:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 2 person to 2<sup>nd</sup> person. person.
  6,62,"Then they are returned to Allah, their True Patron. Undoubtedly, His is the judgment, and He is the Swiftest of reckoners."
  6,63,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Who <span class="h">delivers<sup foot_note="366236">1</sup></span> you from the darkness<small>(es)</small> of land and sea?” You<sup>pl</sup> call upon Him in supplication and in secret. “If He <span class="h">saves<sup foot_note="366237">2</sup></span> us from this, We will surely be of the thankful.”",footnotes:346699:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “Who saves you…”</span>|346700:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “If You save us …”</span>
  6,64,"Say, “It is Allah Who <span class="h">delivers<sup foot_note="366238">1</sup></span> you from it and from every calamity, yet you associate others with Him.”",footnotes:346701:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Zekwan and Ya’qub read it as: “It is Allah Who saves you…”</span>
  6,65,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “He is the One Able to send upon you a punishment from above you or from under your feet, or He can confound you into sects and make you taste one another's violence. Look how We diversify the signs, that they may comprehend.”"
  6,66,"But your people considered it to be a lie, though it is the truth. Say, “I am not a trustee over you.”"
  6,67,"For every tiding is a time of settlement, and you<sup>pl</sup> will come to know."
  6,68,"And when you<sup>sg</sup> see those who engage in blaspheming Our signs, then disregard them until they engage in another discourse. But should Satan <span class="h">make<sup foot_note="366239">1</sup></span> you forget, then do not sit after the Reminding with the unjust people.",footnotes:346702:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “But should Satan try hard to make you forget…”</span>
  6,69,"And in no way are the mindful <small>(of God)</small> responsible for their reckoning, but only <small>(for)</small> reminding—that they may become mindful <small>(of God)</small>."
  6,70,"So leave<sup>sg</sup> alone those who take their religion for a game and a distraction, and whom the Earlier Life has deceived. But remind with it, lest a single self become wrecked on account of what it has earned. Apart from Allah it has neither guardian nor intercessor, and if it offers every conceivable compensation, it will not be accepted from it. Those are the ones who were wrecked on account of what they had earned; for them is a drink of scalding water and a painful punishment on account of how they used to deny."
  6,71,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Are we to call, apart from Allah, upon what can neither benefit us nor harm us and be turned back on our heels after Allah has guided us, like someone who is lured by the Satans on earth and is confused? He has fellows calling him to guidance: 'Come to us'.” Say, “The guidance of Allah is indeed the Guidance, and we have been commanded to surrender to the Lord of all realms,"
  6,72,"and <small>(we were told:)</small> 'perform the prayers and be mindful of Him, for it is to Him that you will be herded.'"
  6,73,"And it is He Who created the heavens and the earth in truth. And on the day when He says: 'Be,' and so it is: His saying is the truth; and to Him belongs the dominion on the day when the Trumpet is blown. The Knower of the hidden realm and the manifest, and He is the All-Wise, the All-Aware.""
  6,74,"And recall when Abraham said to his father <span class="h">Azar<sup foot_note="366240">1</sup></span>, “Do you take human-shaped idols for gods? I see that you and your people are indeed in evident misguidance.”",footnotes:346703:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…Abraham said to his father, “Azar, do you take…”</span>
  6,75,"And thus We show<sup foot_note="366241">1</sup> Abraham the empire of the heavens and the earth, and so that he would be of the ones who believe with certitude.",footnotes:346704:Frequently the Qur’an speaks about the prophets using present tense; this should be pondered by the reader.
  6,76,"So when the night covered him, he saw a planet; he said, “This is my lord.” But when it set, he said, “I do not love those that set.”"
  6,77,"So when he saw the moon rising, he said, “This is my lord.” But when it set, he said, “If my Lord does not guide me, I will most surely be one of the people who have gone astray.”"
  6,78,"So when he saw the sun rising, he said, “This is my lord; this is bigger.” But when it set, he said, “O my people, I am innocent of whatever you associate <small>(with Him)</small>."
  6,79,"I have directed my face towards the One Who originated the heavens and the earth—turning away from all that is false—and in no way am I one of the polytheists.”"
  6,80,"And his people debated with him. He said, “Do you debate with me about Allah when He has guided me? I do not fear what you associate with Him unless my Lord were to will something. My Lord has embraced everything in knowledge. Will you not remind yourselves?"
  6,81,"And how is it that I should fear that which you associate with Him, while you do not fear associating with Allah that of which He has bestowed <span class="h">upon<sup foot_note="366242">1</sup></span> you no authority from on high? So which of the two groups is more entitled to security, if you <small>(really)</small> know?”",footnotes:346705:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…He has sent down to you no…”</span>
  6,82,"Those who have attained faith and have not confounded their faith with injustice—for those is security, and they are guided."
  6,83,"And that was Our argument which We brought to Abraham against his people; We elevate by <span class="h">degrees<sup foot_note="366243">1</sup></span> whomever We will. Indeed, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is All-Wise, All-Knowing.",footnotes:346706:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “… We elevate the degrees (ranks) of whomever We will.”</span>
  6,84,"And We gave him Isaac and Jacob; each of them We guided. And We guided Noah previously, and from his offspring David and Solomon and Job and Joseph and Moses and Aaron. And thus We repay those who excel in doing good."
  6,85,"And Zechariah and John and Jesus and Elias—every one of them is of the righteous."
  6,86,"And Ishmael and Elijah and Jonah and Lot—and every one of them We favored over all communities."
  6,87,"And of their forefathers and their offspring<small>(s)</small> and their brethren—and We chose them and guided them to a straight path."
  6,88,"Such is Allah’s guidance; He guides with it whomever He wills of His servants. But had they associated <small>(others with God)</small>—whatever they used to do would have been nullified."
  6,89,"Those are the ones to whom We gave the Scripture and wise judgment and prophethood. So even if these people now disbelieve in them, we have surely entrusted them to others who do not reject them."
  6,90,"Those are the ones whom Allah has guided, so follow after their guidance. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “I ask of you no reward for it; it is just a reminder for all mankind.”"
  6,91,"And they did not value Allah as He should be valued when they said, “In no way has Allah sent down anything on any human being.” Say, “Who sent down the Scripture which Moses came with—a light and guidance for mankind? You<sup>pl</sup> <span class="h">make<sup foot_note="366244">1</sup></span> of it parchments, disclosing them and hiding much. And you<sup>pl</sup> were taught what you did not know—neither you, nor your forefathers.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Allah <small>(revealed it)</small>.” Then leave them in their indulgence in vain talk, playing.",footnotes:346707:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “They make of it parchments, disclosing them and hiding much.”</span>
  6,92,"And this is a Scripture that We sent down, blessed, confirming what preceded it, and that <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="366245">1</sup></span> may warn the Mother of Towns<sup foot_note="366246">2</sup> and those around it. Thus those who believe in the Hereafter believe in it, and they preserve their prayers.",footnotes:346708:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “… and that it may warn…”</span>|346709:Makkah.
  6,93,"For who is more unjust than someone who fabricated lies against Allah or said, “It was revealed to me,” when nothing had been revealed to him, and someone who said, “I will send down the like of what Allah has sent down”? And if only you<sup>sg</sup> could see the unjust ones in the perplexities of death as the angels stretch their hands: “Get yourselves out; today you are being repaid with the punishment of shame on account of what you used to say about Allah other than the truth, and for acting arrogantly towards His signs.”"
  6,94,"“And most surely you<sup>pl</sup> have come to Us individually, just as We created you the first time, and you have left behind your backs whatever We granted you. Yet We do not see with you your intercessors—those you claimed were associates in you. Most surely, the link between you <span class="h">was<sup foot_note="366247">1</sup></span> severed, and what you had claimed has strayed from you.”",footnotes:346710:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Hafs, Al-Kesa’i and Abu Ja’far read it as: “Most surely, the link between you became severed,”</span>
  6,95,"Indeed, Allah is the Splitter of the grain and the fruit stone. He brings out the living from the dead<sup foot_note="366248">1</sup>, and <small>(He is)</small> the Bringer Out of the dead from the living<sup foot_note="366249">2</sup> . Such is Allah, so how can you<sup>pl</sup> be averted <small>(from the truth)</small>?",footnotes:346711:A grammatical shift in Arabic from a nominal sentence to a verbal sentence.|346712:A grammatical shift in Arabic from a verbal sentence to a nominal sentence.
  6,96,"<small>(He is)</small> the Splitter of the daybreak, and He has <span class="h">made<sup foot_note="366250">1</sup></span> the night for rest and the sun and the moon for calculation; such is the determining of the Almighty, the All-Knowing.",footnotes:346713:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…and the Maker of the night (as a time) for rest…”</span>
  6,97,"And it is He Who made for you the stars, that you may be guided by them in the darkness<small>(es)</small> of land and sea. Surely, We<sup foot_note="366251">1</sup> have detailed the signs for people who know.",footnotes:346714:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 1 person to 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.
  6,98,"And it is He Who initiated you from a single self, then a place of <span class="h">settlement<sup foot_note="366252">1</sup></span> and a storage. Surely, We<sup foot_note="366253">2</sup> have detailed the signs for people who comprehend.",footnotes:346715:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Rouh read it as: “…then a settled one and a stored one.”</span>|346716:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 1 person to 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.
  6,99,"And it is He who sent down water from the sky, and with it We<sup foot_note="366254">1</sup> brought out the germination of everything, then We brought out from it greenery from which We bring out<sup foot_note="366255">2</sup> layered grain. And out of the palm-trees—from their spathes— clusters of dates, hanging low, and gardens of grapevines, and the olives, and the pomegranates—similar<sup foot_note="366256">3</sup> yet dissimilar<sup foot_note="366257">4</sup> . Look at its produce when it has yielded its produce and <small>(look at)</small> its ripening. Most surely in that are signs for people who believe.",footnotes:346717:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 1 person to 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.|346718:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense.|346719:In kind.|346720:In taste.
  6,100,"Yet they made for Allah associates—the unseen beings<sup foot_note="366258">1</sup> —although He created them, and they <span class="h">invented<sup foot_note="366259">2</sup></span> for Him sons and daughters, without <small>(any)</small> knowledge. Highly Exalted is He and Most High, far above what they describe.",footnotes:346721:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.|346722:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “...and they kept inventing for Him sons and daughters,”</span>
  6,101,"Originator of the heavens and the earth—how can He have offspring when He never had a consort? And He created everything, and He is All-Knowing of everything."
  6,102,"Such is Allah, your<sup>pl</sup> Lord; there is no God but He, the Creator of everything, so worship Him, for He is the Ultimate Trustee over everything."
  6,103,"Sight<small>(s)</small> cannot grasp Him, while He grasps all sight<small>(s)</small>, and He is the Subtle, the All-Aware."
  6,104,"“Insights have indeed come to you<sup>pl</sup> from your Lord, so whoever sees does so to his own benefit, while whoever remains blind does so to his own detriment. And I am not a constant preserver over you<sup>pl</sup>.”"
  6,105,"And thus We diversify the signs, and so that they say, “You<sup>sg</sup> have <span class="h">studied<sup foot_note="366260">1</sup></span>,” and so that We make it evident for people who have knowledge.",footnotes:346723:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “…they say, ‘You have studied with someone,’”Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “...they say, ‘(That is) outdated,’”</span>
  6,106,"Follow what was revealed to you from your Lord—there is no god but He—and disregard the polytheists."
  6,107,"And had Allah willed, they would not have associated <small>(others with Him)</small>. And We did not make you as a constant preserver over them, and in no way are you a trustee over them."
  6,108,"Yet do not insult those they call upon apart from Allah lest they insult Allah out of hostility, without knowledge. Thus We<sup foot_note="366261">1</sup> have adorned for every community their work, then to their Lord is their return, and He will inform them of what they used to do.",footnotes:346724:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 1 person to 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.
  6,109,"And they swore by Allah their most solemn oaths that if a sign were to come to them, they would believe in it. Say, “Signs are only with Allah,” but how do you know that <span class="h">even<sup foot_note="366262">1</sup></span> if it did come, <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="366263">2</sup></span> would still not believe?",footnotes:346725:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ya’qub, Khalaf and Shu’ba in one of his narrations read it as: “…but how do you know? Indeed, even if it did come…”</span>|346726:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Hamza read it as: “…you<sup>pl</sup> would still not believe?” would still not believe?”</span>
  6,110,"And We turn away their burning hearts and their sight<small>(s)</small> as they did not believe in it the first time, and We leave them to wander aimlessly while exceeding all limits."
  6,111,"And even if We bestowed the angels upon them from on high and the dead spoke to them and We herded everything before them, they would still not believe unless Allah wills, but most of them are ignorant."
  6,112,"And thus We made for every prophet an enemy—Satans from among humans and unseen beings<sup foot_note="366264">1</sup> —revealing to one another fancy words in order to deceive. But had your<sup>sg</sup> Lord<sup foot_note="366265">2</sup> willed, they would not have done it, so leave them to their fabrications.",footnotes:346727:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.|346728:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  6,113,"And so that the burning hearts of those who do not believe in the Hereafter may incline to it, and that they may be well pleased with it, and that they may perpetrate whatever they perpetrate."
  6,114,"“Shall I seek a judge other than Allah when He is the One Who sent down to you the Scripture, explained in detail?” And those to whom We gave the Scripture know that it is the truth, bestowed from on <span class="h">high<sup foot_note="366266">1</sup></span> by your Lord<sup foot_note="366267">2</sup>, so never be<sup>sg</sup> of those who doubt.",footnotes:346729:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Amer and Hafs read it as: “…sent down by your Lord,”</span>|346730:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  6,115,"Thus the <span class="h">Word<sup foot_note="366268">1</sup></span> of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord has been completed, in truth and justice. None can change His words, and He is the All-Hearing, the All-Knowing.",footnotes:346731:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “Thus the Words of your Lord have been…”</span>
  6,116,"But if you<sup>sg</sup> were to obey most of those on earth, they would make you stray from the way of Allah. They follow nothing but assumptions, and they do nothing but guess."
  6,117,"Indeed, your Lord is the One who knows better about who strays from His way, and it is He who knows better about who the guided are."
  6,118,"So eat<sup>pl</sup> of that over which the Name of Allah has been mentioned<sup foot_note="366269">1</sup>, if you indeed believe in His signs<sup foot_note="366270">2</sup> .",footnotes:346732:The Arabic word used also means ‘remembered’.|346733:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  6,119,"And why should you not eat of that over which the Name of Allah has been mentioned<sup foot_note="366271">1</sup> when He <span class="h">has<sup foot_note="366272">2</sup></span> detailed for you what He <span class="h">has<sup foot_note="366273">3</sup></span> prohibited for you, except that to which you are compelled? And many do indeed lead <span class="h"><small>(others)</small><sup foot_note="366274">4</sup></span> astray with their whims without <small>(any)</small> knowledge. Indeed, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord knows better who the transgressors are.",footnotes:346734:The Arabic word used also means ‘remembered’.|346735:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Nafie’, Hafs, Abu Ja’far, Ya’qub, Shu’ba, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…when what has been prohibited for you has been detailed for you,”</span>|346736:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “….when He has detailed for you what has been prohibited for you,”</span>|346737:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, and Khalaf read it as: “And many do indeed go astray with their whims…”</span>
  6,120,"So leave<sup>pl</sup> aside apparent sin as well as what is concealed thereof. Indeed, those who earn sin will definitely be repaid on account of what they used to perpetrate."
  6,121,"And do not eat from that over which the Name of Allah was not mentioneda, for it is grave disobedience. And the Satans do indeed reveal to their allies to argue with you<sup>pl</sup>; but if you obey them, you would surely be polytheists."
  6,122,"Is he who was lifeless, then We revived him and made for him a light by which he walks among mankind, as one whose likeness is in darkness<small>(es)</small>, never emerging from them? Thus whatever the deniers have been doing was adorned for them."
  6,123,"And thus We set up in every town its leading criminals to scheme in it, but they scheme only against themselves, though they are unaware."
  6,124,"And when a sign comes to them, they say, “We will not believe unless we are brought the like of what was brought to Allah’s messengers.” Allah knows better where to set His <span class="h">message<sup foot_note="366275">1</sup></span>. Abasement <small>(decreed)</small> by Allah will afflict those who committed crimes, and severe punishment <small>(too)</small>, on account of what they used to scheme.",footnotes:346738:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Kathir and Hafs read it as: “…His messages.”</span>
  6,125,"Whomever Allah wants to guide, He expands his chest to <small>(accept)</small> Islam; and whomever He wants to lead astray, He makes his chest tight, <span class="h">constricted<sup foot_note="366276">1</sup></span>, as though he were gradually <span class="h">ascending<sup foot_note="366277">2</sup></span> in the sky. Allah thus lays abomination upon those who do not believe.",footnotes:346739:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Shu’ba and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…He makes his chest tight, very constricted,”</span>|346740:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “as though he were ascending in the sky.”Shu’ba read it as: “…as though he were ascending on and on in the sky.”</span>
  6,126,"And this is your Lord’s path, straight. We<sup foot_note="366278">1</sup> have surely detailed the signs for people who constantly remember.",footnotes:346741:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 1 person to 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.
  6,127,"For them is the Home of Peace with their Lord, and He is their Ultimate Guardian on account of what they used to do."
  6,128,"Thus on the day He <span class="h">herds<sup foot_note="366279">1</sup></span> them all together: “O assembly of unseen beings<sup foot_note="366280">2</sup>, you have surely done so much against humans.” But their allies among humans said<sup foot_note="366281">3</sup>, “Our Lord, we enjoyed one another, and we have reached the term that you have assigned for us.” He said, “The Fire is your dwelling, wherein you abide, except as Allah wills. Indeed, your Lord is All-Wise, All-Knowing.",footnotes:346742:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs and Rouh read it as: “…We herd them…”</span>|346743:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.|346744:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  6,129,"And thus We make the unjust allies of one another on account of what they used to earn."
  6,130,"“O assembly of unseen beings<sup foot_note="366282">1</sup> and humans, did there not come to you messengers from among you, relating to you My signs and warning you of the meeting of this day of yours?” They said, “We have <small>(now)</small> testified against ourselves.” And the Earlier Life deceived them, and they testified against themselves that they were deniers.",footnotes:346745:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.
  6,131,"That is because your<sup>sg</sup> Lord would never destroy towns unjustly while their inhabitants are oblivious."
  6,132,"And for all there are degrees <small>(of rank)</small> according to how <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="366283">1</sup></span> acted, and your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is not oblivious of how they act.",footnotes:346746:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “…how you acted,”</span>
  6,133,"Thus your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is the Self-Sufficient, the Possessor of mercy. If He wills, He can do away with youpl and give succession after you to whomever He wills, just as He initiated you from the offspring of other people."
  6,134,"Indeed, what you are promised is coming, and in no way can you thwart <small>(God)</small>."
  6,135,"Say, “O my people, act according to your <span class="h">position<sup foot_note="366284">1</sup></span>, surely, I am also acting <small>(according to mine)</small>; then you will come to know who will have the future outcome of the <small>(final) </small>Home. Indeed, the unjust never succeed.”",footnotes:346747:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “…your positions”</span>
  6,136,"And they set aside for Allah a share of the <small>(yield of the)</small> fields and the livestock He created, and they said, “This is for Allah,” according to their claim, “and this is for our associates.” But whatever was <small>(deemed)</small> for their associates does not reach Allah, yet whatever was <small>(deemed)</small> for Allah reaches their associates. Evil is their judgment!"
  6,137,"Likewise, their associates have adorned for many polytheists the killing of their <span class="h">children<sup foot_note="366285">1</sup></span> in order to topple them and confound for them their religion. And had Allah willed, they would not have done it, so leave them and what they fabricate.",footnotes:346748:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “Likewise, for many polytheists, the killing of their children has been adorned by their associates in order to…”</span>
  6,138,"And they said, “Such livestock and fields are restricted; none may eat of them except whom we will,” by their claims, and livestock whose backs were forbidden, and livestock over which they do not mention<sup foot_note="366286">1</sup> the name of Allah—fabricating lies against Him. He will repay them on account of what they used to fabricate.",footnotes:346749:The Arabic word used also means ‘remember’.
  6,139,"And they said, “What lies in the bellies of such livestock is exclusively for our males and prohibited to our spouses.” But if it is stillborn, they can share in it. He will repay them for their description. Indeed, He is All-Wise, All-Knowing."
  6,140,"Lost indeed are those who <span class="h">killed<sup foot_note="366287">1</sup></span> their children foolishly with no basis in knowledge, and forbade what Allah had provided for them by fabricating <small>(lies)</small> against Allah. Surely, they went astray and never were they guided.",footnotes:346750:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Ibn ‘Amer read it as: …who kept killing their children…”</span>
  6,141,"And it is He Who initiated gardens, both cultivated and wild, and date-palms and vegetation of diverse crops and olives and pomegranates, similar yet dissimilar. Eatpl of its produce when it has yielded its produce and bring its due on the day of its harvest, and do not be extravagant; surely He does not love the extravagant<sup foot_note="366288">1</sup> .",footnotes:346751:The same Arabic word, <i>musrifeen,</i> is used for extremists.
  6,142,"And of the livestock are load carriers and those too small. Eat of what Allah has provided you and do not follow the footsteps of Satan; indeed, he is to you an evident enemy."
  6,143,"<small>(Suppose there are)</small> eight pairs: of sheep there are two <small>(pairs)</small> and of goats there are two. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Did He forbid the two males or the two females or what the wombs of the two females contain? Inform<sup>pl</sup> me with knowledge, if you are truthful.”"
  6,144,"And of camels there are two, and of cattle there are two. Say, “Did He forbid the two males or the two females or what the wombs of the two females contain? Or were you witnesses when Allah admonished you with this?” So who is more unjust than one who fabricated lies against Allah in order to lead mankind astray without knowledge? Indeed, Allah does not guide unjust people."
  6,145,"Say, “In what was revealed to me, I find nothing forbidden to any eater who would eat it, except carrion or flowing blood or the flesh of swine—because it is an abomination—or an ungodly offering dedicated to other than Allah. But if anyone is compelled by necessity without being deliberate or transgressing, then indeed, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  6,146,"And for the ones who have Judaized We have forbidden everything with claws, and of cattle and sheep We have forbidden them their fat—except what is carried on theirdl backs or the entrails or what is mixed with bone. This is how We repaid them for their oppression, and very truly, We are truthful."
  6,147,"So if they disbelieve you, then say, “Your Lord is Possessor of all-embracing mercy, but His chastisement is never turned back from the criminal people.”"
  6,148,"Those who associated <small>(others with God)</small> will say, “Had Allah willed, we would not have associated <small>(others with Him)</small>, nor would have our forefathers, nor would we have prohibited anything.” Likewise, those before them disbelieved until they tasted Our chastisement. Say, “Do you have any knowledge that you can bring forth for us? You follow nothing but assumptions, and you do nothing but guess.”"
  6,149,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Yet to Allah belongs the conclusive argument, so had He willed, He would have guided you all.”"
  6,150,"Say, “Bring your witnesses who would testify that Allah has prohibited this.” So if they testify, do not testify with them. And do not follow the whims of those who disbelieved in Our signs and those who do not believe in the Hereafter and who equate others with their Lord."
  6,151,"Say, “Come, let me tell you<sup>pl</sup> what your Lord has forbidden: that you shall not associate anything with Him, and towards your parents you shall show kindness, and you shall not kill your children because of poverty—We provide for you and for them, and you shall not come near obscenities—what is apparent of it and what is concealed, and you shall not kill the self which Allah has made inviolable—except in the course of justice. All this He has enjoined upon you, that you may reason."
  6,152,"And you shall not come near the wealth of the orphan except with the best <small>(intentions)</small> until he reaches his full strength. And you shall give full weight and full measure with justice—We never task any self beyond its capacity. And when you<sup>pl</sup><small> </small>speak, you shall be fair, even if it concerns a relative. And you shall fulfil your covenant with Allah. All this He has enjoined upon you, that you may <span class="h">remember<sup foot_note="366289">1</sup></span>.”",footnotes:346752:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…that you may remind yourselves."</span>
  6,153,"<span class="h">And<sup foot_note="366290">1</sup></span><small>(know that)</small> this is My path, straight, so follow<sup>pl</sup> it. And do not follow the <small>(other)</small> ways, lest they divert <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="366291">2</sup></span> from His way. All this He has enjoined upon you, that you may be mindful <small>(of God)</small>.",footnotes:346753:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “And indeed, this is my path,”</span>|346754:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Bazzy read it as: “…lest they divert with you from His way.”</span>
  6,154,"Then We brought Moses the Scripture, perfect for the one who excelled in doing good, and detailing everything, and guidance and mercy, that they may believe in the meeting with their Lord."
  6,155,"And this <small>(too)</small> is a blessed Scripture that We sent down, so follow<sup>pl</sup> it and be righteous, that you may receive mercy."
  6,156,"Lest you<sup>pl</sup> say, “The Scripture was sent down to two factions before us, and we were indeed oblivious of their teachings.”"
  6,157,"Or lest you say, “Had the Scripture been sent down to us, we would have been better guided than them.” Most surely, an evident explanation has come to you from your Lord, and guidance and mercy. Who then does greater injustice than one who considered Allah's signs to be a lie and kept turning away from them? We<sup foot_note="366292">1</sup> will repay those who keep turning away from Our signs with the worst kind of punishment on account of how they used to constantly turn away.",footnotes:346755:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 1 person to 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.
  6,158,"Are they waiting for anything but for the angels to come to them or for your Lord to come or for some of your Lord’s signs to come? On the day when some of your Lord’s signs come, no self will benefit from attaining faith unless it had attained faith previously or had earned goodness through its faith. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Wait; indeed, we too are waiting.”"
  6,159,"Indeed, the ones who have caused disunity <span class="h">in<sup foot_note="366293">1</sup></span> their religion and became sects—you<sup>sg</sup> have nothing to do with them. Rather, their case rests with Allah, then He informs them of what they used to do.",footnotes:346756:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…the ones who have departed from their religion…”</span>
  6,160,"Whoever has come up with a good deed—for him there is ten times its <span class="h">like<sup foot_note="366294">1</sup></span>, and whoever has come up with an evil deed will be repaid only with its equivalent, and they will not be dealt with unjustly.",footnotes:346757:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…for him there are ten (others) like it,”</span>
  6,161,"Say, “Surely <small>(as for)</small> myself, my Lord has guided me to a straight path—an upright <span class="h">religion<sup foot_note="366295">1</sup></span>—the creed of Abraham who turned away from all that is false, and never was he one of the polytheists.”",footnotes:346758:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…a truly upright religion—”</span>
  6,162,"Say, “Indeed, my prayer and my rites and my way of living and my way of dying are for Allah, Lord of all realms."
  6,163,"No associate is there for Him, and to this I have been commanded, and I am the first of the Muslims<sup foot_note="366296">1</sup> .",footnotes:346759:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  6,164,"Say, “Am I to seek a Lord other than Allah when He is the Lord of everything?” And not a single self earns except what it is due, and no bearer of burden bears the burden of another. Then to your<sup>pl</sup> Lord is your return, then He will inform you regarding whatever you used to differ over."
  6,165,"And it is He Who made you successors on the earth and elevated some of you by degrees over others in order to test you through what He has brought you. Indeed, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is Swift in punishment, and He is most surely Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  7,1,"Alif Lām Mīm Sâd."
  7,2,"A Scripture which was sent down to you<small>sg</small>, so let there be no discomfort in your chest because of it, that you may warn with it, and a reminding for the believers:"
  7,3,"“Follow<sup>pl</sup> what was sent down to you from your Lord, and do not follow other guardians apart from Him. Little do you remind <span class="h">yourselves<sup foot_note="366297">1</sup></span>.”",footnotes:346760:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “Little do they remind themselves.”All the others except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Little do you remember.”</span>
  7,4,"And how many a town have We annihilated, such that Our chastisement came upon them while sleeping at night or while they were napping at noon."
  7,5,"But their only cry when Our chastisement came upon them was, “We were indeed unjust.”"
  7,6,"We will most surely ask those to whom messages were sent, and We will most surely ask the emissaries."
  7,7,"Then We will most surely relate to them with knowledge, for We were never absent."
  7,8,"And the scale on that day is the truth. So those whose scales weigh heavy—those are the successful,"
  7,9,"while those whose scales weigh light—those are the ones who have lost themselves on account of the injustice they used to do regarding our signs."
  7,10,"And very truly We have established you<small>pl</small> in the earth and made for you in it livelihood. Rarely do you give thanks."
  7,11,"And very truly We created you, then We designed you, then We said to the angels, “Prostrate to Adam.” So they prostrated—but not Iblis<sup foot_note="366298">1</sup> ; he was not of those who prostrated themselves.",footnotes:346761:Iblis is another name of Satan or <i>Shaytan</i>.
  7,12,"He said, “What prevented you from prostrating yourself when I commanded you?” He said, “I am better than him; You created me from fire and created him from clay.”"
  7,13,"He said, “So get down from it, for it is not for you to behave arrogantly in it. So get out! You are indeed one of the belittled!”"
  7,14,"He said, “Reprieve me until the day they are resurrected.”"
  7,15,"He said, “You are indeed of those reprieved.”"
  7,16,"He said, “So because You have deluded me, I will most surely waylay them on Your straight path."
  7,17,"Then I will most surely come at them from before them and from behind them and from their right and from their left, and you will not find most of them appreciative.”"
  7,18,"He said, “Get out of it, despised, vanquished; whoever of them follows you—I will most surely fill up Hell with you all."
  7,19,"And O Adam, settle in the Garden, you and your spouse, and eat of whatever you<sup>dl</sup> wish. But neither one of you shall approach this tree lest you<sup>dl</sup> become of the unjust.”"
  7,20,"But Satan whispered to them<sup>dl</sup> to reveal to them what had been covered from them of their private parts. And he said, “Your<sup>dl</sup> Lord has only forbidden you<sup>dl</sup> this tree lest you<sup>dl</sup> become angels or become of the immortals.”"
  7,21,"And he swore to them<sup>dl</sup>, “I am most surely a sincere advisor to you<sup>dl</sup>.”"
  7,22,"So he lured them<sup>dl</sup> with deceit. So when they<sup>dl</sup> tasted the tree, their private parts became visible to them and they began covering themselves with the leaves of the Garden, and their Lord called out to them<sup>dl</sup>, “Did I not forbid you both from this tree and tell you<sup>dl</sup> that Satan is an evident enemy to you?”"
  7,23,"They<sup>dl</sup> said, “Our Lord, we have been unjust to ourselves. And unless You forgive us and have mercy on us, we will certainly be of the losers.”"
  7,24,"He said, “Descend<sup>pl</sup> as enemies to one another, and in the earth you will have a place of settlement and enjoyment for a while.”"
  7,25,"He said, “In it you<sup>pl</sup> live, and in it you die, and from it you are brought <span class="h">out<sup foot_note="366299">1</sup></span>.”",footnotes:346762:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Zekwan, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “…and from it you come out.”</span>
  7,26,"O Children of Adam, We have sent down upon you garments to cover your private parts and for luxury. But the <span class="h">garment<sup foot_note="366300">1</sup></span> of mindfulness <small>(of God)</small>—that is better. That is of Allah’s signs, that they<sup foot_note="366301">2</sup> may constantly remember.",footnotes:346763:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer, Al-Kesa’i and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…and for luxury and the garment of mindfulness (of God)—that is good.”</span>|346764:A grammatical shift from 2<sup>nd</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  7,27,"O Children of Adam, never let Satan lure you like he brought your parents out of the Garden, stripping them of their garments to show them their private parts. He surely sees you, He and his clan, from where you cannot see them. Indeed, We have made the Satans allies of those who do not believe."
  7,28,"And when they commit an obscenity, they say, “We found our fathers doing this, and Allah has commanded us to do it.” Say, “Indeed, Allah does not command to obscenities. Are you<sup>pl</sup> saying about Allah what you know not?”"
  7,29,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “My Lord has commanded justice. And set your faces upright at every mosque<sup foot_note="366302">1</sup> and call upon Him, devoting religion to Him. Just as He originated you<sup>pl</sup>, so you will return.”",footnotes:346765:The Arabic word used is <i>masjid</i> which literally means ‘a place for prostration’.
  7,30,"A group He has guided and another group has deserved misguidance. They have taken the Satans as guardians apart from Allah and they assume that they are guided."
  7,31,"O Children of Adam, take your adornment at every mosque<sup foot_note="366303">1</sup>, and eat and drink, but do not be extravagant; surely He does not love the extravagant<sup foot_note="366304">2</sup> .",footnotes:346766:The Arabic word used is <i>masjid</i> which literally means ‘a place for prostration’.|346767:The same Arabic word, <i>musrifeen,</i> is used for extremists.
  7,32,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Who has forbidden Allah’s adornment which He has brought out for His servants and the good things among <small>(His)</small> provision?” Say, “They are for those who attained faith in the Earlier Life,<small> <span class="h"></span></small>exclusively<sup foot_note="366305">1</sup> theirs on the Day of Resurrection.” Thus We detail the signs<sup foot_note="366306">2</sup> for people who know.",footnotes:346768:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ read it as: “Say, ‘They are, for those who attained faith in the Earlier Life, exclusive on the Day of Resurrection.’”</span>|346769:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  7,33,"Say, “Indeed, My Lord has only forbidden obscenities—both manifest and secret—and sin and unjustified aggression, and that you associate with Allah that for which He has never bestowed any authority from on <span class="h">high<sup foot_note="366307">1</sup></span>, and that you say about Allah what you know not.”",footnotes:346770:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…for which He has never sent down any authority,”</span>
  7,34,"And for every community there is an appointed term. So when their term has arrived, they cannot then delay by one hour nor can they advance."
  7,35,"O Children of Adam, whenever messengers from among you come to you, relating to you My signs<sup foot_note="366308">1</sup>, then whoever becomes mindful <small>(of God)</small> and reforms—no <span class="h">fear<sup foot_note="366309">2</sup></span> shall be upon them<sup foot_note="366310">3</sup> nor shall they grieve.",footnotes:346771:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.|346772:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…no fear shall ever be upon them nor shall they grieve.”</span>|346773:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  7,36,"But those who disbelieved in Our signs and were too arrogant to accept them—those are the fellows of the Fire; therein they abide."
  7,37,"So who is more unjust than someone who has fabricated lies against Allah or has considered His signs to be a lie? Those<sup foot_note="366311">1</sup> —their share of the decree will reach them. Until, when Our messengers have come to them to take their souls <small>(at death)</small>, they say, “Where is whatever you used to call upon apart from Allah?” They say, “They have strayed from us,” and they testify against themselves that they were deniers.",footnotes:346774:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  7,38,"He said<sup foot_note="366312">1</sup>, “Enter with the communities of unseen beings<sup foot_note="366313">2</sup> and humans who have gone into the Fire before you.” Every time a community entered, it cursed its sister-community till, when they were all in it, the last of them said about the first of them, “Our Lord, these are the ones who led us astray, so bring upon them double punishment in the Fire.” He said, “Each will have double, but <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="366314">3</sup></span> know not.”",footnotes:346775:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.|346776:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.|346777:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “…but they know not.”</span>
  7,39,"And the first of them said to the last of them, “Thus you had no advantage over us, so taste the punishment on account of what you used to earn.”"
  7,40,"Indeed, those who disbelieved in Our signs and were too arrogant to accept them—the gates of the heaven<small> </small>will not be widely <span class="h">opened<sup foot_note="366315">1</sup></span> for them, nor will they enter the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> until the camel<sup foot_note="366316">2</sup> passes through the eye of the needle. And thus We repay the criminals.",footnotes:346778:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…the gates of Heaven will not be opened for them,”</span>|346779:The Arabic word used is <i>jamal</i> which also means ‘thick rope’.
  7,41,"For them is Hell as a resting place, and above them are sheets of fire. And thus We repay the unjust<sup>pl</sup>."
  7,42,"But those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—We never task any self beyond its capacity—those are the fellows of the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small>; therein they abide."
  7,43,"And We removed<sup foot_note="366317">1</sup> whatever malice was within their chests; rivers flow beneath them. And they said, “Praise be to Allah who has guided us to this, <span class="h">for<sup foot_note="366318">2</sup></span> never would we have been guided had Allah not guided us; most surely, the messengers of our Lord did come with the truth.” And it was called out to them, “This is the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> you are made to inherit on account of what you used to do.”",footnotes:346780:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.|346781:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “Praise be to Allah who has guided us to this. Never would we have been guided had Allah not guided us;”</span>
  7,44,"And the fellows of the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> called out to the fellows of the Fire, “We certainly found what our Lord had promised us to be true, so did you find what your Lord had promised you to be true?” They said, “Yes.” Thereupon an announcer called out in their midst, <span class="h">“Let<sup foot_note="366319">1</sup></span> the curse of Allah be upon the unjust,",footnotes:346782:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Nafie’, Qunbul, Abu Amr, Asem and Ya’qub read it as “‘Indeed, the curse of Allah is upon the unjust,’”</span>
  7,45,"who bar <small>(people)</small> from the way of Allah and seek to make it crooked, while regarding the Hereafter they are deniers.”"
  7,46,"And between them is<sup foot_note="366320">1</sup> a partition, and on the elevations are men who recognize everyone by their features. And they called<sup foot_note="366321">2</sup> to the fellows of the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small>, “Peace be upon you.” They have not entered it, but they are ardently hoping.",footnotes:346783:A grammatical shift to present tense, which serves to create a vivid portrait of future events.|346784:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  7,47,"And when their sight<small>(s)</small> are directed towards the fellows of the Fire, they say, “Our Lord, do not place us with the unjust people.”"
  7,48,"Then the fellows of the elevations called<sup foot_note="366322">1</sup> out to men whom they recognize by their features. They said, “In no way did your multitude avail you, nor did your arrogance.”",footnotes:346785:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  7,49,"“Are these the ones you<sup>pl</sup> swore Allah would not touch with mercy? Enter the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small>; no fear is upon you, nor shall you grieve.”"
  7,50,"And the fellows of the Fire called out to the fellows of the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small>, “Pour some water over us or some of what Allah has provided for you.” They said, “Allah has indeed forbidden them for the deniers"
  7,51,"who took their religion as a distraction and a game, and whom the Earlier Life deceived." So today We forget them like they forgot the meeting on this day of theirs and for how they used to repudiate Our signs."
  7,52,"And most surely, We have given them a Scripture which We have detailed with knowledge—guidance and mercy for people who believe."
  7,53,"Are they waiting for anything but its fulfillment? The day its fulfillment comes true, those who forgot it earlier will say, “The messengers of our Lord did come with the truth, so do we have any intercessors to intercede for us? Or could we be returned back to behave differently from the way we behaved before?” They have certainly lost themselves, and whatever they used to fabricate strayed away from them."
  7,54,"Indeed, your<sup>pl</sup> Lord is Allah, the One who created the heavens and the earth in six days<sup foot_note="366323">1</sup> then settled over the Throne. He causes the night to <span class="h">overwhelm<sup foot_note="366324">2</sup></span> the day, pursuing it persistently, <span class="h">for<sup foot_note="366325">3</sup></span> the sun and the moon and the stars are subjected by His command. Truly, His is the creation and the command. Supremely Blessed be Allah, Lord of all realms.",footnotes:346786:Six equal intervals of time, which may be six heavenly days, each of them being 1000 earthly years long (see surah 22, verse 47).|346787:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “He causes the night to tightly overwhelm the day,”</span>|346788:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “…persistently. And the sun and the moon and the stars are subjected by His command.”</span>
  7,55,"Call upon your Lord in supplication and in secret. Indeed, He does not love the transgressors."
  7,56,"And do not corrupt the earth after its reformation, and call upon Him with fear and ardent hope. Indeed, Allah’s mercy is close to those who excel in doing good."
  7,57,"And it is He Who sends the <span class="h">winds<sup foot_note="366326">1</sup></span> as heralds of glad <span class="h">tidings<sup foot_note="366327">2</sup></span> ahead of His mercy until, when they carry up heavy clouds, We<sup foot_note="366328">3</sup> drive them to a lifeless land where We send down water, and with it We bring out all kinds of products. Thus We bring out the dead, that you may remind <span class="h">yourselves<sup foot_note="366329">4</sup></span>.",footnotes:346789:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “wind”.</span>|346790:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “… as a revival ahead of His mercy”. All others read it as: “…as revivers ahead of His mercy”.</span>|346791:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 1 person to 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.|346792:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…that you may constantly remember”.</span>
  7,58,"And the good land—its plants come out by the leave of its Lord, whereas that which has become nasty does not come <span class="h">out<sup foot_note="366330">1</sup></span> unless useless. Thus We<sup foot_note="366331">2</sup> diversify the signs for people who give thanks.",footnotes:346793:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Wardan, in one of his narrations, read it as: "…which has become nasty does not bring out except the useless.”</span>|346794:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 1 person to 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.
  7,59,"Very truly, We sent Noah to his people. So he said, “O my people, worship Allah; you have no god other than Him. Indeed, I fear for you the punishment of a great day.”"
  7,60,"The chiefs of his people said, “We surely see that you are in evident misguidance.”"
  7,61,"He said, “O my people, there is no misguidance in me, but I am a messenger from the Lord of all realms."
  7,62,"I <span class="h">proclaim<sup foot_note="366332">1</sup></span> to you the messages of my Lord and I advise you, and I know from Allah what you do not know.",footnotes:346795:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “I compile and proclaim to you…”</span>
  7,63,"Are you amazed that a reminder has come to you from your Lord upon a man from among you, to warn you and that you might be mindful <small>(of God)</small> and that you may receive mercy?”"
  7,64,"But they disbelieved him, so We saved him and those with him in the ship, and We drowned those who disbelieved in Our signs. Indeed, they were a blind people."
  7,65,"And to Ād, their brother Hud. He said, “O my people, worship Allah; you have no god other than Him. Will you not be mindful <small>(of Him)</small>?”"
  7,66,"The chiefs of his people, who denied, said, “We surely see that you are in foolishness and we surely think that you are one of the liars.”"
  7,67,"He said, “O my people, there is no foolishness in me, but I am a messenger from the Lord of all realms."
  7,68,"I <span class="h">proclaim<sup foot_note="366333">1</sup></span> to you the messages of my Lord, and I am a trustworthy adviser to you.",footnotes:346796:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “I compile and proclaim to you…”</span>
  7,69,"Are you amazed that a reminder has come to you from your Lord upon a man from among you, to warn you? And call to mind when He made you successors after the people of Noah and increased you greatly in stature, and remember Allah’s blessings, that you may succeed.”"
  7,70,"They said, “Have you come to us in order for us to worship Allah alone and leave what our forefathers used to worship? So bring us what you threaten us with, if you are one of the truthful.”"
  7,71,"He said, “Abomination and wrath have surely befallen you from your Lord. Are you arguing with me over names which you and your forefathers invented, for which Allah sent down no authority? So wait; I am indeed with you among those waiting.”"
  7,72,"So We saved him and those with him by mercy from Us, and We cut off the roots of those who disbelieved in Our signs and never attained faith."
  7,73,"And to Thamûd, their brother Saleh. He said, “O my people, worship Allah; you have no god other than Him; an evident proof has certainly come to you from your Lord: this she-camel of Allah is a sign for you, so let her eat in Allah’s land and do not touch her with any harm lest a painful punishment seize you.”"
  7,74,"“And call to mind when He made you successors after Ād and settled you in the land, taking for yourselves palaces on its plains and carving out houses of the mountains. So remember Allah’s marvels and do not go wickedly about the land, corrupting it.”"
  7,75,"<span class="h">The<sup foot_note="366334">1</sup></span> chiefs of his people, who acted arrogantly, said to those who had been deemed weak and oppressed—those who had attained faith from among them, “Do you know that Saleh is an emissary from his Lord?” They said, “We are indeed believers in what he has been sent with.”",footnotes:346797:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “And the chiefs of his people…”</span>
  7,76,"Those who acted arrogantly said, “Indeed, we deny what you believe in.”"
  7,77,"So they hamstrung the she-camel and defied the command of their Lord and said, “O Saleh, bring upon us what you threaten us with, if you are one of the emissaries.”"
  7,78,"Thereupon the Tremor overtook them, and they became lifeless bodies in their home."
  7,79,"Then he turned away from them and said, “O my people, I have proclaimed to you the message of my Lord and I have advised you, but you do not like those who give advice.”"
  7,80,"And Lot, when he said to his people, “Do you commit such obscenity with which no one in all communities has preceded you?”"
  7,81,"<span class="h">“You<sup foot_note="366335">1</sup></span> do approach men with desire instead of women. Rather, you are an extremist people.”",footnotes:346798:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Nafie’, Hafs, Abu Ja’far and Al-Sousi read it as: “‘Can it be that you do approach men with desire instead of women? Rather, you are …..’”</span>
  7,82,"And his people's only response was to say, “Evict them from your town; indeed, they are a group of people who always keep themselves clean.”"
  7,83,"So We saved him and his family, except for his woman; she was of those who lingered behind."
  7,84,"And We rained down on them a rain! So look what the outcome was for the criminals."
  7,85,"And to Midian, their brother Shuaib. He said, “O my people, worship Allah; you have no god other than Him; an evident proof has come to you from your Lord, so give full measure and balance, and do not defraud people of their belongings, and do not corrupt the land once it has been reformed. That is better for you, if you are believers."
  7,86,"And do not sit on every path, making threats and barring from the way of Allah those who have attained faith in Him, seeking to make it crooked. And call to mind when you were few, then He made you numerous. So look what the outcome was for the corrupters."
  7,87,"And since a faction of you have come to believe in what I was sent with and a faction have not come to believe, then be patient until Allah judges between us, for He is the Best of judges.”"
  7,88,"The chiefs of his people, who acted arrogantly, said “O Shuaib, We will surely evict you from our town, along with those who have attained faith with you, unless you do indeed return to our creed.” He said, “Even if we are reluctant?"
  7,89,"We would definitely be fabricating lies against Allah if we were to return to your creed after Allah has delivered us from it. And it is not for us to return to it unless Allah, our Lord, wills. Our Lord has encompassed everything in knowledge. In Allah we have placed our trust. Our Lord, legislate<sup foot_note="366336">1</sup> justly between us and our people, for You are the Best of legislators.”",footnotes:346799:The Arabic word used is <i>iftah</i> which means ‘open’.
  7,90,"And the chiefs of his people, who denied, said, “If you follow Shuaib, you will definitely be losers.”"
  7,91,"Thereupon, the Tremor overtook them, and they became lifeless bodies in their home."
  7,92,"Those who disbelieved Shuaib—<small>(it was) </small>as if they never prospered therein. Those who disbelieved Shuaib—it was they who were the losers."
  7,93,"So he turned away from them and said, “O my people, I have proclaimed to you the messages of my Lord and I have advised you, so how should I grieve over a denying people<sup foot_note="366337">1</sup> ?”",footnotes:346800:A grammatical shift from 2<sup>nd</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  7,94,"And never did We send any prophet to any town but We afflicted its people with misery and adversity, that they may earnestly supplicate <small>(Us)</small>."
  7,95,"Then We substituted good in place of evil until they thrived and said, “Adversity and prosperity have touched our forefathers.” Then We seized them suddenly while they were unaware."
  7,96,"Yet had the people of the towns attained faith and become mindful <small>(of God)</small>, We would surely have <span class="h">opened<sup foot_note="366338">1</sup></span> for them blessings from the heaven and the earth. But they disbelieved, so We seized them for what they used to earn.",footnotes:346801:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Roways read it as: “…We would surely have widely opened for them…”</span>
  7,97,"Do the fellows of the towns feel secure that Our chastisement will not come upon them by night while they are sleeping?"
  7,98,"And do the fellows of the towns really feel <span class="h">secure<sup foot_note="366339">1</sup></span> that Our chastisement will not come upon them by day while they are playing?",footnotes:346802:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “Or do the fellows of the towns feel secure that Our chastisement will not…”</span>
  7,99,"Do they feel safe from Allah’s scheme? None feel safe from Allah’s scheme except people who are losers."
  7,100,"Is it not guidance for those who inherit the land after its fellows that if We willed, We could strike them for their misdeeds, and seal up their hearts so that they would not hear?"
  7,101,"These towns—We relate to you some of their stories. For very truly their messengers came to them with evident proofs, but they would not believe in what they had disbelieved earlier. Thus Allah seals the hearts of the deniers."
  7,102,"And We did not find most of them true to their covenants; rather, We did find most of them defiantly disobedient."
  7,103,"Then, after them, We sent Moses with Our signs to Pharaoh and his chiefs, but they did injustice to them. So look what the outcome was for the corrupters."
  7,104,"And Moses said, “O Pharaoh, I am a messenger from the Lord of all realms,"
  7,105,"committed to <span class="h">saying<sup foot_note="366340">1</sup></span> nothing about Allah but the truth. I have surely come to you<sup>pl</sup> with an evident proof from your Lord, so send<sup>sg</sup> with me the Children of Israel.”",footnotes:346803:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ read it as: “…realms. It is a commitment upon me to say nothing about Allah but the truth.</span>
  7,106,"He said, “If you have come with a sign, then present it, if you are of the truthful.”"
  7,107,"So he cast his staff and, lo and behold, it was an evident serpent!"
  7,108,"And He pulled out his hand and, lo and behold, it was white for the viewers!"
  7,109,"The chiefs among Pharaoh’s people said, “This is most surely a knowledgeable sorcerer"
  7,110,"who wants to evict you from your land, so what is it that you command?”"
  7,111,"They said, “Put him off, and his brother, and send summoners to the cities"
  7,112,"to bring you every knowledgeable <span class="h">sorcerer<sup foot_note="366341">1</sup></span>.”",footnotes:346804:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “to bring you every knowledgeable, proficient sorcerer”.</span>
  7,113,"Thus the sorcerers came to Pharaoh. They said, “Surely there is a <span class="h">reward<sup foot_note="366342">1</sup></span> for us if we are the overcomers.”",footnotes:346805:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Nafie’, Hafs, Ibn Kathir and Abu Ja’far read it as: “‘Is there a reward for us if we are the overcomers?’”</span>
  7,114,"He said, “Yes, and you will most surely become of those brought near <small>(to me)</small>.”"
  7,115,"They said, “O Moses! Either you cast, or we will be the ones to cast.”"
  7,116,"He said, “You cast!” So when they cast, they affected the eyes of the people with sorcery and intimidated them and came up with great sorcery."
  7,117,"And We revealed to Moses: “Throw your staff,” and, lo and behold, it swallowed what they were faking!"
  7,118,"Thus the truth came to pass, and what they were doing went to waste."
  7,119,"So there and then they were overcome and they returned, utterly belittled."
  7,120,"Then the sorcerers fell prostrating."
  7,121,"They said, “We have attained faith in the Lord of all realms,"
  7,122,"the Lord of Moses and Aaron.”"
  7,123,"Pharaoh said, “How dare you believe in Him before I have given you permission? This is surely a scheme you schemed in the city in order to evict its people from it, but you will come to know."
  7,124,"I will most surely cut off your hands and your feet on opposite sides, then I will most surely crucify you all.”"
  7,125,"They said, “Indeed, it is to our Lord that we will return."
  7,126,"You only resent us because we have believed in the signs of our Lord when they have come to us. Our Lord, pour out patience upon us and take us at death as Muslims.”"
  7,127,"And the chiefs of Pharaoh's people said, “Will you leave Moses and his people to corrupt in the land and leave you and your gods?” He said, “We will relentlessly <span class="h">kill<sup foot_note="366343">1</sup></span> their sons and keep their women alive <small>(in bondage)</small>, and indeed, we are subjugators over them.”",footnotes:346806:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir and Abu Ja’far read it as: “He said, ‘We will kill their sons…’”</span>
  7,128,"Moses said to his people, “Beseech Allah for help and be patient; indeed, the earth belongs to Allah: He gives it in inheritance to whomever He wills of His servants, and the future outcome belongs to the mindful<sup>pl</sup> <small>(of God)</small>.”"
  7,129,"They said, “We were hurt before you came to us and after you came to us.” He said, “Hopefully your Lord will destroy your enemy and make you successors in the land, then He will look at how you act.”"
  7,130,"And We afflicted Pharaoh's folk with years <small>(of drought)</small> and with shortage of products, that they may constantly remember."
  7,131,"Yet when good came to them, they said, “This is ours,” and whenever something bad would afflict them, they would ascribe the evil omen to Moses and those with him. Undoubtedly, their omen is indeed solely with Allah, but most of them do not know."
  7,132,"And they said, “No matter what sign you bring us to bewitch us with, never shall we believe in you.”"
  7,133,"So We sent upon them the flood and the locusts and the lice and the frogs and blood—all explicit signs—but they acted arrogantly, and they were a criminal people."
  7,134,"And when the torment befell them, they said, “O Moses, pray to your Lord for us according to the covenant He made with you; if you lift the torment from us, we will most surely believe in you, and we will most surely send the Children of Israel with you.”"
  7,135,"But when We lifted the torment from them for a term they were to fulfill, they promptly broke their promise."
  7,136,"So We took retribution on them and drowned them in the waters because they rejected Our signs and were oblivious of them."
  7,137,"And We made those who had been deemed weak and oppressed inherit the eastern and western territories of the land which We had blessed. Thus the fair word of your Lord to the Children of Israel was fulfilled because of their endurance, and We destroyed what Pharaoh and his people had done and what they were building."
  7,138,"And We made the Children of Israel pass over the sea, then they came upon a people who were devoted to some human-shaped idols of theirs. They said, “O Moses, make for us a god as they have gods.” He said, “You are truly speaking ignorantly.”"
  7,139,"“What these people are concerned with is surely doomed to perdition, and whatever they used to do is false.”"
  7,140,"He said, “Shall I seek for you a god other than Allah when He has favored you over all communities?”"
  7,141,"And recall how <span class="h">We<sup foot_note="366344">1</sup></span> saved you from Pharaoh’s folk who inflicted upon you an evil punishment, relentlessly <span class="h">killing<sup foot_note="366345">2</sup></span> your sons and keeping your women alive <small>(in bondage)</small>. And in that was a great test from your Lord.",footnotes:346807:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “And recall when He saved you…”</span>|346808:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ read it as: “…evil punishment, killing your sons…”</span>
  7,142,"And We <span class="h">appointed<sup foot_note="366346">1</sup></span> for Moses thirty nights, and completed them with ten. And thus the time appointed by his Lord<sup foot_note="366347">2</sup> was forty nights. And Moses said to his brother Aaron: “Take my place among my people, and be upright, and do not follow the way of the corrupters.”",footnotes:346809:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr, Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “And We promised Moses thirty nights,”</span>|346810:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  7,143,"And when Moses came for Our appointment and his Lord<sup foot_note="366348">1</sup> spoke to him, he said, “My Lord, let me see—to look upon You.” He said, “You will not see Me, but look at the mountain—if it <small>(still)</small> resides in its place, you will see Me.” But when his Lord manifested Himself to the mountain, He turned it into <span class="h">rubble<sup foot_note="366349">2</sup></span>, and Moses fell down unconscious. Then when he recovered, he said, “Highly Exalted are You; I have indeed repented to you, and I am the first of the believers.”",footnotes:346811:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.|346812:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…He turned it into flattened land,”</span>
  7,144,"He said, “O Moses, I have indeed chosen you above mankind for My <span class="h">messages<sup foot_note="366350">1</sup></span> and for My Words, so take what I have given you and be one of the thankful.”",footnotes:346813:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Ja’far and Rouh read it as: “…My message”</span>
  7,145,"And We inscribed for him in the Tablets all kinds of admonition and a detailed explanation of everything. “So hold<sup>sg</sup> fast to them and command your people to adopt the best of them. I will show you<sup>pl</sup> the <small>(final)</small> Home of the defiantly disobedient<sup>pl</sup>.”"
  7,146,"I will turn away from My signs those who behave arrogantly on earth without justification. And even if they see every sign, they will not believe in it. And if they see the way of prudence, they will not adopt it for a way; while if they see the way of delusion, they will adopt it for a way. That is because they disbelieved in Our<sup foot_note="366351">1</sup> signs and were oblivious of them.",footnotes:346814:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  7,147,"And those who disbelieved in Our signs and the meeting of the Hereafter—their deeds were nullified<sup foot_note="366352">1</sup> . Will they be repaid except for what they used to do?",footnotes:346815:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  7,148,"And in his absence the people of Moses took a calf made from their ornaments—a body which lowed. Did they not see that it could not speak to them or guide them to any way? They took it <small>(for worship)</small>, and thus they became unjust."
  7,149,"Then when they felt incapacitated<sup foot_note="366353">1</sup> and they realized that they had gone astray, they said, “Unless our Lord extends His mercy to us and forgives <span class="h">us<sup foot_note="366354">2</sup></span>, we will be of the losers.”",footnotes:346816:Literally ‘their hands were disabled’, an Arabic expression that implies the realization that one has made a wrong decision and is frustrated.|346817:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “‘Unless You extend Your mercy to us, Our Lord, and forgive us…’”</span>
  7,150,"And when Moses returned to his people, wrathful <small>(and)</small> sorrowful, he said, “What a miserable thing you have done in my absence! Were you impatient over the command of your Lord?” And he threw down the Tablets and he took hold of his brother’s head, pulling him towards himself. He said, “Son of my mother, the people deemed me weak and were about to kill me, so do not allow the enemies to gloat over me and do not count me among the unjust people.”"
  7,151,"He said, “My Lord, forgive me and my brother and enter us into Your mercy, for You are the Most Merciful of the merciful.”"
  7,152,"Indeed, those who took the calf will be afflicted by wrath from their Lord and humiliation in the Earlier Life. And thus do We repay the fabricators of falsehood."
  7,153,"Yet those who have done evil deeds and then repented and attained faith—your Lord, thereafter, is surely Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  7,154,"And when the wrath abated in Moses, he took up the Tablets. And in their transcript is guidance and mercy for those in awe of their Lord."
  7,155,"And Moses chose from his people seventy men for Our appointment, then when the Tremor overtook them, he said, “My Lord, had You willed, You could have annihilated them before, and me too. Will you annihilate us for what the fools among us have done? This is but Your test—with it You lead astray whomever You will and guide whomever You will; You are our Ultimate Guardian, so forgive us and have mercy on us, and You are the best of forgivers."
  7,156,"And inscribe for us goodness in this Earlier <small>(Life)</small> and in the Hereafter. We have Judaized<sup foot_note="366355">1</sup> to You.” He said, “My punishment—I inflict it upon whomever I will, but My mercy has encompassed everything, so I will inscribe it for those who are mindful <small>(of God)</small> and bring<sup foot_note="366356">2</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="366357">3</sup>, and those who believe in Our signs—",footnotes:346818:The Arabic word used is <i>hudna</i> which means 'turned back' as well as 'became Jews'.|346819:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|346820:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  7,157,"those who follow the Messenger, the gentile<sup foot_note="366358">1</sup> Prophet whom they find written in the Torah and the Gospel—in their possession—commanding them to what is fair and forbidding them what is deplorable, and allowing for them all good things and prohibiting for them nasty things, and unloading their heavy <span class="h">load<sup foot_note="366359">2</sup></span> and the shackles that were upon them. So those who have attained faith in him and have respected him and have supported him and have followed the light that came down with him—those are the successful.”",footnotes:346821:Literally ‘the unlettered’.|346822:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “…their heavy loads…”</span>
  7,158,"Say, “O mankind, I am indeed the Messenger of Allah to you all—He to whom belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth; there is no god but He. He gives life and causes death, so believe in Allah and His<sup foot_note="366360">1</sup> Messenger, the gentile<sup foot_note="366361">2</sup> Prophet who believes in Allah and His words, and follow him, that you may be guided."",footnotes:346823:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.|346824:Literally ‘the unlettered’.
  7,159,"And of the people of Moses is a community that guides by truth and thereby acts with justice."
  7,160,"And We divided them into twelve tribal communities. And We revealed to Moses when his people asked him for something to drink: “Strike the rock with your staff,” whereupon twelve springs gushed from it; each group of people certainly recognized its drinking-place. And We shaded them with clouds and We sent down upon them manna and quails: “Eat of the good things We have provided for you.” And they were not unjust to Us, but to themselves they used to do injustice."
  7,161,"And recall when it was said to them, “Settle in this town and eat therein whatever you wish and speak modestly and enter the gate in humility—We will forgive you your <span class="h">offenses<sup foot_note="366362">1</sup></span>, and will give more to those who excel in doing good.”",footnotes:346825:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “…We will forgive you your numerous offenses,”Ibn Amer read it as: “…your offense will be forgiven for you,”Nafie’, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “...your numerous offenses will be forgiven for you,”</span>
  7,162,"Then the ones who did injustice among them substituted another word for the word said to them, so We sent down upon them a torment from heaven on account of how they used to do injustice."
  7,163,"And ask them about the town by the sea when they violated the Sabbath. When they observed the Sabbath, their fish would come to them abundantly. But when they violated the Sabbath, their fish would not come to them. Thus We tried them on account of how they used to be defiantly disobedient."
  7,164,"And recall when a group of them said, “Why do you admonish a people whom Allah will annihilate or punish with a severe punishment?” They said, “As an excuse to your Lord, and so that they may become mindful <small>(of God)</small>.”"
  7,165,"Then when they forgot<sup foot_note="366363">1</sup> what they were reminded of, We saved those who forbid<sup foot_note="366364">2</sup> evil, and We seized those who did injustice with a terrible punishment on account of how they used to be defiantly disobedient.",footnotes:346826:Neglected.|346827:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense.
  7,166,"Then when they rebelled against what they had been forbidden to do, We said to them, “Be despicable apes.”"
  7,167,"And recall when your Lord announced that He would most surely send against them someone who would inflict terrible punishment upon them until the Day of Resurrection. Your Lord is most surely swift in punishment, and He is most surely Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  7,168,"And We scattered them into communities on earth—some of them righteous and some of them short of that—and We tested them with good and evil<sup foot_note="366365">1</sup>, that they may return.",footnotes:346828:Good and evil are mentioned in plural form.
  7,169,"Thus they were succeeded by generations who inherited the Scripture while seizing the materials of this lower <small>(world)</small>, and saying, “We will be forgiven.” And should similar materials come their way, they would again seize them. Was not the pledge of the Scripture taken by them, to say nothing about Allah but the truth? Did they not study its contents? But the Home of the Hereafter is better for the mindful<sup>pl</sup> <small>(of God)</small>. Will <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="366366">1</sup></span> not reason?",footnotes:346829:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Nafie’, Ibn Amer, Hafs, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “Will they not reason?”</span>
  7,170,"And those who adhere <span class="h">strictly<sup foot_note="366367">1</sup></span> to the Scripture and have established<sup foot_note="366368">2</sup> the prayer—indeed, We do not waste the reward of the reformers.",footnotes:346830:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “And those who adhere to the Scripture…”</span>|346831:A grammatical shift from present tense to past tense.
  7,171,"And recall when We suspended the mountain over them as if it was a dark cloud, and they thought it would fall on them: “Hold<sup>pl</sup> fast to what We have given you and remember what it contains, that you may remain mindful <small>(of God)</small>.”"
  7,172,"And recall when Your Lord summoned the <span class="h">offspring<sup foot_note="366369">1</sup></span> of the children of Adam from their loins and made them testify about themselves, “Am I not your Lord?” They said, “Yes, we do testify.” Thus <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="366370">2</sup></span> cannot say on the Day of Resurrection, “We were oblivious of this.”",footnotes:346832:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “offspring(s)”</span>|346833:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “Thus they cannot say...”</span>
  7,173,"Nor can <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="366371">1</sup></span> say, “Our forefathers practiced polytheism before, and we were their offspring who came after them. Will you annihilate us for what the advocates of falsehood did?”",footnotes:346834:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “Nor can they say,”</span>
  7,174,"And thus We detail the signs<sup foot_note="366372">1</sup>, and that they may return.",footnotes:346835:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  7,175,"And relate to them the story of the one to whom We brought Our signs, but he detached himself from them, so Satan went after him and he became of the deluded."
  7,176,"And had We willed, We could have elevated him through them, but he clung to the ground and followed his whim. Thus his example is like that of a dog: if you chase it, it pants; and if you leave it alone, it pants. Such is the likeness of the people who disbelieved in Our signs. So narrate the narratives, that they may reflect."
  7,177,"Evil is the parable of the people who disbelieved in Our signs and to themselves they used to do injustice."
  7,178,"Whomever Allah guides is the guided one, and whomever He misguides—those<sup foot_note="366373">1</sup> are the losers.",footnotes:346836:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  7,179,"We have destined for Hell multitudes of unseen beings<sup foot_note="366374">1</sup> and humans; they have hearts with which they do not comprehend, and have eyes with which they do not see, and have ears with which they do not hear. Those are like cattle; in fact, they are further astray. Those are the oblivious.",footnotes:346837:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.
  7,180,"And to Allah belong the most beautiful names, so use them to call upon Him, and leave aside those who blaspheme His names. They will be repaid for what they used to do."
  7,181,"And of those We created is a community that guides by truth and does justice thereby."
  7,182,"But those who disbelieved in Our signs—We will draw them forth gradually <small>(to punishment)</small> from where they do not know."
  7,183,"And I<sup foot_note="366375">1</sup> will give them respite. Indeed, My plot is firm.",footnotes:346838:A grammatical shift from plural to singular.
  7,184,"Have they not reflected? There is no madness in their fellow; he is but an evident warner."
  7,185,"Have they not looked into the dominion of the heavens and the earth and all the things that Allah created and that perhaps their time may have drawn near? In what discourse beyond this will they believe?"
  7,186,"Whomever Allah leads astray has no guide, and He <span class="h">leaves<sup foot_note="366376">1</sup></span> them<sup foot_note="366377">2</sup> to wander aimlessly while exceeding all limits.",footnotes:346839:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…and We leave them...”</span>|346840:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  7,187,"They ask you about the Hour, “When will it take place?” Say, “Knowledge of it rests with my Lord; none can reveal its coming except He. Heavy has its weight become throughout the heavens and the earth. It comes not upon you except suddenly.” They ask you as if you are responsible for it. Say, “Surely, knowledge of it but rests with Allah,” though most of mankind do not know."
  7,188,"Say, “I have no power to benefit or harm <small>(even)</small> myself, except as Allah wills. And had I known the hidden realm, I would have acquired much good, and no harm would have touched me. I am only a warner and a herald of glad tidings to people who believe.”"
  7,189,"It is He Who created you from a single self and made from it its spouse, that he may find rest with her; then when he covered<sup foot_note="366378">1</sup> her, she carried a light <small>(load of)</small> pregnancy, then she passed by with it. But when she grew heavy, they<sup>dl</sup> called upon Allah, their Lord, “If You give us a righteous <small>(child)</small>, we will most surely be of the thankful.”",footnotes:346841:A grammatical shift from present tense to past tense.
  7,190,"But when He gave them a righteous <small>(child)</small>, they set associates with Him in what He has given them. Rather, Most High is Allah above what they associate."
  7,191,"Do they associate <small>(with God)</small> what creates nothing and are themselves<sup foot_note="366379">1</sup> created?",footnotes:346842:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  7,192,"And can neither support them nor support themselves?"
  7,193,"And if you<sup>sg</sup> call them to guidance, they do not follow you. It is the same for you whether you call them or remain silent."
  7,194,"Indeed, those you call upon apart from Allah are servants like you, so call upon them and let them respond to you if you are truthful."
  7,195,"Do they have feet with which they walk, or do they have hands with which they strike, or do they have eyes with which they see, or do they have ears with which they hear? Say, “Call<sup>pl</sup> upon your associates, then plot against me and give me no respite."
  7,196,"Indeed, my Ultimate Guardian is Allah, Who bestowed the Scripture from on high, and He guards the righteous,"
  7,197,"while those you call upon apart from Him cannot support you nor can they support themselves.”"
  7,198,"And if you call them to guidance, they do not hear. And you see them looking at you, yet they do not see."
  7,199,"Take the course of pardoning, and command to benevolence, and disregard ignorant harassers."
  7,200,"And if you<sup>sg</sup> are ever spurred by a spurring from Satan, then seek refuge with Allah; indeed, He is All-Hearing, All-Knowing."
  7,201,"Indeed, those who are mindful <small>(of God)</small>—when an impulse from Satan touches them, they remind themselves and immediately see <small>(the truth)</small>."
  7,202,"But their brethren lead them relentlessly into delusion, and they never stop short."
  7,203,"If you do not bring them a sign, they say, “Why don’t you improvise one.” Say, “I only follow what is revealed to me from my Lord.” This <small>(Scripture)</small> is insights from your Lord, and guidance and mercy for people who believe."
  7,204,"Thus when the Recital<sup foot_note="366380">1</sup> is recited, then listen<sup>pl</sup> to it and pay attention, that you may receive mercy.",footnotes:346843:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  7,205,"And remember your<sup>sg</sup> Lord within yourself in supplication and in fear, and without being loud of voice, in the mornings and before sunset; and do not be of the oblivious."
  7,206,"Indeed, those who are in the presence of your Lord are not too arrogant to worship Him, and they exalt Him, and to Him they prostrate themselves."
  8,1,"They ask you<sup>sg</sup> about the spoils <small>(of war)</small>. Say, “The spoils are for Allah and the Messenger, so be<sup>pl</sup> mindful of Allah and reconcile between yourselves and obey Allah and His Messenger, if you are believers.”"
  8,2,"Surely, the believers are but those whose hearts tremble when Allah is mentioned, and when His signs<sup foot_note="366541">1</sup> are read to them they increase them in faith, and in their Lord they place their trust—",footnotes:347004:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  8,3,"the ones who establish the prayer and from what We have provided them they spend."
  8,4,"Those are truly the believers; for them are degrees <small>(of rank)</small> with their Lord and forgiveness and noble provision."
  8,5,"Just as when your<sup>sg</sup> Lord brought you out of your house with the truth<sup foot_note="366542">1</sup>, while a group of believers were definitely reluctant,",footnotes:347005:According to Ibn Ashour and other exegetes, ‘with the truth’ means ‘for a purpose’.
  8,6,"arguing with you about the truth after it became evident, as if they were being driven to death while they looked on."
  8,7,"And recall: Allah promising you<sup>pl</sup> one of the two factions—that it would be yours, and you wishing that the unarmed group be yours. Yet Allah wants to uphold the truth with His words and to uproot the deniers"
  8,8,"in order to uphold the truth and nullify falsehood, even if the criminals dislike it."
  8,9,"Recall: you crying for help from your Lord, so He responded to you, “I am surely reinforcing you with one thousand angels in <span class="h">succession<sup foot_note="366543">1</sup></span>.”",footnotes:347006:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…one thousand angels succeeding one another.”</span>
  8,10,"And Allah only made it as a glad tiding, and so that your hearts should become serene thereby, for support<sup foot_note="366544">1</sup> is only from Allah; indeed, Allah is Almighty, All-Wise.",footnotes:347007:The Arabic word used for support is <i>nasr </i>which also means victory.
  8,11,"Recall: <small>(Allah)</small> covering you<sup>pl</sup> tightly with <span class="h">drowsiness<sup foot_note="366545">1</sup></span>, as security from Him, and bestowing <span class="h">upon<sup foot_note="366546">2</sup></span> you water from the sky to purify you with it and to remove from you Satan’s distress and to fortify your hearts and to strengthen your foothold.",footnotes:347008:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “Recall: drowsiness covering you, and Him bestowing upon…” Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “Recall: (Allah) covering you<sup>pl</sup> with drowsiness,” with drowsiness,”</span>|347009:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…and sending down to you water from the sky…”</span>
  8,12,"Recall: your<sup>sg</sup> Lord revealing to the angels, “Surely, I am with you<sup>pl</sup>, so support those who have attained faith. I will cast terror into the hearts of those who have denied, so strike above the necks and strike off every fingertip of theirs.”"
  8,13,"That is because they opposed Allah and His Messenger, and whoever opposes Allah and His Messenger—then indeed Allah is stern in retribution."
  8,14,"“There it is, so taste<sup>pl</sup> it.” And <small>(know)</small> that for the deniers is the punishment of the Fire."
  8,15,"O you who have attained faith, when you encounter those who have denied on the march, never turn your backs to them."
  8,16,"For whoever turns his back to them on that day, except while maneuvering for combat or to side with another battalion, then he has surely incurred wrath from Allah, and his shelter is Hell—and what a miserable destiny!"
  8,17,"For it was not you<sup>pl</sup> who killed them, but it was Allah who killed them. And you<sup>sg</sup> threw not when you threw, but it was Allah who threw, and so that He might test the believers with a goodly test <small>(of victory)</small> from Him; indeed, Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing."
  8,18,"Such is the case. And surely, Allah will weaken the plot of the deniers."
  8,19,"“If you<sup>pl</sup> desire a conquest, then the conquest has come to you<sup foot_note="366547">1</sup> ; and if you desist, it would be better for you. But if you return, We will return; and your battalion, however numerous, will not avail you in anything. And <small>(know)</small> <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="366548">2</sup></span> Allah is with the believers.”",footnotes:347010:This is said in sarcasm to the deniers, as they were defeated in the battle of Badr.|347011:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Hafs, Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “For indeed Allah is with…”</span>
  8,20,"O you who have attained faith, obey Allah and His Messenger and do not turn away from him while you hear."
  8,21,"And be not like those who said, “We have heard,” but they hear not."
  8,22,"Indeed, the worst of the treading creatures to Allah are the deaf and dumb—those who do not reason."
  8,23,"And had Allah known any good in them, He would have made them hear. And had He made them hear, they would have turned away in disregard."
  8,24,"O you who have attained faith, respond to Allah and to the Messenger when He calls you to that which revives you, and know that Allah stands between a person and his heart, and that to Him you are herded."
  8,25,"And protect yourselves against a trial which does not befall exclusively those who did injustice among you, and know that Allah is stern in retribution."
  8,26,"And call to mind when you were few, <small>(and)</small> deemed weak and oppressed in the land, fearing that people may capture you, but He sheltered you and aided you with His support<sup foot_note="366549">1</sup> and provided you with good things, that you may give thanks.",footnotes:347012:The Arabic word used for support is <i>nasr </i>which also means ‘victory’.
  8,27,"O you who have attained faith, do not betray Allah and the Messenger, nor betray your trusts while you know."
  8,28,"And know that your possessions and your children are but a means of trial, and that Allah possesses a great reward."
  8,29,"O you who have attained faith, if you become mindful of Allah, He will give you a criterion and will remit your evil deeds for you and will forgive you. For Allah is the Possessor of great grace."
  8,30,"And recall: the deniers scheming against you<sup>sg</sup> to imprison you or kill you or evict you. And they scheme and Allah schemes, but Allah is the best of schemers."
  8,31,"And when Our signs<sup foot_note="366550">1</sup> are read to them, they say, “We have surely heard. Had we willed, we could have said the like of this; this is nothing but legends of the ancients.”",footnotes:347013:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  8,32,"And recall when they said, “Our God, if this is the truth from You, then rain down upon us stones from the sky or bring us a painful punishment.”"
  8,33,"But never would Allah punish them while you<sup>sg</sup> are amongst them. And never was Allah to punish them as long as they seek forgiveness."
  8,34,"Yet why should Allah not punish them when they bar others from the Inviolable Mosque, though they are not its guardians? Rather its guardians are none except the mindful <small>(of God)</small>, but most of them do not know."
  8,35,"And their prayer at the House was nothing but whistling and clapping—so taste<sup>pl</sup> the punishment for what you<sup foot_note="366551">1</sup> used to deny.",footnotes:347014:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 2 person to 2<sup>nd</sup> person. person.
  8,36,"Indeed, those who have denied spend their wealths to bar <small>(others)</small> from the way of Allah. So they will spend it, then it will become a source of sorrow for them and then they will be overcome. And those who have denied are herded to Hell."
  8,37,"That Allah may distinguish the nasty from the good, and heap the nasty <small>(things)</small> on top of one another and pile them together and set it up in Hell; those are the losers."
  8,38,"Tell<sup>sg</sup> those who have denied that if they desist, they will be forgiven whatever has already passed. But if they return—then the rule of <small>(God regarding)</small> the ancients is already established."
  8,39,"And combat<sup>pl</sup> them until there is no more religious persecution and religion is all for Allah. But if they desist—then Allah is All-Seeing of what <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="366552">1</sup></span> do.",footnotes:347015:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Roways read it as: “…All-Seeing of what you<sup>pl</sup> do.” do.”</span>
  8,40,"And if they turn away, then know<sup>pl</sup> that Allah is your Patron; what an excellent Patron and what an excellent Supporter!"
  8,41,"And know that whatever you have gained <small>(as spoils of war)</small>—to Allah belongs its fifth and to the messenger and to the relative and the orphans and the destitute<sup>pl</sup> and to the traveler in need, provided you have <small>(truly)</small> attained faith in Allah and in what We<sup foot_note="366553">1</sup> have sent down upon Our servant on the Day of Distinction, the day when the two armies met. For Allah is All-Powerful over everything.",footnotes:347016:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 1 person to 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.
  8,42,"Recall: you on the nearer bank and they on the further bank and the caravan below you. And had you planned for this meeting, you would indeed have differed over the promised appointment, but Allah was to carry out a predetermined matter—so that those who perish would perish after seeing evident proof, and those who survive would survive after seeing evident proof. And most surely, Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing."
  8,43,"Recall: Allah showing them to you<sup>sg</sup> in your sleep as few, for had He showed them to you as many, you<sup>pl</sup> would have faltered and disagreed with each other about the matter, but Allah saved <small>(the situation).</small> He is indeed All-Knowing of what lies within the chests."
  8,44,"And recall: when you<sup>pl</sup> met, Him showing them to you as few in your eyes and making you appear fewer in their eyes, so that Allah might carry out a predetermined matter. And to Allah all matters are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="366554">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:347017:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “And to Allah all matters return.”</span>
  8,45,"O you who have attained faith, when you encounter a battalion, then stand firm and remember Allah much, that you may be successful."
  8,46,"And obey Allah and His Messenger, and do not disagree with each other lest you falter and your strength depart. And be patient. Indeed, Allah is with the patient<sup>pl</sup>."
  8,47,"And do not be like those who set out of their homes out of boastfulness and for show in front of the people while barring others from the way of Allah, whereas Allah is All-Encompassing of what they do."
  8,48,"And recall how Satan adorned their deeds for them and said, “Today, none of mankind shall overcome you, and I am surely at your side.” But when the two battalions came within sight of one another, he turned on his heels and said, “I am innocent of you; I see what you do not see; I do fear Allah, and Allah is stern in punishment.”"
  8,49,"Recall: the hypocrites and those in whose hearts is sickness saying, “These people's religion has deceived them.” But whoever places his trust in Allah—then indeed, Allah is Almighty, All-Wise."
  8,50,"And if only you<sup>sg</sup> could see as those who denied are taken at death by the <span class="h">angels<sup foot_note="366555">1</sup></span>, striking their faces and their backs and <small>(saying)</small>, “Taste the punishment of burning;",footnotes:347018:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “…as the angels take those who denied at death,”</span>
  8,51,"that is because of what your hands have put forth and because Allah is not a tyrant unto the servants.”"
  8,52,"Such was the case with Pharaoh's folk and those before them. They denied the signs of Allah, so Allah seized them for their misdeeds. Indeed, Allah is All-Powerful, Stern in retribution."
  8,53,"That is because Allah would never change a blessing He has bestowed upon any people unless they changed what is within themselves, and because Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing."
  8,54,"Such was the case with Pharaoh's folk and those before them. They rejected the signs of their Lord, so We annihilated them for their misdeeds, and We drowned Pharaoh's folk—for all were unjust."
  8,55,"Indeed, the worst of the treading creatures before Allah are those who have denied, as they will never believe:"
  8,56,"those of them with whom you<sup>sg</sup> have covenanted, but they violate their covenant every time and they are never mindful <small>(of God)</small>."
  8,57,"So if you confront them in battle, then make of them a fearsome example for those who follow them, that they may constantly remember."
  8,58,"And if you fear treachery from any people, then break off with them in a like manner; indeed, Allah does not like the treacherous."
  8,59,"And let not the deniers think that <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="366556">1</sup></span> are ahead. Indeed, they cannot thwart <small>(God)</small>.",footnotes:347019:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “And do not think that the deniers are ahead.”</span>
  8,60,"And prepare<sup>pl</sup> against them all what you can muster of power and of warhorse garrisons to <span class="h">terrify<sup foot_note="366557">1</sup></span> thereby Allah’s enemy and your enemy and others apart from them whom you do not know <small>(but)</small> whom Allah knows. And whatever you spend in the way of Allah is rendered to you in full, and you are not dealt with unjustly.",footnotes:347020:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Roways read it as: “…to strongly terrify…”</span>
  8,61,"But if they incline towards peace, then incline<sup>sg</sup> towards it and place your trust in Allah. Indeed, it is He who is the All-Hearing, the All-Knowing."
  8,62,"For <small>(even)</small> if they want to deceive you, then surely Allah is enough for you. It is He who aided you with His support<sup foot_note="366558">1</sup> and with the believers.",footnotes:347021:The Arabic word used for support is <i>nasr </i>which also means ‘victory’.
  8,63,"And He attuned their hearts. Had you spent whatever is in the earth, all together, you would not have attuned their hearts, but Allah attuned them. Indeed, He is Almighty, All-Wise."
  8,64,"O Prophet, Allah is sufficient for you and the believers who have followed you."
  8,65,"O Prophet, urge the believers on to combat. If there are twenty patient ones among you, they can overcome two hundred. And if there are a hundred of you, they can overcome a thousand of those who have denied, because they are a people who do not comprehend."
  8,66,"Now Allah has lightened your<sup>pl</sup> burden and He has recognized that there is weakness <span class="h">in<sup foot_note="366559">1</sup></span> you. So if there are a hundred patient ones among you, they can overcome two hundred. And if there are a thousand of you, they can overcome two thousand by Allah’s leave. For Allah is with the patient ones.",footnotes:347022:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…and He has recognized that there are weak people among you.”</span>
  8,67,"Never would it befit any prophet to <small>(stop the battle and)</small> take captives before he has subjugated <small>(the enemy)</small> in the battlefield. You<sup>pl</sup> want the materials of the Earlier <small>(Life)</small>, but Allah wants the Hereafter. For Allah is Almighty, All-Wise."
  8,68,"Were it not for a predetermined decree from Allah, a great punishment would have befallen you for what you have taken."
  8,69,"So consume of what you have gained, legitimate and good, and be mindful of Allah. Indeed, Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  8,70,"O Prophet, say to those you hold prisoners, “If Allah recognizes any good in your hearts, He will give you better than what was taken from you and will forgive you. For Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy.”"
  8,71,"But if they want to betray you, then they have already betrayed Allah earlier, and He has empowered <small>(you)</small> over them. For Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  8,72,"Indeed, those who attained faith and emigrated and struggled in the way of Allah with their wealths and themselves, and those who provided shelter and gave support—those are guardians of one another. But those who attained faith but did not emigrate—you owe them no guardianship until they have emigrated. But if they ask you<sup>pl</sup> for support in the matter of religion, then support is incumbent on you, except against a people with whom you have a pledge. For Allah is All-Seeing of what you do."
  8,73,"And those who denied— they are guardians of one another. Unless you do this, there will be religious persecution in the land and huge corruption."
  8,74,"And those who attained faith and emigrated and struggled in the way of Allah, and those who provided shelter and supported—those are the true believers. For them is forgiveness and noble provision."
  8,75,"And those who attained faith afterwards and emigrated and struggled with you<sup>pl</sup>—then those belong with you. But blood relatives are nearer to one another in the Scripture of Allah<sup foot_note="366560">1</sup> . Indeed, Allah is All-Knowing of everything.",footnotes:347023:More entitled to inherit from one another.
  9,1,"A repeal from Allah and His Messenger <small>(declared)</small> to those whom you<sup>pl</sup> have covenanted from among the polytheists:"
  9,2,"so travel freely through the land for four months and know <small>(well)</small> that you cannot thwart Allah and that Allah will disgrace the deniers."
  9,3,"And an announcement from Allah and His Messenger to mankind on the day of the Greater Pilgrimage that Allah renounces the polytheists, as does His Messenger. So if you<sup foot_note="366561">1</sup> repent, it is better for you; but if you turn away, know that you cannot thwart Allah. And givesg to those who have denied glad tidings<sup foot_note="366562">2</sup> of a painful punishment,",footnotes:347024:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 2 person to 2<sup>nd</sup> person. person.|347025:This is said in sarcasm.
  9,4,"except for those of the polytheists whom you<sup>pl</sup> have covenanted then they did not fail you in anything, nor did they back anyone against you. So fulfill with them their covenant to the end of their term; indeed, Allah loves the people who are mindful <small>(of Him)</small>."
  9,5,"As soon as the inviolable months have passed, kill the polytheists wherever you find them and capture them and besiege them and lie in wait for them at every passage. But if they repent and establish the prayers and bring<sup foot_note="366563">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="366564">2</sup>, then let them go their way; indeed, Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy.",footnotes:347026:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|347027:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  9,6,"And if anyone of the polytheists asks you<sup>sg</sup> for protection, then grant him protection so that he may hear the Speech of Allah, then escort him to where he can be safe. That is because they are people who have no knowledge."
  9,7,"How can there be a covenant with the polytheists on the part of Allah and His Messenger, except for those whom you<sup>pl</sup> have covenanted at the Inviolable Mosque? As long as they are upright with you, be upright with them; indeed, Allah loves the people who are mindful <small>(of Him)</small>."
  9,8,"How <small>(can there be a treaty)</small> when, if they overcome you, they neither respect a god<sup foot_note="366565">1</sup> nor a treaty with you? They please you with lip service, but their hearts refuse, and most of them are defiantly disobedient.",footnotes:347028:The word used is <i>Elah</i> which means ‘God’ in Hebrew.
  9,9,"They purchased, in exchange for Allah's signs<sup foot_note="366566">1</sup>, a small price and barred others from His way; how evil indeed is what they used to do.",footnotes:347029:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  9,10,"Towards a believer they respect neither a god<sup foot_note="366567">1</sup> nor a treaty, and those are the transgressors.",footnotes:347030:The word used is <i>Elah</i> which means ‘God’ in Hebrew.
  9,11,"But if they repent and establish the prayer and bring<sup foot_note="366568">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="366569">2</sup>, then they are your brethren in faith. And We detail the signsw for people who know.",footnotes:347031:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|347032:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  9,12,"But if they renege on their oaths after making their covenant and defame your religion, then combat the leaders of denial—surely, they have no <small>(binding)</small> <span class="h">oaths<sup foot_note="366570">1</sup></span>—so that they may desist.",footnotes:347033:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “…surely, they have no faith”.</span>
  9,13,"Will you not combat a people who have reneged on their oaths and have advanced forward to evict the Messenger, and it was they who initiated <small>(hostilities)</small> against you? Do you fear them? It is Allah who is worthier of being feared, if you are believers."
  9,14,"Combat them, so that Allah may punish them at your hands and disgrace them and support you against them and heal the chests of a believing people"
  9,15,"and remove the rage in their hearts. And Allah grants repentance and accepts it from whomever He wills. And Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  9,16,"Or do you think that you will be left alone without Allah identifying<sup foot_note="366571">1</sup> those of you who strive and take no confidants apart from Allah and His Messenger and the believers? And Allah is All-Aware of what you do.",footnotes:347034:Literally ‘knowing’.
  9,17,"Never was it befitting for the polytheists to attend Allah’s <span class="h">mosques<sup foot_note="366572">1</sup></span> while professing their denial. Those—their deeds were nullified, and in the Fire they abide.",footnotes:347035:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “mosque”.</span>
  9,18,"Surely, Allah’s mosques can only be attended by one who has attained faith in Allah and the Last Day and has established the prayer and brought<sup foot_note="366573">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="366574">2</sup> and feared none but Allah, for hopefully those will become of the guided ones.",footnotes:347036:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|347037:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  9,19,"Do you equate giving water to pilgrims and <span class="h">maintaining<sup foot_note="366575">1</sup></span> the Inviolable Mosque with <small>(the deeds of)</small> whoever have attained faith in Allah and the Last Day and have striven in the way of Allah? They are not equal before Allah. And Allah does not guide the unjust people.",footnotes:347038:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Wardan, in one of his narrations, read it as: “Do you equate the pilgrims’ water-servers and the maintainers of the Inviolable Mosque with…”</span>
  9,20,"Those who attained faith and emigrated and strove in the way of Allah with their wealths and themselves are of a higher degree <small>(of rank)</small> before Allah, and it is those who are the triumphant ones."
  9,21,"Their Lord gives them glad tidings of mercy from Him, and good pleasure and Gardens wherein they have lasting bliss,"
  9,22,"abiding therein forever; indeed with Allah is a great reward."
  9,23,"O you who have attained faith, do not ally yourselves with your fathers and your brethren if they prefer denial over faith, and whoever of you allies himself with them—then those<sup foot_note="366576">1</sup> are the unjust.",footnotes:347039:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  9,24,"Say, “If your fathers, and your sons, and your brethren, and your spouses, and your <span class="h">kinsfolk<sup foot_note="366577">1</sup></span>, and wealths you have acquired, and a trade<sup foot_note="366578">2</sup> wherein you fear decline, and homes that well please you are more beloved to you than Allah and His Messenger and striving in His way, then wait until Allah brings about His command.” And Allah does not guide the defiantly disobedient people.",footnotes:347040:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “kinsfolks”.</span>|347041:The Arabic word used is <i>tijara</i> which is also translated as’ bargain’.
  9,25,"Allah has supported you in many battlefields. But on the day of Hunayn, when your multitude impressed you, it availed you nothing and the earth closed in on you despite its spaciousness, then you turned away, fleeing."
  9,26,"Then Allah sent down His tranquility upon His Messenger and upon the believers<sup foot_note="366579">1</sup>, and He sent down troops you did not see and punished those who had denied. And that is the repayment of the deniers.",footnotes:347042:A grammatical shift from 2<sup>nd </sup>person to 3person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  9,27,"Then after that Allah will grant repentance and accept it from whomever He wills. For Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  9,28,"O you who have attained faith, the polytheists are surely but an impurity, so let them not approach the Inviolable Mosque after this year of theirs. And if you fear need, then Allah will eventually enrich you of His grace if He wills. Indeed, Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  9,29,"Combat those who do not believe in Allah nor in the Last Day, nor forbid what Allah and His Messenger have forbidden, nor abide by the religion of truth—of those who have been brought the Scripture—until they pay the tribute, by hand, fully humbled."
  9,30,"And the Jews said, “Ezra is the son of Allah,” and the Christians said, “The Messiah is the son of Allah.” That is their saying which they utter with their mouths; they emulate the saying of those who denied earlier. May Allah combat them! How can they be averted <small>(from the truth)</small>?"
  9,31,"They have taken their rabbis and their monks as lords apart from Allah, as well as the Messiah, son of Mary, although they were commanded to worship none but one God; there is no god but He. Highly Exalted is He, high above what they associate <small>(with Him)</small>."
  9,32,"They want to extinguish Allah’s light with their mouths, yet Allah refuses but to complete His light, even if the deniers dislike it."
  9,33,"It is He Who sent His Messenger with the guidance and the religion of truth in order to make it prevail over every religion, even if the polytheists dislike it."
  9,34,"O you who have attained faith, indeed, many of the rabbis and monks devour people's wealths illicitly and bar <small>(others)</small> from the way of Allah. So those who hoard gold and silver and do not spend them in the way of Allah—inform<sup>sg</sup> them of a painful punishment"
  9,35,"on the day when they<sup foot_note="366580">1</sup> are heated in the fire of Hell, then their foreheads and their sides and their backs will be branded with them: “This is what you hoarded for yourselves, so taste what you used to hoard.”",footnotes:347043:The hoarded gold and silver.
  9,36,"Indeed, the number of months according to Allah is twelve months—in the record<sup foot_note="366581">1</sup> of Allah <small>(since)</small> the day He created the heavens and the earth, of which four are inviolable. That is the upright religion. So do<sup>pl</sup> not do injustice to yourselves during them, and combat the polytheists collectively as they combat you collectively, and know that Allah is with the mindful <small>(of Him)</small>.",footnotes:347044:Literally ‘scripture’.
  9,37,"Indeed, postponing the inviolable months is but another act of denial by which those who have denied are led <span class="h">astray<sup foot_note="366582">1</sup></span>. They allow it one year and forbid it another year in order to conform to the number made inviolable by Allah, thus permitting what Allah has forbidden. The evil of their deeds was adorned to them. And Allah does not guide the denying people.",footnotes:347045:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…those who have denied lead (others) astray.” All the others except Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Khalaf and Ya’qub read it as: “…those who have denied go astray.”</span>
  9,38,"O you who have attained faith, what is the matter with you that when it is said to you, “Mobilize in the way of Allah,” you cling heavily to the earth? Are you content with the Earlier Life rather than the Hereafter? For the enjoyment of the Earlier Life compared to the Hereafter is but little."
  9,39,"Unless you mobilize, He will punish you with a painful punishment and will replace you with another people, and you will not harm Him in any way. And Allah is Powerful over everything."
  9,40,"If you do not support him, surely Allah already supported him when those who denied evicted him, as he was the second of two in the cave, when he said to his companion, “Do not be sad; Allah is surely with us.” So Allah sent down His tranquility upon him and aided him with troops you did not see and made the word of those who had denied the lowest. And the Word of Allah is the <span class="h">highest<sup foot_note="366583">1</sup></span>. And Allah is Almighty, All-Wise.",footnotes:347046:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “and made the word of those who had denied the lowest and the Word of Allah the highest.”</span>
  9,41,"Mobilize, light or heavy, and strive with your wealths and yourselves in the way of Allah. That is better for you, if you only knew."
  9,42,"Had the profit been immediate and the journey shorter, they would have followed you; but the distance seemed too long for them. And they will swear by Allah: “Had we been able, we would have set out with you.” They ruin themselves, and Allah knows that they are certainly liars."
  9,43,"May Allah pardon you! Why did you give them permission before it became clear to you who were the truthful ones and who were the liars?"
  9,44,"Those who believe in Allah and the Last Day do not ask you for exemption from striving with their wealths and themselves. And Allah is All-Knowing of the ones mindful <small>(of Him)</small>."
  9,45,"Rather, those who ask you for exemption are the ones who do not believe in Allah and the Last Day, and whose hearts have doubted so that in their doubt they are wavering."
  9,46,"For had they wanted to set out, they would have made preparations for it. But Allah disliked their being sent forth, so He discouraged them, and it was said, “Stay behind with those staying behind.”"
  9,47,"Had they set out with you, they would have added nothing to you but confusion, and they would have spread turmoil in your midst<sup foot_note="366584">1</sup>, seeking to sow discord among you— and some of you are avid listeners to them. And Allah is All-Knowing of the unjust<sup>pl</sup>.",footnotes:347047:By spreading rumors.
  9,48,"They have most surely sought to cause discord in the past and have turned things upside down for you<sup>sg</sup>, until the truth came and the command of Allah prevailed in spite of their dislike."
  9,49,"And of them is one who says, “Exempt me and do not try me.” Undoubtedly, they have failed the trial. And Hell will most surely engulf the deniers."
  9,50,"If something good befalls you, it upsets them. And if a calamity befalls you, they say, “We took our precautions in advance,” and they turn away, rejoicing."
  9,51,"Say, “Nothing will befall us except what Allah has prescribed for us; He is our Patron. And in Allah let the believers place their trust.”"
  9,52,"Say, “Are you<sup>pl</sup> awaiting anything to befall us other than one of the two excellent things? Well, we await that Allah should afflict you with a punishment from Himself or at our hands. So await; we are indeed awaiting with you.”"
  9,53,"Say, “Whether you spend willingly or reluctantly, it will not be accepted from you; indeed, you have been a defiantly disobedient people.”"
  9,54,"Yet nothing has prevented them from their contributions being accepted except that they have denied Allah and His Messenger, and that they do not approach the prayer except lazily, and that they do not spend except grudgingly."
  9,55,"So let<sup>sg</sup> neither their wealths nor their children impress you. Indeed, Allah only wants to punish them thereby in the Earlier Life, and that their souls depart while they are deniers."
  9,56,"And they swear by Allah that they are most surely of you, but in no way are they of you<sup>pl</sup>; rather, they are a terrified people."
  9,57,"Were they to find a refuge or some caverns or any entrance, they would turn to it, rushing."
  9,58,"And of them is the one who criticizes you<sup>sg</sup> regarding donations. Yet if they<sup foot_note="366585">1</sup> are given some of it, they are content; but if they are not given any of it, they are promptly angered.",footnotes:347048:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  9,59,"Yet if only they were content with what Allah and His Messenger had brought them and said, “Allah is sufficient for us; Allah will bring to us of His grace, as will His Messenger; indeed to Allah we turn wishfully.”"
  9,60,"Indeed, donations are only for the poor and the destitute<sup>pl</sup> and those who administer them and for those whose hearts are reconciled and for freeing slaves<sup foot_note="366586">1</sup> and for the debt-ridden ones and in the way of Allah and for the homeless traveler—an obligation from Allah. And Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise.",footnotes:347049:Literally ‘necks’.
  9,61,"And of them are those who hurt the Prophet and say, “He is just an ear.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “An ear of goodness for you<sup foot_note="366587">1</sup> . He has faith in Allah and he has faith in the believers and is a <span class="h">mercy<sup foot_note="366588">2</sup></span> for those of you who have attained faith. And those who hurt the Messenger of Allah—for them is a painful punishment.",footnotes:347050:Meaning ‘listens for your own good’.|347051:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “…and in mercy for those of you…”</span>
  9,62,"They swear to you<sup>pl</sup> by Allah to please you. Yet, Allah and His Messenger are worthier of their pleasing Him<sup foot_note="366589">1</sup>, if they are believers.",footnotes:347052:A grammatical shift from plural to singular.
  9,63,"Have they not come to know that whoever opposes Allah and His Messenger—that for him then is the fire of Hell, abiding therein? That is the great disgrace."
  9,64,"The hypocrites worry lest a surah<sup foot_note="366590">1</sup> be bestowed from on high <span class="h">upon<sup foot_note="366591">2</sup></span> them, informing them of what is in their hearts. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Go<sup>pl</sup> on ridiculing; indeed, Allah is sure to bring out what you are afraid of.”",footnotes:347053:Each portion of the Qur'an is called a ‘<i>surah’</i>, which is sometimes translated as ‘chapter’.|347054:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…lest a surah be sent down to them,”</span>
  9,65,"And if you<sup>sg</sup> ask them, they will most surely say, “Indeed, we were but blundering and playing.” Say, “Were you<sup>pl</sup> ridiculing Allah and His signs and His Messenger?”"
  9,66,"Do not make excuses. You have surely denied after having attained faith. If We <span class="h">pardon<sup foot_note="366592">1</sup></span> a faction of you, We will punish another faction because they were criminals.",footnotes:347055:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Asem read it as: “If a faction of you is pardoned,”</span>
  9,67,"The hypocritical men and the hypocritical women are of one another. They command to what is deplorable and forbid what is fair and they withhold their hands; they forgot Allah, so He forgot them. Indeed, the hypocrites are the ones who are defiantly disobedient."
  9,68,"Allah has promised the hypocritical men and the hypocritical women, as well as the deniers, the fire of Hell, abiding therein; it is sufficient for them. And Allah has cursed them, and for them is a perpetual punishment."
  9,69,"Like those before you: they were more powerful than you and had more wealths and children, so they enjoyed their share and you enjoyed your share as those before you enjoyed their share, and you blundered as they blundered. It is those whose deeds were nullified in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> and in the Hereafter, and those are the losers."
  9,70,"Has not the story of those before them come to them? The people of Noah and Ād and Thamûd, and the people of Abraham, and the inhabitants of Midian and the Overturned Cities? Their messengers came to them with evident proofs, for never would Allah do them any injustice, but to themselves they used to do injustice."
  9,71,"And the believing men and the believing women are guardians of one another. They command to what is fair and forbid what is deplorable and establish the prayers and bring<sup foot_note="366593">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="366594">2</sup> and obey Allah and His Messenger. Those—Allah will have mercy on them. Indeed, Allah is Almighty, All-Wise.",footnotes:347056:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|347057:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  9,72,"Allah has promised the believing men and the believing women Gardens beneath which rivers flow, abiding therein, and good homes in the Gardens of Eden. But good pleasure from Allah is even greater; that is the great triumph."
  9,73,"O Prophet, strive against the deniers and the hypocrites and be stern with them, for their shelter is Hell—and what a miserable destiny!"
  9,74,"They swear by Allah that they said nothing, but they did say the word of blasphemy<sup foot_note="366595">1</sup> and they denied after their submission<sup foot_note="366596">2</sup> and they advanced towards what they could not attain. And they were resentful only because Allah and His Messenger enriched them out of His<sup foot_note="366597">3</sup> grace. So if they repent, it would be better for them; but if they turn away, Allah will punish them with a painful punishment in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> and in the Hereafter. And on earth they have neither ally nor supporter.",footnotes:347058:The Arabic word ‘<i>kufr’</i> means ‘denial’ or ‘blasphemy’ or ‘ingratitude’.|347059:Literally ‘after they became Muslims’.|347060:A grammatical shift from plural to singular.
  9,75,"And of them is one who made a covenant with Allah: “If He does bring us of His grace, we will most surely donate and we will most surely be of the righteous.”"
  9,76,"But when He brought them of His grace, they became stingy with it and turned away in disregard."
  9,77,"So as a consequence, He caused hypocrisy to be in their hearts until the day they encounter Him—because they broke their promise to Allah and because they used to lie."
  9,78,"Have they not come to know that Allah knows their secret and private conversations, and that Allah is the Superb Knower of the hidden realms?"
  9,79,"Those who backbite the ones who give donations voluntarily from among the believers and the ones who find nothing <small>(to give)</small> except their own efforts, so they ridicule them—Allah has ridiculed them and for them is a painful punishment."
  9,80,"Ask<sup>sg</sup> forgiveness for them or do not ask forgiveness for them—<small>(even)</small> if you ask forgiveness for them seventy times, Allah will not forgive them. That is because they have denied Allah and His Messenger. And Allah does not guide the defiantly disobedient people."
  9,81,"Those who lagged behind were happy to stay behind <small>(in defiance of)</small> the Messenger of Allah, and they hated to strive with their wealths and themselves in the way of Allah, and they said, “Do not mobilize in the heat.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “The fire of Hell is much hotter, if they only comprehended.”"
  9,82,"So let them laugh a little, and <small>(then)</small> let them weep much in repayment for what they used to earn."
  9,83,"So if Allah ever returns you<sup>sg</sup> back to a faction of them and they ask your permission to go out, then say, “You will not set out with me, ever, nor will you combat any enemy with me; you were indeed content with staying behind the first time, so stay behind with those who lag behind.”"
  9,84,"And do not pray<sup>sg</sup> <small>(the funeral prayer)</small> over anyone of them who has died, ever, nor stand at his graveside; they have indeed denied Allah and His Messenger and have died while defiantly disobedient."
  9,85,"And do not let their possessions and their children impress you. Indeed, Allah wants to punish them thereby in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small>, and that their souls depart while they are deniers."
  9,86,"And when a surah<sup foot_note="366598">1</sup> is sent down <small>(stating)</small>: “Believe<sup>pl</sup> in Allah and strive with His Messenger,” the prominent among them ask you for an exemption, and they say, “Let us be with those who stay behind.”",footnotes:347061:Each portion of the Qur'an is called a ‘<i>surah’</i>, which is sometimes translated as ‘chapter’.
  9,87,"They were content to be with those who lag behind, and their hearts have been sealed, so they do not comprehend."
  9,88,"But the Messenger and those who have attained faith with him have striven with their wealths and themselves. And for those there is all what is good, and those are the successful ones."
  9,89,"Allah has prepared for them Gardens beneath which rivers flow, wherein they abide; that is the great triumph."
  9,90,"And those of the nomadic Arabs who made excuses came to ask for an exemption, while those who lied to Allah and His Messenger stayed behind. A painful punishment will befall those of them who have denied."
  9,91,"There is no blame on the weak ones nor on the sick ones nor on those who find nothing to spend, provided they are true to Allah and His Messenger. In no way should the ones who excel in doing good be blamed, and Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  9,92,"Nor <small>(is there any blame)</small> on those who, when they approached you<sup>sg</sup> to <small>(provide them with horses to)</small> carry them <small>(and)</small> you said, “I cannot find anything to carry you on,” turned away, their eyes overflowing with tears, grieving for not finding the means to spend."
  9,93,"Indeed, blame<sup foot_note="366599">1</sup> is only on those who ask you to exempt them, although they are rich. They were content to be with those who lag behind, and Allah has sealed their hearts, so they do not know.",footnotes:347062:Literally ‘way’: a way leading to punishment.
  9,94,"They present excuses to you<sup>pl</sup> when you come back to them. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Do not make excuses—we will not believe you; Allah has certainly informed us of your news. And Allah will see your deeds, as will His Messenger; then you will be returned to the Knower of the hidden realm and the manifest, and He will inform you of what you used to do.”"
  9,95,"They will swear by Allah to you<sup>pl</sup> when you return to them so that you may disregard them, so disregard them; they are an abomination and their shelter is Hell—a repayment for what they used to earn."
  9,96,"They swear<sup foot_note="366600">1</sup> to you so that you may be well pleased with them. But even if you become well pleased with them, Allah is indeed never pleased with the defiantly disobedient people.",footnotes:347063:A grammatical shift from future tense to present tense.
  9,97,"The nomadic Arabs are more steeped in denial and hypocrisy, and more likely not to know the limits of what Allah has sent down upon His Messenger. And Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  9,98,"And of the nomadic Arabs is one who considers whatever he spends to be a fine, and he awaits for a reversal of your fortunes. May the cycle of misfortune fall upon them! And Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing."
  9,99,"Yet of the nomadic Arabs is one who believes in Allah and the Last Day and considers whatever he spends to be <small>(a means towards) </small>closeness to Allah and the prayers of the Messenger. Undoubtedly, it does draw them<sup foot_note="366601">1</sup> closer. Allah will enter them into His mercy. Indeed, Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy.",footnotes:347064:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  9,100,"And the Pioneers—the first of the Emigrants<sup foot_note="366602">1</sup> and the Supporters<sup foot_note="366603">2</sup> and those who followed them in righteousness—Allah became well pleased with them and they became well pleased with Him, and He has prepared for them Gardens beneath which rivers flow, wherein they abide forever; that is the great triumph.",footnotes:347065:The first generation of Muslims who migrated from Makkah to Madinah.|347066:The inhabitants of Madinah who supported the Prophet (peace be upon him).
  9,101,"And of the nomadic Arabs around you there are hypocrites, and among the inhabitants of Madinah <small>(too)</small>; they have become adamant in hypocrisy. You do not know them; We know them. We will punish them twice, then they will be returned to a great punishment."
  9,102,"And <small>(there are)</small> others who have confessed their misdeeds—having mixed a righteous deed with another evil one—in the hope that Allah will grant them repentance and accept it from them. Indeed, Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  9,103,"Take<sup>sg</sup> a donation from their wealths to sanctify them and purify them with, and pray for them; indeed, your <span class="h">prayer<sup foot_note="366604">1</sup></span> is <small>(a source of)</small> rest for them. And Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing.",footnotes:347067:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “indeed, your prayers are…”</span>
  9,104,"Have they not come to know that Allah is the One Who accepts repentance from His servants, and takes the donations, and that Allah is the Granter and Accepter of repentance, the Bestower of mercy?"
  9,105,"And say, “Work, for Allah will see your work, as will His Messenger and the believers, and then you will be returned to the Knower of the hidden realm and the manifest, and He will inform you of what you used to do.”"
  9,106,"And <small>(there are)</small> others who are deferred until the command of Allah—whether He will punish them or grant them repentance and accept it from them. And Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  9,107,"<span class="h">And<sup foot_note="366605">1</sup></span><small> (there are)</small> the ones who took <small>(for themselves)</small> a mosque to cause harm and disbelief and disunity among the believers, and as an outpost for those who fought Allah and His Messenger earlier, though they will most surely swear: “We only wanted the best,” but Allah bears witness that they are certainly liars.",footnotes:347068:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “(There are) the ones…”</span>
  9,108,"Do not stand in it, ever. Surely, a mosque founded upon mindfulness <small>(of God)</small> from the first day is worthier of your standing in it. In it are men who love to purify themselves, and Allah loves those who always purify themselves."
  9,109,"Is the one who <span class="h">founded<sup foot_note="366606">1</sup></span> his structure upon mindfulness of Allah and <small>(His)</small> good pleasure better or the one who founded his structure on the brink of a cliff that was about to tumble, so that it tumbled with him into the fire of Hell? And Allah does not guide the unjust people.",footnotes:347069:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Ibn Amer read it as: “Is the one whose structure is founded upon ...”</span>
  9,110,"That structure of theirs that they have built will not cease being <small>(a source of)</small> suspicion in their hearts until their hearts are torn to pieces. And Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  9,111,"Allah has indeed purchased from the believers their <small>(very)</small> selves and their wealth, for which they shall have the Garden <small>(of Paradise, as a reward)</small>. They combat in the way of Allah, so they kill and get <span class="h">killed<sup foot_note="366607">1</sup></span>—a promise, binding on Him in the Torah and the Gospel and the Recital<sup foot_note="366608">2</sup> . And who is more faithful to his covenant than Allah? So be<sup>pl</sup> glad with that trade of yours which you have traded. And that is the great triumph.",footnotes:347070:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…so they get killed and kill…”</span>|347071:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  9,112,"The repentant ones, the worshipers, the ones who constantly praise, the travelers <small>(for good causes)</small>, the ones bowing down, the ones prostrating themselves, the ones who enjoin what is good and forbid what is deplorable, and the ones who preserve Allah’s limits. And give<sup>sg</sup> glad tidings to the believers."
  9,113,"Never would it befit the Prophet and those who have attained faith to ask forgiveness for the polytheists, even if they were close relatives, after it has become evident to them that they are the fellows of purgatory."
  9,114,"And Abraham's seeking of forgiveness for his father was only due to a promise he had made to him. But when it became evident to him that he was an enemy of Allah, he disowned him. Abraham is<sup foot_note="366609">1</sup> most surely kind, clement.",footnotes:347072:Frequently the Qur’an speaks about the prophets using present tense; this should be pondered by the reader.
  9,115,"And never would Allah lead any people astray after He had guided them until He made evident to them what they should be mindful of. Indeed, Allah is All-Knowing of everything."
  9,116,"Indeed, to Allah belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth; He gives life and He causes death. And apart from Allah you have neither ally nor supporter."
  9,117,"Allah has very truly granted repentance to the Prophet and the Emigrants and the Supporters who followed him in the hour of difficulty after the hearts of a group of them almost swerved, then He accepted their repentance; indeed, towards them He is Compassionate, Bestowing of mercy."
  9,118,"And <small>(likewise for)</small> the three who lagged behind until, when the earth—vast as it is—closed in on them and their own <small>(inner)</small> selves closed in on them and they thought that there was no refuge from Allah except in Him, He then granted them repentance, so that they may repent. Indeed, Allah is the Granter and Accepter of repentance, the Bestower of mercy."
  9,119,"O you who have attained faith, be mindful of Allah and be with the truthful."
  9,120,"Never would it befit the inhabitants of Madinah and the nomadic Arabs around them to lag behind the Messenger of Allah, nor to prefer themselves to him. That is because they never suffer any thirst or fatigue or starvation in the way of Allah, nor do they take one step that enrages the deniers, nor do they tread any territory that enrages the deniers, nor attain from an enemy any attainment, but it is recorded to their credit as a righteous deed. Indeed, Allah does not waste the reward of those who excel in doing good."
  9,121,"Nor do they spend any expenditure, small or large, nor do they cross any valley but it is recorded to their credit, that Allah may repay them for the best of what they used to do."
  9,122,"And never would it befit the believers to mobilize collectively. So why should there not be, of every section of them, a faction which mobilizes to study the religion and to warn their people when they return to them, so that they may beware?"
  9,123,"O you who have attained faith, combat those of the deniers who are adjacent to you, and let them find harshness in you, and know that Allah is with the people who are mindful <small>(of Him)</small>."
  9,124,"And whenever a surah<sup foot_note="366610">1</sup> is revealed, some of them say, “Which of you has this increased in faith?” As for those who have attained faith—it increases them in faith and they anticipate glad tidings.",footnotes:347073:Each portion of the Qur'an is called a ‘<i>surah’</i>, which is sometimes translated as ‘chapter’.
  9,125,"But as for those in whose hearts is sickness—it adds abomination to their abomination and they die as deniers."
  9,126,"Do they not <span class="h">see<sup foot_note="366611">1</sup></span> that they are tested every year once or twice? Yet they neither repent nor constantly remember.",footnotes:347074:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Ya’qub read it as: “Do you not see...”</span>
  9,127,"And whenever a surah<sup foot_note="366612">1</sup> is sent down, they look at one another, “Does anyone see you?” Then they turn away. Allah has turned away their hearts because they are people who do not comprehend.",footnotes:347075:Each portion of the Qur'an is called a ‘<i>surah’</i>, which is sometimes translated as ‘chapter’.
  9,128,"Very truly, there has come to you a messenger from among yourselves, concerned over your suffering, anxious over you; towards the believers<sup foot_note="366613">1</sup> he is compassionate, bestowing of mercy.",footnotes:347076:A grammatical shift from 2<sup>nd</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  9,129,"Yet if they turn away, then say<sup>sg</sup>, “Allah is sufficient for me; there is no god but He; in Him I have placed my trust, and He is the Lord of the Great Throne.”"
  10,1,"Alif Lām Ra. Those are the signs<sup foot_note="366614">1</sup> of the Wise Scripture.",footnotes:347077:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  10,2,"Was it a wonder to mankind that We revealed to a man from among them: “Warn mankind and give glad tidings to those who have attained faith that they are on a sound footing with their Lord”? The deniers said, “Most surely, this is an evident <span class="h">sorcerer<sup foot_note="366615">1</sup></span>.”",footnotes:347078:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…this is evident sorcery.”</span>
  10,3,"Indeed, your<sup>pl</sup> Lord is Allah, Who created the heavens and the earth in six days<sup foot_note="366616">1</sup> then settled over the Throne, governing every matter; there is no intercessor except after His permission. Such is Allah, your Lord, so worship Him. Will you not remind <span class="h">yourselves<sup foot_note="366617">2</sup></span>?",footnotes:347079:Six equal intervals of time, which may be six heavenly days, each of them being 1000 earthly years long (see 22: 47).|347080:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Will you not constantly remember?”</span>
  10,4,"To Him is your return, all together; the promise of Allah is true. <span class="h">Indeed<sup foot_note="366618">1</sup></span>, He originates creation and then restores it to repay those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds with equity. And those who have denied—for them is a drink of scalding water and a painful punishment on account of how they used to deny.",footnotes:347081:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “the promise of Allah is true: that He originates creation…”</span>
  10,5,"It is He Who made the sun radiance and the moon a light and determined phases for it, that you may know the number of years and the calculation. Allah did not create all this except with the truth<sup foot_note="366619">1</sup> . <span class="h">He<sup foot_note="366620">2</sup></span> details the signs<sup foot_note="366621">3</sup> for people who know.",footnotes:347082:According to Ibn Ashour and other exegetes, ‘with the truth’ means ‘for a purpose’.|347083:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Hafs and Ya’qub read it as: “We detail the signs for…”</span>|347084:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  10,6,"Indeed, in the alternation of night and day and in whatever Allah has created in the heavens and the earth are signs for people who are mindful <small>(of Him)</small>."
  10,7,"Indeed, those who do not expect to meet Us and have been content with the Earlier Life and have become serene thereby, and those who are oblivious of Our signs,"
  10,8,"those—their shelter is the Fire on account of what they used to earn."
  10,9,"Indeed, those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—their Lord guides them in their faith; rivers flow beneath them in the Gardens of Bliss."
  10,10,"Their call therein is, “Highly Exalted are You, our God,” and their greeting therein is, “Peace.” And the last of their call is, “Praise be to Allah, Lord of all realms.”"
  10,11,"And if Allah were to expedite evil for mankind as they wish to expedite good, their term would have been <span class="h">fulfilled<sup foot_note="366622">1</sup></span> for them; so We<sup foot_note="366623">2</sup> leave those who do not expect to meet Us to wander aimlessly while exceeding all limits.",footnotes:347085:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “…He would have fulfilled their term for them”</span>|347086:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 1 person to 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.
  10,12,"And whenever harm touches man, he calls upon Us—reclining on his side or sitting or standing. But when We lift harm off of him, he goes away as though he had never called upon Us for any harm that had touched him. Thus was adorned for the extremists what they used to do."
  10,13,"And very truly We annihilated generations before youpl when they did injustices, while messengers came to them with evident proofs, but they would not believe. Thus We repay the criminal people."
  10,14,"Then We made you successors on earth after them to look how you would behave."
  10,15,"And when Our signs<sup foot_note="366624">1</sup> are read to them as evident explanations, those who do not expect to meet Us say, “Bring<sup>sg</sup> a recital<sup foot_note="366625">2</sup> other than this or change it.” Say, “It is not for me to change it of my own accord; I only follow what is revealed to me; I certainly fear, were I to disobey my Lord, the punishment of a great day.”",footnotes:347087:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.|347088:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  10,16,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Had Allah willed, I would not have read it to you<sup>pl</sup> and He would <span class="h">not<sup foot_note="366626">1</sup></span> have informed you about it, for I have certainly lived among you for a lifetime before it. Do you not reason?”",footnotes:347089:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Bazzi in one of his narrations read it as: “…and He would have informed you about it (through someone else,)”</span>
  10,17,"So who is more unjust than someone who has fabricated lies against Allah or has disbelieved in His signs? Indeed, the criminals never succeed."
  10,18,"And they worship, apart from Allah, what neither harms them nor benefits them, and they say, “These are our intercessors with Allah.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Are you<sup>pl</sup> informing Allah about what He does not know in the heavens or in the earth?” Highly Exalted is He and Most High above whatever <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="366627">1</sup></span> associate <small>(with Him).</small>",footnotes:347090:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…whatever you associate…”</span>
  10,19,"Mankind was but a single community, then they differed. And were it not for a word that had preceded from your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, judgment would have been decreed between them regarding whatever they differ over."
  10,20,"And they say, “If only a <small>(miraculous)</small> sign had been sent down to him from his Lord.” So say<sup>sg</sup>, “Indeed, the hidden realm belongs to Allah, so wait<sup>pl</sup>; I am indeed with you among those waiting.”"
  10,21,"And when We make mankind taste mercy after some adversity has touched them, there they are with a scheme against Our signs. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Allah is Swifter in scheming.” Our messengers are indeed writing down what you<sup>pl</sup> <span class="h">scheme<sup foot_note="366628">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:347091:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Rouh read it as: “…what they scheme.”</span>
  10,22,"It is He Who <span class="h">transports<sup foot_note="366629">1</sup></span> you<sup>pl</sup> across land and sea until, when you are on ships, sailing in a good wind and they<sup foot_note="366630">2</sup> rejoice in it, a stormy wind arrives and the waves surge over them from every side and they realize that they are besieged—thereupon they call upon Allah, devoting religion to Him: “If You save us from this, we will most surely be of the thankful.”",footnotes:347092:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “It is He Who scatters you<sup lang="en-US">pl</sup>…”</span>|347093:A grammatical shift in from 2<sup>nd</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  10,23,"But when He has saved them, there they are, committing unjustified aggression in the land. O mankind, your<sup>pl</sup> oppression is only against yourselves—<small>(you only <span class="h">enjoy)</span></small><sup foot_note="366631">1</sup> the enjoyment of the Earlier Life, then to Us is your<sup>pl</sup> return and We will inform you<sup>pl</sup> of what you used to do.",footnotes:347094:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Hafs read it as: “O mankind, your oppression against yourselves is (only) the enjoyment of the Earlier Life,”</span>
  10,24,"Indeed, the parable of the Earlier Life is but like water that We sent down from the sky, then it was absorbed by the plants of the earth—from which mankind and cattle eat—until, when the earth has put on its decorations and is adorned and its inhabitants think that they have mastered it, Our command comes upon it by night or by day and We turn it into stubble, as if it had not flourished the day before. Thus We detail the signs for people who reflect."
  10,25,"And Allah invites to the Home of Peace and guides whomever He wills to a straight path."
  10,26,"For those who have done good is the best and <small>(even)</small> more, and neither gloom nor humiliation overwhelms their faces. Those are the fellows of the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small>; therein they abide."
  10,27,"But those who have earned evil deeds— the repayment of an evil deed shall be the like of it, and humiliation overwhelms them; they will have no safeguard from Allah, as if their faces have been covered with dark <span class="h">patches<sup foot_note="366632">1</sup></span> of night. Those are the fellows of the Fire; therein they abide.",footnotes:347095:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “…covered by the dark phase of the night."</span>
  10,28,"And on the day when We herd them all together, then say to those who ascribed associates <small>(to God)</small>, “To your place, you and your associates.” Then We separated<sup foot_note="366633">1</sup> between them, and their associates said, “It was not us youpl used to worship.",footnotes:347096:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  10,29,"So Allah is sufficient as a witness between us and you<sup>pl</sup>. Decidedly, we were indeed oblivious to your<sup>pl</sup> worship.”"
  10,30,"There and then every single self <span class="h">experiences<sup foot_note="366634">1</sup></span> what it has previously done. And they were <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="366635">2</sup></span> to Allah, their True Patron, and whatever they used to fabricate strayed away from them.",footnotes:347097:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…every single self reads what it has previously done.”</span>|347098:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “And to Allah all matters return.”</span>
  10,31,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Who <small>(else then)</small> provides for you from the heaven and the earth? And who controls the hearing and the sight<small>(s)</small>? And who brings out the living from the dead and brings out the dead from the living? And who governs every matter?” So they will say, “Allah.” So say<sup>sg</sup>, “Will you<sup>pl</sup> never be mindful <small>(of God)</small>?"
  10,32,"For that is Allah, your true Lord, so what is there beyond the truth except misguidance? So how then are you turned away?”"
  10,33,"Thus your<sup>sg</sup> Lord’s <span class="h">Word<sup foot_note="366636">1</sup></span> proved true against those who defiantly disobeyed: that they do not believe.",footnotes:347099:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “Words”</span>
  10,34,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Can any of your<sup>pl</sup> associates <small>(whom you ascribed to God)</small> originate creation then restore it?” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Allah originates creation then restores it, so how can they be averted <small>(from the truth)</small>?”"
  10,35,"Say, “Can any of your associates <small>(whom you ascribed to God)</small> guide to the truth?” Say, “Allah guides to the truth. Is the One Who guides to the truth more worthy of being followed or the one who finds no <span class="h">guidance<sup foot_note="366637">1</sup></span><small>(for himself or for others)</small> unless he is guided? So what is the matter with you<sup>pl</sup>? How do you judge?”",footnotes:347100:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…or the one who cannot guide (anyone) unless he is guided?”</span>
  10,36,"Thus most of them follow nothing but assumptions; indeed, assumptions avail nothing against the truth. Indeed, Allah is All-Aware of what they do."
  10,37,"And never could this Recital<sup foot_note="366638">1</sup> have been fabricated by anyone despite Allah. Rather, <small>(it is)</small> a confirmation of what preceded it and a detailed elaboration of the inscribed <small>(decrees)</small>. There is no doubt about it—<small>(it is)</small> from the Lord of all realms.",footnotes:347101:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  10,38,"Or do they say, “He has fabricated it”? Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Then produce a single surah<sup foot_note="366639">1</sup> like it and call upon whomever you can apart from Allah, if you are truthful.”",footnotes:347102:Each portion of the Qur'an is called a <i>surah,</i> which is sometimes translated as 'chapter'.
  10,39,"Rather, they have disbelieved in what they could not encompass with their knowledge and the interpretation of which has not yet reached them. Thus those before them disbelieved as well, so look what the outcome was for the unjust<sup>pl</sup>."
  10,40,"And of them are those who believe in it, and of them are those who do not believe in it. And your<sup>sg</sup> Lord knows better of the corrupters."
  10,41,"And if they disbelieve you<sup>sg</sup>, say, “I have my doing and you<sup>pl</sup> have your doing; you are innocent of what I do, and I am innocent of what you do.”"
  10,42,"And of them are those who listen to you<sup>sg</sup>. But can you make the deaf hear, even if they do not reason?"
  10,43,"And of them are those who look at you. But can you guide the blind, even though they do not see?"
  10,44,"Indeed, Allah does not do injustice to mankind in anything, but mankind do injustice to themselves."
  10,45,"And on the day when He <span class="h">herds<sup foot_note="366640">1</sup></span> them, <small>(it will be)</small> as if they had remained for only one hour of a day, getting to know one another. Those who disbelieved in the meeting with Allah have certainly lost, and they were not guided.",footnotes:347103:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as: “…when We herd them,”</span>
  10,46,"Whether We do show you<sup>sg</sup> some of what We promise them or take you at death, to Us is their return. Then Allah<sup foot_note="366641">1</sup> is witness to whatever they do.",footnotes:347104:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  10,47,"And for every community there is a messenger. So when their messenger comes, matters are decreed between them with justice, and they are not dealt with unjustly."
  10,48,"And they say, “When will this promise be fulfilled, if you<sup>pl</sup> are truthful?”"
  10,49,"Say, “I have no power to harm or benefit <small>(even)</small> myself, except as Allah wills. For every community there is a <small>(specified)</small> term. When their term has arrived, they cannot then delay by one hour nor can they advance."
  10,50,"Say, “Have you seen: if His punishment overtakes you<sup>pl</sup> by nighttime or by day, what part of it will the criminals seek to hasten?”"
  10,51,"“Then is it only when it befalls that you believe in it? Now? While <small>(challengingly,)</small> you have been asking for it to be hastened?”"
  10,52,"Then it was said<sup foot_note="366642">1</sup> to those who committed injustice, “Taste the punishment of eternity. Are you being repaid except in accordance with what you used to earn?”",footnotes:347105:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  10,53,"And they inquire of you<sup>sg</sup>, “Is it true?” Say, “Yes, by my Lord, it is most surely true, and in no way can you<sup>pl</sup> thwart <small>(God)</small>.”"
  10,54,"And if every single self which had committed injustice possessed whatever is in the earth, it would offer it as a ransom. And they hid<sup foot_note="366643">1</sup> their remorse when they saw the punishment, and it was judged between them equitably. And they are not dealt with unjustly.",footnotes:347106:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  10,55,"Undoubtedly, to Allah does belong whatever is in the heavens and the earth. Undoubtedly, the promise of Allah is indeed true, but most of them do not know."
  10,56,"He gives life and causes death, and to Him you<sup>pl</sup> are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="366644">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:347107:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “and to Him you return.”</span>
  10,57,"O mankind, there has come to you an admonition from your Lord and a cure for what lies within the chests and guidance and mercy for the believers."
  10,58,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “In Allah’s grace and in His mercy—in that then, let them rejoice; it is better than what they <span class="h">hoard<sup foot_note="366645">1</sup></span>.”",footnotes:347108:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…let them rejoice; it is better than what you<sup>pl</sup> hoard.” hoard.” Roways read it as: “…do rejoice<sup>pl</sup>; it is better than what you hoard.”; it is better than what you hoard.”</span>
  10,59,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Have youpl seen the provision Allah has sent down for you, some of which you made unlawful and some lawful?” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Did Allah give you<sup>pl</sup> permission, or do you fabricate lies and attribute them to Allah?”"
  10,60,"And what assumption do those who fabricate lies and attribute them to Allah have about the Day of Resurrection? Most surely, Allah is the Possessor of grace towards mankind, but most of them do not give thanks."
  10,61,"For you<sup>sg</sup><small> </small>do not engage in any affair, nor do you<sup>sg</sup> read any <small>(portion)</small> of the Recital<sup foot_note="366646">1</sup>, nor do you<sup>pl</sup> do anything, but We are witnessing over you<sup>pl</sup> as you undertake it. And not even the weight of an atom in the earth or in the heaven escapes yoursg Lord<sup foot_note="366647">2</sup>, for nothing smaller than this nor <span class="h">larger<sup foot_note="366648">3</sup></span> but is in an evident record<sup foot_note="366649">4</sup> .",footnotes:347109:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.|347110:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.|347111:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “…escapes your<sup>sg </sup>Lord, nor is there anything smaller or larger but is in an evident record.”Lord, nor is there anything smaller or larger but is in an evident record.”</span>|347112:Literally ‘scripture’.
  10,62,"Undoubtedly, Allah’s allies—indeed no fear shall be upon them, nor shall they grieve:"
  10,63,"those who have attained faith and have been mindful <small>(of God)</small>."
  10,64,"For them are glad tidings in the Earlier Life and in the Hereafter. There is no exchange for the words of Allah; that is the great triumph."
  10,65,"And let not their statements sadden you<sup>sg</sup>. Indeed, all might belongs to Allah; He is the All-Hearing, the All-Knowing."
  10,66,"Undoubtedly, to Allah does belong everyone in the heavens and everyone in the earth. And those who call upon others apart from Allah do not follow associates <small>(of Him)</small>; rather they follow nothing but assumptions, and they do nothing but guess."
  10,67,"It is He Who made the night for you<sup>pl</sup>, that you may rest therein, and the day allowing sight. Most surely in that are signs for people who <small>(can)</small> hear."
  10,68,"They said, “Allah has taken <small>(for Himself)</small> offspring.” Highly Exalted is He; He is the Self-Sufficient; to Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth. Do you<sup>pl</sup> have any manifestation regarding this? Are you saying about Allah what you do not know?"
  10,69,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Those who fabricate lies and attribute them to Allah do not succeed.”"
  10,70,"Enjoyment in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small>, then to Us is their return, then We make them taste the severe punishment on account of how they used to deny."
  10,71,"And read<sup>sg</sup> to them the story of Noah, when he said to his people, “O my people, if my presence among you and my reminding you of Allah’s signs is too much for you, then in Allah I have placed my trust. So agree together about your decision and your <span class="h">associates<sup foot_note="366650">1</sup></span>, and do not let the matter perplex you<sup>pl</sup>; then carry out your decision on me and do not reprieve me.",footnotes:347113:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Roways read it as: “So bring together all your matters, and so should your associates,” Rouh read it as: “So agree together about your decision, and so should your associates,”</span>
  10,72,"But if you<sup>pl</sup> turn away, then <small>(know that)</small> I have not asked you for any reward; my reward is only from Allah, and I was commanded to be of the Muslims<sup foot_note="366651">1</sup> ”",footnotes:347114:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  10,73,"But they disbelieved him, then We delivered him and those with him in the ship and made them successors, and We drowned those who disbelieved in Our signs; so look<sup>sg</sup> at what the outcome was for those forewarned!"
  10,74,"Then, after him, We sent messengers to their people, and they came to them with evident proofs, but they would not believe in anything they had disbelieved in previously. Thus We set a seal on the hearts of the transgressors."
  10,75,"Then, after them, We sent Moses and Aaron with Our signs to Pharaoh and his chiefs, but they acted arrogantly and were a criminal people."
  10,76,"And when the truth came to them from Us, they said, “Most surely, this is evident sorcery.”"
  10,77,"Moses said, “Is this what you<sup>pl</sup> say of the truth when it has come to you? Is this sorcery, when sorcerers are never successful?”"
  10,78,"They said, “Have you come to us to divert us from what we found our fathers practicing, and so that you both become prominent in the land? For we will never believe in you<sup foot_note="366652">1</sup> .”",footnotes:347115:Addressing Moses and Aaron.
  10,79,"And Pharaoh said, “Bring<sup>pl</sup> me every knowledgeable <span class="h">sorcerer<sup foot_note="366653">1</sup></span>.”",footnotes:347116:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Bring<sup lang="en-US">pl</sup> me every knowledgeable, proficient sorcerer.”</span>
  10,80,"Then when the sorcerers came, Moses said to them, “Throw whatever you will throw.”"
  10,81,"So when they threw, Moses said, “What you produced is <span class="h">sorcery<sup foot_note="366654">1</sup></span>; indeed, Allah will nullify it; indeed, Allah does not set aright the work of the corrupters.",footnotes:347117:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr and Abu Ja’far read it as: “What you have produced—is it sorcery? Indeed, Allah will nullify it;”</span>
  10,82,"And Allah upholds the truth with His words, even if the criminals dislike it.”"
  10,83,"But none believed in Moses except some of the offspring of his people, while fearing that Pharaoh and their chiefs would persecute them. And most surely, Pharaoh is highly exalted in the land, and he is<sup foot_note="366655">1</sup> most surely of the extremists.",footnotes:347118:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense.
  10,84,"Thus Moses said, “O my people, if you have attained faith in Allah, then in Him place your trust, if you are <small>(truly)</small> Muslims<sup foot_note="366656">1</sup> .”",footnotes:347119:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  10,85,"So they said, “In Allah we have placed our trust. Our Lord, do not make us a means of trial for the unjust people,"
  10,86,"and deliver us by Your mercy from the denying people.”"
  10,87,"And We revealed to Moses and his brother, “Settle your people in houses in Egypt and make your<sup>pl</sup> houses places which people head to for worship, and establishpl the prayer. And give<sup>sg</sup> glad tidings to the believers.”"
  10,88,"And Moses said, “Our Lord, You have indeed given Pharaoh and his chiefs ornaments and wealth in the Earlier Life, our Lord, <small>(which they used)</small> to make <small>(others)</small> <span class="h">stray<sup foot_note="366657">1</sup></span> from Your way. Our Lord, obliterate their wealths and harden their hearts so that they do not believe until they see the painful punishment.”",footnotes:347120:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…to stray from Your way.”</span>
  10,89,"He said, “Your<sup>dl</sup> prayer has been responded to, so be upright and do not follow the way of those who do not know.”"
  10,90,"And We made the Children of Israel pass over the sea. So Pharaoh and his troops pursued them oppressively and aggressively until, when he was about to drown, he said, “I have attained belief <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="366658">1</sup></span> there is no god except the One the Children of Israel believe in, and I am of the Muslims<sup foot_note="366659">2</sup> .”",footnotes:347121:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “I have attained belief. Indeed, there is no god except the One…”</span>|347122:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  10,91,"Now? While before you truly disobeyed and were of the corrupters?"
  10,92,"Rather, today We <span class="h">deliver<sup foot_note="366660">1</sup></span> you, preserving only your body, so that you become a sign for those after you. But most surely, many among mankind are oblivious of Our signs.",footnotes:347123:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “Rather, today We save you, preserving only your body,”</span>
  10,93,"And We settled the Children of Israel in an agreeable location and provided them with good things, so they did not differ until knowledge came to them. Indeed, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord<sup foot_note="366661">1</sup> judges between them on the Day of Resurrection regarding whatever they used to differ over.",footnotes:347124:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  10,94,"So if yousg are in doubt about what We have sent down to you, then ask those who recite the Scripture before you. Very truly, the truth has come to you from your Lord<sup foot_note="366662">1</sup>, so never be of the skeptics,",footnotes:347125:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  10,95,"and never be of those who have disbelieved in Allah’s signs lest you become of the losers."
  10,96,"Indeed, those against whom your<sup>sg</sup> Lord’s <span class="h">Word<sup foot_note="366663">1</sup></span> proved true do not believe,",footnotes:347126:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “Words”</span>
  10,97,"even if every sign comes to them—until they see the painful punishment."
  10,98,"So if only there was one town that believed and benefited by its belief, besides the people of Jonah—when they believed, We removed from them the punishment of disgrace in the Earlier Life and We gave them enjoyment for a while."
  10,99,"And had your<sup>sg</sup> Lord willed, everyone on earth would have believed, all of them, together. Will you compel mankind to become believers?"
  10,100,"And never could a single self believe except by Allah’s leave. And He <span class="h">lays<sup foot_note="366664">1</sup></span> abomination upon those who do not reason.",footnotes:347127:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “And We lay…”</span>
  10,101,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Look<sup>pl</sup> at what is in the heavens and the earth.” But signs and warnings are of no avail for people who do not believe."
  10,102,"So do they await anything but the like of the days of those who passed on before them? Say<sup>sg</sup>, “So wait<sup>pl</sup>, I am indeed with you among those waiting.”"
  10,103,"Then We <span class="h">deliver<sup foot_note="366665">1</sup></span> Our messengers and those who have attained faith. Thus it is binding upon Us to <span class="h">save<sup foot_note="366666">2</sup></span> the believers.",footnotes:347128:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “Then We save Our messengers…”</span>|347129:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “…to deliver the believers.”</span>
  10,104,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “O mankind, if you are in doubt about my religion, then <small>(know that)</small> I do not worship those you worship apart from Allah; rather I worship Allah, Who takes you at death, and I have been commanded to be of the believers.”"
  10,105,"And dedicate yourself to the religion—turning away from all that is false—and never be of the polytheists."
  10,106,"And do<sup>sg</sup> not call, apart from Allah, upon what neither benefits you nor harms you<sup>sg</sup>, for if you do, you are then one of the unjust."
  10,107,"And if Allah touches you<sup>sg</sup> with harm, none can remove it except He; and if He wants good for you, none can repel His grace. He makes it reach whomever He wills of His servants, for He is the Oft-Forgiving, the Bestower of mercy."
  10,108,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “O mankind, surely the truth has come to you from your Lord, so whoever is guided—he is only guided to his own benefit, while whoever goes astray—he only goes astray to his own detriment; and in no way am I a trustee over you.”"
  10,109,"And follow<sup>sg</sup> what is revealed to you, and be patient until Allah issues His judgment, for He is the Best of judges."
  11,1,"Alif Lām Ra. A Scripture whose signs<sup foot_note="366667">1</sup> were perfected, then detailed, from One Who is All-Wise, All-Aware:",footnotes:347130:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat </i>(singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah </i>means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  11,2,"that you<sup>pl</sup> shall worship none but Allah. <small>(Say)</small>, “Indeed, I am to you from Him a warner and a herald of glad tidings."
  11,3,"So ask<sup>pl</sup> your Lord for forgiveness then repent to Him, that He may grant you good enjoyment for a stated term and bestow His grace upon every graceful one. But if they<sup foot_note="366668">1</sup> <span class="h">turn<sup foot_note="366669">2</sup></span> away, then I fear for you the punishment of a supreme day.",footnotes:347131:A grammatical shift from 2<sup>nd</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.|347132:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Bazzi read it as: “But if you<sup>pl</sup> turn away,” turn away,”</span>
  11,4,"To Allah is your return, and He is All-Powerful over everything.”"
  11,5,"Undoubtedly, they do bend their chests to hide from Him. Undoubtedly, even as they cover themselves with their clothes, He knows whatever they keep secret and whatever they make public; He is indeed All-Knowing of what lies within the chests."
  11,6,"And there is no treading creature in the earth but its provision depends on Allah, and He knows its residence and its depository; all is in an evident record<sup foot_note="366670">1</sup> .",footnotes:347133:Literally ‘scripture’.
  11,7,"And it is He Who created the heavens and the earth in six days<sup foot_note="366671">1</sup> —and His Throne was upon the waters—in order to test you as to which of you is better in conduct. And if you<sup>sg</sup> were to say, “You<sup>pl</sup> will be resurrected after death,” those who denied would most surely say, “This is nothing but evident <span class="h">sorcery<sup foot_note="366672">2</sup></span>.”",footnotes:347134:Six equal intervals of time, which may be six heavenly days, each of them being 1000 earthly years long (see 22:47).|347135:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…an evident sorcerer.”</span>
  11,8,"And if We were to defer the punishment from them until a fixed period of time, they would most surely say, “What holds it back?” Undoubtedly, on the day when it comes to them, it is not averted from them, and they became<sup foot_note="366673">1</sup> surrounded by what they used to ridicule.",footnotes:347136:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  11,9,"And if We were to give man a taste of mercy from Us and then withdraw it from him, he is very truly a constantly despairing, staunch denier."
  11,10,"And if We were to give him a taste of prosperity after some adversity has touched him, he would most surely say, “Troubles have gone away from me;” he is very truly exultant, boastful—"
  11,11,"except for those who have been patient and have done righteous deeds; for those there is forgiveness and a supreme reward."
  11,12,"So would you<sup>sg</sup> possibly leave out some of what is revealed to you, and would your chest be tightened by it, because they say, “If only a treasure were sent down to him or an angel came with him?” Indeed, you are only a warner, and Allah is a Trustee over everything."
  11,13,"Or do they say, “He has fabricated it?” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Then produce ten surahs<sup foot_note="366674">1</sup> like it, fabricated, and call upon whomever you can apart from Allah, if you are truthful.”",footnotes:347137:Each portion of the Qur'an is called a <i>surah,</i> which is sometimes translated as 'chapter'.
  11,14,"But if they do not respond to you<sup>pl</sup>, know that it was sent down with Allah’s knowledge and that there is no god but He, so will you then become Muslims<sup foot_note="366675">1</sup> ?",footnotes:347138:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  11,15,"Whoever has been wanting the Earlier Life and its adornment—We will render to them<sup foot_note="366676">1</sup> in full <small>(the reward for)</small> their deeds therein, and therein they will not be defrauded.",footnotes:347139:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  11,16,"Those are the ones for whom there is nothing in the Hereafter but the Fire, and whatever they used to do therein has been nullified, and worthless is what they used to do."
  11,17,"Is someone who has been relying on evident proof from his Lord, and it is read by a witness from Him, and before it the Scripture of Moses—a guide and a mercy…<sup foot_note="366677">1</sup> ? Those believe in it<sup foot_note="366678">2</sup> . But whoever denies it from among the <small>(various)</small> parties—the Fire is his promised place. So do not regard it with skepticism; it is the truth from your Lord, but most of mankind does not believe.",footnotes:347140:This sentence is left open-ended; according to Al-Beqaʻi and other exegetes its predicate is: “equal to a denier?”|347141:The Qur’an.
  11,18,"And who is more unjust than someone who fabricated lies about Allah? Those are presented before their Lord, and the notable witnesses say, “These are the ones who lied about their Lord.” Undoubtedly, the curse of Allah is upon the unjust"
  11,19,"who bar <small>(others)</small> from the way of Allah and seek to make it crooked, and regarding the Hereafter they are deniers."
  11,20,"Those were never able to thwart <small>(God)</small> on earth, for never did they have any protectors apart from Allah. Punishment for them is multiplied. Never were they able to hear, nor could they see.<sup foot_note="366679">1</sup>",footnotes:347142:According to some exegetes it means: Never were they able to hear the word of God, nor could they see His signs.
  11,21,"Those are the ones who lost their <small>(inner)</small> selves, and whatever they used to fabricate strayed away from them."
  11,22,"Without doubt, in the Hereafter they are the biggest losers."
  11,23,"Indeed, those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds and have humbled themselves before their Lord—those are the fellows of the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small>; therein they abide."
  11,24,"The parable of the two groups is that of one who is blind and deaf, and one who is seeing and hearing. Are they equal in similitude? Will you not remind <span class="h">yourselves<sup foot_note="366680">1</sup></span>?",footnotes:347143:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Will you not constantly remember?”</span>
  11,25,"And very truly We sent Noah to his people, “I am to you an evident warner:"
  11,26,"that you shall worship none but Allah; indeed, I fear for you the punishment of a painful day.”"
  11,27,"So the chiefs of his people, who denied, said, “We do not see that you are anything but a human being like us, and we do not see that you are followed except by the lowliest among us, those of immature opinion, and we do not see that you<sup>pl</sup> have any advantage over us. Rather, we think you are liars.”"
  11,28,"He said, “O my people, have you seen? What if I rely on evident proof from my Lord, and He has given me a mercy of His own, but it was made invisible to <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="366681">1</sup></span>—can we compel you to accept it even though you dislike it?",footnotes:347144:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…but it became invisible to you.”</span>
  11,29,"And O my people, I ask of you no wealth for it; my reward lies only with Allah. And I will never expel those who have attained faith; they are bound to meet their Lord, whereas I see that you are a people who act in ignorance."
  11,30,"And O my people, who will support me against Allah if I expel them? Will you not remind <span class="h">yourselves<sup foot_note="366682">1</sup></span>?",footnotes:347145:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Will you not constantly remember?”</span>
  11,31,"And I do not say to you, 'I possess the treasuries of Allah', and I know not what is hidden; nor do I say, 'I am indeed an angel;' nor do I say of those whom your eyes scorn, 'Allah will never give them any good.' Allah knows better about what lies within their <small>(inner)</small> selves. <small>(If I were to say so,)</small> then I would indeed be one of the unjust.”"
  11,32,"They said, “O Noah, you have argued with us and have kept arguing for too long. Now bring upon us what you promise us, if you have been of the truthful.”"
  11,33,"He said, “It is Allah Who brings it upon you if He wills, and you can never thwart <small>(Him)</small>."
  11,34,"And my advice will not benefit you—even if I wanted to advise you—in case Allah wants to delude you. He is your Lord, and to Him you are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="366683">1</sup></span>.”",footnotes:347146:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “and to Him you return.”</span>
  11,35,"Or do they say, “He has fabricated it?” Say, “If I have fabricated it, then upon me falls my crime, and I am innocent of the crimes you commit.”"
  11,36,"And it was revealed to Noah: “Certainly, none of your people will attain faith except those who have already attained faith, so do not grieve over what they have been doing."
  11,37,"And build the ship under Our eyes and with Our inspiration, and do not address Me regarding those who have done injustice; they are to be drowned.”"
  11,38,"And he builds<sup foot_note="366684">1</sup> the ship, and whenever some chiefs from among his people passed by him, they would mock him. He said, “If you mock us, surely we mock you just as you mock;",footnotes:347147:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense, which serves to create a vivid portrait of past events.
  11,39,"then you will come to know upon whom shall come a punishment that disgraces him, and upon whom a perpetual punishment shall fall.”"
  11,40,"Until, when Our command came and the oven overflowed<sup foot_note="366685">1</sup>, We said, “Carry in it, of each kind, a male and female <span class="h">couple<sup foot_note="366686">2</sup></span>, and your family—except those against whom the sentence has already been passed—and those who have attained faith.” But none attained faith with him except a few.",footnotes:347148:As a sign to embark the ship.|347149:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as:”<big> </big>Carry in it, of each female and male kind, one couple,”Carry in it, of each female and male kind, one couple,”</span>
  11,41,"And he said, “Embark in it. In the name of Allah shall be its <span class="h">sailing<sup foot_note="366687">1</sup></span> and its anchorage. My Lord is most surely Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy.”",footnotes:347150:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr and Warsh read it as: “In the name of Allah who causes it to sail and who causes it to anchor.”</span>
  11,42,"And so it sails<sup foot_note="366688">1</sup> with them amidst waves like mountains. And Noah called to his son who had kept away, “O my child! Embark with us and do not be with the deniers.”",footnotes:347151:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense, which serves to create a vivid portrait of past events.
  11,43,"He said, “I will take shelter on a mountain which can safeguard me from the water.” He said, “There is no safeguard from Allah’s command today, except for the one on whom He has bestowed mercy.” And the waves surged between them, and he became of the drowned."
  11,44,"And it was said, “O land, swallow your waters,” and “O sky, clear up.” And the waters receded, and the matter was concluded, and it settled on <small>(mount)</small> Judei, and it was said: “Away with the unjust people.”"
  11,45,"And Noah called to his Lord and said, “O My Lord, my son is indeed of my family, and Your promise is indeed the truth, and You are the Wisest of all judges.”"
  11,46,"He said, “O Noah, he is not of your family; surely, it is an unrighteous <span class="h">deed<sup foot_note="366689">1</sup></span>, so do <span class="h">not<sup foot_note="366690">2</sup></span> ask Me about something you know nothing about; I surely admonish you lest you be one of the ignorant.”",footnotes:347152:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “…surely, he acted unrighteously,”</span>|347153:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…so never ask me about…”</span>
  11,47,"He said, “O My Lord, I do seek refuge with You from asking You about what I have no knowledge of, and unless You forgive me and have mercy on me, I will be one of the losers.”"
  11,48,"It was said, “O Noah, disembark with peace from Us, and with blessings upon you and upon communities that will spring from those with you. And to <small>(other)</small> communities We shall grant enjoyment, then a painful punishment from Us will touch them.”"
  11,49,"That is of the stories of the hidden realm which we reveal to you<sup>sg</sup>; never were you nor your people to know them before this, so be patient; the future outcome surely belongs to the people who are mindful <small>(of God)</small>."
  11,50,"And to Ād, their brother Hud. He said, “O my people, worship Allah; you have no other god but Him; you are nothing but fabricators."
  11,51,"O my people, I ask you no reward for it; my reward is only from the One who originated me. Do you not reason?"
  11,52,"And, O my people, ask forgiveness from your Lord then repent to Him. He will send down abundant rain from the sky for you and will add strength to your strength. But do not turn away as criminals.”"
  11,53,"They said, “O Hud, you did not come to us with any evident proof, and we shall not abandon our gods for your words, and we shall not believe in you."
  11,54,"We only say that some of our gods have possessed you with evil.” He said, “I call Allah to witness, and you to witness, that I am innocent of what you associate"
  11,55,"apart from Him. So plot against me, all together, then do not reprieve me."
  11,56,"I have indeed placed my trust in Allah, my Lord and your Lord. There is not a treading creature but He holds it by its forelock; indeed, my Lord is on a straight path."
  11,57,"But if <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="366691">1</sup></span> turn away, then I have conveyed to you what I was sent to you with. And my Lord will make other people succeed you, and you will not harm Him at all. My Lord is indeed a Constant Preserver over everything.”",footnotes:347154:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Bazzi read it as: “But if you<sup>pl</sup> turn away,” turn away,”</span>
  11,58,"Thus when Our command came, We delivered Hud and those who had attained faith with him, by mercy from Us, and We delivered them from a harsh punishment."
  11,59,"And that was Ād: they repudiated the signs of their Lord and disobeyed His messengers and followed the command of every stubborn tyrant."
  11,60,"And they were pursued by a curse in this Earlier <small>(Life)</small> and on the Day of Resurrection. Undoubtedly, Ād did deny their Lord. Undoubtedly, away with Ād, the people of Hud."
  11,61,"And to Thamûd, their brother Saleh. He said, “O my people, worship Allah; you have no god other than Him; He initiated you from the earth and assigned you to develop it, so seek His forgiveness and then repent to Him. My Lord is indeed Near, Responsive.”"
  11,62,"They said, “O Saleh, we had hopes in you before this. Are you forbidding us from worshiping what our parents worship? And most surely, we are in serious doubt regarding what you are calling us to.”"
  11,63,"He said, “O my people, have you seen: if I rely on evident proof from my Lord and He has given me mercy from Him? Who then would support me against Allah if I disobeyed Him? For you add nothing to me except causing losses."
  11,64,"And O my people, this is the she-camel of Allah—a sign for you—so let her graze in Allah’s land and do not touch her with any harm lest an imminent punishment overtake you.”"
  11,65,"But they hamstrung her, so he said, “Enjoy yourselves in your home for three days; that is a promise not to be belied.”"
  11,66,"Then when Our command came, We delivered Saleh and those who had attained faith with him, by mercy from Us, and from the disgrace of that day. Indeed, your Lord<sup foot_note="366692">1</sup> is the All-Powerful, the Almighty.",footnotes:347155:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  11,67,"And those who had done injustices were taken away by the Shout and became motionless bodies in their homes,"
  11,68,"as if they had never prospered therein. Undoubtedly, Thamûd did deny their Lord. Undoubtedly, away with Thamûd."
  11,69,"And very truly, Our messengers came to Abraham with glad tidings. They said, “Peace.” He said, “Peace,” and soon after he came with a roasted calf."
  11,70,"But when he saw their hands not reaching towards it, he distrusted them and conceived a fear of them. They said, “Do not fear; we have indeed been sent to the people of Lot.”"
  11,71,"And his wife was standing by, so she laughed. And We gave her glad tidings of Isaac<sup foot_note="366693">1</sup>, and after Isaac, Jacob.",footnotes:347156:The Hebrew word <i>Isaac</i> means 'he will laugh'.
  11,72,"She said, “Woe to me. Shall I give birth when I am an old woman and this, my husband, is an old man? This is truly an amazing thing!”"
  11,73,"They said, “Are you amazed at the command of Allah? The mercy and blessings of Allah are upon you, O people of the house. He is indeed Praiseworthy, Glorious.”"
  11,74,"And when Abraham's fear had subsided and the glad tidings had reached him—he argues<sup foot_note="366694">1</sup> with Us concerning the people of Lot.",footnotes:347157:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense.
  11,75,"Most surely, Abraham is forbearing, imploring, penitent."
  11,76,"“O Abraham, disregard this; surely your Lord's command has come, and an irreversible punishment shall surely be brought upon them.”"
  11,77,"And when Our messengers came to Lot, he was troubled over them and concerned for them, and he said, “This is a dreadful day.”"
  11,78,"And his people came rushing towards him, while earlier they were in the habit of doing evil deeds. He said, “O my people, these are my daughters; they are purer for you, so be mindful of Allah and do not disgrace me concerning my guests. Is there not one prudent man among you?”"
  11,79,"They said, “You have <small>(long)</small> known that we have no right to your daughters, and surely you know well what we want.”"
  11,80,"He said, “If only I had strength against you or could rely on some intense support.”"
  11,81,"They said, “O Lot, we are the messengers of your Lord; they will not reach you, so take your family on a journey while yet a part of the night remains, and let none of you look back. But not your <span class="h">wife<sup foot_note="366695">1</sup></span>—she will be afflicted by that which afflicts them. Indeed, their appointed time is the morning. Is not the morning near?”",footnotes:347158:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “so take your family on a journey while yet a part of the night remains. And let none of you look back except for your wife—she will be afflicted by…”</span>
  11,82,"And when Our command came, We turned it upside down, and We rained down on it stones of baked clay,"
  11,83,"marked from your<sup>sg</sup> Lord<sup foot_note="366696">1</sup>, and never far from the unjust<sup>pl</sup>.",footnotes:347159:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  11,84,"And to Midian, their brother Shuaib. He said, “O my people, worship Allah—you have no god other than Him—and do not give short measure or short weight. I see you are prospering, but I fear for you the punishment of an encompassing day.”"
  11,85,"“O my people, give full measure and full weight with justice, and do not defraud people of their belongings, and do not go wickedly about the land, corrupting it."
  11,86,"A remnant which is granted by Allah is better for you, if you are believers. And I am not a constant preserver over you.”"
  11,87,"They said, “O Shuaib, does your <span class="h">prayer<sup foot_note="366697">1</sup></span> command you that we abandon what our fathers worship or that we should not do with our wealth whatever we will? Very truly, you are the forbearing, prudent one!”",footnotes:347160:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…do your prayers command you…”</span>
  11,88,"He said, “O my people, can you see? What if I rely on evident proof from my Lord and He has provided me with good provision from Himself? And I have no desire to do what I forbid you from doing. I desire nothing but reform as far as I can. And in no way is my success with anyone except with Allah. In Him I have placed my trust, and to Him I turn penitently."
  11,89,"And O my people, let not your hostility towards me cause you to suffer what was suffered by the people of Noah or the people of Hud or the people of Saleh; and the people of Lot are not far off from you."
  11,90,"And ask your Lord for forgiveness and then repent to Him; my Lord is indeed Bestowing of Mercy, Most Loving.”"
  11,91,"They said, “O Shuaib, we do not comprehend much of what you say, and we see that you are weak among us; and were it not for your clan, we would have stoned you, for you have no might against us.”"
  11,92,"He said, “O my people, is my clan mightier to you than Allah? And you have turned your backs on Him? Indeed, my Lord is All-Encompassing of what you do."
  11,93,"And O my people, act according to your <span class="h">position<sup foot_note="366698">1</sup></span>; surely, I am also acting <small>(according to mine)</small>; you will know to whom will come a punishment that disgraces him and who it is that is a liar. So wait and watch; surely I too am watching out with you.”",footnotes:347161:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “…your positions”</span>
  11,94,"And when Our command came, We delivered Shuaib and those who had attained faith with him, by mercy from Us. And the Shout took away those who had done injustices, so they became motionless bodies in their homes"
  11,95,"as if they had never prospered therein. Undoubtedly, away with Midian as was done away with Thamûd."
  11,96,"And very surely, We sent Moses with Our signs and an evident manifestation"
  11,97,"to Pharaoh and his chiefs, but they followed the command of Pharaoh, and never was the command of Pharaoh prudent."
  11,98,"He precedes his people on the Day of Resurrection, and he led<sup foot_note="366699">1</sup> them into the Fire, and what a miserable drinking place to be led to!",footnotes:347162:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  11,99,"And they were followed by a curse in this <small>(life)</small> and on the Day of Resurrection; what a miserable gift to be gifted!"
  11,100,"That is of the stories of the towns—We relate them to you; some are still standing and some have withered away."
  11,101,"And in no way did We do them any injustice, but to themselves they did injustice, so their gods whom they called upon apart from Allah availed them nothing when the command of your Lord arrived, and they did not increase them in anything but ruin."
  11,102,"And such is the seizing of your Lord when He seizes the towns while they are unjust. His seizing is indeed most painful, most severe."
  11,103,"Indeed, in that is a sign for whoever fears the punishment of the Hereafter. That is a day for which mankind will be gathered together, and that is a day to be witnessed,"
  11,104,"and we only postpone it until a predetermined term."
  11,105,"On the day when it arrives, not a single self can speak without His leave, so some will be wretched and some will be happy."
  11,106,"So as for the wretched ones, they are in the Fire—they have therein sighing and gasping,"
  11,107,"abiding therein for as long as the heavens and the earth remain, except as your Lord has willed. Indeed, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is Doer of whatever He wants."
  11,108,"And as for the ones who have been granted <span class="h">happiness<sup foot_note="366700">1</sup></span>, they are in the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small>, abiding therein for as long as the heavens and the earth remain, except as your Lord has willed—an uninterrupted grant.",footnotes:347163:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…the ones who have become happy,”</span>
  11,109,"So do not regard what these people worship with skepticism. They do not worship except as their fathers used to worship before, and most surely We will pay them their due in full, undiminished."
  11,110,"And indeed We already brought Moses the Scripture, but it was differed upon. And were it not for a word that had preceded from your Lord, judgment would have been decreed between them, and they are most surely in perplexing doubt concerning it."
  11,111,"Yet <span class="h">indeed<sup foot_note="366701">1</sup></span>, to every one of them your Lord will certainly render in full <small>(the reward)</small> for their deeds; indeed, He is All-Aware of what they do.",footnotes:347164:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir and Shu’ba read it as: “Yet to every one of them, your Lord will…”</span>
  11,112,"So be<sup>sg</sup> upright as you have been commanded, along with whoever has repented with you, and do<sup>pl</sup> not exceed all limits; indeed, He is All-Seeing of what you do."
  11,113,"And do not rely on those who have done injustices or the Fire will touch you, and you will have no guardians apart from Allah, and you will not be supported."
  11,114,"And establish<sup>sg</sup> the prayer at both extremities of the day and in the early hours of the night. Indeed, good deeds do away with evil deeds. That is a reminding for those who remember."
  11,115,"And be<sup>sg</sup> patient, for surely Allah does not waste the reward of those who excel in doing good."
  11,116,"So if only there were, among the generations before you<sup>pl</sup>, people with a remnant <small>(of wisdom)</small> forbidding corruption in the land, other than the few of them whom We saved. But the unjust ones pursued the luxuries they were indulged in, and thus became criminals."
  11,117,"And in no way would your Lord destroy towns unjustly while their inhabitants are reformers."
  11,118,"And had your<sup>sg</sup> Lord willed, He could have made mankind one community, but they continue to differ,"
  11,119,"except those upon whom your Lord has bestowed mercy—and for that reason He created them. And the Word of your Lord has been fulfilled: “I will most surely fill Hell with <small>(the race of)</small> unseen beings<sup foot_note="366702">1</sup> and human beings, both together.”",footnotes:347165:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.
  11,120,"And all what We relate to you of the stories of the messengers is to strengthen your heart therewith. And the truth has come to you in this, and an admonition and a reminder for the believers."
  11,121,"And say to those who do not believe, “Act according to your <span class="h">position<sup foot_note="366703">1</sup></span>; surely, we are also acting (according to ours).",footnotes:347166:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “Act according to your positions;”</span>
  11,122,"And wait; indeed, we too are waiting.”"
  11,123,"And to Allah belongs the hidden realm of the heavens and the earth, and to Him every matter is <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="366704">1</sup></span>. So worship<sup>sg</sup> Him and place your trust in Him, for your Lord is not oblivious of what you<sup>pl</sup> <span class="h">do<sup foot_note="366705">2</sup></span>.",footnotes:347167:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’ and Hafs read it as: “…and to Him every matter returns.”</span>|347168:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Amer, Hafs, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…of what they do.”</span>
  12,1,"Alif Lām Ra. Those are the signs<sup foot_note="366706">1</sup> of the Evident Scripture.",footnotes:347169:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  12,2,"Indeed, We have sent it down as an Arabic Recital<sup foot_note="366707">1</sup>, that you<sup>pl</sup> may reason.",footnotes:347170:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  12,3,"We relate to you<sup>sg</sup> the most beautiful of stories by revealing to you this Recital<sup foot_note="366708">1</sup>, although prior to it you were indeed one of the oblivious.",footnotes:347171:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation
  12,4,"Recall when Joseph said to his father, “O my father, I saw eleven planets and the sun and the moon; I saw them prostrating to me.”"
  12,5,"He said, “O my child, do not relate your vision to your brothers, lest they plot a plot against you; indeed, Satan is an evident enemy to man."
  12,6,"And thus your Lord will choose you and teach you of the interpretation of dreams and perfect His blessing upon you and upon Jacob's folk, as He perfected it before upon both of your forefathers Abraham and Isaac; indeed, your Lord is All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  12,7,"Very truly, there have been <span class="h">signs<sup foot_note="366709">1</sup></span> in Joseph and his brothers for the askers.",footnotes:347172:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “Very truly, there has been a sign…”</span>
  12,8,"Recall when they said, “Joseph and his brother are certainly dearer to our father than we are, although we are a <small>(whole)</small> band. Most surely, our father is in evident misguidance."
  12,9,"“Kill Joseph or throw him somewhere in the land, and your father‘s attention will be yours, then afterwards you become righteous people.”"
  12,10,"One<sup foot_note="366710">1</sup> of them said, “Do not kill Joseph, but cast him into the invisible <span class="h">cavity<sup foot_note="366711">2</sup></span> of the unlined well—some travelers may pick him up—if you must do something.”",footnotes:347173:Literally ‘a speaker of them’.|347174:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…invisible cavities…”</span>
  12,11,"They said, “O our father, why do you not trust us with Joseph, when we are most surely his advisors?"
  12,12,"Send him with us tomorrow, that <span class="h">he<sup foot_note="366712">1</sup></span> may eat well and play, and we are most surely his preservers.”",footnotes:347175:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ibn Amer read it as: “…that we may eat well…”</span>
  12,13,"He said, “It surely grieves me that you should go away with him, and I fear the wolf may eat him while you are oblivious of <small>(what happens to)</small> him.”"
  12,14,"They said, “If the wolf should eat him while we are a <small>(whole)</small> band, then most surely, we would be losers.”"
  12,15,"So when they went away with him and agreed to put him into the invisible <span class="h">cavity<sup foot_note="366713">1</sup></span> of the unlined well, and We revealed to him, “You will surely inform them of this affair of theirs while they are unaware.”",footnotes:347176:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…invisible cavit ies…”</span>
  12,16,"And they came to their father in the evening, weeping."
  12,17,"They said, “O our father, we went off racing one another and left Joseph by our belongings, so the wolf ate him. But in no way would you believe us, even if we were truthful.”"
  12,18,"And they came with false<sup foot_note="366714">1</sup> blood on his shirt. He said, “Rather, your <small>(inner)</small> selves prompted you <small>(to do)</small> something, so beautiful patience <small>(is most fitting for me)</small>, and Allah alone is besought for help against what you describe.”",footnotes:347177:Literally ‘lying’.
  12,19,"And there came some travelers, so they sent their water-carrier, then he let down his bucket. He said, “What glad <span class="h">tidings<sup foot_note="366715">1</sup></span>! Here is a boy!” And they hid him as merchandise. Yet Allah is All-Knowing of what they do.",footnotes:347178:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “What glad tidings for me!”</span>
  12,20,"And they sold him for a cheap price—a few coins, and they were of those undervaluing him."
  12,21,"Yet the man from Egypt who purchased him said to his wife, “Tend graciously to his dwelling; hopefully he may be useful to us, or we may take him as a son.” And thus We established Joseph in the land, and so that we might teach him of the interpretation of dreams. And Allah always prevails<sup foot_note="366716">1</sup> in His affairs, yet the majority of mankind does not know.",footnotes:347179:Literally ‘overcomes’.
  12,22,"And when he had attained full strength, We brought him wise judgment and knowledge, for thus do We repay those who excel in doing good."
  12,23,"Then she in whose house he was living sought to seduce him, and she shut the doors and said, “<small>(Everything is)</small> ready for you.” He said, "God is my refuge! He is my lord, who has given me a good dwelling; indeed, the unjust ones never succeed.”"
  12,24,"And surely, she advanced towards him, and he would have advanced towards her had he not seen the proof of his Lord. Thus it was, so that We would divert evil and obscenity away from him; indeed, he is one of Our sincere <span class="h">chosen<sup foot_note="366717">1</sup></span> servants.",footnotes:347180:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “…one of Our sincere servants.”</span>
  12,25,"And they raced towards the door, and she tore his shirt from behind, and at the door they ran into her master. She said, “What is the penalty for someone who wanted evil towards your family except imprisonment or a painful punishment?”"
  12,26,"He said, “It was she who sought to seduce me.” And a witness from her own family testified: “If his shirt has been torn from the front, then she has told the truth and he is of the liars."
  12,27,"But if his shirt has been torn from the back, then she has lied and he is of the truthful.”"
  12,28,"Then when he saw that his shirt had been torn from the back, he said, “This is indeed of your<sup foot_note="366718">1</sup> <small>(womanly)</small> plotting; indeed, your plotting is great!”",footnotes:347181:The Arabic wording indicates that these words are directed at a group of women.
  12,29,"“Joseph, disregard this. And you <small>(woman)</small>, ask forgiveness for your misdeed; indeed, you have been one of the wrongdoers.”"
  12,30,"And some ladies in the city said, “The mighty governor's wife seeks to seduce her young assistant; he has certainly impassioned her with love! Indeed, we do see her in evident misguidance.”"
  12,31,"So when she heard of their gossip<sup foot_note="366719">1</sup>, she sent for them and prepared for them reclining <span class="h">cushions<sup foot_note="366720">2</sup></span> and brought each one of them a knife, and she said, “Come out before them.” So when they saw him, they marveled at him and cut their hands and said, “God forbid! In no way is this a human being; this is but a noble angel!”",footnotes:347182:Literally ‘scheming’.|347183:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…and prepared for them citrus fruits and brought each…”</span>
  12,32,"She said, “Here he is—the one you blamed me for, and most surely I did seek to seduce him, but he safeguarded <small>(his chastity)</small>. Yet if he does not do what I command him, he will most surely be imprisoned, and he will most surely become one of the dishonored.”"
  12,33,"He said, “My Lord, <span class="h">prison<sup foot_note="366721">1</sup></span> is dearer to me than what they call me to, and unless You turn their plotting away from me, I might yield to them and become one of the ignorant.”",footnotes:347184:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “My Lord, imprisonment is dearer to me than what they call me to,”</span>
  12,34,"Thereupon his Lord responded to him and diverted their plotting away from him; indeed, He is the All-Hearing, the All-Knowing."
  12,35,"Then it occurred to them, after they had seen the signs, to imprison him for a while."
  12,36,"And two young men entered prison with him. One of them said, “I see myself pressing wine.” And the other said, “I see myself carrying on my head bread from which the birds are eating. Tell us their interpretation; we see that you are of those who excel in doing good.”"
  12,37,"He said, “No food will be provided for you but I will have informed you about their interpretation before it comes to you. That is some of what my Lord has taught me. Indeed, I have forsaken the creed of people who do not believe in Allah, and regarding the Hereafter they are deniers."
  12,38,"And I have followed the creed of my forefathers, Abraham and Isaac and Jacob. Never was it for us to associate anything with Allah. That is of Allah’s grace upon us and upon mankind, but the majority of mankind does not give thanks."
  12,39,"O my fellow inmates, are diverse lords better or Allah, the One, the Subduer?"
  12,40,"You do not worship apart from Him except <small>(mere)</small> names you have named, you and your forefathers, for which Allah has sent down no manifestation. Judgment belongs to none but Allah. He has commanded that you worship none but Him; that is the upright religion, but the majority of mankind does not know."
  12,41,"O my fellow inmates, as for one of you, he will give his lord wine to drink. And as for the other, he will be crucified and the birds will eat from his head. The matter you seek to be elucidated has been settled.”"
  12,42,"And he said to the one he thought would be released, “Remember me to your lord.” But Satan caused him to forget the remembrance to<sup foot_note="366722">1</sup> his lord, so he remained in prison for several years.",footnotes:347185:The Arabic text can also be translated as: “But Satan caused him to forget the remembrance of his Lord”, meaning that Yusuf forgot to say “God willing”.
  12,43,"Then the king said, “I see seven fat cows being eaten by seven lean ones, and seven green ears of corn and others dried up. O chiefs, elucidate for me my vision, if you can explicate visions.”"
  12,44,"They said, “Jumbles of dreams, and we know nothing of the interpretation of dreams.”"
  12,45,"And he of the two who had been released and had recollected after a long time said, “I will inform you<sup>pl</sup> of its interpretation, so send me out.”"
  12,46,"“Joseph, O you unwavering believer, elucidate for us: seven fat cows being eaten by seven lean ones, and seven green ears of corn and others dried up—so that I may return to the people, that they may know.”"
  12,47,"He said, “You<sup>pl</sup> shall plant for seven consecutive years; but whatever you harvest, leave it in its ear, except for a little from which you eat."
  12,48,"Then after that will come seven hard ones consuming what you have forwarded to them, except for a little of what you have stored."
  12,49,"Then after that comes a year during which people are relieved and during which <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="366723">1</sup></span> press<sup foot_note="366724">2</sup> .",footnotes:347186:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…during which you press.”</span>|347187:Press the land's produce for wine and oil.
  12,50,"So the king said, “Bring him to me.” But when the messenger came to him, he said, “Go back to your lord and ask him, 'What about the women who cut their hands?' Surely, my Lord is All-Knowing of their plotting.”"
  12,51,"He said, “What happened with you<sup foot_note="366725">1</sup> when you sought to seduce Joseph?” They said, “God forbid! We knew of no evil committed by him.” The mighty governor’s wife said, “Now the truth has come to light. It was I who sought to seduce him, and he is most surely one of the truthful.”",footnotes:347188:The Arabic wording indicates that these words are directed at a group of women.
  12,52,"“That is so he may know that I did not betray him in his absence, for surely Allah does not guide the plotting of the betrayers.<sup foot_note="366726">1</sup>",footnotes:347189:Linguistically, this whole statement can be understood as the words of Yusuf about his master or the words of the woman about Yusuf.
  12,53,"Yet I do not consider my <small>(inner)</small> self blameless. Most surely, the self commands to evil, except those upon whom my Lord has bestowed mercy; indeed, my Lord is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy.”"
  12,54,"So the king said, “Bring him to me so that I can reserve him for myself.” And when he spoke to him, he said, “Surely, today you are—with us—established, trustworthy.”"
  12,55,"He said, “Put me in charge of the storehouses of the land; I am indeed a knowledgeable constant preserver.”"
  12,56,"And thus We established Joseph in the land to live therein wherever <span class="h">he<sup foot_note="366727">1</sup></span> so willed. We reach<sup foot_note="366728">2</sup> with Our mercy whomever We will, and We never waste the reward of those who excel in doing good.",footnotes:347190:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “…wherever We so willed.”</span>|347191:Literally ‘We strike with our mercy…’
  12,57,"But the reward of the Hereafter is better for those who attained faith and used to be mindful <small>(of God)</small>."
  12,58,"And Joseph's brothers came and presented themselves before him, so he recognized them, but they did not recognize him."
  12,59,"Then when he had supplied them with their supplies, he said, “Bring me a brother of yours from your father. Do you not see that I fill up the measure, and I am the best of hosts?"
  12,60,"But if you do not bring him to me, you will have no <small>(more)</small> measure with me, and you will not come near me <small>(again)</small>.”"
  12,61,"They said, “We will solicit his father for him, and we are sure to do so.”"
  12,62,"So he said to his young <span class="h">assistants<sup foot_note="366729">1</sup></span>, “Put their goods in their saddlebags; perhaps they will recognize them when they return to their families so that they may come back.”",footnotes:347192:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…to his few young assistants,”</span>
  12,63,"So when they returned to their father, they said, “O our father, we were denied measure, so send our brother with us so that <span class="h">we<sup foot_note="366730">1</sup></span> can obtain measure, and we are most surely his preservers.”",footnotes:347193:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…so that he can obtain measure,”</span>
  12,64,"He said, “Am I to entrust him to you as I entrusted his brother to you before? Allah is a Better <span class="h">Preserver<sup foot_note="366731">1</sup></span>, and He is the Most Merciful of the merciful ones.”",footnotes:347194:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Allah is Better in preservation,”</span>
  12,65,"And when they opened their baggage they found that their goods had been returned to them. They said, “O father, what more could we want? Here are our goods, returned to us; we will provide for our family and preserve our brother and have an additional camel-load; that is an easy measure <small>(to obtain)</small>.”"
  12,66,"He said, “I will not send him with you unless you give me a binding pledge before Allah that you will most surely bring him back to me, unless you get trapped.” So when they gave him their binding pledge, he said, “Allah is the Ultimate Trustee over what we say.”"
  12,67,"And he said, “O my children, do not enter through one gate, but enter through different gates, though I cannot avail you anything against Allah; judgment belongs to none but Allah; in Him I have placed my trust, and in Him let those who seek to trust place their trust.”"
  12,68,"And when they entered as their father had commanded them, it did not avail them anything against Allah; it was just a need in Jacob's <small>(inner)</small> self, which he fulfilled. And he is most surely a person of knowledge inasmuch as We have taught him, but the majority of mankind does not know."
  12,69,"And when they presented themselves before Joseph, he drew his brother close to him. He said, “Indeed it is I—I am your brother, so do not be saddened by what they used to do.”"
  12,70,"Then, when he had supplied them with their supplies, he placed the drinking-cup in his brother’s saddlebag. Then an announcer called out, “O caravan<sup foot_note="366732">1</sup>, most surely you are thieves.”",footnotes:347195:A metaphor for the people of the caravan.
  12,71,"They said as they came towards them, “What are you missing?”"
  12,72,"They said, “We are missing the king’s goblet. And whoever comes up with it will have a camel-load, and I<sup foot_note="366733">1</sup> guarantee it.”",footnotes:347196:A grammatical shift from plural to singular.
  12,73,"They said, “<small>(We swear)</small> by Allah, you<sup>pl</sup> have most surely known that we did not come to spread corruption in the land, and never have we been thieves.”"
  12,74,"They said, “What shall be his repayment, if you<sup>pl</sup> are lying?”"
  12,75,"They said, “The repayment should be that he in whose saddlebag it is found, he himself is the repayment<sup foot_note="366734">1</sup> . Thus we repay the unjust ones.”",footnotes:347197:That he becomes enslaved.
  12,76,"So he began with their bags before his brother's bag, then he extracted it from his brother’s bag. Thus We plotted for Joseph; he could not have seized his brother according to the king’s religion<sup foot_note="366735">1</sup> unless Allah wills. We elevate by <span class="h">degrees<sup foot_note="366736">2</sup></span> whomever We so will. For above everyone who has knowledge, there is One who is All-Knowing.",footnotes:347198:The Arabic word used is <i>deen</i> which means ‘a way of life’, ‘religion’ or ‘recompense’.|347199:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “We elevate the degrees (ranks) of whomever…” Ya’qub read it as: “He elevates the degrees (ranks) of whomever…”</span>
  12,77,"They said, “If he steals, well, actually a brother of his has stolen before.” But Joseph kept it secret within himself and did not reveal it to them. He said <small>(to himself)</small>, “You<sup>pl</sup> are in a worse situation, and Allah knows better of what you describe.”"
  12,78,"They said, “O mighty governor, he has a father <small>(who is)</small> a very old man, so take one of us in his place; we see that you are of those who excel in doing good.”"
  12,79,"He said, “God is my refuge! Were we to take anyone except him in whose possession we found our property, we would then most surely be unjust.”"
  12,80,"So when they completely despaired of him, they conferred privately. Their eldest said, “Do you<sup>pl</sup> not know that your father took a binding pledge from you before Allah, and in the past you failed with regard to Joseph? Therefore, I will not leave this land until my father permits me or Allah judges for me, for He is the Best of judges."
  12,81,"Go back to your<sup>pl</sup> father and say, ‘Our father, your son has indeed stolen. And we did not testify <small>(about the punishment of stealing)</small> except according to what we have learned, and we could not have preserved <small>(him) </small>against what is hidden.’"
  12,82,"And ask the town where we were and the caravan in which we came, for indeed, we are truthful.”"
  12,83,"He said, “Rather, your <small>(inner)</small> selves prompted you <small>(to do)</small> something, so beautiful patience <small>(is most fitting for me)</small>; hopefully Allah will bring them all back to me. Indeed, He is the All-Knowing, All-Wise.”"
  12,84,"And he turned away from them and said, “Alas for Joseph!” And his eyes turned white from grief and he suppressed his anguish."
  12,85,"They said, “<small>(We swear)</small> by Allah, you will continue remembering Joseph until you become totally drained or become of those annihilated.”"
  12,86,"He said, “Indeed, I only complain of my anguish and grief to Allah, and I know from Allah what you do not know.”"
  12,87,"“O my children, go and ask around about Joseph and his brother and do not despair of Allah's leniency, for certainly none despair of Allah's leniency except the denying people.”"
  12,88,"Then when they presented themselves before him, they said, “O mighty governor, harm has touched us and our family and we have brought scant merchandise, but give us full measure and be charitable towards us; indeed, Allah rewards the charitable ones.”"
  12,89,"He said, “Do you know what you did with Joseph and his brother when you were ignorant?”"
  12,90,"They said, “Can it be that you really are <span class="h">Joseph?<sup foot_note="366737">1</sup></span>” He said, “I am Joseph, and this is my brother. Allah has certainly been gracious to us; indeed, whoever is mindful <small>(of God)</small> and endures patiently—indeed, Allah never wastes the reward of those who excel in doing good.”",footnotes:347200:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Ja’far read it as: “They said, ‘You really are Joseph!’ ”</span>
  12,91,"They said, “<small>(We swear)</small> by Allah, Allah has certainly preferred you over us, and we were definitely wrongdoers.”"
  12,92,"He said, “There is no blame on you<sup>pl</sup> today; may Allah forgive you, for He is the Most Merciful of the merciful ones."
  12,93,"Take this shirt of mine and cast it over my father’s face <small>(and)</small> he will recover his sight. And bring your whole family to me.”"
  12,94,"And as soon as the caravan departed, their father said, “I sense the scent of Joseph, though you may deem me senile.”"
  12,95,"They said, “<small>(We swear)</small> by Allah, you<sup>sg</sup> are surely in your old misguidance.”"
  12,96,"So when the herald of glad tidings arrived, he cast it over his face and he regained his sight. He said, “Did I not say to you<sup>pl</sup>, ‘Indeed, I know from Allah what you know not.’”?"
  12,97,"They said, “O father, pray for the forgiveness of our misdeeds; we were indeed wrongdoers.”"
  12,98,"He said, “I will ask my Lord to forgive you; indeed, He is the Oft-Forgiving, the Bestower of mercy.”"
  12,99,"So when they presented themselves before Joseph, he drew his parents close to him and said, “Enter Egypt all of you, Allah willing, feeling secure.”"
  12,100,"And he raised his parents on the throne, and they <small>(all)</small> fell prostrate before him, and he said, “O father, this is the interpretation of my vision of long ago. My Lord has certainly made it come true, and He was certainly charitable to me when He brought me out of prison and brought you<sup>pl</sup> from the nomadic life after Satan had sown discord between me and my brothers. Indeed, my Lord is Subtle in fulfilling whatever He wills; indeed, He is the All-Knowing, the All-Wise.”"
  12,101,"“My Lord, You have surely brought me of kingship<sup foot_note="366738">1</sup> and have taught me of the interpretation of dreams. Initiator of the heavens and the earth—You are my Ultimate Guardian in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> and the Hereafter; take me back at death as a Muslim and join me with the righteous.”",footnotes:347201:The Arabic word used is <i>mulk</i> which means ‘kingship’, ‘authority’ or ‘dominion’.
  12,102,"That is of the stories of the hidden realm which We reveal to you, for you were not with them when they agreed together upon their affair as they were scheming."
  12,103,"And most mankind will not believe, no matter how keen you<sup>sg</sup> are,"
  12,104,"though you ask them no reward for it. It is only a reminder for all realms."
  12,105,"And how many a sign in the heavens and the earth do they pass by while they disregard them?"
  12,106,"And most of them do not believe in Allah unless they associate <small>(others with Allah)</small>."
  12,107,"Do they feel secure that an overwhelming event of Allah’s punishment will not come upon them, or that the Hour will not come upon them suddenly while they are unaware?"
  12,108,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “This is my way; I call to Allah with insight—I and whoever has followed me. And Highly Exalted be Allah, and I am not of those who associate <small>(others with Allah)</small>.”"
  12,109,"And in no way did We send <small>(any messengers)</small> before you<sup>sg</sup> except men to whom We <span class="h">reveal<sup foot_note="366739">1</sup></span>, from among the people of the towns. Have they not journeyed through the earth and looked at what the outcome was for those before them? The Home of the Hereafter is surely better for those who have been mindful <small>(of God)</small>. Do you<sup>pl</sup> not <span class="h">reason<sup foot_note="366740">2</sup></span>?",footnotes:347202:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as: “…except men to whom it is revealed, from among…”</span>|347203:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Do they not reason?”</span>
  12,110,"Until, when the messengers had completely despaired and thought that they had been lied <span class="h">to<sup foot_note="366741">1</sup></span><small>(by their own selves)</small>, Our support came to them. Then whomever We willed was <span class="h">delivered<sup foot_note="366742">2</sup></span>, and Our chastisement is never turned back from the criminal people.",footnotes:347204:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “…and thought that they had been deemed liars,”</span>|347205:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Amer, Asem and Ya’qub read it as: “Then We save whomever We will,”</span>
  12,111,"Most surely, in their narrative there has been a lesson for people of understanding. This was not a fabricated tale, but a confirmation of what came before it and a detailed explanation of everything and guidance and mercy for people who believe."
  13,1,"Alif Lām Mīm Ra. Those are the signs of the Scripture. And what has been sent down to you<sup>sg</sup> from your Lord is the truth, but most of mankind do not believe."
  13,2,"Allah is the One Who raised up the heavens without pillars that you see, then He settled over the Throne, and He has subjected the sun and the moon, each running for a stated term. He governs matters; He details signs, that you<sup>pl</sup> may be certain of the meeting with your Lord."
  13,3,"And He is the One Who spread the land and made in it firm mountains and rivers, and of all products he made therein two pairs; He causes the night to <span class="h">overwhelm<sup foot_note="366743">1</sup></span> the day; indeed, in that are signs for people who reflect.",footnotes:347206:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “…the night to tightly overwhelm the day,”</span>
  13,4,"And in the land are neighboring plots and gardens of vines, and vegetation, and <span class="h">date-palms<sup foot_note="366744">1</sup></span>—from the same root or from distinct roots—irrigated with the same water, yet We <span class="h">make<sup foot_note="366745">2</sup></span> the produce of some taste better than others; most surely, in that are signs for people who reason.",footnotes:347207:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Hafs and Ya’qub read it as: “…neighboring plots and gardens of vines and (of) vegetation and (of) date-palms…”</span>|347208:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…yet He makes the produce…”</span>
  13,5,"And if you<sup>sg</sup> are amazed, then more amazing is their saying: “Can it be that when we have become dust—can it be <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="366746">1</sup></span> we will really be <small>(resurrected)</small> in a new creation?” Those are the ones who have denied their Lord, and those are the ones with yokes around their necks, for those are the fellows of the Fire; therein they abide.",footnotes:347209:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “Can it be that when we have become dust we will really be…” Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “When we have become dust—can it be that we will really be…”</span>
  13,6,"And they urge you<sup>sg</sup> to hasten evil before good, though exemplary punishments have occurred before them. And most surely your Lord is the Possessor of forgiveness to mankind despite their injustice, but most surely your Lord is stern in retribution."
  13,7,"And those who have denied say, “If only a sign<sup foot_note="366747">1</sup> would be sent down to him from his Lord?” Indeed, you are only a forewarner, as for every people there is a guide.",footnotes:347210:A physical miracle.
  13,8,"Allah knows what every female carries and what the wombs lose <small>(prematurely)</small> or exceed, and everything with Him is in due measure—"
  13,9,"the Knower of the hidden realm and the manifest; the Supreme, the Highly Exalted."
  13,10,"It is the same: whether one of you speaks secretly or aloud, whether he goes into hiding by night or goes out by day."
  13,11,"For each one there is a succession <small>(of angels)</small> before him and behind him, preserving him from Allah’s command. Indeed, Allah does not change the condition of a people until they change what is within themselves. And if Allah wants an evil for a people, there is no turning it back, and apart from Him they have no guardian."
  13,12,"It is He who shows you<sup>pl</sup> the lightening, <small>(causing)</small> fear and ardent hope, and He produces the heavy clouds."
  13,13,"And the thunder exalts Him with praise, and so do the angels out of fear of Him. And He sends the thunderbolts, striking with them whomever He wills. Yet they argue about Allah, while He is stern in His plan."
  13,14,"To Him belongs the call of truth, while those they call upon apart from Him do not respond to them with anything, except as someone who stretches his hands towards water so that it may reach his mouth, but never will it reach it. Thus the call of the deniers can only go astray."
  13,15,"And to Allah prostrates whoever is in the heavens and the earth, willingly or reluctantly, as do their shadows in the mornings and before sunset."
  13,16,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Who is the Lord of the heavens and the earth?” Say, “Allah.” Say, “Have you taken apart from Him protectors who have no power to benefit or harm <small>(even)</small> themselves?” Say, “Are the blind and the seeing equal? Or are darkness and light equal? Or have they set up to Allah associates who created the like of His creation, so that their creation is indistinguishable to them from His? Say, “Allah is the Creator of everything, and He is the One, the Subduer.”"
  13,17,"He sent down water from the sky, so valleys flowed—each according to its capacity—and the current carried swelling froth. And from what <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="366748">1</sup></span> burn in fire, seeking to make ornaments or utensils, comes a similar froth. Thus Allah exemplifies truth and falsehood: so as for the froth—it fades away, and as for what benefits mankind—it remains in the earth; thus Allah sets forth parables.",footnotes:347211:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…what you burn in fire,”</span>
  13,18,"For those who have responded to their Lord is the best <small>(reward)</small>, but those who have not responded to Him—if they possessed whatever is in the earth, all together and twice as much, they would indeed offer to ransom themselves with it. For those is an evil reckoning, for their shelter is Hell, and what a miserable resting place!"
  13,19,"Is someone who knows that what was sent down to you from your Lord is the truth like someone who is blind? Indeed, only those endowed with understanding remind themselves—"
  13,20,"those who fulfill Allah's covenant and do not violate the pledge;"
  13,21,"and those who join what Allah has commanded to be joined and are in awe of their Lord and fear evil reckoning;"
  13,22,"and those who endured patiently, seeking their Lord's countenance, and established the prayers and spent of what We provided them, secretly and publicly, and who repel<sup foot_note="366749">1</sup> an evil deed with a good deed; for those is the Ultimate Dwelling:",footnotes:347212:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense.
  13,23,"everlasting Gardens which they enter, along with whoever was righteous of their forefathers and their spouses and their offspring<small>(s)</small>, while the angels enter upon them from every gate."
  13,24,"“Peace be upon you<sup>pl</sup> for all you have endured patiently, so how excellent is the Ultimate Dwelling!”"
  13,25,"And those who violate the covenant of Allah after pledging it, and sever what Allah has commanded to be joined and spread corruption in the land—those, for them there is the curse, and for them there is the Very Evil Home."
  13,26,"Allah extends provision for whomever He wills and He restrains <small>(it)</small>. And they rejoiced with the Earlier Life, yet the Earlier Life, compared to the Hereafter, is nothing but <small>(a brief)</small> enjoyment."
  13,27,"And those who have denied say, “If only a sign<sup foot_note="366750">1</sup> would be sent down to him from his Lord?” Say, “Indeed, Allah leads astray whomever He wills, and He guides to Himself whoever has turned penitent:",footnotes:347213:A physical miracle.
  13,28,"those who have attained faith and whose hearts become<sup foot_note="366751">1</sup> serene with the remembrance<sup foot_note="366752">2</sup> of Allah. Undoubtedly, it is indeed in the remembrance of Allah that hearts find comfort.”",footnotes:347214:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense.|347215:The Arabic word zh<i>ikr</i> can be translated as ‘remembrance’, ‘reminder’ or ‘mentioning’.
  13,29,"Those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—for them is blessedness and a beautiful place to return to."
  13,30,"Thus We have sent you<sup>sg</sup> among a community before which other communities have passed away, that you may read to them what We have revealed to you, while they deny the All-Merciful<sup foot_note="366753">1</sup> . Say, “He is my Lord; there is no god but He; in Him I have placed my trust and to Him is my repentance.”",footnotes:347216:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  13,31,"And even if there had been a Recital<sup foot_note="366754">1</sup> by which mountains were made to move or by which the land was cut up or by which the dead were spoken to…<sup foot_note="366755">2</sup> . Rather, to Allah belongs all command. Have those who have attained faith not yet given up and realized that if Allah wills, He can guide all mankind? And shocking events continue to afflict those who have denied—on account of what they have done—or fall near their home, until Allah’s promise comes true; indeed, Allah never breaks a promise.",footnotes:347217:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.|347218:This sentence is left open-ended; according to some exegetes its predicate is “they would still disbelieve.”
  13,32,"And very truly messengers before you were ridiculed, so I reprieved the deniers then I seized them, so how was My punishment?"
  13,33,"Is the One Who is watchful over what every single self has earned…<sup foot_note="366756">1</sup> ? Yet they set up associates to Allah. Say, “Name<sup>pl</sup> them! Or are you to inform Him as to what He knows not in the earth? Or is it a show of words?” Rather, the scheming of those who have denied has been adorned for them, and they were <span class="h">barred<sup foot_note="366757">2</sup></span> from the way. And whomever Allah leads astray, no guide shall there ever be for him.",footnotes:347219:This sentence is left open-ended; according to some exegetes its predicate is “as any other?”|347220:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…and they barred (others) from…”</span>
  13,34,"For them is a punishment in the Earlier Life, but the punishment of the Hereafter is harsher, for they have no shield from Allah."
  13,35,"The likeness of the Garden promised to those mindful <small>(of God)</small>: rivers flow beneath it; its crops are perpetual, and so is its shade. Such is the ultimate outcome for those who were mindful, while the ultimate outcome for the deniers is the Fire."
  13,36,"And those whom We have brought the Scripture rejoice at what was sent down to you, while of the parties are those who reject parts of it. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Indeed, I have only been commanded to worship Allah and to never associate <small>(anything)</small> with Him; to Him I call and to Him is my return.”"
  13,37,"And thus We have sent it down as an Arabic code of law. Thus, were you<sup>sg</sup> to follow their whims after the knowledge that has come to you, you would have against Allah<sup foot_note="366758">1</sup> neither guardian nor shield.",footnotes:347221:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  13,38,"And most surely, We have sent messengers before you and We assigned for them spouses and offspring, and never was it for a messenger to come with a sign except by Allah's<sup foot_note="366759">1</sup> leave. For every term there is a decreed term.",footnotes:347222:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  13,39,"Allah erases whatever He decides and He <span class="h">keeps<sup foot_note="366760">1</sup></span><small>(whatever He decides)</small>, and with Him is the source<sup foot_note="366761">2</sup> of the Scripture.",footnotes:347223:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Asem and Ya’qub read it as: “…and He firmly keeps…”</span>|347224:Literally ‘mother’.
  13,40,"Whether We show you some of what We have promised them or take you at death, your duty is indeed mere proclamation, while Ours is the reckoning."
  13,41,"Do they not see how We approach the land, diminishing it from its edges? Thus Allah<sup foot_note="366762">1</sup> judges; nothing can hold back His judgment, and He is Swift in reckoning.",footnotes:347225:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  13,42,"And the ones who came before them had schemed <small>(as well)</small>, yet to Allah belongs all scheming; He knows what every single self earns. And the <span class="h">deniers<sup foot_note="366763">1</sup></span> will know to whom belongs the Ultimate Dwelling.",footnotes:347226:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Abu Ja’far read it as: “And the denier will know…”</span>
  13,43,"And those who have denied say, “You<sup>sg</sup> are not an emissary.” Say, “Sufficient is Allah as a witness between me and you, and so is whoever has the knowledge of the Scripture.”"
  14,1,"Alif Lām Ra. A Scripture that We sent down to you<sup>sg</sup><small>,</small> that you may bring mankind out from darkness<small>(es)</small> into light—by the leave of their Lord—to the path of the Almighty, the Praiseworthy:"
  14,2,"<span class="h">Allah<sup foot_note="366764">1</sup></span>—the One to Whom belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth. And woe to the deniers from a severe punishment!",footnotes:347227:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “(He is) Allah—the One to whom…” Roways read it as such only when he connected signs 1 and 2.</span>
  14,3,"Those who seek the love of the Earlier Life more than the Hereafter, and bar <small>(people)</small> from the way of Allah and seek to make it crooked—those are in extreme misguidance."
  14,4,"And never did We send any messenger but <small>(he spoke)</small> in the tongue of his people, that he may clarify for them. Then Allah leads astray whom He wills and guides whom He wills, for He is the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  14,5,"And very truly We sent Moses with Our signs: “Bring your<sup>sg</sup> people out of darkness<small>(es)</small> into light and remind them of the Days of Allah<sup foot_note="366765">1</sup> .” Indeed, in that are signs for everyone who is most patient, constantly thankful.”",footnotes:347228:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 2 person to 2<sup>nd</sup> person. person.
  14,6,"And recall when Moses said to his people, “Remember Allah’s blessing upon you when He saved you from Pharaoh's folk: inflicting on you an evil punishment and slaying your sons and keeping your women alive <small>(in bondage)</small>. And in that was a great test from your Lord."
  14,7,"And recall when your<sup>pl</sup> Lord proclaimed, 'If you give thanks, I will indeed increase you; but if you deny, then indeed My punishment is severe.'”"
  14,8,"Thus Moses said, “If you<sup>pl</sup> deny, together with everyone on earth—then Allah is most surely Self-Sufficient, Praiseworthy.”"
  14,9,"Has not the tiding of those before you<sup>pl</sup> come to you—the people of Noah and Ād and Thamûd and those <small>(who came)</small> after them? None know them except Allah. Their messengers came to them with evident proofs, yet they turned back their hands to their mouths<sup foot_note="366766">1</sup> and said, “We surely deny what you have been sent with, and we are indeed in doubt about whatever suspicious <small>(matter)</small> you are calling us to.”",footnotes:347229:To silence them.
  14,10,"Their messengers said, “Is there any doubt about Allah, the Originator of the heavens and the earth? He calls you<sup>pl</sup> to forgive you your misdeeds and to defer you until <small>(you fulfill)</small> a stated term.” They said, “You are only human beings like us; you want to turn us away from what our forefathers used to worship, so bring us an evident manifestation.”"
  14,11,"Their messengers said to them, “We are only human beings like you, but Allah does a favor to whomever He wills of His servants, and in no way could we come up to you with any manifestation except by Allah's leave. And in Allah let the believers place their trust."
  14,12,"And how can we not place our trust in Allah when He has guided us in our ways? And we will most surely endure patiently whichever way you hurt us. And let anyone who trusts, place his trust in Allah.”"
  14,13,"Yet those who denied said to their messengers, “We will most surely evict you from our land unless you return to our creed.” So their Lord revealed to them: “We will most surely annihilate the unjust ones,"
  14,14,"and We will most surely settle you in the land after them. That is for whoever stood in fear of My position and in fear of My threat.""
  14,15,"Thus they sought a legislation<sup foot_note="366767">1</sup>, then every stubborn tyrant failed;",footnotes:347230:The Arabic word used is a derivative of the word <i>fateh</i>, which literally means ‘open’; according to Az-Zamakhshari and other exegetes it means 'open a way for us to distinguish between good and evil’.
  14,16,"beyond him lies Hell, and he is given, for drink, purulent water"
  14,17,"which he sips, though he can barely swallow. And death comes at him from everywhere but he is not to die, and beyond him is a harsh punishment."
  14,18,"The parable of those who denied their Lord: their deeds are like ashes on which the <span class="h">wind<sup foot_note="366768">1</sup></span> blew severely upon a stormy day; they have no control over anything they have earned. That is the extreme misguidance.",footnotes:347231:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “winds”</span>
  14,19,"Have you not seen that Allah <span class="h">created<sup foot_note="366769">1</sup></span> the heavens and the earth with the truth<sup foot_note="366770">2</sup> ? If He wills, He can do away with you<sup>pl</sup> and bring a new creation.",footnotes:347232:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…that Allah is the Creator of the heavens…”</span>|347233:According to Ibn Ashour and other exegetes, ‘with the truth’ means ‘for a purpose’.
  14,20,"And that is not too mighty for Allah."
  14,21,"And they emerged<sup foot_note="366771">1</sup> before Allah all together. And the weak said to the arrogant leaders, “We were your followers, so can you avail us in any way against Allah’s punishment?” They said, “Had Allah guided us, we would have guided you. It is the same for us: whether we mourn or are patient, there is no escape for us.”",footnotes:347234:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  14,22,"Thus Satan said, when the matter had been concluded, “Indeed, Allah promised you<sup>pl</sup> the promise of truth, and I promised you but I failed you. And never did I have any authority over you except that I called you and you responded to me. So do not blame me, but blame yourselves; I cannot come to your aid nor can you come to my aid; <small>(now)</small> I have indeed denied your earlier association of me <small>(with Allah)</small>. Indeed, for the unjust is a painful punishment.”"
  14,23,"But those who had attained faith and had done righteous deeds were entered into Gardens beneath which rivers flow, abiding therein by their Lord's leave; their greeting therein is: “Peace.”"
  14,24,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen how Allah has set forth a parable? A good word is like a good tree—its root is firm and its branches are in heaven,"
  14,25,"yielding its crop every season by its Lord's leave. And Allah sets forth parables for mankind, that they may remind themselves."
  14,26,"And the parable of a nasty word is that of a nasty tree that has been uprooted: it has no stability."
  14,27,"Allah gives firmness to those who have attained faith with the firm statement in the Earlier Life and in the Hereafter, and Allah leads the unjust<sup>pl</sup> astray. And Allah does whatever He wills."
  14,28,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen those who exchanged the blessing of Allah for denial and landed their people into the home of perdition?"
  14,29,"Hell, wherein they roast, and what a miserable settlement!"
  14,30,"And they set up rivals to Allah in order to make <small>(others)</small> <span class="h">stray<sup foot_note="366772">1</sup></span> from His way. Say, “Enjoy yourselves, for surely your destiny is to the Fire.”",footnotes:347235:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Roways read it as: “…in order to stray from His way…”</span>
  14,31,"Tell My servants who have attained faith to establish the prayers and to spend from what We have provided them, secretly and publicly, before a day comes in which there is neither trade nor close friendship."
  14,32,"Allah is the One Who created the heavens and the earth and sent down water from the sky, then brought out with it, of the products, provision for you<sup>pl</sup>; and He has subjected to you the ships to run in the sea by His command, and He has subjected to you the rivers."
  14,33,"And He has subjected to you the sun and the moon, both moving constantly, and He has subjected to you the night and the day."
  14,34,"And He has brought you<sup>pl</sup> of all what you asked Him, and if you were to count Allah’s blessings, you would not be able to enumerate them. Surely, man is constantly unjust, a relentless denier."
  14,35,"And recall when Abraham said, “O my Lord, make this land safe and keep me and my sons away from worshiping human-shaped idols.”"
  14,36,"“My Lord, they have indeed led many people astray. So whoever follows me, then surely he is of me; and whoever disobeys me, then You are Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  14,37,"Our Lord, I have indeed settled of my offspring in a valley devoid of vegetation at Your House which has been made Inviolable, Our Lord, that they may establish the prayers. So make some people's burning hearts incline towards them, and provide them with products, that they may give thanks.”"
  14,38,"“Our Lord, You surely know whatever we hide and whatever we make public. For nothing is hidden from Allah, whether in the earth or in the heaven.”"
  14,39,"“Praise be to Allah Who has given me, in my old age, Ishmael and Isaac; my Lord is indeed All-Hearing of supplication.”"
  14,40,"“My Lord, make me one who establishes the prayer, and <small>(also)</small> of my offspring. Our Lord, and accept my<sup foot_note="366773">1</sup> supplication.”",footnotes:347236:A grammatical shift from plural to singular.
  14,41,"“Our Lord, forgive me and my parents and the believers on the day when the reckoning takes place.”"
  14,42,"Do<sup>sg</sup> not ever think that Allah is oblivious of what the unjust<sup>pl</sup> are doing. He only defers them to a day when sight<small>(s) </small>glaze over,"
  14,43,"as they rush forward with their necks outstretched, their heads upraised, their eyes unblinking and their hearts void."
  14,44,"And warn<sup>sg</sup> mankind of the day when punishment comes upon them, and the unjust<sup>pl</sup> say, “Our Lord, defer us for a little while and we will respond to Your call and follow the messengers.” Did you<sup>pl</sup> not swear earlier that in no way would you face extinction?"
  14,45,"And you settled in the residences of those who were unjust to themselves and it became clear to you how We dealt with them, and We set forth for you the parables."
  14,46,"And very truly they had schemed their scheming, yet their scheming is known to Allah, even though their scheming was enough to remove mountains."
  14,47,"So never think<sup>sg</sup> that Allah will break His promise to His messengers. Indeed, Allah is Almighty, Capable of vengeance"
  14,48,"on the day when the earth is changed into another earth, as well as the heavens, and they emerged<sup foot_note="366774">1</sup> before Allah, the One, the Subduer.",footnotes:347237:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  14,49,"And you<sup>sg</sup> see the criminals on that day bound together in fetters,"
  14,50,"their attires made of tar, and the Fire covering their faces."
  14,51,"That Allah may repay every single self according to what it has earned. Indeed, Allah is Swift in reckoning."
  14,52,"This<small> </small>is a proclamation for mankind, and that they may be warned by it, and that they may know that He is one God, and that people of understanding may constantly remember."
  15,1,"Alif Lām Ra. Those are the signs<sup foot_note="366775">1</sup> of the Scripture and an evident Recital<sup foot_note="366776">2</sup> .",footnotes:347238:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.|347239:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  15,2,"Perhaps those who have denied will wish they had been Muslims."
  15,3,"Let<sup>sg</sup> them eat and enjoy and be distracted by <small>(false)</small> hope, for they will come to know."
  15,4,"For in no way did We annihilate any town except that it had a known written decree."
  15,5,"No community can advance its time, nor can they delay it."
  15,6,"And they said, “O you upon whom the Reminder has been bestowed from on high, very truly you are insane."
  15,7,"If only you would bring us the angels, if you are one of the truthful!”"
  15,8,"We <span class="h">bestow<sup foot_note="366777">1</sup></span> not the angels from on high except with the truth<sup foot_note="366778">2</sup>, and in no way would they<sup foot_note="366779">3</sup> then be respited.",footnotes:347240:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “The angels are not bestowed from on high except with the truth,”</span>|347241:According to Ibn Ashour and other exegetes, ‘with the truth’ means ‘for a purpose’.|347242:The deniers.
  15,9,"Indeed, We—We alone—have bestowed the Reminder from on high, and We will most surely preserve it."
  15,10,"And most surely We sent <small>(messengers)</small> before you<sup>sg</sup> to the sects of the ancients,"
  15,11,"but no messenger comes<sup foot_note="366780">1</sup> to them but they used to ridicule him.",footnotes:347243:Frequently the Qur’an speaks about the prophets using present tense; this should be pondered by the reader.
  15,12,"Thus We insert it<sup foot_note="366781">1</sup> into the hearts of the criminals—",footnotes:347244:The Reminder.
  15,13,"they do not believe in it, though the rule of <small>(God regarding)</small> the ancients has surely passed before."
  15,14,"And if We were to open for them a gateway into the sky so that they were to continue ascending through it,"
  15,15,"they would surely say, “Indeed, our sight<small>(s)</small> have been <span class="h">stupefied<sup foot_note="366782">1</sup></span>; rather, we are a people bewitched.”",footnotes:347245:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “…have been blocked;”</span>
  15,16,"And most surely, We have made constellations in the sky and adorned it to the beholders;"
  15,17,"and We have preserved it from every outcast devil,"
  15,18,"except the one who eavesdrops and is followed by an evident meteor."
  15,19,"And the land—We spread it and cast firm mountains in it, and We germinated therein of everything in proper measure."
  15,20,"And We made livelihoods for you<sup>pl</sup> in it, as well as for those for whom you are not the providers."
  15,21,"For there is not a thing but with Us are its treasuries, yet in no way do We bestow it from on high except in a known measure."
  15,22,"And We sent the <span class="h">winds<sup foot_note="366783">1</sup></span>, fertilizing, then sent down water from the sky and gave it to you<sup>pl</sup> to drink, and in no way are you its keepers.",footnotes:347246:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Khalaf read it as: “wind”</span>
  15,23,"And indeed, We—surely, We—give life and cause death, and We are the Inheritors."
  15,24,"And most surely We have known those of you who passed away, and most surely We have known those who come afterwards;"
  15,25,"and indeed, it is your<sup>sg</sup> Lord Who herds them<sup foot_note="366784">1</sup> together; indeed, He is All-Wise, All-Knowing.",footnotes:347247:A grammatical shift from 2<sup>nd</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  15,26,"And most surely We created man from potter’s clay, of fermented mud,"
  15,27,"while We created the unseen being<sup foot_note="366785">1</sup> before from the fire of the searing wind.",footnotes:347248:The Arabic word used is <i>jānn</i> (the singular of <i>jinn</i>) which is an unseen being that is accountable for its actions.
  15,28,"And recall when your<sup>sg</sup> Lord said to the angels, “I am creating a human being from potter’s clay, of fermented mud."
  15,29,"So when I have formed him and breathed into him of My spirit, fall down to him, prostrating.”"
  15,30,"So the angels prostrated themselves, all of them together—"
  15,31,"but not Iblis<sup foot_note="366786">1</sup> . He refused to be with those who prostrated themselves.",footnotes:347249:Iblis is another name of Satan or <i>Shaytan</i>.
  15,32,"He said, “O Iblis<sup foot_note="366787">1</sup>, what keeps you from being with those who prostrate themselves?”",footnotes:347250:Iblis is another name of Satan or <i>Shaytan</i>.
  15,33,"He said, “Never would I prostrate myself to a human being whom You created from potter’s clay, of fermented mud.”"
  15,34,"He said, “Then get out of it<sup foot_note="366788">1</sup>, for indeed you are an outcast,",footnotes:347251:The Garden.
  15,35,"and indeed the curse is upon you until the Day of Recompense.”"
  15,36,"He said, “My Lord, then reprieve me until the day they are resurrected.”"
  15,37,"He said, “Then, you are indeed of the ones reprieved"
  15,38,"until the Day of the Time Appointed.”"
  15,39,"He said, “My Lord, since You have deluded me, I will most surely adorn for them <small>(evil deeds)</small> on earth, and I will most surely delude them all,"
  15,40,"except for Your sincere <span class="h">chosen<sup foot_note="366789">1</sup></span> servants among them.”",footnotes:347252:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “…except for Your sincere servants…”</span>
  15,41,"He said, “This is a straight path which is binding on <span class="h">Me<sup foot_note="366790">1</sup></span>:",footnotes:347253:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “This is a high, straight path.”</span>
  15,42,"over My servants you<sup>sg</sup> have no authority indeed, except for those who follow you of the deluded ones."
  15,43,"And indeed, Hell is the meeting place for them all."
  15,44,"It has seven gates; for each gate is an assigned class.”"
  15,45,"Indeed, the mindful <small>(of God)</small> are amid Gardens and springs."
  15,46,"“Enter it in peace, feeling safe.”"
  15,47,"And We removed<sup foot_note="366791">1</sup> whatever malice was within their chests—as brethren, on couches facing each other.",footnotes:347254:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  15,48,"No fatigue touches<sup foot_note="366792">1</sup> them therein, nor from it will they ever be brought out.",footnotes:347255:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense.
  15,49,"Inform<sup>sg</sup> My servants that I—only I—am the Oft-Forgiving, the Bestower of mercy,"
  15,50,"and that My punishment is the painful punishment."
  15,51,"And inform them of the guests of Abraham,"
  15,52,"when they entered upon him and said, “Peace.” He said, “We are truly scared of you.”"
  15,53,"They said, “Do not be scared; we bring you<sup>sg</sup> glad tidings of a knowledgeable boy.”"
  15,54,"He said, “Have you brought me glad tidings when old age has touched me? So what glad tidings could you <span class="h">give<sup foot_note="366793">1</sup></span>?”",footnotes:347256:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Ibn Kathir read it as: “…could you give me?”</span>
  15,55,"They said, “We brought you true glad tidings, so be not of the despairing ones.”"
  15,56,"He said, “And who despairs of his Lord’s mercy except for those<sup foot_note="366794">1</sup> astray?”",footnotes:347257:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  15,57,"He said, “So what is your business, O emissaries?”"
  15,58,"They said, “We have been sent to a people of criminals,"
  15,59,"except for Lot's folk; we will most surely <span class="h">deliver<sup foot_note="366795">1</sup></span> them all,",footnotes:347258:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “…we will most surely save them all,”</span>
  15,60,"except for his wife.” We have determined that she will most surely be of those who linger behind."
  15,61,"So when the emissaries came to Lot's folk,"
  15,62,"he said, “You are an unknown people.”"
  15,63,"They said, “Rather, we have come to you<sup>sg</sup> with that about which they were skeptical,"
  15,64,"and we have brought you the truth, and very truly we are truthful."
  15,65,"So journey with your family at the latter part of the night and follow at their rear, and let none of you turn around, and proceed<sup>pl</sup> wherever you<sup>pl</sup> are commanded.”"
  15,66,"And We decreed to him that matter: that the last trace of these would be uprooted by the morning."
  15,67,"And the people of the town came anticipating glad tidings."
  15,68,"He said, “Indeed, these are my guests, so do not embarrass me,"
  15,69,"and be mindful of Allah and do not disgrace me.”"
  15,70,"They said, “Did we not forbid you<sup>sg</sup> from <small>(receiving)</small> any people<sup foot_note="366796">1</sup> ?”",footnotes:347259:The Arabic word used is <i>al-alameen</i> which means ‘all realms’ or ‘all communities’.
  15,71,"He said, “These are my daughters, if you must.”"
  15,72,"By your<sup>sg</sup> life, in their drunkenness they certainly do blunder!"
  15,73,"So the Shout took them away at sunrise."
  15,74,"And We turned it upside down and rained down upon them stones of hard clay."
  15,75,"Indeed, in that are certainly signs for those who contemplate."
  15,76,"And indeed, it<sup foot_note="366797">1</sup> is certainly on an existing way.",footnotes:347260:The ruins of the cities of the people of Lot.
  15,77,"Indeed, in that is certainly a sign for the believers."
  15,78,"And indeed, the fellows of the Thicket were certainly unjust,"
  15,79,"so We took retribution on them, and indeed, both are certainly in an evident archive."
  15,80,"And most surely, the fellows of Al-Hijr<sup foot_note="366798">1</sup> disbelieved the emissaries.",footnotes:347261:<i>Al-Hijr</i> means the stone city which is located in northern Arabia and was inhabited by the people of Thamûd.
  15,81,"So We brought them Our signs, but they used to disregard them."
  15,82,"And of the mountains they used to carve homes, feeling safe."
  15,83,"But the Shout took them away by the morning,"
  15,84,"so all what they used to earn was of no avail to them."
  15,85,"And We did not create the heavens and the earth and whatever lies between them except with the truth<sup foot_note="366799">1</sup> . And indeed, the Hour is coming, so pardon<sup>sg</sup> <small>(with)</small> gracious pardoning.",footnotes:347262:According to Ibn Ashour and other exegetes, ‘with the truth’ means ‘for a purpose’.
  15,86,"Indeed, yoursg Lord is the One who is the All-Creating, the All-Knowing."
  15,87,"And most surely, We have brought you<sup>sg</sup> seven of the oft-repeated<sup foot_note="366800">1</sup> and the great Recital<sup foot_note="366801">2</sup> .",footnotes:347263:The seven verses of the first surah.|347264:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  15,88,"Do<sup>sg</sup> not look longingly at the good things We have given some classes of them to enjoy, and do not grieve over them<sup foot_note="366802">1</sup>, and lower your wing<sup foot_note="366803">2</sup> towards the believers.",footnotes:347265:The deniers.|347266:An expression that implies showing compassion.
  15,89,"And say, “Indeed, it is I—I who am the evident warner.”"
  15,90,"So too did We send down to those who divide among themselves—"
  15,91,"those who have made the Recital<sup foot_note="366804">1</sup> into fragments.",footnotes:347267:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’
  15,92,"So by your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, We will surely ask them all"
  15,93,"about what they used to do."
  15,94,"So proclaim<sup>sg</sup> openly what you are commanded and disregard the polytheists."
  15,95,"Indeed, We have sufficed you<sup>sg</sup> against the mockers:"
  15,96,"those who set up another god with Allah. So they will come to know."
  15,97,"And most surely We are aware that your<sup>sg</sup> chest tightens with what they say."
  15,98,"So exalt your Lord with praise and be of those who prostrate,"
  15,99,"and worship your Lord until Certitude<sup foot_note="366805">1</sup> comes to you.",footnotes:347268:According to Salem Ibn ‘Abdullah and other exegetes, this means death.
  16,1,"Allah's command has come, so do<sup>pl</sup> not rush it. Highly Exalted is He, and Most High above what <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="366806">1</sup></span> associate <small>(with Him)</small>.",footnotes:347269:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…what you<sup>pl</sup> associate…” associate…”</span>
  16,2,"He <span class="h">bestows<sup foot_note="366807">1</sup></span> the angels from on high with the Spirit by His command upon whom He wills of His servants: “Give<sup>pl</sup> warning that there is no god but Me, so be mindful of Me.”",footnotes:347270:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Roways read it as: “He sends down the angels with the Spirit…” Rouh read it as: “The angels are bestowed from on high with the Spirit…”</span>
  16,3,"He created the heavens and the earth with truth. Most High is He above what they associate <small>(with Him)</small>."
  16,4,"He created man from a sperm-drop, yet he becomes an evident adversary!"
  16,5,"And livestock—He created them for you<sup>pl</sup>. In them are warmth and benefits for you, and of them you eat."
  16,6,"And there is beauty in them for you when you drive them home and when you drive them to pasture."
  16,7,"And they carry your heavy burdens to a land you could not have reached without great hardship to yourselves; indeed, your Lord is truly Compassionate, Bestowing of mercy."
  16,8,"And horses and mules and donkeys—that you may ride them, and as an adornment; and He creates what you do not know."
  16,9,"And it is upon Allah to point out the way, but some of them<sup foot_note="366808">1</sup> are crooked. And had He willed, He would surely have guided you all.",footnotes:347271:The ways.
  16,10,"It is He Who sent down to you from the sky water from which is a drink for you and from which are trees where you pasture."
  16,11,"With it He <span class="h">germinates<sup foot_note="366809">1</sup></span> for you vegetation and olives and date-palms and grapevines and of all products. Indeed, in that is a sign for people who reflect.",footnotes:347272:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “With it We germinate for you…”</span>
  16,12,"And He has subjected to you the night and the day and the <span class="h">sun<sup foot_note="366810">1</sup></span> and the moon. And the stars are subjected by His command. Indeed, in that are signs for people who reason.",footnotes:347273:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “…the night and the day. And the sun and the moon and the stars are subjected…” All except for Hafs and Ibn Amer read it as: “…the night and the day and the sun and the moon and the stars—(all) subjected…”</span>
  16,13,"And <small>(He has subjected)</small> whatever He has scattered for you in the earth of varying colors. Indeed, in that is a sign for people who constantly remember."
  16,14,"And He is the One Who subjected the sea, that you may eat from it tender meat and extract from it ornaments that you wear. And you see the ships plowing through it, and <small>(all this)</small> so that you may seek of His bounties, and that you may give thanks."
  16,15,"And He cast firm mountains into the earth lest it sway with you, and rivers and ways, that you may be guided."
  16,16,"And landmarks<sup foot_note="366811">1</sup>, and by the star they are guided.",footnotes:347274:For guidance during the day.
  16,17,"Is One Who creates like one who does not create? Will you never remind <span class="h">yourselves<sup foot_note="366812">1</sup></span>?",footnotes:347275:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Will you not constantly remember?”</span>
  16,18,"And if you<sup>pl</sup> were to count the blessings of Allah, you would not be able to enumerate them. Indeed, Allah is certainly Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  16,19,"And Allah knows whatever you keep secret and whatever you make public."
  16,20,"Yet those <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="366813">1</sup></span> call upon apart from Allah create nothing, while they <small>(themselves)</small> are created.",footnotes:347276:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem and Ya’qub read it as: “Yet those you<sup>pl </sup>call upon…”call upon…”</span>
  16,21,"<small>(They are, in fact)</small> dead, not alive, and they are unaware of when they will be resurrected."
  16,22,"Your<sup>pl</sup> God is one God. Therefore, those who do not believe in the Hereafter—their hearts are in denial and they act arrogantly."
  16,23,"Without doubt, Allah knows whatever they keep secret and whatever they make public; indeed, He does not like those who act arrogantly."
  16,24,"And when it is said to them, “What has your Lord sent down?” They say, “Legends of the ancients.”"
  16,25,"Let them carry their burdens, complete, on the Day of Resurrection, and some of the burdens of those they lead astray without knowledge. Undoubtedly, evil is what they bear."
  16,26,"Those before them did scheme, but Allah struck at the very foundations of their building, so the roof collapsed upon them from above them, and the punishment came upon them from where they were unaware."
  16,27,"Then, on the Day of Resurrection, He disgraces them and says, “Where are My associates for whose sake you used to <span class="h">oppose<sup foot_note="366814">1</sup></span><small>(the believers)</small>? Those who were given knowledge said<sup foot_note="366815">2</sup>, “Today disgrace and misery are indeed upon the deniers",footnotes:347277:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ read it as: “…for whose sake you used to oppose Me?”</span>|347278:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  16,28,"whom the angels take at death while they are unjust to themselves.” Then they offered submission<sup foot_note="366816">1</sup> : “We were doing no evil.” Yes! Indeed, Allah is All-Knowing of what you<sup>pl</sup> used to do.",footnotes:347279:After death.
  16,29,"Thus enter the gates of Hell, abiding therein.” And how miserable is the dwelling of the arrogant!"
  16,30,"And it was said to those who were mindful <small>(of God)</small>, “What did your Lord send down?” They said, “<small>(All that is) </small>good.” To those who have excelled in doing good in this Earlier <small>(Life)</small> is goodness, and the Home of the Hereafter is even better. And indeed, how excellent is the home of the people who are mindful <small>(of God)</small>:"
  16,31,"Gardens of Perpetuity which they enter, beneath which rivers flow; therein they have whatever they desire. Thus Allah rewards the mindful<sup>pl</sup> <small>(of Him)</small>:"
  16,32,"those whom the angels take up <small>(at death)</small> while they are goodly, saying, “Peace be upon you; enter the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> on account of what you used to do.”"
  16,33,"Are they but waiting for the angels to come to them, or for the command of your Lord to come? Those before them did likewise. And Allah did not do them any injustice, but to themselves they used to do injustice."
  16,34,"So the evils of what they had done afflicted them, and they became surrounded by what they used to ridicule."
  16,35,"And those who had associated <small>(others with Allah)</small> said, “Had Allah willed, we would never have worshiped anything apart from Him—neither us, nor our forefathers, nor would we have prohibited anything without <small>(permission from)</small> Him.” Those before them did likewise. So are the messengers responsible for anything but evident proclamation?"
  16,36,"For very truly, in every community We sent a messenger: “Worship<sup>pl</sup> Allah and avoid false masters.” So some of them Allah has guided, and some of them have deserved misguidance. So journey<sup foot_note="366817">1</sup> through the earth and look what the outcome was for the disbelievers.",footnotes:347280:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 2 person to 2<sup>nd</sup> person. person.
  16,37,"<small>(Even)</small> if you<sup>sg</sup> are concerned about their guidance, <small>(still)</small> Allah surely does not guide whomever He <span class="h">leads<sup foot_note="366818">1</sup></span> astray, and they will have no helpers.",footnotes:347281:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…(still)<big> </big>whomever Allah leads astray surely cannot be guided,”whomever Allah leads astray surely cannot be guided,”</span>
  16,38,"And they have sworn by Allah their most solemn oaths that Allah does not resurrect whoever dies. Yes indeed, it is a promise binding on Him, but the majority of mankind does not know."
  16,39,"<small>(This is)</small> to clarify for them what they differ over, and so that those who have denied know that they were liars."
  16,40,"Indeed, Our only saying to anything, once We have wanted it, is to say to it, “Be,” and so it <span class="h">is<sup foot_note="366819">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:347282:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…is to say to it, ‘Be,’ so it is.”</span>
  16,41,"And those who emigrated for Allah after they had been dealt with unjustly—We will surely settle them in a good place in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small>, and the reward of the Hereafter is truly greater, if they only knew."
  16,42,"Those are the ones who endured patiently, and in their Lord they place<sup foot_note="366820">1</sup> their trust.",footnotes:347283:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense.
  16,43,"And never did We send as messengers before you<sup>sg</sup> except men to whom We <span class="h">reveal<sup foot_note="366821">1</sup></span>. So ask<sup>pl</sup> the people of the Reminder if you do not know.",footnotes:347284:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as: “…to whom it is revealed.”</span>
  16,44,"<small>(We sent them)</small> with evident proofs and books. And We sent down to you<sup>sg</sup> the Reminder, that you may clarify to mankind what was bestowed upon them from on high, and that they may reflect."
  16,45,"Do those who have schemed evils feel secure that Allah will not cause the earth to cave in beneath them, or that the punishment will not come upon them from where they are unaware?"
  16,46,"Or that He will not seize them <small>(suddenly)</small> during their movement so that they cannot thwart <small>(Him)</small>?"
  16,47,"Or that He will not seize them gradually? Yet indeed, your Lord is truly Compassionate, Bestowing of mercy."
  16,48,"Have <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="366822">1</sup></span> not seen all things that Allah has created—their shadows revolving from the right and the left, prostrating to Allah as they shrink away?",footnotes:347285:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Have you<sup>pl</sup> not seen…” not seen…”</span>
  16,49,"And to Allah prostrates whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth of every treading creature, as well as the angels, and they do not act arrogantly—"
  16,50,"fearing their Lord above them and doing whatever they are commanded."
  16,51,"And Allah has said: “Do<sup>pl</sup> not take two gods; He is but One God, so of Me<sup foot_note="366823">1</sup> alone be in awe.”",footnotes:347286:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 1 person to 1<sup>st </sup>person.person.
  16,52,"And to Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth, and religion is His forever. Are you then mindful of anyone other than Allah?"
  16,53,"And whatever blessing you<sup>pl</sup> have is from Allah, then when harm touches you, it is to Him that you cry for help."
  16,54,"Then when He lifts off harm from you, a group of you associate <small>(others)</small> with their Lord,"
  16,55,"so as to deny what We have given them. So enjoy yourselves, for you will come to know."
  16,56,"And they set up to what they do not know a share of what We have provided for them. By Allah, you<sup foot_note="366824">1</sup> will surely be asked about what you<sup>pl</sup> used to fabricate.",footnotes:347287:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 2 person to 2<sup>nd</sup> person. person.
  16,57,"And they set up to Allah daughters—Highly Exalted is He—and unto themselves whatever they desire."
  16,58,"But when one of them is given the glad tidings<sup foot_note="366825">1</sup> of a female <small>(infant)</small>, his countenance remains darkened as he suppresses his anguish.",footnotes:347288:Said in sarcasm.
  16,59,"He hides himself from people because of the evilness of the glad tidings he has been given. Should he keep it, in shame, or bury it <small>(alive)</small> in the dust? Undoubtedly, evil is the way they judge!"
  16,60,"For those who do not believe in the Hereafter is an evil example, while to Allah belongs the highest example. And He is the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  16,61,"And if Allah were to hold mankind for their injustices, He would not leave upon it a single treading creature, but He defers them to a stated term. Then, when their term has arrived<sup foot_note="366826">1</sup>, they cannot delay it by one hour nor can they advance it.",footnotes:347289:By death.
  16,62,"And they set up for Allah what they themselves hate, while their tongues describe the lie that theirs is the best <small>(reward)</small>; without doubt, for them is the Fire and <small>(without doubt)</small> they will be driven to it <span class="h">quickly<sup foot_note="366827">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:347290:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…for them is the Fire and (without doubt) they have been neglecting (their tasks).” Nafie read it as: “…for them is the Fire and (without doubt) they have gone too far.”</span>
  16,63,"<small>(I swear )</small> by Allah, We sent messengers to communities before you<sup>sg</sup>, but Satan adorned their deeds for them, so that he is their master today, and they will have a painful punishment."
  16,64,"And We have not sent down to you<sup>sg</sup> the Scripture but that you may clarify for them what they have differed over, and as a guidance and a mercy for people who believe."
  16,65,"And Allah has sent down, from the sky, water with which He revived the earth after it was lifeless; indeed, in this is a sign for people who hear."
  16,66,"And indeed, there is a lesson for you<sup>pl</sup> in livestock: <span class="h">We<sup foot_note="366828">1</sup></span> give you to drink of what is in their bellies—from between filth and blood—pure milk, palatable to the drinkers.",footnotes:347291:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…livestock: they give you to drink…”</span>
  16,67,"And from the products of date-palms and grapevines you make an intoxicating beverage and good food. Surely, in that is a sign for people who reason."
  16,68,"And your<sup>sg</sup> Lord revealed to the bee: “Take for yourself<sup>sg</sup> homes of the mountains, and of the trees and of whatever they trellis,"
  16,69,"then eat of all products and go along the ways of your Lord, made smooth”. From their bellies comes out a drink of diverse colors, wherein is a cure for mankind. Surely, in that is a sign for people who reflect."
  16,70,"And Allah created you<sup>pl</sup>, then He takes you <small>(at death)</small>. Yet among you is the one who is turned back to the most abject age, so that he no longer knows anything after having acquired knowledge; indeed, Allah is All-Knowing, All-Powerful."
  16,71,"And Allah has favored some of you over others in provision, yet those who were favored do not give their provision to those whom they rightfully possess, to the extent of making them equal partners in it. Do <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="366829">1</sup></span> then repudiate the blessing of Allah?",footnotes:347292:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba and Roways read it as: “Do you<sup>pl</sup> then repudiate…” then repudiate…”</span>
  16,72,"And Allah has set up for you spouses from among yourselves, and has assigned for you from your spouses, children and grandchildren, and has provided you with good things. Yet is it in falsehood that they<sup foot_note="366830">1</sup> believe, while it is the blessing of Allah that they deny?",footnotes:347293:A grammatical shift from 2<sup>nd</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  16,73,"And yet they worship apart from Allah what possesses no provisions for them in the heavens or the earth, nor are they capable <small>(of doing anything)</small>."
  16,74,"So do<sup>pl</sup> not set forth any parables for Allah; indeed, Allah knows and you know not."
  16,75,"Allah set forth a parable: an owned bondman who has no power over anything, and <small>(on the other hand)</small> someone to whom We<sup foot_note="366831">1</sup> have given goodly provision from which he gives, secretly and openly. Can they be equal? All praise be to Allah; rather, most of them know not.",footnotes:347294:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 1 person to 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.
  16,76,"And Allah set forth a parable of two men: one of them a mute who has no power over anything, and he is wholly dependent upon his patron; wherever he directs him, he achieves nothing good. Can he be equal to one who commands to justice and is on a straight path?"
  16,77,"And to Allah belongs the hidden realm of the heavens and the earth, and the matter of the Hour is only as the twinkling of the eye or even nearer; indeed, Allah is Powerful over everything."
  16,78,"And Allah brought you<sup>pl</sup> out of your mothers’ bellies not knowing anything, and He assigned for you hearing and sight<small>(s)</small> and burning hearts, that you may give thanks."
  16,79,"Have <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="366832">1</sup></span> not seen the birds subjected in the midst of the sky? None holds them up except Allah. Surely, in that are signs for people who believe.",footnotes:347295:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer, Hamza, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “Have you<sup>pl</sup> not seen…” not seen…”</span>
  16,80,"And Allah has made for you, of your houses, <small>(places of)</small> rest and has assigned for you out of the skins of livestock <small>(portable)</small> homes which you find light on the day you travel and on the day you encamp and, from their wool and fur and hair, furnishings and an enjoyment for a while."
  16,81,"And Allah has made for you<sup>pl</sup> shades out of what He created, and has made for you shelters of the mountains, and has made for you garments to protect you from the heat and garments to protect you from your violence; thus He completes His blessings upon you, that you may submit."
  16,82,"So if they<sup foot_note="366833">1</sup> turn away, then certainly your<sup>sg</sup> only duty is evident proclamation.",footnotes:347296:A grammatical shift from 2<sup>nd</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  16,83,"They recognize Allah’s blessing then they deny it, as most of them are the deniers."
  16,84,"And on the day when We raise up a witness from every community —then those who denied are not permitted, nor are they allowed to make amends."
  16,85,"And when those who did injustice see the punishment, <small>(they will realize that)</small> never shall it be lightened for them, nor shall they be given respite."
  16,86,"And when the ones who associated <small>(others with God)</small> see their associates<sup foot_note="366834">1</sup>, they will say, “Our Lord, these are our associates whom we used to call upon apart from You.” So they cast<sup foot_note="366835">2</sup> to them the statement, “Very truly, you are liars.”",footnotes:347297:The false gods.|347298:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  16,87,"And they cast forth to Allah, on that day, <small>(their)</small> submissiveness, and whatever they used to fabricate strayed away from them."
  16,88,"Those who denied and barred from the way of Allah—We<sup foot_note="366836">1</sup> added punishment to their punishment on account of the corruption they used to cause.",footnotes:347299:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd </sup>person to 1person to 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.
  16,89,"And on a day when We raise in every community a witness against them from among them, and We brought<sup foot_note="366837">1</sup> you<sup>sg</sup> as a witness against these. For We have bestowed upon you the Scripture from on high, as an explanation of everything and guidance and mercy and glad tidings for the Muslims<sup foot_note="366838">2</sup> .",footnotes:347300:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.|347301:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  16,90,"Indeed, Allah commands to justice and excelling in doing good and bringing<sup foot_note="366839">1</sup> <small>(charity)</small> to the relative, and He forbids obscenity and what is deplorable and oppression. He admonishes you, that you may remind <span class="h">yourselves<sup foot_note="366840">2</sup></span>.",footnotes:347302:The Qur’an always uses ‘bringing’ rather than ‘giving’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|347303:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…that you may<big> </big>constantly remember.”constantly remember.”</span>
  16,91,"And fulfill<sup>pl</sup> Allah’s covenant when you make a covenant, and do not violate your oaths after ratifying them, for surely you have made Allah your guarantor; indeed, Allah knows what you do."
  16,92,"And do<sup>pl</sup> not be like she who unravels her yarn, breaking it into pieces after she has spun it strongly, by using your oaths as a means of deception among you because one community is more prosperous than another community. Indeed, Allah is testing you thereby, and He will most surely clarify to you on the Day of Resurrection whatever you used to differ over."
  16,93,"And had Allah willed, He would have made you one community, but He leads astray whom He wills, and He guides whom He wills, and you will most surely be asked about what you used to do."
  16,94,"And do not use your oaths as a means of deception among you, lest a foot slip after being firm and you taste misery for barring <small>(others)</small> from the way of Allah, and for you there will be a great punishment."
  16,95,"And do<sup>pl</sup> not purchase, in exchange for Allah’s covenant, a small price; indeed, what is with Allah is better for you, if you only knew."
  16,96,"What you have runs out, but what is with Allah remains. And <span class="h">We<sup foot_note="366841">1</sup></span> will most surely repay those who were patient their reward in accordance with the best of what they used to do.",footnotes:347304:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Kathir, Asem, Abu Ja’far and Ibn Zekwan in one of his narrations read it as: “And He will most surely repay…”</span>
  16,97,"Whoever has acted righteously, whether male or female, while being a believer—We will most surely grant him a good life, and We will most surely repay them<sup foot_note="366842">1</sup> their reward in accordance with the best of what they used to do.",footnotes:347305:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  16,98,"So when you<sup>sg</sup> recite the Recital<sup foot_note="366843">1</sup> seek refuge with Allah from Satan, the outcast.",footnotes:347306:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  16,99,"Indeed, he has no authority over those who have attained faith and in their Lord they place their trust."
  16,100,"Indeed, his authority is only over those who take him as an ally and those who through him associate <small>(others with God)</small>."
  16,101,"Yet whenever We substitute a sign in place of another sign—and Allah<sup foot_note="366844">1</sup> knows better what He bestows from on <span class="h">high<sup foot_note="366845">2</sup></span>—they say, “Indeed, you are nothing but a fabricator.” Rather, most of them do not know.",footnotes:347307:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.|347308:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “…what He sends down…”</span>
  16,102,"Say, The Holy Spirit has bestowed it from on high from your<sup>sg</sup> Lord<sup foot_note="366846">1</sup>, with the truth, in order to strengthen those who have attained faith, and as guidance and glad tidings for Muslims<sup foot_note="366847">2</sup> .",footnotes:347309:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 2 person to 2<sup>nd</sup> person. person.|347310:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  16,103,"And most surely, We know that they say, “Indeed, it is a human being who is teaching him.” But the tongue of the one they allude to is foreign, while this is an evident Arabic tongue."
  16,104,"Indeed, those who do not believe in Allah’s signs—Allah does not guide them, and for them is a painful punishment."
  16,105,"Indeed, it is those who do not believe in Allah’s signs who fabricate falsehood, and those are the liars."
  16,106,"Whoever has denied Allah after attaining faith—except for someone who was compelled<sup foot_note="366848">1</sup> while his heart rests securely in faith, but <small>(rather)</small> whoever <small>(willingly)</small> opens a chest to denial—upon them is wrath from Allah, and for them is a great punishment.",footnotes:347311:God excuses anyone who is compelled to renounce his faith.
  16,107,"That is because they have sought the love of the Earlier Life over the Hereafter, and because Allah does not guide the denying people."
  16,108,"Those are the ones whose hearts and hearing and sight<small>(s)</small> Allah has sealed, and those are the oblivious ones."
  16,109,"Without doubt, in the Hereafter they are the losers."
  16,110,"Then surely your<sup>sg</sup> Lord—for those who emigrated after being persecuted, then strove and patiently persevered—indeed, your Lord thereafter is surely Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  16,111,"On the day when every single self comes arguing for itself, and every soul is paid in full <small>(for)</small> what it has done, and they are not done any injustice."
  16,112,"And Allah set forth a parable: a town that was safe <small>(and)</small> secure, its provision coming to it abundantly from everywhere. Yet it denied Allah’s blessings, so Allah made it taste the garment of hunger and fear on account of what they used to do."
  16,113,"And very truly, a messenger from among them had come to them, but they disbelieved him, so the punishment seized them while they were unjust."
  16,114,"So eat<sup>pl</sup> of the lawful and good things Allah has provided for you, and be thankful for Allah’s blessing, if it is Him that you worship."
  16,115,"Indeed, He has only forbidden you<sup>pl</sup> carrion and blood and the flesh of swine and anything consecrated to other than Allah; but if anyone is compelled by necessity without being deliberate or transgressing, then Allah is indeed Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  16,116,"And do not say lies concerning that which your tongues describe: “This is lawful and this is unlawful,” in order to fabricate lies and attribute them to Allah; indeed, those who fabricate lies and attribute them to Allah do not succeed."
  16,117,"A brief enjoyment, then for them is a painful punishment."
  16,118,"And for the ones who Judaized We have prohibited what We related to you<sup>sg</sup> before, and in no way did We do them any injustice, but to themselves they used to do injustice."
  16,119,"But indeed your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, towards those who did evil in ignorance and then repented afterwards and reformed—indeed, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord thereafter is surely Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  16,120,"Indeed, Abraham was a nation, devout towards Allah, turning away from all that is false, for never was he of the polytheists."
  16,121,"<small>(He was) </small>thankful for His blessings. He elected him and guided him to a straight path."
  16,122,"And We<sup foot_note="366849">1</sup> brought him goodness in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small>, and in the Hereafter he is surely of the righteous.",footnotes:347312:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 1 person to 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.
  16,123,"Then We revealed to you<sup>sg</sup>: “Follow<sup>sg</sup> the creed of Abraham, who turned away from all that is false, for never was he of the polytheists.”"
  16,124,"Indeed, the Sabbath was ordained upon those who differed over it. And most surely, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord will judge between them on the Day of Resurrection regarding whatever they used to differ over."
  16,125,"Call<sup>sg</sup> to the way of your Lord with wisdom and good admonition, and debate with them by that which is better. Indeed, it is your Lord Who knows better of those who stray from His way, and it is He Who knows better of those who are guided."
  16,126,"And if you<sup>pl</sup> punish, then punish with the like of that with which you were punished. But if you resort to patience, it is surely better for the patient ones."
  16,127,"So be patient<sup>sg</sup>, for your patience is solely from Allah. And do not grieve over them and do not be distressed because of what they scheme."
  16,128,"Indeed, Allah is with those who are mindful <small>(of Him)</small> and those who excel in doing good."
  17,1,"Highly Exalted is the One Who took His servant on a journey by night from the Inviolable Mosque<sup foot_note="366850">1</sup> to the Farthest Mosque<sup foot_note="366851">2</sup>, whose precincts We<sup foot_note="366852">3</sup> have blessed, in order to show him of Our signs; indeed, He is the All-Hearing, the All-Seeing.",footnotes:347313:<i>Al-masjid Al-Harām</i> in Makkah.|347314:<i>Al-masjid Al-Aqsa</i> in Jerusalem<i>.</i>|347315:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> to person 1 to person 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.
  17,2,"And We brought Moses the Scripture and made it guidance for the Children of Israel: <span class="h">“Take<sup foot_note="366853">1</sup></span> none for trustee other than Me,",footnotes:347316:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “…for the Children of Israel, that they may take none for trustee other than Me.</span>
  17,3,"<small>(O)</small> offspring of those We carried with Noah; indeed, he was a constantly thankful servant.”"
  17,4,"And We decreed for the Children of Israel in the Scripture: “You will most surely corrupt in the land twice, and you will most surely rise to a great height."
  17,5,"Then when the promise of the first of the two times came true, We sent against you<sup>pl</sup> servants of Ours possessing intense force, and they ransacked the homes, and it was a promise fulfilled.”"
  17,6,"Then We gave you<sup>pl</sup> back your turn against them and supplied you with wealth and offspring and made you more numerous."
  17,7,"If you excel in doing good, you excel in doing good to your own benefit; and if you do evil, you do so against yourselves. Then when the promise of the second time comes true, <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="366854">1</sup></span> will defile your faces, and they will enter the Mosque as they entered it the first time, and they will utterly destroy all that falls into their power.",footnotes:347317:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer, Shu’ba, Hamza and Khalaf read it as: “…He will defile…” Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…We will defile…”</span>
  17,8,"Hopefully your<sup>pl</sup> Lord will have mercy on you. But if you revert, We<sup foot_note="366855">1</sup> will revert. And We have made Hell a prison for the deniers.",footnotes:347318:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> to person 1 to person 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.
  17,9,"Indeed, this Recital<sup foot_note="366856">1</sup> guides to what is most upright and gives glad tidings to the believers who do righteous deeds that for them there is a supreme reward,",footnotes:347319:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  17,10,"and that those who do not believe in the Hereafter—We have prepared for them a painful punishment."
  17,11,"And man calls for evil as he calls for good, and man has always been very hasty."
  17,12,"And We have made the night and the day as two signs, then We erased the sign of the night and made the sign of the day as an eye-opener, that you<sup>pl</sup> may seek grace from your Lord<sup foot_note="366857">1</sup> and that you may learn the number of years and the calculation; and everything have We explained in detail.",footnotes:347320:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  17,13,"And for every person We have attached his augury to his neck, and on the Day of Resurrection We will bring out for him a record<sup foot_note="366858">1</sup> which he will find spread <span class="h">open<sup foot_note="366859">2</sup></span>.",footnotes:347321:Literally, ‘scripture’.|347322:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…and on the Day of Resurrection a record, which he will receive spread open, is brought out for him.”Ya’qub read it as: “…and on the Day of Resurrection a record, which he will find spread open, comes out for him.”Ibn Amer read it as: “…and on the Day of Resurrection We will bring out for him a record which he will receive spread open.”</span>
  17,14,"“Recite<sup>sg</sup> your record; today your own soul is sufficient as a reckoner.”"
  17,15,"Whoever is guided—he is only guided to his own benefit, while whoever goes astray—he goes astray to his own detriment. And no bearer of burden carries the burden of another, for never do We punish until We have sent a messenger."
  17,16,"And when We want to annihilate a town We <span class="h">command<sup foot_note="366860">1</sup></span> its affluent ones <small>(to be righteous)</small>, yet they defiantly disobey <small>(Our commands)</small> in it, so it deserves the decree and We annihilate it completely.",footnotes:347323:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…We make its affluent ones in command, yet they…”</span>
  17,17,"And how many generations have We annihilated after Noah? Thus sufficient is your Lord<sup foot_note="366861">1</sup> as All-Aware, All-Seeing of the misdeeds of His servants.",footnotes:347324:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> to 3 to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  17,18,"Whoever has been wanting the hasty <small>(life of this world)</small>—We hasten for him therein whatever We will to whomever We desire. Then We assigned<sup foot_note="366862">1</sup> for him Hell where he roasts, condemned, defeated.",footnotes:347325:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  17,19,"But whoever wanted the Hereafter and, as a believer, pursued it as it should be pursued, those—their pursuit has always been thanked."
  17,20,"To all—these and these <small>(as well)</small>—We extend from the gifts of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord<sup foot_note="366863">1</sup>, for the gifts of your Lord have never been restricted.",footnotes:347326:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  17,21,"Look<sup>sg</sup> at how We have favored some of them over others, yet the Hereafter is more superior in degrees <small>(of rank)</small> and more superior in preference."
  17,22,"Do<sup>sg</sup> not set up another god with Allah, lest you remain condemned,<small> </small>damned."
  17,23,"And your<sup>sg</sup> Lord has decreed that you<sup>pl</sup> shall worship none but Him, and <small>(He has decreed)</small> excelling in doing good to both parents. If either of them or both of them reach old age with you<sup>sg</sup>, then do not say to them “Fie” nor scold them, but speak to them using noble words."
  17,24,"And lower to them the wing<sup foot_note="366864">1</sup> of humility, out of mercy, and say, “My Lord, have mercy on both of them as they raised me when I was a child.”",footnotes:347327:An expression that implies showing compassion.
  17,25,"Your<sup>pl</sup> Lord knows better what is within yourselves. If you are righteous—indeed, He has always been Oft-Forgiving to the ones who often turn <small>(to Him)</small>."
  17,26,"And give<sup>sg</sup> the relative his rights, and the destitute<sup>sg</sup> and the traveler in need, and do not squander wastefully."
  17,27,"Indeed, the squanderers have always been brethren of the Satans, for Satan has always been a staunch denier of his Lord."
  17,28,"But if you<sup>sg</sup> disregard them, seeking mercy<sup foot_note="366865">1</sup> which you expect from your Lord, then speak to them using gentle words.",footnotes:347328:According to exegetes, ‘mercy’ here means ‘provision’.
  17,29,"And do not keep your hand tied to your neck<sup foot_note="366866">1</sup> nor spread it out fully, lest you end up blamed, regretful.",footnotes:347329:A metaphor for miserliness.
  17,30,"Indeed, your Lord extends provision for whomever He wills and He restrains <small>(it)</small>; indeed, He has always been All-Aware, All-Seeing of His servants."
  17,31,"And do<sup>pl</sup> not kill your children for fear of poverty; We provide for them and for you<sup>pl</sup>. Indeed, killing them has always been a grave offense."
  17,32,"And do<sup>pl</sup> not come near fornication; indeed, it is an obscenity and an evil way."
  17,33,"And do<sup>pl</sup> not kill the self which Allah has made inviolable, except in the course of justice. And if someone is killed unjustly, We have given authority to his kinsman who seeks retribution, but <span class="h">he<sup foot_note="366867">1</sup></span> should not be excessive in killing; indeed, he is bound to be aided.",footnotes:347330:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…but you<sup>sg</sup> should not be excessive …” should not be excessive …”</span>
  17,34,"And do<sup>pl</sup> not come near the orphan’s wealth except with that which is better <small>(for him)</small>, until he has attained his full strength. And fulfill every covenant; indeed, the covenant has always been a responsibility."
  17,35,"And give<sup>pl</sup> full measure when you measure, and weigh with accurate scales; that is fair and the best determination."
  17,36,"And do<sup>sg</sup> not follow what you have no knowledge of; indeed, the hearing and the sight and the burning heart—all of those—<small>(one) </small>is bound to be questioned about."
  17,37,"And do<sup>sg</sup> not walk merrily on earth; you<sup>sg</sup> will surely not pierce the earth, nor will you match the mountains in height."
  17,38,"All of that— its evil has always <span class="h">been<sup foot_note="366868">1</sup></span> disliked by your Lord.",footnotes:347331:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “All of that has always been an evil deed before your<sup>sg</sup> Lord (and) disliked.” Lord (and) disliked.”</span>
  17,39,"That is some of the wisdom your<sup>sg</sup> Lord has revealed to you. And do not set up with Allah another god, lest you be thrown in Hell, blamed, banished."
  17,40,"Has your<sup>pl</sup> Lord favored you with sons and taken for Himself from the angels females? You<sup>pl</sup> are certainly saying a great<sup foot_note="366869">1</sup> saying.",footnotes:347332:The Arabic word <i>azeem</i> is sometimes used with a negative connotation to denote the seriousness of a matter.
  17,41,"And very truly, We have explained in this Recital<sup foot_note="366870">1</sup> in various ways, that they may constantly <span class="h">remember<sup foot_note="366871">2</sup></span>, but it only adds to their aversion.",footnotes:347333:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.|347334:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…that they may remember,”</span>
  17,42,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “If there were other gods with Him as <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="366872">1</sup></span> say, they would have sought a way to the Possessor of the Throne.”",footnotes:347335:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Kathir and Hafs read it as: “…as you<sup>pl</sup> say…” say…”</span>
  17,43,"Highly Exalted is He. He is Most High, far above what they say."
  17,44,"Exalting Him are the seven heavens and the earth and whoever is in them. And there is not a thing that does not exalt Him with praise, but you<sup>pl</sup> do not comprehend their exaltation. Indeed, He has always been Forbearing, Oft-Forgiving."
  17,45,"And when you<sup>sg</sup> recite the Recital<sup foot_note="366873">1</sup>, We place between you and those who do not believe in the Hereafter an invisible barrier.",footnotes:347336:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  17,46,"And We have placed veils over their hearts preventing them from comprehending it, and heaviness in their ears. And when you mention your Lord<sup foot_note="366874">1</sup> alone in the Recital<sup foot_note="366875">2</sup>, they turn their backs in aversion.",footnotes:347337:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.|347338:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  17,47,"We know better what <small>(intention)</small> it is that they listen with as they listen to you and as they secretly converse, as the unjust say, “You<sup>pl</sup> are following nothing but a man bewitched.”"
  17,48,"Look<sup>sg</sup> at how they have set forth parables for you<sup>sg</sup> and gone astray, so they cannot find a way."
  17,49,"And they said, “Can it be that when we have become bones and fragments—can it be <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="366876">1</sup></span> we will really be resurrected as a new creation?”",footnotes:347339:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “Can it be that when we have become bones and fragments we will really…” Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “When we have become bones and fragments—can it be that we will really …”</span>
  17,50,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, <small>“</small>Become<sup>pl</sup> rocks or iron"
  17,51,"or any sort of creation which is greatly admired in your<sup>pl</sup> chests.” Then they will say, “Who will restore us?” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “The One Who originated you<sup>pl</sup> the first time.” Then they will nod their heads at you<sup>sg</sup> and say, “When will it be?” Say, “Hopefully, it will be soon,"
  17,52,"on the day when He calls you<sup>pl</sup>, then you respond with His praise and you think that you stayed only a little.”"
  17,53,"And tell<sup>sg</sup> My servants to say what is better. Indeed, Satan spurs <small>(discord)</small> between them; indeed, Satan has always been, to man, an evident enemy."
  17,54,"Your<sup>pl</sup> Lord knows better about you. If He wills, He bestows mercy on you; and if He wills, He punishes you. Thus We never sent you<sup>sg</sup> as a trustee over them."
  17,55,"And your<sup>sg</sup> Lord knows better about whoever is in the heavens and the earth. And We<sup foot_note="366877">1</sup> have most surely favored some prophets over others, and to David We gave a Book<sup foot_note="366878">2</sup> .",footnotes:347340:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd</sup> person to 1 person to 1<sup>st</sup> person. person.|347341:The <i>Zaboor</i> or the Psalms.
  17,56,"Say, “Call upon those you claimed apart from Him. But they have no power to lift off harm from you, nor can they change it.”"
  17,57,"Those whom they call upon are themselves seeking means of access to their Lord—whichever of them will be nearer—and hoping for His mercy and fearing His punishment; indeed, the punishment of your Lord has always been dreaded."
  17,58,"So there is no town but We are to annihilate it before the Day of Resurrection or punish it with a severe punishment; this has been inscribed in the Scripture."
  17,59,"And nothing prevented Us from sending <small>(miraculous)</small> signs except that the ancients disbelieved in them. So We gave Thamûd<sup foot_note="366879">1</sup> the she-camel as an eye-opener, but they mistreated it. For We never send signs except to frighten <small>(people of destruction)</small>.",footnotes:347342:The pagan tribe of Prophet Salih.
  17,60,"And recall when We said to you<sup>sg</sup> that your Lord<sup foot_note="366880">1</sup> has encompassed mankind. And We did not make the vision We showed you except as a means of trial for mankind, and <small>(recall)</small> the tree which is cursed in the Recital<sup foot_note="366881">2</sup> . And We frighten them, but that increases them in nothing but supreme transgression.",footnotes:347343:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.|347344:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  17,61,"And recall when We said to the angels, “Prostrate to Adam,” so they prostrated—but not Iblis<sup foot_note="366882">1</sup> . He said, “Shall I prostrate down to someone You created of clay?”",footnotes:347345:Iblis is another name of Satan or <i>Shaytan</i>.
  17,62,"He said, “Do You see this one whom You have honored more than me? If You reprieve me until the Day of Resurrection, I will most surely bridle his offspring, except for a few.”"
  17,63,"He said, “Go! Whoever of them follows you—then indeed, Hell is your<sup>pl</sup> repayment, an ample repayment."
  17,64,"And entice whomever of them you can with your voice, and rally against them your cavalry and your infantry, and share with them in wealth and children, and promise them.” But Satan promises them nothing but a deception."
  17,65,"“You surely have no authority over My servants.” And sufficient is your Lord as a trustee."
  17,66,"Your<sup>pl</sup> Lord is the One Who propels for you the ships at sea, that you may seek of His grace; indeed, to you He has always been Merciful."
  17,67,"And when harm touches you<sup>pl</sup> at sea, <small>(all)</small> those you call upon become lost except for Him. But when He delivered<sup foot_note="366883">1</sup> you to the shore, you disregarded <small>(Him)</small>; thus man has always been a staunch denier.",footnotes:347346:A grammatical shift from present tense to past tense.
  17,68,"Are you<sup>pl</sup> confident that <span class="h">He<sup foot_note="366884">1</sup></span> will not cause a side of the shore to collapse beneath you or unleash a tornado against you, and then you find no trustee?",footnotes:347347:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “…that We will not cause a side of the shore to collapse…”</span>
  17,69,"Or are you<sup>pl</sup> confident that <span class="h">He<sup foot_note="366885">1</sup></span> will not return you to it once again and unleash a hurricane of <span class="h">wind<sup foot_note="366886">2</sup></span> against you and <span class="h">drown<sup foot_note="366887">3</sup></span> you for your denial, and then you find no attending followers against Us?",footnotes:347348:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “…that We will not return you to it once again and unleash…”</span>|347349:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “winds”</span>|347350:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far and Roways read it as: “…against you which then drowns you…”</span>
  17,70,"Yet very truly We have honored the Children of Adam and carried them on land and sea and provided them with good things and greatly favored them over many of those We have created."
  17,71,"On the day when We call every group of people by their leader, then whoever is given his record<sup foot_note="366888">1</sup> in his right hand—those will read their record, and they will not be dealt with unjustly by as much as the hair upon a date-stone.",footnotes:347351:Literally ‘scripture’.
  17,72,"But whoever is blind in this <small>(life)</small>—he will be blind in the Hereafter and further astray from the way."
  17,73,"And they almost lured you<sup>sg</sup> away from what We have revealed to you so that you would fabricate something else in Our name, and in that case they would have taken you for a close friend."
  17,74,"Had We not given you<sup>sg</sup> stability, you were about to incline towards them a little."
  17,75,"Then We would have made you<sup>sg</sup> taste double in life and double at death, then you would have found for yourself no supporter against Us."
  17,76,"They almost provoked you<sup>sg</sup> so as to evict you from the land, and in that case they would not have lasted after you except briefly;"
  17,77,"such has been Our rule with the messengers We have sent before you, and you never find any change in Our rule."
  17,78,"Establish<sup>sg</sup> the prayer at the decline of the sun until the dusk of the night, as well as the Recitation<sup foot_note="366889">1</sup> at dawn; indeed, Recitation at dawn has always been witnessed.",footnotes:347352:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  17,79,"And keep vigil with it during parts of the night as an extra <small>(deed)</small>; hopefully your<sup>sg</sup> Lord will raise you to a laudable position."
  17,80,"And say<sup>sg</sup>, “My Lord, let me enter through an entry of truth and let me exit through an exit of truth and grant me from You a supporting manifestation.”"
  17,81,"And say<sup>sg</sup>, “Truth has come while falsehood has withered away; indeed, falsehood is bound to wither away.”"
  17,82,"And We bestow from on <span class="h">high<sup foot_note="366890">1</sup></span> of the Recital<sup foot_note="366891">2</sup> that which is a healing and a mercy for the believers, but it does not increase the unjust except in loss.",footnotes:347353:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “And We send down of the Recital that which…”</span>|347354:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  17,83,"And when We bless man, he disregards <small>(Us)</small> and distances <span class="h">himself<sup foot_note="366892">1</sup></span>. But when evil touches him, he staunchly despairs.",footnotes:347355:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Zekwan and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…and turns his back (literally ‘his side’).”</span>
  17,84,"Say, “Each does according to his disposition, but your<sup>pl</sup> Lord knows better who of the one who is more guided to the way.”"
  17,85,"And they ask you<sup>sg</sup> about the Spirit; say, “The Spirit is by the command of my Lord, and you<sup>pl</sup> were not given of knowledge but little.”"
  17,86,"And if We will, we can surely take away what We have revealed to you<sup>sg</sup>, then you would find for yourself no trustee against Us—"
  17,87,"except through a mercy from your Lord<sup foot_note="366893">1</sup> ; indeed, His grace upon you has been supreme.",footnotes:347356:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  17,88,"Say, “Most surely, if all humans and all unseen beings<sup foot_note="366894">1</sup> were to come together to bring forth the like of this Recital<sup foot_note="366895">2</sup>, they could never bring forth the like of it, even if they backed up one another.”",footnotes:347357:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.|347358:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  17,89,"And most surely, We have diversified for mankind in this Recital<sup foot_note="366896">1</sup> every kind of parable, but most of mankind refused anything but constant denial.",footnotes:347359:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  17,90,"And they said, “We will not believe in you<sup>sg</sup> until you make a spring gush forth from the ground for us;"
  17,91,"or possess a garden of palms and vines, then cause rivers to gush forth, pouring through them;"
  17,92,"or make the sky fall on us in pieces, as you claimed; or bring Allah and the angels before us;"
  17,93,"or possess a house of gold; or ascend into the sky. Even then, we will not believe in your ascension until you bestow upon us from on <span class="h">high<sup foot_note="366897">1</sup></span> a scripture that we can read.” Say, “Highly Exalted is my Lord. Have I been anything except a human messenger?”",footnotes:347360:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “...until you send down upon us a scripture that we can read.”</span>
  17,94,"And what prevented mankind from believing when guidance came to them, except that they said, “Did Allah send a human messenger?”"
  17,95,"<span class="h">Say<sup foot_note="366898">1</sup></span>, “If there were angels on earth walking around in peace, We would have bestowed upon them from heaven an angel messenger.”",footnotes:347361:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Ibn Amer read it as: “He said,”</span>
  17,96,"Say, “Allah is an adequate witness between you and me; indeed, He has always been All-Aware, All-Seeing of His servants.”"
  17,97,"And whomever Allah guides is the guided one, and whomever He leads astray—for them<sup foot_note="366899">1</sup> you will find no guardians apart from Him, and We will herd them on the Day of Resurrection on their faces, blind and dumb and deaf; their shelter is Hell; whenever it abates, We intensify the blaze for them.",footnotes:347362:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  17,98,"That is their repayment for having denied Our signs and for having said, “Can it be that when we have become bones and fragments—can it be <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="366900">1</sup></span> we will really be resurrected as a new creation?”",footnotes:347363:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “Can it be that when we have become bones and fragments we will really…” Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “When we have become bones and fragments—can it be that we will really …”</span>
  17,99,"Have they not seen that Allah, Who created the heavens and the earth, is Able to create the likes of them? And He has assigned for them a term in which there is no doubt. But the unjust refused anything but constant denial."
  17,100,"Say, “If youpl were to possess the treasuries of my Lord’s mercy, you would withhold them for fear of spending <small>(them)</small>.” And man has always been stingy."
  17,101,"And very truly We gave Moses nine evident signs, so ask the Children of Israel about when he went to them, then Pharaoh said to him, “Indeed, I think that you, O Moses, are bewitched.”"
  17,102,"He said, “You<sup>sg</sup> <span class="h">have<sup foot_note="366901">1</sup></span> most surely known that none sent these down except the Lord of the heavens and the earth, <small>(as)</small> insights. And indeed I think that you, O Pharaoh, are doomed to demise.”",footnotes:347364:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al Kesa’i read it as: “He said, ‘I have most surely known…’”</span>
  17,103,"So he wanted to provoke them to leave the land, but We drowned him and those with him, all together."
  17,104,"And after him, We said to the Children of Israel, “Settle in the land; yet when the promise of the Hereafter comes, We will bring you forth in a mixed multitude.”"
  17,105,"And with the truth We sent it down, and with the truth it descended. Thus We have not sent you but as a bearer of glad tidings and as a warner."
  17,106,"And a Recital<sup foot_note="366902">1</sup> which We apportioned, that you<sup>sg</sup> may recite it to mankind leisurely. And We surely bestowed it from on high.",footnotes:347365:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  17,107,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Believe in it or do not believe.” Indeed, those who were brought knowledge before it—when it is recited to them, they fall to their chins, prostrating."
  17,108,"And they say, “Highly Exalted is our Lord. The promise of our Lord is sure to be fulfilled.”"
  17,109,"And they fall to their chins weeping, and it adds to their humility."
  17,110,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Call upon Allah or call upon the All-Merciful; whichever you call upon, to Him belong the most beautiful names.” And be neither loud in your prayer nor silent in it, but follow a way in between."
  17,111,"And say<sup>sg</sup>, “All praise be to Allah, Who has not taken any offspring <small>(for Himself)</small>, nor has He ever had an associate in the dominion, nor has He ever had an ally out of humbleness. And glorify Him constantly.”"
  18,1,"All praise be to Allah, Who sent down the Scripture upon His servant and has not made therein any crookedness;"
  18,2,"most upright, to warn of a severe chastisement from Himself, and <small>(to)</small> give glad tidings to the believers who do righteous deeds that for them is an excellent reward,"
  18,3,"wherein they stay forever;"
  18,4,"and <small>(to)</small> warn those who have said, “Allah has taken <small>(for Himself)</small> offspring.”"
  18,5,"They have no knowledge of it, nor did their forefathers; massive is the word that comes out of their mouths! They say nothing but a lie!"
  18,6,"So perhaps you<sup>sg</sup> would decimate yourself, sorrowing after them, if they do not believe in this discourse."
  18,7,"Indeed, We have made whatever is on earth as an ornament for it, to test them as to which of them excels in work."
  18,8,"And indeed, We will turn what is on it into barren soil."
  18,9,"Or did you<sup>sg</sup> think that the fellows of the cave and the Inscription<sup foot_note="365238">1</sup> were among Our signs a wonder?",footnotes:345701:A tablet recording their story.
  18,10,"Recall when the young men took shelter in the cave, then said, “Our Lord, bring us mercy from Yourself and furnish us with prudence in our affair.”"
  18,11,"So We drew <small>(a seal)</small> upon their ears in the cave for a number of years."
  18,12,"Then We resurrected them to know which of the two parties could better enumerate the length of their stay."
  18,13,"We relate to you<sup>sg</sup> their story in truth; they are indeed young men who believed in their Lord and We increased them in guidance."
  18,14,"And We strengthened their hearts when they stood up and said, “Our Lord is the Lord of the heavens and the earth; we will never call upon any god apart from Him; most surely then we would have spoken untruthfully."
  18,15,"These, our people, have taken for themselves gods apart from Him. If only they would come forth with a clear manifestation of them. So who is more unjust than one who fabricated lies against Allah?”"
  18,16,"Now that you<sup>pl</sup> have withdrawn from them and from whatever they worship but Allah, take shelter in the cave, and your Lord will unfold His mercy for you and will set your affair towards ease.”"
  18,17,"And you<sup>sg</sup> see<sup foot_note="365239">1</sup> the sun when it rises, veering away from their cave towards the right, and when it sets, moving away from them to the left as they lie in a hollow therein; that is of Allah’s signs. Whomever Allah guides is the <small>(truly)</small> guided one, but whomever He leads astray—for him you<sup>sg</sup> will find no guiding guardian.",footnotes:345702:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense, which serves to create a vivid portrait of past events.
  18,18,"And you<sup>sg</sup> think them awake, although they are asleep. And We turn them over to the right and to the left, with their dog stretching its paws across the threshold. Had you looked at them, you would surely have turned away from them in flight and been filled with fear of them."
  18,19,"And thus We made them rise again so that they may ask one another. A speaker among them said, “How long have youpl stayed?” They said, “We have stayed a day or part of a day.” They said, “Yourpl Lord knows better how long you have stayed. So send one of you to the city with this silver <small>(coin)</small> of yours and let him look for whichever of them has the purest food and let him bring you some provision thereof. And let him go with discretion so that no one becomes aware of you."
  18,20,"If they prevail over you<sup>pl</sup>, they will surely either stone you or force you back into their creed, and then you would never succeed, ever.”"
  18,21,"And thus We caused them to be discovered, that they<sup foot_note="365240">1</sup> would know that the promise of Allah<sup foot_note="365241">2</sup> is true and that of the Hour there is no doubt. As they were disagreeing with each other about their affair, they said, “Build over them a structure.” Their Lord knows better about them. Those who prevailed over their affair<sup foot_note="365242">3</sup> said, “We will set up over them a mosque<sup foot_note="365243">4</sup> .”",footnotes:345703:The people of the city who discovered them.|345704:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.|345705:Literally ‘those who overcame (the others) in their affair’.|345706:The Arabic word is <i>masjid</i> which literally means ‘a place for prostration’.
  18,22,"Some will say, “Three, their fourth being their dog.” And some will say, “Five, their sixth being their dog,” —guessing at the unknown. And some will say, “Seven, and their eighth being their dog.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “My Lord knows better of their exact number”. None knows <small>(the reality about)</small> them except a few. So enter<sup>sg</sup> not into controversies concerning them except on a matter that is clear, and do not consult any of them<sup foot_note="365244">1</sup> about them.",footnotes:345707:The People of the Scripture.
  18,23,"And never say about anything, “I will do that tomorrow”"
  18,24,"without <small>(saying)</small>, “God willing.” And remember your Lord if you forget <small>(to say it)</small> and say, “Hopefully my Lord will guide me to something nearer to prudence than this.”"
  18,25,"And they remained in their cave for three hundred years, adding nine."
  18,26,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Allah knows better how long they remained; to Him belongs the hidden realm of the heavens and the earth. How clearly He sees and how finely He hears! They have no guardian apart from Him, and He <span class="h">does<sup foot_note="365245">1</sup></span> not associate anyone in His judgment.”",footnotes:345708:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “…and do not associate anyone in His judgement.”</span>
  18,27,"And read<sup>sg</sup> what was revealed to you from the Scripture of your Lord; none can change His words, and you will find no refuge apart from Him."
  18,28,"And keep<sup>sg</sup> yourself patient in the company of those who pray to their Lord morning and evening, seeking His Countenance<sup foot_note="365246">1</sup>, and do not turn your eyes away from them, seeking the adornment of the Earlier Life, and do not obey one whose heart We have made heedless of Our remembrance<sup foot_note="365247">2</sup> so that he has followed his own whim and his affairs have become confused.",footnotes:345709:Some schools of thought interpret this expression as ‘to please Him’.|345710:The Arabic word <i>zhikr</i> can be translated as ‘remembrance’, ‘reminder’ or ‘mentioning’.
  18,29,"And say<sup>sg</sup>, “Truth comes from your Lord. So whoever wills—let him believe, and whoever wills—let him disbelieve”. We have indeed prepared for the unjust a fire whose curtains have hemmed them in, and when they cry for relief, they are relieved with water like molten brass which scalds the faces. What a miserable drink, and what a bad place of rest!"
  18,30,"Indeed, those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds…<sup foot_note="365248">1</sup> —indeed, We do not waste the reward of whoever excels in work.",footnotes:345711:This sentence is left open-ended; according to some exegetes its predicate is sign 31.
  18,31,"For those, there are the Gardens of Eden,<small> </small>rivers flowing beneath them. In it, they are<sup foot_note="365249">1</sup> adorned with bracelets of gold and wear green garments of silk and brocade, reclining therein on couches. What a wonderful recompense, and what an excellent place of rest!",footnotes:345712:A grammatical shift to present tense, which serves to create a vivid portrait of future events.
  18,32,"And set<sup>sg</sup> forth for them a parable of two men. To one of them We gave two gardens of grapevines, and We bordered them with palm-trees and We placed between them vegetation."
  18,33,"Each of the two gardens brought forth its crops in full and failed not in the least therein, and We caused a river to burst forth throughout them."
  18,34,"And thus he had riches<sup foot_note="365250">1</sup>, so he said to his fellow as he conversed with him, “I am wealthier than you and greater in manpower.”",footnotes:345713:The Arabic word used is <i>thamar</i> which can be pronounced as <i>thumr</i> or <i>thumur</i> according to the majority of reciters, and in all cases it also means “produce”.
  18,35,"And he entered his garden while unjust to himself. He said, “I do not think that this will ever perish,"
  18,36,"and I do not think that the Hour is ever coming. And even if I am taken back to my Lord, I will most surely find something better than <span class="h">it<sup foot_note="365251">1</sup></span> as a destination.”",footnotes:345714:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…better than them both as…”</span>
  18,37,"His fellow said to him as he conversed with him, “Have you denied the One who created you from dust, then from a sperm-drop, then formed you as a man?"
  18,38,"But as for me, He is Allah, my Lord, and I never associate anyone with my Lord."
  18,39,"Now, if only when you had entered your garden you had said, 'As Allah wills; there is no power except through Allah,' although you see me inferior to you in wealth and children."
  18,40,"Hopefully my Lord will give me better than your garden and send upon it thunderbolts from the sky so that it becomes slippery soil,"
  18,41,"or its water sinks into the ground so that you become unable to draw it.”"
  18,42,"And ruin closed in on his riches and he began wringing his hands over what he had spent therein, as it lay fallen upon its trellises, saying, “I wish I had never associated anyone with my Lord.”"
  18,43,"And he had no battalion to support him apart from Allah, and he was unable to help himself."
  18,44,"In that situation, <span class="h">protection<sup foot_note="365252">1</sup></span> belongs to Allah, the Truth; He is better in rewarding and better in requiting.",footnotes:345715:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “In that situation, authority belongs to Allah…”</span>
  18,45,"And set<sup>sg</sup> forth for them a parable for the Earlier Life: <small>(it is)</small> like water that We sent down from the sky, then the plants of the earth were mixed with it, so it became debris scattered by the <span class="h">wind<sup foot_note="365253">1</sup></span>. And Allah<sup foot_note="365254">2</sup> has always had absolute power over everything.",footnotes:345716:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “winds.”</span>|345717:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.
  18,46,"Wealth and children are the adornments of the Earlier Life, while abiding deeds of righteousness are more rewardable by your<sup>sg</sup> Lord and worthier of being hoped for."
  18,47,"And on the day when We set the <span class="h">mountains<sup foot_note="365255">1</sup></span> in motion and you<sup>sg</sup> see the earth emerging; and We herded<sup foot_note="365256">2</sup> them together and left none of them behind.",footnotes:345718:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ibn Amer read it as: “And on the day when the mountains are set in motion…”</span>|345719:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  18,48,"And they were presented, lining up before your<sup>sg</sup> Lord. “Very truly, you<sup>pl</sup> have come to Us as We created you the first time. No indeed, you claimed We would never set an appointment for you.”"
  18,49,"And the record<sup foot_note="365257">1</sup> was placed, and you<sup>sg</sup> see<sup foot_note="365258">2</sup> the criminals fearful of whatever is in it, and they say, “Woe to us! What is with this record that leaves nothing, small or big, but it has enumerated it?” And they found<sup foot_note="365259">3</sup> whatever they had done present <small>(before them)</small>, for your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is never unjust to anyone.",footnotes:345720:Literally ‘scripture’.|345721:A grammatical shift to present tense, which serves to create a vivid portrait of future events.|345722:A grammatical shift, where the tense reverts to past tense.
  18,50,"And recall when We said to the angels, “Prostrate to Adam.” So they prostrated—but not Iblis<sup foot_note="365260">1</sup> . He was one of the unseen beings<sup foot_note="365261">2</sup>, so he defied the command of his Lord. Will you take him and his offspring as guardians apart from Me when they are an enemy to you? What a miserable bargain for the unjust!",footnotes:345723:Iblis is another name of Satan or <i>Shaytan</i>.|345724:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.
  18,51,"<span class="h">I<sup foot_note="365262">1</sup></span> did not make them witness the creation of the heavens and the earth, nor their own creation, and never was I <span class="h">to<sup foot_note="365263">2</sup></span> take the misguiding people for assistants.",footnotes:345725:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “We did not make them witness…”</span>|345726:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…and never were you to take the misguiding people for assistants.”</span>
  18,52,"And on the day when He <span class="h">says<sup foot_note="365264">1</sup></span>, “Call on My associates whom you have claimed.” So they called<sup foot_note="365265">2</sup> on them, but they did not respond to them. And We<sup foot_note="365266">3</sup> placed between them a barrier.",footnotes:345727:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “…when We say,”</span>|345728:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.|345729:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.
  18,53,"Then the criminals saw the Fire, so they realized that they were bound to tumble into it and they found no escape from it."
  18,54,"And We have elaborated in this Recital<sup foot_note="365267">1</sup> for mankind every kind of parable, but man has always been the most argumentative being.",footnotes:345730:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  18,55,"And what prevented mankind from attaining faith when guidance came to them and from seeking their Lord’s forgiveness? Unless they are waiting for the rule of <small>(God regarding)</small> the ancients to come upon them or to have the punishment come upon them in many <span class="h">types<sup foot_note="365268">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:345731:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “…or to have the punishment come upon them face to face.”</span>
  18,56,"And We do not send emissaries except as bearers of glad tidings and as forewarners. But those who have denied argue using falsehood in order to defeat the truth thereby, and they took<sup foot_note="365269">1</sup> My signs and what they were warned of for a joke.",footnotes:345732:A grammatical shift from present tense to past tense.
  18,57,"And who is more unjust than the one who was reminded of his Lord’s signs then disregarded them and forgot what his hands had put forth? Indeed, We have placed veils over their hearts, preventing them from comprehending it, and heaviness in their ears. And if you call them to guidance they will not be guided, ever."
  18,58,"And your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is the Forgiver, the Possessor of mercy. Were He to call them to account for what they have earned, He would hasten the punishment for them. Rather, for them is an appointment from which they will find no escape."
  18,59,"And those towns—We annihilated them when they committed injustices, and We set an appointment for their moment of <span class="h">annihilation<sup foot_note="365270">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:345733:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem read it as: “…and We set an appointment for their annihilation.”</span>
  18,60,"And recall when Moses said to his young assistant, “I will not give up until I reach the junction of the two seas, even if it takes me eons.”"
  18,61,"So when they reached the junction between them, they forgot about their fish, and so it found its way into the sea, slipping away."
  18,62,"Then when they went further, he said to his young assistant, “Bring us our lunch; very truly, we have encountered in our travel much fatigue.”"
  18,63,"He said, “Did you see when we rested by the rock? I forgot about the fish, and none except Satan made me forget it. And it found its way to the sea, wondrously.”"
  18,64,"He said, “That is what we were looking for.” And so they turned back, retracing their footsteps."
  18,65,"Then they came upon a servant of Our servants whom We had given mercy from Us and whom We had taught knowledge from Our Own."
  18,66,"Moses said to him, “May I follow you so that you may teach me some of the prudence you were taught?”"
  18,67,"He said, “Indeed, you<sup>sg</sup> will not be able to endure patiently with me."
  18,68,"And how can you endure patiently what you have not encompassed with knowledge?”"
  18,69,"He said, “You will find me patient, Allah willing, and I will not disobey you in any command of yours.”"
  18,70,"He said, “So if you<sup>sg</sup> follow me, then do not ask <span class="h">me<sup foot_note="365271">1</sup></span> about anything until I bring about a mention of it to you.”",footnotes:345734:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…then do not ever ask me about…”</span>
  18,71,"So they both set out until, when they had boarded the ark, he holed it. He said, “Did you hole it so as to <span class="h">drown<sup foot_note="365272">1</sup></span> its people? You have done something awful.”",footnotes:345735:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Did you hole it so that its people would drown?”</span>
  18,72,"He said, “Did I not tell you that you would not be able to endure patiently with me?”"
  18,73,"He said, “Do not rebuke me for forgetting, and do not make my matters difficult.”"
  18,74,"Then they both set out until, as soon as they encountered a boy, he killed him. He said, “Did you kill a <span class="h">sinless<sup foot_note="365273">1</sup></span> self<sup foot_note="365274">2</sup> which killed no one? Most surely, you have done something dreadful.”",footnotes:345736:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Abu Ja’far and Roways read it as: “Did you kill an inherently sinless self…”</span>|345737:Literally, a ‘pure’ self.
  18,75,"He said, “Did I not tell you that you would not be able to endure patiently with me?”"
  18,76,"He said, “If I ask you about anything after this, then do not keep company with me; certainly, by then you would have had enough of an excuse from me.”"
  18,77,"So they both set out until, when they reached the people of a town, they asked them for food, but they refused to offer them hospitality. There they found a wall tending to collapse, so he repaired it. He said, “If you wanted, you could have <span class="h">charged<sup foot_note="365275">1</sup></span> a reward for it.”",footnotes:345738:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “He said, ‘If you had wanted, you could have taken a reward for it.’”</span>
  18,78,"He said, “This is the parting between you and me. I will tell you the interpretation of what you were unable to endure patiently."
  18,79,"As for the ark, it belonged to some destitute people working at sea, so I wanted to make it defective, for there was a king coming after them, seizing every ark by force."
  18,80,"And as for the boy, his parents were believers and we feared he would overwhelm them with transgression and denial."
  18,81,"So we wanted their Lord to replace him with someone of better purity and nearer to mercy."
  18,82,"And as for the wall, it belonged to two orphaned boys in the city, and beneath it was a treasure that belonged to them, and their father was a righteous man, so your Lord desired that they attain their full strength and <small>(then)</small> extract their treasure—a mercy from your Lord. And I never did it of my own accord. This is the interpretation of what you were unable to endure patiently.”"
  18,83,"And they ask you<sup>sg</sup> about Zul-Qarnayn. Say, “I will read for you an account of him as a reminder.”"
  18,84,"Indeed, We empowered him in the land and brought him all kinds of means."
  18,85,"So he pursued a certain course"
  18,86,"until, when he had reached the setting of the sun, he found it setting in a <span class="h">murky<sup foot_note="365276">1</sup></span> spring, and found a people in its vicinity. We said, “O Zul-Qarnayn, you may either punish or else treat them kindly.”",footnotes:345739:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Hafs and Ya’qub read it as: “…in a hot spring,”</span>
  18,87,"He said, “As for the one who has committed injustices, we will punish him, then he will be returned to his Lord and He will punish him with a dreadful punishment."
  18,88,"But as for the one who has attained faith and has acted righteously, then for him is the excellent <small>(reward)</small> as <span class="h">repayment<sup foot_note="365277">1</sup></span>, and we will speak to him with ease regarding our command.”",footnotes:345740:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer, Shu’ba and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…then for him is the repayment for the excellent (deed), and we will…”</span>
  18,89,"Then he pursued a course"
  18,90,"until, when he reached the rising of the sun, he found it rising on a people for whom We had provided no shelter from it."
  18,91,"So it was. And surely We encompassed what he had with knowledge."
  18,92,"Then he pursued a course"
  18,93,"until, when he reached the point separating the two barriers, he found beside them a people who could barely <span class="h">comprehend<sup foot_note="365278">1</sup></span> any word.",footnotes:345741:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…who could barely make others comprehend any word.”</span>
  18,94,"They said, “O Zul-Qarnayn, Gog and Magog are corrupting the land, so can we make for you a tribute on condition that you build a barrier between us and them?”"
  18,95,"He said, “What my Lord has empowered me with is better. <small>(Just)</small> assist me with <small>(man)</small> power, and I will set a barricade between you<sup>pl</sup> and them."
  18,96,"Bring me blocks of iron.” Then when he had leveled up between the two cliffs, he said, “Blow.” And having turned it into a fire, he said, “Bring me tar to pour over it.”"
  18,97,"So neither could they climb it, nor could they penetrate it."
  18,98,"He said, “This is a mercy from my Lord; but when the promise of my Lord comes true, He will turn it into a flat <span class="h">surface<sup foot_note="365279">1</sup></span>. And the promise of my Lord has always been true.”",footnotes:345742:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…turn it into rubble.”</span>
  18,99,"And We left<sup foot_note="365280">1</sup> them surging upon one another on that day, and the Trumpet was blown and We gathered them together.",footnotes:345743:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  18,100,"And We displayed Hell to the deniers on that day in full display—"
  18,101,"those whose eyes were covered from My Reminder and were unable to hear."
  18,102,"Did those who have denied think that they could take My servants for masters apart from Me? Indeed, We have prepared Hell for the hospitality of the deniers."
  18,103,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Shall We inform you<sup>pl</sup> of the biggest losers regarding deeds?"
  18,104,"Those whose efforts in the Earlier Life have gone astray, while they assume that they are doing well.”"
  18,105,"Those are the ones who denied the signs of their Lord and the meeting with Him, so their deeds were nullified, and on the Day of Resurrection We will consider them of no weight."
  18,106,"That is their repayment—Hell—on account of their denial and their taking My signs and My messengers in mockery."
  18,107,"Indeed, those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—the Gardens of Paradise have always been there for their hospitality,"
  18,108,"abiding therein, never seeking to leave it."
  18,109,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “If the sea were to become ink for the words of my Lord, the sea would run out before the words of my Lord ran out, even if We were to bring the like of it in replenishment.”"
  18,110,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Indeed, I am only a human being like you<sup>pl</sup>. It is revealed to me that your god is One God, so whoever expects to meet his Lord, let him do righteous work and never associate anyone in the worship of his Lord.”"
  19,1,"Kāf, Hā Yā, ‘Ain, Sād."
  19,2,"A reminder of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord's mercy towards His servant Zechariah,"
  19,3,"when he called out to his Lord a call in seclusion."
  19,4,"He said, “My Lord, my bones have become feeble and my hair is aflame with gray, and never, in calling upon You my Lord, have I been wretched."
  19,5,"And indeed, I am afraid of what my protégés will do when I am gone, for my wife has always been barren. So grant me from Yourself a guardian"
  19,6,"to inherit from me and inherit from Jacob's folk, and make him, my Lord, pleasing.”"
  19,7,"“O Zechariah, indeed, We give you glad tidings of a boy whose name is John; We have never made anyone similar to him<sup foot_note="365281">1</sup> before.”",footnotes:345744:At-Tabari mentioned that some exegetes said that among the meanings of the Arabic word “<i>sameyya</i>” is ‘someone with the same name’, so they considered him to be the first ever to be named as such.
  19,8,"He said, “My Lord, how can I have a boy when my wife has always been barren and I have become decrepit with old age?”"
  19,9,"He said, “Thus said your Lord, `It is easy for Me, and <span class="h">I<sup foot_note="365282">1</sup></span> have certainly created you before when you were nothing.'”",footnotes:345745:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…and We have certainly created you…”</span>
  19,10,"He said, “My Lord, give me a sign.” He said, “Your sign is that you do not speak to people for three nights, <small>(despite)</small> being in perfect shape.”"
  19,11,"So he came out to his people from the sanctuary and signaled to them to exalt <small>(God)</small>, morning and evening."
  19,12,"“O John, hold on to the Scripture firmly,” and We gave him wise judgment in his youth"
  19,13,"and tenderness from Us and purity, and he was mindful <small>(of God)</small>,"
  19,14,"and was very kind to his parents, and he was never a disobedient coercer."
  19,15,"And peace be upon him the day he was born and the day he dies and the day he is resurrected alive."
  19,16,"And remember<sup>sg</sup> in the Scripture Mary, when she secluded herself from her family in an eastern location."
  19,17,"And she took a cover for herself away from them, and We sent to her Our spirit, so He appeared to her as a human being in perfect shape."
  19,18,"She said, “I seek refuge from you with the All-Merciful, if you are mindful <small>(of God)</small>.”"
  19,19,"He said, “I am only a messenger of your Lord to <span class="h">grant<sup foot_note="365283">1</sup></span> you a pure boy.”",footnotes:345746:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Warsh, Abu Amr, Ya’qub and Qaloun, in one of his narrations, read it as: “…of your Lord so that He may grant you…”</span>
  19,20,"She said, “How can I have a boy when no human being has touched me, nor have I ever been a harlot?”"
  19,21,"He said, “Thus said your Lord, `It is easy for Me, and We will make him a sign for humanity and a mercy from Us, and it has been a matter already decreed.'”"
  19,22,"So she carried him and secluded herself with him in a remote place."
  19,23,"Then the birth pangs compelled her to come to the trunk of the palm tree. She said, “If only I had died before this and been a thing forgotten, completely forgotten!”"
  19,24,"So he called her from beneath <span class="h">her<sup foot_note="365284">1</sup></span>: “Be not sad; your Lord has made a stream beneath you.",footnotes:345747:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer, Shu’ba and Roways read it as: “So the one beneath her called her:”</span>
  19,25,"And shake the trunk of the palm tree towards <span class="h">you—it<sup foot_note="365285">1</sup></span> will drop ripe dates upon you.”",footnotes:345748:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…it (masculine – referring to the trunk) will drop…” All others read it as: “…it (feminine – referring to the palm tree itself) will drop...”</span>
  19,26,"“So eat and drink and let your eye be comforted, but if you see any human being, say, ‘I have vowed a fast to the All-Merciful, so I will not speak to any human today.'”"
  19,27,"Then she came to her people, carrying him. They said, “O Mary, you have done something terrible."
  19,28,"O sister of Aaron<sup foot_note="365286">1</sup>, neither was your father an evil man, nor was your mother a harlot.”",footnotes:345749:Aaron, to Jews, was an example of pious people who repent after sinning.
  19,29,"So she pointed to him. They said, “How can we speak to an infant in the cradle?”"
  19,30,"He said, “I am Allah's servant. He has brought me the Scripture and has made me a prophet."
  19,31,"And He has made me blessed wherever I may be and has enjoined upon me prayer and purifying charity<sup foot_note="365287">1</sup> so long as I live.",footnotes:345750:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  19,32,"And He has made me very kind to my mother and has not made me a wretched coercer."
  19,33,"And peace be upon me the day I was born and the day I die and the day I get resurrected alive.”"
  19,34,"That is Jesus, son of Mary—the <span class="h">word<sup foot_note="365288">1</sup></span> of truth about which they are skeptical.",footnotes:345751:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Ibn Amer, Asem and Ya’qub read it as: “…son of Mary; (that is) the word of truth…”</span>
  19,35,"Never was it for Allah to have any offspring—Highly Exalted is He; whenever He decrees a matter, He only says to it, “Be,” and so it is."
  19,36,"“And indeed, Allah is my Lord and your<sup>pl</sup> Lord, so worship Him; this is a straight path.”"
  19,37,"But the parties differed among themselves, so woe to those who have denied from the spectacle of a great day."
  19,38,"How well they shall hear and see on the day they come to Us! But the unjust are today in evident misguidance."
  19,39,"And warn<sup>sg</sup> them of the Day of Regret, when the matter has been concluded. Yet they are in oblivion, and they do not believe."
  19,40,"Indeed, We—We alone—will inherit the earth and everyone on it, and to Us they will be <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365289">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:345752:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…and to Us they return.”</span>
  19,41,"And mention<sup>sg</sup> in the Scripture Abraham; he was indeed an unwavering believer <small>(and)</small> a prophet."
  19,42,"Recall when he said to his father, “O my father, why do you worship what can neither hear nor see nor avail you anything?"
  19,43,"O my father, most surely there has come to me of knowledge what has never come to you, so follow me and I will guide you to a straight path."
  19,44,"O my father, do not worship Satan; indeed Satan has always been disobedient to the All-Merciful."
  19,45,"O my father, indeed I fear that a punishment from the All-Merciful may touch you so that you would become an ally for Satan.”"
  19,46,"He said, “Are you renouncing my gods, O Abraham? If you do not desist, I will certainly stone you, so leave me for a long while.”"
  19,47,"He said, “Peace be upon you; I will ask my Lord to forgive you; indeed, He has always been gracious to me."
  19,48,"And I shall withdraw from you<sup>pl</sup> and from what you<sup>pl</sup> call upon apart from Allah, and I will call upon my Lord; hopefully, in calling upon my Lord, I shall never be wretched.”"
  19,49,"So when he withdrew from them and what they worshiped apart from Allah, We granted him Isaac and Jacob, and each We made a prophet."
  19,50,"And We granted them of Our mercy and gave them a high and true renown."
  19,51,"And mention<sup>sg</sup> in the Scripture Moses. He was indeed a sincere, chosen <span class="h">one<sup foot_note="365290">1</sup></span>, and he was a messenger <small>(and)</small> a prophet.",footnotes:345753:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “He was indeed sincere, and he was a messenger…”</span>
  19,52,"And We called out to him from the right side of Mount Tur, and brought him near in communion."
  19,53,"And We granted him, of Our mercy, his brother Aaron as a prophet."
  19,54,"And mention in the Scripture Ishmael; he was indeed true to his promise, and he was a messenger <small>(and)</small> a prophet."
  19,55,"And he used to command his family to prayer and purifying charity<sup foot_note="365291">1</sup>, and with his Lord he was always rendered pleased.",footnotes:345754:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  19,56,"And mention in the Scripture Enoch; he was indeed an unwavering believer <small>(and)</small> a prophet."
  19,57,"And We raised him to a high position."
  19,58,"Those are the ones whom Allah<sup foot_note="365292">1</sup> blessed of the prophets from the offspring of Adam, and from those We<sup foot_note="365293">2</sup> carried with Noah, and from the offspring of Abraham and Israel, and from those We guided and selected. Whenever the signs<sup foot_note="365294">3</sup> of the All-Merciful<sup foot_note="365295">4</sup> were recited to them, they would fall down prostrating and weeping.",footnotes:345755:A grammatical shift from 1st person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.|345756:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.|345757:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i>(singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i>means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.|345758:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.
  19,59,"Then they were succeeded by generations who wasted the prayers and followed desires, and thus they will encounter <small>(the sequel of their)</small> delusion—"
  19,60,"except for whoever repented and believed and acted righteously, for those shall <span class="h">enter<sup foot_note="365296">1</sup></span> the Garden and shall not be dealt with unjustly in any way—",footnotes:345759:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Shu’ba, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…shall be entered into the Garden…”</span>
  19,61,"the Gardens of Eden which have been promised by the All-Merciful to His servants in the hidden realm; indeed, His promise has ever been coming true."
  19,62,"Therein they hear no idle talk, but only peace. And therein they have their own provision, morning and evening."
  19,63,"Such is the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> which We give as inheritance to whoever of Our servants who has been mindful <small>(of God)</small>."
  19,64,"“And we<sup foot_note="365297">1</sup> do not descend except by the command of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord; to Him belongs whatever is before us and whatever is behind us and whatever is between them, and your Lord has never been forgetful.”",footnotes:345760:Gabriel speaks about himself and about the angels.
  19,65,"Lord of the heavens and the earth and whatever is between them, so worship Him and persevere in worshiping Him. Do you know of anyone similar to Him?"
  19,66,"And man says, “Can it be that <span class="h">when<sup foot_note="365298">1</sup></span> I am dead, I will be brought out alive?”",footnotes:345761:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Zekwan, in one of his narrations, read it as: “…says, ‘When I am dead, will I be brought out alive?’”</span>
  19,67,"Does man not remember that We created him earlier when he was nothing?"
  19,68,"By your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, We will surely herd them and the devils, then We will surely bring them around Hell on their knees."
  19,69,"Then out of every sect We will surely snatch those most defiant to the All-Merciful."
  19,70,"Then <small>(they will realize that)</small> We surely know better of those who are most deserving to roast in it."
  19,71,"But every single one of you is bound to approach it; this has been an unavoidable decree of your Lord."
  19,72,"Then We<sup foot_note="365299">1</sup> <span class="h">deliver<sup foot_note="365300">2</sup></span> those who were mindful <small>(of God)</small> and leave the unjust in it on their knees.",footnotes:345762:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.|345763:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “Then We save those who…”</span>
  19,73,"And when Our signs<sup foot_note="365301">1</sup> are read to them, evident, those who have denied say to those who have attained faith, “Which of the two groups is better in <span class="h">position<sup foot_note="365302">2</sup></span> and fairer in company?”",footnotes:345764:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.|345765:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “‘Which of the two groups has a better dwelling place and is fairer in company?’”</span>
  19,74,"And how many a generation have We annihilated before them who surpassed them in riches and splendor?"
  19,75,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Whoever has been in utter misguidance, may the All-Merciful fully extend for him<sup foot_note="365303">1</sup> .” Until, when they see what they were promised—either punishment or the Hour—then they will know who was in a worse position and weaker as an army.",footnotes:345766:In wealth and time.
  19,76,"And Allah increases in guidance those who seek guidance. And abiding deeds of righteousness are more rewardable by your Lord and better in return."
  19,77,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> seen the one who denied Our signs and said, “I will most surely be given wealth and children”?"
  19,78,"Has he viewed the hidden realm, or has he taken with the All-Merciful<sup foot_note="365304">1</sup> a covenant?",footnotes:345767:A grammatical shift from 1st person to 3rd person.
  19,79,"But no! We will write what he says and keep extending the agony for him exceedingly,"
  19,80,"and we will inherit from him whatever he says, and he will come to Us solitary."
  19,81,"And they took, apart from Allah, other gods to be a source of might for them."
  19,82,"But no! They will deny their worship of them and become opponents against them."
  19,83,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen that We have dispatched the devils against the deniers, exciting them with incitement?"
  19,84,"So do not hurry about them; indeed, We are only counting <small>(down)</small> for them precisely."
  19,85,"On a day when We herd the ones who were mindful <small>(of God)</small> to the All-Merciful<sup foot_note="365305">1</sup> as a delegation,",footnotes:345768:A grammatical shift from 1st person to 3rd person.
  19,86,"and flock the criminals into Hell, thirsty,"
  19,87,"with no power of intercession—except for the one who had taken with the All-Merciful a covenant."
  19,88,"And they said, “The All-Merciful has taken <small>(for himself)</small> offspring.”"
  19,89,"You<sup foot_note="365306">1</sup> have<sup>pl</sup> come up with something monstrous!",footnotes:345769:A grammatical shift from 3<sup>rd </sup>person to 2person to 2<sup>nd</sup> person. person..
  19,90,"The heavens almost rupture at it, and the earth splits and the mountains fall, crumbling:"
  19,91,"that they have attributed a son to the All-Merciful!"
  19,92,"And in no way is it fitting for the All-Merciful to take <small>(for Himself)</small> a son."
  19,93,"There is none in the heavens and the earth but is bound to come to the All-Merciful as a servant."
  19,94,"He has enumerated them and counted them precisely."
  19,95,"And each one of them is bound to come to Him on the Day of Resurrection solitary."
  19,96,"Indeed, those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—the All-Merciful will give them love."
  19,97,"So indeed, We have made it easy in your<sup>sg</sup> tongue, that you may give glad tidings to the ones who were mindful <small>(of God)</small> and warn with it a hostile people."
  19,98,"And how many a generation have We annihilated before them? Can you feel a single one of them or hear from them the slightest whisper?"
  20,1,"Tâ Ha."
  20,2,"We have not sent down the Recital<sup foot_note="365307">1</sup> upon you<sup>sg</sup> for you to be wretched,",footnotes:345770:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  20,3,"but only as a reminding for one who fears."
  20,4,"A bestowal from on high by the One Who created the earth and the highest heavens—"
  20,5,"the All-Merciful; on the Throne He settled<sup foot_note="365308">1</sup> .",footnotes:345771:How He settled is beyond human understanding.
  20,6,"To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth and whatever is between them and whatever is beneath the ground."
  20,7,"And if you<sup>sg</sup> speak aloud, indeed, He knows the secret and the most hidden."
  20,8,"Allah—there is no god but He; to him belong the most beautiful names."
  20,9,"And has the story of Moses reached you<sup>sg</sup>?"
  20,10,"When he saw a fire, so he said to his family, “Stay; I have noticed a fire; perhaps I can bring you<sup>pl</sup> a torch therefrom or find some guidance by the fire.”"
  20,11,"So when he reached it, he was called, “O Moses."
  20,12,"Indeed, I—I am your Lord. So take off your sandals; you are indeed in the sacred valley of Tuwa."
  20,13,"And <span class="h">I<sup foot_note="365309">1</sup></span> have chosen you, so listen to what is revealed.",footnotes:345772:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “And We have indeed chosen you,”</span>
  20,14,"Indeed I—I alone—am Allah. There is no God but I, so worship Me and establish the prayer for My remembrance."
  20,15,"The Hour is indeed coming—I almost hide it—so that every single self is paid for what it endeavors."
  20,16,"So let not the one who denies it and has been following his own whim bar you from it, lest you fall <small>(into doom)</small>."
  20,17,"And what is that in your right-hand, O Moses?”"
  20,18,"He said, “This is my staff. I lean on it, and I beat down <small>(leaves)</small> for my sheep with it, and I have other uses for it.”"
  20,19,"He said, “Cast it, O Moses.”"
  20,20,"So he cast it, and thereupon it became a moving serpent."
  20,21,"He said, “Pick it up and be not afraid; We will restore it to its original condition."
  20,22,"And press your hand to your side; it will come out white without any bad affliction—another sign,"
  20,23,"that We may show you of Our greatest signs."
  20,24,"Go to Pharaoh; indeed, he has exceeded all limits.”"
  20,25,"He said, “My Lord, expand my chest for me,"
  20,26,"and ease my mission for me,"
  20,27,"and untie the knot from my tongue"
  20,28,"so that they can comprehend my speech,"
  20,29,"and appoint for me an assistant from my family:"
  20,30,"Aaron, my brother;"
  20,31,"strengthen me with him"
  20,32,"and associate him with me in my <span class="h">mission<sup foot_note="365310">1</sup></span>,",footnotes:345773:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “….my brother, (so that) I (can) strengthen myself with him <sub><small>32 </small></sub>32 and (so that) I (can) associate him with me in my mission.”</span>
  20,33,"that we may exalt You much"
  20,34,"and remember You much."
  20,35,"Indeed, You have always been All-Seeing of us.”"
  20,36,"He said, “You<sup>sg</sup> have been granted your request, O Moses."
  20,37,"And most surely, We have conferred favor upon you on another occasion,"
  20,38,"when We revealed to your mother what was revealed:"
  20,39,"‘Throw him in the coffer then throw it into the waters, so that the waters will cast it onto the bank where an enemy of Mine and an enemy of his will pick him up.' For I bestowed upon you love from Me and so that you may be <span class="h">modeled<sup foot_note="365311">1</sup></span> before My eye.",footnotes:345774:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…and (I said): may you be modeled before My eye.”</span>
  20,40,"Recall your sister walking along and saying, ‘Shall I tell you about someone who can foster him?' So We returned you to your mother, that her eye may be comforted and <small>(that she may)</small> not grieve. And you killed a person, but We delivered you from stress and We tested you thoroughly. Then you stayed for years among the people of Midian. Then you came as ordained, O Moses."
  20,41,"And I modeled you for Myself."
  20,42,"Go<sup>sg</sup>, you and your brother, with My signs, and do<sup>dl</sup> not slacken in remembering Me."
  20,43,"Go<sup>dl</sup> to Pharaoh—he has indeed exceeded all limits—"
  20,44,"but say<sup>dl</sup> a lenient word to him, that he may remind himself or be fearful.”"
  20,45,"They said, “Our Lord, we fear he may persecute us or exceed all limits.”"
  20,46,"He said, “Be not afraid; I am indeed with you<sup>dl</sup>, hearing and seeing."
  20,47,"So approach<sup>dl</sup> him and say, `We<sup>dl</sup> are the messengers of your Lord, so send the Children of Israel with us and do not punish them; we have surely brought you a sign from your Lord, for peace is upon whoever has followed the guidance."
  20,48,"It has indeed been revealed to us that punishment falls upon whoever has disbelieved and turned away.'”"
  20,49,"He said, “So who is your<sup>dl</sup> Lord, O Moses?”"
  20,50,"He said, “Our Lord is the One who gave everything its creation then guided <small>(it)</small>.”"
  20,51,"He said, “So what about the former generations?”"
  20,52,"He said, “Knowledge thereof is with my Lord in a record<sup foot_note="365312">1</sup> ; my Lord never goes astray nor does He forget.”",footnotes:345775:Literally ‘scripture’.
  20,53,"<small>(He is)</small> the One who has made the earth a <span class="h">cradle<sup foot_note="365313">1</sup></span> for you<sup>pl</sup> and traced in it ways for you<sup>pl</sup>, and sent down from the sky water with which We<sup foot_note="365314">2</sup> brought out pairs of diverse plants.",footnotes:345776:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…a resting place for you…”</span>|345777:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.
  20,54,"Eat<sup>pl</sup> and pasture your livestock. Most surely, in that are signs for ones endowed with intelligence."
  20,55,"From it We created you<sup>pl</sup>, and into it We return you, and from it We bring you out once again."
  20,56,"And very truly We showed him all of Our signs, but he disbelieved and refused."
  20,57,"He said, “Have you come to us to evict us from our land with your sorcery, O Moses?"
  20,58,"We will most surely bring you sorcery like it; so make between us and you an appointment which we <span class="h">will<sup foot_note="365315">1</sup></span> not break—neither us nor you—in a suitable place.”",footnotes:345778:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…we should not fail…”</span>
  20,59,"He said, “Your<sup>pl</sup> appointment is the day of the festival, so let the people be herded together at forenoon.”"
  20,60,"Then Pharaoh turned away and put together his plot, and then he came."
  20,61,"Moses said to them, “Woe to you<sup>pl</sup>. Do not fabricate lies against Allah or He will destroy you<sup>pl</sup> with a punishment, and surely, the one who fabricates lies is bound to fail.”"
  20,62,"Then they disagreed with each other about their matter and conversed secretly."
  20,63,"They said, “These two are nothing <span class="h">but<sup foot_note="365316">1</sup></span> sorcerers who want to evict you from your land with their sorcery and abolish your exemplary way of life.",footnotes:345779:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs and Ibn Kathir read it as: “They said, ‘Most surely, these two are sorcerers…’”</span>
  20,64,"So <span class="h">decide<sup foot_note="365317">1</sup></span> your<sup>pl</sup> plot, then come, lined up <small>(in ranks)</small>; and the one who gains the upper hand is surely bound to succeed today.”",footnotes:345780:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “So put together your plot…”</span>
  20,65,"They said, “O Moses, either you cast or we will be the first to cast.”"
  20,66,"He said, “Rather, you<sup>pl</sup> cast.” And suddenly, their ropes and staffs were made to <span class="h">appear<sup foot_note="365318">1</sup></span> to him, because of their sorcery, to be slithering.",footnotes:345781:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Zekwan and Rouh read it as: “…their ropes and staffs appeared to him…”</span>
  20,67,"So Moses felt apprehensive within himself."
  20,68,"We said, “Be not afraid; yousg are the highest."
  20,69,"And cast what is in your right hand—it will <span class="h">swallow<sup foot_note="365319">1</sup></span> what they have crafted; what they have crafted is only a <span class="h">sorcerer’s<sup foot_note="365320">2</sup></span> trickery, for the sorcerer will not succeed wherever he may go.”",footnotes:345782:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Zekwan read it as: “And cast what is in your right hand, to swallow…”</span>|345783:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…a sorcery trickery,”</span>
  20,70,"So the sorcerers fell down prostrate. They said, “We have attained faith in the Lord of Aaron and Moses.”"
  20,71,"He said, “Have you<sup>pl</sup> attained faith in him before I have given you permission? He must be your chief who has taught you sorcery. So I will most surely cut off your hands and your feet on alternate sides, and I will most surely crucify you on the trunks of the palm-trees. Then you will most surely know which of us is more severe in punishment and more lasting.”"
  20,72,"They said, “We will not prefer you over what has come to us of evident proofs nor <small>(over)</small> the One Who originated us, so decree whatever you decree; you can only decree for this Earlier Life."
  20,73,"We have indeed attained faith in our Lord so that He may forgive us our offenses and what you have compelled us to practice of sorcery, for Allah is better and more lasting.”"
  20,74,"Indeed, whoever comes to his Lord as a criminal, then surely for him is Hell, where he neither dies nor lives."
  20,75,"But whoever comes to Him as a believer, having done righteous deeds, then for those<sup foot_note="365321">1</sup> are the highest degrees <small>(of rank)</small>:",footnotes:345784:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  20,76,"Gardens of Perpetuity beneath which rivers flow, abiding therein, for that is the repayment of the one who purifies himself."
  20,77,"And very truly, We revealed to Moses: “Journey by night with My servants and strike for them a dry road across the sea. You will not <span class="h">be<sup foot_note="365322">1</sup></span> afraid of being overtaken nor apprehensive.”",footnotes:345785:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “Be not afraid of being overtaken…”</span>
  20,78,"So Pharaoh pursued them with his troops, but there overwhelmed them of the waters that which overwhelmed them."
  20,79,"Thus Pharaoh led his people astray and never did he guide <small>(them)</small>."
  20,80,"O Children of Israel, <span class="h">We<sup foot_note="365323">1</sup></span> have surely saved you from your enemy, and have made an appointment <span class="h">with<sup foot_note="365324">2</sup></span> you by the right side of Mount Tûr, and sent down to you manna and quails.",footnotes:345786:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “I have surely saved you…”</span>|345787:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…and have promised you by the right…”</span>
  20,81,"Eat of the good things We have provided for you<sup>pl</sup>, but do not exceed the limits in it lest you deserve My wrath upon you, for the one upon whom My wrath is <span class="h">deserved<sup foot_note="365325">1</sup></span> has surely fallen.",footnotes:345788:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…lest My wrath descend upon you, for the one upon whom My wrath descends has surely fallen.”</span>
  20,82,"And very truly I am Forgiving towards the one who repented and attained faith and acted righteously and then remained guided."
  20,83,"“And what made you rush ahead of your people, O Moses?”"
  20,84,"He said, “They are following in my footsteps. And I hurried on to You, my Lord, that You may be well pleased.”"
  20,85,"He said, “Yet, We have surely tested your people in your absence, and the Samiri led them astray.”"
  20,86,"So Moses returned to his people, wrathful <small>(and)</small> sorrowful. He said, “O my people, did your Lord not promise you a good promise? Was the <small>(time of the)</small> covenant too long for you? Or did you want wrath from your Lord to descend upon you, so you broke your promise to me?”"
  20,87,"They said, “We did not break our promise to you by our choice, but we were made to <span class="h">carry<sup foot_note="365326">1</sup></span> burdens of the people’s ornaments, so we cast them and so did the Samiri cast.”",footnotes:345789:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr, Shu’ba, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Rouh and Khalaf read it as: “…but we carried burdens…”</span>
  20,88,"So he brought out for them a calf—a mere body with a lowing sound. And they<sup foot_note="365327">1</sup> said, “This is your god and the god of Moses, but he has forgotten.”",footnotes:345790:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  20,89,"Do they not see that it cannot return a word to them, nor does it possess for them harm or benefit?"
  20,90,"And Aaron had most surely said to them before, “O my people, you are indeed being tested by this, and indeed your Lord is the All-Merciful, so follow me and obey my command.”"
  20,91,"They said, “We will not give up consecrating it until Moses returns to us.”"
  20,92,"He said, “O Aaron, what prevented you, when you saw them going astray,"
  20,93,"from following me? Have you disobeyed my command?”"
  20,94,"He said, “O son of my mother, do not seize me by my beard nor by my head; I feared you would say, ‘You have caused division among the Children of Israel and have not regarded my word.'”"
  20,95,"He said, “What do you have to say, O Samiri?”"
  20,96,"He said, “I perceived what <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="365328">1</sup></span> did not perceive, so I grasped a handful from the messenger’s traces and I flung it away, and thus my soul prompted me.”",footnotes:345791:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…what you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> did not perceive…”</span>
  20,97,"He said, “Be gone! For indeed your lot in this life is to say, ‘No touching’, and indeed you have an appointment that you will not be allowed to <span class="h">break<sup foot_note="365329">1</sup></span>. And look at your god that you kept consecrating—we will certainly burn it <span class="h">up<sup foot_note="365330">2</sup></span> then blow it away completely into the waters.”",footnotes:345792:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…that you will not break.”</span>|345793:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “‘…we will certainly burn it then blow it…’”</span>
  20,98,"Surely your<sup>pl</sup> god is none but Allah, the One besides Whom there is no other god; He has embraced everything in knowledge."
  20,99,"Thus We narrate to you<sup>sg</sup> of the stories that have passed before, for We have brought you a Reminder from Us."
  20,100,"Whoever has disregarded it will indeed carry on the Day of Resurrection a burden,"
  20,101,"abiding<sup>pl</sup> in it, and how bad their load became<sup foot_note="365331">1</sup> on the Day of Resurrection—",footnotes:345794:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  20,102,"the day when the Trumpet is <span class="h">blown<sup foot_note="365332">1</sup></span>! And We herd the criminals on that day, blue,",footnotes:345795:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “…when We blow the Trumpet!”</span>
  20,103,"murmuring among themselves: “You<sup>pl</sup> have stayed only for ten.”"
  20,104,"We know better what they say, when the most exemplary of them in conduct says, “You<sup>pl</sup> have stayed for no more than a day.”"
  20,105,"And they ask you about the mountains. So say, “My Lord will blow them away"
  20,106,"and leave them as desolate waste."
  20,107,"You will see in them neither crookedness nor deviation.”"
  20,108,"On that day, they follow the caller without any crookedness, and voices were<sup foot_note="365333">1</sup> <small>(hushed)</small> in reverence to the All-Merciful, so that you<sup>sg</sup> hear nothing but a murmur.",footnotes:345796:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  20,109,"On that day, intercession does not avail except for the one permitted by the All-Merciful, and He was pleased for him to speak."
  20,110,"He knows what is before them and what is behind them, and they cannot encompass Him with knowledge."
  20,111,"And faces were humbleda to the Living One, the All-Sustaining, and surely whoever carried injustice is bound to fail."
  20,112,"But whoever does righteous deeds while being a believer, then he neither <span class="h">fears<sup foot_note="365334">1</sup></span> injustice nor curtailment.",footnotes:345797:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “…then he should neither fear injustice nor curtailment.”</span>
  20,113,"And thus We have sent it down as an Arabic Recital<sup foot_note="365335">1</sup>, and We have diversified the warnings in it, that perhaps they would become mindful <small>(of God)</small> or it would bring about in them a remembrance.",footnotes:345798:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  20,114,"Most high above all is Allah, the True King. Do<sup>sg</sup> not be hasty with the Recital<sup foot_note="365336">1</sup> before its revelation to you is <span class="h">concluded<sup foot_note="365337">2</sup></span>, and say, “My Lord, increase me in knowledge.”",footnotes:345799:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.|345800:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…before We conclude its revelation to you…”</span>
  20,115,"And most surely We covenanted with Adam before, but he forgot, and We found in him no resolve."
  20,116,"And recall when We said to the angels, “Prostrate yourselves to Adam.” So they prostrated themselves— but not Iblis<sup foot_note="365338">1</sup> ; he refused.",footnotes:345801:Iblis is another name of Satan or <i>Shaytan</i>.
  20,117,"So We said, “O Adam, indeed this is an enemy to you and to your spouse. So do not let him get you<sup>dl</sup> out of the Garden, for then you<sup>sg</sup> will<sup foot_note="365339">1</sup> suffer.",footnotes:345802:A grammatical shift from dual to singular.
  20,118,"In it, indeed, you<sup>sg</sup> will never go hungry nor be naked."
  20,119,"Nor will you be thirsty in it nor will you swelter.”"
  20,120,"But Satan whispered to him. He said, “O Adam, shall I show you the Tree of Immortality and a kingdom that never decays?”"
  20,121,"So they<sup>dl</sup> ate from it, whereupon their private parts became exposed to them, and they started covering themselves with the leaves of the Garden. Thus Adam disobeyed his Lord and was deluded."
  20,122,"Then his Lord recalled him and granted him repentance and accepted it from him and guided <small>(him)</small>."
  20,123,"He said, “Descend from it, all together, some of you as enemies of some others. But whenever guidance comes to you from Me, whoever follows My guidance will neither go astray nor suffer."
  20,124,"But whoever has disregarded My Reminder—for him is a miserable life, and We<sup foot_note="365340">1</sup> will herd him on the Day of Resurrection blind.”",footnotes:345803:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  20,125,"He said, “My Lord, why did You herd me blind though I used to see?”"
  20,126,"He said, “Just as Our signs came to you<sup>sg</sup> and you forgot them, today you will be forgotten.”"
  20,127,"And thus We repay the one who was an extremist and did not believe in the signs of his Lord. And surely the punishment of the Hereafter is more severe and more lasting."
  20,128,"Did it give them no guidance <small>(to learn)</small> how many generations before them We annihilated, amidst whose residences they walk? Indeed, in that are signs for the ones endowed with intelligence."
  20,129,"And were it not for a word that had preceded from your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, the inevitable would have happened, but <small>(there is)</small> a stated term."
  20,130,"So bear patiently what they say and exalt your<sup>sg</sup> Lord with praise before the rising of the sun and before its setting, and during the hours of the night exalt Him, and at the <small>(two)</small> ends of the day, that you may be well <span class="h">pleased<sup foot_note="365341">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:345804:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…that you may be rendered well pleased.”</span>
  20,131,"And never extend your eyes towards what We have given some classes of them to enjoy—the splendor<sup foot_note="365342">1</sup> of the Earlier Life—that We may test them thereby, for your Lord’s<sup foot_note="365343">2</sup> provision is better and more lasting.",footnotes:345805:Literally ‘flower’.|345806:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.
  20,132,"And command your people to prayer, and patiently adhere to it; We ask of you<sup>sg</sup> no provision; it is We who provide for you. For the future outcome is for mindfulness (of God)."
  20,133,"And they said, “If only he were to bring us a sign from his Lord!” Were they not given evidence of whatever is in the former scrolls?"
  20,134,"Had We annihilated them with a punishment before him, they would have said, “Our Lord, if only You had sent us a messenger so that we would have followed Your signs before we were humiliated and disgraced.”"
  20,135,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Everybody is waiting, so wait<sup>pl</sup>, for you will know who the people of the even path are and who was rightly-guided."
  21,1,"Mankind’s reckoning has drawn near, while they are in oblivion, disregarding <small>(it)</small>."
  21,2,"No fresh reminder comes to them from their Lord but they listen to it playfully,"
  21,3,"their hearts distracted. And secretly did the unjust converse, “Is this anything but a human being like you<sup>pl</sup>? Will you go along with sorcery while you see?”"
  21,4,"He <span class="h">said<sup foot_note="365344">1</sup></span>, “My Lord knows what is said in the heaven and the earth, for He is the All-Hearing, the All-Knowing.”",footnotes:345807:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Say<sup><small>sg</small></sup>”.</span>
  21,5,"But they said, “A jumble of dreams; rather, he fabricated it; rather, he is a poet, so let him bring us a sign like those sent to the ancients.”"
  21,6,"None of the towns We annihilated before them had believed. Will they, then, believe?"
  21,7,"And never did We send before you<sup>sg</sup> but men to whom We <span class="h">reveal<sup foot_note="365345">1</sup></span>, so ask the people of the Reminder if you<sup>pl</sup> do not know.",footnotes:345808:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as: “…to whom it is revealed, so ask…”</span>
  21,8,"And never did We make them a mere body<sup foot_note="365346">1</sup>, (ones) who eat<sup>pl</sup> no food, for never were they immortal.",footnotes:345809:A grammatical shift from plural to singular.
  21,9,"Then We fulfilled the promise to them, so We saved them together with whomever We will<sup foot_note="365347">1</sup>, and We annihilated the extremists.",footnotes:345810:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense.
  21,10,"Most surely, We have sent down to you<sup>pl</sup> a Scripture containing your reminder. Do you not reason?"
  21,11,"And how many an unjust town have We crushed and established thereafter another people?"
  21,12,"Thus when they sensed Our force, they immediately ran away from it."
  21,13,"Do not run, but come back to the luxuries you<sup>pl</sup> were immersed in, and your residences, that you may be questioned."
  21,14,"They said, “Woe to us; indeed, we have been unjust.”"
  21,15,"Thus this continued to be their cry until We made them extinguished ashes."
  21,16,"And in no way did We create the sky and the earth and what is between them playfully."
  21,17,"If We wanted amusement, We could have obtained it from very close to Us, were We to do so."
  21,18,"Rather, We hurl the truth against falsehood so that it crushes it, and thus it vanishes. And woe unto you<sup>pl</sup> for what you describe."
  21,19,"For to Him belongs whomever is in the heavens and the earth. And those in His presence are not too arrogant to worship Him, nor do they grow weary."
  21,20,"They give due exaltation <small>(to Him)</small> night and day, never tiring."
  21,21,"Or have they taken to themselves gods from the earth who <small>(can)</small> resurrect?"
  21,22,"If there were in them gods other than Allah, they would have surely become corrupted. So Highly Exalted is Allah, Lord of the Throne, far above what they describe."
  21,23,"He is not asked about what He does, but they shall be asked."
  21,24,"Or have they taken apart from Him other gods? Say, “Bring your<sup>pl</sup> proof; this<sup foot_note="365348">1</sup> <small> </small>is the reminder of those with me and the reminder of those before me.” Rather, most of them do not know the truth, so they disregard <small>(it)</small>.",footnotes:345811:This Qur’an.
  21,25,"And never did We send any messenger before you<sup>sg</sup> but <span class="h">We<sup foot_note="365349">1</sup></span> reveal<sup foot_note="365350">2</sup> to him that: “There is no god but I, so worship<sup>pl</sup> Me.”",footnotes:345812:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…but it is revealed to him…”</span>|345813:Frequently the Qur’an speaks about the prophets using present tense; this should be pondered by the reader.
  21,26,"Yet they said, “The All-Merciful has taken to himself offspring.” Highly Exalted is He; rather, they are honored servants"
  21,27,"who never speak before Him, and they only act on His command."
  21,28,"He knows what is before them and what is behind them, and they do not intercede except for those whom He approves, and they tremble in awe of Him."
  21,29,"And whoever of them says, “I am a god apart from Him,” We will repay him with Hell; thus We repay the unjust."
  21,30,"Do the deniers not see that the heavens and the earth were one mass, and then We tore them apart? And We made from water every living thing; will they not believe?"
  21,31,"And We put firm mountains on the earth, lest it sway with them; and We set broad pathways on it, that they might be guided."
  21,32,"And We made the sky a preserved ceiling, yet they disregard its signs."
  21,33,"And it is He who created the night and the day, and the sun and the moon, each floating in an orbit."
  21,34,"And never did We grant immortality to any human being before you<sup>sg</sup>. Should you die, are they then the immortal?"
  21,35,"Every single self is bound to taste death, for We test you<sup>pl</sup> with evil and good as a means of trial, and to Us you are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365351">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:345814:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…and to Us you return.”</span>
  21,36,"And when those who have denied see you<sup>sg</sup>, they treat you only with ridicule: “Is this the one who mentions your gods?” For of the reminder of the All-Merciful they themselves are deniers."
  21,37,"Man was created of haste. I will show you<sup>pl</sup> My signs, so do not ask Me to hasten."
  21,38,"And they say, “When will this promise come true, if you are truthful?”"
  21,39,"If those who have denied only knew the time when they will not be able to keep the Fire off their faces nor off their backs, nor will they be supported!"
  21,40,"Rather, it will come upon them suddenly and bewilder them, so they will not be able to repel it, nor will they be given respite."
  21,41,"And most surely <small>(other)</small> messengers before you<sup>sg</sup> were ridiculed, but those who mocked were surrounded by what they used to ridicule."
  21,42,"Say, “Who guards you by night and day from the All-Merciful?” But they disregard the reminder of their Lord."
  21,43,"Or do they have gods that can defend them against Us? They cannot support themselves, nor will they find anyone to side with them against Us."
  21,44,"Rather, We gave these people and their forefathers enjoyments until time grew long upon them. Do they not see how We gradually reduce the land from its extremities? Are they then the overcomers?"
  21,45,"Say, “Indeed, I am only warning you<sup>pl</sup> through revelation.” But the deaf cannot <span class="h">hear<sup foot_note="365352">1</sup></span> the call when they are being warned.",footnotes:345815:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “But you<sup><small> </small></sup>cannot make the deaf hear…”</span>
  21,46,"And if a whiff of your Lord’s punishment touches them, they say, “Woe to us, We have truly been unjust.”"
  21,47,"And We set up the scales of justice for the Day of Resurrection so that not a single self suffers the least injustice, and even if it be the weight of a mustard seed, We bring it forth. For sufficient are We as reckoners."
  21,48,"And very truly, We gave Moses and Aaron the Criterion and illumination and a reminder for the ones who were mindful <small>(of God)</small>:"
  21,49,"those who fear their Lord, though Unseen, and are apprehensive of the Hour."
  21,50,"And this <small>(too)</small> is a blessed Reminder that We have sent down. Are you<sup>pl</sup> going to reject it?"
  21,51,"And most surely, We brought Abraham his prudence before, and We well knew of him"
  21,52,"when he said to his father and his people, “What are these statues to which you are devoted?”"
  21,53,"They said, “We found our forefathers worshiping them.”"
  21,54,"He said, “You<sup>pl</sup> and your forefathers have been in evident misguidance.”"
  21,55,"They said, “Have you come to us with the truth, or are you one of the jesters?”"
  21,56,"He said, “Rather, your Lord is the Lord of the heavens and the earth, the One who originated them, and to that, I am one of those who bear witness."
  21,57,"And by Allah, I shall certainly plot against your human-shaped idols after you have turned away, fleeing.”"
  21,58,"So he reduced them into pieces, except for their biggest, that they may return to it."
  21,59,"They said, “Who did this to our gods? Indeed, he is certainly one of the unjust.”"
  21,60,"They said, “We heard a young man mentioning them; he is called Abraham.”"
  21,61,"They said, “So bring him before the eyes of the people, that they may witness.”"
  21,62,"They said, “Are you the one who did this to our gods, O Abraham?”"
  21,63,"He said, “Rather, it was this biggest of them that did it, so ask them, if they can talk.”"
  21,64,"So they turned to one another and said, “Indeed, you yourselves are the unjust.”"
  21,65,"But they reverted to their old ideas: “You<sup>sg</sup> certainly know well that these do not talk.”"
  21,66,"He said, “Do you worship, apart from Allah, what can neither benefit you in anything nor harm you?"
  21,67,"Fie on you and on what you worship apart from Allah. Do you not reason?”"
  21,68,"They said, “Burn him and support your gods, if you are going to act.”"
  21,69,"We said, “O fire, be cool and peaceful upon Abraham.”"
  21,70,"For they wanted to plot against him, so We made them the biggest losers."
  21,71,"And We delivered him and Lot to the land that We blessed for all <small>(people of all)</small> realms."
  21,72,"And We granted him Isaac and Jacob as an additional gift, and each We made righteous."
  21,73,"And We made them leaders, guiding by Our command, and We revealed to them <small>(the command of)</small> performing good works and establishing the prayer and bringing<sup foot_note="365353">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="365354">2</sup>, for of Us they were worshipers.",footnotes:345816:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|345817:The Arabic word used is z<i>akāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  21,74,"And Lot—We gave him wise judgment and knowledge, and We delivered him from the town that used to practice nasty things. They were indeed a wicked, defiantly disobedient people."
  21,75,"And We entered him into Our mercy; He is<sup foot_note="365355">1</sup> indeed one of the righteous.",footnotes:345818:Frequently the Qur’an speaks about the prophets using present tense; this should be pondered by the reader.
  21,76,"And Noah, when he called before, so We responded to him and delivered him and his family from the great calamity."
  21,77,"And We supported him against the people who disbelieved Our Signs; indeed, they were a wicked people, so We drowned them all."
  21,78,"And David and Solomon, when they gave judgment in the case of the field, when some people’s sheep wandered therein by night. And to their judgment We were witnesses."
  21,79,"Yet We made Solomon understand it, and to each We gave wise judgment and knowledge. And We subjected the mountains to give <small>(God)</small> due exaltation along with David, and the birds as well—surely We did."
  21,80,"And We taught him the making of shields for you<sup>pl</sup>, so that they may <span class="h">secure<sup foot_note="365356">1</sup></span> you from your violence, so are you then appreciative?",footnotes:345819:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba and Roways read it as: “…so that We may secure you…”All others except for Ibn ʻAmer, Hafs and Abu Jaʻfar read it as: “so that He may secure you…”</span>
  21,81,"And to Solomon the stormy <span class="h">wind<sup foot_note="365357">1</sup></span>, blowing at his command towards the land that We had blessed. And We well knew of everything.",footnotes:345820:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “winds”.</span>
  21,82,"And of the devils were some that would dive for him and perform other, lesser tasks, but We were preserving of them."
  21,83,"And Job, when he called upon his Lord: “Great harm has touched me, yet You are the Most Merciful of the merciful.”"
  21,84,"So We responded to him and lifted the harm which had afflicted him, and We brought him his family and their like with them—a mercy from Us, and a reminding for the worshipers."
  21,85,"And Ishmael and Enoch and Ezekiel; each is<sup foot_note="365358">1</sup> one of the steadfast.",footnotes:345821:Frequently the Qur’an speaks about the prophets using present tense; this should be pondered by the reader
  21,86,"And We entered them into Our mercy; indeed, they are<sup foot_note="365359">1</sup> of the righteous.",footnotes:345822:Frequently the Qur’an speaks about the prophets using present tense; this should be pondered by the reader
  21,87,"And Jonah, when he went off angrily and he thought that We would not restrain <span class="h">him<sup foot_note="365360">1</sup></span>. But then He cried out in the darkness<small>(es)</small>, “There is no god but You! Highly Exalted are You! Indeed, I have been one of the unjust!”",footnotes:345823:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…and he thought that he would not be restrained.”</span>
  21,88,"So We responded to him and delivered him from stress, for thus We save the <span class="h">believers<sup foot_note="365361">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:345824:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Shu’ba read it as: “…and thus the believers were saved.”</span>
  21,89,"And Zechariah, when he called out to his Lord, “My Lord, do not leave me solitary, while You are the best of inheritors.”"
  21,90,"So We responded to him and granted him John, and We rehabilitated his spouse for him. Indeed, they used to hasten towards good works and call upon Us wishfully and in awe, for they used to be reverent towards Us."
  21,91,"And she who guarded her chastity, so We breathed into her of Our Spirit and made her and her son a sign to <small>(all people of)</small> all realms."
  21,92,"Indeed, this community of yours<sup>pl</sup> is one community and I am your Lord, so worship Me."
  21,93,"But they tore themselves into sects; they are all returning to Us."
  21,94,"So whoever does righteous deeds and is a believer—his endeavor will never be denied. And indeed, We are writing it down for him."
  21,95,"And there is a ban on any town that We have annihilated—that they do not return,"
  21,96,"until, when Gog and Magog are <span class="h">opened<sup foot_note="365362">1</sup></span>, and they swarm down from every mound,",footnotes:345825:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…until, when Gog and Magog are opened wide…”</span>
  21,97,"and the true promise has drawn near— then, the sight<small>(s)</small> of those who denied glaze over: “Woe to us. We have been oblivious to this. Rather, we were unjust.”"
  21,98,"You<sup>pl</sup> and what you worship apart from Allah are indeed fuel for Hell. You are bound to approach it."
  21,99,"Had these been gods, they would not have approached it. And all will abide in it."
  21,100,"In it they wail, and in it they do not hear."
  21,101,"Indeed, those who deserved goodness from Us—those are kept away from it."
  21,102,"They do not hear its hissing, and in what their hearts have desired they abide."
  21,103,"The most supreme fear does not worry them, for the angels receive them: “This is your<sup>pl</sup> day which you were promised.”"
  21,104,"On the day when We fold the <span class="h">heaven<sup foot_note="365363">1</sup></span> as the scribe rolls up <span class="h">scriptures<sup foot_note="365364">2</sup></span>. Just as We began the first creation, We restore it—a promise from Us. We will indeed act.",footnotes:345826:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “On the day when the heaven is folded as the scribe…”</span>|345827:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “a scripture.”</span>
  21,105,"And most surely We have written in the Book<sup foot_note="365365">1</sup>, after the Reminder<sup foot_note="365366">2</sup>, that the land will be inherited by My righteous servants.",footnotes:345828:The Arabic word <i>Zabour</i> means ‘a book’ and it is the name of the book of David.|345829:The Torah.
  21,106,"Indeed, in this is a proclamation for people who are worshipers<small> (of Allah)</small>."
  21,107,"For We have not sent you but as a mercy to all realms."
  21,108,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “It is revealed to me that your<sup>pl</sup> God is but One God, so are you going to submit?”"
  21,109,"But if they turn away, say, “I have informed you sufficiently, although I do not know whether what you<sup>pl</sup> are promised is near or far."
  21,110,"Indeed, He knows whatever is said aloud of speech, and He knows whatever you<sup>pl</sup> conceal."
  21,111,"And I do not know whether it is perhaps a means of trial for you<sup>pl</sup>, and an enjoyment for a while.”"
  21,112,"He <span class="h">said<sup foot_note="365367">1</sup></span>, “My Lord, judge with justice.” “For our Lord is the All-Merciful, Whose help is sought against what you allege.”",footnotes:345830:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as: “Say<sup><small>sg</small></sup>,”</span>
  22,1,"O mankind, be mindful of your Lord. Indeed, the quaking of the Hour is something great."
  22,2,"On the day when youpl see it: every nursing female discards whatever she has nursed, and every pregnant female aborts her pregnancy, and you<sup>sg</sup> see mankind drunk, even though they are not drunk—but the punishment of Allah is severe."
  22,3,"And of mankind is one who argues about Allah without knowledge and follows every defiant Satan."
  22,4,"It was destined for him that whoever takes him as a guardian—he surely leads him astray and leads him to the punishment of the Blaze."
  22,5,"O mankind, if you are in doubt about the Resurrection—We have indeed created you from dust, then from a drop of semen, then from a clinging form, then from a lump of flesh, <small>(partly)</small> differentiated and <small>(partly)</small> undifferentiated, in order to clarify things for you. And We settle in the wombs whatever We will for a stated term, and then We bring you<sup>pl</sup> out as infants until you attain your full strength. And of you is one who is taken <small>(at death)</small>, and of you is one who is returned to the most abject age, so that he may not know anything after having known. And yousg see the land still, but when We send down water on it, it shakes and <span class="h">swells<sup foot_note="365368">1</sup></span> and germinates all kinds of lovely plant.",footnotes:345831:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…and becomes higher...”</span>
  22,6,"That is because indeed Allah is the Truth, and because indeed He gives life to the dead, and because indeed He is Powerful over everything."
  22,7,"And because the Hour is indeed coming—there is no doubt about it—and because indeed Allah resurrects those in the graves."
  22,8,"And of mankind is one who argues about Allah without knowledge or guidance or an illuminating scripture,"
  22,9,"turning aside in contempt, to make <small>(others)</small> <span class="h">stray<sup foot_note="365369">1</sup></span> from the way of Allah; for him in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> is disgrace, and on the Day of Resurrection We make him taste the punishment of burning:",footnotes:345832:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Roways read it as: “…to stray from the way of Allah;”</span>
  22,10,"“That is for what your<sup>sg</sup> hands<sup foot_note="365370">1</sup> have put forth, and because Allah is not a tyrant unto the servants.”",footnotes:345833:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 2<sup><small>nd</small></sup> person.
  22,11,"And of mankind is one who worships Allah on edge, so that if something good befalls him, he is reassured by it; but if a trial befalls him, he turns about-face, losing the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> and the hereafter; that is the evident loss."
  22,12,"Apart from Allah, he calls upon what can neither harm him nor benefit him; that is the extreme misguidance."
  22,13,"He calls upon one whose harm is closer than his benefit; truly, what a miserable patron, and truly, what a miserable consort."
  22,14,"Indeed, Allah enters those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds into Gardens beneath which rivers flow; indeed, Allah does whatever He wants."
  22,15,"Whoever has been thinking that Allah will not support him<sup foot_note="365371">1</sup> in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> and the Hereafter—let him extend a means<sup foot_note="365372">2</sup> to the sky, then cut <small>(it)</small> off, and see whether his plotting eliminates what enrages <small>(him)</small>.",footnotes:345834:Referring to Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him).|345835:Literally ‘rope’
  22,16,"And thus We sent it down as evident signs<sup foot_note="365373">1</sup>, for Allah guides whomever He wants.",footnotes:345836:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  22,17,"Indeed, those who have attained faith and those who have Judaized, and the Sabians<sup foot_note="365374">1</sup> and the Christians and the Zoroastrians<sup foot_note="365375">2</sup> and the Polytheists—indeed, Allah judges between them on the Day of Resurrection. Indeed, Allah is witness to everything.",footnotes:345837:The Sabians were a monotheistic religious community.|345838:Followers of an ancient Asian religion based on monotheism.
  22,18,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen that to Allah prostrates whoever is in the heavens and whoever is in the earth, and the sun and the moon and the stars and the mountains and the trees and the treading creatures and many of mankind? But many others deserved the punishment. And whomever Allah shames, there is none to honor him. Indeed, Allah does whatever He wills."
  22,19,"Here are two adversaries who have disputed regarding their Lord, so those who denied—garments of fire were tailored<sup foot_note="365376">1</sup> for them, with scalding water pouring over their heads,",footnotes:345839:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  22,20,"melting their insides and the skins."
  22,21,"And for them there are maces of iron;"
  22,22,"whenever they try to depart it out of anguish, they are driven back into it and <small>(told)</small>, “Taste<sup>pl</sup> the punishment of burning.”"
  22,23,"Indeed, Allah enters those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds into Gardens beneath which rivers flow, wherein they are decorated with bracelets of gold and <span class="h"><small>(with)</small><sup foot_note="365377">1</sup></span> pearls, and their garments therein are of silk.",footnotes:345840:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Nafie’, Ya’qub and Abu Ja’far read it as: “… with bracelets of gold and (of) pearls,”</span>
  22,24,"And they were guided to the best of words, and they were guided to the path of the Praiseworthy."
  22,25,"Indeed, those who have denied and bar <small>(others)</small> from the way of Allah and from the Inviolable Mosque, which We have designated for all mankind <span class="h">equally<sup foot_note="365378">1</sup></span>, <small>(including)</small> the one who consecrates himself therein and the visitor. And whoever wants any blasphemy unjustly therein—We will make him taste of a painful punishment.",footnotes:345841:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as: “which We have designated for all mankind, equally for the one who consecrates himself therein and the visitor. And whoever…”</span>
  22,26,"And recall when We located the House for Abraham: “Do not associate anything with Me, and cleanse My House for the circumambulators and those who stand to pray and those who kneel and prostrate."
  22,27,"And announce the pilgrimage to mankind—they will come to you<sup>sg</sup> on foot and on every lean mount; they will come from every distant pathway,"
  22,28,"that they may witness benefits for themselves and remember<sup foot_note="365379">1</sup> the name of Allah during the known days<sup foot_note="365380">2</sup> for providing them with livestock animals. So eat<sup>pl</sup> of it and feed the unfortunate poor.",footnotes:345842:The Arabic word used also means ‘mention’.|345843:The days of Pilgrimage.
  22,29,"Then let them end their untidiness and let them fulfill their vows and let them circumambulate the Ancient House.”"
  22,30,"All that. And whoever venerates Allah’s inviolable rites, then it is good for him with his Lord. And livestock have been made lawful to you<sup>pl</sup>, except what is recited to you. So avoid the abomination of idols and avoid saying falsehood,"
  22,31,"turning to Allah, away from all that is false, without associating anything with Him. And whoever associates anything with Allah—it is as though he has fallen from the sky so that the birds snatch him or the wind sweeps down with him to a far-off place."
  22,32,"All that. And whoever venerates the rituals of Allah—it is indeed out of the hearts' mindfulness <small>(of God)</small>."
  22,33,"In them are benefits for you<sup>pl</sup> for a stated term, then their place <small>(of sacrifice)</small> is towards the Ancient House."
  22,34,"And for every community We have appointed a rite, that they may commemorate Allah’s name over the livestock animals which He has provided for them. Thus your<sup>pl</sup> God is One God, so to Him submit. And give glad tidings to the humble:"
  22,35,"those whose hearts tremble when Allah is mentioned, and those who endure patiently what has befallen them, and those who establish the prayer and spend from what We have provided for them."
  22,36,"And We have made for you<sup>pl</sup> the <small>(offering of)</small> fleshy cattle among Allah’s rituals. In them is much good for you, so mention<sup foot_note="365381">1</sup> Allah’s name upon them as they line up. Then when they have fallen to their sides<sup foot_note="365382">2</sup>, eat of them and feed the contented and the beggar. Thus We have subjected them to you, that you may give thanks.",footnotes:345844:The Arabic word used also means ‘remember’.|345845:A metaphor for having been slaughtered.
  22,37,"Never shall their flesh nor their blood reach Allah. Rather, what reaches Him from you is mindfulness <small>(of Him)</small>. Thus He has subjected them to you, that you may glorify Allah for guiding you. And give glad tidings to those who excel in doing good."
  22,38,"Indeed, Allah <span class="h">defends<sup foot_note="365383">1</sup></span> those who have attained faith. Indeed, Allah does not love every treacherous staunch denier.",footnotes:345846:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “Indeed, Allah repels (harm) from those who ...”</span>
  22,39,"Permission has been <span class="h">granted<sup foot_note="365384">1</sup></span> to those who are <span class="h">combated<sup foot_note="365385">2</sup></span>, because they have been dealt with unjustly—and most surely Allah is Able to give them support:",footnotes:345847:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Abu Amr, Asem, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “He has granted permission to those…”</span>|345848:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Amer, Hafs, and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…to those who combat…”</span>
  22,40,"those who have been unjustifiably evicted from their homes merely for saying, “Our Lord is Allah.” And were it not that Allah repels people by means of others, monasteries and churches and synagogues and mosques—where the name of Allah is mentioned frequently—would have been utterly <span class="h">demolished<sup foot_note="365386">1</sup></span>. And most surely, Allah will support whoever supports Him. Indeed, Allah is certainly All-Powerful, Almighty.",footnotes:345849:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…would have been demolished.”</span>
  22,41,"Those who, when We give them authority in the land, establish the prayer and bring<sup foot_note="365387">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="365388">2</sup> and command to what is fair and forbid what is deplorable. And with Allah rests the outcome of all events.",footnotes:345850:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|345851:The Arabic word used is z<i>akāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  22,42,"And if they disbelieve you<sup>sg</sup>—so before them the people of Noah and Ād<sup foot_note="365389">1</sup> and Thamud<sup foot_note="365390">2</sup> <small>(also)</small> disbelieved,",footnotes:345852:The pagan tribe of Prophet Hûd.|345853:The pagan tribe of Prophet Salih.
  22,43,"and the people of Abraham and the people of Lot,"
  22,44,"and the inhabitants of Midian <small>(as well).</small> And Moses was disbelieved. So I reprieved the deniers then I seized them, so how terrible was My condemnation?"
  22,45,"So how many a town have <span class="h">We<sup foot_note="365391">1</sup></span> annihilated while it was unjust, so that it lies devastated upon its trellises, with an abandoned well and a lofty mansion?",footnotes:345854:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…have I annihilated…”</span>
  22,46,"Have they not journeyed in the land and had hearts to reason with or ears to listen with? Therefore, it is not the sight<small>(s)</small> that go blind, but it is the hearts within the chests that go blind."
  22,47,"And they urge you<sup>sg</sup> to hasten the punishment. But Allah will not break His promise. And indeed, a single day with your Lord is like a thousand years of what you<sup>pl</sup> <span class="h">count<sup foot_note="365392">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:345855:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…of what they count.”</span>
  22,48,"And how many a town did I respite while it was unjust? Then I seized it, for to Me is the destiny."
  22,49,"Say, “O mankind, indeed, I am only an evident warner to you.”"
  22,50,"Therefore, those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—for them is forgiveness and noble provision."
  22,51,"But those who strove against Our signs<sup foot_note="365393">1</sup> attempting to <span class="h">challenge<sup foot_note="365394">2</sup></span><small>(the believers)</small>—those are the fellows of purgatory.",footnotes:345856:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.|345857:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “…attempting to thwart…”</span>
  22,52,"And never did We send any messenger before you nor a prophet but when he wished <small>(to guide people)</small> Satan cast <small>(obstacles)</small> to his wish. Yet Allah nullifies what Satan casts, then Allah affirms His signs. And Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  22,53,"Thus He makes whatever Satan casts a means of trial for those whose hearts harbor disease and those who are hard-hearted. For the unjust are indeed in profound discord."
  22,54,"And let those endowed with knowledge know that it is the truth from your Lord, and believe in it so that their hearts soften to it. And indeed, Allah will guide those who have attained faith to a straight path,"
  22,55,"while those who have denied continue to be in skepticism about it until the Hour comes upon them suddenly or there comes to them the punishment of a desolate day."
  22,56,"Dominion on that day belongs to Allah; He judges between them. Thus those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds are in Gardens of Bliss,"
  22,57,"while those who have denied and disbelieved Our signs—for those there is a demeaning punishment."
  22,58,"And those who emigrated in Allah’s way then were killed or died—Allah will most surely provide them with good provision. And indeed, it is Allah who is certainly the Best of providers."
  22,59,"He will most surely enter them an entrance that well pleases them. For indeed, Allah is certainly All-Knowing, Clement."
  22,60,"All that. And whoever punishes with the like of the punishment he was made to suffer and then he is oppressed <small>(again)</small>, Allah will most surely support him. Indeed, Allah is certainly Pardoning, Oft-Forgiving."
  22,61,"That is because Allah causes the night to penetrate the day and He causes the day to penetrate the night, and because Allah is All-Hearing, All-Seeing."
  22,62,"That is because Allah is the Truth, and because whatever <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="365395">1</sup></span> call upon apart from Him is falsehood, and because Allah is the All-High, the Supreme.",footnotes:345858:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Ibn Amer, Shu’ba and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…whatever you call upon…”</span>
  22,63,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen that Allah has sent down water from the sky, then the land becomes green? Indeed, Allah is Subtle, All-Aware."
  22,64,"To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth. For indeed it is Allah who is certainly the Self-sufficient, the Praiseworthy."
  22,65,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen that Allah has subjected to you<sup>pl</sup> whatever is in the earth and the ships that sail at sea by His command, and that He holds up <small>(whatever is in)</small> the heaven lest it fall on earth, except by His permission? Allah is indeed truly Compassionate towards mankind, Bestowing of mercy."
  22,66,"And it is He who gave you<sup>pl</sup> life, then makes you die, then revives you. Indeed, man is surely a staunch denier."
  22,67,"For every community We have appointed a rite which they observe, so do not let them dispute with you<sup>sg</sup> in this matter. And do call to your Lord; you are most surely rightly guided upon the straight way."
  22,68,"But if they argue with you<sup>sg</sup>, say, “Allah knows better what you<sup>pl</sup> do.”"
  22,69,"Allah judges between you on the Day of Resurrection regarding whatever you used to differ over."
  22,70,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not come to know that Allah knows whatever is in the heaven and the earth? Indeed, that is in a record<sup foot_note="365396">1</sup> ; indeed, that is easy for Allah.",footnotes:345859:Literally ‘scripture’.
  22,71,"Yet they worship, apart from Allah, things for which He sent <span class="h">down<sup foot_note="365397">1</sup></span> no authority and what they have no knowledge of. And for the unjust<sup>pl</sup> there is no supporter.",footnotes:345860:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…things for which He bestowed no authority from on high …”</span>
  22,72,"And when Our signs<sup foot_note="365398">1</sup> are read to them, evident, you<sup>sg</sup> recognize deploring <small>(looks)</small> on the faces of those who have denied; they nearly assault those who read to them Our signs. Say “Shall I inform you of something worse than that? The Fire! Allah has promised it to those who have denied—and what a miserable destiny!”",footnotes:345861:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  22,73,"O mankind, a parable has been set forth, so listen to it: indeed, those whom <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="365399">1</sup></span> call upon apart from Allah shall never create a fly, even if they were to band together for that purpose; and if a fly snatches anything from them, they cannot recover it from it. Weak are the pursuer and the pursued.",footnotes:345862:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…whom they call upon….”</span>
  22,74,"They have not respected Allah with the respect due to Him. Indeed, Allah is certainly All-Powerful, Almighty."
  22,75,"Allah elects messengers from among the angels and from among mankind; indeed, Allah is All-Hearing, All-Seeing."
  22,76,"He knows what is before them and what is behind them. For to Allah all matters are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365400">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:345863:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “…all matters return.”</span>
  22,77,"O you who have attained faith, kneel and prostrate and worship your Lord and do good <small>(deeds),</small> that you may succeed."
  22,78,"And strive for Allah with the striving due to Him. He has chosen you and has not imposed upon you any discomfort in religion—the creed of your father Abraham. It is He Who named you Muslims before and in this <small>(Scripture)</small>, so that the Messenger may be a witness over you and you may be witnesses over mankind. So establish the prayer and bring<sup foot_note="365401">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="365402">2</sup> and hold fast to Allah. He is your Patron, so what an excellent Patron and what an excellent Supporter!",footnotes:345864:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|345865:The Arabic word used is z<i>akāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  23,1,"Surely the believers have attained success:"
  23,2,"those who are reverent in their prayers;"
  23,3,"and those who disregard idle talk;"
  23,4,"and those who are observant of the purifying charity<sup foot_note="365403">1</sup> ;",footnotes:345866:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  23,5,"and those who preserve their private parts,"
  23,6,"except from their spouses or those whom they rightfully possess—for then they are free from blame."
  23,7,"But whoever seeks anything beyond that—those are the transgressors."
  23,8,"And those who to their <span class="h">trusts<sup foot_note="365404">1</sup></span> and their covenant are faithful,",footnotes:345867:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “…their trust…”</span>
  23,9,"and those who preserve their <span class="h">prayers<sup foot_note="365405">1</sup></span>—",footnotes:345868:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…their prayer…”</span>
  23,10,"those are the ones who are the <small>(true)</small> inheritors"
  23,11,"who inherit Paradise; therein they abide."
  23,12,"And most surely, We created man from an extract of clay;"
  23,13,"then We made him a sperm-drop, lodged in a secure place;"
  23,14,"then We developed the sperm-drop into a clinging form, and We developed the clinging form into a morsel-like lump, and We developed the morsel-like lump into <span class="h">bones<sup foot_note="365406">1</sup></span>, and We clothed the <span class="h">bones<sup foot_note="365407">2</sup></span> with flesh, then We produced him into another creation. So supremely blessed be Allah, the Best of creators.",footnotes:345869:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Shu’ba read it as: “bone”.</span>|345870:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Shu’ba read it as: “bone”.</span>
  23,15,"Then after that you<sup>pl</sup> are surely bound to die."
  23,16,"Then on the Day of Resurrection you<sup>pl</sup> are bound to be raised."
  23,17,"And surely We created above you<sup>pl</sup> seven <small>(heavenly)</small> roads, and never have We been oblivious of the creation."
  23,18,"And We sent down water from the sky in due measure and settled it in the earth, and We are certainly able to take it away."
  23,19,"And with it We produced for you<sup>pl</sup> gardens of palms and grapevines; in them you have abundant fruits, and of them you eat."
  23,20,"And a tree springing out of Mount Sinai, germinating oil and seasoning for the eaters."
  23,21,"And there is indeed a lesson for you<sup>pl</sup> in livestock: We <span class="h">give<sup foot_note="365408">1</sup></span> you to drink from what is in their bellies, and you have many benefits in them, and from them you eat,",footnotes:345871:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…in livestock: It gives you to drink…”</span>
  23,22,"and on them and on ships you are carried."
  23,23,"And most surely We sent Noah to his people, so he said, “O my people, worship Allah; you have no god other than Him. Will you not be mindful <small>(of God)</small>?”"
  23,24,"So the chiefs of his people, who denied, said, “This is nothing but a human being like you<sup>pl</sup>, who wants to gain superiority over you. And had Allah willed, He would have sent down angels. We never heard of this among our forefathers of old;"
  23,25,"he is nothing but a man in whom is madness, so wait for a while and see what happens to him.”"
  23,26,"He said, “My Lord, support me with what they have disbelieved me about.”"
  23,27,"So We revealed to him: “Build the ship under Our eyes and according to Our revelation. And when Our command comes and the oven overflows<sup foot_note="365409">1</sup>, carry in it of each kind, a <small>(male and female)</small> <span class="h">couple<sup foot_note="365410">2</sup></span>, and your family except those of them against whom the word has already been pronounced. And do not speak to me concerning those who have done injustice; they will surely be drowned.",footnotes:345872:That was the sign to embark the ship.|345873:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as: “‘…of each (male and female) kind, one couple…’”</span>
  23,28,"Then, when you and those with you are settled on the ship, say, ‘Praise be to Allah who has delivered us from the unjust people.’"
  23,29,"And say, ‘My Lord, land me at a blessed landing-place, for You are the best of those who bring <small>(people)</small> to land.’”"
  23,30,"Indeed, in that are surely signs, and surely We have always been testing <small>(mankind)</small>."
  23,31,"Then after them We brought forth another generation,"
  23,32,"and We sent among them a messenger from themselves: “Worship Allah; you<sup>pl</sup> have no god other than Him; will you not be mindful <small>(of God)</small>?”"
  23,33,"And said the chiefs of his people who denied and disbelieved in the meeting of the Hereafter, and whom We had indulged in the Earlier Life, “This is nothing but a human being like you<sup>pl</sup>, who eats what you eat and drinks what you drink."
  23,34,"And if you obey a human being like yourselves, then you are bound to lose."
  23,35,"Does he promise you<sup>pl</sup> that when you have died and have become dust and bones you will be brought out?"
  23,36,"Farfetched, farfetched is what you are promised."
  23,37,"There is nothing but our Earlier Life<small> </small>—we die and we live, and we will never be raised."
  23,38,"He is nothing but a man who has fabricated lies against Allah, and never will we believe him.”"
  23,39,"He said, “My Lord, support me with what they have disbelieved me about.”"
  23,40,"He said, “Soon they will definitely become remorseful.”"
  23,41,"So the Shout took them away, according to the true <small>(promise)</small>, and We turned them into scum. So away with the unjust people."
  23,42,"Then after them We brought forth other generations."
  23,43,"No community can advance its time, nor can they delay it."
  23,44,"Then We sent Our messengers in succession; every time a messenger came to his community, they disbelieved him. So We made them follow one another<sup foot_note="365411">1</sup> and made them history. So away with a people who do not believe.",footnotes:345874:Follow one another into destruction.
  23,45,"Then We sent Moses and his brother Aaron with Our signs and an evident manifestation"
  23,46,"to Pharaoh and his chiefs, but they acted arrogantly and they were a haughty people."
  23,47,"So they said, “Are we to believe in two human beings like us while their people are servants to us?”"
  23,48,"So they disbelieved them both, and thus they became of those who were annihilated."
  23,49,"And indeed We gave Moses the Scripture, that they may be guided."
  23,50,"And We made the son of Mary and his mother a sign, and We sheltered them in a secure place on a hilltop with a spring."
  23,51,"“O messengers, eat of the good foods and do righteousness; indeed, I am All-Knowing of what you <span class="h">do<sup foot_note="365412">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:345875:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafieʻ, Ibn Kathir, Abu ʻAmr, Abu Jaʻfar and Yaʻqub read it as: “. . . of what you do. And (know) that this community …”</span>
  23,52,"For indeed, this community of yours is one community and I am your Lord, so be mindful of Me.”"
  23,53,"But they tore themselves into sects, each party rejoicing in what they had."
  23,54,"So leave<sup>sg</sup> them in their perplexity for a while."
  23,55,"Do they assume that, in supplying them with wealth and children,"
  23,56,"We hasten to give them the good things? In fact, they are unaware."
  23,57,"Indeed, those who, out of awe for their Lord, are fearful,"
  23,58,"and those who believe in their Lord’s signs,"
  23,59,"and those who associate none with their Lord,"
  23,60,"and those who bring whatever they bring while their hearts tremble, knowing that to their Lord they are returning—"
  23,61,"those are the ones who hasten towards good works, and it is they who will reach it first."
  23,62,"And We never task any self beyond its capacity, and with Us is a record<sup foot_note="365413">1</sup> that tells the truth, and they will not be dealt with unjustly.",footnotes:345876:Literally ‘scripture’.
  23,63,"But their hearts are in perplexity as to this, and they have deeds other than that which they are doing,"
  23,64,"until when We seize the affluent ones among them with punishment, they promptly begin to groan."
  23,65,"“Do not groan today; indeed, you<sup>pl</sup> will not be supported by Us."
  23,66,"Surely, My signs<sup foot_note="365414">1</sup> used to be recited to you, but you used to turn back on your heels",footnotes:345877:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  23,67,"in arrogance regarding it, conversing by night <small>(about it)</small>, <small>(yet)</small> <span class="h">deserting<sup foot_note="365415">1</sup></span> it<sup foot_note="365416">2</sup> .”",footnotes:345878:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ read it as: “…conversing by night (about it), (yet) blaspheming.”</span>|345879:The pronoun in Arabic may be referring to either the Qur’an or the Prophet (peace be upon him).
  23,68,"Have they not pondered the Word? Or has there come to them what came not to their forefathers of old?"
  23,69,"Or is it that they did not recognize their messenger so they disacknowledge him?"
  23,70,"Or do they say, “He is possessed?” Rather, he has come to them with the truth, but most of them are hateful of the truth."
  23,71,"Yet were the Truth to follow their whims, the heavens and the earth and everyone in them would have become corrupted. Rather, We have come up to them with their Reminder, but they keep disregarding their Reminder."
  23,72,"Or are you<sup>sg</sup> asking them for a payment? Rather, your Lord's payment is better, for He is the best of providers."
  23,73,"And indeed, you<sup>sg</sup> are surely calling them to a straight path,"
  23,74,"for those who do not believe in the Hereafter are most surely swerving from the path."
  23,75,"And were We to have mercy upon them and remove whatever harm is upon them, surely they would continue to wander aimlessly while exceeding all limits."
  23,76,"And most surely We gripped them with punishment, but they did not surrender to their Lord, nor do they supplicate <small>(Him)</small>"
  23,77,"until, when We have opened before them a gate of intense punishment, they suddenly despair."
  23,78,"And it is He Who initiated for you<sup>pl</sup> the hearing and the sight<small>(s)</small> and the burning hearts; scarcely do you give thanks!"
  23,79,"And it is He Who scattered you<sup>pl</sup> on earth, and to Him you will be herded."
  23,80,"And it is He Who gives life and causes death, and to Him is the alternation of night and day. Do you<sup>pl</sup> not reason?"
  23,81,"Rather, they said the like of what the ancients had said."
  23,82,"They said, “Can it be that when we have died and become dust and bones, can it be <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="365417">1</sup></span> we will really be resurrected?",footnotes:345880:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “‘Can it be that when we have died and become dust and bones we will really be resurrected?’” Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “‘When we have died and become dust and bones, can it be that we will really be resurrected?’”</span>
  23,83,"Most surely, we were promised this before, we and our forefathers—these are nothing but legends of the ancients.”"
  23,84,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “To whom does the earth and everyone in it belong, if you<sup>pl</sup> happen to know?”"
  23,85,"They will say, “To Allah.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Will you never <span class="h">remember<sup foot_note="365418">1</sup></span>?”",footnotes:345881:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Say<sup><small>sg</small></sup>, ‘Will you not constantly remember?’”</span>
  23,86,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Who is the Lord of the seven heavens and Lord of the Great Throne?”"
  23,87,"They will say, <span class="h">"To<sup foot_note="365419">1</sup></span> Allah." Say<sup>sg</sup>, "Will you never be mindful <small>(of God)</small>?"",footnotes:345882:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “They will say, ‘Allah.’”</span>
  23,88,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “In whose hand is the dominance of everything, and He grants refuge but cannot be granted refuge, if you happen to know?”"
  23,89,"They will say, <span class="h">“To<sup foot_note="365420">1</sup></span> Allah.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Then are you bewitched?”",footnotes:345883:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “They will say, ‘Allah.’”</span>
  23,90,"Rather, We have come up to them with the truth, yet they are surely liars."
  23,91,"Never has Allah taken any offspring nor has there ever been any god with Him, for then each god would have taken away what he had created, and some of them would have gained supremacy over others. Highly Exalted is Allah, far above what they describe:"
  23,92,"the <span class="h">Knower<sup foot_note="365421">1</sup></span> of the hidden realm and the manifest. So Most High is He, far above what they associate <small>(as gods with Him)</small>.",footnotes:345884:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Shu’ba, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Abu Ja’far and Khalaf read it as: “…describe. (He is) the Knower of…”</span>
  23,93,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “My Lord, if You would show me what they are promised,"
  23,94,"my Lord, do not make me among the unjust people.”"
  23,95,"And We are surely able to show you<sup>sg</sup> what We promise them."
  23,96,"Repel<sup>sg</sup> what is bad by what is better. We know better what they describe."
  23,97,"And say<sup>sg</sup>, “My Lord, I seek refuge with You from the urgings of the devils,"
  23,98,"and I seek refuge with You, my Lord, lest they become present with me.”"
  23,99,"Until, when death comes to one of them, he says, “My Lord, send me back,"
  23,100,"that I may act righteously in that which I have left <small>(behind)</small>.” But no! It is just a word that he says, and behind them is a barrier until the day they are resurrected."
  23,101,"So when the Horn is blown, no ties of kinship between them exist on that day, nor do they ask one another."
  23,102,"So those whose scales weigh heavy—those are the successful."
  23,103,"And those whose scales weigh light—those are the ones who have lost themselves; in Hell they abide."
  23,104,"The Fire lashes their faces, and therein they grimace."
  23,105,"“Were not My signs<sup foot_note="365422">1</sup> recited to you<sup>pl</sup>, but you used to disbelieve them?”",footnotes:345885:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  23,106,"They said<sup foot_note="365423">1</sup>, “Our Lord, our wretchedness overcame us, and we were a people astray.",footnotes:345886:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  23,107,"Our Lord, bring us out of this, and if we ever return, we would truly be unjust.”"
  23,108,"He said, “Be despised<sup>pl</sup> therein and do not speak to Me."
  23,109,"Indeed, there was a group of My servants who used to say, `Our Lord, we have attained faith, so forgive us and have mercy on us, and You are the best of the merciful.'"
  23,110,"But you<sup>pl</sup> made them a target of ridicule until they made you forget My remembrance, and you used to laugh at them."
  23,111,"Today I have indeed rewarded them for what they endured patiently, for <span class="h">it<sup foot_note="365424">1</sup></span> is they who are the triumphant ones.”",footnotes:345887:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…patiently. Indeed, it is they…”</span>
  23,112,"He <span class="h">said<sup foot_note="365425">1</sup></span>, “How long did you remain on earth in terms of number of years?”",footnotes:345888:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Hamza and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “Say<sup><small>sg</small></sup>, ‘How long…’”</span>
  23,113,"They said, “We remained a day or part of a day, so ask those who keep count.”"
  23,114,"He <span class="h">said<sup foot_note="365426">1</sup></span>, “You<sup>pl</sup> remained but for a little while, if you only knew.",footnotes:345889:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “Say<sup><small>sg</small></sup>, ‘You remained…’”</span>
  23,115,"Did you<sup>pl</sup> think that We had created you in vain, and that to Us you would not be <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365427">1</sup></span>?”",footnotes:345890:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “…you would not return?”</span>
  23,116,"Rather, Most High is Allah, the True King; there is no god but He, the Lord of the Noble Throne."
  23,117,"And whoever calls upon another god with Allah—he has no proof thereof—his reckoning rests with his Lord; indeed, the deniers never succeed."
  23,118,"And say<sup>sg</sup>, “My Lord, forgive and have mercy, for You are the best of the merciful.”"
  24,1,"A surah<sup foot_note="365428">1</sup> that We have sent down and <span class="h">ordained<sup foot_note="365429">2</sup></span> and sent down in it evident signs<sup foot_note="365430">3</sup>, that you may remind <span class="h">yourselves<sup foot_note="365431">4</sup></span>.",footnotes:345891:Each portion of the Qur'an is called a ‘surah’, which is sometimes translated as ‘chapter’.|345892:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “…and did ordain…”</span>|345893:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.|345894:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…that you may constantly remember.”</span>
  24,2,"The fornicating woman and the fornicating man—whip each one of them a hundred lashes and let no compassion towards them keep you<sup>pl</sup> from carrying out Allah’s religion, if you <small>(truly)</small> believe in Allah and the Last Day, and let their punishment be witnessed by a group<sup foot_note="365432">1</sup> of believers.",footnotes:345895:The Arabic word used is the same as that translated as ‘faction’.
  24,3,"The fornicating man marries none but a fornicating woman or an idolatress, and the fornicating woman marries none but a fornicating man or an idolater, and that has been prohibited for the believers."
  24,4,"And those who accuse chaste women then cannot bring four witnesses—whip<sup>pl</sup> them eighty lashes and do not ever accept their testimony, for those are the defiantly disobedient—"
  24,5,"except for those who have repented afterwards and reformed, for indeed, Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  24,6,"And those who accuse their own spouses but have no witnesses except themselves, then let the testimony of one of them be four <span class="h">oaths<sup foot_note="365433">1</sup></span> by Allah that he is surely of the truthful.",footnotes:345896:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…then the testimony of one of them (is binding)—four oaths by Allah…”</span>
  24,7,"And the fifth is: <span class="h">may<sup foot_note="365434">1</sup></span> Allah’s curse indeed be upon him if he is of the liars.",footnotes:345897:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Ya’qub read it as: “...may Allah’s curse be upon him…”</span>
  24,8,"But what averts punishment from her is that she testifies under oath four times by Allah that he is surely of the liars,"
  24,9,"<span class="h">while<sup foot_note="365435">1</sup></span> the fifth is: may Allah’s wrath indeed be upon her if he is of the truthful.",footnotes:345898:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ya’qub and Hafs read it as: “…liars. <sub><small>9</small></sub>9 And the fifth is: may Allah’s wrath indeed be upon her…. ” Nafie’ read it as: “...liars. <sub><small>9</small></sub>9 And the fifth is that Allah’s wrath will have fallen upon her...” Ya’qub read it as: “…liars. <sub><small>9</small></sub>9 And the fifth is: may Allah’s wrath be upon her…”</span>
  24,10,"And were it not for Allah’s grace upon you<sup>pl</sup><small>,</small> and His mercy, and that Allah is the Granter and Accepter of repentance, All-Wise...<sup foot_note="365436">1</sup>",footnotes:345899:According to most exegetes, this sentence is left open-ended in order to magnify the predicate and leave it to the reader's imagination.
  24,11,"Indeed, those who produced the fabrication are a band of you. Do not consider it bad for you<sup>pl</sup>; rather, it is good for you. For each person of them is whatever sin he has earned, yet the one who played the major role—for him is a great punishment."
  24,12,"If only when you<sup>pl</sup> heard it, the believing men and the believing women had thought well of themselves<sup foot_note="365437">1</sup> and said, “This is an evident fabrication!”",footnotes:345900:The Qur’an used the term “themselves" rather than “each other” to make the believers sympathize with one another by considering any defamation to one as defamation to all.
  24,13,"If only they had produced four witnesses against it. Yet since they did not come up with the witnesses, then before Allah they are the liars."
  24,14,"And were it not for Allah’s grace upon you<sup>pl</sup><small>,</small> and His mercy in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> and the Hereafter, you would have been touched by a great punishment for what you have ventured into."
  24,15,"Recall receiving it with your tongues and saying with your mouths what you had no knowledge of, and considering it trivial while with Allah it is greatly serious."
  24,16,"And if only when you<sup>pl</sup> heard it you had said, “It is not lawful for us to speak about this. Highly Exalted are You; this is a great slander.”"
  24,17,"Allah admonishes you never to return to the like of it if you are believers."
  24,18,"And Allah clarifies the signs to you<sup>pl</sup>, for Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  24,19,"Indeed, those who love that obscenity should spread among the believers—for them is a painful punishment in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> and the Hereafter, for Allah knows while you know not."
  24,20,"And were it not for Allah’s grace upon you<sup>pl</sup><small>,</small> and His mercy, and that Allah is Compassionate, Bestowing of mercy...<sup foot_note="365438">1</sup>",footnotes:345901:According to most exegetes, this sentence is left open-ended in order to magnify the predicate and leave it to the reader's imagination.
  24,21,"O you who have attained faith, do not follow Satan’s footsteps, for whoever follows Satan’s footsteps <small>(should know that)</small> indeed he commands to obscenity and what is deplorable. And were it not for Allah’s grace towards you, and His mercy, not one of you would ever have been purified, ever, but Allah purifies whomever He wills. For Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing."
  24,22,"And let not the ones endowed with grace and affluence swear not to give to the close relatives and the destitute<sup>pl</sup> and the emigrants in the way of Allah, and let them pardon and let them overlook. Do you<sup>pl</sup> not love that Allah should forgive you? For Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  24,23,"Those who accuse chaste, unwary, believing women are indeed cursed in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> and the Hereafter, and for them is a great punishment"
  24,24,"on the day when their tongues and their hands and their feet testify against them regarding what they used to do."
  24,25,"On that day, Allah pays them their true recompense in full, and they learn that it is Allah who is the Evident Truth."
  24,26,"Nasty<sup foot_note="365439">1</sup> <small>(women)</small> are for nasty men, and nasty men are for nasty <small>(women)</small>, and good <small>(women)</small> are for good men, and good men are for good <small>(women)</small>. Those are acquitted of what they say; for them is forgiveness and a noble provision.",footnotes:345902:The words ‘nasty’ and ‘good’ are mentioned in feminine form and may refer either to ‘nasty women’ and ‘good women’ or to ‘nasty words and ‘good words’.
  24,27,"O you who have attained faith, do not enter houses other than your own houses until you announce your presence and greet their inhabitants with the greeting of peace. That is better for you, that you may remind yourselves."
  24,28,"But if you<sup>pl</sup> find no one in them, then do not enter them until you are given permission. And if it is said to you, “Turn back,” then turn back; it is purer for you, for Allah is All-Knowing of what you do."
  24,29,"You<sup>pl</sup> commit no sin by entering uninhabited houses in which there is convenience for you, for Allah knows whatever you disclose and whatever you conceal."
  24,30,"Tell<sup>sg</sup> the believing men to restrain their sight<small>(s)</small><sup foot_note="365440">1</sup> and to preserve their private parts; that is purer for them. Indeed, Allah is All-Aware of what they do.",footnotes:345903:Mentioned in plural form in Arabic, denoted by (s) in English for grammatical reasons.
  24,31,"And tell<sup>sg</sup> the believing women to restrain their sight<small>(s)</small> and to preserve their private parts, and not display their adornment except what is apparent thereof, and to draw their head coverings over their bosoms and not display their adornment except to their husbands, or their fathers, or their husbands' fathers, or their sons, or their husbands' sons, or their brothers, or their brothers' sons, or their sisters' sons, or their womenfolk, or those whom they rightfully possess, or their male attendants who have no <small>(sexual)</small> urge, or children who are not yet aware of women's privacies, and they should not strike their feet to draw attention to their hidden adornment. Thus repent to Allah, all of you, O believers, that you may succeed."
  24,32,"And marry the singles among you and those who are fit among your bondmen and bondwomen. If they are poor, Allah will enrich them from His grace. For Allah is All-Encompassing, All-Knowing."
  24,33,"And let those who do not find the means to marry remain chaste until Allah enriches them from His grace. And if any of those whom you<sup>pl</sup> rightfully possess desire an <small>(emancipation)</small> agreement, write an agreement with them if you recognize some good in them, and give them of Allah’s wealth which He has given you. And do not compel your maids to prostitution, seeking the materials of the Earlier <small>(Life)</small>, if they want to remain chaste. But should anyone compel them—then after their compulsion, Allah is indeed Oft-Forgiving<sup foot_note="365441">1</sup>, Bestowing of mercy.",footnotes:345904:Of such maids.
  24,34,"And We have most surely sent down to you<sup>pl</sup> <span class="h">clarifying<sup foot_note="365442">1</sup></span> signs and a parable from those who passed on before you<sup foot_note="365443">2</sup>, and an admonition for the ones who were mindful <small>(of God)</small>.",footnotes:345905:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Amer, Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…clarified signs…”</span>|345906:Referring to the story of the slander of Yusuf.
  24,35,"Allah is the Light of the heavens and the earth. The parable of His light is as a niche wherein is a lamp; the lamp is in a glass; the glass is like a glittering planet, kindled<sup foot_note="365444">1</sup> from a blessed tree—an olive tree—neither eastern nor western. Its oil would almost illuminate even if no fire were to touch it. Light upon light. Allah guides to His light whomever He wills. Thus Allah sets forth parables for mankind. For Allah is All-Knowing of everything.",footnotes:345907:Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Abu Ja’far, Ya’qub, Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Hafs read “Kindled” in masculine form referring to the lamp being kindled from the oil of a blessed tree. All others read it in feminine form referring to the glass being kindled.
  24,36,"<small>(Such light shines)</small> in houses which Allah has permitted to be raised up and in which His name is remembered. Highly <span class="h">exalted<sup foot_note="365445">1</sup></span> therein, mornings and before sunset,",footnotes:345908:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn ʻAmer, and Shuʻba read it as: “He is highly exalted therein, mornings and before sunset— <sub>37 </sub>men whommen whom …”</span>
  24,37,"by men whom neither bargain nor sale distracts from Allah’s remembrance or from establishing the prayers or from bringing<sup foot_note="365446">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="365447">2</sup>, fearing a day when hearts and sight<small>(s)</small> are overturned,",footnotes:345909:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|345910:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  24,38,"<small>(in the hope)</small> that Allah may repay them according to the best of what they have done and increase them from His grace. For Allah provides for whomever He wills without measure."
  24,39,"But those who have denied—their deeds are like a mirage in a desert: the thirsty one thinks it is water until when he has reached it he finds it to be nothing, but there he finds Allah, Who settles his account in full. For Allah is Swift in reckoning."
  24,40,"Or <small>(they are)</small> like darkness<small>(es)</small><sup foot_note="365448">1</sup> in an abysmal sea, covered by waves, above which are waves, above which are <span class="h">clouds—darkness<small>(es)</small><sup foot_note="365449">2</sup></span>, one upon the other. If one holds out his hand, he can hardly see it. For whomever Allah has not granted a light has no light.",footnotes:345911:Mentioned in plural form in Arabic, denoted by (es) in English for grammatical reasons.|345912:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Bazzi read it as: “…above which are clouds of darkness(es)” Qunbul read it as: “…above which are clouds. (These) darkness(es) (are) one upon the other.”</span>
  24,41,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen how Allah is highly exalted by whoever is in the heavens and the earth and by the birds outstretching their wings, each having come to know its <small>(way of)</small> prayer and exaltation? And Allah is All-Knowing of what they do."
  24,42,"For to Allah belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth, and to Allah is the destiny."
  24,43,"Have you not seen how Allah propels clouds, then brings them together, then piles them up in heaps so you see rainfall coming out of its midst? And He sends <span class="h">down<sup foot_note="365450">1</sup></span> from the sky—from mountains in it— some hail, striking with it whomever He wills and diverting it from whomever He wills? The flash of its lightening almost does away with the sight<small>(s)</small>.",footnotes:345913:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “And He bestows from on high, from the sky—from mountains…”</span>
  24,44,"Allah alternates night and day. Indeed, in that is a lesson for those endowed with sight<small>(s)</small>."
  24,45,"And Allah <span class="h">created<sup foot_note="365451">1</sup></span> every treading creature from water, so of them is one<small> (kind)</small> that treads upon its belly, and one<small> (kind)</small> that treads upon two legs, and one <small>(kind)</small> that treads upon four; Allah creates whatever He wills; Allah is indeed Powerful over everything.",footnotes:345914:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “And Allah is the Creator of every treading creature…”</span>
  24,46,"Most surely, We have sent down <span class="h">clarifying<sup foot_note="365452">1</sup></span> signs<sup foot_note="365453">2</sup>, and Allah guides whomever He wills to a straight path.",footnotes:345915:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Amer, Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…clarified signs…”</span>|345916:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  24,47,"And they say, “We have attained faith in Allah and in the Messenger, and we have obeyed.” Then a group of them turn away afterwards, for in no way are those ever believers."
  24,48,"And when they are called to Allah and His Messenger in order to <span class="h">judge<sup foot_note="365454">1</sup></span> between them, a group of them promptly disregards <small>(it)</small>;",footnotes:345917:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…in order to have it judged between them…”</span>
  24,49,"but if the truth is in their favor, they come to Him in obedience."
  24,50,"Is there sickness in their hearts? Or have they doubted? Or do they fear that Allah may oppress them, or <small>(that)</small> His Messenger <small>(may do so)</small>? In fact, they themselves are the unjust."
  24,51,"However, the response of the believers when they are called to Allah and His Messenger in order to <span class="h">judge<sup foot_note="365455">1</sup></span> between them has always been to say, “We have heard and obeyed”, for those are the successful.",footnotes:345918:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…in order to have it judged between them…”</span>
  24,52,"And whoever obeys Allah and His Messenger and fears Allah and is mindful of Him—then it is those who are the triumphant ones."
  24,53,"And they swore by Allah their most solemn oaths that if you<sup>sg</sup> commanded them, they would set out. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Do<sup>pl</sup> not swear; <small>(your)</small> obedience is well-known<sup foot_note="365456">1</sup> . Allah is indeed All-Aware of what you do.”",footnotes:345919:Their obedience is well known to be false.
  24,54,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Obey<sup>pl</sup> Allah and obey the Messenger.” But if you<sup>pl</sup> turn away, then he<sup foot_note="365457">1</sup> is only responsible for what <small>(duty)</small> he is made to carry, and you<sup>pl</sup> are responsible for whatever <small>(duty)</small> you are made to carry. For if you obey him, you will be guided, while the only responsibility of the Messenger is evident proclamation.",footnotes:345920:The Prophet (peace be upon him).
  24,55,"Allah has promised those of you who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds that He will most surely make them successors in the land as He made those before them <span class="h">successors<sup foot_note="365458">1</sup></span><small>(of others)</small>, and that He will most surely establish for them their religion which He has approved for them, and that He will most surely substitute security in place of their fear—as they worship Me<sup foot_note="365459">2</sup>, never associating anything with Me. But whoever denies after that—those are the defiantly disobedient.",footnotes:345921:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “…as those before them were made successors (of others),”</span>|345922:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.
  24,56,"And establish<sup>pl</sup> the prayer and bring<sup foot_note="365460">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="365461">2</sup> and obey the Messenger, that you may be granted mercy.",footnotes:345923:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|345924:The Arabic word used is z<i>akāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  24,57,"Never think<sup>sg</sup> <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="365462">1</sup></span> those who have denied can thwart <small>(God)</small> on earth. For their shelter is the Fire, and indeed, what a miserable destiny!",footnotes:345925:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Hamza read it as: “Those who have denied should never think that they can thwart…”</span>
  24,58,"O you who have attained faith, let those whom you rightfully possess and those of you who have not reached puberty seek your <span class="h">permission<sup foot_note="365463">1</sup></span><small>(before entering)</small> on three occasions: before the dawn prayer and at noon when you lay aside your clothes and after the evening prayer—three occasions of privacy for you. At other times, neither you nor they commit sin by intermingling with one another; Allah thus clarifies the signs for you. For Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise.",footnotes:345926:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Shu’ba, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…seek your permission (before entering). Three occasions…”</span>
  24,59,"And when the children among you reach puberty, let them seek permission as those before them have sought permission; Allah thus clarifies His signs for you. For Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  24,60,"And elderly women who do not expect <small>(to be desired in)</small> marriage—they commit no sin by taking off their outer clothing without flaunting their adornment, but to maintain modesty is better for them. For Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing."
  24,61,"There is no blame on the blind, nor any blame on the lame, nor any blame on the sick, nor on yourselves for eating at your houses, or your fathers’ houses, or your mothers’ houses, or your brothers’ houses, or your sisters’ houses, or the houses of your paternal uncles, or the houses of your paternal aunts, or the houses of your maternal uncles, or the houses of your maternal aunts, or those whose keys you own, or that of a friend of yours. You commit no sin by eating together or separately. But when you enter such houses, greet yourselves with a greeting from Allah, blessed <small>(and)</small> good; Allah thus explains the signs for you, that you may reason."
  24,62,"Indeed, the believers are but those who have attained faith in Allah and His Messenger and, when they are with him for a matter of common interest, they do not leave until they have sought his permission. Indeed, those who seek your<sup>sg</sup> permission—those are the ones who believe in Allah and His Messenger. So if they seek your permission to attend to some affair of theirs, give permission to any of them you wish and seek Allah’s forgiveness for them; indeed, Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  24,63,"Do not make the calling of the Messenger among yourselves like your calling of one another. Allah certainly knows those<sup foot_note="365464">1</sup> among you who slip away, concealed by others. So let those who oppose his command beware, lest a trial afflict them or a painful punishment afflict them.",footnotes:345927:The hypocrites.
  24,64,"Undoubtedly, to Allah does belong whatever is in the heavens and the earth; surely, He knows your<sup>pl</sup> condition. And on the day they are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365465">1</sup></span> to Him, He informs them of what they did. For Allah is All-Knowing of everything.",footnotes:345928:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…they return to Him,”</span>
  25,1,"Supremely Blessed be the One Who bestowed the Criterion from on high upon His servant, to be a warner<sup foot_note="365466">1</sup> to all realms.",footnotes:345929:The Arabic text can imply either the Prophet (peace be upon him) as a warner, or the Criterion as a warning.
  25,2,"The One to Whom belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth, and Who has not taken for Himself any offspring nor has He any associate in the dominion, and He has created everything and determined its measure."
  25,3,"And they have taken apart from Him gods who do not create anything, but are themselves created, and who possess for themselves neither harm or benefit, and have no power over life or death or resurrection."
  25,4,"Moreover, those who have denied said, “This is nothing but a fabrication that he has forged, while other people have helped him with it.” They have certainly come forth with injustice and falsehood."
  25,5,"And they said, “Legends of the ancients that he has sought to be written down; thus they are dictated to him morning and evening.”"
  25,6,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “It was sent down by the One Who knows the Secret in the heavens and the earth; indeed, He has always been Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy.”"
  25,7,"And they said, “What sort of messenger is this who eats food and walks in marketplaces? If only an angel had been sent down to him to be a warner alongside him,"
  25,8,"or if a treasure were to be cast to him, or if he had a garden from which he <span class="h">eats<sup foot_note="365467">1</sup></span>.” And the unjust ones said, “You<sup>pl</sup> are only following a bewitched man.”",footnotes:345930:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “‘…from which we eat.’”</span>
  25,9,"Look<sup>sg</sup> how they have set forth parables for you and gone astray, so they cannot find a way."
  25,10,"Supremely Blessed be the One Who, if He so willed, would provide you<sup>sg</sup> with better than that—Gardens beneath which rivers flow—and <span class="h">make<sup foot_note="365468">1</sup></span> for you palaces.",footnotes:345931:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Ibn Amer and Shu’ba read it as: “…would provide you<sup><small>sg</small></sup> with better than that—Gardens beneath which rivers flow. And He would make for you palaces.”</span>
  25,11,"Rather, they have considered the Hour to be a lie, and We have prepared a blaze for those who have disbelieved in the Hour."
  25,12,"When it sees them from a distant place, they hear its raging and roaring."
  25,13,"And when they are cast, shackled, into a tight place therein, there they plead for demise."
  25,14,"“Do not call<sup>pl</sup> for one demise today, but call for many demises.”"
  25,15,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Is that better or the Garden of Eternity promised to the ones who were mindful <small>(of God)</small>? For them it has always been a repayment and<small> </small>a destiny."
  25,16,"They have therein whatever they desire, as they abide. That has always been your<sup>sg</sup> Lord's promise, <small>(worthy)</small> to be requested."
  25,17,"And on the day when <span class="h">He<sup foot_note="365469">1</sup></span> herds them and what they worship apart from Allah, then <span class="h">says<sup foot_note="365470">2</sup></span>, “Was it you<sup>pl</sup> who misguided these servants of Mine, or was it they who strayed from the way?”",footnotes:345932:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Kathir, Hafs, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…when We herd them…”</span>|345933:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “…then We say,”</span>
  25,18,"They said<sup foot_note="365471">1</sup>, “Highly Exalted are You. We should not have taken <span class="h">any<sup foot_note="365472">2</sup></span> masters apart from You. But you allowed them to enjoy, as well as their fathers, until they forgot the Reminder and became a ruined people.”",footnotes:345934:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.|345935:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “We should not have been taken as masters…”</span>
  25,19,"Thus they<sup foot_note="365473">1</sup> have certainly disbelieved you<sup>pl</sup> regarding what you say, so <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="365474">2</sup></span> can neither avoid <small>(punishment)</small> nor get any support. And whoever of you commits injustice, We will make him taste a supreme punishment.",footnotes:345936:The false masters.|345937:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as: “…so they can neither avoid (punishment)…”</span>
  25,20,"And never did We send any emissaries before you<sup>sg</sup> but they used to eat food and walk in the marketplaces. And We made some of you a means of trial for others—will you be patient? And your Lord has always been All-Seeing."
  25,21,"And those who do not expect to meet Us said, “If only the angels were sent down to us or we could see our Lord.” They have acted arrogantly regarding themselves and have become excessively defiant."
  25,22,"On the day when they see the angels—no glad tidings for the criminals on that day, and they<sup foot_note="365475">1</sup> say, “an insurmountable separator<sup foot_note="365476">2</sup> .”",footnotes:345938:The angels.|345939:From bliss.
  25,23,"And We proceeded<sup foot_note="365477">1</sup> to the work they had done and turned them into scattered dust.",footnotes:345940:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  25,24,"The fellows of the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> on that day have a better residence and are more fairly accommodated."
  25,25,"And it is the day when the sky is cleft with clouds and the angels were<sup foot_note="365478">1</sup> sent <span class="h">down<sup foot_note="365479">2</sup></span> in streams.",footnotes:345941:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.|345942:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “…and We send down the angels in streams.”</span>
  25,26,"Dominion on that day belongs to the All-Merciful, and it has been a difficult day for the deniers."
  25,27,"And it is the day when the unjust bites his hands, saying, “If only I had followed the way with the Messenger."
  25,28,"Woe to me! I wish I had not taken so-and-so for a close friend;"
  25,29,"he definitely made me stray away from the Reminder after it had come to me.” And Satan has always been a betrayer of man.”"
  25,30,"And the Messenger said<sup foot_note="365480">1</sup>, “My Lord, my people have dealt with this Qur’an by deserting it.”",footnotes:345943:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  25,31,"Likewise, to every prophet We assigned enemies from among the criminals. But sufficient is your<sup>sg</sup> Lord as a Guide and Supporter."
  25,32,"And those who denied said, “If only the Qur'an had been sent down upon him as one complete whole!” Yet <small>(it is sent in this way)</small> in order to strengthen your heart thereby, and We <small>(revealed it to be)</small> chanted slowly and distinctly."
  25,33,"And whatever similitude they come to you<sup>sg</sup> with, We provide you with the truth and a better exposition."
  25,34,"Those who are herded to Hell on their faces—those are in a worse position and further astray from the way."
  25,35,"And surely We gave Moses the Scripture and appointed his brother Aaron as an assistant,"
  25,36,"then We said, “Go<sup>dl</sup> to the people who have disbelieved Our signs,” then We destroyed them completely."
  25,37,"And when the people of Noah disbelieved the messengers, We drowned them and made them a sign for mankind. And We have prepared a painful punishment for the unjust,"
  25,38,"and <small>(for)</small> Ād<sup foot_note="365481">1</sup> and Thamûd<sup foot_note="365482">2</sup> and the fellows of Al-Russ<sup foot_note="365483">3</sup> and many generations in between.",footnotes:345944:The pagan tribe of Prophet Hûd.|345945:The pagan tribe of Prophet Salih.|345946:At-Tabari mentioned that some exegetes said that<b> </b>Al-Russ was a huge water pit. Al-Russ was a huge water pit.
  25,39,"Thus to each We set forth parables, and each We devastated utterly."
  25,40,"And indeed they have already come across the city<sup foot_note="365484">1</sup> upon which was rained the woeful rain. Have they not seen it then? Rather, they did not expect any resurrection.",footnotes:345947:The city inhabited by the people of Lot.
  25,41,"And when they see you<sup>sg</sup>, they take you not except in ridicule: “Is this the one Allah has sent as a messenger?"
  25,42,"He was about to make us stray away from our gods, had we not patiently adhered to them.” And they will eventually know, when they witness the punishment, who is further astray from the way."
  25,43,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> seen the one who took his own whim as his god? Would you be a trustee for him?"
  25,44,"Or do you<sup>sg</sup> assume that most of them hear or reason? They are but like livestock; rather, they are even further astray from the way."
  25,45,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen how your Lord extended the shade? And had He willed, He could have made it still. Then We made the sun a guide to it."
  25,46,"Then We drew it to Us easily."
  25,47,"And it is He Who made the night for you<sup>pl</sup> as a garment and sleep for repose, and made the day a <small>(time of)</small> resurrection."
  25,48,"And it is He Who sent the <span class="h">winds<sup foot_note="365485">1</sup></span> as heralds of glad <span class="h">tidings<sup foot_note="365486">2</sup></span> ahead of His mercy. And We<sup foot_note="365487">3</sup> sent down from the sky pure water",footnotes:345948:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “wind”.</span>|345949:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…as revivers ahead of His mercy”. All except for Asem, Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “… as a revival ahead of His mercy”.</span>|345950:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.
  25,49,"to revive a lifeless land thereby, and to provide drink for a multitude of animals and humans We have created."
  25,50,"And most surely We have circulated it among them, that they may constantly <span class="h">remember<sup foot_note="365488">1</sup></span>, yet most of mankind refused anything but constant denial.",footnotes:345951:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…that they may remember,”</span>
  25,51,"And had We willed, We could have sent to every town a warner."
  25,52,"So do not obey<sup>sg</sup> the deniers, but strive against them with it<sup foot_note="365489">1</sup> a supreme striving.",footnotes:345952:The Qur’an.
  25,53,"And it is He Who merged the two seas, this one fresh and sweet and this one salty and bitter, and He made between them a barrier and an insurmountable separator."
  25,54,"And it is He Who created of water a human being, then made him related by lineage and marriage. And your<sup>sg</sup> Lord has always been All-Able."
  25,55,"Yet they worship, apart from Allah, what neither benefits them nor harms them. And the denier has always been a backup against his Lord."
  25,56,"And We have not sent you but as a bearer of glad tidings and as a warner."
  25,57,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “I ask of you no reward for this—only that whoever wills may take a way to his Lord.”"
  25,58,"And place your<sup>sg</sup> trust in the Ever-Living One Who never dies, and exalt Him with praise. And sufficient is He as the All-Aware of the misdeeds of His servants."
  25,59,"The One Who created the heavens and the earth and whatever is between them in six days<sup foot_note="365490">1</sup> then settled on the Throne. The All-Merciful. So ask about Him one <small>(who is)</small> well aware.",footnotes:345953:Six equal intervals of time, which may be six heavenly days, each of them being 1000 earthly years long (see 22: 47).
  25,60,"And when it is said to them, “Prostrate yourselves to the All-Merciful,” they say, “And what is the All-Merciful? Shall we prostrate ourselves to what you <span class="h">command<sup foot_note="365491">1</sup></span> us?” And it increases their aversion.",footnotes:345954:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…what He commands us?”</span>
  25,61,"Supremely Blessed be the One Who placed constellations in the sky and placed in it a <span class="h">lamp<sup foot_note="365492">1</sup></span> and an illuminating moon.",footnotes:345955:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…in it lamps and …”</span>
  25,62,"And it is He Who made the night and the day alternate—for whoever wants to constantly <span class="h">remember<sup foot_note="365493">1</sup></span> or wants to give constant thanks.",footnotes:345956:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Khalaf read it as: “…wants to remember or wants to…”</span>
  25,63,"And the servants of the All-Merciful are those who walk the earth gently<sup foot_note="365494">1</sup>, and when the ignorant harassers address them, they say, “Peace.”",footnotes:345957:Humbly.
  25,64,"And they are those who spend the night prostrating themselves to their Lord and standing <small>(in prayer)</small>."
  25,65,"And they are those who say, ‘‘Our Lord, avert from us the punishment of Hell; indeed, its suffering has been ever adhering;"
  25,66,"it is indeed bad as a residence and dwelling place.”"
  25,67,"And they are those who, when they spend, are neither extravagant nor stingy, for the upright method has always been between both."
  25,68,"And they are those who do not call upon any other god with Allah and do not kill the self which Allah has made inviolable—except in the pursuit of justice—and do not fornicate. And whoever does that encounters penalties."
  25,69,"The punishment is doubled for him on the Day of Resurrection, and he abides therein humiliated—"
  25,70,"except for whoever has repented and has attained faith and has done righteous work, for those—Allah replaces their evil deeds with good deeds. And Allah has always been Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  25,71,"And whoever has repented and has acted righteously, then surely he repents to Allah a true repentance."
  25,72,"And they are those who do not bear false witness, and when they come across idle talk, they pass by with dignity."
  25,73,"And they are those who, when reminded of the signs<sup foot_note="365495">1</sup> of their Lord, do not fall before them deaf and blind.",footnotes:345958:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  25,74,"And they are those who say, “Our Lord, grant us in our spouses and our <span class="h">offspring<small>(s)</small><sup foot_note="365496">1</sup></span> a comfort to the eyes, and make us a good example of the ones who were mindful <small>(of God)</small>.”",footnotes:345959:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn kathir, Ibn Amer, Hafs, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “… our offspring…”</span>
  25,75,"Those are awarded the Chamber <small>(in Heaven)</small> for their patience, and are <span class="h">received<sup foot_note="365497">1</sup></span> therein with greetings and peace,",footnotes:345960:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shuʻba, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “. . . and will encounter therein greetings and peace …”</span>
  25,76,"abiding therein—an excellent residence and dwelling place."
  25,77,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “What are you<sup>pl</sup> to my Lord without your calling upon Him? But you have certainly disbelieved, so the inevitable is bound to come.”"
  26,1,"Tâ Sîn Mīm."
  26,2,"Those are the signs of the Evident Scripture."
  26,3,"Perhaps you<sup>sg</sup> are going to destroy yourself with sorrow because they do not believe?"
  26,4,"If We will, We can <span class="h">bestow<sup foot_note="365498">1</sup></span> upon them a sign from heaven, at which their necks would stay bent in humility.",footnotes:345961:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…We can send down upon them…”</span>
  26,5,"But no fresh reminder comes to them from the All-Merciful but they disregard it."
  26,6,"Thus they have certainly disbelieved, but soon will come to them the tidings of what they used to ridicule."
  26,7,"Have they not seen the land— how many noble kinds of plants We have germinated therein?"
  26,8,"Indeed, in that is a sign, and in no way were most of them believers."
  26,9,"And indeed, it is your<sup>sg</sup> Lord who is surely the Almighty, the Bestower of mercy."
  26,10,"And recall when Your Lord called to Moses, “Go to the unjust people—"
  26,11,"the people of Pharaoh. Will they never be mindful?”"
  26,12,"He said, “My Lord, I fear that they will disbelieve me."
  26,13,"And my chest <span class="h">tightens<sup foot_note="365499">1</sup></span> and my tongue is not fluent, so send for Aaron <small>(too)</small>.",footnotes:345962:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “I fear that they will disbelieve me <sub><small>13</small></sub>13 and that my chest will tighten and my tongue will not be fluent,”</span>
  26,14,"And they hold <small>(a charge of)</small> a misdeed against me, so I fear they will kill me.”"
  26,15,"He said, “By no means! So go<sup>dl</sup>, with Our signs; We are with you<sup>pl</sup>, listening."
  26,16,"So go<sup>dl</sup> to Pharaoh and say, ‘We are indeed the Messenger of the Lord of all realms:"
  26,17,"send the Children of Israel with us.’”"
  26,18,"He said, “Did we not raise you<sup>sg</sup> among us as a child, and you stayed among us for many years of your life?"
  26,19,"And you<sup>sg</sup> committed that base deed of yours that you committed while you were one of the deniers<sup foot_note="365500">1</sup> .”",footnotes:345963:A denier of Pharaoh's grace.
  26,20,"He said, “I did it then while I was one of those astray."
  26,21,"And I fled from you<sup>pl</sup> when I feared you, then my Lord gave me wise judgment and made me one of the emissaries."
  26,22,"And is that a favor you<sup>sg</sup> remind me of: that you have enslaved the Children of Israel?”"
  26,23,"Pharaoh said, “And what is the Lord of all realms?”"
  26,24,"He said, “The Lord of the heavens and the earth and whatever is between them, if you<sup>pl</sup> <small>(can ever)</small> believe with certitude.”"
  26,25,"He said to those around him, “Are you listening?”"
  26,26,"He said, “Your<sup>pl</sup> Lord and the Lord of your ancient fathers.”"
  26,27,"He said, “This messenger of yours who has been sent to you is certainly a madman.”"
  26,28,"He said, “The Lord of the east and the west and whatever is between them, if you<sup>pl</sup> can <small>(ever)</small> reason.”"
  26,29,"He said, “If you<sup>sg</sup> accept any god other than me, I will surely make you of the imprisoned.”"
  26,30,"He said, “What if I bring you<sup>sg</sup> something evident?”"
  26,31,"He said, “Bring it, if you<sup>sg</sup> are of the truthful.”"
  26,32,"So he cast his staff and thereupon it was an evident serpent."
  26,33,"And he pulled his hand and thereupon it was white for the beholders."
  26,34,"He said to the chiefs around him, “This is indeed a knowledgeable sorcerer"
  26,35,"who wants to evict you from your land with his sorcery, so what do you command?”"
  26,36,"They said, “Put him off, and his brother, and send summoners to the cities"
  26,37,"to bring you<sup>sg</sup> every knowledgeable magician.”"
  26,38,"So the sorcerers were assembled for the appointment on a specified day."
  26,39,"And people were told, “Are you going to assemble,"
  26,40,"that we may follow the sorcerers if they are the overcomers?”"
  26,41,"So when the sorcerers arrived, they said to Pharaoh, “Is there a reward for us if we are the overcomers?”"
  26,42,"He said, “Yes, and you will then most surely become of those brought near <small>(to me)</small>.”"
  26,43,"Moses said to them, “Cast whatever you intend to cast.”"
  26,44,"So they cast their ropes and their staffs and said, “By Pharaoh's might, we are most surely the overcomers.”"
  26,45,"Then Moses threw his staff, and thereupon it swallowed what they had fabricated."
  26,46,"So the sorcerers fell down prostrating."
  26,47,"They said, “We have attained faith in the Lord of all realms,"
  26,48,"the Lord of Moses and Aaron.”"
  26,49,"He said, “Have you<sup>pl</sup> believed in him before I have given you permission? He must be your leader who taught you sorcery. Well, you will certainly know soon; I will most surely cut off your hands and feet on opposite sides, and I will most surely crucify you all.”"
  26,50,"They said, “No problem; indeed, to our Lord we are returning."
  26,51,"We ardently hope our Lord will forgive us our offenses, as we were the first of the believers.”"
  26,52,"And We revealed to Moses: “Journey with My servants by night; you<sup>pl</sup> will indeed be followed.”"
  26,53,"So Pharaoh sent summoners to the cities."
  26,54,"“Indeed, these are just a small gang,"
  26,55,"and they certainly do enrage us."
  26,56,"But indeed, we are <span class="h">cautious<sup foot_note="365501">1</sup></span>.”",footnotes:345964:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Hisham, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…we are constantly cautious.”</span>
  26,57,"So We got them out from gardens and springs"
  26,58,"and treasures and a noble domicile."
  26,59,"So it was. And We made the Children of Israel inherit them."
  26,60,"And they pursued them at sunrise."
  26,61,"And when the two groups sighted each other, the followers of Moses said, “We are indeed overtaken!”"
  26,62,"He said, “By no means! My Lord is indeed with me; He will guide me.”"
  26,63,"So We revealed to Moses: “Strike the sea with your staff,” whereupon it split, so that each part was like a great hill."
  26,64,"And thereupon, we brought the others near."
  26,65,"Then We saved Moses and those with him, all of them."
  26,66,"Then We drowned the others."
  26,67,"Most surely in that is a sign, and in no way were most of them believers."
  26,68,"And most surely, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is the Almighty, the Bestower of mercy."
  26,69,"And relate to them the tiding of Abraham,"
  26,70,"when he said to his father and his people, “What do you worship?”"
  26,71,"They said, “We worship human-shaped idols and we remain consecrating ourselves to them.”"
  26,72,"He said, “Can they hear you<sup>pl</sup> when you call?"
  26,73,"Or can they benefit you, or can they do harm?”"
  26,74,"They said, “Rather, we found our forefathers doing so.”"
  26,75,"He said, “Have you seen what you have been worshiping,"
  26,76,"you and your ancient fathers?"
  26,77,"They are enemies to me, except for the Lord of all realms,"
  26,78,"Who created me and therefore He guides me;"
  26,79,"and Who feeds me and gives me to drink;"
  26,80,"and when I get sick, He heals me;"
  26,81,"and Who makes me die and then revives me;"
  26,82,"and Whom I ardently hope will forgive me my offense on the Day of Recompense.”"
  26,83,"“My Lord, grant me wise judgment and include me with the righteous,"
  26,84,"and make me a reputation of truth among later generations,"
  26,85,"and make me of the inheritors of the Garden of Bliss,"
  26,86,"and forgive my father—he was indeed one of those astray,"
  26,87,"and do not disgrace me on the day they are resurrected:"
  26,88,"the day when neither wealth nor children are of help—"
  26,89,"except for one who has come<sup foot_note="365502">1</sup> to Allah with a sound heart.”",footnotes:345965:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  26,90,"And the Garden <small>(of Paradise) </small>was brought<sup foot_note="365503">1</sup> near for those who had been mindful,",footnotes:345966:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  26,91,"while purgatory was displayed to the deluded ones."
  26,92,"And they were told, “Where is what you used to worship"
  26,93,"apart from Allah? Can they support you or get support for themselves?”"
  26,94,"Then they were toppled into it, together with the deluded ones"
  26,95,"and the troops of Iblis<sup foot_note="365504">1</sup>, all of them.",footnotes:345967:Iblis is another name of Satan or <i>Shaytan</i>.
  26,96,"They said, as they disputed about it,"
  26,97,"<small>“(We swear) </small>by Allah, we were surely in evident misguidance"
  26,98,"for equating you<sup>pl</sup> with the Lord of all realms."
  26,99,"But no one misguided us except the criminals."
  26,100,"And now we neither have intercessors"
  26,101,"nor any intimate friend."
  26,102,"So if only we could have another chance, we would be of the believers.”"
  26,103,"Most surely in that is a sign, and in no way were most of them believers."
  26,104,"And most surely, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is the Almighty, the Bestower of mercy."
  26,105,"The people of Noah disbelieved the emissaries"
  26,106,"when their brother Noah said to them, “Will you never be mindful?"
  26,107,"Indeed, I am to you a trustworthy messenger."
  26,108,"So be mindful of Allah and obey me."
  26,109,"And I ask of you no reward for this, for my reward is only from the Lord of all realms."
  26,110,"So be mindful of Allah and obey me.”"
  26,111,"They said, “Shall we believe in you, when <small>(only)</small> the lowliest have followed <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="365505">1</sup></span>?”",footnotes:345968:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “Shall we believe in you and your followers— the lowliest?”</span>
  26,112,"He said, “What do I know about what they used to do?"
  26,113,"Their reckoning rests only with my Lord, if only you were aware."
  26,114,"And in no way would I expel the believers;"
  26,115,"I am only an evident warner.”"
  26,116,"They said, “If you do not refrain, O Noah, you will most surely be of those stoned.”"
  26,117,"He said, “My Lord, my people have disbelieved me."
  26,118,"So legislate between me and them decisively, and deliver me and those who are with me of the believers."
  26,119,"So We saved him and those with him in the laden ship."
  26,120,"Then We drowned the rest."
  26,121,"Most surely in that is a sign, and in no way were most of them believers."
  26,122,"And most surely, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is the Almighty, the Bestower of mercy."
  26,123,"Ād<sup foot_note="365506">1</sup> disbelieved the emissaries",footnotes:345969:The pagan tribe of Prophet Hûd.
  26,124,"when their brother Hûd said to them, “Will you never be mindful?"
  26,125,"Indeed, I am to you<sup>pl</sup> a trustworthy messenger."
  26,126,"So be mindful of Allah and obey me."
  26,127,"And I ask of you no reward for this, for my reward is only from the Lord of all realms."
  26,128,"Do you build a sign on every height for vanity's sake?"
  26,129,"And you set up fortresses, hoping to live eternally?"
  26,130,"And when you<sup>pl</sup> strike, you strike mercilessly?"
  26,131,"So be mindful of Allah and obey me."
  26,132,"And be mindful of the One who supplied you with whatever you know."
  26,133,"He supplied you with livestock and children"
  26,134,"and gardens and springs."
  26,135,"Indeed, I fear for you the punishment of a great day.”"
  26,136,"They said, "It is equal to us, whether you admonish or be not of those who admonish."
  26,137,"This is nothing but the <span class="h">character<sup foot_note="365507">1</sup></span> of the ancients,",footnotes:345970:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Amer, Asem, Hamza and Khalaf read it as: “…but the creation of the ancients,”</span>
  26,138,"and we will never be punished.”"
  26,139,"So they disbelieved him; thus We annihilated them. Most surely in that is a sign, and in no way were most of them believers."
  26,140,"And most surely, Your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is the Almighty, the Bestower of mercy."
  26,141,"Thamûd<sup foot_note="365508">1</sup> disbelieved the emissaries",footnotes:345971:The pagan tribe of Prophet Salih.
  26,142,"when their brother Salih said to them, “Will you never be mindful?"
  26,143,"Indeed, I am to you a trustworthy messenger."
  26,144,"So be mindful of Allah and obey me."
  26,145,"And I ask of you no reward for this, for my reward is only from the Lord of all realms."
  26,146,"Will you <small>(always)</small> be left secure in whatever is here?"
  26,147,"In gardens and springs"
  26,148,"and vegetation<small>(s)</small>, and palm-trees with tender yield?"
  26,149,"And you carve houses in the mountains, with <span class="h">skill<sup foot_note="365509">1</sup></span>?",footnotes:345972:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…with great skill?”</span>
  26,150,"So be mindful of Allah and obey me."
  26,151,"And do not obey the command of the extremists:"
  26,152,"those who spread corruption in the land and do not reform.”"
  26,153,"They said, “You are surely one of the bewitched;"
  26,154,"you are nothing but a human being like us, so bring us a sign if you are of the truthful.”"
  26,155,"He said, “This is a she-camel; she has her turn to drink, and you have your turn to drink on a well-known day."
  26,156,"And do not touch her with any harm, lest the punishment of a great day seize you.”"
  26,157,"But they hamstrung her, then became remorseful<sup foot_note="365510">1</sup> .",footnotes:345973:When they saw the signs of punishment.
  26,158,"So the punishment seized them. Most surely in that is a sign, and in no way were most of them believers."
  26,159,"And most surely, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is the Almighty, the Bestower of mercy."
  26,160,"The people of Lot disbelieved the emissaries"
  26,161,"when their brother Lot said to them, “Will you never be mindful?"
  26,162,"Indeed, I am to you a trustworthy messenger."
  26,163,"So be mindful of Allah and obey me."
  26,164,"And I ask of you no reward for this, for my reward is only from the Lord of all realms."
  26,165,"Of all the creatures in all realms, do you<sup>pl</sup> approach males?"
  26,166,"And you leave what your Lord has created for you of spouses? Rather, you are a people who have transgressed.”"
  26,167,"They said, “Unless you refrain, O Lot, you will most surely be of those evicted.”"
  26,168,"He said, “I am certainly one of those who abhor your practice.”"
  26,169,"“My Lord, deliver me and my family from what they practice.”"
  26,170,"So We delivered him and his family, all of them,"
  26,171,"except for an old woman among those who lingered behind."
  26,172,"Then We destroyed the others."
  26,173,"And We rained down upon them a rain, so how bad was the rain of those forewarned!"
  26,174,"Most surely in that is a sign, and in no way were most of them believers."
  26,175,"And most surely, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is the Almighty, the Bestower of mercy."
  26,176,"The Fellows of the Thicket disbelieved the emissaries"
  26,177,"when Shu’aib said to them, “Will you never be mindful?"
  26,178,"Indeed, I am to you a trustworthy messenger."
  26,179,"So be mindful of Allah and obey me."
  26,180,"And I ask of you no reward for this, for my reward is only from the Lord of all realms."
  26,181,"Give full measure and do not be of the cheaters,"
  26,182,"and weigh with accurate scales"
  26,183,"and do not defraud people of their belongings, and do not go wickedly about the land, corrupting it."
  26,184,"And be mindful of the One Who created you<sup>pl</sup> and the masses of old.”"
  26,185,"They said, “You are surely one of the bewitched."
  26,186,"And you are nothing but a human being like us, and we think that you are surely of the liars."
  26,187,"So make <span class="h">pieces<sup foot_note="365511">1</sup></span> from heaven fall on us, if you are of the truthful.”",footnotes:345974:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as: “…make fragments from heaven…”</span>
  26,188,"He said, “My Lord knows better what you do.”"
  26,189,"But they disbelieved him, so the punishment of the Day of Gloom seized them; it was indeed the punishment of a great day."
  26,190,"Most surely in that is a sign, and in no way were most of them believers."
  26,191,"And most surely, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is the Almighty, the Bestower of mercy."
  26,192,"And most surely, it is a bestowal from on high from the Lord of all realms."
  26,193,"The Trustworthy Spirit came down with <span class="h">it<sup foot_note="365512">1</sup></span>",footnotes:345975:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Hafs and Abu Ja’far read it as: “He bestowed the Trustworthy Spirit with it from on high…”</span>
  26,194,"upon your<sup>sg</sup> heart, that you may be of the forewarners,"
  26,195,"in an evident Arabic tongue."
  26,196,"And it is in the books of the ancients."
  26,197,"Is it not a sign for them that the scholars of the Children of Israel recognized it?"
  26,198,"And had We bestowed it from on high upon some non-Arabs"
  26,199,"and he had recited it to them, they would still not have believed in it."
  26,200,"Thus We inserted it into the hearts of the criminals."
  26,201,"They will not believe in it until they witness the painful punishment"
  26,202,"which will come to them suddenly while they are unaware."
  26,203,"Then they will say, “Will we be reprieved?”"
  26,204,"So do they seek to hasten Our punishment?"
  26,205,"So have you<sup>sg</sup> seen if We let them enjoy <small>(life)</small> for <small>(many)</small> years,"
  26,206,"then there comes to them what they were promised,"
  26,207,"of what avail to them will their past enjoyments be?"
  26,208,"And never did We destroy a town but it had forewarners—"
  26,209,"a reminding, and in no way have We been unjust."
  26,210,"And in no way have the devils been descending with it,"
  26,211,"for it neither suits them nor is it in their power."
  26,212,"They are indeed barred from hearing <small>(it)</small>."
  26,213,"So do not call upon any other god with Allah, lest you<sup>sg</sup> be of those punished."
  26,214,"And warn your<sup>sg</sup> kinsfolk,"
  26,215,"and lower your wing<sup foot_note="365513">1</sup> for those of the believers who have followed you.",footnotes:345976:An expression that implies showing compassion.
  26,216,"But if they disobey you, say, “I am indeed innocent of what you do.”"
  26,217,"<span class="h">And<sup foot_note="365514">1</sup></span> place your trust in the Almighty, the Bestower of mercy,",footnotes:345977:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “Then place your trust…”</span>
  26,218,"Who sees you when you rise,"
  26,219,"as well as your movement among those who prostrate;"
  26,220,"indeed, He is the All-Hearing, the All-Knowing."
  26,221,"Shall I inform you<sup>pl</sup> upon whom the devils keep descending?"
  26,222,"They keep descending upon every sinful fabricator."
  26,223,"They give ear, and most of them are liars."
  26,224,"And as for the poets—the deluded ones follow them."
  26,225,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen that they aimlessly roam in every valley?"
  26,226,"And that they say what they do not do?"
  26,227,"Except for those who attained faith and did righteous deeds and remembered Allah frequently and defended themselves after they had been dealt with unjustly. And those who have been unjust will know the place of return to which they are bound to return."
  27,1,"Tâ Sîn. Those are the signs<sup foot_note="365515">1</sup> of the Recital<sup foot_note="365516">2</sup> and an Evident Scripture—",footnotes:345978:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.|345979:The Arabic word used is Quran which means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  27,2,"guidance and glad tidings for the believers"
  27,3,"who establish the prayer and bring<sup foot_note="365517">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="365518">2</sup> and, of the Hereafter, they are certain.",footnotes:345980:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|345981:The Arabic word used is z<i>akāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  27,4,"Indeed, those who do not believe in the Hereafter—We have adorned their deeds for them, so they wander aimlessly;"
  27,5,"those are the ones for whom is the worst punishment, and in the Hereafter they are the biggest losers."
  27,6,"And indeed, you<sup>sg</sup> are surely receiving the Recital<sup foot_note="365519">1</sup> from One who is All-Wise, All-Knowing.",footnotes:345982:The Arabic word used is Quran which means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  27,7,"Recall when Moses said to his family, “I have surely glimpsed a fire. I will bring you some news from it, or bring you a firebrand, a borrowed <span class="h">flame<sup foot_note="365520">1</sup></span>, that you may warm yourselves.”",footnotes:345983:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…or bring you a firebrand of a borrowed flame,”</span>
  27,8,"Then when he reached it, he was called: “Blessed is whoever is in the fire and whoever is around it, and Highly Exalted is Allah, Lord of all realms."
  27,9,"O Moses, it is indeed I, Allah, the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  27,10,"Now, cast your staff.” So when he saw it shaking as though it were a snake, he turned away, fleeing, and did not look back. “O Moses, fear not! Truly, in My presence emissaries have nothing to fear,"
  27,11,"except for one who did an injustice then substituted kindness for evil—then I am surely Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  27,12,"And put your hand inside the opening of your garment <small>(and)</small> it will come out white, without any evil affliction—among nine signs to Pharaoh and his people; they have indeed been a defiantly disobedient people.”"
  27,13,"So when Our signs came to them as an eye-opener, they said, “This is evident sorcery.”"
  27,14,"And they repudiated them, though their <small>(inner)</small> selves were certain of them—out of injustice and haughtiness; so look<sup>sg</sup> what the outcome was for the corrupters."
  27,15,"And indeed, We brought David and Solomon knowledge, and they said, “Praise be to Allah, Who has favored us over many of His believing servants.”"
  27,16,"And Solomon succeeded David, and he said, “O mankind, we have been taught the language of birds, and we have been given of everything; this is most surely the evident grace.”"
  27,17,"And to the service of Solomon were herded his troops of unseen beings<sup foot_note="365521">1</sup> and men and birds, all held in strict order,",footnotes:345984:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.
  27,18,"until, when they came upon the valley of ants, an ant said, “O you ants! Enter into your homes, lest Solomon and his troops crush you while they are unaware.”"
  27,19,"So he smiled, laughing at her speech, and said, “My Lord, direct me to be thankful for Your blessings which you have bestowed upon me and upon my parents, and to do righteousness that well pleases You. And include me, by Your mercy, among Your righteous servants.”"
  27,20,"Then he inspected the birds and said, “What is it with me? Can I not see the hoopoe, or is he among the absentees?"
  27,21,"Most surely, I will either punish him severely or slay him, unless he brings me an evident excuse.”"
  27,22,"But he did not stay away for long and he said, “I have encompassed that which you have not encompassed, and I have come to you from Sheba with sure tidings."
  27,23,"I found a woman reigning over them, and she has been given of everything, and she has a great throne."
  27,24,"I found her and her people prostrating to the sun apart from Allah, for Satan has adorned their deeds for them and has thus barred them from the way, so that they are not guided—"
  27,25,"that they do <span class="h">not<sup foot_note="365522">1</sup></span> prostrate themselves to Allah, Who brings out what is hidden in the heavens and the earth, and knows whatever <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="365523">2</sup></span> hide and whatever you make public.",footnotes:345985:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Kesa’i, Abu Ja’afar and Roways read it as: “…that they are not guided. <sub><small>25</small></sub>25 ‘How can they not prostrate themselves to Allah, Who brings out what is hidden in the heavens and the earth …….make public?’”</span>|345986:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…whatever they hide and whatever they make public.”</span>
  27,26,"Allah—there is no god but He, Lord of the Great Throne.”"
  27,27,"He said, “We will see whether you have spoken the truth or have been one of the liars."
  27,28,"Go with this letter of mine and cast it to them, then turn away from them and wait to see what they say to each other.”"
  27,29,"She said, “O chiefs, a noble letter has indeed been cast down to me;"
  27,30,"it is indeed from Solomon, and it is indeed, ‘In the name of Allah, the All-Merciful, the Bestower of mercy:"
  27,31,"You must not exalt yourselves above me and must come to me as Muslims<sup foot_note="365524">1</sup> .’”",footnotes:345987:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  27,32,"She said, “O chiefs, give me your opinion in this matter of mine. I never take a decision on any matter except in your presence.”"
  27,33,"They said, “We are a people of power and of intense force, and you are in command, so see what you wish to command.”"
  27,34,"She said, “Indeed, when kings enter a town, they corrupt it and humiliate its dignified people, and this is what they <small>(always)</small> do."
  27,35,"Thus I am sending them a gift and will see what the emissaries return with.”"
  27,36,"So when he came to Solomon, he said, “Are you<sup>pl</sup> supplying me with wealth? What Allah has brought me is better than what He has brought you. Rather, it is you who rejoice when given gifts."
  27,37,"Return<sup>sg</sup> back to them. Indeed, we will come upon them with troops they cannot resist, and indeed, we will evict them from it, humiliated and dishonored.”"
  27,38,"He said, “O chiefs, which one of you can bring me her throne before they come to me as Muslims<sup foot_note="365525">1</sup> ?”",footnotes:345988:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  27,39,"A powerful one of the unseen beings<sup foot_note="365526">1</sup> said, “I will bring it to you<sup>sg</sup> before you rise from your seat, and indeed, I am certainly strong (<small>and</small>) trustworthy enough to do it.”",footnotes:345989:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.
  27,40,"The one who had knowledge of the Scripture said, “I will bring it to you before you blink your eye.” So when he saw it settled before him, he said, “This is of my Lord’s grace, to test me: whether I will thank or will deny. For whoever is thankful is only thankful to his own benefit, and whoever has denied<sup foot_note="365527">1</sup> —my Lord is, indeed, Self-Sufficient, Noble.”",footnotes:345990:The Arabic word used is '<i>kafar</i> which has two connotations: ‘disbelief’ if denying God or ‘ingratitude’ if denying His grace.
  27,41,"He said, “Disguise her throne for her, and we shall see whether she will be guided or be one of those who are never guided.”"
  27,42,"So when she arrived, it was said, “Is your throne like this?” She said, “As if this is it.” <small>(Solomon said,)</small> “And We were given knowledge before her and we have always been Muslims<sup foot_note="365528">1</sup> .”",footnotes:345991:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  27,43,"But she was barred by whatever she used to worship apart from Allah; indeed, she was of a denying people."
  27,44,"She was told, “Enter the tower.” And when she saw it, she thought it was a deep pond and she bared her legs. He said, “It is a tower paved with glass.” She said, “My Lord, I have indeed been unjust to myself, and I have submitted with Solomon to Allah, Lord of all realms.”"
  27,45,"And indeed, We sent to Thamûd their brother Saleh <small>(saying)</small>, “Worship Allah.” But they promptly became two disputing groups."
  27,46,"He said, “O my people, why do you ask that the bad be hastened before the good? If only you would ask Allah’s forgiveness so that you may be shown mercy.”"
  27,47,"They said, “We consider you<sup>sg</sup> a bad omen, and those with you <small>(too)</small>.” He said, “Your omen is with Allah. In fact, you are a people being tried.”"
  27,48,"And there were nine persons in the city who were spreading corruption in the land and would not reform."
  27,49,"They said, “Swear by Allah to one another that <span class="h">we<sup foot_note="365529">1</sup></span> will surely attack him and his family at night, and then we will emphatically tell his kinsman seeking retribution, 'We did not witness the murder of his family, and we are indeed truthful.'”",footnotes:345992:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “that you will surely attack him and his family at night, and then you will emphatically tell his kinsman…”</span>
  27,50,"And they schemed a scheme, and We schemed a scheme while they were unaware."
  27,51,"So look<sup>sg</sup> at how the outcome of their scheming was that <span class="h">We<sup foot_note="365530">1</sup></span> did destroy them and their people, all of them.",footnotes:345993:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…how the outcome of their scheming was: We did destroy them…”</span>
  27,52,"So here are their houses, vacant, on account of their injustice. Indeed, in this is surely a sign for people who know."
  27,53,"And We saved those who believed and were mindful <small>(of God)</small>."
  27,54,"And Lot <small>(too)</small>, when he said to his people, “Do you commit obscenity while you can see <small>(its shamefulness)</small>?"
  27,55,"Do you approach men with lust instead of women? Rather you are an ignorant people.”"
  27,56,"But the only response of his people was to say, “Evict Lot's folk from your town; indeed, they are a few people who always keep themselves clean.”"
  27,57,"So We saved him and his family, except for his wife, whom We destined to be of those who lingered behind."
  27,58,"And We rained upon them a rain, and so evil was the rain of the forewarned."
  27,59,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Praise be to Allah and peace be upon His servants whom He has elected. Is Allah better or what <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="365531">1</sup></span> associate?”",footnotes:345994:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Abu Amr, Asem and Ya’qub read it as: “…what you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> associate?”</span>
  27,60,"Or who <small>(else then)</small> is the one who created the heavens and the earth, and sent down to you<sup>pl</sup> from the sky water with which We<sup foot_note="365532">1</sup> germinated gardens full of beauty, whose trees you could not have germinated? Is there any other god with Allah? Rather, they are a people who equate<sup foot_note="365533">2</sup> .",footnotes:345995:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.|345996:Equate others with God.
  27,61,"Or who <small>(else then)</small> is the one who made the earth habitable and made rivers flow through it and set firm mountains for it and placed a partition between the two seas? Is there any other god with Allah? Rather, most of them do not know."
  27,62,"Or who <small>(else then) </small>is the one who responds to someone in need when he calls upon Him and relieves evil and makes you successors on earth? Is there any other god with Allah? Little do you <span class="h">remind<sup foot_note="365534">1</sup></span> yourselves.",footnotes:345997:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr, Hisham and Rouh read it as: “Little do they constantly remember.” All except for Abu Amr, Hisham, Rouh, Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and khalaf read it as: ““…little do you<sup><small>p</small></sup> constantly remember”.</span>
  27,63,"Or who <small>(else then) </small>is the one who guides you<sup>pl</sup> through the darkness<small>(es)</small> of the land and the sea, and Who sends the <span class="h">winds<sup foot_note="365535">1</sup></span> as heralds of glad <span class="h">tidings<sup foot_note="365536">2</sup></span> before His mercy? Is there any other god with Allah? Most High is Allah above what they associate.",footnotes:345998:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “wind”.</span>|345999:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Abu Ja’far, Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “… as revivers ahead of His mercy.”All except for Asem, Nafie, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Abu Ja’far, Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “….as a revival ahead of His mercy.”</span>
  27,64,"Or who <small>(else then) </small>is the one who originates creation and then restores it, and Who provides for you<sup>pl</sup> from the sky and the land? Is there any other god with Allah? Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Produce your<sup>pl</sup> proof, if you are truthful.”"
  27,65,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “No one in the heavens or the earth knows what is hidden except Allah.” For they are unaware of when they will be resurrected;"
  27,66,"rather, their knowledge has been <span class="h">reached<sup foot_note="365537">1</sup></span> in the Hereafter; rather, they are in doubt about it; rather, they are completely blind to it.",footnotes:346000:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Abu Ja’far, and Ya’qub read it as: “…rather, their knowledge has been grasped in the Hereafter;”</span>
  27,67,"And those who denied said, “Can it be <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="365538">1</sup></span> when we have become dust, and our forefathers—can it be that we will really be brought out?",footnotes:346001:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “Can it be that when we have become dust, and our forefathers, we will really be brought out?” Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “When we have become dust, and our forefathers—can it be that we will really …”</span>
  27,68,"Most surely, we were promised this before, we and our forefathers; this is nothing but the legends of the ancients.”"
  27,69,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Journey through the earth and look what the outcome was for the criminals.”"
  27,70,"But do<sup>sg</sup> not grieve over them and do not be troubled by what they scheme."
  27,71,"And they say, “When is this promise, if you are truthful?”"
  27,72,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Perhaps some of what you are asking to be hastened has drawn near.”"
  27,73,"And indeed, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is surely the Possessor of grace towards mankind, but most of them are not thankful."
  27,74,"And indeed, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord knows whatever their chests harbor and whatever they make public."
  27,75,"And never is there anything hidden in the heaven or the earth but it is in an evident record<sup foot_note="365539">1</sup> .",footnotes:346002:Literally ‘scripture’.
  27,76,"This Recital<sup foot_note="365540">1</sup> indeed narrates to the Children of Israel most of what they differ over,",footnotes:346003:The Arabic word used is <i>Quran</i> which means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  27,77,"and most surely it is a guidance and a mercy to the believers."
  27,78,"Indeed, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord decrees between them by His wise judgment, and He is the Almighty, the All-Knowing."
  27,79,"So place yoursg trust in Allah; you are indeed upon the evident truth."
  27,80,"Indeed, you<sup>sg</sup> cannot make the dead hear, nor can you <span class="h">make<sup foot_note="365541">1</sup></span> the deaf hear the call if they withdraw and turn their backs.",footnotes:346004:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “…nor can the deaf hear…”</span>
  27,81,"Nor can you<sup>sg</sup> <span class="h">guide<sup foot_note="365542">1</sup></span> the blind out of their utter misguidance; you can make no one hear except those who believe in Our signs, and are <small>(thus)</small> Muslims<sup foot_note="365543">2</sup> .",footnotes:346005:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “Nor do you guide the blind…”</span>|346006:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimoon</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  27,82,"And when the decree is fulfilled against them, We will bring out for them—from the earth—a treading creature that will tell them <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="365544">1</sup></span> mankind used to have no certitude in Our signs.",footnotes:346007:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…a treading creature that will speak to them. Indeed, mankind…”</span>
  27,83,"On the day when We herd from every community a crowd of those who disbelieve our signs, so that they are held in strict order."
  27,84,"Until, when they come <small>(before their Lord)</small>, He will say, "Did you deny My signs and did you not encompass them in knowledge, or what were you doing?""
  27,85,"And the decree shall be fulfilled against them for the injustices they did, and they shall be speechless."
  27,86,"Have they not seen that We have made the night for them to rest therein and the day allowing sight? Indeed, in that are signs for people who believe."
  27,87,"And on the day when the Trumpet is blown, and everyone in the heavens and the earth was<sup foot_note="365545">1</sup> horrified, except whomever Allah willed, and everyone came before Him in humility.",footnotes:346008:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  27,88,"And you<sup>sg</sup> see the mountains, thinking them fixed, yet they pass as the passing of the clouds—the making of Allah Who has perfected everything; He is indeed All-Aware of what <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="365546">1</sup></span> do.",footnotes:346009:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Hisham, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…what they do.”</span>
  27,89,"Whoever comes with a good deed—for him is one better than it and they are safe from <span class="h">horror<sup foot_note="365547">1</sup></span> on that day,",footnotes:346010:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…from the horror of that day,”</span>
  27,90,"while whoever comes with an evil deed—their faces are tumbled into the Fire. “Are you<sup foot_note="365548">1</sup> being repaid except for what you used to do?”",footnotes:346011:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 2<sup><small>nd</small></sup> person.
  27,91,"<small>(Say</small><small>sg</small><small>)</small> “Indeed, I have only been commanded to worship the Lord of this township, Who has made it inviolable and to Whom everything belongs, and I have been commanded to be of the Muslims<sup foot_note="365549">1</sup>",footnotes:346012:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  27,92,"and to read the Recital<sup foot_note="365550">1</sup> ; so whoever is guided, then he is surely guided to his own benefit. And whoever goes astray, then say, "Indeed, I am only one of the forewarners."",footnotes:346013:The Arabic word used is <i>Quran</i> which means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  27,93,"And say<sup>sg</sup>, “Praise be to Allah; He will show you<sup>pl</sup> His signs and you will recognize them. For in no way is your<sup>sg</sup> Lord oblivious of what you<sup>pl</sup> <span class="h">do<sup foot_note="365551">1</sup></span>.”",footnotes:346014:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Amer, Hafs, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…what they do.”</span>
  28,1,"Tâ Sîn Mīm."
  28,2,"Those are the signs<sup foot_note="365552">1</sup> of the Evident Scripture.",footnotes:346015:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular a<i>yah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  28,3,"We read to you<sup>sg</sup> from the tiding of Moses and Pharaoh in truth for people who believe."
  28,4,"Indeed, Pharaoh became exalted in the land and divided its people into sects, deeming a faction of them weak and oppressed: slaughtering their sons while keeping their women alive <small>(in bondage)</small>. Indeed, he was one of the corrupters."
  28,5,"Thus We are willing to favor those who were deemed weak and oppressed in the land and to make them leaders and to make them the inheritors"
  28,6,"and to establish them in the land and to show Pharaoh and Hamān and their troops from them the very thing they used to <span class="h">fear<sup foot_note="365553">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346016:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…and so that Pharaoh and Hamān and their troops would see from them the very thing they used to fear.”</span>
  28,7,"And We revealed to Moses' mother, “Nurse him, then when you fear for him, cast him into the waters and do not fear and do not grieve; We are surely returning him to you and making him one of the emissaries.”"
  28,8,"Then Pharaoh’s folk picked him up <small>(only)</small> to be an enemy and a <small>(source of)</small> grief for them. Indeed, Pharaoh and Hamān and their troops were wrongdoers."
  28,9,"So Pharaoh’s wife said, “A comfort to the eye for me and for you<sup>sg</sup>. Do<sup>pl</sup> not kill him; hopefully he may be useful to us, or we may take him as a son.” And they were unaware."
  28,10,"And Moses’ mother felt a void in her burning heart so that she almost declared him, had We not steadied her heart, that she may remain of the believers."
  28,11,"Thus she said to his sister, “Trail him.” So she watched him from afar while they were unaware."
  28,12,"And We had forbidden all wet nurses for him, so she said, “Shall I tell you<sup>pl</sup> about a household that can raise him for you and look after him?”"
  28,13,"Thus We returned him to his mother, that her eye might be comforted and that she may not grieve, and so that she would know that Allah’s promise is true; yet most of them do not know."
  28,14,"And when he had attained his full strength and had matured, We gave him wise judgment and knowledge, for thus do We repay those who excel in doing good."
  28,15,"And <small>(one day)</small> he entered the city unnoticed by its people and found in it two men fighting—one of his own sect and one from his enemies, so the one of his sect solicited his assistance against the one from his enemies, so Moses struck him and put an end to him. He said, “This is of Satan's work; he is indeed an evidently misguiding enemy.”"
  28,16,"He said, “My Lord, I have indeed been unjust to myself, so forgive me.” So He forgave him; indeed, He is the Oft-Forgiving, the Bestower of mercy."
  28,17,"He said, “My Lord, because of the blessings You have bestowed upon me, I shall not be a backup for criminals.”"
  28,18,"So the next morning he was walking about the city, fearful (<small>and</small>) vigilant, when suddenly the man who had sought his support the day before cried out to him. Moses said to him, “You are an evident deluder.”"
  28,19,"And as he was about to strike the one who was their enemy, he said, “O Moses, do you want to kill me as you killed someone yesterday? You only want to be a tyrant in the land and do not want to be of the reformers.”"
  28,20,"And a man came running from the farthest part of the city; he said, “O Moses, the chiefs are conspiring to kill you, so get out; I am indeed one of those who seek to advise you.”"
  28,21,"So he went out of it, fearful (<small>and</small>) vigilant; he said, “My Lord, deliver me from the unjust people.”"
  28,22,"And as he headed towards Midian, he said, “Hopefully, my Lord will guide me to the right way.”"
  28,23,"And when he arrived at the waters of Midian he found there a crowd of people drawing water, and he found two women holding their flocks on the side. He said, “What is the matter with you<sup>dl</sup>?” They said, “We cannot draw water until the shepherds depart, and our father is a very old man.”"
  28,24,"So he drew water for them and then turned away to the shade and said, “My Lord, I am in dire need of whatever good you have sent down for me.”"
  28,25,"Then one of them came to him, walking bashfully. She said, “My father is calling you to repay you, as a reward for drawing water for us.” So when he came to him and narrated to him the narratives, he said, “Do not fear; you are <small>(now)</small> safe from the unjust people.”"
  28,26,"One of them said, “Father, hire him; indeed, the best one you can hire is one who is strong and trustworthy.”"
  28,27,"He said, “I surely wish to marry you to one of these two daughters of mine, provided you work for me for the term of eight pilgrimages; but if you complete ten, that is up to you, for I do not desire to impose any hardship on you. You will find me, Allah willing, one of the righteous.”"
  28,28,"He said, “Let this be <small>(an agreement)</small> between you and me; whichever of the two terms I fulfill, I will not have transgressed, and Allah is a trustee over what we say.”"
  28,29,"So when Moses had completed the term and journeyed with his family, he noticed a fire by the side of Mount Tûr. He said to his family, “Stay here; I have surely glimpsed a fire. Perhaps I can bring you<sup>pl</sup> some information from there, or an ember from the fire, that you may warm yourselves.”"
  28,30,"So when he reached it, he was called from the right side of the valley at the blessed spot, from the tree: “O Moses, indeed I—I alone—am Allah, Lord of all realms."
  28,31,"So throw down your<sup>sg</sup> staff.” And when he saw it shaking as if it were a snake, he turned away, fleeing, and did not look back. “O Moses, come forward and do not fear; you are indeed of the secure ones."
  28,32,"Put your<sup>sg</sup> hand inside your garment; it will come out white, without any bad affliction. And clasp to you your arm, that you should not be overawed, for those are two proofs from your Lord to Pharaoh and his chiefs; indeed, they have been a defiantly disobedient people.”"
  28,33,"He said, “My Lord, I have in fact killed one of them, and I fear lest they kill me."
  28,34,"And my brother Aaron—he is more eloquent than me, so send him with me as an assistant to confirm me; I do fear that they will disbelieve me.”"
  28,35,"He said, “We will strengthen your<sup>sg</sup> shoulder with your brother and give you<sup>dl</sup> authority so they will not be able to reach you. With Our signs, you<sup>dl</sup> and those who follow you will be the overcomers.”"
  28,36,"So when Moses came to them with Our signs, evident, they said, “This is nothing but fabricated sorcery, and We never heard of this among our ancient forefathers.”"
  28,37,"Thus <span class="h">Moses<sup foot_note="365554">1</sup></span> said, “My Lord knows better of the one who brings guidance from Him and who will have the future outcome of the Home; indeed, the unjust never succeed.”",footnotes:346017:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “Moses said…”</span>
  28,38,"And Pharaoh said, “O chiefs, I have never known of any god for you other than me. So fire-up clay-bricks for me, O Haman, and build me a tower, that perhaps I may view the God of Moses, though I definitely think he is of the liars.”"
  28,39,"Thus he and his troops went arrogantly about the land without any right, and they thought that they would not be <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365555">1</sup></span> to Us.",footnotes:346018:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “…would not return to Us.”</span>
  28,40,"So We took him and his troops and We threw them into the waters, so look what the outcome was for the unjust ones."
  28,41,"And We made them leaders calling to the Fire, and on the Day of Resurrection they are not supported."
  28,42,"And We caused a curse to follow them in this Earlier <small>(Life)</small>, and on the Day of Resurrection they are of the despised."
  28,43,"And We certainly brought Moses the Scripture after We had annihilated the earliest generations, as insights for mankind, and guidance and mercy, that perhaps they would remind themselves."
  28,44,"And you<sup>sg</sup> were not on the western side <small>(of the Mount)</small> when We decreed the command to Moses, nor were you<sup>sg</sup> of the witnesses."
  28,45,"Yet We established many generations<sup foot_note="365556">1</sup>, then the ages became seemingly long. Nor were you among the people of Midian, reading Our signs<sup foot_note="365557">2</sup> to them; but We have been sending emissaries.",footnotes:346019:After Moses.|346020:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  28,46,"Nor were you by the side of Mount Tûr when We called out. Rather, it was a mercy from your Lord so that you may warn a people to whom no warner had come before you, that perhaps they would remind themselves."
  28,47,"And <small>(We have sent you as a messenger)</small> lest a calamity befall them as a result of what their hands have put forth, and they say, “Our Lord, if only You had sent us a messenger, we would have followed Your signs and been among the believers.”"
  28,48,"But when the truth came to them from Our Providence, they said, “If only he was given the like of what was given to Moses.” Did they not deny what was given to Moses in the past? They said, “Two works<sup foot_note="365558">1</sup> of <span class="h">sorcery<sup foot_note="365559">2</sup></span>, backing one another.” And they said, “We deny both.”",footnotes:346021:The Qur'an and the Torah.|346022:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Two sorcerers, backing…”</span>
  28,49,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Then bring a scripture from Allah more conducive to guidance than both of them and I will follow it, if you<sup>pl</sup> are truthful.”"
  28,50,"But if they do not respond to you<sup>sg</sup>, know that they only follow their whims. And who is more misguided than one who follows his own whim without guidance from Allah? Indeed, Allah does not guide the unjust people."
  28,51,"And surely We have conveyed the Word to them, that they may remind themselves."
  28,52,"Those to whom We brought the Scripture before it believe in it,"
  28,53,"and when it is recited to them, they say, “We have believed in it; indeed, it is the truth from our Lord; indeed, we were Muslims<sup foot_note="365560">1</sup> prior to it.”",footnotes:346023:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  28,54,"Those are brought their reward twice on account of how they persevered patiently. And they counter evil with good and they spend from what We have provided them."
  28,55,"And when they hear idle talk they disregard it and say, “We have our deeds and you<sup>pl</sup> have your deeds; peace be upon you; we do not seek <small>(the company of)</small> ignorant people.”"
  28,56,"Indeed, you<sup>sg</sup> cannot guide whom you love, but Allah guides whom He wills, and He knows better of those who are guided."
  28,57,"And they said, “If we follow the guidance with you<sup>sg</sup>, we will be snatched from our land.” Did We not establish for them a safe sanctuary to which all kinds of fruit are brought as provision from Ourself? But most of them do not know."
  28,58,"And how many a town did We annihilate for becoming unappreciative of its livelihood? So here are their residences, uninhabited after them but little, and We have always been the inheritors."
  28,59,"And in no way would your<sup>sg</sup> Lord annihilate towns until He had sent to their mother-town a messenger reading to them Our signs<sup foot_note="365561">1</sup> . And in no way would We annihilate towns except if their people are unjust.",footnotes:346024:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.
  28,60,"And whatever you<sup>pl</sup> have been brought is <small>(merely)</small> the enjoyment of the Earlier Life and its adornment, but what is with Allah is better and longer lasting. Do <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="365562">1</sup></span> not reason?",footnotes:346025:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “Do they not reason?”</span>
  28,61,"Can someone to whom We have made a fine promise—which he is bound to encounter—be equal to someone whom We have allowed to enjoy the enjoyment of the Earlier Life, then on the Day of Resurrection will be one of the arraigned?"
  28,62,"On the day when He calls to them and says, “Where are My associates whom you used to claim?”"
  28,63,"Those against whom the sentence was justified said<sup foot_note="365563">1</sup>, “Our Lord, these are the ones whom we deluded. We deluded them as we ourselves were deluded. We declare our innocence before You; it was not us that they used to worship.”",footnotes:346026:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense, this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  28,64,"And it was said, “Call on your<sup>pl</sup> associates.” So they called them, but they did not respond to them, and they saw the punishment. If only they had sought guidance!"
  28,65,"And on the day when He calls<sup foot_note="365564">1</sup> to them and says, “What did you respond to the emissaries?”",footnotes:346027:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense.
  28,66,"Then all tidings were obscured<sup foot_note="365565">1</sup> for them on that day so they are unable to ask each other.",footnotes:346028:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense, this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  28,67,"But as for one who has repented and has attained faith and has acted righteously—hopefully, he will become of the successful."
  28,68,"And your<sup>sg</sup> Lord creates whatever He wills and He chooses. Never could the choice be theirs. Highly Exalted is Allah, and Most High is He above the associations they make."
  28,69,"And your<sup>sg</sup> Lord knows whatever their chests harbor and whatever they make public."
  28,70,"And He is Allah; there is no god but He. To Him belongs all praise in the first <small>(life)</small> and in the Hereafter, and to Him you<sup>pl</sup> are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365566">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346029:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…you return.”</span>
  28,71,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Have you<sup>pl</sup> seen if Allah were to make the night perpetual over you until the Day of Resurrection, which god other than Allah would bring you illumination? Do you not hear?”"
  28,72,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Have you<sup>pl</sup> seen if Allah were to make the day perpetual over you until the Day of Resurrection, which god other than Allah would bring you night to rest in? Do you not observe?”"
  28,73,"But out of His mercy, He has made for you<sup>pl</sup> night and day so that you may rest in it and seek of His grace, and that you may give thanks."
  28,74,"And on the day when He calls to them and says, “Where are My associates whom you used to claim?”"
  28,75,"And We drew<sup foot_note="365567">1</sup> out from every community a witness, then said, “Produce your proof,” so they realized that the truth belongs to Allah, and whatever they used to fabricate strayed away from them.",footnotes:346030:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  28,76,"Indeed, Qarun was of the people of Moses, but he oppressed them. And We had given him treasures, the keys of which would weigh down a band of strong men. Recall when his people said to him, “Do not exult; surely, Allah does not love the exultant."
  28,77,"And seek in whatever Allah has brought you<sup>sg</sup> the Home of the Hereafter, and do not forget your share of the Earlier <small>(Life) </small>, and do good as Allah has done good to you, and do not seek corruption in the land; indeed, Allah does not like the corrupters.”"
  28,78,"He said, “Indeed, it was only brought to me on account of knowledge I possess.” Did he not know that before him Allah had annihilated many generations who were stronger than he and had collected greater riches? And the criminals will not be asked about their misdeeds."
  28,79,"And he came out before his people in his splendor; those who wanted the Earlier Life said, “If only we possessed the likes of what Qarun was given. He is indeed very fortunate.”"
  28,80,"But those who were given knowledge said, “Woe to you! The recompense of Allah is better for those who have attained faith and have acted righteously.” Yet none is granted it except the patient ones."
  28,81,"So We caused the earth to swallow him and his home, then he had no battalion to support him apart from Allah, and he was not of those who could help themselves."
  28,82,"And by morning the ones who only yesterday had wished they were in his position were saying, “Indeed, it is Allah who extends His provision for whomever He wills of His servants, and He restrains <small>(it)</small>. Had Allah not been gracious to us, He would have caused it to swallow <span class="h">us<sup foot_note="365568">1</sup></span>. No wonder the deniers never succeed.”",footnotes:346031:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Hafs and Ya’qub read it as: “Had Allah not been gracious to us, we would have been swallowed. No wonder…”</span>
  28,83,"That is the Home of the Hereafter—We assign it for those who want no exaltation in the land nor corruption. And the future outcome is for those who are mindful <small>(of God)</small>."
  28,84,"Whoever has come with a good deed—for him there is better than it, but whoever has come with an evil deed—those who have done evil deeds will only be rewarded for what they used to do."
  28,85,"Indeed, He Who ordained the Recital<sup foot_note="365569">1</sup> upon you<sup>sg</sup> will surely return you to a great place of return. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “My Lord knows better who brings guidance and who is the one in evident misguidance.”",footnotes:346032:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  28,86,"And you did not <small>(even)</small> expect the Scripture would be cast to you<sup>sg</sup>, yet <small>(it was revealed to you)</small> as a mercy from your Lord, so never be a backup for the deniers."
  28,87,"And do not let them bar you<sup>sg</sup> from Allah’s signs<sup foot_note="365570">1</sup> after they have been sent down to you. And call to your Lord, and never be of those who associate <small>(others with God)</small>.",footnotes:346033:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  28,88,"And do not call<sup>sg</sup> upon any other god with Allah; there is no god but He. All things perish except His Countenance. Judgment belongs <small>(only)</small> to Him, and to Him you<sup>pl</sup> are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365571">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346034:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…you return.”</span>
  29,1,"Alif Lām Mīm."
  29,2,"Do people think that they will be left to say, "We believe" without being tested?"
  29,3,"Yet certainly We have tested those before them; thus Allah will surely know the truthful and He will surely know the liars."
  29,4,"Or do those who do evil deeds think that they can outstrip Us? Terrible is their judgment!"
  29,5,"Whoever expects the meeting with Allah—the appointed time of Allah is sure to come, and He is the All-Hearing, the All-Knowing."
  29,6,"Thus whoever strives—he only strives to his own benefit; most surely, Allah is Self-Sufficient <small>(without need for any of the creatures)</small> of all realms."
  29,7,"And as for those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—We will certainly remit their evil deeds and We will certainly repay them according to the best of what they used to do."
  29,8,"And We have enjoined upon man kindness towards his parents. But if they urge you<sup foot_note="365572">1</sup> to associate with Me something you<sup>sg</sup> have no knowledge of, do not obey them. To Me is your<sup>pl</sup> return, and I will inform you of what you used to do.",footnotes:346035:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 2<sup><small>nd</small></sup> person.
  29,9,"Those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—We will surely enter them among the righteous."
  29,10,"And among mankind is one who says, “We have attained faith in Allah.” Yet when he is hurt on Allah’s account, he equates the people's persecution with Allah’s punishment. And if help comes from your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, he will definitely say, “We were actually with you<sup>pl</sup>.” Does not Allah know better whatever is within the chests of <small>(all creatures of)</small> all realms?"
  29,11,"And Allah will surely know those who have attained faith, and He will surely know the hypocrites."
  29,12,"And those who denied said to those who had attained faith, “Follow our way and we will carry your offenses.” But never will they <small>(willingly)</small> carry any of their offenses; they are indeed liars."
  29,13,"Yet, they will surely carry their own heavy burdens and other heavy burdens with their own heavy burdens, and they will surely be asked on the Day of Resurrection about what they used to fabricate."
  29,14,"And We certainly sent Noah to his people, and He stayed among them for a thousand years, less fifty seasons. Then the Flood took them, for they were unjust."
  29,15,"But We saved him together with the fellows of the Ark, and We made it a sign for <small>(all people of)</small> all realms."
  29,16,"And Abraham—recall when he said to his people, “Worship Allah and be mindful of Him; that is better for you if you only knew."
  29,17,"Indeed, whatever you<sup>pl</sup> worship apart from Allah are nothing but idols, and you create fabrications. Those you worship apart from Allah possess no provision for you, so seek your provision with Allah and worship Him and thank Him; to Him you are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365573">1</sup></span>.”",footnotes:346036:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…you return.”</span>
  29,18,"And if you<sup>pl</sup> disbelieve, other communities before you have also disbelieved. And there is no responsibility upon the messenger except evident proclamation."
  29,19,"Have <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="365574">1</sup></span> not seen how Allah starts creation and then restores it? This is indeed easy for Allah.",footnotes:346037:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Have you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> not seen…”</span>
  29,20,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Journey throughout the earth and look how He started creation.” Then Allah will bring about the next existence; Allah is indeed All-Powerful over everything.”"
  29,21,"He punishes whomever He wills and He grants mercy to whomever He wills, and to Him you<sup>pl</sup> are turned back."
  29,22,"And you<sup>pl</sup> can neither thwart <small>(God)</small> on earth nor in heaven, and apart from Allah you have neither ally nor supporter."
  29,23,"And those who denied Allah’s signs and the meeting with Him—those have despaired of My<sup foot_note="365575">1</sup> mercy, and for those is a painful punishment.",footnotes:346038:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.
  29,24,"But there was no response from his people except that they said, “Kill him or burn him.” But Allah saved him from the fire; indeed, in that are signs for people who believe."
  29,25,"And he said, “You<sup>pl</sup> have chosen idols apart from Allah, as a bond of love for one another in the Earlier Life. Then on the Day of Resurrection you will deny one another and curse one another, and your shelter is the Fire, and you will have no helpers.”"
  29,26,"Then Lot believed in him and said, “I am emigrating to my Lord; He is indeed the Almighty, the All-Wise.”"
  29,27,"And We granted him Isaac and Jacob, and conferred upon his offspring the prophethood and the scripture, and brought him his reward in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small>. And indeed, he is in the Hereafter among the righteous."
  29,28,"And Lot—recall when he said to his people, “Indeed, you do <span class="h">approach<sup foot_note="365576">1</sup></span> obscenity such as nobody in all communities has ever committed before you.",footnotes:346039:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Ibn Amer, Hafs, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “Can it be that you do approach obscenity such as nobody in all realms has ever committed before you?”</span>
  29,29,"Can it be that you do approach men and cut off the way<sup foot_note="365577">1</sup> and commit what is deplorable in your gatherings?” But there was no response from his people except that they said, “Bring upon us Allah’s punishment if you<sup>sg</sup> are of the truthful.”",footnotes:346040:This may imply cutting off the natural way of reproduction or obstructing the way and attacking travelers.
  29,30,"He said, “My Lord, help me against the corruptive people.”"
  29,31,"And when Our messengers came to <span class="h">Abraham<sup foot_note="365578">1</sup></span> with the glad tidings, they said, “We are going to destroy the people of this town; indeed, its people have been unjust.”",footnotes:346041:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as <i>Ibrahim</i>, Hisham and Ibn Zekwan in one of his narrations read it as: “Abraham”.</span>
  29,32,"He said, “Yet Lot is in it.” They said, “We know better of who is in it; we will most surely <span class="h">deliver<sup foot_note="365579">1</sup></span> him and his family, except for his wife; she has become one of those who linger behind.”",footnotes:346042:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “…we will most surely save him…”</span>
  29,33,"Then, when Our messengers came to Lot, he was troubled and distressed on their account. But they said, “Do not fear nor grieve; we will <span class="h">deliver<sup foot_note="365580">1</sup></span> you and your family, except for your wife; she has become one of those who linger behind.",footnotes:346043:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer, Hafs and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…we will save you and…”</span>
  29,34,"Indeed, We will <span class="h">send<sup foot_note="365581">1</sup></span> down upon the people of this town a torment from heaven on account of having been defiantly disobedient.”",footnotes:346044:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “Indeed, We will send from on high upon the people of this town…”</span>
  29,35,"And We left behind something of it as an evident sign for people who reason."
  29,36,"And to Midian <small>(We sent)</small> their brother Shuaib. So he said, “O my people, worship Allah and expect the Last Day, and do not go wickedly about the land, corrupting it.”"
  29,37,"But they disbelieved him, so the Tremor overtook them and they became lifeless bodies in their home."
  29,38,"And Ād<sup foot_note="365582">1</sup> and Thamûd<sup foot_note="365583">2</sup> as well, as it has become evident for you<sup>pl</sup> from their <small>(ruined)</small> residences. And Satan adorned their deeds for them, barring them from the way, even though they could see.",footnotes:346045:The pagan tribe of Prophet Hûd.|346046:The pagan tribe of Prophet Salih.
  29,39,"And Qarun and Pharaoh and Hamān—Moses certainly went to them with clear proofs, but they went about arrogantly in the land, and in no way were they forerunners."
  29,40,"Each We seized by his misdeed: so of them are those upon whom We sent a sandstorm, and of them are those who were taken away by the Shout, and of them are those whom We caused the earth to swallow, and of them are those whom We drowned. For never would Allah do them any injustice, but to themselves they used to do injustice."
  29,41,"The likeness of those who take for themselves guardians apart from Allah is as the likeness of the spider that takes for itself a house, and surely the feeblest of houses is indeed the house of the spider, if they only knew."
  29,42,"Indeed, Allah knows whatever thing <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="365584">1</sup></span> call upon apart from Him, and He is the Almighty, the All-Wise.",footnotes:346047:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Abu Amr, Asem and Ya’qub read it as: “…what you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> call upon…”</span>
  29,43,"And such parables We set forth for mankind, but none grasps them except the learned."
  29,44,"Allah created the heavens and the earth with truth; indeed, in that is a sign for the believers."
  29,45,"Recite what is revealed to you<sup>sg</sup> of the Scripture and establish the prayer; indeed the prayer forbids obscenity and what is deplorable. And surely the remembrance of Allah is greater. And Allah knows what you<sup>pl</sup> do."
  29,46,"And do not argue with the People of the Scripture except in the best manner, unless it be those of them who have done injustice, and say, “We believe in what was revealed to us and what was revealed to you, and our God and your God is One, and to Him we are Muslims<sup foot_note="365585">1</sup> .”",footnotes:346048:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimoon</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  29,47,"Likewise, We sent down to you<sup>sg</sup> the Scripture. So those to whom We gave the Scripture believe in it, and some of these ones believe in it, but none repudiate Our signs except the deniers."
  29,48,"And you<sup>sg</sup> never used to read any Scripture before it, and you never used to write it down with your right hand; otherwise the advocates of falsehood would have doubted."
  29,49,"In fact, it is evident signs in the chests of those given knowledge, and none repudiate Our signs except the unjust ones."
  29,50,"And they said, “Why are no <span class="h">signs<sup foot_note="365586">1</sup></span> sent down to him from his Lord?” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Surely the signs are only in the Providence of Allah, and surely I am only an evident warner.”",footnotes:346049:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Shu’ba, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Why is no sign sent down…”</span>
  29,51,"Does it not suffice them that We revealed to you<sup>sg</sup> the Scripture which is recited to them? Indeed, in that is mercy and a reminding for people who believe."
  29,52,"Say, “Allah suffices as witness between you and me; He knows whatever is in the heavens and the earth. And those who believed in falsehood and denied Allah—it is those who are the losers.”"
  29,53,"And they urge you<sup>sg</sup> to hasten the punishment. And were it not for a stated term, the punishment would have come to them. But it will come upon them suddenly while they are unaware."
  29,54,"They urge you to hasten the punishment, and indeed, Hell is surely encompassing of the deniers."
  29,55,"On the day when the punishment envelops them from above them and from beneath their feet, and He <span class="h">says<sup foot_note="365587">1</sup></span>, “Taste what you used to do!",footnotes:346050:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Nafie’, Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…and We say…”</span>
  29,56,"O My servants who have attained faith: My earth is vast, so worship Me alone."
  29,57,"Every single self is sure to taste death, then to Us you<sup>pl</sup> are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365588">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346051:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “…then to Us they are returned.” Ya’qub read it as: “…then to Us you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> return.”</span>
  29,58,"And those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—We will <span class="h">settle<sup foot_note="365589">1</sup></span> them in the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> in Chambers under which rivers flow, abiding therein; how good is the reward of the workers",footnotes:346052:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…We will lodge them in…”</span>
  29,59,"who endured patiently and in their Lord they place their trust!""
  29,60,"How many a treading creature is there that does not carry its provision? Allah provides for it and for you<sup>pl</sup>, and He is the All-Hearing, the All-Knowing."
  29,61,"And surely, if you were to ask them, “Who created the heavens and the earth and subjected the sun and the moon?” They would say, “Allah.” So how can they be averted <small>(from the truth)</small>?"
  29,62,"Allah expands provision for whomever He wills of His servants and He restrains for him; indeed, Allah is All-Knowing of everything."
  29,63,"And surely, if you<sup>sg</sup> were to ask them, “Who sent down from the sky water with which He revived the earth after it had died?” They would say, “Allah.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Praise be to Allah.” Rather, most of them do not reason."
  29,64,"This Earlier Life is nothing but a distraction and a game, and indeed the Home of the Hereafter is truly the perennial life, if they only knew."
  29,65,"So when they embark on ships they call upon Allah, devoting religion to Him. But once He has delivered them safely to land, they promptly associate others <small>(with Him)</small>,"
  29,66,"so that they deny whatever We have brought them and so that they <span class="h">enjoy<sup foot_note="365590">1</sup></span>, for they will eventually know!",footnotes:346053:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Qaloun, Ibn Kathir, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, and Khalaf read it as: “…and let them enjoy,”</span>
  29,67,"Have they not seen that We have established a safe sanctuary, while all around them people are being snatched away? Do they believe in falsehood and deny the blessings of Allah?"
  29,68,"And who is more unjust than one who has fabricated lies and attributed them to Allah or disbelieved the truth when it has come to him? Is there not in Hell a dwelling for the deniers?"
  29,69,"And those who strove for Us—We will surely guide them in Our ways, for Allah<sup foot_note="365591">1</sup> is most surely with those who excel in doing good.",footnotes:346054:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.
  30,1,"Alif Lām Mīm."
  30,2,"The Romans have been overcome"
  30,3,"in the nearest<sup foot_note="365592">1</sup> land. But after having been overcome, they will overcome <small>(their enemy)</small>",footnotes:346055:The Arabic word used is <i>a</i><i>dna</i> which can also mean ‘lowest’.
  30,4,"in a few years<sup foot_note="365593">1</sup> . The command belongs to Allah, in the past and in the future. And on that day, the believers will exult",footnotes:346056:The Arabic word used is <i>bed’</i> which stands for numbers more than three and less than ten.
  30,5,"in Allah’s support. He supports whomever He wills, and He is the Almighty, the Bestower of mercy."
  30,6,"The promise of Allah—Allah never breaks His promise, but most of mankind knows not."
  30,7,"They know an outer aspect of the Earlier Life, but they are oblivious of the Hereafter."
  30,8,"Have they not reflected within themselves? Allah did not create the heavens and the earth and whatever is between them except with the truth and for a stated term. But many among mankind do deny the meeting with their Lord."
  30,9,"Have they not journeyed through the earth and looked at what the outcome was for those before them? They were more powerful than them, and they cultivated the land and developed it more than they developed it, and their messengers came to them with evident proofs. For never would Allah do them any injustice, but to themselves they used to do injustice."
  30,10,"Then absolute evil was the consequence for those who committed <span class="h">evil<sup foot_note="365594">1</sup></span>; that is because they rejected Allah’s signs and used to ridicule them.",footnotes:346057:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “Then the consequence for those who committed evil was absolute evil;”</span>
  30,11,"Allah originates creation and then restores it, then to Him you<sup>pl</sup> are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365595">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346058:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr and Shu’ba read it as: “…then to Him they are returned.” Rouh read it as: “…then to Him they return.” Roways read it as: “…then to Him you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> return.”</span>
  30,12,"And on the day when the Hour takes place, the criminals despair."
  30,13,"And they had<sup foot_note="365596">1</sup> no intercessors from among their associate-gods, and they became deniers of their associate-gods.",footnotes:346059:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  30,14,"And on the day when the Hour takes place—on that day they separate."
  30,15,"So, as for those who had attained faith and had done righteous deeds—they are in a meadow, delighted."
  30,16,"But as for those who had denied and had rejected Our signs and the meeting of the Hereafter—those are arraigned in the punishment."
  30,17,"So Highly Exalted is Allah when you<sup>pl</sup> reach nightfall and when you reach morning."
  30,18,"And to him is all praise in the heavens and the earth, and in the evening, and when you<sup>pl</sup> reach midday."
  30,19,"He brings out the living from the dead and He brings out the dead from the living, and He revives the land after it has died, and likewise you<sup>pl</sup> are brought <span class="h">out<sup foot_note="365597">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346060:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Khalaf and Ibn Zekwan read it as: “…and likewise you<sup><span class="role-mark"><small>pl</small></span></sup>pl come out.”</span>
  30,20,"And of His signs is that He created you<sup>pl</sup> from dust, and there you are, human beings spreading about."
  30,21,"And of His signs is that He created for you spouses from among yourselves so that you may find rest with them, and He has set between you love and mercy; indeed, in that are signs for people who reflect."
  30,22,"And of His signs is the creation of the heavens and the earth, and the diversity of your<sup>pl</sup> tongues<sup foot_note="365598">1</sup> and colors; indeed, in that are signs for those who <span class="h">know<sup foot_note="365599">2</sup></span>.",footnotes:346061:Languages.|346062:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as: “…for (people of) all realms.”</span>
  30,23,"And of His signs is your<sup>pl</sup> sleep by night and day, and your pursuit of His grace; indeed, in that are signs for people who listen."
  30,24,"And of His signs is that He shows you<sup>pl</sup> lightning, causing fear and ardent hope. And He <span class="h">bestows<sup foot_note="365600">1</sup></span> water from the sky, and with it He revives the earth after its death; indeed, in that are signs for people who reason.",footnotes:346063:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…and He sends down water…”</span>
  30,25,"And of His signs is that the heaven and the earth remain <small>(firm)</small> by His command, then when He calls you<sup>pl</sup> out of the earth, you promptly come out."
  30,26,"To Him belongs whoever is in the heavens and the earth; all surrender to Him."
  30,27,"It is He who originates creation and then restores it, and that is even easier for Him. And His is the Most Exalted example in the heavens and the earth. And He is the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  30,28,"He has set forth for you<sup>pl</sup> a parable from yourselves: do you make those whom you rightfully possess full partners in the wealth We have given you, so that you are equal in regard to it, fearing them as you have fear of each other? We thus detail the signs for people who reason."
  30,29,"Yet those who did injustice followed their whims without knowledge. But who can guide those whom Allah has misguided? And they will have no helpers."
  30,30,"So set your<sup>sg</sup> face upright towards the religion, turning away from all that is false; <small>(this religion is)</small> the original disposition from Allah upon which He originated mankind. There cannot be any change in Allah's creation; this is the upright religion, but most of mankind does not know."
  30,31,"<small>(Keep)</small> turning<sup>pl</sup> to Him in penitence, and be mindful of Him and establish the prayer, and do not be of those who associate others <small>(with Him)</small> —"
  30,32,"of the ones who have caused disunity <span class="h">in<sup foot_note="365601">1</sup></span> their religion and become sects, each party exulting in whatever they have.",footnotes:346064:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…the ones who have separated from their religion…”</span>
  30,33,"And when harm touches people they call upon their Lord, turning to Him in penitence. Thereafter, when He makes them taste mercy from Him, a group of them associate others with their Lord"
  30,34,"so as to deny what We have brought them. So take your<sup>pl</sup> enjoyment, then you will come to know."
  30,35,"Or have We sent down to them any authority which speaks in support of what they have been associating with Him?"
  30,36,"And when We make people taste a mercy, they rejoice in it; but when adversity befalls them because of what their hands have put forth, they promptly become despondent."
  30,37,"Have they not seen that Allah extends provision for whomever He wills and He restrains <small>(it)</small>? Surely in that are signs for people who believe."
  30,38,"So bring<sup>sg</sup> to the relative his rights, and the destitute<sup>sg</sup> and the traveler in need; that is best for those who seek Allah’s Countenance, and those are the successful."
  30,39,"And whatever you<sup>pl</sup> have <span class="h">brought<sup foot_note="365602">1</sup></span> in usury so that it <span class="h">increases<sup foot_note="365603">2</sup></span> through people’s money is not <small>(considered)</small> an increase with Allah, but whatever you have brought<sup foot_note="365604">3</sup> as purifying charity<sup foot_note="365605">4</sup>, seeking Allah’s Countenance—those<sup foot_note="365606">5</sup> are the multipliers.",footnotes:346065:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn kathir read it as: “And whatever you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> have come up with in usury so that it increases…”</span>|346066:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…in usury to increase it through people’s…”</span>|346067:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|346068:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.|346069:A grammatical shift from 2<sup><span class="role-mark"><small>nd</small></span></sup>nd person to 3<sup><span class="role-mark"><small>rd</small></span></sup>rd person.
  30,40,"Allah is the One Who created you<sup>pl</sup>, then provided for you, then makes you die, then brings you back to life. Can any of your associate-gods do any of that? Highly Exalted is He, and Most High above what they <span class="h">associate<sup foot_note="365607">1</sup></span><small>(with Him)</small>.",footnotes:346070:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, and Khalaf read it as: “…above what you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> associate…”</span>
  30,41,"Corruption has appeared throughout the land and sea because of what people’s hands have earned, so that <span class="h">He<sup foot_note="365608">1</sup></span> may make them taste some of what they have done, that they may return.",footnotes:346071:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Qunbul and Rouh read it as: “so that We may make them taste…”</span>
  30,42,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Journey<sup>pl</sup> through the earth and look what the outcome was for those who came before; most of them were polytheists”."
  30,43,"So set your<sup>sg</sup> face upright towards the upright religion before there comes from Allah a day that cannot be turned back; on that day they will be divided:"
  30,44,"whoever has denied—upon him falls his denial, and whoever has acted righteously—they<sup foot_note="365609">1</sup> smooth a way for themselves.",footnotes:346072:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  30,45,"So that He may repay those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds out of His grace. Indeed, He does not love the deniers."
  30,46,"And of His signs is that He sends the winds bearing glad tidings, and that He may let you<sup>pl</sup> taste of His mercy, and so that ships may sail by His command, and so that you may seek of His grace, and so that you may give thanks."
  30,47,"And indeed, before you<sup>sg</sup> We sent messengers to their people, and they came to them with evident proofs. So We took retribution from those who had committed crimes, and incumbent upon Us was support of the believers."
  30,48,"Allah is the One Who sends the <span class="h">winds<sup foot_note="365610">1</sup></span> so they stir up clouds, then He spreads them in the sky as He wills and makes them into <span class="h">pieces<sup foot_note="365611">2</sup></span>, then you see rain drops coming out from their midst; then when He makes it fall upon whom He wills of His servants, there they are, anticipating glad tidings",footnotes:346073:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…wind so it stirs…”</span>|346074:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Zekwan, Abu Ja’far and Hisham, in one of his narrations, read it as: “…into fragments,”</span>
  30,49,"although before it was <span class="h">bestowed<sup foot_note="365612">1</sup></span> upon them from on high they were indeed in despair.",footnotes:346075:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…before it was sent down upon them they were…”</span>
  30,50,"So looksg at the <span class="h">effects<sup foot_note="365613">1</sup></span> of Allah’s mercy—how He revives the earth after its death; indeed, He is the Reviver of the dead, and He is All-Powerful over everything.",footnotes:346076:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Shu’ba, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…the effect of…”</span>
  30,51,"But if We sent a wind and they saw it turning things yellow, they would continue thereafter to deny."
  30,52,"So surely you<sup>sg</sup> cannot make the dead hear, nor can you make the deaf <span class="h">hear<sup foot_note="365614">1</sup></span> the call when they turn away, fleeing.",footnotes:346077:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “…nor can the deaf hear the call…”</span>
  30,53,"Nor will you<sup>sg</sup> <span class="h">guide<sup foot_note="365615">1</sup></span> the blind out of their misguidance; you can make hear only those who believe in Our signs and are thus Muslims<sup foot_note="365616">2</sup> .",footnotes:346078:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “Nor do you<sup><small>sg</small></sup> guide the blind…”</span>|346079:Willingly submissive to God.
  30,54,"Allah is the One Who created you<sup>pl</sup> out of weakness, then after weakness gave <small>(you)</small> strength, then after strength gave <small>(you)</small> weakness and gray hair. He creates whatever He wills, and He is the All-Knowing, the All-Powerful."
  30,55,"And on the day when the Hour takes place, the criminals swear they had not stayed but for an hour; thus they used to be averted <small>(from the truth)</small>."
  30,56,"But <small>(on Judgment Day)</small> those endowed with knowledge and faith said<sup foot_note="365617">1</sup>, “Surely, you<sup>pl</sup> have remained <small>(in existence from the time of your creation)</small> until the Day of Resurrection <small>(in accordance with the decree)</small> in Allah’s Scripture; so this is the Day of Resurrection, but you did not know.”",footnotes:346080:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  30,57,"On that day the excuses of those who were unjust do not benefit them, nor are they allowed to make amends."
  30,58,"And We have certainly set forth in this Recital<sup foot_note="365618">1</sup> for mankind every sort of parable. But even if you<sup>sg</sup> bring them a <small>(miraculous)</small> sign, those who have denied will surely say, “You are nothing but fakers.”",footnotes:346081:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  30,59,"Allah thus seals the hearts of those who do not know,"
  30,60,"so be<sup>sg</sup> patient. The promise of Allah is true, so do not let those who lack certitude belittle you."
  31,1,"Alif Lām Mīm."
  31,2,"These are the signs of the Wise Scripture,"
  31,3,"a guidance and a mercy for those who excel in doing good:"
  31,4,"those who establish the prayer and bring<sup foot_note="365619">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="365620">2</sup> and of the Hereafter they are certain.",footnotes:346082:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|346083:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  31,5,"Those are rightly guided by their Lord, and those are the successful."
  31,6,"And among mankind is one who trades in distracting tales to make <small>(people)</small> <span class="h">stray<sup foot_note="365621">1</sup></span> from the way of Allah without knowledge, and to take <span class="h">it<sup foot_note="365622">2</sup></span> for a mockery; for those is a demeaning punishment.",footnotes:346084:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “…to stray from the way…”</span>|346085:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer, Shu’ba and Abu Ja’far read it as: “and he takes it for…”</span>
  31,7,"And when Our signs<sup foot_note="365623">1</sup> are recited to him, he turns away arrogantly as though he did not hear them, as though there is deafness in his ears. So give<sup>sg</sup> him glad tidings<sup foot_note="365624">2</sup> of a painful punishment.",footnotes:346086:The Arabic word used is (singular <i>ayat</i>). <i>ayah</i><i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.|346087:This is said in sarcasm.
  31,8,"Indeed, those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—for them are the Gardens of Bliss,"
  31,9,"abiding therein, a true promise of Allah. And He is the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  31,10,"He created the heavens without any pillars that you<sup>pl</sup> can see, and cast firm mountains into the earth lest it sway with you, and scattered throughout it all kinds of treading creatures. And from the sky We sent down water, and We germinated therein many noble kinds of plants."
  31,11,"Such is Allah’s creation, so show<sup>pl</sup> me what those apart from Him have created; rather, the unjust are in evident misguidance."
  31,12,"And truly, We endowed Luqman with wisdom: “Give<sup>sg</sup> thanks to Allah.” For whoever is thankful is only thankful to his own benefit, and whoever has denied<sup foot_note="365625">1</sup>, then Allah is indeed Self-Sufficient, Praiseworthy.",footnotes:346088:His grace.
  31,13,"And recall when Luqman said to his son, as he was admonishing him, “O my child, do not associate <small>(anything)</small> with Allah; indeed, associating <small>(others with Allah)</small> is surely a great injustice.”"
  31,14,"And We have enjoined upon man the care of his parents. His mother carried him with hardship upon hardship, besides weaning him in two years. So give<sup>sg</sup> thanks to Me and to your parents; to Me is the destiny."
  31,15,"But if they<sup>dl</sup> strive to have you<sup>sg</sup> associate with Me whatever you have no knowledge of, do not obey them. Yet accompany them in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> kindly, and follow the way of the one who has turned to Me in penitence. Then to Me is your<sup>pl</sup> return, and I will inform you of what you used to do."
  31,16,"“O my child, if it be the <span class="h">weight<sup foot_note="365626">1</sup></span> of a mustard-seed, and be it in a rock or in the heavens or in the earth, Allah brings it forth; indeed, Allah is Subtle, All-Aware.",footnotes:346089:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “O my child, if the weight of a mustard-seed be then in a rock…”</span>
  31,17,"O my child, establish the prayer and command to what is fair and forbid what is deplorable, and be patient over what has befallen you; indeed, that is of the matters requiring determination."
  31,18,"And do not turn your cheek away from people <small>(in pride)</small>, nor walk about the earth merrily; indeed, Allah does not love every self-admiring boaster."
  31,19,"And moderate your stride and lower your voice; indeed, the most deplorable of all voices is surely the donkey’s voice.”"
  31,20,"Have you<sup>pl</sup> not seen that Allah has subjected to you whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth and showered you with His <span class="h">blessings<sup foot_note="365627">1</sup></span>, both manifest and hidden? Yet among mankind is one who argues about Allah without any knowledge nor any guidance nor any illuminating Scripture.",footnotes:346090:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Abu Amr, Hafs and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…with a blessing, both…”</span>
  31,21,"And when it is said to them, “Follow what Allah has sent down,” they say, “Rather, we follow what we found our forefathers doing.” Even if Satan has been calling them to the punishment of the Blaze?"
  31,22,"And whoever surrenders his face to Allah while excelling in doing good, then he has truly grasped the firmest handhold. And with Allah rests the outcome of all events."
  31,23,"And whoever denies—let not his denial sadden you<sup>sg</sup>; to Us is their<sup foot_note="365628">1</sup> return, then We will inform them of what they did; indeed, Allah is All-Knowing of what lies within the chests.",footnotes:346091:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  31,24,"We give them a little enjoyment, then We compel them to a harsh punishment."
  31,25,"And if you<sup>sg</sup> ask them, “Who created the heavens and the earth?” They will surely say, “Allah.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Praise be to Allah.” Rather, most of them do not know."
  31,26,"To Allah belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth. Indeed, Allah is the Self-Sufficient, the Praiseworthy."
  31,27,"And were all the trees on earth pens, with the <span class="h">sea<sup foot_note="365629">1</sup></span> replenished<sup foot_note="365630">2</sup> by seven seas following it, never would the Words of Allah run out. Indeed, Allah is Almighty, All-Wise.",footnotes:346092:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “And were all the trees on earth pens, and were the sea replenished…”</span>|346093:The Arabic word <i>yamuduhu</i> which means ‘replenish’ comes from the same root of the Arabic word <i>med</i><i>ā</i><i>d</i> which means ‘ink’, so it serves the meaning of ‘replenishing with ink'.
  31,28,"Neither your<sup>pl</sup> creation nor your resurrection are but as that of a single soul. Indeed, Allah is All-Hearing, All-Seeing."
  31,29,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen that Allah causes the night to penetrate the day, and causes the day to penetrate the night? And that He subjected the sun and the moon, each running for a stated term? And that Allah is All-Aware of whatever you<sup>pl</sup> do?"
  31,30,"That is because Allah is the Truth, and because what they <span class="h">call<sup foot_note="365631">1</sup></span> upon apart from Him is falsehood, and because Allah is the All-High, the Supreme.",footnotes:346094:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Ibn Amer, Shu’ba and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…what you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> call upon…”</span>
  31,31,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen that the ships sail through the sea by the blessing of Allah, to show you of His signs? Indeed, in that are signs for everyone who is most patient, constantly thankful."
  31,32,"And when waves like canopies cover them, they call upon Allah, devoting religion to Him. But when He has delivered them ashore, some of them waver. But no one repudiates Our signs except every perfidious staunch denier."
  31,33,"O mankind, be mindful of your Lord, and fear a day when no parent can repay anything on behalf of his child, nor can a child repay anything on behalf of his parent. The promise of Allah is indeed true, so let not the Earlier Life deceive you<sup>pl</sup>, and let not the Deceiver deceive you regarding Allah."
  31,34,"Indeed, with Allah rests the knowledge of the Hour. And He <span class="h">bestows<sup foot_note="365632">1</sup></span> the rain from on high and He knows what the wombs contain. But in no way does any soul know what it will earn tomorrow, and in no way does any soul know in what land it will die; indeed, Allah is All-Knowing, All-Aware.",footnotes:346095:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Nafie’, Ibn Amer, Asem and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…and He sends down the rain and He knows…”</span>
  32,1,"Alif Lām Mīm."
  32,2,"The bestowal of the Scripture from on high is—no doubt about it—by the Lord of all realms."
  32,3,"Yet they say, “He has fabricated it.” Rather, it is the truth from your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, so that you may warn a people to whom no warner came before you, that they may be guided."
  32,4,"Allah is the One Who created the heavens and the earth and whatever is between them in six days<sup foot_note="365633">1</sup>, and then settled over the Throne; apart from Him, you<sup>pl</sup> have neither ally nor intercessor. Will you not remind yourselves?",footnotes:346096:Six equal intervals of time, which may be six heavenly days, each of them being 1000 earthly years long (see 22: 47).
  32,5,"He governs every matter from the heavens to the earth, then it ascends to Him on a day the length of which is a thousand years by your<sup>pl</sup> count."
  32,6,"That is the Knower of the hidden realm and the manifest, the Almighty, the Bestower of mercy"
  32,7,"Who has made excellent everything He <span class="h">created<sup foot_note="365634">1</sup></span>, and He originated the creation of man from clay,",footnotes:346097:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…Who has made everything excellent regarding its composition, and He…”</span>
  32,8,"then made his progeny from an extract of a despicable fluid,"
  32,9,"then He proportioned him and breathed into him of His Spirit, and He gave you<sup>pl</sup> hearing and sight<small>(s)</small> and burning hearts; little do you give thanks."
  32,10,"And they said, “Can it be that when we have become lost into the earth—can it be that we <span class="h">will<sup foot_note="365635">1</sup></span> really be brought to a new creation?” Rather, they do deny the meeting with their Lord.",footnotes:346098:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “Can it be that when we have become lost into the earth we will really…” Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “When we have become lost into the earth— can it be that we will really …”</span>
  32,11,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “The angel of death put in charge of you<sup>pl</sup> takes you, then to your Lord you are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365636">1</sup></span>.”",footnotes:346099:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…to your Lord you return.”</span>
  32,12,"And if only you<sup>sg</sup> could see the criminals bowing their heads before their Lord: “Our Lord, we have seen and we have heard, so send us back, that we may act righteously; we are <small>(now)</small> certain.”"
  32,13,"And had We willed, We could have brought every soul its guidance, but the declaration from Me will come true: “I will most surely fill Hell with <small>(the race of)</small> unseen beings<sup foot_note="365637">1</sup> and human beings, both together.”",footnotes:346100:The Arabic word used is <i>jinnah</i> which is the race of unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.
  32,14,"So taste, on account of how you<sup>pl</sup> forgot the meeting of this day of yours; indeed, We have forgotten you, so taste the eternal punishment on account of what you used to do."
  32,15,"The only people who <small>(truly)</small> believe in Our signs are those who, when they are reminded of them, fall down prostrating and highly exalt their Lord with praise, and they are not arrogant."
  32,16,"Their sides shun the beds as they pray to their Lord out of fear and ardent hope, and from Our provisions to them they spend."
  32,17,"No soul knows what has been <span class="h">hidden<sup foot_note="365638">1</sup></span> for them<sup foot_note="365639">2</sup> of comfort to the eyes—a repayment on account of what they used to do.",footnotes:346101:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Ya’qub read it as: “No soul knows what I am hiding for them…”</span>|346102:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  32,18,"So, is the one who has been a believer like the one who has been defiantly disobedient? They are not equal."
  32,19,"As for those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds, for them are the Gardens of Shelter—hospitality on account of what they used to do."
  32,20,"But as for those who have defiantly disobeyed, their shelter is the Fire; every time they want to depart it, they are brought back into it, and it is said to them, “Taste the punishment of the Fire which you used to deny.”"
  32,21,"And We will certainly make them taste the lesser punishment <small>(in this life)</small> prior to the greater punishment, that they may return."
  32,22,"And who is more unjust than one who was reminded of his Lord’s signs, then disregarded them? We will certainly wreak vengeance upon the criminals."
  32,23,"And We certainly gave Moses the Scripture, so do<sup>sg</sup> not regard his meeting with scepticism. And We made it a guidance for the Children of Israel."
  32,24,"And of them We appointed leaders guiding by Our command, <span class="h">when<sup foot_note="365640">1</sup></span> they persevered patiently and were certain of Our signs.",footnotes:346103:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Roways read it as: “…guiding by Our command, for they persevered patiently…”</span>
  32,25,"Indeed, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is the One who judges between them on the Day of Resurrection regarding whatever they used to differ over."
  32,26,"Is it not a guidance for them: how many generations We caused to perish before them, amidst whose residences they <small>(now)</small> walk? Surely in that are signs. Do they not hear?"
  32,27,"Have they not seen that We conduct the water to a dry land, and with it We bring out vegetation from which their livestock eat, and they themselves? Do they not see?"
  32,28,"And they say, “When is this conquest, if you<sup>pl</sup> are truthful?”"
  32,29,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “On the Day of Conquest the belief of the ones who had denied will not benefit them, and they will not be given respite.”"
  32,30,"So disregard<sup>sg</sup> them and wait. Indeed, they <small>(too)</small> are waiting."
  33,1,"O Prophet, be mindful of Allah and do not obey the deniers and the hypocrites. Indeed, Allah has always been All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  33,2,"And follow what is revealed to you<sup>sg</sup> from your Lord; indeed, Allah has always been All-Aware of what you<sup>pl</sup> <span class="h">do<sup foot_note="365641">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346104:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “…of what they do.”</span>
  33,3,"And place your<sup>sg</sup> trust in Allah, for Allah is sufficient as a Trustee."
  33,4,"Never did Allah make two hearts inside any man's body, nor did He ever make your<sup>pl</sup> spouses whom you reject and compare to your mothers' backs into your actual mothers. Nor did He make your adopted sons your actual sons. That is your saying coming out of your mouths, and Allah speaks the truth and He guides to the way."
  33,5,"Call them after their fathers; that is more equitable with Allah. But if you<sup>pl</sup> do not know their fathers, then your brethren in faith and your protégés. And you commit no sin if you err therein, except for what your hearts premeditate. And Allah has always been Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  33,6,"The Prophet is worthier as a guardian of the believers than they are of themselves, and his spouses are <small>(as)</small> mothers to them. And blood relatives are worthier than the <small>(other)</small> believers or the immigrants<sup foot_note="365642">1</sup> as heirs of one another according to Allah’s Scripture—except that you<sup>pl</sup> may do an upright act to your allies; that has been inscribed in the Scripture.",footnotes:346105:The believers who fled Makkah to Madinah.
  33,7,"And recall that We took from the prophets their pledge, and from you<sup>sg</sup> and from Noah and Abraham and Moses and Jesus, son of Mary, and We took from them a solid pledge,"
  33,8,"that He<sup foot_note="365643">1</sup> may ask the truthful<sup foot_note="365644">2</sup> about their truthfulness. Yet He has prepared for the deniers a painful punishment.",footnotes:346106:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.|346107:On the Day of Judgment.
  33,9,"O you who have attained faith, remember Allah’s blessings upon you when troops advanced towards you, and We<sup foot_note="365645">1</sup> sent against them a wind and troops that you did not see. And Allah has always been All-Seeing of what you <span class="h">do<sup foot_note="365646">2</sup></span>.",footnotes:346108:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><span class="role-mark"><small>rd</small></span></sup>rd person to 1<sup><span class="role-mark"><small>st</small></span></sup>st person|346109:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “…of what they do.”</span>
  33,10,"When they came upon you<sup>pl</sup> from above you and from beneath you, and when sight(s)<small>(s)</small> swerved and hearts reached the larynges, and you assume<sup foot_note="365647">1</sup> about Allah various assumptions.",footnotes:346110:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense, which serves to create a vivid portrait of past events.
  33,11,"There and then the believers were tested and were made to quake with a severe earthquake,"
  33,12,"as the hypocrites and those in whose hearts is sickness say, “Allah and His Messenger promised us nothing but a deception.”"
  33,13,"Recall, too, when a faction of them said, “O people of Yathrib, there is no <span class="h">staying<sup foot_note="365648">1</sup></span> for you here, so retreat.” And a group of them ask<sup foot_note="365649">2</sup> the Prophet to excuse them, saying, “Indeed, our houses are exposed,” although they are not exposed, but they want nothing but to flee.",footnotes:346111:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as: “…there is no standing-place for you here,”</span>|346112:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense, which serves to create a vivid portrait of past events
  33,14,"And had it<sup foot_note="365650">1</sup> been invaded from all its sides, then they were asked tribulation, they would have brought <span class="h">it<sup foot_note="365651">2</sup></span> and tarried not but a little.",footnotes:346113:The city of Madinah.|346114:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie, Ibn Kathir and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…they would have come to it…”</span>
  33,15,"And certainly, they had previously covenanted with Allah that they would not turn their backs. And Allah’s covenant must be answered for."
  33,16,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Flight will not benefit you<sup>pl</sup> if you flee from death or killing; even then you will be given no enjoyment but a little.”"
  33,17,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Who is it who can safeguard you<sup>pl</sup> from Allah if He desires adversity for you or desires mercy for you?” Apart from Allah, they can find for themselves neither guardian nor supporter."
  33,18,"Allah already knows the hinderers among you and those who say to their brethren, “Come along to us,” whereas they do not mobilize for battle but a little,"
  33,19,"begrudging support to you<sup>pl</sup>. And when fear approaches, you<sup>sg</sup> see them looking at you, their eyes rolling—like someone fainting at death; then, when panic is over, they scald you<sup>pl</sup> with sharp tongues, begrudging you any good. Those have not believed, so Allah has nullified their deeds, and this matter has always been easy for Allah."
  33,20,"They assume that the parties have not gone away. But were the parties to come <small>(again)</small>, they would wish they were in the desert with the nomadic Arabs, <span class="h">asking<sup foot_note="365652">1</sup></span> about your<sup>pl</sup> news. And if they were among you, they would not combat but a little.",footnotes:346115:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Roways read it as: “…asking each other about…”</span>
  33,21,"Most surely, there has always been an excellent role model for you<sup>pl</sup> in the Messenger of Allah <small>(and)</small> for anyone who has been putting hope in Allah and expecting the Last Day, and has remembered Allah frequently."
  33,22,"And when the believers saw the parties, they said, “This is what Allah and His messenger have promised us, and Allah and His messenger have told the truth.” And it only increased them in faith and submission."
  33,23,"Of the believers are men who have been true to what they have covenanted with Allah: so of them is one who fulfilled his obligation<sup foot_note="365653">1</sup>, and of them is one who still waits, and they have not changed in the least.",footnotes:346116:Fulfilled his obligation by sacrificing his life in battle.
  33,24,"That Allah may repay the truthful for their truthfulness and punish the hypocrites, if He wills, or grant them repentance and accept it from them. Indeed, Allah has always been Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  33,25,"And Allah repelled those who denied in their rage—they gained no advantage. And Allah thus spared the believers combat, and Allah has always been All-Powerful, Almighty."
  33,26,"And He brought down those of the People of the Scripture who backed them from their strongholds, and threw terror into their hearts, <small>(while)</small> you<sup>pl</sup> kill<sup foot_note="365654">1</sup> one group, and another group you capture.",footnotes:346117:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense, which serves to create a vivid portrait of past events.
  33,27,"And He made you<sup>pl</sup> inherit their land and their homes and their possessions and a land you had never trodden. And Allah has always been Powerful over everything."
  33,28,"O Prophet, say to your spouses, “If you want the Earlier Life and its adornment, then come, let me compensate you and release you kindly."
  33,29,"But if you want Allah and His Messenger and the Home of the Hereafter, then indeed, Allah has prepared a great reward for those of you who excel in doing good.”"
  33,30,"O wives of the Prophet, if any one of you were ever to commit an evident <span class="h">obscenity<sup foot_note="365655">1</sup></span>, the punishment for her would be <span class="h">doubled<sup foot_note="365656">2</sup></span> twofold. And that has always been easy for Allah.",footnotes:346118:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Shu’ba read it as: “…to commit an evidenced obscenity,”</span>|346119:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Ibn Amer read it as: “…We would double the punishment for her twofold.”</span>
  33,31,"But whoever of you is devout towards Allah and His Messenger and acts <span class="h">righteously—We<sup foot_note="365657">1</sup></span> will bring her her reward twice over, and We have prepared for her a noble provision.",footnotes:346120:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…He will bring her her reward…”</span>
  33,32,"O wives of the Prophet, you are not like any of the other women. If you are truly mindful <small>(of God)</small>, then do not speak too softly, lest the sick at heart lust after you, but speak forthright words."
  33,33,"And <span class="h">settle<sup foot_note="365658">1</sup></span> in your houses and do not display yourselves as in the former days of pagan ignorance, and establish the prayer and bring<sup foot_note="365659">2</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="365660">3</sup> and obey Allah and His Messenger; indeed, Allah only wants to keep abomination away from you, O people of the <small>(Prophet’s)</small> household, and to cleanse you thoroughly.",footnotes:346121:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Asem and Abu Ja’far read it as: “And settle, revered, in your houses…”</span>|346122:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|346123:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  33,34,"And remember what is recited in your<sup foot_note="365661">1</sup> houses of Allah's signs<sup foot_note="365662">2</sup>, and wisdom; indeed, Allah has always been Subtle, All-Aware.",footnotes:346124:Plural feminine possessive adjective denoting that once again the addressed are the wives of the Prophet (peace be upon him).|346125:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  33,35,"Indeed, Muslim men and Muslim women, and believing men and believing women, and devout men and devout women, and truthful men and truthful women, and patient men and patient women, and reverent men and reverent women, and charitable men and charitable women, and fasting men and fasting women, and men who preserve their private parts<sup foot_note="365663">1</sup> and women who <small>(likewise)</small> preserve, and men who remember Allah frequently and women who <small>(likewise)</small> remember—Allah has prepared for them forgiveness and a great reward.",footnotes:346126:A metaphor for chastity.
  33,36,"It is not for any believing man or believing woman, when Allah and His Messenger have decreed a command, to have a choice in their affair. And whoever disobeys Allah and His Messenger, then he has strayed into evident misguidance."
  33,37,"And recall as you say to the one upon whom Allah had bestowed His grace, and upon whom you<sup>sg</sup> had <small>(also)</small> bestowed your grace, “Hold on to your spouse and be mindful of Allah,” while hiding within yourself what Allah was to reveal, and fearing mankind, whereas Allah is more worthy of your fear. Then when Zaid ended his relationship with her<sup foot_note="365664">1</sup>, We married her to you, that there may be no blame on the believers regarding the spouses of their adopted sons when their relationship has ended, for the command of Allah has always been fulfilled.",footnotes:346127:By divorce.
  33,38,"Never has there been any blame on the Prophet regarding what Allah has ordained for him; such is Allah's rule among those <small>(prophets)</small> who passed on before, and the command of Allah has always been a determined determination."
  33,39,"Those who proclaim the messages of Allah and fear Him and fear no one except Allah. And Allah is sufficient as a Reckoner."
  33,40,"Never has Muhammad been the father of any of your<sup>pl</sup> men, but a Messenger of Allah and the <span class="h">seal<sup foot_note="365665">1</sup></span> of the prophets. And Allah has always been All-Knowing of everything.",footnotes:346128:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem read it as: “…the sealer of the prophets.”</span>
  33,41,"O you who have attained faith, remember Allah with frequent remembrance,"
  33,42,"and highly exalt Him morning and evening."
  33,43,"It is He Who blesses you<sup>pl</sup>, as do His angels<sup foot_note="365666">1</sup>, to get you out of darkness(es)<small>(es)</small> into light, and He has always been Merciful to the believers.",footnotes:346129:Angels bless people by praying to God for them.
  33,44,"Their greeting on the day they meet Him is, “Peace.” And He has prepared for them a noble reward."
  33,45,"O Prophet, We have sent you as a witness and a bearer of glad tidings and a warner,"
  33,46,"and a caller to Allah by His leave and an illuminating beacon."
  33,47,"And give<sup>sg</sup> the believers glad tidings that for them is a supreme grace from Allah."
  33,48,"And do<sup>sg</sup> not obey the deniers and the hypocrites, and ignore their hurtfulness, and place your trust in Allah, for Allah is sufficient as a Trustee."
  33,49,"O you who have attained faith, if you marry believing women but then divorce them before having touched<sup foot_note="365667">1</sup> <span class="h">them<sup foot_note="365668">2</sup></span>, you have no right to expect a waiting period on their part. But compensate them and release them in a graceful manner.",footnotes:346130:In sexual intercourse.|346131:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa'i and Khalaf read it as: "...before having touched each other,"</span>
  33,50,"O Prophet, We have permitted to you your spouses to whom you have given their dowries, and those whom you rightfully possess from what Allah has granted you, and the daughters of your paternal uncle, and the daughters of your paternal aunts, and the daughters of your maternal uncle, and the daughters of your maternal aunts who emigrated with you, and a believing woman—if she grants herself to the Prophet<sup foot_note="365669">1</sup>, if the Prophet wishes to marry her; <small>(this is)</small> exclusively for you, and not for the believers. We already know what We have ordained for them regarding their spouses and those whom they rightfully possess; this is to spare you any discomfort. And Allah has always been Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy.",footnotes:346132:Granting herself in marriage by forgoing her dowry.
  33,51,"You may defer any of them you wish and receive any of them you wish, and should you desire any of those you had set aside, then no sin is committed by you. This is more proper, so that they are comforted and are not grieved, and are content with what you have brought them—all of them. And Allah knows what is within your hearts, for Allah has always been All-Knowing, Forbearing."
  33,52,"You<sup>sg</sup> are not allowed <small>(to</small> <small>marry)</small> any further women, nor to exchange the spouses you have for others, even if you are impressed by their beauty, except for those whom you rightfully possess. And Allah has always been Watchful over everything."
  33,53,"O you who have attained faith, do not enter the houses of the Prophet unless you are given permission to come for a meal. And do not wait for its preparation, but when you are invited, then go in. And when you have eaten, disperse without seeking to remain for a talk. This used to hurt the Prophet, but he shied away from telling you, but Allah does not shy away from the truth. And when you<sup>pl</sup> ask them<sup foot_note="365670">1</sup> for something, ask them from behind a screen; that is cleaner for your hearts and their hearts. For it is not for you to hurt the Messenger of Allah, nor must you ever marry his spouses after him; that would indeed be <small>(a)</small> great <small>(offense)</small> with Allah.",footnotes:346133:The pronoun “them” is mentioned in plural feminine form and therefore refers to the wives of the Prophet (peace be upon him).
  33,54,"Whether you<sup>pl</sup> disclose anything or hide it, indeed, Allah has always been All-Knowing of everything."
  33,55,"No sin is committed by them<sup foot_note="365671">1</sup> regarding their fathers or their sons or their brothers or their brothers’ sons or their sisters’ sons or their women or those whom they rightfully possess. Yet be mindful<sup foot_note="365672">2</sup> of Allah; indeed, Allah has always been a Witness over everything.",footnotes:346134:The wives of the Prophet (peace be upon him).|346135:The Arabic pronoun used is plural feminine, indicating that Allah means the wives of the Prophet (peace be upon him).
  33,56,"Indeed, Allah and His angels give blessings<sup foot_note="365673">1</sup> to the Prophet. O you who have attained faith, pray for blessings upon him and greet him with a prayer of peace.",footnotes:346136:Literally ‘prayers’.
  33,57,"Indeed, those who hurt Allah and His Messenger— Allah has cursed them in the Earlier<small> (Life) </small>and the Hereafter, and has prepared for them a demeaning punishment."
  33,58,"And those who hurt believing men and believing women for acts they did not earn have surely burdened themselves with perjury and evident sin."
  33,59,"O Prophet, tell your spouses and your daughters and the women of the believers to make their outer garments hang low over them; that is more likely that they will be recognized and not hurt. And Allah has always been Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  33,60,"If the hypocrites do not desist, as well as those with sickness in their hearts and the rumormongers in the City <small>(of Madinah)</small>, We will surely incite you<sup>sg</sup> against them; then they will not neighbor you in it except for a short while."
  33,61,"Accursed; wherever they are found, they should be captured and relentlessly killed outright."
  33,62,"Such has been Allah’s rule with those who passed on before, and you<sup>sg</sup> will never find any change in Allah’s rule."
  33,63,"People ask you about the Hour. Say, “Indeed, knowledge thereof rests only with Allah. But what could make you<sup>sg</sup> realize? Perhaps the Hour could be near.”"
  33,64,"Indeed, Allah has cursed the deniers and has prepared for them a blaze,"
  33,65,"abiding therein forever, finding neither ally nor supporter."
  33,66,"On the day when their faces are flipped in the Fire, they say, “If only we had obeyed Allah and obeyed the Messenger.”"
  33,67,"And they said<sup foot_note="365674">1</sup>, “Our Lord, indeed we obeyed our <span class="h">masters<sup foot_note="365675">2</sup></span> and our dignitaries, but they led us away from the way.",footnotes:346137:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.|346138:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “…our many masters and our…”</span>
  33,68,"Our Lord, give them double the punishment and curse them with a <span class="h">supreme<sup foot_note="365676">1</sup></span> curse.”",footnotes:346139:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem read it as: “…with a lot of curses.”</span>
  33,69,"O you who have attained faith, do not be like those who hurt Moses, though Allah cleared him of what they had said. And he has been well-esteemed with Allah."
  33,70,"O you who have attained faith, be mindful of Allah and speak for justice;"
  33,71,"He will set aright your deeds for you and will forgive you your misdeeds. And whoever obeys Allah and His Messenger—then he has surely triumphed a great triumph."
  33,72,"Indeed, We offered the trust<sup foot_note="365677">1</sup> to the skies and the land and the mountains, but they refused to carry it and were apprehensive of it, but man carried it; he has always been constantly unjust, constantly ignorant.",footnotes:346140:Of reason and moral responsibility.
  33,73,"That Allah may punish the hypocrites, men and women, and the polytheists, men and women. And <small>(that)</small> Allah may grant repentance to the believers and accept it from them, men and women, for Allah has always been Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  34,1,"All praise be to Allah to Whom belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth, and all praise be to Him in the Hereafter, and He is the All-Wise, the All-Aware."
  34,2,"He knows what penetrates into the earth and what comes out of it, and what descends from the sky and what ascends to it, and He is the Bestower of mercy, the Oft-Forgiving."
  34,3,"Yet those who have denied have said, “The Hour is not coming upon us.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Yes indeed, by my Lord, the <span class="h">Knower<sup foot_note="365678">1</sup></span> of the hidden realm, it will come upon you.” Not an atom's weight in the heavens or in the earth escapes His knowledge, nor anything smaller or larger, except that it is in an evident record<sup foot_note="365679">2</sup> —",footnotes:346141:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Roways read it as: “‘…by my Lord, it will come upon you. (He is) the Knower of the hidden realm.’” Hamza and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “‘…by my Lord, the Superb Knower of the hidden realm, it will come upon you.’”</span>|346142:Literally ‘scripture’.
  34,4,"that He may repay those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds; for those is forgiveness and noble provision."
  34,5,"Those who strove against Our signs, attempting to <span class="h">challenge<sup foot_note="365680">1</sup></span><small>(God)</small> — those ones, for them is a painful punishment of <span class="h">torment<sup foot_note="365681">2</sup></span>.",footnotes:346143:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “…attempting to thwart…”</span>|346144:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Kathir, Hafs and Ya’qub read it as: “…for them is a punishment of painful torment.”</span>
  34,6,"And those who have received knowledge see that what was sent down to you<sup>sg</sup> from your Lord is the truth and guides to the path of the Almighty, the Praiseworthy."
  34,7,"And those who have denied said, “Shall we point out to you<sup>pl</sup> a man who tells you that, once you are torn into shreds, you will surely be in a new creation?”"
  34,8,"Did he invent a lie about Allah or is there madness in him? Rather, those who do not believe in the Hereafter are in punishment and extreme misguidance."
  34,9,"Have they not seen what lies before them and behind them of the heaven and the earth? If We <span class="h">will<sup foot_note="365682">1</sup></span>, We can make the earth cave in beneath them, or let fall down on them <span class="h">pieces<sup foot_note="365683">2</sup></span> from the sky; indeed, in that is a sign for every penitent servant.",footnotes:346145:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “If He wills, He can…”</span>|346146:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as: “fragments”.</span>
  34,10,"And surely, We bestowed upon David grace from Us: “O mountains, echo with him <small>(My praises)</small>, and you birds <small>(too)</small>.” And We softened iron for him."
  34,11,"“Make<sup>sg</sup> coats of armor and measure the links well, and do<sup>pl</sup> righteousness<sup foot_note="365684">1</sup> ; indeed I am All-Seeing of what you<sup>pl</sup> do.”",footnotes:346147:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  34,12,"And for Solomon <small>(I subjected)</small> the <span class="h">wind<sup foot_note="365685">1</sup></span>—its morning course <small>(reaching a distance otherwise attained in)</small> one month, and its evening course <small>(reaching a distance otherwise attained in) </small>one month. And We made a spring of molten brass flow for him, and there would be unseen beings<sup foot_note="365686">2</sup> working under him by the leave of his Lord. But whoever of them would swerve from Our command, We would make him taste of the punishment of the Blaze.",footnotes:346148:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…the winds…” Shu’ba read it as: “And the wind (was subjected) for Solomon—its…”</span>|346149:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.
  34,13,"They would make for him whatever he wished of sanctuaries, and statues, and bowls like pools, and heavy cauldrons. “O David's folk, work in thankfulness.” But few of My servants are constantly thankful."
  34,14,"Then, when We decreed death for him, nothing indicated his death to them except the woodworm eating his staff. Then, when he fell down, it became <span class="h">clear<sup foot_note="365687">1</sup></span> to the unseen beings that, had they known what was hidden, they would not have remained in the demeaning punishment.",footnotes:346150:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Roways read it as: “…it became clear that, had the unseen beings known what was hidden, they would not have remained…”</span>
  34,15,"Surely, there used to be a sign for <small>(the people of)</small> Sheba in their <span class="h">residence<sup foot_note="365688">1</sup></span>: two gardens, on the right and on the left. “Eat<sup>pl</sup> of your Lord’s provision and give thanks to Him.” A good land and an Oft-Forgiving Lord.",footnotes:346151:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…in their residences…”</span>
  34,16,"But they disregarded <small>(God)</small>, so We sent against them the torrent of the Arim <small>(Dam)</small>, and We substituted for them their two gardens with two gardens of bitter crops and thorny shrubs and something of sparse lote-trees."
  34,17,"Thus We repaid them on account of how they denied, and do We <small>(thus)</small> <span class="h">repay<sup foot_note="365689">1</sup></span> anyone except the staunch denier?",footnotes:346152:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer, Shu’ba and Abu Ja’far read it as: “and who is (thus) repaid except the staunch denier…?”</span>
  34,18,"And We made between them<sup foot_note="365690">1</sup> and the towns We had blessed<sup foot_note="365691">2</sup> visible towns, and We well determined the journey between. “Journey<sup>pl</sup> between them safely by night and day.”",footnotes:346153:In Yemen.|346154:Palestine.
  34,19,"But they said, “Our Lord, <span class="h">lengthen<sup foot_note="365692">1</sup></span> the distances of our journeys.” Thus they were unjust to themselves, so We made them history and We scattered them in every direction; indeed, in this are signs for everyone who is most patient, constantly thankful.",footnotes:346155:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “Our Lord has lengthened the distances…”</span>
  34,20,"And surely, Iblis<sup foot_note="365693">1</sup> <span class="h">confirmed<sup foot_note="365694">2</sup></span> his assumption about them. So they followed him, except for a group of believers.",footnotes:346156:Iblis is another name of Satan or <i>Shaytan</i>.|346157:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “And surely, Iblis’s assumption about them was confirmed.”</span>
  34,21,"And never did he have any authority over them, except that We may know the one who believes in the Hereafter from the one who is doubtful about it. And your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is a Constant Preserver over everything."
  34,22,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Call upon those whom you claimed <small>(to be gods)</small> apart from Allah; they do not possess an atom's weight in the heavens nor in the earth, and they do not have therein any association <small>(with God)</small>, and He does not have any assistant from among them.”"
  34,23,"And intercession cannot be of benefit before Him, except for one to whom He has given <span class="h">permission<sup foot_note="365695">1</sup></span>. Until, when fear has been <span class="h">dispelled<sup foot_note="365696">2</sup></span> from their hearts, they say<sup foot_note="365697">3</sup>, “What did your<sup>pl</sup> Lord say?” They say, “The truth; and He is the All-High, the Supreme.”",footnotes:346158:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…except for one who has been given permission.”</span>|346159:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “Until, when He has dispelled fear from their hearts, they say…”</span>|346160:They are either asking one another, or are being asked by the angels.
  34,24,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Who provides for you<sup>pl</sup> from the heavens and the earth?” Say, “Allah—and indeed, either you or we are rightly guided or in evident misguidance.”"
  34,25,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “You<sup>pl</sup> will not be asked about the crimes we committed, nor will we be asked about what you do.”"
  34,26,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Our Lord will bring us together, then He will legislate<sup foot_note="365698">1</sup> justly for us with the truth, for He is the Legislator<sup foot_note="365699">2</sup>, the All-Knowing.”",footnotes:346161:The Arabic word used is a derivative of the word <i>fateh</i> which literally means open; some exegetes said that it means 'open a way for us to distinguish between good and evil', i.e. legislate for us a legislation.|346162:Determiner of justice.
  34,27,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Show me those you have attached to Him as associates. But no! Rather, He is Allah, the Almighty, the All-Wise.”"
  34,28,"And We have not sent you but to the whole of mankind, as a herald of glad tidings and a warner, but the majority of mankind does not know."
  34,29,"Thus they say, “When is this promise due, if you<sup>pl</sup> are truthful?”"
  34,30,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “You<sup>pl</sup> are promised a day which you can neither postpone for a while nor bring forward.”"
  34,31,"Those who denied said, “We will never believe in this Recital<sup foot_note="365700">1</sup> nor in what came before it.” And if only you<sup>sg</sup> could see the unjust as they are brought to stand before their Lord, throwing back allegations at one another: those who had been deemed weak and oppressed say to the arrogant leaders, “Were it not for you<sup>pl</sup>, we would have been believers.”",footnotes:346163:The Arabic word used is<i> ‘Qur’an’</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  34,32,"The arrogant leaders said<sup foot_note="365701">1</sup> to those who had been deemed weak and oppressed, “Did we bar you from guidance after it had come to you? Rather, you yourselves were criminals.”",footnotes:346164:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  34,33,"And those who had been deemed weak and oppressed said to the arrogant leaders, “Rather, it was your scheming by night and day as you used to command us to deny Allah and to set up rivals to Him.” Thus they hid their remorse when they saw the punishment. And We put the yokes around the necks of those who had denied. Are they being repaid except for what they used to do?"
  34,34,"And never have We sent a warner to any town except that its affluent said, “Indeed, we deny what you<sup>pl</sup> have been sent with.”"
  34,35,"And they said, “We have more wealth and more children <small>(than the believers)</small>, and never shall we be punished.”"
  34,36,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Indeed, my Lord extends provision for whomever He wills and He restrains <small>(it)</small>, but the majority of mankind does not know.”"
  34,37,"And it is neither your<sup>pl</sup> wealth nor your children that bring you closer in position to Us—except whoever has attained faith and has acted righteously, for for those<sup foot_note="365702">1</sup> is a repayment of <span class="h">double(measure)<small>(measure)</small><sup foot_note="365703">2</sup></span> for what they did, and in the <span class="h">Chambers<sup foot_note="365704">3</sup></span><small>(of Paradise)</small> they remain safe.",footnotes:346165:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.|346166:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Roways read it as: “…for for those there is double as a repayment…”</span>|346167:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “Chamber”.</span>
  34,38,"But those who strove against Our signs<sup foot_note="365705">1</sup> attempting to <span class="h">challenge<sup foot_note="365706">2</sup></span><small>(God)</small>—those are arraigned in the punishment.",footnotes:346168:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.|346169:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “…attempting to thwart…”</span>
  34,39,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Indeed, My Lord extends provision for whomever He wills of His servants and He restrains <small>(it)</small>. And anything you<sup>pl</sup> spend <small>(in His cause)</small> He replaces it, and He is the Best of providers.”"
  34,40,"And on the day when He <span class="h">herds<sup foot_note="365707">1</sup></span> them all together, then says to the angels, “Is it you that these used to worship?”",footnotes:346170:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs and Ya’qub read it as: “…when We herd them…”</span>
  34,41,"They said<sup foot_note="365708">1</sup>, “Highly Exalted are You; You are our Ultimate Guardian, not them. Rather, they used to worship the unseen beings<sup foot_note="365709">2</sup> ; most of them are believers in them.”",footnotes:346171:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.|346172:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.
  34,42,"“So today youpl possess for one another neither benefit nor harm.” And We will say to those who did injustices, “Taste the punishment of the Fire in which you used to disbelieve.”"
  34,43,"And when Our signs<sup foot_note="365710">1</sup> are read to them, evident, they say, “This is nothing but a man who wants to bar you<sup>pl</sup> from what your forefathers used to worship.” And they say, “This is nothing but a fabricated lie.” And the deniers said of the truth when it came to them, “This is nothing but evident sorcery.”",footnotes:346173:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  34,44,"Yet never before had We given them any books to study, nor had We sent them any warner before you<sup>sg</sup>."
  34,45,"And those before them also disbelieved, and never did they attain even a tenth of what We gave them. And they disbelieved My messengers, so how terrible was My condemnation!"
  34,46,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Indeed, I admonish you<sup>pl</sup> with one thing: that you rise up for Allah in pairs or individually, then reflect. There is no madness in your fellow. He is just a warner to you before the advent of a severe punishment.”"
  34,47,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Whatever reward I have asked of you<sup>pl</sup>, it is yours; my reward comes only from Allah, and He is Witness over everything.”"
  34,48,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Indeed, My Lord projects the truth. He is the Superb Knower of the hidden realms.”"
  34,49,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “The truth has come, while falsehood can neither originate nor restore.”"
  34,50,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “If I go astray, I go astray only to my own loss; but if I am guided, it is by what my Lord reveals to me; He is indeed All-Hearing, Near.”"
  34,51,"And if you<sup>sg</sup> could only see when they were<sup foot_note="365711">1</sup> terrified and there was no escape, and they were seized from a nearby place.",footnotes:346174:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  34,52,"And they said, “We have believed in it.” But how can they attain it from such a distant place"
  34,53,"when they had denied it before<sup foot_note="365712">1</sup> ? And they throw about conjectures regarding the hidden realm from such a distant place.",footnotes:346175:In the Earlier Life of this world.
  34,54,"And a barrier was placed between them and what they desire, as was done formerly with their likes. Indeed, they were in disturbing doubt."
  35,1,"All praise be to Allah, Originator of the heavens and the earth, Maker of the angels as messengers with two and three and four wings. He adds to creation as He wills; indeed, Allah is Powerful over everything."
  35,2,"Whatever mercy Allah unfolds for mankind, none can withhold it; and whatever He withholds, none can release it thereafter. And He is indeed the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  35,3,"O mankind, remember Allah’s blessing upon you. Is there a creator other than Allah who provides for you from the heaven and the earth? There is no god but He, so how can you be averted <small>(from the truth)</small>?"
  35,4,"And if they disbelieve you<sup>sg</sup>, surely messengers before you were also disbelieved. And to Allah all matters are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365713">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346176:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “…all matters return.”</span>
  35,5,"O mankind, indeed the promise of Allah is true, so let not the Earlier Life deceive you, and let not the Deceiver deceive you regarding Allah."
  35,6,"Indeed, Satan is an enemy to you<sup>pl</sup>, so take him as an enemy; indeed, he only invites his party to be among the fellows of the Blaze."
  35,7,"For those who have denied is a severe punishment, while for those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds is forgiveness and a supreme reward."
  35,8,"What about the one whose evil deed was adorned for him and so he came to regard it as good? Allah misguides whomever He wills and He guides whomever He wills, so let not your self be <span class="h">wasted<sup foot_note="365714">1</sup></span> sorrowing over them; indeed, Allah is All-Knowing of what they do.",footnotes:346177:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…so do not waste your self sorrowing over them;”</span>
  35,9,"And Allah is the One who sent the <span class="h">winds<sup foot_note="365715">1</sup></span>, stirring up clouds, then We<sup foot_note="365716">2</sup> drove them to a lifeless land whereby We revived the earth after it had died; likewise is Resurrection.",footnotes:346178:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, and Khalaf read it as: “wind”.</span>|346179:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.
  35,10,"Whoever wants might—to Allah belongs all might. To Him ascends good speech, and righteous work lifts it up. But as for those who scheme evil, there is a severe punishment, and the scheming of those is bound to fail."
  35,11,"And Allah created you<sup>pl</sup> from dust, then from a sperm drop, then He made you pairs. And no female carries or delivers except with His knowledge. And no person is given a long life or has his life cut <span class="h">short<sup foot_note="365717">1</sup></span> except that it is in a record<sup foot_note="365718">2</sup> ; indeed, that is easy for Allah.",footnotes:346180:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “And no person is given a long life nor does He cut his life short except…”</span>|346181:Literally ‘scripture’.
  35,12,"And the two waters are not equal: this one is fresh, sweet, good to drink, while this is salty, bitter. Yet from each you<sup>pl</sup> eat tender meat and extract jewelry which you wear, and you see the ships plowing through them, that you may seek of His grace, and that you may give thanks."
  35,13,"He causes the night to penetrate the day and He causes the day to penetrate the night, and He has subjected the sun and the moon, each running for a stated term. Such is Allah, your<sup>pl</sup> Lord; to Him belongs the dominion. But those you call upon apart from Him do not own so much as the mere skin of a date stone."
  35,14,"If you<sup>pl</sup> call upon them, they do not hear your call; and even if they heard, never would they respond to you. And on the Day of Resurrection, they will reject your polytheism. And none informs you<sup>sg</sup> like One Who is all-aware."
  35,15,"O mankind, it is you who stand in need of Allah, while Allah is the Self-Sufficient, the Praiseworthy."
  35,16,"If He wills, He can do away with you<sup>pl</sup> and bring about a new creation."
  35,17,"And that would not be too mighty for Allah."
  35,18,"And no bearer of burden bears the burden of another. And even if a heavily laden one calls for help with its load, nothing of it will be carried, even if the one called be a relative. You are only to warn those who fear their Lord, though unseen, and have established the prayer. And whoever purifies himself only purifies himself to his own benefit. And to Allah is the destiny."
  35,19,"Not equal are the blind one and the one who can see,"
  35,20,"nor are the darkness(es)<small>(es)</small> and the light,"
  35,21,"nor are the shade and the torrid heat,"
  35,22,"nor equal are the living and the dead. Indeed, Allah causes whomever He wills to hear, but you<sup>sg</sup> cannot make those in the graves hear."
  35,23,"You<sup>sg</sup> are only a warner."
  35,24,"Indeed, We have sent you<sup>sg</sup> with the truth, as a herald of glad tidings and a warner. And there is no community but a warner has passed through it."
  35,25,"And if they disbelieve you<sup>sg</sup>, those before them also disbelieved. Their messengers came to them with evident proofs and with the Books and with the illuminating Scripture."
  35,26,"Then I seized those who denied—so how terrible was My condemnation?"
  35,27,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen that Allah has sent down water from the sky, and with it We<sup foot_note="365719">1</sup> have brought out products of various colors? And in the mountains are streaks of white and red, varying in their hue, and pitch-black.",footnotes:346182:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.
  35,28,"Likewise, human beings and animals and livestock come in various colors. Indeed, from among His servants, only the learned fear Allah. Indeed, Allah is Almighty, Oft-Forgiving."
  35,29,"Indeed, those who read the Scripture of Allah and have established the prayer and have spent of what We have provided for them, secretly and publicly, expect a bargain that will not fail."
  35,30,"That He may render to them their rewards in full and increase them of His grace; He is indeed Oft-Forgiving, Ever Thankful."
  35,31,"And what We have revealed to you<sup>sg</sup> of the Scripture is the truth, confirming what preceded it. Allah is most surely All-Aware, All-Seeing of His servants."
  35,32,"Then We gave the Scripture as a heritage to those of Our servants whom We selected: so of them is one who is unjust to himself, and one who follows a middle course, and one who is a forerunner in good deeds—by Allah’s leave. That is what the great grace is."
  35,33,"Gardens of Eden which they <span class="h">enter<sup foot_note="365720">1</sup></span>; they are adorned therein with gold bracelets and <span class="h">pearls<sup foot_note="365721">2</sup></span>, and their garments therein are of silk.",footnotes:346183:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “…into which they are entered…”</span>|346184:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Asem and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…with bracelets of gold and (of) pearls…”</span>
  35,34,"And they said<sup foot_note="365722">1</sup>, “All praise be to Allah Who has lifted all sorrow from us; our Lord is most surely Oft-Forgiving, Ever Thankful.",footnotes:346185:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  35,35,"He Who settled us in the Home of Everlasting Stay, by His grace, where neither toil touches us nor fatigue afflicts us.”"
  35,36,"And those who have denied—for them is the fire of Hell wherein they are never finished off and thus die, nor is its punishment lightened for them. Thus We repay every staunch <span class="h">denier<sup foot_note="365723">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346186:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “Thus every staunch denier is repaid.”</span>
  35,37,"And they scream aloud therein, “Our Lord, get us out, that we may act righteously, unlike the way we used to act.” “Did We not give you<sup>pl</sup> a life long enough to take warning if you were going to? And the warner did come to you, so taste<sup foot_note="365724">1</sup>, for there is no supporter for the unjust.”",footnotes:346187:The punishment of your deeds.
  35,38,"Indeed, Allah is the Knower of the hidden realm of the heavens and the earth. Indeed, He is All-Knowing of what lies within the chests."
  35,39,"It is He who made you<sup>pl</sup> successors on earth. So whoever denies—his denial is upon him, and the denial of the deniers adds only to their Lord's loathing of them, and the denial of the deniers adds only to their perdition."
  35,40,"Say, “Have you regarded those associates of yours that you worship apart from Allah? Show me what they have created on earth." Or do they have any share in the heavens? Or have We given them a scripture such that they rely on an evident <span class="h">proof<sup foot_note="365725">1</sup></span> from it? Rather, the unjust promise one another nothing but a deception.",footnotes:346188:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Hafs, Hamza and Khalaf read it as: “…rely on evident proofs …”</span>
  35,41,"Indeed, Allah holds the heavens and the earth, lest they vanish. And were they to vanish, there is none to hold them both except He; indeed, He has always been Forbearing, Oft-Forgiving."
  35,42,"And they swore by Allah their most solemn oaths: that if a warner came to them, they would be more guided than any of the other communities. Yet when a warner came to them, it only increased them in aversion—"
  35,43,"behaving arrogantly in the land and scheming evil. But evil scheming surrounds none but its people. So do they expect anything but the precedent of the ancients? For you<sup>sg</sup> will never find any change in Allah’s rule, and you will never find any deviation in Allah’s rule."
  35,44,"And have they not journeyed through the earth and observed the consequences for those before them, though they were superior to them in strength? But in no way could Allah be thwarted by anything in the heavens or in the earth. Indeed, He has always been All-Knowing, All-Powerful."
  35,45,"And if Allah were to hold mankind accountable for what they have earned, He would not leave a single treading creature on its surface. But He defers them for a stated term, and then when their term is due—indeed, Allah has always been All-Seeing of His servants."
  36,1,"Ya-Sîn."
  36,2,"By the all-wise Recital<sup foot_note="365726">1</sup> .",footnotes:346189:The Arabic word used is<i> Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  36,3,"You<sup>sg</sup> are indeed of the emissaries"
  36,4,"on a straight path."
  36,5,"(God bestowed it as) a <span class="h">bestowal<sup foot_note="365727">1</sup></span> from on high by the Almighty, the Bestower of mercy,",footnotes:346190:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Amer, Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “(It is) a bestowal from on high…”</span>
  36,6,"to warn a people whose forefathers were not warned, so they are oblivious."
  36,7,"Certainly, most of them deserved the decree on them, for they refuse to believe."
  36,8,"Indeed, We placed shackles around their necks up to their chins, so that their heads are forced up."
  36,9,"And We placed a barrier in front of them and a barrier behind them, and thus We blocked their vision so they cannot see."
  36,10,"And it is the same for them whether you<sup>sg</sup> warn them or do not warn them—they believe not."
  36,11,"Indeed, you<sup>sg</sup> can only warn one who has followed the Reminder and has feared the All-Merciful though unseen—so give him glad tidings of forgiveness and a noble reward."
  36,12,"Indeed, We—We alone—revive the dead and write down what they have put forth and their traces. And everything have We tallied in an evident archive."
  36,13,"And set<sup>sg</sup> forth for them the parable of the fellows of the town when the Emissaries came to it—"
  36,14,"when We sent them two persons but they disbelieved them, so We <span class="h">reinforced<sup foot_note="365728">1</sup></span>(them) with a third. Then they said, “Truly, We are emissaries sent to you.”",footnotes:346191:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’bah read it as: “…so We overpowered with a third.”</span>
  36,15,"They said, “You are nothing but human beings like us, and the All-Merciful did not send down anything; you are only lying.”"
  36,16,"They said, “Our Lord knows that we are indeed emissaries sent to you,"
  36,17,"and our only duty is evident proclamation.”"
  36,18,"They said, “We see an evil omen in you<sup>pl</sup>; if you do not give up, we will most surely stone you, and a painful punishment from us will most surely afflict you.”"
  36,19,"They said, “Your evil omen is within yourselves. Can it be that it is because you were <span class="h">reminded<sup foot_note="365729">1</sup></span>? Rather, you are an extremist people!”",footnotes:346192:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “Is it because you were mentioned?”</span>
  36,20,"And there came a man rushing from the farthest end of the city. He said, “O my people, follow the emissaries."
  36,21,"Follow those who do not ask you<sup>pl</sup> any reward, and are themselves guided."
  36,22,"And why should I not worship the One Who originated me, and to Whom you<sup>pl</sup> are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365730">1</sup></span>?",footnotes:346193:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…you return?”</span>
  36,23,"Shall I take other gods apart from Him? If the All-Merciful wants harm for me, their intercession does not avail me at all, nor can they rescue me."
  36,24,"In that case, I should indeed be in evident misguidance."
  36,25,"Indeed, I have attained faith in your<sup>pl</sup> Lord, so listen to me.”"
  36,26,"It was said, “Enter the Garden (of Paradise).” He said, “Oh if only my people could know"
  36,27,"how my Lord has forgiven me and made me one of the honored!”"
  36,28,"And after him, We sent down no soldiers from heaven to his people, nor would We ever send any down."
  36,29,"It was <span class="h">just<sup foot_note="365731">1</sup></span> a single Shout, and suddenly they were extinct.",footnotes:346194:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “Nothing happened but a single shout…”</span>
  36,30,"Alas for the servants! No messenger comes to them but they ridicule him."
  36,31,"Have they not seen how many generations We annihilated before them—that they will not return to them?"
  36,32,"And none of <span class="h">them<sup foot_note="365732">1</sup></span> but will be arraigned before Us.",footnotes:346195:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Amer, Asem, Hamza and Ibn Jammaz read it as: “And all of them, all together, will be arraigned before Us.”</span>
  36,33,"And there is a sign for them in the lifeless land: We have revived it and have brought out from it grains, so from it they eat."
  36,34,"And We have made in it gardens of palm-trees and grapevines, and have caused springs to burst forth in it,"
  36,35,"that they may eat from its produce and (from) what<sup foot_note="365733">1</sup> their hands have <span class="h">made<sup foot_note="365734">2</sup></span>. So will they not give thanks?",footnotes:346196:The word <i>ma</i><i> </i>in Arabic can mean ‘what’ or ‘not’; if interpreted as the latter, the meaning of the statement becomes “…that they may eat from its fruits, though their hands have not made it…”|346197:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…from its produce and (from) their own handiwork…”</span>
  36,36,"Highly Exalted is He who created all pairs—of what the earth germinates and of their own selves<sup foot_note="365735">1</sup> and of what they do not know.",footnotes:346198:i.e. Males and females.
  36,37,"And a sign for them is the night: We strip the day out of it—and they are suddenly in darkness."
  36,38,"And the sun runs towards its destination; such is the determining of the Almighty, the All-Knowing."
  36,39,"And We have determined the <span class="h">moon<sup foot_note="365736">1</sup></span> in phases until it returned like an old palm-branch.",footnotes:346199:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Rouh read it as: “And the moon: We have determined it in phases…”</span>
  36,40,"The sun is not to overtake the moon, nor is the night to outpace the day, and each floats in an orbit."
  36,41,"And a sign for them is that We carried their <span class="h">offspring<sup foot_note="365737">1</sup></span> in the laden ship,",footnotes:346200:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…their offspring(s)…”</span>
  36,42,"and We created for them the like of it in which they ride."
  36,43,"And if We will, We can drown them—with no screaming to be heard from them, nor will they be rescued,"
  36,44,"except by a mercy from Us and enjoyment for a while."
  36,45,"And when it is said to them, “Be mindful of what lies before you and what lies behind you, that you may receive mercy”,...<sup foot_note="365738">1</sup>",footnotes:346201:This sentence is left open-ended. Some exegetes considered its predicate to be: “…they invariably disregard (it).”
  36,46,"Yet never does a sign of their Lord’s signs come to them, but they disregard it."
  36,47,"And when it is said to them, “Spend of what Allah has provided for you,” those who deny say to those who have attained faith, “Shall we feed someone whom Allah could feed, if He so wills? You are but in evident misguidance.”"
  36,48,"And they say, “When will this promise be, if you<sup>pl</sup> are truthful?”"
  36,49,"All they can expect is a single Shout, which will take them away while they feud,"
  36,50,"so that they will neither be able to make a will nor return to their own people."
  36,51,"And the trumpet was blown<sup foot_note="365739">1</sup>, whereupon they walked quickly out from the tombs to their Lord.",footnotes:346202:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  36,52,"They said, “Woe to us! Who has resurrected us from our resting place?” This is what the All-Merciful has promised, and the emissaries have spoken the truth.”"
  36,53,"It was <span class="h">just<sup foot_note="365740">1</sup></span> a single Shout, and suddenly they were all arraigned before Us.",footnotes:346203:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “It was nothing but a single shout…”</span>
  36,54,"So today no soul is dealt with unjustly in the least, and you<sup>pl</sup> are not repaid except for what you used to do."
  36,55,"Indeed, today the fellows of the Garden (of Paradise) are happily busy,"
  36,56,"they and their spouses, in <span class="h">shades<sup foot_note="365741">1</sup></span>, reclining on couches.",footnotes:346204:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…they and their spouses, under sunshades, reclining…”</span>
  36,57,"For them are fruits therein, and for them is whatever they call for."
  36,58,""Peace"—a word from a Lord Bestowing of mercy."
  36,59,"But step aside today, you criminals."
  36,60,"Did I not covenant with you, O Children of Adam, that you shall not worship the devil—indeed, for you he is an evident enemy—"
  36,61,"and that you shall worship Me? This is a straight path."
  36,62,"Yet he has certainly led a great multitude of you astray. Did you not use reason?"
  36,63,"This is Hell which you<sup>pl</sup> were promised."
  36,64,"Roast in it today on account of how you used to deny."
  36,65,"Today, We put a seal upon their mouths, and their hands speak to Us, and their feet testify to whatever they used to earn."
  36,66,"And if We will, We can obliterate their eyes, then they race with each other to (find) the Path—but how will they see?"
  36,67,"And if We will, We can disfigure them right in their <span class="h">place<sup foot_note="365742">1</sup></span>, so that they can neither move forward nor go back.",footnotes:346205:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “…in their places…”</span>
  36,68,"And to whomever We give long life, We reverse his development—so will <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="365743">1</sup></span> not reason?",footnotes:346206:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Zekwan, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “so will you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> not reason?”</span>
  36,69,"And never did We teach him<sup foot_note="365744">1</sup> poetry, nor is it proper for him; it is but a Reminder and an Evident Recital<sup foot_note="365745">2</sup> —",footnotes:346207:Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him).|346208:The Arabic word used is<i> Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  36,70,"so that it may <span class="h">forewarn<sup foot_note="365746">1</sup></span> whoever is alive, and so that God’s decree may be deserved by the deniers.",footnotes:346209:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…so that you<sup><small>sg</small></sup> may forewarn…….”</span>
  36,71,"Have they not seen that We have created for them, of Our Handiwork, livestock, so that they are their owners?"
  36,72,"And We made them manageable by them, so some they ride and some they eat."
  36,73,"And they have in them other benefits and drinks, so will they not give thanks?"
  36,74,"Yet they have taken to themselves gods other than Allah, that perhaps they may be supported."
  36,75,"They cannot support them, even if they are arraigned for them as an army."
  36,76,"So let not their words sadden you<sup>sg</sup>. Indeed, We know whatever they keep secret and whatever they make public."
  36,77,"Has man not regarded that We created him from a sperm-drop? Yet he became an evident adversary,"
  36,78,"and he set forth a parable for Us and forgot his own creation. He said, “Who can revive the bones when they have decayed?”"
  36,79,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “He who initiated them the first time revives them, for He is All-Knowing of every creation.”"
  36,80,"He who made fire for you<sup>pl</sup> out of green trees, so that with them you kindle."
  36,81,"Is not He who created the heavens and the earth <span class="h">capable<sup foot_note="365747">1</sup></span> of creating the like of them? Yes indeed, and He is the All-Creating, the All-Knowing.",footnotes:346210:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Roways read it as: “Cannot He who created the heavens and the earth create the like of them?”</span>
  36,82,"Indeed, His only command once He has desired anything is to say to it, “Be,” and so it <span class="h">is<sup foot_note="365748">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346211:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…is to say to it, ‘Be,’ so it is.”</span>
  36,83,"So Highly Exalted is the One in Whose hand is the dominion of everything, and to Him yousg will be <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365749">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346212:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…to Him you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> will return.”</span>
  37,1,"By those aligned, lined up in ranks."
  37,2,"Then by the propellers propelling firmly."
  37,3,"Then by the readers of a Reminder—"
  37,4,"indeed, your<sup>pl</sup> God is surely One,"
  37,5,"Lord of the heavens and the earth and whatever is between them, and Lord of the Easts."
  37,6,"Indeed, We have adorned the lowest<sup foot_note="365750">1</sup> heaven with an adornment, the <span class="h">planets<sup foot_note="365751">2</sup></span>,",footnotes:346213:The Arabic word <i>dunya</i> translated here as “lowest” is the same word used to describe the life of this world as the “Earlier” Life, as it carries both meanings: lowest and earlier.|346214:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “We have adorned the lower heaven by adorning the planets,” All except for Shu’ba, Hafs and Hamza read it as: “We have adorned the lower heaven with the adornment of planets,”</span>
  37,7,"and as a protection against every defiant devil."
  37,8,"They cannot <span class="h">eavesdrop<sup foot_note="365752">1</sup></span> on the Higher Assembly, for they get bombarded from every side—",footnotes:346215:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “They cannot hear the Higher…”</span>
  37,9,"repelled, and they will have an unremitting punishment,"
  37,10,"except for one who snatched a fragment and was then pursued by a piercing meteor."
  37,11,"So inquire<sup>sg</sup> of them, “Are they more difficult to create, or the others We created?” Indeed, We created them from sticky clay."
  37,12,"Rather, you<sup>sg</sup> were <span class="h">amazed<sup foot_note="365753">1</sup></span>, while they ridicule.",footnotes:346216:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Rather, I gravely noted as they ridicule.”</span>
  37,13,"And when reminded, they remember not."
  37,14,"And when they see a sign, they exaggerate in ridiculing"
  37,15,"and say, “This is nothing but evident sorcery."
  37,16,"Can it be that when we have died and become dust and bones, can it be <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="365754">1</sup></span> we will really be resurrected?",footnotes:346217:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Al-Kesa’i, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “Can it be that when we have died and become dust and bones we will really be resurrected?” Ibn Amer read it as: “When we have died and become dust and bones, can it be that we will really be resurrected?”</span>
  37,17,"<span class="h">And<sup foot_note="365755">1</sup></span> our ancient forefathers?”",footnotes:346218:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Qaloun, Abu Ja’far and Ibn Amer read it as: “Or our ancient…”</span>
  37,18,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Yes indeed, and you will be totally subdued.”"
  37,19,"It is but a single nudge, and there they are looking on (in bewilderment)!<small>(in bewilderment)</small>!"
  37,20,"And they said<sup foot_note="365756">1</sup>, “Woe to us! This is the Day of Recompense.”",footnotes:346219:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  37,21,"“This is the Day of Decision which you<sup>pl</sup> used to deny."
  37,22,"Herd<sup>pl</sup> those who were unjust and their spouses, and what they used to worship"
  37,23,"apart from Allah, and guide them to the path to purgatory."
  37,24,"And stop them—indeed, they are to be questioned.”"
  37,25,"“What is the matter with you<sup>pl</sup> that you do not help one another?”"
  37,26,"Rather, on this day, they are submissive."
  37,27,"And they cameb to one another, asking one another."
  37,28,"They<sup foot_note="365757">1</sup> said, “Indeed, you<sup>pl</sup> used to come at us from the right<sup foot_note="365758">2</sup> ”",footnotes:346220:The misled.|346221:This may mean that they used to force them or convince them of the rightness of their deeds.
  37,29,"They<sup foot_note="365759">1</sup> said, “Rather, you<sup>pl</sup> yourselves were not believers,",footnotes:346222:Those who misled.
  37,30,"and we had no authority over you; rather, you yourselves were a people who exceeded all limits."
  37,31,"And therefore we deserved our Lord’s decree on us. Most surely we will all get a taste,"
  37,32,"for we deluded you<sup>pl</sup>; indeed, we were deluded.”"
  37,33,"So on that day, they are indeed partners in the punishment."
  37,34,"This is what We do with the criminals."
  37,35,"Indeed, when it was said to them, “There is no god except Allah,” they would act arrogantly"
  37,36,"and say, “Are we really to abandon our gods for a mad poet?”"
  37,37,"In fact, he came with the truth, and he confirmed the emissaries."
  37,38,"Most surely, you<sup>pl</sup> will taste the painful punishment,"
  37,39,"and in no way will you be repaid except for what you used to do,"
  37,40,"except for Allah’s sincere <span class="h">chosen<sup foot_note="365760">1</sup></span> servants.",footnotes:346223:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “…except for Allah’s sincere servants.”</span>
  37,41,"For those, there is a known provision:"
  37,42,"fruits, and they are honored"
  37,43,"in the Gardens of Bliss,"
  37,44,"on couches facing one another."
  37,45,"A drink is passed round among them from a flowing spring:"
  37,46,"white, a delight to those who drink,"
  37,47,"no headiness in it, nor by it are <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="365761">1</sup></span> drained<sup foot_note="365762">2</sup> .",footnotes:346224:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “nor by it do they drain (themselves).”</span>|346225:A metaphor for being drunk.
  37,48,"And with them are bashful maidens with lovely eyes,"
  37,49,"as if they were closely guarded eggs."
  37,50,"So they came<sup foot_note="365763">1</sup> to one another, asking one another.",footnotes:346226:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  37,51,"One of them said, “Indeed, I did have a comrade"
  37,52,"who would say, ‘Can it be that you<sup>sg</sup> are really of those who believe?"
  37,53,"Can it be that when we have died and become dust and bones, can it be <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="365764">1</sup></span> we will really be called to account?’ ”",footnotes:346227:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “Can it be that when we have died and become dust and bones we will really be called to account?” Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “When we have died and become dust and bones, can it be that we will really be called to account?”</span>
  37,54,"He said <small>(to his companions in Paradise)</small>, “Can you<sup>pl</sup> view <small>(him)</small>?”"
  37,55,"Then he viewed <small>(him)</small> and saw him in the midst of purgatory."
  37,56,"He said, <small>“(I swear)</small> by Allah, you<sup>sg</sup> almost ruined me."
  37,57,"And were it not for the blessing of my Lord, I would have been of the arraigned.”"
  37,58,"“Are we <small>(then)</small> not to die"
  37,59,"except for our first death? And are we never to be punished?”"
  37,60,"60 It is most surely this which is the great triumph."
  37,61,"For the like of this let the workers work."
  37,62,"Is this a better hospitality or the Tree of Zaqqum<sup foot_note="365765">1</sup> ?",footnotes:346228:Trees in Hell which produce hot, bitter, rotten fruit.
  37,63,"Indeed, We have made it a means of trial for the unjust."
  37,64,"Indeed, it is a tree that comes out from the very origin of purgatory."
  37,65,"Its yield is as if it were devils’ heads."
  37,66,"So they are sure to eat from it and fill their bellies with it."
  37,67,"Then, on top of it, they will have a brew of scalding water."
  37,68,"Then their return is sure to be to purgatory."
  37,69,"Indeed, they found their forefathers astray,"
  37,70,"so they rush along in their footsteps."
  37,71,"And certainly, most of the ancients before them went astray."
  37,72,"And certainly, We sent among them forewarners."
  37,73,"So looksg at what the outcome was for those who were warned,"
  37,74,"except for Allah's sincere <span class="h">chosen<sup foot_note="365766">1</sup></span> servants.",footnotes:346229:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “…except for Allah’s sincere servants.”</span>
  37,75,"And certainly, Noah called out to Us, so the very excellent of responders are We!"
  37,76,"Thus We delivered him and his family from the great calamity,"
  37,77,"and We made his offspring the sole survivors,"
  37,78,"and We left him thus to be remembered among later generations."
  37,79,"Peace be upon Noah among <small>(all creatures of)</small> all realms."
  37,80,"Indeed, thus do We repay those who excel in doing good."
  37,81,"Indeed, he is one of Our believing servants."
  37,82,"Then We drowned the others."
  37,83,"And, indeed, of his kind is Abraham."
  37,84,"Recall when he came to his Lord with a sound heart."
  37,85,"He said to his father and his people, “What are you worshiping?"
  37,86,"Is it false gods, instead of Allah, that you<sup>pl</sup> want?"
  37,87,"So what is your<sup>pl</sup> opinion about the Lord of all realms?”"
  37,88,"Then he took one look at the stars"
  37,89,"and said, “I am sick.”"
  37,90,"So they turned away from him, fleeing,"
  37,91,"whereupon he turned to their gods and said, “Will you<sup>pl</sup> not eat?"
  37,92,"What is it with you<sup>pl</sup>? Do you not speak?”"
  37,93,"Then he turned on them, striking with his right hand."
  37,94,"So they came towards him, <span class="h">dashing<sup foot_note="365767">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346230:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “So they came towards him, urging (each other) to dash.”</span>
  37,95,"He said, “Do you worship what you carve,"
  37,96,"when Allah has created you<sup>pl</sup> and all that you do?”"
  37,97,"They said, “Build a structure for him and throw him into purgatory.”"
  37,98,"So they desired to plot against him, but We made them the lowest."
  37,99,"And then he said, “I am going to my Lord—He will guide me.”"
  37,100,"“My Lord, give me one of the righteous.”"
  37,101,"So We gave him glad tidings of a forbearing boy."
  37,102,"Then, when he was old enough to accompany him, he said, “O my child, I see in a dream that I am sacrificing you, so look—what do you <span class="h">see<sup foot_note="365768">1</sup></span>?” He said, “O my father, do as you are commanded; you will find me, Allah willing, of the patient ones.”",footnotes:346231:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “so look—what would you show (me) to do?”</span>
  37,103,"Then, when they<sup>dl</sup> had submitted and he laid him down on his forehead,"
  37,104,"We then called out to him, “O Abraham!"
  37,105,"You<sup>sg</sup> have truly fulfilled the vision.” Thus indeed do We repay those who excel in doing good."
  37,106,"Indeed, this was certainly the evident test."
  37,107,"And We redeemed him with a great sacrifice,"
  37,108,"and We left him thus to be remembered among later generations:"
  37,109,""Peace be upon Abraham.""
  37,110,"Thus We repay those who excel in doing good."
  37,111,"Indeed, he is one of Our believing servants."
  37,112,"And We gave him glad tidings of Isaac, a prophet, one of the righteous."
  37,113,"And We blessed him and Isaac. But of their offspring is one who excels in doing good and one who is evidently unjust to himself."
  37,114,"And We certainly conferred Our favor upon Moses and Aaron,"
  37,115,"and We delivered them<sup>dl</sup> and their people from the great calamity."
  37,116,"And We supported them<sup>pl</sup>, so they were the overcomers."
  37,117,"And We gave them<sup>dl</sup> the evidential Scripture,"
  37,118,"and We guided them<sup>dl</sup> upon the straight path."
  37,119,"And We left them<sup>dl</sup> thus to be remembered among later generations:"
  37,120,""Peace be upon Moses and Aaron.""
  37,121,"Thus do We repay those who excel in doing good."
  37,122,"Indeed, they are of Our believing servants."
  37,123,"And Elijah is indeed one of the emissaries."
  37,124,"Recall when he said to his people, “Will you not be mindful <small>(of God)</small>?"
  37,125,"Do you<sup>pl</sup> call upon Baal<sup foot_note="365769">1</sup> and leave the best of creators—",footnotes:346232:The name of an idol.
  37,126,"Allah, your <span class="h">Lord<sup foot_note="365770">1</sup></span> and the Lord of your ancient fathers?”",footnotes:346233:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “…the best of creators. <sub><small>126</small></sub>126 Allah is your Lord and the Lord…”</span>
  37,127,"But they disbelieved him, and thus they will certainly be arraigned,"
  37,128,"except for Allah’s sincere <span class="h">chosen<sup foot_note="365771">1</sup></span> servants.",footnotes:346234:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “…except for Allah’s sincere servants.”</span>
  37,129,"And We left him thus to be remembered among later generations:"
  37,130,""Peace be upon <span class="h">Elijah<sup foot_note="365772">1</sup></span>."",footnotes:346235:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “Peace be upon Elijah’s folk.”</span>
  37,131,"Thus do We repay those who excel in doing good."
  37,132,"Indeed, he is one of Our believing servants."
  37,133,"And Lot is indeed one of the emissaries."
  37,134,"Recall when We delivered him and all of his family,"
  37,135,"except for an old woman<sup foot_note="365773">1</sup> who lingered behind.",footnotes:346236:His wife.
  37,136,"Then We annihilated the others."
  37,137,"And most surely you<sup>pl</sup> pass by them in the morning"
  37,138,"and at night. Do you not reason?"
  37,139,"And Jonah is indeed one of the emissaries."
  37,140,"Recall when he fled to the overloaded ship,"
  37,141,"and he drew lots and was of those who lost."
  37,142,"Then the whale took him into its mouth, and he was to blame."
  37,143,"And had he not been one of those who highly exalt God,"
  37,144,"he would have stayed in its belly until the day they are resurrected."
  37,145,"Then We threw him into the wilderness while he was sick,"
  37,146,"and We germinated a gourd tree over him."
  37,147,"Then We sent him to a hundred thousand or more."
  37,148,"And they attained faith, so We gave them enjoyment for some time."
  37,149,"So inquire<sup>sg</sup> of them, “Are the daughters for your<sup>sg</sup> Lord while for them are the sons?”"
  37,150,"Or did We create the angels as females while they witnessed?”"
  37,151,"Undoubtedly, it is out of their utter falsehood that they do indeed say,"
  37,152,"“Allah has begotten.” But they are most surely liars."
  37,153,"Has He selected daughters over sons?"
  37,154,"What is it with you<sup>pl</sup>? How do you judge?"
  37,155,"Will you not <span class="h">remind<sup foot_note="365774">1</sup></span> yourselves?",footnotes:346237:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Will you not constantly remember?”</span>
  37,156,"Or do you<sup>pl</sup> have an evident manifestation?"
  37,157,"Then bring your<sup>pl</sup> scripture, if you have been truthful."
  37,158,"And they invented a relationship between Him and <small>(the race of)</small> unseen beings<sup foot_note="365775">1</sup> . And certainly, <small>(the race of) </small>unseen beings knew that they <small>(who made the claims)</small> would surely be arraigned—",footnotes:346238:The Arabic word used is <i>jinnah</i> which is the race of unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.
  37,159,"Highly Exalted is Allah far above what they describe—"
  37,160,"except for Allah’s sincere <span class="h">chosen<sup foot_note="365776">1</sup></span> servants.",footnotes:346239:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “…except for Allah’s sincere servants.”</span>
  37,161,"Thus surely, you<sup>pl</sup> and what you worship"
  37,162,"can never seduce <small>(anyone)</small> away from Him,"
  37,163,"except for one who is to roast in purgatory."
  37,164,"“And there is not one of us<sup foot_note="365777">1</sup> but has an assigned position.",footnotes:346240:The angels.
  37,165,"And we are indeed the aligned."
  37,166,"And we are indeed those who exalt God.”"
  37,167,"Even though they<sup foot_note="365778">1</sup> used to say,",footnotes:346241:The disbelievers.
  37,168,"“Had we received a Reminder from the ancients<sup foot_note="365779">1</sup>,",footnotes:346242:Ponder this with 38:1.
  37,169,"we would have been Allah's sincere chosen servants.”"
  37,170,"But they denied it, so they will find out."
  37,171,"And most surely Our Word has already gone out to our servant emissaries:"
  37,172,"indeed, it is they who shall surely be supported,"
  37,173,"and indeed it is Our soldiers who shall surely be the overcomers."
  37,174,"So turn<sup>sg</sup> away from them for some time,"
  37,175,"and watch them—for they will soon see."
  37,176,"Do they seek to hasten Our punishment?"
  37,177,"Yet, when it descends into their courtyard, miserable shall be the morning of those forewarned<sup foot_note="365780">1</sup> .",footnotes:346243:Ponder this with 38:11.
  37,178,"And turn<sup>sg</sup> away from them for a while,"
  37,179,"and watch—they will soon see."
  37,180,"Highly Exalted is your Lord, the Lord of Might, far above what they describe."
  37,181,"And peace be upon the emissaries."
  37,182,"And all praise be to Allah, Lord of all realms."
  38,1,"Sād. By the Qur’an containing the Reminder."
  38,2,"Yet those who denied are in a state of might<sup foot_note="365781">1</sup> and opposition.",footnotes:346244:Self-perceived might.
  38,3,"How many generations have We caused to perish before them, so they called out when it was too late to escape!"
  38,4,"And they marveled that a forewarner had come to them from among them, and the deniers said, “This is a sorcerer, a sheer liar."
  38,5,"Did he make all the gods into one God? Surely this is indeed something strange.”"
  38,6,"And the chiefs among them proceeded, <small>(saying)</small>, “Walk away <small>(from the Prophet)</small> and hold fast to your<sup>pl</sup> gods; indeed this is certainly something planned."
  38,7,"Never have we heard of this in the former creed. This is nothing but an invention."
  38,8,"Was the Reminder sent down to him out of all of us?” Rather, they are doubtful about My Reminder; rather, they have not yet tasted My punishment."
  38,9,"Or do they possess the treasuries of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord's mercy, the Almighty, the Giver?"
  38,10,"Or do they possess the dominion of the heavens and the earth and what is between them? Then let them ascend by any means."
  38,11,"An army of confederates will be defeated there."
  38,12,"Before them the people of Noah disbelieved, as did Ād<sup foot_note="365782">1</sup>, and Pharaoh of the stakes,",footnotes:346245:The pagan tribe of Prophet Hûd.
  38,13,"and Thamûd<sup foot_note="365783">1</sup> and the people of Lot and the fellows of the thicket. Those were the parties.",footnotes:346246:The pagan tribe of Prophet Salih.
  38,14,"None of them but disbelieved the messengers, so My punishment was deserved."
  38,15,"For these await nothing but a single shout, from which there is no recovery."
  38,16,"Yet they said, “Our Lord, hasten for us our share of punishment before the Day of Reckoning.”"
  38,17,"Endure<sup>sg</sup> patiently what they say and remember Our servant David who was endowed with strong faith; indeed, he often turns<sup foot_note="365784">1</sup> to Us.",footnotes:346247:Frequently the Qur’an speaks about the prophets using present tense; this should be pondered by the reader.
  38,18,"Indeed, We subjected the mountains to give due exaltations <small>(to God)</small> with him in the evening and at daybreak,"
  38,19,"with the birds made to flock, each often turning to Him."
  38,20,"Thus We strengthened his dominion and brought him wisdom and decisive speech."
  38,21,"And has the tiding of the disputants reached you<sup>sg</sup>, as they climbed the sanctuary—"
  38,22,"as they entered upon David, and he was startled by them? They said, “Do not fear; two disputants, one of whom has oppressed the other. So judge between us with the truth and do not be untrue, and guide us to the right path.”"
  38,23,"“Indeed, this is my brother; he has ninety-nine ewes and I have just one ewe, and he said, ‘Entrust it to me,’ and he pressured me with words.”"
  38,24,"He said, “He has done you<sup>sg</sup> wrong by asking your ewe in addition to his ewes, and indeed many partners do oppress one another— except those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds, but these are so few.” And David realized that We were testing him, so he sought forgiveness from his Lord and fell down to his knees and turned penitent."
  38,25,"So We forgave him that, and indeed there is most surely for him nearness to Us and a beautiful place to return to."
  38,26,"“O David, We have appointed you as a viceroy in the land, so judge between mankind with the truth and do not follow the whim, lest it misguide you from the way of Allah. Indeed, for those who stray from the way of Allah there is a severe punishment for their having forgotten the Day of Reckoning.”"
  38,27,"And in no way have We created the heaven and the earth and whatever is between them in vain. That is the assumption of those who have denied. So woe to those who have denied from the Fire!"
  38,28,"Or are We to make those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds equal to those who spread corruption in the earth? Or are We to make the people who are mindful <small>(of God)</small> equal to the wicked?"
  38,29,"A Scripture that We sent down to you<sup>sg</sup>, blessed, that <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="365785">1</sup></span> may ponder its signs<sup foot_note="365786">2</sup> and that those endowed with understanding may remind themselves.",footnotes:346248:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…that you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> may ponder…”</span>|346249:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  38,30,"And to David We gave Solomon, an excellent servant; indeed, he often turns<sup foot_note="365787">1</sup> to Us.",footnotes:346250:Frequently the Qur’an speaks about the prophets using present tense; this should be pondered by the reader.
  38,31,"Recall when the beautiful horses were paraded before him in the evening,"
  38,32,"so he said, "Indeed, I have loved the good things with a love more than the remembrance of my Lord, until it<sup foot_note="365788">1</sup> disappeared behind the veil <small>(of night)</small>.",footnotes:346251:Referring to the sun.
  38,33,"Bring<sup>pl</sup> them back to me.” And he started to stroke their legs and necks."
  38,34,"And surely, We tested Solomon and cast a body on his throne, then he turned penitent."
  38,35,"He said, “My Lord, forgive me and grant me a dominion never to be attained by anyone after me; indeed, You— only You—are the Giver.”"
  38,36,"So We subjected to him the <span class="h">wind<sup foot_note="365789">1</sup></span>, flowing gently by his command wherever he directed;",footnotes:346252:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “winds”.</span>
  38,37,"and the demons—every builder and diver;"
  38,38,"and others bound together in fetters."
  38,39,"“This is Our gift, so give<sup>sg</sup> generously or withhold, without measure.”"
  38,40,"And indeed, for him is nearness to Us and a beautiful place to return to."
  38,41,"And recall Our servant Job, when he called out to his Lord, “Satan has touched me with toil and suffering.”"
  38,42,"“Stamp your foot—this is a cool washing-place and drinking-place.”"
  38,43,"And We gave him back his family and doubled them—a mercy from Us and a reminding for those endowed with understanding."
  38,44,"“And take with your<sup>sg</sup> hand a bundle of grass, and strike with it so as not to breach (your oath).”<small>(your oath)</small>.” Indeed, We found him patient. What an excellent servant; indeed, he often turns<sup foot_note="365790">1</sup> unto Us.",footnotes:346253:Frequently the Qur’an speaks about the prophets using present tense; this should be pondered by the reader.
  38,45,"And recall<sup>sg</sup> Our <span class="h">servants<sup foot_note="365791">1</sup></span> Abraham and Isaac and Jacob—those endowed with strong faith and with sight<small>(s)</small>.",footnotes:346254:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “And recall<sup><small>sg</small></sup> Our servant Abraham…”</span>
  38,46,"Surely We distinguished them with a distinct <span class="h">quality<sup foot_note="365792">1</sup></span>—the remembrance of the <small>(final) </small>Home.",footnotes:346255:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Hisham and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…with the distinct quality of the remembrance…”</span>
  38,47,"And indeed, to Us they are of the elect, the outstanding."
  38,48,"And recall<sup>sg</sup> Ishmael and Elisha and Ezekiel—and all are of the outstanding."
  38,49,"This is a Reminder. For indeed, for the mindful <small>(of God)</small> is a beautiful place to return to:"
  38,50,"the Gardens of Eden, with their doors wide-open for them,"
  38,51,"relaxing therein and calling for abundant fruit and beverage."
  38,52,"And with them are bashful maidens of equal age."
  38,53,"This is what <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="365793">1</sup></span> are promised for the Day of Reckoning.",footnotes:346256:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “This is what they are promised…”</span>
  38,54,"Indeed, such is Our provision, inexhaustible."
  38,55,"All this. But indeed, for those who exceed all limits is a miserable place to return to:"
  38,56,"Hell, in which they roast—so what a miserable resting place!"
  38,57,"All this, so let them taste it—scalding water and purulence."
  38,58,"And <span class="h">another<sup foot_note="365794">1</sup></span><small>(torment)</small> similar to it, of diverse kinds.",footnotes:346257:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “And other (torments) similar…”</span>
  38,59,"“This is a crowd rushing headlong with you<sup>pl</sup>.” They are not welcome; indeed, they are to be roasted in the Fire."
  38,60,"They said, “But it is you<sup>pl</sup> who are not welcome! It is you who brought it upon us! So what a miserable end!”"
  38,61,"They said, “Our Lord, whoever brought this upon us, give him double punishment in the Fire.”"
  38,62,"And they said, “What is it with us that we do not see men whom we used to count among the villains?"
  38,63,"63 Did we take them with <span class="h">mockery<sup foot_note="365795">1</sup></span>, or have our sight(s)<small>(s)</small> swerved from them?",footnotes:346258:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: ...used to count among the villains—<sub><span class="role-mark"><small>63</small></span></sub>63 whom we took with mockery, or have our sight(s) swerved from them?Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…..used to count among the villains? Did we abuse them, or have our sight(s) swerved from them?Hamza, Al Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: ......used to count among the villains— <sub><span class="role-mark"><small>63</small></span></sub>63 whom we abused, or have our sight(s) swerved from them?</span>
  38,64,"Indeed, that is certainly true: the disputing among the inhabitants of the Fire."
  38,65,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Indeed, I am only a forewarner, for there is no god except Allah—the One, the Subduer,"
  38,66,"Lord of the heavens and the earth and whatever is between them, the Almighty, the Forgiver.”"
  38,67,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “It is a great tiding"
  38,68,"which you<sup>pl</sup> disregard."
  38,69,"I have had no knowledge of the Highest Assembly as they disputed."
  38,70,"It is only revealed to me <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="365796">1</sup></span> I am an evident warner.”",footnotes:346259:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “It is only revealed to me: indeed, I am an evident warner.”</span>
  38,71,"Recall when Your<sup>sg</sup> Lord said to the angels, “Indeed, I am creating a human being from clay."
  38,72,"So when I have formed him and breathed into him of My spirit, fall prostrate before him."
  38,73,"So the angels fell prostrate, all of them, entirely—"
  38,74,"but not Iblis<sup foot_note="365797">1</sup> ; he acted arrogantly and became one of the deniers.",footnotes:346260:Iblis is another name of Satan or <i>Shaytan</i>.
  38,75,"He said, “O Iblis, what prevented you from prostrating before what I created with My Own hands? Have you acted arrogantly, or have you become one of the exalted?”"
  38,76,"He said, “I am better than him; You created me from fire and created him from clay.”"
  38,77,"He said, “Then get out of it, for you are indeed an outcast!"
  38,78,"And indeed, My curse is upon you until the Day of Recompense.”"
  38,79,"He said, “My Lord, then reprieve me until the day they are resurrected.”"
  38,80,"He said, “Then indeed, You are of those reprieved"
  38,81,"until the Day of the Time Appointed.”"
  38,82,"He said, “Then, by Your majesty, I will most surely delude them all,"
  38,83,"except for your sincere <span class="h">chosen<sup foot_note="365798">1</sup></span> servants among them.”",footnotes:346261:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “…except for your sincere servants among them.”</span>
  38,84,"He said, “So the <span class="h">truth<sup foot_note="365799">1</sup></span> is—and only the truth I say—",footnotes:346262:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Asem, Hamza and Khalaf read it as: “So (by) the truth—and only the truth I say—”</span>
  38,85,"I will surely fill Hell with you<sup>sg</sup> and with whoever of them who follows you, all together.”"
  38,86,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “I ask of you no reward for this, and I am not a pretender."
  38,87,"It is but a Reminder to <small>(all creatures of)</small> all realms."
  38,88,"And you<sup>pl</sup> will certainly know its tiding after a while.”"
  39,1,"The bestowal of the Scripture from on high is by Allah the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  39,2,"Indeed, We have sent down to you<sup>sg</sup> the Scripture with the truth, so worship Allah, devoting religion to Him."
  39,3,"Undoubtedly, faithful religion is due to Allah! And those who take guardians apart from Him—<small>(they say,)</small> “We only worship them so that they may bring us closer to Allah.” Indeed, Allah will judge between them regarding whatever they used to differ over. Indeed, Allah does not guide one who is a liar, a relentless denier."
  39,4,"Had Allah desired to have a child, He would have selected whatever He so willed from whatever He created. Highly Exalted is He; He is Allah, the One, the Subduer."
  39,5,"He created the heavens and the earth with truth; He rolls the night around the day, and He rolls the day around the night. And He has subjected the sun and the moon, each running for a stated term. Undoubtedly, He is the Almighty, the Forgiving."
  39,6,"He created you<sup>pl</sup> from a single self, then made from it its spouse, and sent down to you of livestock eight kinds in pairs. He creates you in your mothers' bellies, one act of creation after another, in threefold darkness<small>(es)</small>. That is Allah, your<sup>pl</sup> Lord; to Him belongs the dominion; there is no god but Him, so how then are you turned away?"
  39,7,"If you<sup>pl</sup> deny, then indeed Allah is Self-sufficient without <small>(any need of)</small> you, yet He does not approve denial on the part of His servants, and if you are thankful He approves it for you. And no bearer of burden bears the burden of another. Then to your Lord is your return, whereupon He informs you of what you used to do; indeed, He is All-Knowing of what lies within the chests."
  39,8,"And when some harm touches man, he calls upon his Lord, in penitence to Him. But then, when He confers on him a blessing of His, he forgets what he was previously calling upon for, and he sets up rivals to Allah in order to make <small>(people)</small> <span class="h">stray<sup foot_note="365800">1</sup></span> from His way. Say, “Enjoy your<sup>sg</sup> denial for a little while; you are one of the fellows of the Fire.”",footnotes:346263:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Roways read it as: “…in order to stray from His way.”</span>
  39,9,"Or <span class="h">what<sup foot_note="365801">1</sup></span> about one who worships devoutly during the watches of the night, prostrating himself and standing up, wary of the Hereafter and hoping for the mercy of his Lord? Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Are those who know and those who do not know equal?” Indeed, only those endowed with understanding remind themselves.",footnotes:346264:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir and Hamza read it as: “What about one who…”</span>
  39,10,"Say<sup>sg</sup> <small>(on My behalf)</small>, “O My servants who have attained faith, be mindful of your<sup foot_note="365802">1</sup> Lord. For those who do good in this Earlier <small>(Life) </small>is goodness, and Allah’s land is vast. Indeed, the patient ones will be rendered their reward in full without measure.”",footnotes:346265:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 2<sup><small>nd</small></sup> person.
  39,11,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Indeed, I have been commanded to worship Allah, devoting religion to Him,"
  39,12,"and I was commanded to become the first of the Muslims<sup foot_note="365803">1</sup> .”",footnotes:346266:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means ‘those who willingly submit to God’.
  39,13,"Say, “I fear, if I disobey my Lord, the punishment of a great day.”"
  39,14,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “It is Allah I worship, devoting my religion to Him.”"
  39,15,"“So worshippl whatever you wish apart from Him.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Indeed, the losers are those who lost themselves and their people on the Day of Resurrection.” Undoubtedly, that is the evident loss."
  39,16,"They have layers of fire above them, and layers beneath them. That is how Allah puts fear into His servants. “O My servants, therefore, be mindful of Me!”"
  39,17,"And those who avoided false masters—that they should worship them, and turned to Allah in penitence—for them are glad tidings. So give<sup>sg</sup> glad tidings to My servants"
  39,18,"who listen to what is said and follow the best of it; those are the ones whom Allah has guided, and those are the people of understanding."
  39,19,"What about the one who has deserved the decree of punishment? Is it you<sup>sg</sup> who <small>(can)</small> rescue those in the Fire?"
  39,20,"But those who were mindful of their Lord—for them are compartments above which are compartments built high, with rivers flowing beneath them<small>:</small> the promise of Allah; Allah never breaks a promise."
  39,21,"Have you<sup>pl</sup> not seen that Allah has sent down water from the sky, then He made it flow into springs in the earth, then He brings out with it vegetation of various colors, then they wither and you see them yellowing, then He turns them into debris? Indeed, in this is a reminding for the people of understanding."
  39,22,"What about someone whose chest Allah has expanded to <small>(accept)</small> Islam, so that he follows a light from His Lord? So woe to those whose hearts are hardened against the remembrance of Allah; those are in evident misguidance."
  39,23,"Allah has bestowed the most beautiful of all teachings from on high: a Scripture consistent and paired. The skins of those who fear their Lord shiver from it, then their skins and their hearts soften up to the remembrance of Allah. Such is Allah’s guidance; He guides with it whomever He wills. But whomever Allah misguides, no guide shall there ever be for him."
  39,24,"What about someone who covers his face against the terrible punishment of the Day of Resurrection? And it was said<sup foot_note="365804">1</sup> to the unjust, “Taste what you<sup>pl</sup> used to earn.”",footnotes:346267:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  39,25,"Those before them disbelieved, so the punishment came up to them from where they were unaware."
  39,26,"So Allah made them taste disgrace in the Earlier Life, and surely the punishment of the Hereafter is more grievous, if they only knew."
  39,27,"And surely, We have put forth in this Recital<sup foot_note="365805">1</sup> for mankind all kinds of parables, that they may remind themselves:",footnotes:346268:The Arabic word used is<i> ‘Qur’an’</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  39,28,"an Arabic Recital<sup foot_note="365806">1</sup>, free from any distortion, that they may become mindful <small>(of God)</small>.",footnotes:346269:The Arabic word used is<i> ‘Qur’an’</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  39,29,"Allah set forth the parable of a man owned by quarreling associates, and a man belonging exclusively to one man. Are they equal in status? All praise be to Allah. But most of them do not know."
  39,30,"You<sup>sg</sup> will certainly die, and they will certainly die."
  39,31,"Then certainly on the Day of Resurrection you will dispute with one another in the presence of your Lord."
  39,32,"So who is more unjust than one who lied about Allah and disbelieved the truth when it came to him? Is there not in Hell a dwelling for the deniers?"
  39,33,"But the one who came with the sincere belief and sincerely believed in it—those<sup foot_note="365807">1</sup> are the mindful <small>(of God)</small>.",footnotes:346270:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  39,34,"For them, with their Lord, is whatever they will; such is the repayment for those who excel in doing good."
  39,35,"So that Allah may remit the worst of what they have done and repay them their reward in accordance with the best of what they used to do."
  39,36,"Is not Allah enough for His <span class="h">servant<sup foot_note="365808">1</sup></span>? And they <small>(seek to)</small> frighten you<sup>sg</sup> with those apart from Him. Thus whomever Allah misguides, no guide shall there ever be for him.",footnotes:346271:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Abu Ja’far and Khalaf read it as: “servants”.</span>
  39,37,"And whomever Allah guides, for him there is no misleader. Is Allah not Almighty, Capable of vengeance?"
  39,38,"And if you<sup>sg</sup> asked them, “Who created the heavens and the earth?” they would say, “Allah.” Say, “Have you<sup>pl</sup> seen those whom you call upon apart from Allah? If Allah desired any harm for me, would they be capable of preventing His harm? And if He desired a blessing for me, would they be capable of preventing His mercy?” Say, “Allah suffices for me; those who trust, place their trust in Him.”"
  39,39,"Say, ‘My people, act according to your <span class="h">position<sup foot_note="365809">1</sup></span>; surely, I am also acting <small>(according to mine)</small>. Then you shall come to know",footnotes:346272:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “positions”.</span>
  39,40,"who will receive a punishment that disgraces him, and upon whom a perpetual punishment shall fall.”"
  39,41,"Indeed, We have sent down the Scripture upon you<sup>sg</sup> for mankind with the truth. So whoever seeks guidance does so to his own benefit, while whoever goes astray—he only does so to his own detriment, and you are not a trustee over them."
  39,42,"Allah takes up the selves at the time of their death, and those that have not died <small>(He takes up)</small> during their sleep. Then He retains those for which He has <span class="h">decreed<sup foot_note="365810">1</sup></span> death and releases the others to <small>(fulfill)</small> a stated term. Most surely, in that are signs for people who reflect.",footnotes:346273:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Then He retains those for which death has been decreed…”</span>
  39,43,"Or have they chosen intercessors other than Allah? Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Even though they have no power over anything, nor do they reason?”"
  39,44,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “All intercession is up to Allah; to Him belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth, then to Him you<sup>pl</sup> are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365811">1</sup></span>.”",footnotes:346274:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…then to Him you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> return.”</span>
  39,45,"And when Allah is mentioned alone, the hearts of those who do not believe in the Hereafter are disgusted. But when those apart from Him are mentioned, they promptly start anticipating glad tidings."
  39,46,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Our God, Originator of the heavens and the earth, Knower of the hidden realm and the manifest, You judge between Your servants regarding whatever they used to differ over.”"
  39,47,"If those who were unjust owned whatever is in the earth, all together, and the like of it with it, they would <small>(seek to)</small> redeem themselves with it from the terrible punishment on the Day of Resurrection. But there appeared<sup foot_note="365812">1</sup> to them from Allah what they never anticipated.",footnotes:346275:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  39,48,"And there appeared to them the evil deeds of whatever they had earned, and so they became surrounded by what they used to ridicule."
  39,49,"And when harm touches man, he calls upon Us; then when We grant him a blessing from Us, he says, “I have been brought it solely because of <small>(my)</small> knowledge.” Rather, it is a means of trial, but most of them do not know."
  39,50,"Those before them previously said that, but what they used to earn did not avail them,"
  39,51,"so they were afflicted by the evil deeds of whatever they had earned. And the unjust among these will also be afflicted by the evil deeds of whatever they have earned, and in no way can they thwart <small>(God)</small>."
  39,52,"Have they not come to know that Allah extends provision for whomever He wills, and He restrains <small>(it)</small>? In that are signs for people who believe."
  39,53,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “O My servants who have gone to extremes against themselves: despair not of Allah’s mercy, for indeed Allah forgives all misdeeds; indeed, He is the Oft-Forgiving, the Bestower of mercy.”"
  39,54,"And turn penitent to your<sup>pl</sup> Lord and submit to Him before the punishment comes upon you and you are not supported."
  39,55,"And follow the best of what was sent down to you<sup>pl</sup> from your Lord before the punishment comes upon you suddenly while you are unaware."
  39,56,"So that no soul may say, “Alas, for having neglected my duty towards Allah and for having been of the mockers.”"
  39,57,"Or it may say, “Had Allah guided me, I would have been of the mindful <small>(of God)</small>.”"
  39,58,"Or it may say, when it sees the punishment, “If only I had another chance, I would be of those who excel in doing good.”"
  39,59,"Yes indeed! My signs did come to you<sup>sg</sup>, but you disbelieved in them and acted arrogantly and were of the deniers."
  39,60,"And on the Day of Resurrection you<sup>sg</sup> see those who told lies about Allah with their faces blackened. Is there not in Hell a dwelling for the arrogant?"
  39,61,"And Allah <span class="h">delivers<sup foot_note="365813">1</sup></span> those who were mindful <small>(of Him) </small>to their <span class="h">place<sup foot_note="365814">2</sup></span> of triumph; no harm touches them, nor do they grieve.",footnotes:346276:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Rouh read it as: “And Allah saves those…”</span>|346277:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…to their places of triumph…”</span>
  39,62,"Allah is the Creator of everything, and He is the Ultimate Trustee over everything."
  39,63,"To Him belong the treasures of the heavens and the earth. But those who have denied the signs of Allah—it is they who are the losers."
  39,64,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Is it other than Allah, then, that you command me to worship, you ignorant ones?”"
  39,65,"And it was revealed to you<sup>sg</sup> and to those before you that if you<sup>sg</sup> associate <small>(others with God)</small>, your work will certainly be nullified, and you will certainly be of the losers."
  39,66,"Rather, worship Allah and be of the appreciative."
  39,67,"Yet they did not render to Allah the respect that He deserves, for the entire earth is in His grip on the Day of Resurrection, and the heavens are folded in His right. Highly Exalted is He and Most High beyond the associations they make."
  39,68,"And the Trumpet was blown<sup foot_note="365815">1</sup>, so all who were in the heavens and the earth were stunned, except whomever Allah willed. Then it was blown another time, whereupon they all stood looking on.",footnotes:346278:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  39,69,"And the earth shone with the Light of its Lord, and the record<sup foot_note="365816">1</sup> was placed, and the prophets and the witnesses<sup foot_note="365817">2</sup> were brought in, and it was judged between them in truth, and they were not dealt with unjustly.",footnotes:346279:Literally ‘scripture’.|346280:The Arabic word used is <i>shuhada’</i>, which literally means ‘witnesses’ and is usually used to describe martyrs.
  39,70,"And every soul was fully compensated for what it had done, for He knows better what they do."
  39,71,"And those who denied were driven to Hell in throngs, until, when they had reached it, its gates were <span class="h">opened<sup foot_note="365818">1</sup></span> and its keepers said to them, “Did not messengers from among you come to you, reading to you the signs<sup foot_note="365819">2</sup> of your Lord and warning you of the meeting of this day of yours?” They said, “Yes, indeed!" But the word of punishment proved true against the deniers.",footnotes:346281:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “…its gates were opened wide and…”</span>|346282:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  39,72,"It was said, “Enter the gates of Hell, abiding therein.” So how miserable is the dwelling of the arrogant!"
  39,73,"And those who were mindful of their Lord were driven to the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> in throngs, until, when they had reached it and its gates were opened<sup foot_note="365820">1</sup> and its keepers said to them, “Peace be upon you, you have been good, so enter it, to abide.”",footnotes:346283:The Arabic word used is <i>shuhada’</i>, which literally means ‘witnesses’ and is usually used to describe martyrs.
  39,74,"And they said, “All praise be to Allah Who has fulfilled His promise to us and made us inherit the land, enjoying the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> as we please.” So how excellent is the reward of the workers!"
  39,75,"And you<sup>sg</sup> see<sup foot_note="365821">1</sup> the angels hovering around the Throne, exalting their Lord with praise. And it was judged between them equitably, and it was said, “Praise be to Allah, Lord of all realms.”",footnotes:346284:A grammatical shift to present tense, which serves to create a vivid portrait of future events.
  40,1,"Ha, Mīm."
  40,2,"The bestowal of the Scripture from on high is by Allah the Almighty, the All-Knowing,"
  40,3,"the Forgiver of <small>(every)</small> misdeed and the Granter and Accepter of repentance, the Severe in punishment, the Bountiful in bounty; there is no god but He; to Him is the ultimate return."
  40,4,"None argues against Allah’s signs except those who have denied, so do<sup>sg</sup> not be deceived by their movement in the land."
  40,5,"Before them the people of Noah disbelieved, as did the parties after them. And every community sought after their<sup foot_note="365822">1</sup> messenger in order to capture him, and they argued using falsehood to defeat with it the truth. But I seized them, so how was My punishment!",footnotes:346285:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  40,6,"Thus your<sup>sg</sup> Lord’s <span class="h">Word<sup foot_note="365823">1</sup></span> came true against those who denied: that they are the fellows of the Fire.",footnotes:346286:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “Words”.</span>
  40,7,"Those who carry the Throne and those around it exalt their Lord with praise and believe in Him and ask for forgiveness for those who have attained faith: “Our Lord, You have encompassed everything in mercy and knowledge, so forgive those who have repented and followed Your way, and protect them from the punishment of purgatory."
  40,8,"Our Lord, and enter them into the Gardens of Eden which You have promised them—and the righteous among their forefathers and their spouses and their offspring(s)<small>(s)</small>; indeed, it is You, You <small>(alone),</small> who are the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  40,9,"And shield them from evil deeds, for whomever You shield from evil deeds on that day, You have had mercy on him. And that is the great triumph.”"
  40,10,"Indeed, those who denied will be addressed, “The loathing of Allah is greater than your loathing of yourselves—for you were invited to the faith, but you refused.”"
  40,11,"They said<sup foot_note="365824">1</sup>, “Our Lord, you caused us to die twice, and you gave us life twice. Now we have acknowledged our misdeeds, so is there any way out?”",footnotes:346287:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  40,12,"That is because whenever Allah alone was called upon, you<sup>pl</sup> denied. But if others are associated with Him, you believe. But judgment rests with Allah the All-High, the Supreme."
  40,13,"It is He who shows you<sup>pl</sup> His signs and <span class="h">bestows<sup foot_note="365825">1</sup></span>—from on high—provision from heaven for you. But none reminds himself except whoever is penitent.",footnotes:346288:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…and sends down provision from heaven…”</span>
  40,14,"So call<sup>pl</sup> upon Allah, devoting religion to Him, even if the deniers hate it."
  40,15,"Exalted in degrees (of <small>(of </small>rank)<small>rank)</small>, Owner of the Throne—He casts the spirit <small>(of inspiration)</small> by His command upon whomever He wills of His servants to warn of the Day of Encounter:"
  40,16,"the day when they emerge; nothing about them is hidden from Allah. “To whom does the dominion belong today?” “To Allah, the One, the Subduer.”"
  40,17,"Today, every soul is repaid for what it has earned. There is no injustice today; indeed, Allah is Swift in reckoning."
  40,18,"And warn<sup>sg</sup> them of the Day of the Inevitable Event, when hearts are at throats, while they block them<sup foot_note="365826">1</sup> . The evildoers will have neither intimate <small>(friend)</small> nor intercessor to be obeyed.",footnotes:346289:Lest their hearts jump out of their throats, out of fear.
  40,19,"He knows the treacherous look of the eyes and whatever the chests hide."
  40,20,"And Allah decrees with the truth, while those whom <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="365827">1</sup></span> call upon apart from Him do not decree at all. Indeed, it is Allah who is the All-Hearing, the All-Seeing.",footnotes:346290:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Hisham read it as: “…while those whom you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> call upon…”</span>
  40,21,"Have they not journeyed through the earth and looked at how the outcome was for those before them? They were superior to <span class="h">them<sup foot_note="365828">1</sup></span> in strength and in the traces which they left in the land, but Allah seized them for their misdeeds, for they had no shield from Allah.",footnotes:346291:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “They were superior to you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> in strength…”</span>
  40,22,"That is because their messengers used to come to them with evident proofs, but they denied, so Allah seized them. He is All-Powerful, Stern in retribution."
  40,23,"And We sent Moses with Our signs and an evident manifestation"
  40,24,"to Pharaoh and Hamān and Qarun, but they said, “A sorcerer, a sheer liar.”"
  40,25,"Then when he came to them with the truth from Us, they said, “Kill the sons of those who have attained faith with him and keep their women alive <small>(in bondage)</small>.” But the plotting of the deniers can only go astray."
  40,26,"And Pharaoh said, “Let me kill Moses, and let him call upon his Lord; indeed, I am afraid that he may exchange your<sup>pl</sup> religion or that he may cause corruption to <span class="h">appear<sup foot_note="365829">1</sup></span> in the land.”",footnotes:346292:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Abu Amr and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…religion and that he may cause corruption to appear in the land.” Ibn Kathir and Ibn Amer read it as: “…religion and that corruption may appear in the land.” Shu’ba, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…religion or that corruption may appear in the land.”</span>
  40,27,"And Moses said, “I have sought refuge with my Lord and your<sup>pl</sup> Lord from every arrogant one who does not believe in the Day of Reckoning.”"
  40,28,"And a believing man from Pharaoh's folk who had concealed his faith said, “Do you<sup>pl</sup> kill a man for saying, ‘My Lord is Allah,’ and he has come to you with evident proofs from your Lord? If he is a liar, then his lying is upon him. But if he is truthful, then some of what he promises you will befall you; indeed, Allah does not guide anyone who is an extremist, a sheer liar."
  40,29,"O My people, yours is the dominion today, prevailing in the land. But who will help us against Allah’s chastisement, should it fall upon us?” Pharaoh said, “I do not show you<sup>pl</sup> except what I see, and I do not guide you except to the way of prudence.”"
  40,30,"But the one who had attained faith said, “O my people, I fear for you the like of the Day of the Parties—"
  40,31,"like the custom of the people of Noah and Ād<sup foot_note="365830">1</sup> and Thamûd<sup foot_note="365831">2</sup> and those after them. For Allah wants no injustice for the servants.",footnotes:346293:The pagan tribe of Prophet Hûd.|346294:The pagan tribe of Prophet Salih.
  40,32,"O my people, I fear for you the Day of Calling Out—"
  40,33,"the day when you turn away, fleeing, with no safeguard from Allah. And whomever Allah misguides, no guide shall there ever be for him."
  40,34,"And surely Joseph did come to you<sup>pl</sup> with the evident proofs, but you continued to doubt what he came to you with, until when he perished, you said, “Allah will never send a messenger after him.” Thus Allah misguides whoever is an extremist, constantly doubting."
  40,35,"Those who argue against Allah’s signs without any manifestation having come to them—this is most loathsome to Allah and to those who have attained faith; thus Allah seals the <span class="h">heart<sup foot_note="365832">1</sup></span> of every arrogant compeller.",footnotes:346295:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr and Ibn Zekwan read it as: “…thus Allah seals every arrogant compelling heart.”</span>
  40,36,"And Pharaoh said, “O Hamān, build me a tower, that I may reach the means—"
  40,37,"the means of the heavens, so that I may <span class="h">view<sup foot_note="365833">1</sup></span> the God of Moses, though I surely think he is a liar.” And thus Pharaoh’s evil deeds were adorned for him and he was <span class="h">barred<sup foot_note="365834">2</sup></span> from the way, for Pharaoh's plotting is in nothing but ruin.",footnotes:346296:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Hafs read it as: “…of the heavens, and view the God of Moses…”</span>|346297:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “… and he barred (others) from the way…”</span>
  40,38,"And the one who had attained faith said, “O my people, follow me and I will guide you to the way of prudence."
  40,39,"O my people, this Earlier Life is nothing but (<small>(</small>fleeting)<small>fleeting)</small> enjoyment, while the Hereafter is indeed the Home of Permanence."
  40,40,"Whoever has committed an evil deed will not be repaid except with its like, but whoever has acted righteously, whether male or female, while a believer—then those shall <span class="h">enter<sup foot_note="365835">1</sup></span> the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> where they shall be provided for without measure.",footnotes:346298:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Shu’ba, Abu Jaʻfar and Yaʻqub read it as: “…then those shall be entered into the Garden…”</span>
  40,41,"And O my people, how is it that I call you to salvation and you call me to the Fire?"
  40,42,"You<sup>pl</sup> call me to deny Allah and associate with Him what I have no knowledge of, while I call you to the Almighty, the Forgiver."
  40,43,"Without doubt, what you<sup>pl</sup> call me to has no say in the Earlier <small>(Life)</small> or in the Hereafter, and that our turning back is to Allah, and that it is the extremists who are the fellows of the Fire."
  40,44,"You<sup>pl</sup> will remember what I am telling you. So I entrust my affairs to Allah; indeed, Allah is All-Seeing of the servants.”"
  40,45,"So Allah shielded him from the evils of their scheming, while an awful punishment surrounded Pharaoh’s folk:"
  40,46,"the Fire—they are exposed to it in the early morning and at nightfall, and on the day the Hour takes place <small>(it is said)</small>: “Enterpl Pharaoh's <span class="h">folk<sup foot_note="365836">1</sup></span> into the most intense punishment.”",footnotes:346299:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer and Shu’ba read it as: “Enter<sup><span class="role-mark"><small>pl</small></span></sup>pl, O Pharaoh's folk…”</span>
  40,47,"And as they debate in the Fire, the weak say to the arrogant leaders, “Indeed, we were followers of yours, so will you now spare us a portion of the Fire?”"
  40,48,"The arrogant leaders said<sup foot_note="365837">1</sup>, “We are all in it; indeed, Allah has judged between the servants.”",footnotes:346300:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  40,49,"And those in the Fire said to the keepers of Hell, “Call upon your Lord to lighten one day of the punishment for us.”"
  40,50,"They said, “Did not your messengers come to you with evident proofs?” They said, “Yes.” They said, “Then call.” But the calling of the deniers is but in vain."
  40,51,"Most surely, We support Our messengers and those who have attained faith in the Earlier Life and on the day when all sorts of witnesses arise—"
  40,52,"the day when the excuses of the unjust do them no benefit, and for them is the curse, and for them is the worst (final)<small>(final)</small> Home."
  40,53,"And certainly We gave Moses the guidance and made the children of Israel inherit the Scripture,"
  40,54,"as guidance and a reminding for those endowed with understanding."
  40,55,"So be patient<sup>sg</sup>; indeed the promise of Allah is true. And ask forgiveness for your<sup>sg</sup> misdeed and exalt your Lord with praise evening and morning."
  40,56,"Indeed, those who argue against Allah’s signs without any manifestation having come to them—there is nothing in their chests but a feeling of greatness which they will never attain. So seek<sup>sg</sup> refuge in Allah; indeed, it is He who is the All-Hearing, the All-Seeing."
  40,57,"The creation of the heavens and the earth is certainly greater than the creation of humanity, but the majority of mankind does not know."
  40,58,"And in no way are the blind and the seeing equal, nor are those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds <small>(equal)</small> to the evildoer. How little <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="365838">1</sup></span> remind yourselves!",footnotes:346301:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “How little they remind themselves!”</span>
  40,59,"Indeed, the Hour is coming—no doubt about it—but the majority of mankind does not believe."
  40,60,"Yet your Lord has said, “Call upon Me <small>(and)</small> I will respond to you. Indeed, those who are too arrogant to serve Me will <span class="h">enter<sup foot_note="365839">1</sup></span> Hell in humiliation.”",footnotes:346302:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Shu’ba, Abu Ja’far and Roways read it as: “…will be entered into Hell…”</span>
  40,61,"It is Allah Who made the night for you<sup>pl</sup>, that you may rest therein, and the day allowing sight; indeed, Allah is certainly Gracious towards mankind, but the majority of mankind does not give thanks."
  40,62,"Such is Allah, your<sup>pl</sup> Lord, Creator of everything; there is no god except Him, so how can you be averted <small>(from the truth)</small>?"
  40,63,"Thus are averted those who used to repudiate the signs of Allah."
  40,64,"It is Allah who made the earth a habitat for you<sup>pl</sup>, and the sky a structure, and He designed you and perfected your designs, and He provided you with the good things. Such is Allah, your Lord, so supremely blessed be Allah, Lord of all realms."
  40,65,"He is the Living One; there is no god except He, so call<sup>pl</sup> upon Him, devoting religion to Him. All praise be to Allah, Lord of all realms."
  40,66,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Indeed, I have been forbidden to worship those whom you<sup>pl</sup> call upon apart from Allah, now that the evident proofs have come to me from my Lord. And I have been commanded to submit to the Lord of all realms.”"
  40,67,"It is He who created you<sup>pl</sup> from dust, then from a drop of semen, then from a clinging form, then He brings you out as infants, then He lets you attain your full strength, then you become elderly—although some of you are taken <small>(at death)</small> sooner—and that you may reach a predetermined age, and so that you may reason."
  40,68,"It is He who gives life and death, so whenever He decrees a matter, He says to it, “Be,” and so it <span class="h">is<sup foot_note="365840">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346303:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “He only says to it, ‘Be,’ so it is.”</span>
  40,69,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen those who argue regarding Allah's signs? How are they turned away?"
  40,70,"Those who disbelieved the Scripture and what We sent Our messengers with, for they will come to know"
  40,71,"when the yokes are around their necks, as well as the chains, as they are dragged"
  40,72,"into the scalding water, then in the Fire they are seethed."
  40,73,"Then it was said<sup foot_note="365841">1</sup> to them, “Where are those you used to associate",footnotes:346304:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  40,74,"apart from Allah?” They said, “They have strayed from us. In fact, we were calling upon nothing before.” Thus Allah misguides the deniers."
  40,75,"“That is on account of how you<sup>pl</sup> used to rejoice on earth in untruth and on account of how you used to behave with vanity."
  40,76,"Enter<sup>pl</sup> the gates of Hell, abiding therein. So how miserable is the dwelling of the arrogant!”"
  40,77,"So be patient<sup>sg</sup>; indeed, the promise of Allah is true. So whether We show you some of what We have promised them or take you up to Us, to Us they are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365842">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346305:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…to Us they return.”</span>
  40,78,"And surely We sent messengers before you<sup>sg</sup>, some of whose stories We related to you, and some We did not. And it was never for any messenger to bring about a sign except by Allah's leave. So when the command of Allah comes, matters are decreed between them with fairness, and there and then the advocates of falsehood will lose."
  40,79,"It is Allah who made livestock for you<sup>pl</sup>, that you may ride some of them and of some you eat."
  40,80,"And in them you have benefits, and through them you satisfy a need within your chests, and on them and on ships you are carried."
  40,81,"And He shows you<sup>pl</sup> His signs, so which of Allah’s signs do you deny?"
  40,82,"Have they not journeyed through the earth and looked at how the outcome was for those before them? They were superior to them in strength and in the traces which they left in the land, but what they had achieved availed them nothing."
  40,83,"When their messengers came to them with evident proofs they rejoiced in the knowledge they had, so they became surrounded by what they used to ridicule."
  40,84,"Then when they witnessed Our chastisement they said, “We believe in Allah alone and we deny what we used to associate with Him.”"
  40,85,"But their faith could not help them once they witnessed Our chastisement; such has been Allah’s rule in <small>(dealing with)</small> His servants, and there and then did the deniers lose."
  41,1,"Ha Mīm."
  41,2,"A bestowal from on high by the All-Merciful, the Bestower of mercy—"
  41,3,"a Scripture whose signs<sup foot_note="365843">1</sup> were detailed as an Arabic Recital<sup foot_note="365844">2</sup> for people who know.",footnotes:346306:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.|346307:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  41,4,"A herald of glad tidings and a warner, but most of them disregard (it), so they do not hear."
  41,5,"And they said, “Our hearts are screened from what you<sup>sg</sup> call us to, and in our ears is deafness, and between us and you is a barrier. So do what you want, and so will we.”"
  41,6,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “I am only a human being like you<sup>pl</sup>. To me it is revealed that your god is One God. So be upright towards Him and seek forgiveness from Him.” And woe to the polytheists—"
  41,7,"those who do not bring about the purifying act<sup foot_note="365845">1</sup>, and regarding the Hereafter they are deniers.",footnotes:346308:The Arabic word here, <i>zak</i><i>āt</i>, is the same word used for purifying charity, and which literally means purification and growth.
  41,8,"Indeed, those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—for them is an unfailing reward."
  41,9,"Say, “Can it be that you<sup>pl</sup> really deny the One who created the earth in two (heavenly) days and attribute rivals to Him? That is the Lord of all realms.”"
  41,10,"And He made therein firm mountains on top of it, and He blessed it and determined its sustenance in four days, <span class="h">equal,<sup foot_note="365846">1</sup></span> for those who ask.",footnotes:346309:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…in four days; (they are) equal for those who ask.” Ya’qub read it as: “…in four equal days for those who ask.”</span>
  41,11,"Then He settled<sup foot_note="365847">1</sup> to the heaven while it was smoke, and said to it and to the earth, “Come, willingly or reluctantly.” They said, “We have come willingly.”",footnotes:346310:How He settled is beyond human understanding.
  41,12,"So He decreed them as seven heavens in two days, and He revealed within each heaven its command. And We adorned the lowest<sup foot_note="365848">1</sup> heaven with lamps, and for preservation; that is the determining of the Almighty, the All-Knowing.",footnotes:346311:The Arabic word <i>dunya</i> translated here as ‘lowest’ is the same word used to describe the life of this world as the “Earlier” Life, as it carries both meanings: lowest and earlier.
  41,13,"But if they disregard (you), then say<sup>sg</sup>, “I have warned you of a thunderbolt like the thunderbolt of Ād<sup foot_note="365849">1</sup> and Thamûd<sup foot_note="365850">2</sup> .”",footnotes:346312:The pagan tribe of Prophet Hûd.|346313:The pagan tribe of Prophet Salih.
  41,14,"Recall when their messengers came to them from before them and from behind them, saying, “Do not worship anyone but Allah.” They said, “Had our Lord willed, He would have sent down angels; therefore, of what you are sent with, we are deniers.”"
  41,15,"So, as for Ād, they turned unjustifiably arrogant in the land and said, “Who is more powerful than us?” Had they not seen that Allah, who created them, is more powerful than them? And they used to repudiate Our signs,"
  41,16,"so We sent upon them a screaming wind for a few days of unrelenting misfortune, to make them taste the punishment of disgrace in the Earlier Life. But the punishment of the Hereafter is surely more disgraceful, and they will not be supported."
  41,17,"But as for Thamûd, We had guided them, but they preferred blindness over guidance. So the thunderbolt of the degrading punishment seized them on account of what they used to earn."
  41,18,"Meanwhile, We delivered those who had attained faith and had been mindful (of God)."
  41,19,"And the day when Allah’s enemies are <span class="h">herded<sup foot_note="365851">1</sup></span> into the Fire in an organized manner—",footnotes:346314:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Ya’qub read it as: “And the day when We herd Allah’s enemies into the Fire…”</span>
  41,20,"until, when they reach it, their hearing and their sight(s) and their skins testify against them regarding what they used to do."
  41,21,"And they say to their skins, “Why did you testify against us?” They say, “Allah, Who made everything speak, made us speak.” It is He who created you<sup>pl</sup> the first time, and to Him you are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365852">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346315:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…and to him you return.”</span>
  41,22,"And you<sup>pl</sup> were unable to hide yourselves in a way that neither your hearing nor your sight(s) nor your skins were prevented from testifying against you, and you thought that Allah does not know much of what you do."
  41,23,"And it is that thought of yours about your<sup>pl</sup> Lord that led you to ruin—so you became of the losers."
  41,24,"So even if they endure patiently, the Fire is (still) a dwelling for them; and if they ask to make amends, they will not be allowed to amend."
  41,25,"And We assigned for them comrades who then adorned for them what was before them and what was behind them, and the Word came to pass against them among communities of unseen beings<sup foot_note="365853">1</sup> and humans that passed away before them; indeed, they were losers.",footnotes:346316:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.
  41,26,"Those who denied said, “Do not listen to this recitation<sup foot_note="365854">1</sup> and speak noisily during it so that you<sup>pl</sup> may overcome.”",footnotes:346317:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  41,27,"We will certainly make those who have denied taste a severe punishment, and We will certainly repay them for the worst of what they used to do."
  41,28,"Such is the repayment of Allah’s enemies—the Fire; therein for them is the Home of Eternity, a repayment on account of how they used to repudiate Our signs."
  41,29,"And those who denied said, “Our Lord, show us those two (groups) which misguided us—among unseen beings<sup foot_note="365855">1</sup> and humankind—so that we can trample them both under our feet so they become of the lowest.”",footnotes:346318:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.
  41,30,"Indeed, those who said: “Our Lord is Allah,” and then led a righteous life—the angels descend upon them: “Do not fear and do not grieve, but have glad tidings of the Garden (of Paradise) which you were promised."
  41,31,"We are your allies in the Earlier Life and in the Hereafter, and you have therein whatever your (inner) selves desire, and for you therein is whatever you claim,"
  41,32,"as hospitality from One Who is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy.”"
  41,33,"And who is better in speech than one who called to Allah and did righteousness and said, “I am of the Muslims<sup foot_note="365856">1</sup> ”?",footnotes:346319:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  41,34,"For good and evil are never equal. Repel (evil) with that which is better, and thereupon the one between whom and you<sup>sg</sup> is enmity becomes like an intimate ally."
  41,35,"But none receives it except those who were patient, and none receives it except the very fortunate."
  41,36,"And if you<sup>sg</sup> are ever spurred by a spurring from Satan, take refuge with Allah; indeed, He is the All-Hearing, the All-Knowing."
  41,37,"And of His signs are the night and the day and the sun and the moon. Do not prostrate yourselves to the sun nor to the moon, but prostrate yourselves to Allah Who created them, if it is Him that you worship."
  41,38,"But if they act arrogantly, then those in the presence of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord highly exalt Him with praise night and day, and never do they tire."
  41,39,"And of His signs is that you<sup>sg</sup> see the land still<sup foot_note="365857">1</sup>, but when We send down water upon it, it shakes and <span class="h">swells<sup foot_note="365858">2</sup></span>. Indeed, He Who revived it will certainly revive the dead; indeed, He is All-Powerful over everything.",footnotes:346320:Literally, ‘reverent’.|346321:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…it shakes and becomes higher.”</span>
  41,40,"Indeed, those who blaspheme Our signs are not hidden from Us. Is one who is cast into the Fire better, or one who comes safely on the Day of Resurrection? Do as you wish; He is All-Seeing of what you do."
  41,41,"Indeed, those who denied the Reminder when it came to them…<sup foot_note="365859">1</sup> —whereas it is indeed a mighty Scripture",footnotes:346322:This sentence is left open-ended; according to some exegetes its predicate is “—those are being called out from a distant place” mentioned in sign 44.
  41,42,"which falsehood cannot approach from before it or behind it—a bestowal from on high by One Who is Wise, Praiseworthy."
  41,43,"Nothing is said to you<sup>sg</sup> but was said to the messengers before you. Indeed, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is certainly Possessor of forgiveness and Possessor of painful retribution."
  41,44,"Had We made it a Recital<sup foot_note="365860">1</sup> in a foreign language, they would have said, “If only its signs<sup foot_note="365861">2</sup> were detailed.” A foreign language while (the messenger is) an Arab? Say<sup>sg</sup>, “For those who have attained faith, it is guidance and healing. But as for those who do not believe—there is deafness in their ears, and it is blindness upon them. Those are being called out from a distant place.”",footnotes:346323:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.|346324:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  41,45,"And surely, We brought Moses the Scripture, but it was differed upon. And were it not for a word that had preceded from your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, judgment would have been decreed between them. But indeed, they are surely in perplexing doubt concerning it."
  41,46,"Whoever acts righteously does so to his own benefit, while whoever commits evil does so to his own detriment. And your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is never a tyrant unto the servants."
  41,47,"To Him is referred (all) knowledge of the Hour. And no <span class="h">products<sup foot_note="365862">1</sup></span> come out of their sheaths nor does any female carry or deliver but with His knowledge. And on the day when He calls out to them, “Where are My associates?” They said<sup foot_note="365863">2</sup>, “We declare to You, none of us is a witness.”",footnotes:346325:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Amer, Hafs and Abu Ja’far read it as: “And no produce comes out of its sheath nor does any female conceive or deliver but with His knowledge.”</span>|346326:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  41,48,"And whatever they used to call upon earlier strayed away from them, and they realized that there was no escape for them."
  41,49,"Man never tires of supplication for good things, but if evil touches him, he becomes despairing, despondent."
  41,50,"And if We do let him taste a mercy from Us after an adversity that has touched him, he will surely say, “This is mine, and I do not think that the Hour is coming. And even if I am returned to my Lord, I will have the very best with Him.” We will inform those who denied of what they did, and We will make them taste a harsh punishment."
  41,51,"And when We bestow Our blessings upon Man, he disregards (Us) and distances himself. But when evil touches him, he has lengthy supplication."
  41,52,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Have you<sup>pl</sup> seen? If it is from Allah and then you deny it—who is more misguided than he who is in profound discord?”"
  41,53,"We will show them Our signs in the horizons and in themselves until it becomes evident to them that He<sup foot_note="365864">1</sup> is the Truth. Is it not sufficient that your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is witness over everything?",footnotes:346327:The Arabic pronoun can mean ‘He’ for God or ‘it’ for the Quran or Islam.
  41,54,"Undoubtedly, they do regard the meeting with their Lord with skepticism. Undoubtedly, He is indeed All-Encompassing of everything."
  42,1,"Ha Mīm."
  42,2,"’Ayn Sîn Qaf."
  42,3,"Thus <span class="h">reveals<sup foot_note="365865">1</sup></span>—to you<sup>sg</sup> and to those before you—Allah the Almighty, the All-Wise.",footnotes:346328:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “Thus it is revealed to you<sup lang="en-US"><small>sg</small></sup> and to those before you: Allah the Almighty, the All-Wise— <sub><small>4</small></sub>4 to Him belongs…”</span>
  42,4,"To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth, and He is the All-High, the Great."
  42,5,"The heavens almost <span class="h">splinter<sup foot_note="365866">1</sup></span> from above them, while the angels exalt their Lord with praise and ask forgiveness for those on earth. Undoubtedly, Allah is indeed the Oft-Forgiving, the Bestower of mercy.",footnotes:346329:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr, Shu’ba and Ya’qub read it as: “The heavens almost split apart from above them,”</span>
  42,6,"And those who take guardians apart from Him—Allah is a Constant Preserver over them, for you<sup>sg</sup> are not a trustee over them."
  42,7,"And thus We revealed to you<sup>sg</sup> an Arabic Recital<sup foot_note="365867">1</sup>, that you may warn the Mother of Towns<sup foot_note="365868">2</sup> and those around it and warn of the Day of Assembly, of which there is no doubt: a group in the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> and a group in the Blaze.",footnotes:346330:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.|346331:Makkah.
  42,8,"And had Allah willed, He could have made them one community, but He enters into His mercy whomever He wills, while the unjust have neither ally nor supporter."
  42,9,"Or have they taken others as guardians apart from Him? Yet Allah is the Ultimate Guardian, and He gives life to the dead, and He is All-Powerful over everything."
  42,10,"And whatever matter you<sup>pl</sup> differ over— its judgment rests with Allah. “Such is Allah, my Lord; in Him I have placed my trust and to Him I turn penitently.”"
  42,11,"The Originator of the heavens and the earth; He has made for you spouses from among yourselves, and of the animals mates<sup foot_note="365869">1</sup>, by means of which He multiplies you. The like of Him has nothing like him, and He is the All-Hearing, the All-Seeing.",footnotes:346332:The Arabic word used is the same as that translated as ‘spouses’ for humans.
  42,12,"To Him belong the treasures of the heavens and the earth. He extends provision for whomever He wills and He restrains <small>(it)</small>; indeed He is All-Knowing of everything."
  42,13,"He legislated for you<sup>pl</sup> the same religion He enjoined upon Noah, and what We revealed to you<sup>sg</sup>, and what We enjoined upon <span class="h">Abraham<sup foot_note="365870">1</sup></span> and Moses and Jesus: “You shall establish the religion and not be disunited therein.” To the polytheists, outrageous is what you call them to. Allah chooses to Himself whomever He wills, and He guides to Himself whoever is penitent.",footnotes:346333:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as <i>Ibrahim</i>, Hisham read it as: “Abraham”.</span>
  42,14,"And they did not become disunited except after knowledge had come to them, thereby oppressing one another. And were it not for a word that had preceded from your<sup>sg</sup> Lord <small>(to defer judgment)</small> to a stated term, judgment would have been decreed between them. And indeed, those who were made to inherit the Scripture after them are in grave doubt about it."
  42,15,"So, because of that, go<sup>sg</sup> on calling, and be upright as you have been commanded, and do not follow their whims, and say, “I have attained faith in what Allah has sent down in every Scripture, and I have been commanded to judge between you equitably. Allah is our Lord and your Lord; we have our deeds and you<sup>pl</sup> have your deeds; there is no debate between us and you; Allah will bring us together, for to Him is the destiny.”"
  42,16,"And those who continue to debate about Allah after He has been responded to—their argument is invalid with their Lord, and upon them falls wrath, and for them is a severe punishment."
  42,17,"It is Allah who sent down the Scripture with the truth, and the Balance<sup foot_note="365871">1</sup> . But what could make you<sup>sg</sup> realize that perhaps the Hour is near?",footnotes:346334:Balance by which to weigh conduct.
  42,18,"Those who do not believe in it seek to hasten it, but those who have attained faith are apprehensive of it and know it to be the truth. Undoubtedly, those who cast doubts about the Hour are most surely far astray."
  42,19,"Allah is Subtle towards His servants; He provides for whomever He wills, and He is the All-Powerful, the Almighty."
  42,20,"Whoever wants the harvest of the Hereafter—We increase for him his harvest, and whoever wants the harvest of the Earlier <small>(Life)</small>—We give him thereof, yet he has no share of the Hereafter."
  42,21,"Or is it that they have associates who have legislated for them as religion that which Allah has not given permission? And were it not for the conclusive decision, it would have been settled between them. For indeed, there is a painful punishment for the unjust."
  42,22,"You<sup>sg</sup> see the unjust apprehensive of what they have earned, and it is sure to befall them. But those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds are in the meadows of the Gardens <small>(of Paradise)</small>. For them is whatever they will in the presence of their Lord; that is what the supreme grace is."
  42,23,"Those are the glad tidings Allah gives to His servants who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “I ask of you no reward for it except the genuine love offered among those of kinship.” And whoever scores a good deed, We will increase its goodness for him; indeed, Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Ever Thankful."
  42,24,"Or do they say, “He has fabricated lies about Allah.” Yet if Allah so willed, He could seal your<sup>sg</sup> heart. But Allah erases falsehood and upholds the truth by His Words; indeed, He is All-Knowing of what lies within the chests."
  42,25,"And it is He who accepts the repentance of His servants, and pardons evil deeds, and knows what you<sup>pl</sup> <span class="h">do<sup foot_note="365872">1</sup></span>;",footnotes:346335:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…and knows what they do;”</span>
  42,26,"and He responds <small>(to)</small> those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds, and He increases them of His grace. But for the deniers is a severe punishment."
  42,27,"And if Allah were to extend provision for His servants, they would oppress <small>(others)</small> on earth. Rather, He <span class="h">bestows<sup foot_note="365873">1</sup></span> from on high in precise measure whatever He wills; indeed, regarding His servants, He is All-Aware, All-Seeing.",footnotes:346336:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…but He sends down in precise measure whatever He wills…”</span>
  42,28,"And it is He who <span class="h">bestows<sup foot_note="365874">1</sup></span> rain from on high, after they have despaired, and unfolds His mercy, and it is He Who is the Ultimate Guardian, the Praiseworthy.",footnotes:346337:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Amer, Asem and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…He who sends down rain after they…”</span>
  42,29,"And of His signs are the creation of the heavens and the earth and the treading creatures He has spread throughout them, for He is All-Able to gather them at will."
  42,30,"And whatever disaster befalls you<sup>pl</sup>—it is because of what your hands have earned, yet He pardons much."
  42,31,"And you<sup>pl</sup> cannot thwart <small>(God)</small> on earth, and apart from Allah you have neither ally nor supporter."
  42,32,"And of His signs are the ships sailing the sea like flags."
  42,33,"If He wills, He can still the <span class="h">wind<sup foot_note="365875">1</sup></span>, leaving them motionless on its surface; indeed, in that are signs for everyone who is most patient, constantly thankful.",footnotes:346338:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “winds”.</span>
  42,34,"Or He can wreck them on account of what they have earned, yet He pardons much—"
  42,35,"35 so that those who dispute Our signs may <span class="h">know<sup foot_note="365876">1</sup></span> that there is no escape for them.",footnotes:346339:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer, and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…yet He pardons much. <sub><small>35</small></sub>35 Thus those who dispute Our signs know that there is no escape for them.</span>
  42,36,"So whatever you are given of anything is only an enjoyment of the Earlier Life, but what Allah has is better and more lasting for those who have attained faith and in their Lord they have placed their trust;"
  42,37,"and those who avoid the <span class="h">gravest<sup foot_note="365877">1</sup></span> of sins and obscenities, and if they feel wrathful, they <small>(then)</small> forgive;",footnotes:346340:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…and those who avoid the grave kind of sin and…”</span>
  42,38,"and those who responded to their Lord and established the prayer, and whose affairs are conducted by mutual consultation, and of what We<sup foot_note="365878">1</sup> have provided them they spend;",footnotes:346341:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.
  42,39,"and those who, when oppression befalls them, defend themselves."
  42,40,"And the repayment of an evil deed is an evil deed equivalent to it. But whoever has pardoned and made reconciliation—his reward lies with Allah; indeed, He does not love the unjust."
  42,41,"And for one who has defended himself after being dealt with unjustly—on those<sup foot_note="365879">1</sup> there is no blame.",footnotes:346342:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  42,42,"Rather, blame lies on those who do injustice to mankind and commit unjustified aggression in the land; for those is a painful punishment."
  42,43,"But whoever has endured patiently and has forgiven—that is certainly a sign of real resolve."
  42,44,"And whoever Allah misguides has no guardian apart from Him. And you<sup>sg</sup> see the unjust when they have seen the punishment, saying, “Is there a way of going back?”"
  42,45,"And you<sup>sg</sup> see them exposed to it<sup foot_note="365880">1</sup>, reverent with humility, looking with a stealthy glance. And those who had attained faith said<sup foot_note="365881">2</sup>, “Indeed, the losers are those who lost themselves and their families on the Day of Resurrection.” Undoubtedly, the unjust are indeed in a lasting punishment.",footnotes:346343:The fire of Hell.|346344:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  42,46,"And they had no allies to support them against Allah. And whomever Allah misguides has no way out."
  42,47,"Respond to your<sup>pl</sup> Lord before there comes from Allah a day that cannot be turned back. You will have neither refuge on that day, nor possibility of denial."
  42,48,"But if they disregard <small>(you)</small>—We have not sent you<sup>sg</sup> as a constant preserver over them; your only duty is proclamation. And indeed, whenever We let man taste a mercy from Us, he rejoices in it. But when something evil befalls them as a consequence of what their hands have put forth, then man is indeed a staunch denier."
  42,49,"To Allah belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth; He creates whatever He wills. He grants females to whomever He wills, and He grants males to whomever He wills."
  42,50,"Or He pairs them, males and females, and He makes whomever He wills barren; indeed, He is All-Knowing, All-Powerful."
  42,51,"And it is not for any human that Allah should speak to him except by revelation or from behind a veil or by <span class="h">sending<sup foot_note="365882">1</sup></span> a messenger to reveal by His permission whatever He wills; indeed, He is All-High, All-Wise.",footnotes:346345:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ read it as: “…a veil, or He sends a messenger then reveals to him by His permission.”</span>
  42,52,"And thus have We revealed a spirit to you<sup>sg</sup> by Our command. You<sup>sg</sup> did not know what the Scripture was nor what faith was, but We made it a light with which We guide whomever We will of Our servants. And most surely, you guide to a straight path—"
  42,53,"the path of Allah to whom belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth. Undoubtedly, to Allah are destined all commands."
  43,1,"Ha Mīm."
  43,2,"By the Evident Scripture,"
  43,3,"indeed, We made it an Arabic Recital<sup foot_note="365883">1</sup>, that you<sup>pl</sup> may reason.",footnotes:346346:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  43,4,"And indeed, it is with Us in the Source of Scriptures, all-high, all-wise."
  43,5,"So shall We ignore reminding you<sup>pl</sup>, <span class="h">because<sup foot_note="365884">1</sup></span> you have been an extremist people?",footnotes:346347:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Abu Ja’far and Khalaf read it as: “…you<sup>pl</sup>, if you have been an extremist people?”</span>
  43,6,"And how many a prophet did We send to the ancients!"
  43,7,"Yet not a prophet came to them but that they used to ridicule him."
  43,8,"Thus We annihilated people more powerful than them, and so the example of the ancients has passed away."
  43,9,"And were you<sup>sg</sup> to ask them, “Who created the heavens and the earth?” They would say, “The Almighty, the All-Knowing created them.”"
  43,10,"He Who made the earth a <span class="h">cradle<sup foot_note="365885">1</sup></span> for you<sup>pl</sup> and traced in it ways for you, that you may be guided.",footnotes:346348:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…a resting place for you…”</span>
  43,11,"And He Who sent down water from the sky in due proportion, whereby We revived a lifeless land; thus you<sup>pl</sup> are brought <span class="h">out<sup foot_note="365886">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346349:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Zekwan, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “…thus you come out.”</span>
  43,12,"And He who created all pairs and provided you<sup>pl</sup> with ships and livestock on which you ride,"
  43,13,"that you<sup>pl</sup> may mount their backs then remember the blessing of your Lord as you settle upon them and say, “Highly Exalted is the One Who has subjected this to us, and in no way could we have done it by ourselves,"
  43,14,"and indeed to our Lord we are certainly returning.”"
  43,15,"Yet they ascribed to Him a portion of His servants. Surely, man is indeed an evidently staunch denier."
  43,16,"Or has He chosen for Himself daughters from what He creates, and favored you<sup>pl</sup> with sons?"
  43,17,"Yet when one of them is given glad tidings<sup foot_note="365887">1</sup> of what he ascribed to the All-Merciful, his face becomes dark as he suppresses his anguish,",footnotes:346350:This is said in sarcasm.
  43,18,"<small>(thinking)</small> “What! Someone brought <span class="h">up<sup foot_note="365888">1</sup></span> amid adornments and, in conflict, cannot be evident?”<sup foot_note="365889">2</sup>",footnotes:346351:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Someone growing up amid…”</span>|346352:Pagans looked at women in a demeaning way.
  43,19,"And they considered the angels, who are <span class="h">servants<sup foot_note="365890">1</sup></span> of the All-Merciful, to be females. Did they <span class="h">witness<sup foot_note="365891">2</sup></span> their creation? Their claim will be recorded and they will be asked.",footnotes:346353:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…who are with the All-Merciful…”</span>|346354:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “Were they made to witness their creation?”</span>
  43,20,"And they said, “Had the All-Merciful willed, we would not have worshiped them.” But they have no knowledge of that; they are merely conjecturing."
  43,21,"Or have We brought them a scripture prior to this one<sup foot_note="365892">1</sup>, so that they are adhering to it?",footnotes:346355:The Qur’an.
  43,22,"Rather, they said, “Indeed, we found our forefathers on a course<sup foot_note="365893">1</sup>, and indeed we are being guided in their footsteps.”",footnotes:346356:Literally, ‘a nation: a community’.
  43,23,"Likewise, We sent no warner before you<sup>sg</sup> to any town but its affluent ones said, “Indeed, we found our forefathers on a course<sup foot_note="365894">1</sup>, and indeed we are following in their footsteps.”",footnotes:346357:Literally, ‘a nation: a community’.
  43,24,"He would <span class="h">say<sup foot_note="365895">1</sup></span>, “Even if <span class="h">I<sup foot_note="365896">2</sup></span> have come to you<sup>pl</sup> with better guidance than what you found your forefathers following?” They would say, “Indeed, we deny what you<sup>pl</sup> are sent with.”",footnotes:346358:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Hafs and Ibn Amer read it as: “Say<sup><small> sg</small></sup>, “Even if I…”</span>|346359:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “Even if we bring…”</span>
  43,25,"Thus We took retribution on them, so look<sup>sg</sup> at what the outcome was for the disbelievers."
  43,26,"And recall when Abraham said to his father and his people, “I am innocent of what you worship"
  43,27,"except for the One Who originated me, for He will guide me.”"
  43,28,"And he made it an enduring word in his posterity, so that they may return."
  43,29,"Yet I let these and their forefathers enjoy (life) until the truth and an evident messenger came to them."
  43,30,"But when the truth came to them, they said, “This is sorcery, and indeed we are deniers of it.”"
  43,31,"They also said, “If only this Recital<sup foot_note="365897">1</sup> had been sent down to any great man from the two towns<sup foot_note="365898">2</sup> .”",footnotes:346360:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.|346361:Makkah and Al-ta’if.
  43,32,"Is it they who allocate the mercy of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord? It is We who have allocated their livelihood in the Earlier Life. And We elevated some of them by degrees above others, that some of them may employ one another in service. But your Lord’s mercy is better than what they hoard."
  43,33,"Were it not that humanity would become a single <small>(ungodly) </small>community, We would have provided those who deny the All-Merciful with <span class="h">roofs<sup foot_note="365899">1</sup></span> of silver to their houses, and stairways <small>(of silver)</small> by which they ascend,",footnotes:346362:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…with a roof of silver…”</span>
  43,34,"and doors <small>(of silver)</small> to their houses, and furnishings on which they recline,"
  43,35,"and <small>(golden)</small> decorations. Yet all that is <span class="h">nothing<sup foot_note="365900">1</sup></span> but the enjoyment of the Earlier Life, whereas the Hereafter with your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is for the ones who are mindful <small>(of God)</small>.",footnotes:346363:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza and Hisham in one of his narrations read it as: “…decorations. Indeed all that is merely the enjoyment…”</span>
  43,36,"And whoever shuns the remembrance of the All-Merciful, We <span class="h">assign<sup foot_note="365901">1</sup></span> for him a Satan who then becomes his comrade.",footnotes:346364:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…He assigns for him…”</span>
  43,37,"And indeed, they certainly bar them from the way, though they think they are guided."
  43,38,"Until, when he comes to Us, he says, “If only there were between me and you<sup>sg</sup> the distance of the two easts.” What a miserable comrade!"
  43,39,"Yet never will it benefit you<sup>pl</sup> on that day, since you have committed injustices, that you are partners in the punishment."
  43,40,"Can you<sup>sg</sup> make the deaf hear, or guide the blind and one who has been in evident misguidance?"
  43,41,"So We will either take you<sup>sg</sup> away, then surely wreak vengeance upon them,"
  43,42,"or We will surely show you what We have promised them, for indeed We have absolute power over them."
  43,43,"So adhere<sup>sg</sup> to what has been revealed to you; indeed you are upon a straight path."
  43,44,"And indeed it is surely a message for you<sup>sg</sup> and for your people, and you<sup>pl</sup> will be asked."
  43,45,"And ask those of Our messengers We sent before you<sup>sg</sup>: “Did We appoint gods apart from the All-Merciful to be worshiped?”"
  43,46,"And We certainly sent Moses with Our signs to Pharaoh and his chiefs, so He said, “Indeed, I am the messenger of the Lord of all realms.”"
  43,47,"Yet, as soon as he came to them with Our signs, they promptly started laughing at them,"
  43,48,"even though each sign We showed them was more supreme than its counterpart, and We took hold of them with the punishment, that possibly they would return."
  43,49,"And they said <small>(to Moses)</small>, “O sorcerer, pray to your Lord for us according to His covenant with you, and then we will surely be guided.”"
  43,50,"But when We lifted the punishment from them, they promptly broke their promise."
  43,51,"And Pharaoh called out among his people; he said, “O my people, do I not have the dominion over Egypt, and are these rivers not flowing beneath me? Do you not see?"
  43,52,"Or am I not better than this one who is despicable and can barely express himself?"
  43,53,"So, if only some bracelets of gold had been cast on him, or if angels had come with him in comradeship!”"
  43,54,"Thus he fooled his people, and they obeyed him; indeed they were a defiantly disobedient people."
  43,55,"So when they displeased Us, We took vengeance on them and We drowned them all."
  43,56,"So We made them a <span class="h">precedent<sup foot_note="365902">1</sup></span> and an example for later people.",footnotes:346365:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Al Kesa’i read it as: “So We made them predecessors and an example…”</span>
  43,57,"And when the son of Mary was set forth as an example, your<sup>sg</sup> people promptly <span class="h">clapped<sup foot_note="365903">1</sup></span> him",footnotes:346366:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Al-Kesa’i, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Khalaf read it as: “…your<sup><small>pl</small></sup> people promptly barred (themselves and others) because of it…”</span>
  43,58,"and said, “Are our gods better, or he?” They cited him only for argument; in fact, they are a quarrelsome people."
  43,59,"He is but a servant whom We blessed, and We made him an example for the children of Israel."
  43,60,"And had We willed, We would have made from among you<sup>pl</sup> angels to be successors on earth."
  43,61,"And indeed he<sup foot_note="365904">1</sup> is a portent of the Hour, so never be<sup>pl</sup> skeptical about it and follow Me; this is a straight path.",footnotes:346367:Referring to Jesus, son of Mary.
  43,62,"And let not Satan bar you<sup>pl</sup>; indeed, he is an evident enemy to you."
  43,63,"And when Jesus came with the evident proofs, he said, “I have come to you<sup>pl</sup> with wisdom, and to clarify for you some of what you differ over, so be mindful of Allah and obey me."
  43,64,"Indeed, Allah is my Lord and your Lord, so worship Him; this is a straight path.”"
  43,65,"But the parties differed among themselves, so woe to those who committed injustices from the punishment of a painful day."
  43,66,"Are they only waiting for the Hour to come upon them suddenly, while they are unaware?"
  43,67,"On that day, close friends will be enemies to one another, except for the ones who were mindful <small>(of God)</small>."
  43,68,"O My servants, no fear shall be upon you today, nor shall you grieve."
  43,69,"Those who believed in Our signs<sup foot_note="365905">1</sup> and were Muslims<sup foot_note="365906">2</sup> :",footnotes:346368:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Quran, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.|346369:A Muslim is one who is submissive to Allah.
  43,70,"enter the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small>, you and your spouses, filled up with joy."
  43,71,"They are served around with trays of gold and cups, and therein is whatever is <span class="h">desired<sup foot_note="365907">1</sup></span> by the selves and delights the eyes, and therein you<sup>pl</sup> abide.",footnotes:346370:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Amer, Hafs and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…whatever the selves desire and delights the eyes…”</span>
  43,72,"And that is the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> you<sup>pl</sup> were made<sup foot_note="365908">1</sup> to inherit on account of what you used to do.",footnotes:346371:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  43,73,"For you<sup>pl</sup> therein is abundant fruit from which you eat."
  43,74,"Indeed, the criminals abide in the punishment of Hell"
  43,75,"which is never palliated for them, and in it they are devastated."
  43,76,"Yet in no way did We do them injustice, but it was they who were the unjust."
  43,77,"And they cried, “O Malek<sup foot_note="365909">1</sup>, let your Lord finish us off.” He said, “You are staying.",footnotes:346372:Malek is the angel in charge of Hell.
  43,78,"We certainly came to you with the truth, but most of you<sup>pl</sup> are hateful of the truth.”"
  43,79,"Or have they contrived to do something? So indeed, We too are contriving."
  43,80,"Or do they think that We cannot hear their secret and their private conversations? Yes indeed, Our messengers are by them, writing down."
  43,81,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “If the All-Merciful had a <span class="h">child<sup foot_note="365910">1</sup></span>, I would be the first of <small>(his)</small> worshipers.”",footnotes:346373:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Al Kesa’i read it as: “If the All-Merciful had children…”</span>
  43,82,"Highly Exalted is the Lord of the heavens and the earth, the Lord of the Throne, beyond what they describe."
  43,83,"So leave<sup>sg</sup> them to blunder and play until they <span class="h">meet<sup foot_note="365911">1</sup></span> their day which they are promised.",footnotes:346374:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…until they encounter their…”</span>
  43,84,"And it is He who in the heaven is God, and in the earth is God, and He is the All-Wise, the All-Knowing."
  43,85,"And supremely blessed be the One to Whom belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth and whatever is between them, and Who alone has knowledge of the Hour, and to Whom you<sup>pl</sup> are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365912">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346375:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Hamza, Al Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…and to Whom they are returned.”Roways read it as: “…and to Whom they return.” Rouh read it as: “…and to Whom you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> return.”</span>
  43,86,"And those they call upon apart from Him are incapable of intercession, except those who testify to the truth knowingly."
  43,87,"And surely if you asked them, “Who created them?” they would certainly say, “Allah.” So how can they be averted <small>(from the truth)</small>?"
  43,88,"And <small>(God hears)</small> his<sup foot_note="365913">1</sup> statement: “My Lord, indeed, these are people who do not believe.”",footnotes:346376:That of the Prophet (peace be upon him).
  43,89,"Then grant<sup>sg</sup> them amnesty and say, “Peace.” For <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="365914">1</sup></span> shall come to know.",footnotes:346377:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “For you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> shall come to know.”</span>
  44,1,"Ha Mīm."
  44,2,"By the Evident Scripture,"
  44,3,"We have indeed sent it down on a blessed night<sup foot_note="365915">1</sup> . Indeed, We have always been warning.",footnotes:346378:This night is known as the night of <i>Qadr </i>(Surah number 97), in the month of Ramadan.
  44,4,"On<small> </small>it, every wise command is distinguished—"
  44,5,"a command from Us; indeed, We have always been sending"
  44,6,"mercy from your<sup>sg</sup> Lord—indeed, it is He who is the All-Hearing, the All-Knowing—"
  44,7,"<small>(from the)</small> <span class="h">Lord<sup foot_note="365916">1</sup></span> of the heavens and the earth and what is between them, if you<sup>pl</sup> <small>(can ever)</small> believe with certitude.",footnotes:346379:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…the All-Knowing. <sub lang="en-GB"><small>7</small></sub>7 (He is the) Lord of the…”</span>
  44,8,"There is no god but He; He gives life and causes death—your<sup>pl</sup> Lord and the Lord of your ancient fathers."
  44,9,"Yet they play around in doubt."
  44,10,"So wait<sup>sg</sup> and watch out for the day when the sky produces evident smoke"
  44,11,"that overwhelms mankind; this is a painful punishment."
  44,12,"“Our Lord, lift the punishment from us; we are truly believers.”"
  44,13,"But how can the reminding benefit them when an evident messenger had already come to them,"
  44,14,"then they turned away from him and said, “<small>(He is)</small> taught <small>(by others)</small>, a madman!”"
  44,15,"Indeed, if We lift off the punishment a little, you<sup>pl</sup> will revert."
  44,16,"On the day when We assault with the biggest onslaught, We will indeed wreak vengeance upon them."
  44,17,"And surely before them We tested the people of Pharaoh when a noble messenger<sup foot_note="365917">1</sup> came to them,",footnotes:346380:Prophet <i>Musa</i>, or Moses.
  44,18,"saying, “Hand over Allah’s servants to me; indeed, I am to you<sup>pl</sup> a trustworthy messenger."
  44,19,"And do not consider yourselves to be above Allah; indeed, I come to you with an evident manifestation."
  44,20,"And I have indeed sought refuge with my Lord and your<sup>pl</sup> Lord lest you stone me."
  44,21,"Thus if you<sup>pl</sup> do not believe in me, just keep away from me.”"
  44,22,"Then he called upon his Lord—that these people are criminals."
  44,23,"<small>(Then His Lord commanded,)</small> “Journey with My servants by night; indeed, you<sup>pl</sup> will be followed."
  44,24,"And leave<sup>sg</sup> the sea parted <small>(behind you)</small>; indeed, they are an army to be drowned.”"
  44,25,"How many gardens and springs did they leave behind,"
  44,26,"as well as vegetation<small>(s)</small> and a noble domicile"
  44,27,"and a blessing they used to enjoy?"
  44,28,"So it was. And We made another people inherit it."
  44,29,"So neither heaven nor earth wept over them, nor were they reprieved."
  44,30,"And surely, We delivered the Children of Israel from the demeaning punishment—"
  44,31,"from Pharaoh; indeed, he was of the extremists."
  44,32,"And We chose them knowingly over all communities,"
  44,33,"and gave them of the signs that which was an evident test."
  44,34,"Indeed, these people surely say,"
  44,35,"“There is nothing but our first death, for we will not be resurrected."
  44,36,"So bring<sup>pl</sup> back our forefathers, if you are truthful!”"
  44,37,"Are they better, or the people of Tubba’<sup foot_note="365918">1</sup> and those before them? We annihilated them; indeed, they were criminals.",footnotes:346381:<i>Tubba’</i> is the name of a Yemenite tribal chief.
  44,38,"And We did not create the heavens and the earth and what is between them to play."
  44,39,"We did not create them except with truth, but most of them do not know."
  44,40,"Indeed, the Day of Decision is the appointed time for them all—"
  44,41,"a day when no patron will avail a protégé in any way, and they cannot be supported,"
  44,42,"except for one upon whom Allah has had<sup foot_note="365919">1</sup> mercy; indeed, He is the Almighty, the Bestower of mercy.",footnotes:346382:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  44,43,"Indeed, the Tree of Zaqqum<sup foot_note="365920">1</sup>",footnotes:346383:Trees in Hell which produce hot, bitter, rotten fruit.
  44,44,"is the food of the sinful one,"
  44,45,"like molten brass <span class="h">boiling<sup foot_note="365921">1</sup></span> in the bellies",footnotes:346384:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Kathir and Hafs read it as: “Indeed, the tree of Zaqqum is the food of the sinful one— <sub>45 </sub>like molten brass—boiling in the bellies…”like molten brass—boiling in the bellies…”</span>
  44,46,"like the boiling of scalding water."
  44,47,""Take<sup>pl</sup> him and drag him into the midst of Hell,"
  44,48,"then pour over his head some of the punishment of scalding water!”"
  44,49,""Taste<sup>sg</sup>! <span class="h">You<sup foot_note="365922">1</sup></span>—indeed you—are the mighty, the noble<sup foot_note="365923">2</sup> .",footnotes:346385:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Kesa’i read it as: “Taste<sup>sg</sup>, , that you—indeed you—are the…”</span>|346386:This is said in sarcasm.
  44,50,"Indeed, this is what you<sup>pl</sup> were<sup foot_note="365924">1</sup> skeptical about."",footnotes:346387:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  44,51,"Indeed, the mindful <small>(of God)</small> are in a safe domicile,"
  44,52,"amidst Gardens and springs,"
  44,53,"dressed in silk and brocade, facing one another."
  44,54,"So it is. And We married<sup foot_note="365925">1</sup> them to spouses with lovely wide eyes.",footnotes:346388:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  44,55,"They call therein for every kind of fruit, feeling safe."
  44,56,"Therein they do not taste death beyond the first death, and He shielded<sup foot_note="365926">1</sup> them from the punishment of Hell—",footnotes:346389:A grammatical shift from 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.
  44,57,"a grace from your<sup>sg</sup> Lord; that is the great triumph."
  44,58,"Thus have We made it<sup foot_note="365927">1</sup> easy through your<sup>sg</sup> tongue, that they may remind themselves.",footnotes:346390:The Qur’an.
  44,59,"So wait and watch<sup>sg</sup>. Indeed, they too are waiting and watching."
  45,1,"Ha, Mîm."
  45,2,"The bestowal of the Scripture from on high is by Allah the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  45,3,"Indeed, in the heavens and the earth are signs for the believers."
  45,4,"And in your<sup>pl</sup> own creation, and in the treading creatures He scatters, are signs for people who believe with certitude."
  45,5,"And the alternation of night and day, and the provision Allah has sent down from the sky, with which He has revived the earth after its death, and the shifting of the <span class="h">winds<sup foot_note="365928">1</sup></span> are signs for people who reason.",footnotes:346391:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “wind”.</span>
  45,6,"Those are Allah’s signs<sup foot_note="365929">1</sup> which We read to you<sup>sg</sup> in truth. So in which discourse, after Allah and His signs, will <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="365930">2</sup></span> believe?",footnotes:346392:The Arabic word used is a<i>yat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.|346393:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Hafs, Abu Ja’far and Rouh read it as: “…will you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> believe?”</span>
  45,7,"Woe to every sinful liar"
  45,8,"who hears Allah's signsb being read to him, yet he persists arrogantly, as though he did not hear them. So give<sup>sg</sup> him glad tidings<sup foot_note="365931">1</sup> of a painful punishment.",footnotes:346394:This is said in sarcasm.
  45,9,"And when he learns something of Our signs, he takes them in mockery; for those<sup foot_note="365932">1</sup> is a demeaning punishment.",footnotes:346395:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  45,10,"Beyond them lies Hell, and what they have earned will not benefit them at all, nor will those whom they took as guardians apart from Allah, for them is a great punishment."
  45,11,"This is guidance, but those who have denied their Lord’s signs—for them is a painful punishment of <span class="h">torment<sup foot_note="365933">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346396:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Kathir, Hafs and Ya’qub read it as: “…for them is a punishment of a painful torment.”</span>
  45,12,"Allah is the one Who has subjected to you<sup>pl</sup> the sea, that ships may run in it by His Command, and that you may seek of His grace, and that you may give thanks."
  45,13,"And He has subjected to you<sup>pl</sup> whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth—all is from Him. Indeed, in that are signs for people who reflect."
  45,14,"Tell<sup>sg</sup> those who have attained faith to forgive those who do not expect the Days of Allah, that He may <span class="h">repay<sup foot_note="365934">1</sup></span> people for what they used to earn.",footnotes:346397:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…that We may repay people…” Abu Ja’far read it as: “…that people may be repaid…”</span>
  45,15,"Whoever acts righteously does so to his own benefit, while whoever commits evil does so to his own detriment, then to your<sup>pl</sup> Lord you are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="365935">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346398:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…then to your Lord you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> return.”</span>
  45,16,"And surely We had given the Children of Israel the Scripture and wise judgment and prophethood, and We provided them with good things and favored them above all communities"
  45,17,"and gave them evident explanations regarding matters. Thus they differed not except after knowledge had come to them, thereby oppressing one another. Indeed, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord judges between them on the Day of Resurrection regarding whatever they used to differ over."
  45,18,"Then We set you<sup>sg</sup> upon a <small>(path of)</small> legislation regarding matters, so follow it and do not follow the whims of those who do not know."
  45,19,"Indeed, they will never avail you<sup>sg</sup> against Allah in any way, for indeed, the unjust are guardians of one another, while Allah is the Ultimate Guardian of the ones mindful <small>(of Him)</small>."
  45,20,"This provides insights for mankind, and guidance and mercy for people who believe with certitude."
  45,21,"Or do those who have perpetrated evil deeds assume that We will make them as equal to those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds, <span class="h">whether<sup foot_note="365936">1</sup></span> in their life or their death? Miserable is their judgment!",footnotes:346399:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Or do those who have perpetrated evil deeds assume that We will make them as those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds? Equal is their life or their death; miserable is their judgment!”</span>
  45,22,"And Allah created the heavens and the earth with truth, and so that every soul will be repaid for what it has earned, for they will not be dealt with unjustly."
  45,23,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> seen the one who has taken his own whim as his god, and Allah has misguided him despite his knowledge, and has sealed his hearing and his heart, and has placed a veil over his sight? Who will guide him after Allah? Will you not <span class="h">remind<sup foot_note="365937">1</sup></span> yourselves?",footnotes:346400:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Will you not constantly remind yourselves?”</span>
  45,24,"And they said, “There is nothing but our Earlier Life; we die and we live, for nothing annihilates us except time.” But they have no knowledge of that; they are only guessing."
  45,25,"And when Our signs<sup foot_note="365938">1</sup> are recited to them, evident, their only argument is to say, “Bring back our forefathers, if you<sup>pl</sup> are truthful.”",footnotes:346401:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  45,26,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Allah gives you life, then He makes you die, then He gathers you for the Day of Resurrection about which there is no doubt; but most of mankind does not know.”"
  45,27,"And to Allah belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth. Thus on the day when the Hour takes place—on that day the advocates of falsehood lose."
  45,28,"And you<sup>sg</sup> see every community kneeling; <span class="h">every<sup foot_note="365939">1</sup></span> community is called to its Scripture: “Today you<sup>pl</sup> are being repaid for what you used to do:",footnotes:346402:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “And you<sup><small>sg</small></sup> see every community kneeling, every community being called…”</span>
  45,29,"here is Our Scripture speaking about you<sup>pl</sup> in truth. Surely, We have been transcribing what you<sup>pl</sup> have been doing.”"
  45,30,"As for those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—their Lord enters them into His mercy; that is the evident triumph."
  45,31,"But as for those who have denied <small>(it will be said to them)</small>: “Were My signs not read to you<sup>pl</sup>, yet you acted arrogantly and were a criminal people?”"
  45,32,"And when it is said, “Indeed, the promise of Allah is true”—while of the <span class="h">Hour<sup foot_note="365940">1</sup></span> there is no doubt—you<sup>pl</sup> say, “We do not know what the Hour is; we are only making a guess; we are not certain.”",footnotes:346403:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “And when it is said, “Indeed, the promise of Allah is true, and of the Hour there is no doubt,” you<sup lang="en-US"><small>pl</small></sup> say…”</span>
  45,33,"And the evils of what they had done became evident to them<sup foot_note="365941">1</sup>, and they became surrounded by what they used to ridicule.",footnotes:346404:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  45,34,"And it was said, “Today We forget you<sup>pl</sup> as you forgot the meeting of this day of yours. Thus your shelter is the Fire, and there are no helpers for you."
  45,35,"That is because you<sup>pl</sup> dealt with Allah’s signs<sup foot_note="365942">1</sup> with ridicule, and the Earlier Life deceived you.” So today they are not <span class="h">brought<sup foot_note="365943">2</sup></span> out of it, and they are not allowed to make amends.",footnotes:346405:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God|346406:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “So today they do not come out of it.”</span>
  45,36,"So praise be to Allah—Lord of the heavens and Lord of the earth, Lord of all realms."
  45,37,"And to Him belongs all supremacy in the heavens and the earth, for He is the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  46,1,"Ha Mīm."
  46,2,"The bestowal of the Scripture from on high is by Allah, the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  46,3,"We did not create the heavens and the earth and what lies between them except in accordance with truth and for a stated term. But the deniers continue to disregard the warnings which they have received."
  46,4,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Have you<sup>pl</sup> seen what you call upon apart from Allah? Show me what they have created of the earth, or do they own a share of the heavens? Bring me a scripture prior to this one, or some trace of knowledge, if you are truthful.”"
  46,5,"And who is more misguided than one who calls upon, apart from Allah, those who will not respond to him until the Day of Resurrection and who are oblivious to their invocation?"
  46,6,"And when mankind is herded, those (false gods) become enemies to them and deny their worship of them."
  46,7,"And when Our signs<sup foot_note="365944">1</sup> are read to them, evident, those who deny say of the truth when it has come to them, “This is evident sorcery.”",footnotes:346407:The Arabic word used is ayat (singular ayah). Ayah means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  46,8,"Or do they say, “He has fabricated it!” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “If I have fabricated it myself, there is nothing you<sup>pl</sup> can do to protect me from Allah. He knows better what you are engaged in; sufficient is He as a witness between me and you, and He is the Oft-Forgiving, the Bestower of mercy.”"
  46,9,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “I am not different from the other messengers, and I do not know what will be done with me or with you<sup>pl</sup>. I only follow what is revealed to me, and I am only an evident warner.”"
  46,10,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Have you<sup>pl</sup> seen: if it is truly from Allah and you deny it? And a witness from the Children of Israel has testified to its like and has attained faith, while you have acted arrogantly. Indeed, Allah does not guide the unjust people.”"
  46,11,"Those who denied said of those who had attained faith, “If it were anything good, they would not have preceded us to it.” And since they were not guided by it, they will say, “This is an ancient lie.”"
  46,12,"And before it was the Scripture of Moses, a guide and a mercy. And this is a confirming Scripture in the Arabic tongue, that it may <span class="h">warn<sup foot_note="365945">1</sup></span> those who have done injustice, and as glad tidings for those who excel in doing good.",footnotes:346408:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Al-Bazzi, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “… that you may warn those…”</span>
  46,13,"Indeed, those who said, “Our Lord is Allah,” then led a righteous life—no fear shall be upon them, nor shall they grieve;"
  46,14,"those are the fellows of the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small>, abiding therein—a repayment on account of what they used to do."
  46,15,"And We have enjoined upon man excelling in showing <span class="h">kindness<sup foot_note="365946">1</sup></span> to his parents; his mother carried him with difficulty and delivered him with difficulty; his carriage and weaning are thirty months. Until, when he has attained his full strength and has reached forty years, he says, “Lord, enable me to appreciate the blessings with which You have blessed me and my parents, and to do righteousness that well pleases You, and grant me righteousness in my offspring. Indeed, I have repented to You, and indeed I am of the Muslims<sup foot_note="365947">2</sup> .”",footnotes:346409:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…upon man kindness to…”</span>|346410:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  46,16,"Those are the ones from whom We accept the best of what they have done and whose misdeeds We <span class="h">overlook<sup foot_note="365948">1</sup></span>; <small>(they are)</small> among the fellows of the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small>—the promise of truth which they had been promised.",footnotes:346411:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…from whom the best of what they have done is bound to be accepted and whose misdeeds are bound to be overlooked;”</span>
  46,17,"As for the one who said to his parents, “Fie on both of you! Are you promising me that I will be brought out when generations have passed away before me?” Meanwhile, they both cry for Allah’s help, “Woe to you, believe! The promise of Allah is true!” But he says, “These are nothing but legends of the ancients.”"
  46,18,"Those are the ones upon whom the sentence is justified, among the communities that have passed away before them of unseen beings<sup foot_note="365949">1</sup> and humans; they were indeed losers.",footnotes:346412:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.
  46,19,"And for all, there are degrees according to what they have done, and that He may <span class="h">render<sup foot_note="365950">1</sup></span> to them in full <small>(the reward)</small> for their deeds, and they will not be dealt with unjustly.",footnotes:346413:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Hisham, Asem and Ya’qub read it as: “…and that We may render…”</span>
  46,20,"And on the day when those who denied the truth are paraded before the Fire: “You<sup>pl</sup> have squandered your good things in your Earlier Life and you enjoyed them. So today you are being repaid with the punishment of shame on account of your unjustifiable arrogance on earth, and on account of how you used to defiantly disobey.”"
  46,21,"And recall the brother of Ād<sup foot_note="365951">1</sup> when he warned his people at the dunes—and warnings had passed away before him and after him: “Worship none but Allah; I fear for you<sup>pl</sup> the punishment of a great day.”",footnotes:346414:Prophet <i>Hûd</i> who was sent to the people of <i>Ād</i>.
  46,22,"They said, “Have you<sup>sg</sup> come to us to divert us from our gods? Then bring us what you promise us, if you are of the truthful.”"
  46,23,"He said, “Indeed, all knowledge is only with Allah, and I <span class="h">proclaim<sup foot_note="365952">1</sup></span> to you what I have been sent with, but I see you are an ignorant people.”",footnotes:346415:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “…and I compile and proclaim to you…”</span>
  46,24,"Then, when they saw it as a cloud approaching their valleys, they said, “This is a cloud that will bring us rain.” “Rather, it is what you<sup>pl</sup> sought to hasten: a wind in which is painful punishment,"
  46,25,"destroying everything by the command of its Lord." And when the morning came upon them, nothing could be <span class="h">seen<sup foot_note="365953">1</sup></span> except their residences. Thus We repay the criminal people.",footnotes:346416:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “… you<sup><small>sg</small></sup> could see nothing except…”</span>
  46,26,"And surely We had empowered them in the same way as We empowered you<sup>pl</sup> and We gave them hearing, and sight<small>(s)</small><sup foot_note="365954">1</sup>, and burning hearts. But neither their hearing, nor their sight<small>(s)</small>, nor their burning hearts availed them in any way. That is because they used to repudiate the signs<sup foot_note="365955">2</sup> of Allah, and so they became surrounded by what they used to ridicule.",footnotes:346417:Mentioned in plural form in Arabic, denoted by (s) in English for grammatical reasons.|346418:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  46,27,"And most surely We have annihilated many towns around you<sup>pl</sup> and diversified the signs, that they may return <small>(to the truth)</small>."
  46,28,"Why then did those whom they worshiped as means of nearness to Allah not support them? Rather, they abandoned<sup foot_note="365956">1</sup> them. It was their lie, a fabrication of their own making.",footnotes:346419:Literally “…they strayed from them.”
  46,29,"And recall when We dispatched towards you<sup>sg</sup> several unseen beings<sup foot_note="365957">1</sup> to listen to the Recital<sup foot_note="365958">2</sup> . When they came in its presence, they said, “Listen<sup>pl</sup> quietly!” Then, when it was concluded, they turned to their people, forewarning them.",footnotes:346420:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.|346421:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  46,30,"They said, “O our people, we have heard a Scripture, sent down after Moses, confirming what came before it. It guides to the truth and to a straight path."
  46,31,"O our people, respond to the caller to Allah and believe in Him, and He will forgive you your misdeeds and grant you protection from a painful punishment.”"
  46,32,"And he who does not respond to the caller to Allah cannot incapacitate <small>(God)</small> on earth and has no protectors apart from Him; those are in evident misguidance."
  46,33,"Have they not seen that Allah, Who created the heavens and the earth and was never tired by creating them, is <span class="h">capable<sup foot_note="365959">1</sup></span> of reviving the dead? Yes indeed; He is indeed powerful over all things.",footnotes:346422:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…by creating them, can revive the dead?”</span>
  46,34,"And on the day when those who denied are presented to the Fire: “Is this not real?” They said, “Yes, indeed, by our Lord.” He said, “Then taste the punishment on account of how you<sup>pl</sup> used to deny.”"
  46,35,"So be<sup>sg</sup> patient, as the messengers with resolve were patient, and do not be hasty regarding them. On the day when they witness what they are promised, it will seem as if they had lasted for only an hour of a day. A proclamation: will any be annihilated except the defiantly disobedient people?"
  47,1,"Those who denied and barred <small>(others)</small> from the way of Allah—He made their deeds go to waste."
  47,2,"And those who attained faith and did righteous deeds, and attained faith in what was sent down to Muhammad—and it is the truth from their Lord—He remitted their evil deeds and set aright their state of mind."
  47,3,"That is because those who denied followed falsehood, while those who attained faith followed the truth from their Lord. Allah thus sets forth for mankind their examples."
  47,4,"Thus, when you<sup>pl</sup> encounter those who have denied, strike at their necks. Then when you have subjugated them, bind them firmly<sup foot_note="365960">1</sup> . Then either release them by grace or by ransom until war lays down its burdens. Had Allah willed, He could have defeated them Himself, but He thus tests some of you by means of others. As for those who were <span class="h">killed<sup foot_note="365961">2</sup></span> in the way of Allah, He will not let their deeds go to waste.",footnotes:346423:<sup></sup>i.e. Take them as captives.i.e. Take them as captives.|346424:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Abu Amr, Hafs and Ya’qub read it as: “As for those who combated in the way of Allah,”</span>
  47,5,"He will guide them and set aright their state of mind"
  47,6,"and will enter them into the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small>—He has identified it for them."
  47,7,"O you who have attained faith, if you support Allah, He will support you and strengthen your foothold."
  47,8,"But as for those who denied, for them is perdition, and He made their deeds go to waste."
  47,9,"That is because they hated what Allah had sent down, so He nullified their deeds."
  47,10,"Have they not journeyed through the earth and looked at what the outcome was for those before them? Allah poured destruction upon them. For for the deniers there is something comparable."
  47,11,"That is because Allah is the Patron of those who have attained faith, while the deniers have no Patron."
  47,12,"Indeed, Allah enters those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds into Gardens beneath which rivers flow. And those who have denied enjoy themselves and eat as cattle eat, but the Fire is a dwelling for them."
  47,13,"And how many a town was more powerful than your town<sup foot_note="365962">1</sup> which evicted you<sup>sg</sup>? We annihilated them, and there was no helper for them.",footnotes:346425:Addressing Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) about the town which evicted him (Makkah).
  47,14,"Is someone who relies on evident proof from his Lord like someone the evil of whose work was adorned for him? And they<sup foot_note="365963">1</sup> followed their own whims.",footnotes:346426:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  47,15,"The likeness of the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> that the mindful<sup>pl</sup> <small>(of God) </small>have been promised: rivers of water, not <span class="h">staling<sup foot_note="365964">1</sup></span>; and rivers of milk whose taste has not changed; and rivers of wine, a delight for those who drink; and rivers of honey, clarified and pure. And they have therein of all products and forgiveness from their Lord. <small>(How can this be)</small> compared to the fate of those abiding in the Fire and were given, for drink, scalding water, so that it tore their bowels?",footnotes:346427:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: "…rivers of water, never staling;"</span>
  47,16,"And among them is one who listens to you<sup>sg</sup>, but when they<sup foot_note="365965">1</sup> depart from your presence, they say to those given knowledge, “What did he say just now?” Those are the ones whose hearts Allah has sealed, and they followed their own whims.",footnotes:346428:A grammatical shift from singular to plural. The difference between this shift and the one in sign number 14 should be pondered by the reader.
  47,17,"But as for those who wanted guidance, He has increased them in guidance and has brought them their mindfulness <small>(of God)</small>."
  47,18,"So are they but waiting until the Hour comes to them suddenly? In fact, its tokens have already come. But how will they be reminded when it has come to them?"
  47,19,"So know<sup>sg</sup> that there is no god but Allah, and ask forgiveness for your misdeed, and for believing men and believing women. For Allah knows your moving about and your dwelling."
  47,20,"And those who have attained faith say, “If only a Surah<sup foot_note="365966">1</sup> was sent down.” Yet when a decisive Surah is sent down and combat is mentioned in it, you<sup>sg</sup> see those in whose hearts is sickness looking at you with the look of someone fainting at death. Yet worthier of them would be",footnotes:346429:<sup></sup>Each portion of the Qur'an is called a ‘surah’, which is sometimes translated as ‘chapter’.Each portion of the Qur'an is called a ‘surah’, which is sometimes translated as ‘chapter’.
  47,21,"obedience and upright speech. Then, when the matter is settled, had they been true to Allah, it would have been better for them."
  47,22,"Would you<sup>pl</sup> then, in case you became in <span class="h">charge<sup foot_note="365967">1</sup></span>, spread corruption in the earth and <span class="h">sever<sup foot_note="365968">2</sup></span> your family ties<sup foot_note="365969">3</sup> ?",footnotes:346430:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Roways read it as: “…in case you were made in charge, spread corruption…”</span>|346431:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…and cut your family ties?</span>|346432:Literally “sever your wombs”.
  47,23,"Those are the ones whom Allah has cursed, so He made them deaf and blinded their sight<small>(s)</small><sup foot_note="365970">1</sup> .",footnotes:346433:<sup></sup>Mentioned in plural form in Arabic, denoted by (s) in English for grammatical reasons.Mentioned in plural form in Arabic, denoted by (s) in English for grammatical reasons.
  47,24,"Will they not ponder the Recital<sup foot_note="365971">1</sup>, or are there locks upon their hearts?",footnotes:346434:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means recital or recitation.
  47,25,"Indeed, those who turned on their heels after guidance became evident to them—Satan has enticed them and has <span class="h">filled<sup foot_note="365972">1</sup></span> them with false hopes.",footnotes:346435:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “Satan has enticed them. Thus they were filled with false hopes.” Ya’qub read it as: “Satan has enticed them. Thus I filled them with false hopes.”</span>
  47,26,"That is because they said to those who hated what Allah had bestowed from on high, “We will obey you in certain matters.” But Allah knows their secret <span class="h">exchanges<sup foot_note="365973">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346436:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…their secrets.”</span>
  47,27,"How will it be when the angels take them at death, beating their faces and their backs?"
  47,28,"That is because they followed what angered Allah, and they disliked His good pleasure, so He nullified their deeds."
  47,29,"Or did those in whose hearts is sickness think that Allah would not bring out <small>(to the open)</small> their malice?"
  47,30,"Had We willed, We could have shown them to you<sup>sg</sup>, and you would have recognized them by their marks. Yet you will recognize them by their tone of speech, and Allah knows all your<sup>pl</sup> deeds."
  47,31,"And <span class="h">We<sup foot_note="365974">1</sup></span> will certainly test you<sup>pl</sup> until We know those of you who strive and those who are steadfastly patient, and <small>(until We)</small> <span class="h">test<sup foot_note="365975">2</sup></span> your reactions.",footnotes:346437:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “And He will certainly test you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> until He knows those of you who strive and those who are steadfastly patient, and (until He) tests your reactions.”</span>|346438:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Roways read it as: “…those who are steadfastly patient. And We will test your reactions.”</span>
  47,32,"Indeed, those who denied and barred <small>(others)</small> from the way of Allah and opposed the Messenger after guidance had become clear to them—they will not harm Allah at all, but He will nullify their deeds."
  47,33,"O you who have attained faith, obey Allah and obey the Messenger, and do not let your deeds go to waste."
  47,34,"Indeed, those who denied and barred<small> (others)</small> from the way of Allah and then died as deniers—Allah will not forgive them."
  47,35,"So do not waver and call for peace while you<sup>pl</sup> have the upper hand; Allah is with you and He will not divest you of your deeds."
  47,36,"Indeed, the Earlier Life is nothing but a game and a distraction. But if you<sup>pl</sup> attain faith and are mindful <small>(of God)</small>, He will grant you your rewards, and He will not ask you for your possessions."
  47,37,"Were He to ask you<sup>pl</sup> for it and press you, you would become miserly, and He would bring out <small>(to the open)</small> your malice."
  47,38,"Here you<sup>pl</sup> are, being called to spend in the way of Allah. Among you are those who become miserly, but whoever becomes miserly, becomes miserly only against himself. And Allah is the Self-Sufficient, while you are the needy. And if you turn away <small>(from Him)</small>, He will replace you with another people, then they will not be like you."
  48,1,"Indeed, We have unlocked for you<sup>sg</sup> an evident conquest,"
  48,2,"that Allah may forgive you what has passed of your misdeeds and what is yet to come, and complete His blessing upon you and guide you to a straight path"
  48,3,"and support you with mighty support."
  48,4,"It is He who sent down tranquility into the hearts of the believers, to add faith to their faith, for to Allah belong the troops of the heavens and the earth, and Allah has always been All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  48,5,"So as to enter believing men and believing women into Gardens beneath which rivers flow, abiding therein, and to remit their evil deeds. And that, with Allah, has always been a great triumph."
  48,6,"And to punish hypocritical men and hypocritical women and idolatrous men and idolatrous women—those who harbor evil thoughts about Allah; they are encircled by evil, and Allah’s wrath is upon them and has cursed them and has prepared for them Hell, and what an evil destiny."
  48,7,"For to Allah belong the troops of the heavens and the earth, and Allah has always been Almighty, All-Wise."
  48,8,"Indeed, We have sent you<sup>sg</sup> as a witness and a bearer of glad tidings and a warner,"
  48,9,"that you<sup>pl</sup> may <span class="h">believe<sup foot_note="365976">1</sup></span> in Allah and His Messenger, and rally to Him and honor Him and highly exalt Him morning and evening.",footnotes:346439:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: "... that they may believe in Allah ..."</span>
  48,10,"Indeed, those who pledge allegiance to you<sup>sg</sup> are actually pledging allegiance to Allah: the hand of Allah is over their hands. So whoever reneges in fact reneges to his own detriment. And whoever fulfills what he has covenanted with Allah, then <span class="h">He<sup foot_note="365977">1</sup></span> will grant him a great reward.",footnotes:346440:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie', Ibn kathir, Abu Ja'far and Rouh read it as: "... then We will grant him a great reward."</span>
  48,11,"The nomadic Arabs who lagged behind will say to you<sup>sg</sup>, “Our belongings and our families have preoccupied us, so ask forgiveness for us.” They say with their tongues what is not in their hearts. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Who can avail you anything against Allah if He desires harm for you or desires benefit for you?” In fact, Allah has always been All-Aware of what you do."
  48,12,"But you<sup>pl</sup> thought that the Messenger and the believers would never return to their families, and that was adorned in your hearts. And you harbored evil thoughts, for you have always been a worthless people."
  48,13,"And whoever has not believed in Allah and His Messenger— We have prepared for the deniers a Blaze."
  48,14,"And to Allah belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth; He forgives whomever He wills, and He punishes whomever He wills, for Allah has always been Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  48,15,"Those who lagged behind will say when you<sup>pl</sup> depart to collect the gains<sup foot_note="365978">1</sup>, “Let us follow you.” They want to change the <span class="h">Speech<sup foot_note="365979">2</sup></span> of Allah. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “You will not follow us; Allah has said so before.” Then they will say, “Rather, you<sup>pl</sup> envy us.” In fact, they have not comprehended except a little.",footnotes:346441:The spoils of war.|346442:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…the Words of Allah.”</span>
  48,16,"Say<sup>sg</sup> to the nomadic Arabs who lagged behind, “You will be called against a people of intense force to combat them, unless they surrender. So if you obey, Allah will give you an excellent reward. But if you turn away as you turned away before, He will punish you with a painful punishment.”"
  48,17,"There is no blame on the blind, nor any blame on the lame, nor any blame on the sick. And whoever obeys Allah and His <span class="h">Messenger—He<sup foot_note="365980">1</sup></span> will enter him into Gardens beneath which rivers flow. But whoever turns away—He will punish him with a painful punishment.",footnotes:346443:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…We will enter him...We will punish him…”</span>
  48,18,"Surely, Allah was well pleased with the believers as they pledged allegiance to you<sup>sg</sup> under the tree, and He knew what was in their hearts, so He sent down tranquility upon them and rewarded them with an imminent conquest"
  48,19,"and a multitude of gains<sup foot_note="365981">1</sup> for them to capture. For Allah has always been Almighty, All-Wise.",footnotes:346444:The spoils of war.
  48,20,"Allah has promised you<sup>pl</sup> a multitude of gains<sup foot_note="365982">1</sup> to capture, so He has expedited this for you and has restrained people’s hands from you, that it may be a sign to the believers, and to guide you to a straight path.",footnotes:346445:The spoils of war.
  48,21,"And other <small>(war booty)</small> of which you<sup>pl</sup> were incapable <small>(of capturing)</small>, but Allah has encompassed it, and Allah has always been Powerful over everything."
  48,22,"And if those who have denied had combated you, they would have turned their backs, then they would find neither ally nor supporter."
  48,23,"Such has been Allah’s rule that has passed on before, for you<sup>sg</sup> will never find any change in Allah’s rule."
  48,24,"And it is He who withheld their hands from you<sup>pl</sup> and your hands from them in the valley of Makkah after giving you advantage over them, for Allah has always been All-Seeing of what <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="365983">1</sup></span> do.",footnotes:346446:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “…what they do.”</span>
  48,25,"It is they who have denied, and barred you<sup>pl</sup> from the Inviolable Mosque, and prevented the offering from reaching its destination. And were it not for <small>(the presence among them of)</small> some faithful men and some faithful women whom you did not know of and whom you would have hurt, thus incurring dishonor unknowingly on their account…<sup foot_note="365984">1</sup> —that Allah may enter into His mercy whomever He wills. If they had been apart, We would have punished those of them who denied with a painful punishment.",footnotes:346447:This sentence is left open-ended; according to Al-Qurtubi and other exegetes the predicate is elided but can be understood as: “I would not have prevented you from retaliating.”
  48,26,"Those who denied filled their hearts with chauvinism—the chauvinism of pagan<small> </small>ignorance<sup foot_note="365985">1</sup> . But Allah sent His tranquility down upon His Messenger and upon the believers and imposed on them the word of mindfulness <small>(of God)</small> of which they were most worthy and deserving, for Allah has always been All-Knowing of everything.",footnotes:346448:The Arabic word used is <i>jahiliyah</i> which is derived from <i>jahl</i> or ‘ignorance’ and refers to the pre-Islamic phase of paganism.
  48,27,"Surely, Allah has fulfilled His Messenger’s vision in truth: “You<sup>pl</sup> will surely enter the Inviolable Mosque by the will of Allah in security, heads shaven or hair cut short, not fearing anything. Yet He knew what you did not know and so set up for you, apart from that, a near conquest.”"
  48,28,"It is He who sent His Messenger with the guidance and the religion of truth to make it prevail over all religions, for Allah suffices as Witness."
  48,29,"Muhammad is the Messenger of Allah, and those with him are stern against the deniers, merciful to one another; you<sup>sg</sup> see them kneeling, prostrating, seeking grace from Allah and <small>(His)</small> good pleasure; their marks are on their faces from the effect of prostration. Such is their description in the Torah and their description in the Gospel: like vegetation that sprouted, then became strong, then grew thick, then rested on its stem, impressing the farmers. Through them He enrages the deniers. Allah has promised those of them who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds forgiveness and a great reward."
  49,1,"O you who have attained faith, do not proceed ahead of Allah and His Messenger, and be mindful of Allah; indeed, Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing."
  49,2,"O you who have attained faith, do not raise your voices above the voice of the Prophet, and do not speak loudly to him as you speak loudly to one another, lest your deeds be nullified while you are unaware."
  49,3,"Indeed, those who lower their voices before Allah’s Messenger—those are the ones whose hearts Allah has tested for mindfulness <small>(of Him)</small>; for them is forgiveness and a great reward."
  49,4,"Indeed, those who call you<sup>sg</sup> from behind the chambers—most of them do not reason."
  49,5,"Had they remained patient until you<sup>sg</sup> came out to them, it would have been better for them. But Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  49,6,"O you who have attained faith, if an ungodly person brings you any news, <span class="h">ascertain<sup foot_note="365986">1</sup></span><small>(the truth)</small>, lest you harm a people out of ignorance and thus become regretful for what you have done.",footnotes:346449:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “… brings you any news, investigate (the matter),”</span>
  49,7,"And know that among you is the Messenger of Allah; if he were to obey you in many matters, you would suffer hardship. But Allah has endeared faith to you and adorned it in your hearts and made denial and ungodliness and rebellion hateful to you; those are the prudent ones."
  49,8,"A grace from Allah and a blessing, and Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise."
  49,9,"And if two factions of believers fall to fighting each other, reconcile<sup>pl</sup> between them. But if one group oppresses the other, then combat the one which oppresses until it complies with the command of Allah. But once it has complied, reconcile between them with justice and be equitable; indeed, Allah loves the equitable."
  49,10,"Indeed, all the believers are but brothers, so reconcile between your<sup>pl</sup> two <span class="h">brothers<sup foot_note="365987">1</sup></span> and be mindful of Allah, that you may receive mercy.",footnotes:346450:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…so reconcile between your<sup><small>pl</small></sup> brothers…”</span>
  49,11,"O you who have attained faith, no people shall ridicule other people, for they may be better than them. Nor shall any women ridicule other women, for they may be better than them. Nor shall you defame yourselves<sup foot_note="365988">1</sup>, nor shall you insult one another by nicknames. What a miserable label ungodliness is after attaining faith! And whoever has not repented—then those<sup foot_note="365989">2</sup> are the unjust.",footnotes:346451:The Qur’an used the term “yourselves" rather than “each other” to make the believers sympathize with one another by regarding any defamation to one as defamation to all.|346452:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  49,12,"O you who have attained faith, avoid making too many assumptions—indeed, some assumptions are sinful. And do not spy on one another nor backbite one another. Would any of you like to eat the flesh of his dead brother? You would detest it. So be mindful of Allah; indeed, Allah is Granting and Accepting of repentance, Bestowing of mercy."
  49,13,"O mankind, We have created you from a male and a female and made you into races and tribes, that you may know one another; indeed, the most noble of you in the sight of Allah are the most mindful <small>(of Him)</small> among you; indeed, Allah is All-Knowing, All-Aware."
  49,14,"The nomadic Arabs said, “We have attained faith.” Say<sup>sg</sup>, “You have not attained faith; rather say, ‘We have become Muslims,’ for faith has not yet entered into your hearts. But if you obey Allah and His Messenger, He will not diminish any of your deeds; indeed, Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy.”"
  49,15,"The believers are those who have attained faith in Allah and His Messenger, and then have not doubted and have striven with their wealth and their lives in the way of Allah; those are the truthful."
  49,16,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Are you<sup>pl</sup> going to teach Allah about your religion, when Allah knows whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth, for Allah is All-Knowing of everything?”"
  49,17,"They keep reminding you<sup>sg</sup> of the favor they did you by becoming Muslims. Say, “Do not consider your submission (to Allah) a favor to me; it is Allah who does you a favor by guiding you to the faith, if you are truthful.”"
  49,18,"Allah knows the hidden realm of the heavens and the earth, for Allah is All-Seeing of what <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="365990">1</sup></span> do.",footnotes:346453:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “…what they do.”</span>
  50,1,"Qāf. By the Glorious Recital<sup foot_note="365991">1</sup> …<sup foot_note="365992">2</sup>",footnotes:346454:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.|346455:That which is sworn is omitted so that the reader may ponder.
  50,2,"But they marveled that a forewarner had come to them from among them, so the deniers said, “How strange!"
  50,3,"Can it be that when we have died and become dust…?<sup foot_note="365993">1</sup> This is a far-fetched return.”",footnotes:346456:This sentence is left open-ended; according to Al-Alousi and other exegetes the predicate is elided but can be understood as: “…that we shall be brought back again?”
  50,4,"We have already known what the earth consumes of them, and with Us is a constantly preserving record<sup foot_note="365994">1</sup> .",footnotes:346457:Literally ‘scripture’.
  50,5,"But they rejected the truth when it came to them, so they are in a state of confusion."
  50,6,"Have they not looked at the sky above them—how We constructed it and decorated it and how it has no fractures?"
  50,7,"And the earth—how We spread it out and set on it firm mountains and germinated therein all kinds of lovely plants,"
  50,8,"an eye opener and a reminder for every penitent servant?"
  50,9,"And We brought down from the sky blessed water and germinated with it gardens and grain to harvest,"
  50,10,"and the soaring palm trees with clustered dates—"
  50,11,"provision for the servants. And We revived thereby a lifeless land; likewise is the emergence."
  50,12,"Before them the people of Noah disbelieved, and <small>(so did)</small> the fellows of Al-Russ and Thamûd"
  50,13,"and Ād and Pharaoh and the brethren of Lot"
  50,14,"and the fellows of the Thicket and the people of Tubba’; they all disbelieved the messengers, so My threat came true."
  50,15,"Were We fatigued by the first creation? Rather, they are in doubt of a new creation."
  50,16,"And surely We created man and know what his <small>(inner)</small> self whispers to him, for We are nearer to him than his jugular vein."
  50,17,"As the two receptors<sup foot_note="365995">1</sup> receive <small>(him)</small>, one on the right and one on the left, constantly seated.",footnotes:346458:Two angels who receive everyone’s words and deeds during his/her life and record them.
  50,18,"Not a word does he utter, but close to him is a watcher, constantly ready."
  50,19,"Then came the daze of death with the truth: “That is what you<sup>sg</sup> were trying to avoid.”"
  50,20,"And the Trumpet was blown<sup foot_note="365996">1</sup> : “That is the Day of the Threat.”",footnotes:346459:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense, this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  50,21,"And every soul came forward, accompanied by a driver and a witness<sup foot_note="365997">1</sup> .",footnotes:346460:Two angels: one drives the person to the place of assembly and the other is a witness to all his/her deeds.
  50,22,"“Indeed, you<sup>sg</sup> were oblivious to this, so We removed your veil and your sight today is <small>(as sharp as)</small> iron.”"
  50,23,"And His comrade<sup foot_note="365998">1</sup> said, “This is what I have ready with me.”",footnotes:346461:According to Ibn Ashour, some exegetes said that this comrade is an angel, and others said it is his intimate friend in life, while others said it is his devil which used to whisper to him.
  50,24,"“Cast<sup>dl</sup> into Hell, every stubborn relentless denier,"
  50,25,"preventer of good, transgressor, doubter,"
  50,26,"who has set up another deity with Allah. So cast<sup>dl</sup> him into the severe punishment.”"
  50,27,"His comrade said, “Our Lord, I did not make him exceed all limits, but he was in extreme misguidance.”"
  50,28,"He said, “Do not dispute in My presence, for I have warned you<sup>pl</sup> in advance."
  50,29,"The decree from Me cannot be changed, and I am not a tyrant unto the servants.”"
  50,30,"On the day when We <span class="h">say<sup foot_note="365999">1</sup></span> to Hell, “Are you full?” And it says, “Are there any more?”",footnotes:346462:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Shu’ba read it as: “…when He says to Hell…”</span>
  50,31,"And the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> was brought closer to those mindful <small>(of God)</small>, not far away."
  50,32,"This is what you<sup>pl</sup> are <span class="h">promised<sup foot_note="366000">1</sup></span>—for every constant preserver who often turns to God,",footnotes:346463:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “This is what they are promised…”</span>
  50,33,"the one who inwardly feared the All-Merciful and came with a penitent heart."
  50,34,"“Enter<sup>pl</sup> it in peace; that is the Day of Eternity.”"
  50,35,"Therein they have whatever they desire, and We have even more."
  50,36,"And how many generations before them who were more powerful than they did We destroy! And they explored the lands—was there any escape?"
  50,37,"Indeed, in that is a reminder for whoever possesses a heart or cares to listen and witness."
  50,38,"And surely We created the heavens and the earth and what is between them in six days<sup foot_note="366001">1</sup>, and never were We touched by any fatigue.",footnotes:346464:Six equal intervals of time, which may be six heavenly days, each of them being 1000 earthly years long (see 22: 47).
  50,39,"So endure<sup>sg</sup> what they say, and highly exalt your Lord with praise before the rising of the sun and before sunset."
  50,40,"And highly exalt<sup>sg</sup> Him with praise in the night and <span class="h">after<sup foot_note="366002">1</sup></span> prostrations.",footnotes:346465:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Hamza, Abu Ja’far and Khalaf read it as: “…and at the ends of prostrations.”</span>
  50,41,"And listen<sup>sg</sup> on the day when the caller calls from a nearby place."
  50,42,"The day when they hear the Shout in all truth; that is the Day of Emergence."
  50,43,"Indeed, We—We alone—give life and cause death, and to Us is the destiny."
  50,44,"The day the earth <span class="h">ruptures<sup foot_note="366003">1</sup></span> open from above them, letting them rush out; that is an easy exodus for Us.",footnotes:346466:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…the earth vigorously ruptures open…”</span>
  50,45,"We know better what they say, and you<sup>sg</sup> are not a compeller over them, so remind by the Recital<sup foot_note="366004">1</sup> whoever fears My warning.",footnotes:346467:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  51,1,"By the spreaders spreading<sup foot_note="366005">1</sup>,",footnotes:346468:The first four signs are interpreted as the winds spreading the clouds, carrying them, moving them and distributing them.
  51,2,"and by those bearers of loads,"
  51,3,"and by those moving gently,"
  51,4,"and by those distributing as commanded—"
  51,5,"what you<sup>pl</sup> are promised is true."
  51,6,"And, indeed, the Recompense is sure to come."
  51,7,"By the heaven comprising interwoven tracks,"
  51,8,"indeed, you<sup>pl</sup> are of different opinions<sup foot_note="366006">1</sup> .",footnotes:346469:Different opinions about the judgment.
  51,9,"Averted from it is he who is averted."
  51,10,"May the conjecturers perish!<sup foot_note="366007">1</sup>",footnotes:346470:Literally ‘May the conjecturers be killed’.
  51,11,"Those who are unmindful and in perplexity,"
  51,12,"asking, “When is the Day of Recompense?”"
  51,13,"The day they are heated on the Fire:"
  51,14,"“Taste your trial; this is what you<sup>pl</sup>, <small>(challengingly)</small> have been asking to be hastened.”"
  51,15,"Indeed, the mindful <small>(of God)</small> are amidst Gardens <small>(of Paradise) </small>and springs,"
  51,16,"taking what their Lord has given them. Indeed, before that, they used to excel in doing good:"
  51,17,"they used to lie down but little of the night,"
  51,18,"and at dawn they would seek forgiveness,"
  51,19,"and in their wealth was a share for the asker and the deprived."
  51,20,"And on earth are signs for those who believe with certitude,"
  51,21,"and within yourselves; do you not see?"
  51,22,"And in the heaven is your provision and what you are promised."
  51,23,"So by the Lord of the heaven and the earth, indeed, it is as true as the fact that you<sup>pl</sup> <small>(can)</small> pronounce."
  51,24,"Has the story of <span class="h">Abraham’s<sup foot_note="366008">1</sup></span> honorable guests reached you<sup>sg</sup>?",footnotes:346471:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as Ibrahim, Hisham in one of his narrations read it as: “Abraham”.</span>
  51,25,"When they entered upon him they said, “Peace.” He said, “Peace, strangers.”"
  51,26,"And he slipped away to his family and brought a fatted calf"
  51,27,"and set it before them. He said, “Will you not eat?”"
  51,28,"And he was filled with apprehension towards them. They said, “Do not be afraid,” and they announced to him the glad tidings of a knowledgeable boy."
  51,29,"So his wife came forward with a shriek, then clasped her face and said, “A barren old woman!”"
  51,30,"They said, “Thus your Lord has said; He is the All-Wise, the All- Knowing.”"
  51,31,"He said, “So what is your business, O emissaries?”"
  51,32,"They said, “We have been sent to a criminal people,"
  51,33,"to unleash upon them rocks of clay,"
  51,34,"marked by your<sup>sg</sup> Lord for the extremists.”"
  51,35,"Then We brought out all the believers who were in it."
  51,36,"Yet We found in it only one household of Muslims,"
  51,37,"and We left in it a sign for those who fear the painful punishment."
  51,38,"And in Moses <small>(there is also a sign)</small> —when We sent him to Pharaoh with an evident manifestation."
  51,39,"But he turned away with his warlords and said, “A sorcerer or a madman.”"
  51,40,"So We seized him and his troops and flung them into the waters, and he was to blame."
  51,41,"And <small>(likewise)</small> in <small>(the people of) </small>Ād<sup foot_note="366009">1</sup> —We sent against them the Barren Wind,",footnotes:346472:The pagan tribe of Prophet Hûd.
  51,42,"sparing nothing it came upon without rendering it like decayed ruins."
  51,43,"And <small>(likewise)</small> in <small>(the people of)</small> Thamûd<sup foot_note="366010">1</sup> —they were told, “Enjoy yourselves for a while.”",footnotes:346473:The pagan tribe of Prophet Salih.
  51,44,"But they defied the command of their Lord, so the Lightning <span class="h">struck<sup foot_note="366011">1</sup></span> them as they looked on,",footnotes:346474:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…so the strike of lightning struck them as they…”</span>
  51,45,"and they could not rise up, nor could they help themselves."
  51,46,"And <small>(recall)</small> before that, the <span class="h">people<sup foot_note="366012">1</sup></span> of Noah—indeed, they were a defiantly disobedient people.",footnotes:346475:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “And (likewise) before that, (in) the people of Noah…”</span>
  51,47,"And the universe—We constructed it with power, and We are surely expanding it."
  51,48,"And the earth—We spread it out. So how excellent are We who prepared it!"
  51,49,"And We created all things in pairs, that you may <span class="h">remind<sup foot_note="366013">1</sup></span> yourselves.",footnotes:346476:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…that you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> may constantly remember.”</span>
  51,50,"“So flee to Allah; I am to you<sup>pl</sup> from Him an evident warner."
  51,51,"And do not set up any other god with Allah; I am to you from Him an evident warner.”"
  51,52,"Likewise, no messenger came to those before them but they said, “A sorcerer or a madman.”"
  51,53,"Did they recommend it to one another? In fact, they are a people who exceed all limits."
  51,54,"So turn away from them, for you<sup>sg</sup> are not to blame."
  51,55,"And remind, for the reminder benefits the believers."
  51,56,"And I did not create the unseen beings<sup foot_note="366014">1</sup> and humans but to worship Me.",footnotes:346477:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.
  51,57,"I need no provision from them, nor do I need them to feed Me."
  51,58,"Allah is the All-Providing, the Possessor of power, the All-Firm."
  51,59,"So, indeed, those who do injustice will have their lot like the lot of their fellows, so let them not hasten Me."
  51,60,"So woe to those who have denied from that day of theirs which they are promised."
  52,1,"By Mount Tûr."
  52,2,"By a scripture inscribed"
  52,3,"in an unrolled parchment."
  52,4,"By the frequented House <small>(of God)</small>."
  52,5,"By the raised canopy."
  52,6,"By the sea flared up with fire—"
  52,7,"the punishment of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is sure to come;"
  52,8,"there is nothing to avert it"
  52,9,"on the day when the sky sways in agitation"
  52,10,"and the mountains go into motion."
  52,11,"So woe on that day to the disbelievers"
  52,12,"who are indulged in vain talk, playing."
  52,13,"The day when they are shoved into the Fire of Hell forcefully."
  52,14,"“This is the Fire in which you<sup>pl</sup> used to disbelieve."
  52,15,"Is this magic, or do you<sup>pl</sup> not see?"
  52,16,"Roast in it, and be patient or be impatient—it is the same for you<sup>pl</sup>; indeed, you are only being repaid for what you used to do.”"
  52,17,"Indeed, the mindful <small>(of God)</small> are in Gardens and bliss,"
  52,18,"enjoying what their Lord has brought them, and their Lord has shielded them from the punishment of purgatory."
  52,19,""Eat and drink pleasantly on account of what you<sup>pl</sup> used to do.""
  52,20,"Relaxing on luxurious furnishings, and We coupled them with spouses with lovely wide eyes."
  52,21,"And those who attained faith and whose <span class="h">offspring<sup foot_note="366015">1</sup></span> followed them in faith—We have united<sup foot_note="366016">2</sup> them with their <span class="h">offspring<sup foot_note="366017">3</sup></span>, and We have not deprived them of anything of their work; every person is in pledge for what <small>(deeds)</small> he has earned.",footnotes:346478:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “…and whose offspring(s) followed them…” Abu Amr read it as: “And those who attained faith and whom We followed (with) their offspring(s) in faith…”</span>|346479:Frequently, the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.|346480:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…their offspring(s)…”</span>
  52,22,"And We have supplied them with fruit and meat such as they desire."
  52,23,"They exchange therein a cup which does not lead to any idle talk or recrimination."
  52,24,"And serving them are youths like nestled pearls."
  52,25,"And they approached one another, inquiring."
  52,26,"They said, “When we were still with our families<sup foot_note="366018">1</sup> we used to live in fear<sup foot_note="366019">2</sup>,",footnotes:346481:During their life on earth.|346482:Fear of falling into sin.
  52,27,"so Allah has conferred favor upon us and has shielded us from the punishment of the Scorching Fire."
  52,28,"Indeed, before this we used to pray to Him; <span class="h">indeed<sup foot_note="366020">1</sup></span>, He is the Fulfiller of promises, the Bestower of mercy.”",footnotes:346483:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Al-Kesa’i and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…to Him, for He is…”</span>
  52,29,"So remind, for you<sup>sg</sup> are neither a soothsayer nor a madman."
  52,30,"Or do they say, “A poet<sup foot_note="366021">1</sup> for whom we await a calamity of time”?",footnotes:346484:Some pagans claimed that Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) was a poet who authored the Qur’an.
  52,31,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Go on awaiting, for I am with you<sup>pl</sup> among those awaiting.”"
  52,32,"Or is it that their discerning minds command them to this? Or are they a people who exceed all limits?"
  52,33,"Or do they say, “He made it up”? In fact, they do not believe."
  52,34,"So let them produce a discourse like it if they are truthful."
  52,35,"Or were they created out of nothing? Or are they the creators?"
  52,36,"Or did they create the heavens and the earth? In fact, they are not certain."
  52,37,"Or do they possess the treasuries of your Lord? Or are they the controllers?"
  52,38,"Or do they have a stairway <small>(to heaven)</small> by means of which they listen? Then let their listener bring an evident manifestation."
  52,39,"Or is He to have the daughters and you<sup>pl</sup> the sons?"
  52,40,"Or do you<sup>sg</sup> ask them for a reward so that they are weighed down by debt?"
  52,41,"Or do they have <small>(knowledge of)</small> the hidden realm and they are writing it down?"
  52,42,"Or do they want a plot? Rather, the plot will only befall the deniers."
  52,43,"Or do they have a god other than Allah? Highly Exalted is Allah above what they associate."
  52,44,"And if they were to see lumps of sky falling, they would say, “A mass of clouds.”"
  52,45,"So leave<sup>sg</sup> them until they <span class="h">meet<sup foot_note="366022">1</sup></span> their day in which they are stunned—",footnotes:346485:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…until they encounter their…”</span>
  52,46,"the day when their plots avail them nothing, nor are they supported."
  52,47,"And indeed, for those who did injustice there is a punishment apart from that, but most of them do not know."
  52,48,"So wait patiently for the decree of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, for you are before Our Eyes. And highly exalt your Lord with praise when you arise,"
  52,49,"and highly exalt Him during the night and at the receding of the stars."
  53,1,"By the star as it goes down,"
  53,2,"your<sup>pl</sup> fellow has not gone astray, nor has he been deluded,"
  53,3,"nor does he speak out of whim."
  53,4,"It is but a revelation being revealed,"
  53,5,"taught to him by the extremely powerful,<sup foot_note="366023">1</sup>",footnotes:346486:Referring to Angel Gabriel.
  53,6,"the one of vigor. He settled"
  53,7,"while he was at the highest horizon,"
  53,8,"then he came near and descended"
  53,9,"so that he was within two bows’ length or closer."
  53,10,"Then He revealed to His servant that which He revealed."
  53,11,"The burning heart did not <span class="h">lie<sup foot_note="366024">1</sup></span> about what it saw.",footnotes:346487:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hisham and Abu Ja’far read it as: “The burning heart did not disbelieve what it saw.”</span>
  53,12,"Will you<sup>pl</sup> enter into <span class="h">controversies<sup foot_note="366025">1</sup></span> with him despite what he sees?",footnotes:346488:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Khalaf and Ya’qub read it as: “Will you<sup lang="en-US"><small>pl</small></sup> discredit him despite what he sees?”</span>
  53,13,"And he saw him on another descent,"
  53,14,"at the Lote-tree of the Extremity<sup foot_note="366026">1</sup>,",footnotes:346489:The Lote-tree of the Extremity is a spot above the seven firmaments; none has ever crossed it, and it is where Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) saw Angel Gabriel in the heavens at the night of his ascendance (<i>Mi’raj)</i>.
  53,15,"near which is the Garden of Shelter,"
  53,16,"when there covered the Lote-tree what covered it."
  53,17,"The sight <small>(of the Prophet)</small> did not swerve, nor did it exceed."
  53,18,"He certainly saw some of the great signs of his Lord."
  53,19,"Have you<sup>pl</sup> seen Al-Lāt and Al-Uzza?"
  53,20,"And Manāt<sup foot_note="366027">1</sup>, the third one, the other?",footnotes:346490:<i>Al-lāt</i>, <i>Al-Uzza</i> and <i>Manāt</i> were names of three goddesses in Arabia.
  53,21,"Are you<sup>pl</sup> to have the males and He the females<sup foot_note="366028">1</sup> ?",footnotes:346491:Though pagan Arabs considered having daughters to be shameful, they attributed it to God, so the Qur’an is debating them according to their own logic.
  53,22,"What a bizarre distribution!"
  53,23,"These are nothing but names which you<sup>pl</sup> have named, you and your forefathers, for which Allah sent down no manifestation. They follow nothing but assumptions and what the <small>(inner)</small> selves desire, even though guidance has come to them from their Lord."
  53,24,"Or is there for man whatever he wishes?"
  53,25,"To Allah belong the Hereafter and the first (life)."
  53,26,"And how many an angel is there in the heavens whose intercession avails nothing except after Allah gives permission to whomever He wills and is well pleased with."
  53,27,"Indeed, those who do not believe in the Hereafter name the angels with female names,"
  53,28,"though they have no knowledge of that. They only follow assumptions, yet surely assumptions do not substitute for the truth."
  53,29,"So disregard<sup>sg</sup> the one who has turned away from Our Reminder and has wanted nothing but the Earlier Life."
  53,30,"That is the extent of their knowledge. Indeed, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is the One who knows better who has strayed from His way and He is the One who knows better who has accepted guidance."
  53,31,"And to Allah belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth, that He may repay those who have done evil according to what they have done and repay those who have excelled in doing good with the best."
  53,32,"Those who avoid the <span class="h">gravest<sup foot_note="366029">1</sup></span> of sins and obscenities—except for minor lapses—your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is of vast forgiveness. He knows better about you<sup>pl</sup>, ever since He initiated you from the earth, and ever since you were fetuses in your mothers’ bellies. So do not acclaim your own purity—He knows better who is mindful <small>(of Him)</small>.",footnotes:346492:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Those who avoid the grave kind of sin and…”</span>
  53,33,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> seen the one who turned away"
  53,34,"and gave a little, then held back?"
  53,35,"Does he possess knowledge of the hidden realm and can therefore foresee?"
  53,36,"Or was he not informed of what is in the Scrolls of Moses,"
  53,37,"and of <span class="h">Abraham<sup foot_note="366030">1</sup></span> who fulfilled <small>(conveying the commandments)</small>:",footnotes:346493:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as <i>Ibrahim</i>, Hisham read it as: “Abraham”.</span>
  53,38,"that no bearer of burden bears the burden of another;"
  53,39,"and that man attains only what he has striven for;"
  53,40,"and that surely his pursuit will eventually be seen,"
  53,41,"then he is repaid for it with the fullest repayment;"
  53,42,"and that to your<sup>pl</sup> Lord is the finality;"
  53,43,"and that it is He Who caused laughter and weeping;"
  53,44,"and that it is He Who caused death and gave life;"
  53,45,"and that He created the two spouses<sup foot_note="366031">1</sup> —the male and the female,",footnotes:346494:The Arabic word, <i>zawjayn,</i> can also mean ‘two kinds’ or ‘two types’.
  53,46,"from a sperm drop when emitted;"
  53,47,"and that upon Him is the next creation;"
  53,48,"and that it is He Who enriched and impoverished;"
  53,49,"and that it is He Who is the Lord of Sirius<sup foot_note="366032">1</sup> ;",footnotes:346495:<i>Sirius</i> was a star worshiped by pagan Arabs.
  53,50,"and that He annihilated ancient Ād<sup foot_note="366033">1</sup>",footnotes:346496:The pagan tribe of Prophet Hûd.
  53,51,"and Thamûd<sup foot_note="366034">1</sup>, sparing no one;",footnotes:346497:The pagan tribe of Prophet Salih.
  53,52,"and the people of Noah before that; indeed, they were more unjust and more exceeding of all limits<sup foot_note="366035">1</sup> .",footnotes:346498:Comparing their injustices and atrocities to those of the people of Quraysh, the tribe of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him).
  53,53,"And He brought down the Ruined Cities<sup foot_note="366036">1</sup>",footnotes:346499:Where the people of Prophet Lot lived.
  53,54,"and covered them by that which He covered."
  53,55,"So which of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord's marvels do you enter into controversies about?"
  53,56,"This is a warning just like the first warnings."
  53,57,"The inevitable is imminent;"
  53,58,"none apart from Allah can unveil it."
  53,59,"Do you<sup>pl</sup> marvel at this discourse,"
  53,60,"and laugh and do not weep,"
  53,61,"lost in your frivolity?"
  53,62,"So prostrate yourselves to Allah and worship!"
  54,1,"The Hour has drawn near and the moon has ruptured."
  54,2,"Yet whenever they see a miracle, they disregard <small>(it)</small> and say, “Continuous magic!”"
  54,3,"And they disbelieved and followed their whims. And every matter is bound to <span class="h">settle<sup foot_note="366037">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346500:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “And every settled matter (has drawn near).”</span>
  54,4,"And most surely there have come to them tidings containing a deterrent—"
  54,5,"profound wisdom, but warnings are of no avail."
  54,6,"So turn away<sup>sg</sup> from them. On the day when the Summoner summons to something terrible,"
  54,7,"with their sight<small>(s)</small> <small>(subdued)</small> in reverence they come out of the tombs like swarming locusts,"
  54,8,"scrambling towards the Summoner; the deniers say, “This is a hard day.”"
  54,9,"The people of Noah disbelieved before them, so they disbelieved Our servant and said, “A madman!”, and he was rebuked."
  54,10,"So he called upon his Lord, “I am overcome, so bestow help!”"
  54,11,"So We <span class="h">opened<sup foot_note="366038">1</sup></span> the gates of the sky with water pouring down,",footnotes:346501:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “So We widely opened the…”</span>
  54,12,"and We made the earth burst with springs, so the waters met for a matter already determined."
  54,13,"And We carried him on a craft of planks and nails,"
  54,14,"sailing before Our eyes—a repayment for the one who had been denied."
  54,15,"And most surely We have left it as a sign, so is there anyone to remind himself?"
  54,16,"So how were My punishment and My warnings!"
  54,17,"And most surely We have made the Recital<sup foot_note="366039">1</sup> easy for remembrance, so is there anyone to remind himself?",footnotes:346502:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  54,18,"Ād<sup foot_note="366040">1</sup> disbelieved, so how were My punishment and My warnings!",footnotes:346503:The pagan tribe of Prophet Hûd.
  54,19,"Indeed, We sent against them a screaming wind on a day of unrelenting misfortune,"
  54,20,"plucking people away as though they were trunks of uprooted palm trees."
  54,21,"So how were My punishment and My warnings!"
  54,22,"And most surely We made the Recital<sup foot_note="366041">1</sup> easy for remembrance, so is there anyone to remind himself?",footnotes:346504:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  54,23,"Thamûd<sup foot_note="366042">1</sup> disbelieved in the warnings",footnotes:346505:The pagan tribe of Prophet Salih.
  54,24,"and said, “Are we to follow a human being from among us? Indeed, we would then be astray and insane!"
  54,25,"Has the Reminder been cast to him out of all of us? Rather, he is a wicked sheer liar.”"
  54,26,"<span class="h">They<sup foot_note="366043">1</sup></span> will know tomorrow who the wicked sheer liar is.",footnotes:346506:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Hamza read it as: “You<sup><small>pl</small></sup> will know tomorrow…”</span>
  54,27,"We are sending the she-camel as a means of trial for them, so watch<sup>sg</sup> them and be patient."
  54,28,"And inform<sup>sg</sup> them that the water is to be shared between them<sup foot_note="366044">1</sup> ; each one should drink in turn.",footnotes:346507:The water is to be shared between them and the she-camel.
  54,29,"But they called their fellow, and he dared and hamstrung <small>(it)</small>."
  54,30,"So how were My punishment and My warnings!"
  54,31,"Indeed, We sent against them a single Shout, and they ended up like a fence-maker’s dry sticks."
  54,32,"And most surely We made the Recital<sup foot_note="366045">1</sup> easy for remembrance, so is there anyone to remind himself?",footnotes:346508:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  54,33,"The people of Lot disbelieved in the warnings."
  54,34,"Indeed, We sent against them a shower of stones, except for Lot's folk–We delivered them at dawn—"
  54,35,"a blessing from Us; thus We repay whoever gives thanks."
  54,36,"And most surely he<sup foot_note="366046">1</sup> had warned them of Our onslaught, but they entered into controversies about the warnings.",footnotes:346509:Prophet Lot.
  54,37,"And most surely they solicited of him his guests, so We obliterated their eyes— “So taste My punishment and My warnings.”"
  54,38,"And most surely an abiding punishment came upon them in the morning—"
  54,39,"“So taste<sup>pl</sup> My punishment and My warnings.”"
  54,40,"And most surely We made the Recital<sup foot_note="366047">1</sup> easy for remembrance, so is there anyone to remind himself?",footnotes:346510:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  54,41,"And most surely the warnings came to Pharaoh's folk—"
  54,42,"they disbelieved all Our signs. So We seized them <small>(with)</small> the seizure of an Almighty, Invincible One."
  54,43,""Are your<sup>pl</sup> deniers better than all those? Or do you have immunity in the Books?""
  54,44,"Or do they say, “We, all together, will be victorious”?"
  54,45,"The multitude will be defeated, and they will turn their backs."
  54,46,"Nay, the Hour is their appointed time, and the Hour is more disastrous and more bitter."
  54,47,"Indeed, the criminals are in confusion and insanity."
  54,48,"The day when they are dragged upon their faces into the Fire: “Taste the touch of Saqar<sup foot_note="366048">1</sup> .”",footnotes:346511:<i>Saqar</i> is one of the names which the Qur’an gave to the fire of Hell.
  54,49,"Indeed, We have created everything in due measure."
  54,50,"And Our command is but once, like the twinkling of an eye."
  54,51,"And most surely We have annihilated your<sup>pl</sup> likes, so is there anyone to remind himself?"
  54,52,"And everything they have done is in the Books—"
  54,53,"for everything, small or large, is written down."
  54,54,"Indeed, the mindful <small>(of God)</small> are amidst Gardens and rivers,"
  54,55,"in a seat of truth, in the presence of an Invincible King."
  55,1,"The All-Merciful"
  55,2,"taught the Recital<sup foot_note="366049">1</sup>,",footnotes:346512:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  55,3,"created man,"
  55,4,"and taught him clear expression."
  55,5,"The sun and the moon move according to plan,"
  55,6,"and the plants<sup foot_note="366050">1</sup> and the trees prostrate themselves.",footnotes:346513:The Arabic word used is <i>najm</i> which also means ‘star’; notice the suitability of the term which connects what is before it with what is after it.
  55,7,"And the sky—He raised it and set up the balance,"
  55,8,"so do<sup>pl</sup> not exceed in the balance,"
  55,9,"but maintain the weights justly and do not fall short in the balance."
  55,10,"And the earth—He set it up for living creatures;"
  55,11,"in it are fruits and sheathed palm trees,"
  55,12,"and <span class="h">grains<sup foot_note="366051">1</sup></span> in the blades, and fragrant plants.",footnotes:346514:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “…palm trees. <sub><small>12 </small></sub>12 And (He created) grains in the blades, and (he created) fragrant plants.” Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…and (grains of) fragrant plants.”</span>
  55,13,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in<sup foot_note="366052">1</sup> ?",footnotes:346515:The Qur’an is addressing the two types of responsible creatures: humans and <i>jinn</i>.
  55,14,"He created man from potter’s clay like pottery"
  55,15,"and created the unseen being<sup foot_note="366053">1</sup> from a smokeless flame of fire.",footnotes:346516:The Arabic word used is <i>jānn</i> (the singular of jinn), which is an unseen being that is accountable for its actions.
  55,16,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,17,"Lord of the two Easts and Lord of the two Wests."
  55,18,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,19,"He merged the two waters<sup foot_note="366054">1</sup>, converging together;",footnotes:346517:Either the fresh water of rivers and the salty water of seas, or the waters of two different oceans.
  55,20,"between them is a barrier which they do not overrun."
  55,21,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,22,"From them come <span class="h">out<sup foot_note="366055">1</sup></span> pearls and corals.",footnotes:346518:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Abu Amr, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “From them are brought out pearls and corals.”</span>
  55,23,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,24,"His are the running ships, whose sails are <span class="h">raised<sup foot_note="366056">1</sup></span> in the sea like banners<sup foot_note="366057">2</sup> .",footnotes:346519:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Shu’ba in one of his narrations read it as: “His are the running ships that raise their sails in the sea like banners.”</span>|346520:The Arabic word used is <i>A’lām</i> which also means ‘tall mountains’.
  55,25,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,26,"Everyone upon it<sup foot_note="366058">1</sup> is bound to perish,",footnotes:346521:The earth.
  55,27,"and all that remains is your<sup>sg</sup> Lord's Countenance, the Possessor of majesty and nobility."
  55,28,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,29,"Everyone in the heavens and the earth asks Him; every day He is bringing about a matter."
  55,30,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,31,"<span class="h">We<sup foot_note="366059">1</sup></span> will attend to you<sup>pl</sup>, O two huge communities<sup foot_note="366060">2</sup> .",footnotes:346522:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “He will attend to you,”</span>|346523:The two types of responsible creatures: humans and <i>jinn</i>.
  55,32,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,33,"O society of unseen beings and humans, if you<sup>pl</sup> can penetrate the bounds of the heavens and the earth then go ahead and penetrate; you will never penetrate except with authority<sup foot_note="366061">1</sup> .",footnotes:346524:The Qur’anic style involves leaving part of the meaning to be deduced by the listener; some exegetes said that this means ‘except with authority from God’, while others said it means ‘except with authority that you do not have’.
  55,34,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,35,"Flares of fire, and <span class="h">brass<sup foot_note="366062">1</sup></span>, will be sent upon you<sup>dl</sup>, and you will not find help<small>.</small>",footnotes:346525:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Rouh read it as: “Flares of fire and (of) brass…”</span>
  55,36,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,37,"And when the sky ruptures and becomes rose-colored like oil—"
  55,38,"so which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,39,"On that day neither any human nor unseen being<sup foot_note="366063">1</sup> is asked about his misdeeds.",footnotes:346526:The Arabic word used is <i>jānn</i> (the singular of jinn), which is an unseen being that is accountable for its actions..
  55,40,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,41,"The criminals are recognized by their marks then taken by the forelocks and the feet."
  55,42,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,43,"This is Hell in which the criminals disbelieve;"
  55,44,"they circulate between it and an intensely scalding water."
  55,45,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,46,"But for whoever feared standing before his Lord there are two Gardens <small>(in Paradise)</small>."
  55,47,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,48,"Both having varieties."
  55,49,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,50,"In them are two flowing springs."
  55,51,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,52,"In them, of every kind of fruit there is a pair."
  55,53,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,54,"Reclining on furnishings lined with brocade, and the yield of the two Gardens are near at hand."
  55,55,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,56,"In them are bashful maidens, untouched before by any human or unseen being<sup foot_note="366064">1</sup> .",footnotes:346527:The Arabic word used is <i>jānn</i> (the singular of jinn), which is an unseen being that is accountable for its actions.
  55,57,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,58,"Like rubies and corals."
  55,59,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,60,"Is the repayment of kindness anything but kindness?"
  55,61,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,62,"And beneath them are two gardens."
  55,63,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,64,"Both of deepest green."
  55,65,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,66,"In them are two gushing springs."
  55,67,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,68,"In them are fruits and date-palms and pomegranates."
  55,69,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,70,"In them are good, beautiful ones."
  55,71,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,72,"Spouses with lovely wide eyes, secluded in pavilions."
  55,73,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,74,"Untouched before by any human or unseen being<sup foot_note="366065">1</sup> .",footnotes:346528:The Arabic word used is the singular of jinn), which is an unseen being that is accountable for its actions.<i>jānn</i> (
  55,75,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,76,"Reclining on green cushions and exquisite carpets."
  55,77,"So which of your Lord’s marvels do you<sup>dl</sup> disbelieve in?"
  55,78,"Supremely Blessed be the Name of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, the <span class="h">Possessor<sup foot_note="366066">1</sup></span> of majesty and nobility.",footnotes:346529:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “…the Name of your<sup><small>sg</small></sup> Lord, which possesses majesty and nobility.”</span>
  56,1,"When the inevitable event befalls,"
  56,2,"no disbelief will there be about its befalling,"
  56,3,"bringing low, raising high."
  56,4,"When the earth is shaken violently,"
  56,5,"and mountains are crushed and crumbled"
  56,6,"and become scattered dust,"
  56,7,"and you become three classes:"
  56,8,"the fellows of the rightness; what of the fellows of the rightness!"
  56,9,"And the fellows of the ill-omened; what of the fellows of the ill-omened!"
  56,10,"And the pioneers, the pioneers:"
  56,11,"those are the ones brought near <small>(to God)</small>"
  56,12,"in the Gardens of Bliss—"
  56,13,"a throng from the ancients"
  56,14,"and a small band from the latecomers,"
  56,15,"on luxurious couches,"
  56,16,"leaning on them, facing one another."
  56,17,"Serving them will be immortal youths"
  56,18,"with glasses, and pitchers, and a cup from a flowing spring,"
  56,19,"causing them neither headache nor <span class="h">intoxication<sup foot_note="366067">1</sup></span>,",footnotes:346530:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…causing them no headache, and they are not intoxicated,”</span>
  56,20,"and fruit of their choice,"
  56,21,"and meat of any bird they may desire."
  56,22,"And <small>(in it are)</small> <span class="h">spouses<sup foot_note="366068">1</sup></span> with lovely wide eyes,",footnotes:346531:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…and meat of any bird they may desire, <sub><small>22</small></sub>22 and (leaning on) spouses with…”</span>
  56,23,"like well-preserved pearls,"
  56,24,"as a repayment on account of what they used to do."
  56,25,"Therein they will hear no idle talk and no recrimination"
  56,26,"except for the saying: “Peace, peace.”"
  56,27,"And the fellows of the right—what of the fellows of the right?"
  56,28,"Amid thornless lote-trees"
  56,29,"and clustered banana-trees"
  56,30,"and extended shade"
  56,31,"and outpouring water"
  56,32,"and abundant fruit,"
  56,33,"neither withheld nor forbidden."
  56,34,"And high-class spouses;"
  56,35,"We have created them perfectly"
  56,36,"and made them virgins,"
  56,37,"tender, of matching age,"
  56,38,"for the fellows of the right—"
  56,39,"a throng from the ancients"
  56,40,"and a throng from the latecomers."
  56,41,"And the fellows of the left—what of the fellows of the left?"
  56,42,"Amid searing wind and scalding water"
  56,43,"and a shadow of thick smoke,"
  56,44,"neither cool nor refreshing<sup foot_note="366069">1</sup> .",footnotes:346532:The Arabic word used for refreshing is <i>kareem</i> which literally means ‘noble’.
  56,45,"They had lived before that indulging in affluence,"
  56,46,"and they used to insist on great violation,"
  56,47,"and they used to say, “Can it be that when we have died and become dust and bones—can it be <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="366070">1</sup></span> we will really be resurrected?",footnotes:346533:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Al-Kesa’i, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “Can it be that when we have died and become dust and bones we will really be…”</span>
  56,48,"<span class="h">And<sup foot_note="366071">1</sup></span> our ancient forefathers, too?”",footnotes:346534:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Qaloun, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…really be resurrected? <sub><small>48</small></sub>48Or our ancient forefathers?”</span>
  56,49,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Indeed, the ancients and the latecomers"
  56,50,"will be gathered for the appointment of a well-known day!"
  56,51,"Then indeed all of you, O misguided disbelievers,"
  56,52,"will certainly be eating from the trees of Zaqqum<sup foot_note="366072">1</sup>",footnotes:346535:Trees in Hell which produce hot, bitter, rotten fruit.
  56,53,"and filling your bellies with it"
  56,54,"and will be drinking on top of it scalding water,"
  56,55,"thus drinking as a thirst-mad camel drinks.""
  56,56,"That is their hospitality on the Day of Recompense."
  56,57,"We have created you<sup>pl</sup>; if only you would believe!"
  56,58,"Have you<sup>pl</sup> seen what you ejaculate?"
  56,59,"Is it you<sup>pl</sup> who create it or are We the Creators?"
  56,60,"We have decreed death among you<sup>pl</sup>, and We will not be outstripped"
  56,61,"in replacing you with your likes and transforming you into what you do not know."
  56,62,"And you<sup>pl</sup> have certainly known the first formation; if only you would <span class="h">remind<sup foot_note="366073">1</sup></span> yourselves!",footnotes:346536:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…if only you would constantly remember!”</span>
  56,63,"Have you<sup>pl</sup> seen what you cultivate?"
  56,64,"Is it you who plant it or are We the Planters?"
  56,65,"If We will, We can turn it into rubble, then you<sup>pl</sup> will lament,"
  56,66,"“Indeed, <span class="h">we<sup foot_note="366074">1</sup></span> are in debt;",footnotes:346537:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “Can it be that we will really be in debt? Rather…”</span>
  56,67,"rather, we are dispossessed!”"
  56,68,"Have you<sup>pl</sup> seen the water you drink?"
  56,69,"Is it you who sent it down from the rainclouds or are We the Senders?"
  56,70,"If We will, We can make it salty. Will you<sup>pl</sup> not be thankful?"
  56,71,"Have you seen the fire you kindle?"
  56,72,"Is it you who produced the tree for it, or are We the Producers?"
  56,73,"We have made it a reminding and a comfort for the travelers."
  56,74,"So highly exalt the Name of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, the Great."
  56,75,"I swear by the <span class="h">locations<sup foot_note="366075">1</sup></span> of the stars—",footnotes:346538:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…by the location of the stars…”</span>
  56,76,"and it is certainly a great oath if only you<sup>pl</sup> were to know."
  56,77,"It is indeed a Noble Recital<sup foot_note="366076">1</sup>",footnotes:346539:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation'.
  56,78,"in a well-protected Scripture."
  56,79,"None touches it except the cleansed,"
  56,80,"a bestowal from on high by the Lord of all realms."
  56,81,"Is it this discourse that you<sup>pl</sup> take so lightly?"
  56,82,"And you render due thanks for being provided with it by disbelieving in it?"
  56,83,"So when it<sup foot_note="366077">1</sup> has reached the throat,",footnotes:346540:The soul of a dying person.
  56,84,"and you are at that moment looking on,"
  56,85,"and We are nearer to him than you are, but you do not see—"
  56,86,"why, if you are not to be held to account,"
  56,87,"do you not bring it<sup foot_note="366078">1</sup> back if you are truthful?",footnotes:346541:The soul of a dying person.
  56,88,"Yet, if he is one of those brought near <small>(to God)</small>,"
  56,89,"then <span class="h">serenity<sup foot_note="366079">1</sup></span> and fragrant plants and a Garden of Bliss.",footnotes:346542:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Roways read it as: “…then a soul with fragrant plants and a Garden of bliss.”</span>
  56,90,"And if he is one of the fellows of the right,"
  56,91,"then, “Peace for you<sup>sg</sup>,” from the fellows of the right."
  56,92,"But if he is one of the misguided disbelievers,"
  56,93,"then the welcome will be scalding water"
  56,94,"and roasting in purgatory."
  56,95,"Indeed, this is surely the truth of certitude."
  56,96,"So highly exalt the Name of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, the Great."
  57,1,"Whatever is in the heavens and the earth has been highly exalting Allah, and He is the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  57,2,"To Him belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth; He gives life and causes death, for He is All-Powerful over everything."
  57,3,"He is the First and the Last and the Manifest and the Innermost, and He is All-Knowing of everything."
  57,4,"It is He who created the heavens and the earth in six days<sup foot_note="366080">1</sup> then settled over the Throne. He knows what penetrates the earth and what comes out of it, and what descends from the sky and what ascends to it, for He is with you<sup>pl</sup> wherever you may be. And Allah is All-Seeing of what you do.",footnotes:346543:Six equal intervals of time, which may be six heavenly days, each of them being 1000 earthly years long; (see 22:47).
  57,5,"To Him belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth, and to Allah all matters are <span class="h">returned<sup foot_note="366081">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346544:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Asem and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…all matters return.”</span>
  57,6,"He causes the night to penetrate the day and He causes the day to penetrate the night, and He is All-Knowing of what lies within the chests."
  57,7,"Believe in Allah and His Messenger, and spend of that over which He has made you trustees, for those of you who have attained faith and spent—for them is a supreme reward."
  57,8,"And what is the matter with you<sup>pl</sup> that you do not believe in Allah when the Messenger calls you to believe in your Lord—when He has <span class="h">taken<sup foot_note="366082">1</sup></span> your pledge<sup foot_note="366083">2</sup> — if you are believers?",footnotes:346545:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “—when your pledge has been taken…”</span>|346546:God took a pledge from all humans in a pre-earthly existence; see (7:172).
  57,9,"It is He who <span class="h">bestows<sup foot_note="366084">1</sup></span> upon His servant evident signs from on high to bring you<sup>pl</sup> out of darkness<small>(es)</small> into light. And towards you Allah is truly Compassionate, Bestowing of mercy.",footnotes:346547:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “It is He who sends down upon His servant evident signs to bring…”</span>
  57,10,"And why is it that you<sup>pl</sup> do not spend in the way of Allah when to Allah belongs the inheritance of the heavens and the earth? Not equal among you are those who spent before the conquest and combated; those are higher in degrees <small>(of rank) </small>than those who spent afterwards and combated, yet to <span class="h">each<sup foot_note="366085">1</sup></span> Allah has promised the best <small>(reward)</small>, and Allah is All-Aware of what you do.",footnotes:346548:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “…and combated. Yet each—Allah has promised (him)…”</span>
  57,11,"Who is it that will lend Allah a good loan, that He may multiply it for him, and for him is a noble reward?"
  57,12,"On the day when you<sup>sg</sup> see the believing men and believing women with their light radiating ahead of them and to their right: “Glad tidings for you today: Gardens beneath which rivers flow, abiding therein; it is that which is the great triumph.”"
  57,13,"On the day when the hypocritical men and hypocritical women say to those who believed, “Wait <span class="h">for<sup foot_note="366086">1</sup></span> us so that we may borrow from your light.” They were told<sup foot_note="366087">2</sup> : “Go back behind you and seek light.” Then a wall with a door was raised between them: within it is mercy and outside of it is punishment.",footnotes:346549:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “Reprieve us so that…”</span>|346550:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense, this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  57,14,"They<sup foot_note="366088">1</sup> call to them<sup foot_note="366089">2</sup>, “Were we not with you?” They said, “Yes, but you tempted yourselves and waited and doubted and became deceived by fancies until the command of Allah arrived, and the deceiver<sup foot_note="366090">3</sup> deceived you regarding Allah.",footnotes:346551:The hypocrites.|346552:The believers.|346553:Satan.
  57,15,"So today no ransom is accepted from you<sup>pl</sup> nor from those who have denied. The Fire is your shelter; it is your patron—and what a miserable destiny!”"
  57,16,"Is it not time for those who have attained faith: that their hearts should become reverent towards Allah's Reminder and to that which came <span class="h">down<sup foot_note="366091">1</sup></span> of the truth, and not <span class="h">be<sup foot_note="366092">2</sup></span> like those who were given the Scripture previously, but for whom time became prolonged so that their hearts hardened, and many of them are defiantly disobedient?",footnotes:346554:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’ and Hafs read it as: “…to that which He bestowed from on high of the truth…”</span>|346555:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Roways read it as: “…of the truth. And do not be like those…”</span>
  57,17,"Know that Allah revives the earth after its death; We have made the signs evident for you, that you may reason."
  57,18,"Indeed, charitable men and charitable <span class="h">women<sup foot_note="366093">1</sup></span> who have loaned Allah a good loan—it will be multiplied for them, and for them is a noble reward.",footnotes:346556:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Shu’ba read it as: “Indeed, men who believe and women who believe, who have loaned…”</span>
  57,19,"And as for those who have attained faith in Allah and His messengers—those are the unwavering believers and the witnesses<sup foot_note="366094">1</sup> who will come as witnesses with their Lord; for them is their reward and their light. But as for those who denied and rejected Our signs—those are the fellows of purgatory.",footnotes:346557:The Arabic word used is <i>shuhada’</i>, which literally means ‘witnesses’ and is usually used to describe martyrs.
  57,20,"Know<sup>pl</sup> that the Earlier Life is only a game and a distraction and an adornment and boasting among you and rivalry in wealth and children: like a rainfall producing plants that delighted the farmers, then it withers and you see it yellowing, then it becomes debris. But in the Hereafter is severe punishment and forgiveness from Allah and <small>(His)</small> good pleasure, for the Earlier Life is nothing but the enjoyment of deception."
  57,21,"Race towards forgiveness from your<sup>pl</sup> Lord and a Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> whose width is like the width of the heavens and the earth—prepared for those who have attained faith in Allah and His messengers. That is Allah’s grace; He bestows it upon whomever He wills, and Allah is the Possessor of great grace."
  57,22,"No calamity occurs on earth or among yourselves but it is already written in a Record<sup foot_note="366095">1</sup> before We make it— indeed, that is easy for Allah—",footnotes:346558:Literally ‘scripture’.
  57,23,"so that you<sup>pl</sup> do not grieve over what you have missed nor exult over what He has <span class="h">given<sup foot_note="366096">1</sup></span> you. And Allah does not love every self-admiring boaster—",footnotes:346559:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “…nor exult over what has come to you.”</span>
  57,24,"those who are miserly and command mankind to miserliness. And whoever turns away—indeed, it is Allah who <span class="h">is<sup foot_note="366097">1</sup></span> the Self-Sufficient, the Praiseworthy.",footnotes:346560:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…indeed, Allah is the Self-Sufficient, the Praiseworthy.”</span>
  57,25,"And We certainly sent Our messengers with evident proofs, and We sent down with them the Scripture and the Balance, that mankind may uphold justice. And We sent down iron in which there is intense force and benefits for humanity, and that Allah may know who supports Him and His messengers, though unseen. Indeed, Allah is All-Powerful, Almighty."
  57,26,"And We certainly sent Noah and <span class="h">Abraham<sup foot_note="366098">1</sup></span> and established Prophethood and Scripture among their offspring, so some of them are rightly guided, while many of them are defiantly disobedient.",footnotes:346561:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as <i>Ibrahim</i>, Hisham read it as: “Abraham”.</span>
  57,27,"Then We sent in their wake Our messengers and followed them with Jesus, son of Mary, and We gave him the Gospel and instilled in the hearts of those who followed him compassion and mercy. But the monasticism which they invented was only to seek Allah’s good pleasure—We did not ordain it for them— yet they did not observe it with its due observance. So We gave those of them who attained faith their reward, but many of them are defiantly disobedient."
  57,28,"O you who have attained faith, be mindful of Allah and believe in His Messenger: He shall <small>(then)</small> bring you a double share of His mercy and shall make for you a light by which you walk and shall forgive you, for Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  57,29,"So that the People of the Scripture may know that they have no power whatsoever over Allah’s grace and that all grace is in Allah’s hand; He brings it to whomever He wills, for Allah is the Possessor of great grace."
  58,1,"Allah has surely heard the statement of she who argues with you<sup>sg</sup> concerning her spouse and complains to Allah, and Allah hears your<sup>dl</sup> conversation; indeed, Allah is All-Hearing, All-Seeing."
  58,2,"Those of you who estrange their wives by equating them with their mothers—they are not their mothers; their mothers are only those who gave birth to them. And indeed, what they say is truly a deplorable thing to say and a blatant lie. But indeed, Allah is Pardoning, Oft-Forgiving."
  58,3,"And those who estrange their wives by equating them with their mothers then go back on what they have said—a slave must be set free before they may touch one another. With this you<sup>pl</sup> are admonished, and Allah is All-Aware of what you do."
  58,4,"But whoever cannot find the means must fast for two consecutive months before they may touch one another, and if he is unable—then the feeding of sixty destitute people. This is to affirm your<sup>pl</sup> faith in Allah and His Messenger, and these are the limits of Allah. And for the deniers is a painful punishment."
  58,5,"Indeed, those who oppose Allah and His Messenger have been subdued as those before them were subdued. And we have certainly sent down evident signs. And for the deniers is a demeaning punishment"
  58,6,"on the day when Allah resurrects them all and informs them of what they did. Allah has kept count of it, but they have forgotten it, and Allah is Witness over all things."
  58,7,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen that Allah knows whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth? There is no secret conversation between three but He is their fourth, nor between five but He is their sixth, nor less than that nor <span class="h">more<sup foot_note="366099">1</sup></span> but He is with them wherever they may be. Then on the Day of Resurrection He will inform them of what they did; indeed, Allah is All-Knowing of everything.",footnotes:346562:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…nor less than that, nor (is there) more but He is with them…”</span>
  58,8,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen those who were prohibited from conversing secretly but then revert to what they were prohibited from? They converse <span class="h">secretly<sup foot_note="366100">1</sup></span> in sin and hostility and <small>(in)</small> disobedience to the Messenger. And when they come to you<sup>sg</sup> they greet you with a greeting that Allah never greeted you with, and they say within themselves, “Why does Allah not punish us for what we say?” Hell is enough for them; they will roast in it—so what a miserable destiny!",footnotes:346563:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Roways read it as: “…they converse with one another secretly in sin…”</span>
  58,9,"O you who have attained faith, when you converse secretly, do not converse <span class="h">secretly<sup foot_note="366101">1</sup></span> in sin and hostility and <small>(in)</small> disobedience to the Messenger, but converse in virtue and mindfulness <small>(of God)</small>, and be mindful of Allah to Whom you will be herded.",footnotes:346564:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Roways read it as: “…do not converse with one another secretly in sin…”</span>
  58,10,"Indeed, <small>(malicious)</small> private conversations are from Satan, that those who have attained faith may be <span class="h">sad<sup foot_note="366102">1</sup></span>. But he cannot harm them at all except by Allah's leave. And in Allah let the believers place their trust.",footnotes:346565:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ read it as: “…that he may make those who have attained faith sad.”</span>
  58,11,"O you who have attained faith, when you are told, "Make room for one another in <span class="h">assemblies<sup foot_note="366103">1</sup></span>," then make room so that Allah makes room for you. And when you are told, “Arise,” then arise. Allah elevates by degrees those of you who have attained faith and those given knowledge. And Allah is All-Aware of what you do.",footnotes:346566:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except Asem read it as: “in the assembly”.</span>
  58,12,"O you who have attained faith, when you converse privately with the Messenger, give a donation ahead of your private conversation. That is better for you and cleaner. But if you do not find the means, then Allah is indeed Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  58,13,"Are you<sup>pl</sup> reluctant to give donations before your private conversation? If you do not do so and Allah pardons you, then establish the prayer and bring<sup foot_note="366104">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="366105">2</sup> and obey Allah and His Messenger. And Allah is All-Aware of what you do.",footnotes:346567:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|346568:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  58,14,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen those who allied themselves with a people upon whom is Allah’s wrath? They are neither of you<sup>pl</sup> nor of them, and they swear to lies while they know <small>(the truth)</small>."
  58,15,"Allah has prepared for them a severe punishment; evil indeed is what they used to do."
  58,16,"They took their oaths as a cover and barred <small>(others)</small> from the way of Allah, so for them is a demeaning punishment."
  58,17,"Neither their possessions nor their children will avail them anything against Allah. Those are the fellows of the Fire; therein they abide."
  58,18,"On the day when Allah resurrects them all together, they swear to Him as they swear to you<sup>pl</sup>, thinking that they are <small>(standing)</small> upon something. Undoubtedly, it is indeed they themselves who are the liars."
  58,19,"Satan has taken hold of them and so has caused them to forget the remembrance of Allah. Those are the party of Satan. Undoubtedly, it is indeed the party of Satan who are the losers."
  58,20,"Indeed, those who oppose Allah and His Messenger are among the most humiliated<sup foot_note="366106">1</sup> .",footnotes:346569:They shall be humiliated in the Hereafter.
  58,21,"Allah has prescribed: “I will most surely overcome, I and My messengers.” Indeed, Allah is All-Powerful, Almighty."
  58,22,"You<sup>sg</sup> will not find a people who believe in Allah and the Last Day loving those who oppose Allah and His Messenger, even if they were their fathers or their sons or their brethren or their kinsfolk. Those—He has prescribed faith in their hearts and has aided them with a spirit from Him, and He will enter them into Gardens <small>(of Paradise)</small> beneath which rivers flow, wherein they will abide. Allah became well pleased with them and they became well pleased with Him. Those are the party of Allah. Undoubtedly, it is indeed the party of Allah who are the successful."
  59,1,"Whatever is in the heavens and in the earth has been highly exalting Allah, and He is the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  59,2,"It is He who evicted those who denied among the People of the Scripture from their homes at the first exodus<sup foot_note="366107">1</sup> . You<sup>pl</sup> did not think they would depart, and they thought their fortresses would protect them from Allah, but Allah came at them from where they never expected and threw terror into their hearts. They<sup foot_note="366108">2</sup> <span class="h">wreck<sup foot_note="366109">3</sup></span> their houses with their own hands and by the hands of the believers. So take a lesson, O you who are endowed with sight(s).",footnotes:346570:The Jewish tribe of <i>Banu al-Nadir</i> was besieged by the Muslims for trying to assassinate the Prophet (peace be upon him). An arbiter ruled that its members had to leave <i>Madinah</i>; some of them left to <i>Khaybar</i> while the rest left to the Levant.|346571:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense, which serves to create a vivid portrait of past events.|346572:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “They vigorously wreck their houses…”</span>
  59,3,"Had Allah not prescribed evacuation for them, He would have punished them in the Earlier (Life), and for them in the Hereafter is the punishment of the Fire."
  59,4,"That is because they went against Allah and His Messenger, and whoever goes against Allah—indeed, Allah is stern in retribution."
  59,5,"Whatever palm tree you<sup>pl</sup> cut down or left standing on its roots, then that was by Allah’s leave and that He may disgrace those who are defiantly disobedient."
  59,6,"And whatever Allah has turned over to His Messenger from them, you have spurred neither horse nor camel for them, but Allah gives authority to His messengers over whomever He wills, and Allah is All-Powerful over everything."
  59,7,"Whatever Allah has turned over to His Messenger from the people of the towns, then that is for Allah and for the Messenger and for the relative and the orphans and the destitute<sup>pl</sup> and to the traveler in need, so that it does not circulate <span class="h">exclusively<sup foot_note="366110">1</sup></span> between the wealthy among you. And whatever the Messenger brings you—accept it, and whatever he forbids you—abstain from it. And be mindful of Allah; indeed, Allah is stern in retribution.",footnotes:346573:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far and Hisham read it as: “…so that a closed circuit is not created between the wealthy among you.”</span>
  59,8,"(It is) for the poor immigrants<sup foot_note="366111">1</sup> who were evicted from their homes and their possessions, seeking grace from Allah, and (His) good pleasure, and supporting Allah and His Messenger— those are the sincere.",footnotes:346574:The Arabic word used is <i>muhajereen,</i> which refers to the Muslims of <i>Makkah</i> who were forced to flee as refugees from their homes to <i>Madinah</i> where they were welcomed.
  59,9,"And (for) those who, before them, had settled in the homeland and (adopted) the faith—they love those who emigrated to them and find no need in their chests for what has been brought to them, and they give them priority over themselves even if they themselves are needy. And whoever is protected from the stinginess of his (inner) self—then it is those<sup foot_note="366112">1</sup> who are the successful.",footnotes:346575:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  59,10,"And those who came after them, saying, “Our Lord, forgive us and our brethren who preceded us in faith, and leave no malice in our hearts towards those who have attained faith. Our Lord, You are indeed Compassionate, Bestowing of mercy.”"
  59,11,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen those who became hypocrites, saying to their brethren who denied among the People of the Scripture, “Indeed, if you are evicted, we will certainly depart with you and not obey anyone against you, ever, and should anyone combat you, we will certainly support you”? But Allah bears witness that they are certainly liars."
  59,12,"Indeed, if they are evicted, they will not depart with them; and indeed, if anyone combats them, they will not support them. And (even) if they do support them, they will (then) certainly turn their backs, then they will not be supported."
  59,13,"Indeed, fear of you<sup>pl</sup> is surely more intense in their chests than fear of Allah; that is because they are people who do not comprehend."
  59,14,"They do not combat you<sup>pl</sup> all together except from fortified strongholds or from behind <span class="h">walls<sup foot_note="366113">1</sup></span>. Their hostility towards each other is severe. You<sup>sg</sup> would think them united, but their hearts are diverse; that is because they are people who do not reason.",footnotes:346576:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “…or from behind a wall.”</span>
  59,15,"Like those who shortly before them tasted the grievous consequences of their affairs, and for them is a painful punishment."
  59,16,"Like the example of Satan when he said to man, “Deny,” but when he had denied, he said, “I disown you; I fear Allah, Lord of all realms.”"
  59,17,"So the consequence for both of them was<sup foot_note="366114">1</sup> that they are<sup foot_note="366115">2</sup> in the Fire, abiding therein, and such is the repayment of the unjust.",footnotes:346577:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense, this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.|346578:A grammatical shift to present tense, which serves to create a vivid portrait of future events.
  59,18,"O you who have attained faith, be mindful of Allah, and let every soul look what it has put forth for tomorrow, and be mindful of Allah; indeed, Allah is All-Aware of what you do."
  59,19,"And do<sup>pl</sup> not be like those who forgot Allah, so He made them forget themselves; those are the defiantly disobedient."
  59,20,"Not equal are the fellows of the Fire and the fellows of the Garden (of Paradise); it is the fellows of the Garden who are the triumphant ones."
  59,21,"Had We sent this Recital<sup foot_note="366116">1</sup> down upon a mountain, you<sup>sg</sup> would have seen it (trembling) in reverence, crumbling in awe of Allah. And these parables We set forth for mankind, that they may reflect.",footnotes:346579:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  59,22,"He is Allah, besides Whom there is no god, the Knower of the hidden realm and the manifest; He is the All-Merciful, the Bestower of mercy."
  59,23,"He is Allah, besides Whom there is no god, the King, the Holy, the Peace (Giver), the Believer, the Overseer, the Almighty, the Irresistible, the Sublime; Highly Exalted is Allah beyond what they associate."
  59,24,"He is Allah, the Creator, the Maker, the Designer; His are the Most Beautiful Names. Whatever is in the heavens and the earth highly exalts Him, and He is the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  60,1,"O you who have attained faith, do not take My enemies and your enemies as guardians, extending love towards them when they have denied what has come to you of the truth, evicting the Messenger and yourselves because you believe in Allah, your Lord—if you have set out to strive in My way and to seek My pleasure. How can you secretly express love towards them while I know better what you have hidden and what you have made public? And whoever of you does that has certainly strayed from the right way."
  60,2,"If they encounter you<sup>pl</sup>, they are enemies to you and they extend their hands and tongues against you with malice, for they would love that you become deniers."
  60,3,"Neither your relatives<sup foot_note="366117">1</sup> nor your children will benefit you; on the Day of Resurrection He will <span class="h">decide<sup foot_note="366118">2</sup></span> between you, for Allah is All-Seeing of what you do.",footnotes:346580:Literally ‘your wombs’.|346581:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…on the Day of Resurrection a decision will be made between you,” Ibn Amer read it as: “…on the Day of Resurrection you will be separated,” All except for Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Abu Ja’far, Ibn Amer, Asem and Ya’qub read it as: “on the Day of Resurrection He will separate you,”</span>
  60,4,"Surely, there has always been an excellent role model for you<sup>pl</sup> in <span class="h">Abraham<sup foot_note="366119">1</sup></span> and those with him, when they said to their people, “We disown you and what you worship apart from Allah. We have disbelieved<sup foot_note="366120">2</sup> in you, and enmity and hatred have surfaced between us and you forever until you believe in Allah alone.” Except for the words of Abraham to his father, “I will ask forgiveness for you, though I cannot protect you from Allah.” “Our Lord, in You we have placed our trust, and to You we have turned penitent, for to You is the destiny.",footnotes:346582:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Though pronounced in Arabic as <i>Ibrahim</i>, Hisham read it as: “Abraham”.</span>|346583:Literally ‘denied’.
  60,5,"Our Lord, do not make us a means of trial for those who have denied, and forgive us, our Lord; You are indeed the Almighty, the All-Wise.”"
  60,6,"Indeed, there has always been an excellent role model in them for you<sup>pl</sup> <small>(and)</small> for anyone who has been putting hope in Allah and <small>(expecting)</small> the Last Day. But whoever turns away—indeed, Allah is the Self-Sufficient, the Praiseworthy."
  60,7,"Hopefully, Allah will produce love between you and those of them whom you took for enemies, for Allah is All-Powerful, and Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  60,8,"Allah does not forbid you<sup>pl</sup> from those who have neither combated you over religion nor evicted you from your homes—that you deal with them very kindly and equitably. Indeed, Allah loves the equitable."
  60,9,"Rather, Allah forbids you<sup>pl</sup> from<sup foot_note="366121">1</sup> those who combated you over religion and evicted you from your homes and backed up <small>(your enemies)</small> in your eviction. And whoever takes them as guardians—those are the unjust.",footnotes:346584:The prohibition is from befriending them or forming an alliance with them.
  60,10,"O you who have attained faith, when believing women come to you immigrating, test them; Allah knows better about their faith. And if you<sup>pl</sup> find them to be faithful, do not send them back to the deniers; they are not lawful for them<sup foot_note="366122">1</sup> nor are they lawful for them<sup foot_note="366123">2</sup> . But give them what they have spent<sup foot_note="366124">3</sup> . And no sin is committed by you if you marry them, provided you give them their compensation<sup foot_note="366125">4</sup> . And do not hold on to ties with unbelieving women, but demand what you have spent and let them demand what they have spent. This is Allah's judgment—He judges among you, for Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise.",footnotes:346585:As wives.|346586:As husbands.|346587:The dowries paid to the brides.|346588:The dowries paid to the brides.’.
  60,11,"And if any of your<sup>pl</sup> wives should go over to the deniers and then you punish <small>(them in retaliation)</small>, then give those whose wives have gone away the equivalent of what they had spent. And be mindful of Allah in whom you are believers."
  60,12,"O Prophet, if believing women come to you pledging allegiance to you that they will not associate anything with Allah, nor steal, nor fornicate, nor kill their children, nor commit perjury as to parenthood, nor disobey you in anything righteous—then accept their allegiance and ask Allah’s forgiveness for them; indeed, Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  60,13,"O you who have attained faith, do not take for guardians people upon whom is Allah’s wrath—they have indeed despaired of the Hereafter as the deniers have despaired of the fellows of the graves."
  61,1,"Whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth has been highly exalting Allah, and He is the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  61,2,"O you who have attained faith, why do you say what you do not do?"
  61,3,"It is most loathsome to Allah that you<sup>pl</sup> say what you do not do."
  61,4,"Indeed, Allah loves those who combat in His way, lining up in ranks as though they were a compact structure."
  61,5,"And recall when Moses said to his people, “O my people, why do you hurt me, though you know that I am Allah’s Messenger to you?” And when they swerved, Allah caused their hearts to swerve, for Allah does not guide the defiantly disobedient people."
  61,6,"And recall when Jesus, son of Mary, said, “O Children of Israel, I am Allah’s Messenger to you, confirming what preceded me of the Torah and a bearer of glad tidings of a messenger who comes after me, whose name is Ahmad.” Yet when he came to them with evident proofs, they said, “This is evident <span class="h">sorcery<sup foot_note="366126">1</sup></span>.”",footnotes:346589:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “‘This is an evident sorcerer.’”</span>
  61,7,"And who is more unjust than one who fabricated lies against Allah when he was being invited to Islam? Thus Allah does not guide the unjust people."
  61,8,"They want to extinguish Allah’s Light with their mouths, but Allah shall perfect His Light, even though the deniers hate it."
  61,9,"It is He who sent His Messenger with the guidance and the religion of truth to make it prevail over all religion, even though the pagans hate it."
  61,10,"O you who have attained faith, shall I inform you of a bargain that will <span class="h">save<sup foot_note="366127">1</sup></span> you from a painful punishment?",footnotes:346590:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “…that will deliver you from…”</span>
  61,11,"That you<sup>pl</sup> believe in Allah and His Messenger, and strive in the way of Allah with your wealth and yourselves; that is better for you, if you only knew—"
  61,12,"He will forgive you<sup>pl</sup> your misdeeds and will enter you into Gardens beneath which rivers flow, and into beautiful residences in the Gardens of Eden; that is the great triumph."
  61,13,"And something else you<sup>pl</sup> love: support from Allah and an imminent conquest. So give glad tidings to the believers."
  61,14,"O you who have attained faith, be the <span class="h">supporters<sup foot_note="366128">1</sup></span> of Allah as Jesus, son of Mary, said to the disciples, “Who are my supporters towards Allah?” The disciples said, “We are the supporters of Allah.” Then a faction of the Children of Israel attained faith while another faction denied it, and We aided those who had attained faith against their enemy, so they came to prevail.",footnotes:346591:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…be supporters for Allah…”</span>
  62,1,"Whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth highly exalts Allah, the Sovereign, the Holy, the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  62,2,"It is He who sent among the gentiles<sup foot_note="366129">1</sup> a messenger from among themselves, reading His signs<sup foot_note="366130">2</sup> to them and purifying them and teaching them the Scripture and wisdom—although they were indeed in evident misguidance before that—",footnotes:346592:Literally ‘the unlettered’.|346593:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  62,3,"and (to) others of them who have not yet joined them<sup foot_note="366131">1</sup> . And He is the Almighty, the All-Wise.",footnotes:346594:Non-Arab believers.
  62,4,"That is Allah’s grace which He brings to whomever He wills, and Allah is the Possessor of great grace."
  62,5,"The likeness of those who were made to carry (the responsibility of) the Torah but then failed to carry it is as the likeness of the donkey carrying tomes. How miserable is the example of the people who rejected Allah’s signs, for Allah does not guide the unjust people."
  62,6,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “O you who have Judaized, if you claim to be the allies of Allah apart from (the rest of) mankind, then wish for death if you are truthful.”"
  62,7,"But they will not wish for it ever due to what their hands have put forth, and Allah is All-Knowing of the unjust."
  62,8,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Indeed, the death from which you<sup>pl</sup> flee—it is bound to encounter you, then you will be returned to the Knower of the hidden realm and the manifest, and He will inform you of what you used to do.”"
  62,9,"O you who have attained faith, when the call to prayer is made on Friday, hasten to the remembrance of Allah and leave aside all selling; that is better for you if you only knew."
  62,10,"Then when the prayer is concluded, disperse through the land and seek Allah’s grace and remember Allah much, that you<sup>pl</sup> may succeed."
  62,11,"Yet whenever they<sup foot_note="366132">1</sup> come across a bargain or distraction they scramble towards it and leave you<sup>sg</sup> standing. Say, “What is with Allah is better than (any) distraction or bargain, and Allah is the Best of providers.”",footnotes:346595:A grammatical shift from 2<sup><small>nd</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.
  63,1,"When the hypocrites come to you<sup>sg</sup>, they say, “We bear witness that you are most surely Allah’s Messenger.” And Allah knows that you are most surely His Messenger, and Allah bears witness that the hypocrites are most surely liars:"
  63,2,"they have taken their oaths as a cover, and so they have barred <small>(others)</small> from the way of Allah; indeed, evil is what they have been doing."
  63,3,"That is because they believed then they denied, so their hearts were sealed—thus they do not comprehend."
  63,4,"Yet when you<sup>sg</sup> see them, their physiques impress you, and when they speak, you listen to what they say. They are like propped-up timber; they think every shout is aimed at them. They are the enemy, so beware of them. May<small> </small>Allah strike them down! How can they be averted <small>(from the truth)</small>?"
  63,5,"And when it is said to them, “Come, the Messenger of Allah will ask forgiveness for you,” they keep <span class="h">turning<sup foot_note="366133">1</sup></span> their heads aside and you<sup>sg</sup> see them turning away while acting arrogantly.",footnotes:346596:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Rouh read it as: “…they turn their heads…”</span>
  63,6,"It is the same for them whether you<sup>sg</sup> ask forgiveness for them or do not ask forgiveness for them—Allah will not forgive them; indeed, Allah does not guide the defiantly disobedient people."
  63,7,"It is they who say: “Do not spend anything on those who side with Allah’s Messenger, that they may disperse.” And to Allah belong the treasuries of the heavens and the earth, but the hypocrites do not comprehend."
  63,8,"They say, “If we return to al-Madinah, the mightier ones will surely evict the inferior ones.” But might belongs to Allah and His Messenger and the believers, but the hypocrites do not know."
  63,9,"O you who have attained faith, let neither your wealth nor your children distract you from the remembrance of Allah, and whoever does that—then those are the losers."
  63,10,"And spend from what We have provided for you<sup>pl</sup> before death approaches one of you, whereupon he says, “My Lord, if only You would delay me for a short while so that I may donate and become of the righteous!”"
  63,11,"But Allah will not delay a soul when its time has come, for Allah is All-Aware of what you<sup>pl</sup> <span class="h">do<sup foot_note="366134">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346597:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “…what they do.”</span>
  64,1,"Whatever is in the heavens and whatever is in the earth highly exalts Allah; to Him belongs the dominion and to Him all praise is due, and He is All-Powerful over everything."
  64,2,"It is He who created you: so some of you are deniers and some of you are believers. And Allah is All-Seeing of what you do."
  64,3,"He created the heavens and the earth with truth, and He designed you<sup>pl</sup> and perfected your designs, and to Him is the destiny."
  64,4,"He knows whatever is in the heavens and the earth, and He knows whatever you<sup>pl</sup> keep secret and whatever you make public. For Allah is All-Knowing of what lies within the chests."
  64,5,"Has the news not reached you<sup>pl</sup> of those who denied before, so they tasted the grievous consequences of their affairs? For for them is a painful punishment."
  64,6,"That is because their messengers came to them with evident proofs, but they said, “Are human beings going to guide us?” So they denied and turned away, but Allah had no need <small>(for anyone)</small>, for Allah is Self-Sufficient, Praiseworthy."
  64,7,"Those who have denied have claimed that they will not be resurrected. Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Yes indeed, by my Lord, you<sup>pl</sup> will be resurrected, then you will be informed of whatever you did, for that is easy for Allah.”"
  64,8,"So have faith in Allah and His Messenger and the Light<sup foot_note="366135">1</sup> which We have sent down. For Allah is All-Aware of what you do.",footnotes:346598:The Qur’an.
  64,9,"The day when <span class="h">He<sup foot_note="366136">1</sup></span> gathers you<sup>pl</sup> for the Day of Gathering—that is the Day of Mutual Loss and Gain. And whoever attains faith in Allah and acts righteously, <span class="h">He<sup foot_note="366137">2</sup></span> will remit his evil deeds and He will enter him into Gardens beneath which rivers flow, abiding therein forever; that is the great triumph.",footnotes:346599:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “The day when We gather you…”</span>|346600:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…We will remit his evil deeds and We will enter him into…”</span>
  64,10,"But those who denied and rejected Our signs—those are the fellows of the Fire, abiding therein, and what a miserable destiny!"
  64,11,"No disaster occurs except by Allah’s leave. And whoever believes in Allah—He guides his heart. For Allah is All-Knowing of everything."
  64,12,"So obey Allah and obey the Messenger. But if you<sup>pl</sup> turn away, then surely Our Messenger's only<small> </small>duty is evident proclamation."
  64,13,"Allah—there is no god but He. So in Allah let the believers place their trust."
  64,14,"O you who have attained faith, indeed, among your spouses and your children are enemies to you, so beware of them. But if you pardon and overlook and forgive—then indeed, Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  64,15,"Indeed, your wealth and your children are but a means of trial, while with Allah is a great reward."
  64,16,"So be mindful of Allah as much as you<sup>pl</sup> can, and listen and obey and give <small>(in charity)</small> for your own good. For whoever is protected from the stinginess of his <small>(inner)</small> self—those are the successful."
  64,17,"If you<sup>pl</sup> lend Allah a good loan, He will multiply it for you and will forgive you, for Allah is Ever Thankful, Forbearing—"
  64,18,"the Knower of the hidden realm and the manifest, the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  65,1,"O Prophet, when you<sup>pl</sup> divorce<sup foot_note="366138">1</sup> women, then divorce them at a time when their <small>(waiting)</small> period can properly start, and calculate the period carefully. And be mindful of Allah, your<sup>pl</sup> Lord. Do not evict them from their houses nor shall they depart, unless they have committed an evident <span class="h">obscenity<sup foot_note="366139">2</sup></span>. Those are the limits of Allah, and whoever oversteps Allah’s limits, then he has surely been unjust to himself. You<sup>sg</sup> never know—Allah may afterwards bring about a new matter.",footnotes:346601:It is obvious from the masculine plural pronoun that the Qur’an is addressing men.|346602:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Shu’ba read it as: “…committed an evidenced obscenity.”</span>
  65,2,"Once they have reached their term, either retain<sup>pl</sup> them in accordance with what is fair or separate from them in accordance with what is fair. And call to witness two just people from among you and give upright testimony for Allah. That is to admonish whoever believes in Allah and the Last Day, for whoever is mindful of Allah—He will make for him a way out <small>(of every difficulty)</small>"
  65,3,"and will provide for him from where he never expects, and whoever places his trust in Allah—He will suffice him. Allah shall indeed conclude His decreed matters; Allah has set a due measure for everything."
  65,4,"And those of your women<small> </small>who have despaired of <small>(further)</small> menstruation—if you have any doubts, their <small>(waiting)</small> period shall be three months, and also for those who have not menstruated<sup foot_note="366140">1</sup> . And those who are pregnant—their term shall be until they have delivered. And whoever is mindful of Allah—He will ease his affairs.",footnotes:346603:Puberty is a condition for marriage in Islam; some women do not menstruate because of abnormalities of the reproductive tract.
  65,5,"That is Allah's command which He has sent down to you<sup>pl</sup>. And whoever is mindful of Allah—He will remit his evil deeds and amplify his reward."
  65,6,"Allow them<sup foot_note="366141">1</sup> to reside where you<sup>pl</sup> have been residing according to your means, and do not harass them to make things difficult for them. And if they are pregnant, spend for them until they deliver. And if they nurse your infant, pay them their reward and conduct your relation in accordance with what is fair. But if you disagree, then another woman will nurse him.",footnotes:346604:The divorced women.
  65,7,"The wealthy one shall spend according to his means, and the one whose resources have been restrained shall spend according to what Allah has given him. Allah never tasks any self beyond what He has brought it; Allah shall bring ease after hardship."
  65,8,"And how many a town has defied the command of its Lord and His messengers, so We held it to a strict reckoning and We punished it with a dreadful punishment:"
  65,9,"it tasted the grievous consequence of its affairs, and the consequence of its affairs was perdition."
  65,10,"Allah has prepared for them a severe punishment, so beware of Allah, O you who possess intellect and have attained faith. Allah has sent down to you a Reminder—"
  65,11,"a messenger who reads to you Allah’s signs<sup foot_note="366142">1</sup>, <small>(which are)</small> <span class="h">clarifying<sup foot_note="366143">2</sup></span>, in order to bring out those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds from darkness into light. And whoever believes in Allah and acts <span class="h">righteously—He<sup foot_note="366144">3</sup></span> will enter him into Gardens beneath which rivers flow, abiding therein forever; Allah has surely given him an excellent provision.",footnotes:346605:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). Ayah means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.|346606:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn kathir, Abu Amr, Shu’ba, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…Allah’s signs, clarified,”</span>|346607:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…We will enter him into…”</span>
  65,12,"Allah is He Who created seven heavens, and their like of earth. The command descends between them so that you<sup>pl</sup> may know that Allah is Powerful over everything and that Allah has encompassed everything in knowledge."
  66,1,"O Prophet, why do you prohibit what Allah has permitted for you, seeking to please your spouses? Yet Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  66,2,"Allah has already ordained for you<sup>pl</sup> the dissolution of your oaths, for Allah is your Patron, and He is the All-Knowing, the All-Wise."
  66,3,"And recall when the Prophet confided a matter to some of his spouses, then as soon as one <small>(of them)</small> disclosed it <small>(to another wife)</small> and Allah made it known to him, he communicated part of <span class="h">it<sup foot_note="366145">1</sup></span> and disregarded another part. Then, when he informed her of it, she said, “Who informed you of this?” He said, “The All-Knowing, the All-Aware informed me.”",footnotes:346608:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…he harboured part of it and disregarded another part.”</span>
  66,4,"If you<sup>dl</sup> repent<sup foot_note="366146">1</sup> to Allah, then your hearts have listened. But if both of you band together against him, then Allah is his Patron, as are Gabriel and the righteous believers. And, in addition, the angels will back him.",footnotes:346609:Addressing two of the wives of the Prophet (peace be upon him): the one who disclosed the secret and the one who listened to her.
  66,5,"Perhaps, if he divorces<sup foot_note="366147">1</sup> you<sup>pl</sup>, his Lord will give him in exchange better spouses than you: Muslim<sup foot_note="366148">2</sup>, believing, devout, repentant, given to worshiping, given to fasting—whether previously married or virgins.",footnotes:346610:The Qur’an is addressing all the wives of the Prophet (peace be upon him) using the feminine plural pronoun.|346611:The word Arabic word <i>Muslimāt (feminine and plural form of Muslim)</i> means women who willingly submit to God.
  66,6,"O you who have attained faith, shield yourselves and your families from a fire whose fuel is people and stones; over it are fierce and powerful angels who never disobey Allah in anything He commands them, and they carry out whatever they are commanded."
  66,7,"O you who have denied, make no excuses today; indeed, you are only being repaid for what you used to do."
  66,8,"O you who have attained faith, repent to Allah with <span class="h">sincere<sup foot_note="366149">1</sup></span> repentance; hopefully your Lord will remit your evil deeds and enter you into Gardens beneath which rivers flow, on the day when Allah will never disgrace the Prophet and those who believed with him. With their light streaming before them and to their right, they say, “Our Lord, perfect our light for us and forgive us; You are indeed All-Powerful over everything.”",footnotes:346612:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba read it as: “…repent to Allah with a repentance of sincerity…”</span>
  66,9,"O Prophet, strive hard against the deniers and the hypocrites, and be stern with them. And their shelter is Hell, and what a miserable destiny!"
  66,10,"Allah has set forth a parable for those who denied: the wife of Noah and the wife of Lot; they were under two servants of Our righteous servants but they betrayed them, so they availed them nothing against Allah, and it was said, “Enter the Fire with those who are entering.”"
  66,11,"And Allah has set forth a parable for those who have attained faith: the wife of Pharaoh, when she said, “My Lord, build for me, with you, a house in the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small>, and deliver me from Pharaoh and his actions, and deliver me from the unjust people.”"
  66,12,"And Mary, the daughter of Imran, who guarded her chastity, and so We breathed into her of Our Spirit, and she believed in her Lord’s Words and His <span class="h">Scriptures<sup foot_note="366150">1</sup></span> and was one of the devout.",footnotes:346613:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…and His Scripture and was…”</span>
  67,1,"Supremely Blessed be He in whose hand is the dominion, and He is All- Powerful over everything;"
  67,2,"the One Who created death and life to test you<sup>pl</sup> as to which of you is better in conduct, for He is the Almighty, the Oft-Forgiving;"
  67,3,"the One Who created seven heavens in layers: you<sup>sg</sup> see no discrepancy in the creation of the All-Merciful. So look again: can you see any splits?"
  67,4,"Then look again and again—your<sup>sg</sup> sight will return to you bedazzled and exhausted."
  67,5,"And indeed, We have adorned the lowest<sup foot_note="366381">1</sup> heaven with lanterns and made them missiles against the Satans, and We have prepared for them the punishment of the Blaze.",footnotes:346844:The Arabic word <i>dunya</i> translated here as “lowest” is the same word used to describe the life of this world as the “Earlier” Life, as it carries both meanings: lowest and earlier.
  67,6,"And for those who have denied their Lord is the punishment of Hell, and what a miserable destiny!"
  67,7,"When they are thrown into it, they hear it roaring as it seethes—"
  67,8,"it almost bursts with rage. Every time a crowd is thrown into it, its keepers ask them, “Did no warner come to you?”"
  67,9,"They said<sup foot_note="366382">1</sup>, “Yes, a warner did come to us, but we disbelieved and said, ‘Allah did not bestow anything from on high; it is you<sup>pl</sup> who are greatly misguided!’”",footnotes:346845:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  67,10,"And they said, “Had we listened or reasoned, we would not have been among the fellows of the Blaze.”"
  67,11,"Thus they acknowledged their misdeed, so away with the fellows of the Blaze."
  67,12,"Indeed, for those who fear their Lord though Unseen, there is forgiveness and a supreme reward."
  67,13,"And keep your<sup>pl</sup> words secret or say them aloud—indeed, He is All-Knowing of what lies within the chests."
  67,14,"Would He not know whomever He has created, while He is the Subtle, the All-Aware?"
  67,15,"It is He who made the earth manageable for you<sup>pl</sup>, so walk through its regions and eat of His provision, and to Him is the Resurrection."
  67,16,"Are you<sup>pl</sup> confident that the One in heaven will not cause the earth to collapse beneath you as it spins?"
  67,17,"Or are you confident that the One in heaven will not unleash against you a violent storm? Then you will know what My<sup foot_note="366383">1</sup> warning is like.",footnotes:346846:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.
  67,18,"And surely those before them disbelieved <small>(as well)</small>, so how terrible was My condemnation!"
  67,19,"Have they not seen the birds above them, spreading their wings and folding them? None holds them except the All-Merciful; indeed, He is All-Seeing of everything."
  67,20,"Or who is this who is an army for you<sup>pl</sup>, supporting you, apart from the All-Merciful? Indeed, the deniers are in nothing but a deception."
  67,21,"Or who is this that will provide for you if He withholds His provision? Rather, they persist in defiance and aversion."
  67,22,"Is one who walks bent on his own face better guided or one who walks upright on a straight path?"
  67,23,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “It is He Who initiated you<sup>pl</sup> and made for you hearing and sight<small>(s)</small> and burning hearts; rarely do you give thanks.”"
  67,24,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “It is He Who scattered you<sup>pl</sup> on earth, and to Him you will be herded.”"
  67,25,"And they say, “When will this promise be fulfilled if you<sup>pl</sup> are truthful?”"
  67,26,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Indeed, knowledge is only with Allah, and indeed, I am only an evident warner.”"
  67,27,"But when they saw it approaching, the faces of those who had denied turned gloomy, and it was said, “This is what you<sup>pl</sup> used to <span class="h">claim<sup foot_note="366384">1</sup></span><small>(would never happen)</small>.”",footnotes:346847:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “‘This is what you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> used to (challengingly) call for.’”</span>
  67,28,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Have you seen: if Allah makes me and those with me perish or has mercy on us, who then will protect the deniers from a painful punishment?”"
  67,29,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “He is the All-Merciful; we have attained faith in Him, and in Him alone we have placed our trust, and soon you<sup>pl</sup> will <span class="h">know<sup foot_note="366385">1</sup></span> who is in evident misguidance.”",footnotes:346848:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…and soon they will know who is…”</span>
  67,30,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Have you<sup>pl</sup> seen:<small> </small>if your water drains away, who then will bring you pure running water?”"
  68,1,"Nûn. By the pen and all that they inscribe."
  68,2,"Your<sup>sg</sup> Lord's blessing does not make you a madman."
  68,3,"And most surely, for you<sup>sg</sup> is an unfailing reward."
  68,4,"And very truly, you<sup>sg</sup> are of great moral character."
  68,5,"Thus you<sup>sg</sup> shall see and they shall see"
  68,6,"which of you is the demented."
  68,7,"Indeed, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is He Who knows better who has strayed from His way, and it is He Who knows better of the rightly guided."
  68,8,"So do not obey the disbelievers;"
  68,9,"they would like you to compromise, then they too would compromise."
  68,10,"And do not obey any despicable swearer,"
  68,11,"backbiter, spreader of malicious gossip,"
  68,12,"preventer of good, transgressor, sinful,"
  68,13,"brutal; moreover, of spurious parentage!"
  68,14,"<span class="h">Just<sup foot_note="366386">1</sup></span> because he has money and sons,",footnotes:346849:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu ‘Amr, Hafs, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “Is it true that because he has money and sons, <sub><small>15</small></sub>15 when Our signs are recited to him, he says, ‘Legends of the ancients!’?”</span>
  68,15,"when Our signs<sup foot_note="366387">1</sup> are read to him, he says, “Legends of the ancients!”",footnotes:346850:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Quran, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  68,16,"We will brand him on the snout."
  68,17,"Indeed, We have tested them as We tested the fellows of the garden, when they swore to harvest it in the morning"
  68,18,"without any reservation."
  68,19,"Then a sweeping visitation from your<sup>sg</sup> Lord swept through it while they were asleep,"
  68,20,"and in the morning it was as though harvested."
  68,21,"So they called to each other in the early morning:"
  68,22,"“Go early to your<sup>pl</sup> field if you are going to harvest.”"
  68,23,"So they set out, murmuring to one another,"
  68,24,"“Not one destitute person is to enter it upon you<sup>pl</sup> today.”"
  68,25,"And early they went, resolved in intent."
  68,26,"But when they saw it, they said, “Indeed, we are surely misguided;"
  68,27,"rather, we are deprived.”"
  68,28,"The most reasonable of them said, “Did I not tell you<sup>pl</sup>, ‘if only you would highly exalt <small>(God)</small>?’”"
  68,29,"They said, “Highly Exalted is our Lord; indeed, we were unjust.”"
  68,30,"Then they turned to each other, blaming one another."
  68,31,"They said, “Woe to us; indeed, we have exceeded all limits."
  68,32,"Perhaps our Lord will give us a better substitute for it. Indeed, to our Lord we turn wishfully.”"
  68,33,"Such is the punishment <small>(of this world)</small>; but the punishment of the Hereafter is greater, if they only knew."
  68,34,"Indeed, for the people who are mindful <small>(of God)</small> are Gardens of Bliss, with their Lord."
  68,35,"Shall We treat the Muslims<sup foot_note="366388">1</sup> like the criminals?",footnotes:346851:The Arabic word used is <i>Muslimeen</i> which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  68,36,"What is the matter with you<sup>pl</sup>? How do you judge?"
  68,37,"Or do you have a scripture in which you study,"
  68,38,"wherein there is whatever you choose?"
  68,39,"Or do you have oaths from Us, binding until the Day of Resurrection, that you will have whatever you demand?"
  68,40,"Ask<sup>sg</sup> them which of them guarantees that."
  68,41,"Or do they have associates? Then let them bring their associates if they are truthful."
  68,42,"On the day when the shin is exposed<sup foot_note="366389">1</sup> and they are called to prostrate themselves, but they<sup foot_note="366390">2</sup> are unable to.",footnotes:346852:A metaphor meaning ‘when matters become dire’; it refers to the Day of Judgment.|346853:This verse refers to the disbelievers.
  68,43,"Their sight<small>(s)</small> <small>(</small><small>subdued)</small> in reverence, humiliation overwhelms them, for they had been called to prostrate themselves when they were sound."
  68,44,"So leave<sup>sg</sup> Me to those who reject this discourse; We will draw them forth gradually <small>(to punishment)</small> from where they do not know."
  68,45,"And I will give them respite. Indeed, My plot is firm."
  68,46,"Or do you<sup>sg</sup> ask them for a reward, so they are burdened with debt?"
  68,47,"Or do they have <small>(knowledge of)</small> the hidden realm and they are writing it down?"
  68,48,"So wait patiently for the Decree of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, and do not be like the Fellow of the Whale, who cried out in despair."
  68,49,"Were it not for his Lord’s favor that reached him, he would have been thrown into the wilderness, fully despised."
  68,50,"But his Lord chose him and made him one of the righteous."
  68,51,"Those who have denied almost stab you<sup>sg</sup> with their sight<small>(s)</small> when they hear the Reminder, and say, “He is indeed a madman!”"
  68,52,"But it is nothing other than a Reminder to <small>(all creatures of)</small> all realms."
  69,1,"The Reality."
  69,2,"What is the Reality?"
  69,3,"And what can make you<sup>sg</sup> realize what the Reality is?"
  69,4,"Thamûd and Ād disbelieved in the Shocking Event."
  69,5,"So as for Thamûd, they were annihilated by the Overwhelming."
  69,6,"And as for Ād, they were annihilated by a furious, roaring wind"
  69,7,"which He unleashed upon them for seven nights and eight days in succession, so you<sup>sg</sup> could see the people tossed around as though they were stumps of hollow palm trees."
  69,8,"So can you<sup>sg</sup> see any remnant of them?"
  69,9,"Then Pharaoh and whoever was before <span class="h">him<sup foot_note="366391">1</sup></span> and the Overturned Cities<sup foot_note="366392">2</sup> came up with grave offenses",footnotes:346854:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu ‘Amr, Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “Then Pharaoh and whoever was on his side and the…”</span>|346855:The Overturned Cities of the people of Lot.
  69,10,"and disobeyed the messenger of their Lord, so He seized them with an overpowering grip."
  69,11,"Indeed, when the waters overflowed We carried you<sup>pl</sup> in the running ship,"
  69,12,"making it a lesson for you<sup>pl</sup>—so that an attentive ear may take heed."
  69,13,"Then, when the Trumpet is blown with a single blast,"
  69,14,"and the earth and the mountains are lifted up and crushed with a single crush—"
  69,15,"on that day, the Inevitable Event shall come to pass"
  69,16,"and the heaven shall crack, for on that day it shall be frail."
  69,17,"And the angels are ranged around its borders, while eight carry the Throne of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord above them on that day."
  69,18,"On that day you<sup>pl</sup> are presented, and no hidden secret of yours remains hidden."
  69,19,"So as for the one who was given his record<sup foot_note="366393">1</sup> in his right hand, he says, “Here, take my record and read it.",footnotes:346856:Literally ‘scripture’.
  69,20,"Indeed, I was certain that I would meet my reckoning.”"
  69,21,"So he will be in a well-pleasing living,"
  69,22,"in a lofty Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small>,"
  69,23,"its clusters <small>(of fruit)</small> within reach—"
  69,24,"“Eat and drink with satisfaction on account of what you<sup>pl</sup> did<sup foot_note="366394">1</sup> in the days gone by.”",footnotes:346857:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  69,25,"But as for the one who was given his record<sup foot_note="366395">1</sup> in his left hand, he says, “I wish I was never given my record",footnotes:346858:Literally ‘scripture’.
  69,26,"and never knew what my reckoning was."
  69,27,"If only it was the end!"
  69,28,"My money cannot avail me;"
  69,29,"my power has vanished from me.”"
  69,30,"“Take<sup>pl</sup> him and shackle him,"
  69,31,"then scorch him in purgatory,"
  69,32,"then in a chain whose length is seventy cubits tie him up."
  69,33,"For he would not believe in Allah, the Great,"
  69,34,"nor would he urge <small>(others to serve)</small> food to the destitute<sup>sg</sup>."
  69,35,"So he has no intimate <small>(friend)</small> here today,"
  69,36,"nor any food except scum,"
  69,37,"which none eats except the wrongdoers.""
  69,38,"So I swear by what you<sup>pl</sup> see"
  69,39,"and what you do not see:"
  69,40,"it is indeed the word<sup foot_note="366396">1</sup> of a noble messenger",footnotes:346859:The Qur’an.
  69,41,"and in no way is it the word of a poet—little do you<sup>pl</sup> <span class="h">believe<sup foot_note="366397">1</sup></span>,",footnotes:346860:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Ya’qub, Hisham and Ibn Zekwan in one of his narrations read it as: “…little do they believe, <sub><small>42</small></sub>42 nor is it the speech of a soothsayer—little do they remember.”</span>
  69,42,"nor is it the speech of a soothsayer—little do you remind <span class="h">yourselves<sup foot_note="366398">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346861:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Abu ‘Amr, Shu’ba, Abu Ja’far and Ibn Zekwan in one of his narrations read it as: “…little do you remember.”</span>
  69,43,"<small>(It is)</small> a bestowal from on high by the Lord of all realms."
  69,44,"And had he falsely attributed some statements to Us,"
  69,45,"We would certainly have seized him strongly<sup foot_note="366399">1</sup>,",footnotes:346862:Literally ‘by the right arm’, which is a metaphor for strength.
  69,46,"then We would certainly have slashed his aorta,"
  69,47,"and in no way could any of you have defended him."
  69,48,"And indeed, it is a reminding for the mindful<sup>pl</sup> <small>(of God)</small>."
  69,49,"And indeed, We do know that some of you are disbelievers."
  69,50,"And indeed, it is surely a source of grief for the deniers."
  69,51,"And indeed, it is surely the truth of certitude."
  69,52,"So highly exalt the name of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, the Great."
  70,1,"An asker <span class="h">asked<sup foot_note="366400">1</sup></span> about a punishment sure to come",footnotes:346863:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn ‘Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “A flood has flooded with a punishment sure to come…” According to the dialect of the tribes of <i>Hijaz</i>, the narration of Nafie’, Ibn ‘Amer and Abu Ja’far means exactly the same as all the others.</span>
  70,2,"for the deniers, that none can repel—"
  70,3,"from Allah, Lord of the Ways of Ascent."
  70,4,"Unto Him the angels and the Spirit ascend on a day the duration of which is fifty thousand years."
  70,5,"So be<sup>sg</sup> patient with beautiful patience."
  70,6,"Indeed, they see it distant,"
  70,7,"but We see it near—"
  70,8,"on the day when the sky is like molten brass,"
  70,9,"and the mountains are like tufted wool,"
  70,10,"and no intimate <small>(friend)</small> <span class="h">asks<sup foot_note="366401">1</sup></span> his intimate <small>(friend)</small>—",footnotes:346864:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far and Al-Bazzi in one of his narrations read it as: “…and no intimate (friend) is asked (about) his intimate (friend)…”</span>
  70,11,"though they are shown each other. The criminal wishes he could be redeemed from the punishment of that <span class="h">day<sup foot_note="366402">1</sup></span> by sacrificing his children",footnotes:346865:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Al-Kesa’i and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…redeemed from punishment on that day by…”</span>
  70,12,"and his female companion and his brother"
  70,13,"and his kinsfolk who shelter him"
  70,14,"and everyone on earth, so it would then save him."
  70,15,"But no! It is a raging fire"
  70,16,"that <span class="h">strips<sup foot_note="366403">1</sup></span> away the scalps,",footnotes:346866:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as: “…It is a raging fire. <sub><small>16</small></sub>16 It strips away the scalps…”</span>
  70,17,"inviting the one who had retreated and turned away<sup foot_note="366404">1</sup>",footnotes:346867:This may mean ‘turned away from the truth’.
  70,18,"and accumulated <small>(wealth)</small> and hoarded."
  70,19,"Indeed, man was created fretful:"
  70,20,"when touched by adversity he is impatient,"
  70,21,"and when touched by good he is ungenerous;"
  70,22,"except the prayerful<sup>pl</sup>"
  70,23,"who are<sup foot_note="366405">1</sup> constant at their prayers;",footnotes:346868:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  70,24,"and those in whose wealth is a rightfully acknowledged share"
  70,25,"for the asker and the deprived;"
  70,26,"and those who believe in the Day of Recompense;"
  70,27,"and those who fear the punishment of their Lord—"
  70,28,"indeed, none can feel secure from their Lord’s punishment;"
  70,29,"and those who preserve their private parts<sup foot_note="366406">1</sup>,",footnotes:346869:A metaphor for maintaining chastity.
  70,30,"except from their spouses or those whom they rightfully possess—for then they are indeed not blameworthy."
  70,31,"But whoever seeks to go beyond that, then those are the transgressors;"
  70,32,"and those who are faithful to their <span class="h">trusts<sup foot_note="366407">1</sup></span> and their covenant;",footnotes:346870:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “…to their trustworthiness and their covenant…”</span>
  70,33,"and those who stand by their <span class="h">testimonies<sup foot_note="366408">1</sup></span>;",footnotes:346871:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs and Ya’qub read it as: “…by their testimony…”</span>
  70,34,"and those who preserve their prayers—"
  70,35,"those are honored in Gardens <small>(of Paradise)</small>."
  70,36,"So what is with those who have denied, craning their necks towards you<sup>sg</sup>,"
  70,37,"from the right and from the left, banding together?"
  70,38,"Does every one of them ardently hope to be entered into a Garden of Bliss?"
  70,39,"But no! Indeed, We created them from what they know."
  70,40,"So I swear by the Lord of the Easts and the Wests that We are surely able"
  70,41,"to replace them with better than them, and We cannot be outstripped."
  70,42,"So let<sup>sg</sup> them blunder and play until they <span class="h">meet<sup foot_note="366409">1</sup></span> their day which they are promised—",footnotes:346872:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…until they encounter their day…”</span>
  70,43,"the day when they come out of the tombs in a rush, as though they are hurrying towards some <span class="h">statues<sup foot_note="366410">1</sup></span>,",footnotes:346873:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs and Ibn ‘Amer read it as: "...hurrying towards a statue..."</span>
  70,44,"their sight<small>(s)</small> <small>(subdued)</small> in reverence, humiliation overwhelming them. That is the day which they were promised."
  71,1,"Indeed, We sent Noah to his people: “Warn your people before there comes upon them a painful punishment.”"
  71,2,"He said, “O my people, indeed, I am an evident warner to you:"
  71,3,"that you should worship Allah and be mindful of Him, and obey me."
  71,4,"He will then forgive you<sup>pl</sup> your misdeeds and reprieve you until <small>(you </small><small>fulfill</small><small>)</small> a stated term; indeed, Allah’s term cannot be deferred once it has come, if you only knew.”"
  71,5,"He said, “My Lord, I have called my people night and day,"
  71,6,"but my call has only made them flee the more."
  71,7,"And indeed, every time I called them, that You may forgive them, they put their fingers into their ears and wrapped themselves in their garments and insisted and became extremely arrogant."
  71,8,"Then I called them openly,"
  71,9,"then I spoke to them publicly and I spoke to them privately,"
  71,10,"and I said, ‘Ask your Lord for forgiveness–indeed, He has always been Forgiving."
  71,11,"He will send <small>(rain from)</small> the sky upon you<sup>pl</sup> in showers"
  71,12,"and supply you with wealth and children and allot for you Gardens <small>(of Paradise)</small> and allot for you rivers."
  71,13,"What is the matter with you<sup>pl</sup> that you do not expect <small>(a reward for having)</small> reverence towards Allah"
  71,14,"although He created you in stages?"
  71,15,"Have you<sup>pl</sup> not seen how Allah has created seven heavens in layers?"
  71,16,"And He has made the moon therein a light, and He has made the sun a lamp."
  71,17,"And Allah has germinated you<sup>pl</sup> from the <small>(dust of the)</small> land,"
  71,18,"then He will return you into it and will bring you out again."
  71,19,"And Allah has made the land a spread for you<sup>pl</sup>,"
  71,20,"that you may travel its pathways made broad.’”"
  71,21,"Noah said, “My Lord, indeed, they have disobeyed me and followed one whose wealth and children increased him in nothing but in loss."
  71,22,"And they schemed outrageous schemes,"
  71,23,"saying, ‘Do not abandon your<sup>pl</sup> gods, and do not abandon Wadd, nor Souwa’, nor Yaghooth and Ya'ooq and Nasra<sup foot_note="366411">1</sup> .",footnotes:346874:Names of idols.
  71,24,"And truly, they have misguided many, so do not increase the unjust except in misguidance.”"
  71,25,"For their offenses, they were drowned then hurled into a fire, and they did not find any supporters apart from Allah."
  71,26,"And Noah said, “My Lord, do not leave of the deniers a single dweller in the land."
  71,27,"Indeed, if You leave them, they will misguide your servants and beget none but wicked relentless deniers."
  71,28,"My Lord, forgive me and my parents and anyone who enters my house as a believer, and all the believing men and believing women, and do not increase the unjust except in perdition.”"
  72,1,"1 Say<sup>sg</sup>, “It was revealed to me that a band of unseen beings<sup foot_note="366412">1</sup> listened in and said, ‘Indeed, we have heard a wondrous Recital<sup foot_note="366413">2</sup>",footnotes:346875:The Arabic word used is <i>jinn</i> which are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.|346876:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  72,2,"that guides to prudence, so we have come to believe in it, and we will never associate anyone with our Lord."
  72,3,"And <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="366414">1</sup></span> most high is the Grandeur of our Lord—He never took a female companion nor a child.",footnotes:346877:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn ‘Amer, Abu Ja’far, Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “And indeed…”</span>
  72,4,"And thatc our fool used to speak untruthfully about Allah."
  72,5,"And <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="366415">1</sup></span> we thought that humans and unseen beings would never <span class="h">say<sup foot_note="366416">2</sup></span> a lie about Allah.",footnotes:346878:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn ‘Amer, Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “And indeed…”</span>|346879:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…would never attribute a lie to Allah.”</span>
  72,6,"And thatc certain men among humans used to seek refuge in certain men among the unseen beings, but they only increased them in confusion."
  72,7,"And thatd they thought, as you<sup>pl</sup> thought, that Allah would never resurrect anyone."
  72,8,"And thatd we sought to reach the heaven and found it filled with stern guards and meteors."
  72,9,"And thatd we used to take up positions to listen in, but whoever listens now finds a meteor in wait for him."
  72,10,"And thatd we do not know whether ill has been desired for those on earth, or if their Lord has desired prudence for them."
  72,11,"And thatd some of us are righteous, but some of us are less than that: we have been following divergent roads."
  72,12,"And <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="366417">1</sup></span> we realized that we cannot thwart Allah on earth, nor can we thwart Him by fleeing.",footnotes:346880:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn ‘Amer, Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “And indeed…”</span>
  72,13,"And thata when we heard the guidance we believed in it, for whoever believes in his Lord fears neither loss nor confusion."
  72,14,"And thata among us are Muslims<sup foot_note="366418">1</sup> and among us are those who swerve from justice, so whoever has become Muslim—it is they who have pursued prudence.",footnotes:346881:The Arabic word used is Muslimoun which means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  72,15,"But as for those who swerve from justice—they have become firewood for Hell.’”"
  72,16,"But had they gone straight on the right mode (of life), We would have given them plenty of water to drink,"
  72,17,"so as to test them with it. And whoever disregards the remembrance of his <span class="h">Lord—He<sup foot_note="366419">1</sup></span> will insert him into a mounting punishment.",footnotes:346882:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu ‘Amr, Ibn ‘Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…We will insert him into…”</span>
  72,18,"And (say) that mosques belong to Allah, so do not call upon anyone along with Allah."
  72,19,"And thata when the servant of Allah got up, calling upon Him (in prayers), they almost fell on him in a <span class="h">mass<sup foot_note="366420">1</sup></span>.",footnotes:346883:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hisham in one of his narrations read it as: “…in masses.”</span>
  72,20,"<span class="h">Say<sup foot_note="366421">1</sup></span>, “Indeed, I pray only to my Lord, and I never associate anyone with Him.”",footnotes:346884:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza and Abu Ja’far read it as: “He said…”</span>
  72,21,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Indeed, I possess for you<sup>pl</sup> neither harm nor prudence.”"
  72,22,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “Indeed, no one can protect me from Allah, and I will not find any refuge except with Him."
  72,23,"(I have nothing) except for a proclamation from Allah and His messages, and whoever disobeys Allah and His Messenger—for him is the fire of Hell, abiding therein forever."
  72,24,"Only when they see what they are promised, will they then know who has weaker helpers and is fewer in numbers."
  72,25,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “I do not know whether what you<sup>pl</sup> are promised is near, or whether my Lord will extend it for a period."
  72,26,"The Knower of the hidden realm—so He does not disclose His hidden realm to anyone"
  72,27,"except to a Messenger of His choosing, for He then dispatches guards before him and behind him,"
  72,28,"that He may <span class="h">know<sup foot_note="366422">1</sup></span> that they have compiled and proclaimed the messages of their Lord. But He has encompassed what they have, and has tallied everything by number.”",footnotes:346885:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Roways read it as: “…that it may be known that they have…”</span>
  73,1,"O you enwrapped one,"
  73,2,"stand up<sup foot_note="366423">1</sup> during the night except a little–",footnotes:346886:‘Stand up’ denotes adoration of Allah in night prayers.
  73,3,"for half of it or reduce it a little"
  73,4,"or add to it, and chant the Recital<sup foot_note="366424">1</sup> slowly and distinctly.",footnotes:346887:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  73,5,"Indeed, We are about to cast upon you<sup>sg</sup> a heavy word."
  73,6,"The vigil of the night is indeed more <span class="h">intense<sup foot_note="366425">1</sup></span> and more upright for articulation.",footnotes:346888:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu ‘Amr and Ibn ‘Amer read it as: “…is indeed more suitable and…”</span>
  73,7,"Indeed, in the daytime you<sup>sg</sup> have lengthy work to do."
  73,8,"So remember the Name of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord and devote yourself to Him with <small>(solemn)</small> devotion."
  73,9,"<small>(He is)</small> the <span class="h">Lord<sup foot_note="366426">1</sup></span> of the East and the West; there is no god but He, so take Him as a Trustee.",footnotes:346889:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu ‘Amr, Hafs and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…devotion— <sub><small>9</small></sub>9 the Lord of the East…”</span>
  73,10,"And endure patiently what they say, and withdraw from them politely."
  73,11,"And leave to Me the disbelievers, those of luxury, and give them a brief respite."
  73,12,"Indeed, We have shackles and a purgatory"
  73,13,"and food that chokes and a painful punishment"
  73,14,"on the day when the earth and the mountains tremble and the mountains became<sup foot_note="366427">1</sup> heaps of sand.",footnotes:346890:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  73,15,"Indeed, We have sent to you<sup>pl</sup> a messenger as a witness over you, as We sent to Pharaoh a messenger."
  73,16,"But Pharaoh disobeyed the Messenger, so We seized him with a terrible seizing."
  73,17,"So how, if you<sup>pl</sup> deny, will you guard yourselves from a day which turns children gray-haired?"
  73,18,"The heaven shatters thereby; His promise has always been fulfilled."
  73,19,"Indeed, this is a reminding, so whoever wills, let him take a way to his Lord."
  73,20,"Indeed, your<sup>sg</sup> Lord knows that you stand up nearly two-thirds of the night, and <small>(sometimes you stand up)</small> half of <span class="h">it<sup foot_note="366428">1</sup></span>, and <small>(sometimes you stand up)</small> one-third of it, along with a faction of those with you. And Allah determines the night and the day. He has known that you<sup>pl</sup> will be unable to sustain it, so He has pardoned you. So recite of the Recital<sup foot_note="366429">2</sup> whatever is easy <small>(for you)</small>. He knew that some of you will be ill, and others traveling through the land seeking a share of Allah’s grace, and others combating in the way of Allah, so read of it what is possible for you, and establish the prayer, and bring<sup foot_note="366430">3</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="366431">4</sup>, and lend Allah a good loan. And whatever good you advance for yourselves, you will find it with Allah; it will be better and greater in reward. And seek Allah’s forgiveness; indeed, Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy.",footnotes:346891:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Abu ‘Amr, Ibn ‘Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…nearly two-thirds of the night, and (sometimes nearly) half of it, and (sometimes nearly) one-third of it…”</span>|346892:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.|346893:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|346894:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.
  74,1,"O you shrouded <small>(in your mantle)</small>—"
  74,2,"stand up and warn!"
  74,3,"And your<sup>sg</sup> Lord glorify!"
  74,4,"And your<sup>sg</sup> clothes purify!"
  74,5,"And abominations forsake<sup>sg</sup>!"
  74,6,"And show<sup>sg</sup> no favor, seeking self-gain!"
  74,7,"And to your<sup>sg</sup> Lord endure patiently!"
  74,8,"So when the Trumpet is blown,"
  74,9,"that day will be a difficult day"
  74,10,"for the deniers—not easy."
  74,11,"Leave<sup>sg</sup> to Me the one whom I created alone,"
  74,12,"and to whom I gave vast wealth"
  74,13,"and children by his side,"
  74,14,"and smoothed things for him—"
  74,15,"yet he ardently hopes that I give more!"
  74,16,"But no! He was stubborn towards Our signs<sup foot_note="366432">1</sup>",footnotes:346895:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat </i>(singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah </i>means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote theunit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered asign from God.
  74,17,"I will exhaust him increasingly."
  74,18,"He thought and determined."
  74,19,"May he perish<sup foot_note="366433">1</sup> —how he determined!",footnotes:346896:Literally ‘May he be killed’.
  74,20,"Again: may he perish—how he determined!"
  74,21,"Then he looked,"
  74,22,"then he frowned and scowled,"
  74,23,"then he retreated and acted arrogantly"
  74,24,"and said, “This is nothing but sorcery from the past."
  74,25,"This is nothing but the word of a human being.”"
  74,26,"I will roast him in Saqar<sup foot_note="366434">1</sup> .",footnotes:346897:<i>Saqar</i> is one of the names used for the fire of Hell.
  74,27,"But what can make you<sup>sg</sup> realize what Saqar is?"
  74,28,"It neither leaves nor spares;"
  74,29,"it scorches the flesh;"
  74,30,"over it are nineteen."
  74,31,"And We have not appointed except angels to be wardens of the Fire and have made their number nothing but a means of trial for the deniers—so that those given the Scripture may attain certitude, and those who have attained belief may increase in faith, and those given the Scripture and the believers may not doubt, and so that those in whose hearts is sickness and the deniers may say, “What did Allah desire by this parable?” Thus Allah misguides whomever He wills and guides whomever He wills, and none knows the soldiers of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord except He, and this is nothing but a reminder to human beings."
  74,32,"But no! By the moon."
  74,33,"By the night as it retreated."
  74,34,"By the morning when it lights up—"
  74,35,"indeed, it is one of the greatest things:"
  74,36,"a warning to human beings,"
  74,37,"to whomever of you who wishes to advance or regress."
  74,38,"Every single self is held in pledge for what it has earned,"
  74,39,"except for those on the Right—"
  74,40,"in Gardens <small>(of Paradise)</small>, inquiring"
  74,41,"about the criminals:"
  74,42,"“What drove you into Saqar?”"
  74,43,"They said, “We were not of those who prayed,"
  74,44,"nor did we feed the destitute<sup>sg</sup>,"
  74,45,"and we used to indulge <small>(in falsehood)</small> with those who indulged,"
  74,46,"and we used to deny the Day of Recompense,"
  74,47,"until the certitude <small>(of death)</small> came to us.”"
  74,48,"So in no way can the intercession of intercessors help them."
  74,49,"So why are they disregarding the Reminder,"
  74,50,"as though they were panicked <span class="h">donkeys<sup foot_note="366435">1</sup></span>,",footnotes:346898:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie, Ibn ‘Amer and Abu Ja'far read it as: "as though they were donkeys made to panic,"</span>
  74,51,"having fled from a lion?"
  74,52,"Yet every one of them wants to be given scrolls unrolled."
  74,53,"But no! Rather, they do not fear the Hereafter."
  74,54,"But no! It is a Reminder."
  74,55,"So whoever wills shall remember it."
  74,56,"Yet <span class="h">they<sup foot_note="366436">1</sup></span> will not remember unless Allah wills; He is Worthy of mindfulness and Worthy of <small>(bestowing)</small> forgiveness.",footnotes:346899:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ read it as: “Yet you<sup><small>pl </small></sup>will not remember unless…”</span>
  75,1,"<span class="h">No!<sup foot_note="366437">1</sup></span> I swear by the Day of Resurrection.",footnotes:346900:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Qunbol and Al-Bazzi in his second narration read it as: “Surely, I swear by…”</span>
  75,2,"And, no! I swear by the reproaching <small>(inner)</small> self."
  75,3,"Does man think that We will not reassemble his bones?"
  75,4,"Yes indeed; We are Able to form his very fingertips."
  75,5,"Rather, man wants to commit vice ever onward."
  75,6,"He asks, “When is the Day of Resurrection?”"
  75,7,"So, when the sight is <span class="h">dazzled<sup foot_note="366438">1</sup></span>,",footnotes:346901:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “So, when the sight glows…”</span>
  75,8,"and the moon is eclipsed,"
  75,9,"and the sun and the moon are joined together—"
  75,10,"man says on that day, “Where is the escape?”"
  75,11,"But no! There is no refuge."
  75,12,"To your<sup>sg</sup> Lord on that day everything comes to reside."
  75,13,"Man is informed on that day of whatever he put forth and whatever he left behind."
  75,14,"Rather, man is an eyewitness against himself,"
  75,15,"even as he presents his excuses."
  75,16,"Do not rush your<sup>sg</sup> tongue with it<sup foot_note="366439">1</sup> to hurry on with it.",footnotes:346902:Referring to the Qur’an.
  75,17,"Indeed, upon Us is its collection and its recitation."
  75,18,"So, when We have recited it, follow<sup>sg</sup> its recitation;"
  75,19,"then upon Us is its explanation."
  75,20,"But no! Rather, you<sup>pl</sup> love the fleeting life"
  75,21,"and <span class="h">you<sup foot_note="366440">1</sup></span> leave aside the Hereafter.",footnotes:346903:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu ‘Amr, Ibn ‘Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “But no! Rather, they love the fleeting life <sub><small>21</small></sub>21 and they leave aside the Hereafter.”</span>
  75,22,"Some faces on that day are radiant,"
  75,23,"looking towards their Lord."
  75,24,"And some faces on that day are gloomy,"
  75,25,"expecting that a back-breaking blow will be dealt them."
  75,26,"But no! Rather, when it<sup foot_note="366441">1</sup> has reached the collarbone,",footnotes:346904:Referring to the soul as it leaves the body.
  75,27,"and it is said, “Who is the healer?”"
  75,28,"And one realizes that it is the final departure,"
  75,29,"and leg is entwined with leg<sup foot_note="366442">1</sup> —",footnotes:346905:Referring to the shrouding of the body after death, before burial.
  75,30,"to your<sup>sg</sup> Lord on that day is the driving <small>(of people)</small>."
  75,31,"Then, <small>(as for)</small> one who neither believed nor prayed,"
  75,32,"but disbelieved and turned away,"
  75,33,"then went to his family, strutting—"
  75,34,"<small>(this punishment is)</small> more and more suitable for you<sup>sg</sup>."
  75,35,"Then again, more and more suitable for you."
  75,36,"Does man think that he will be left without purpose?"
  75,37,"Was he not a drop of emitted <span class="h">semen<sup foot_note="366443">1</sup></span>?",footnotes:346906:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs and Ya’qub read it as: “Was he not an emitted drop of semen?”</span>
  75,38,"Then he became a clinging form, which He then created and formed?"
  75,39,"And made of him the two spouses<sup foot_note="366444">1</sup>, the male and the female?",footnotes:346907:The Arabic word <i>zawjayn</i> can also mean ‘two kinds’ or ‘two types’.
  75,40,"Is not that One able to revive the dead?"
  76,1,"Has there come upon man a period of time when he was nothing to be mentioned?"
  76,2,"Indeed, We created man from a mingled sperm drop to try him, and We made him hearing and seeing."
  76,3,"Indeed, We have guided him to the way, be he thankful or a staunch denier."
  76,4,"Indeed, We have prepared for the deniers chains and yokes and a blaze."
  76,5,"Indeed, the virtuous drink from a cup whose mixture is camphor—"
  76,6,"a spring from which Allah's servants drink, making it gush abundantly."
  76,7,"They fulfill <small>(their)</small> vows and fear a day of widespread evil,"
  76,8,"and they feed—for the love of Him—<small>(</small><small>any)</small><small> </small>destitute person and <small>(</small><small>any)</small> orphan and <small>(</small><small>any)</small> captive."
  76,9,"“Indeed, we only feed you<sup>pl</sup> for the sake of Allah; We want from you neither repayment nor thankfulness."
  76,10,"Indeed, we fear from our Lord a frowning, grim day.”"
  76,11,"So Allah shielded them from the ills of that day and made them receive radiance and joy"
  76,12,"and repaid them for their patience with a Garden <small>(in paradise)</small> and silk <small>(garments)</small>;"
  76,13,"reclining therein on couches, they see therein neither <small>(the heat of a)</small> sun nor freezing cold."
  76,14,"And its shades hover over them, and its clusters <small>(of fruit)</small> are brought low within reach."
  76,15,"And passing around them are vessels of silver and cups of crystal—"
  76,16,"crystalline silver cups—that they measured out with perfect measure."
  76,17,"And they are served in it with a cup whose flavor is a mixture of ginger,"
  76,18,"<small>(from)</small> a spring therein named Salsabeel."
  76,19,"And passing among them are immortal youths; when you<sup>sg</sup> see them, you think them sprinkled pearls."
  76,20,"And when you<sup>sg</sup> see, you see there bliss and a vast Dominion."
  76,21,"Upon them are green garments of silk, and <small>(upon them is) <span class="h"></span></small>brocade<sup foot_note="366445">1</sup>, and they have been adorned with bracelets of silver, and their Lord has offered them a pure drink.",footnotes:346908:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn kathir and Shu’ba read it as: “Upon them are garments of green silk, and (upon them is) brocade,”Abu ‘Amr, Ibn ‘Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…green garments of silk and of brocade…”Nafei’ read it as Hafs, while all the rest read it as: “…them are garments of green silk and of brocade...”</span>
  76,22,"“Indeed, this is a repayment for you<sup>pl</sup>, and your efforts have been well thanked.”"
  76,23,"Indeed, We—We alone—have surely bestowed the Recital<sup foot_note="366446">1</sup> upon you<sup>sg</sup> from on high.",footnotes:346909:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  76,24,"So wait patiently for the judgment of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, and do not obey any sinner or any staunch denier among them."
  76,25,"And remember<sup foot_note="366447">1</sup> the Name of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord morning and evening,",footnotes:346910:The Arabic word used also means ‘mention’.
  76,26,"and for part of the night prostrate yourself to Him, and highly exalt Him long into the night."
  76,27,"Indeed, these<sup foot_note="366448">1</sup> love the fleeting life and leave behind them a heavy day.",footnotes:346911:Referring to the disbelievers.
  76,28,"We have created them and have strengthened their frame, and whenever We will, We can replace them entirely with others like them."
  76,29,"Indeed, this is a Reminder. So whoever wills, let him take a way to his Lord."
  76,30,"Yet you<sup>pl</sup> <span class="h">cannot<sup foot_note="366449">1</sup></span> will, unless Allah wills. Indeed, Allah has always been All-Knowing, All- Wise.",footnotes:346912:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu ‘Amr and Ibn ‘Amer read it as: “Yet they cannot will…”</span>
  76,31,"He enters into His mercy whomever He wills, and the unjust— He has prepared for them a painful punishment."
  77,1,"By those unleashed in succession<sup foot_note="366450">1</sup>,",footnotes:346913:According to Al-Qurtubi, exegetes differed about whether this refers to winds or angels.
  77,2,"and by those storming turbulently<sup foot_note="366451">1</sup> .",footnotes:346914:According to Al-Qurtubi, the majority of exegetes mentioned that this refers to the winds.
  77,3,"By those scattering far and wide,"
  77,4,"and by those separating decisively,"
  77,5,"and by those casting a Reminder<sup foot_note="366452">1</sup>,",footnotes:346915:According to Al-Qurtubi, the majority of exegetes mentioned that this refers to the angels.
  77,6,"excusing or warning––"
  77,7,"indeed, what you<sup>pl</sup> are promised is sure to come."
  77,8,"So when the stars are obliterated,"
  77,9,"and when the sky is fractured,"
  77,10,"and when the mountains are blown away,"
  77,11,"and when the messengers are gathered to their appointed time––"
  77,12,"to which day is it deferred?"
  77,13,"To the Day of Decision."
  77,14,"And what can make you<sup>sg</sup> realize what the Day of Decision is?"
  77,15,"Woe on that day to the disbelievers."
  77,16,"Did We not destroy the ancients,"
  77,17,"then follow them up with the later ones?"
  77,18,"This is how We deal with the criminals."
  77,19,"Woe on that day to the disbelievers."
  77,20,"Did We not create you<sup>pl</sup> from a despicable fluid,"
  77,21,"then lodged it in a secure place"
  77,22,"for a known term?"
  77,23,"And We have determined, so what excellent determiners are We!"
  77,24,"Woe on that day to the disbelievers."
  77,25,"Did We not make the earth a homestead"
  77,26,"for the living and the dead,"
  77,27,"and set on it lofty, firm mountains, and gave you pure water to drink?"
  77,28,"Woe on that day to the disbelievers."
  77,29,"“Proceed to what you<sup>pl</sup> used to disbelieve in."
  77,30,"<span class="h">Proceed<sup foot_note="366453">1</sup></span> to a shadow that rises in three different columns,",footnotes:346916:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Roways read it as: “‘Proceed to what you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> used to disbelieve in.’ <sub><small>30</small></sub>30 They proceeded to a shadow that rises in three different columns, <sub><small>31</small></sub>31 offering no shade and unavailing against the flames.”</span>
  77,31,"offering no shade and unavailing against the flames.”"
  77,32,"It shoots sparks like huge buildings,"
  77,33,"as if they are <span class="h">yellow<sup foot_note="366454">1</sup></span> camels.",footnotes:346917:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Hafs, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Khalaf and Roways read as: “…as if they are herds of yellow camels.” Roways read it as: “…as if they are thick yellow ropes.”</span>
  77,34,"Woe on that day to the disbelievers"
  77,35,"This is a day when they do not speak,"
  77,36,"nor are they allowed to apologize."
  77,37,"Woe on that day to the disbelievers."
  77,38,"This is the Day of Decision; We have gathered you<sup>pl</sup>, together with the ancients."
  77,39,"So if you have a plot, then plot against Me."
  77,40,"Woe on that day to the disbelievers."
  77,41,"Indeed, the mindful <small>(of God)</small> are amidst shades and springs"
  77,42,"and fruits as they desire."
  77,43,"“Eat and drink pleasantly on account of what you<sup>pl</sup> used to do.”"
  77,44,"Indeed, this is how We repay those who excel in doing good."
  77,45,"Woe on that day to the disbelievers."
  77,46,"“Eat and enjoy yourselves a little; you<sup>pl</sup> are indeed criminals.”"
  77,47,"Woe on that day to the disbelievers."
  77,48,"And when it is said to them, “Bow down”, they do not bow down."
  77,49,"Woe on that day to the disbelievers."
  77,50,"So in what discourse, beyond this, will they believe?"
  78,1,"What are they asking one another about?"
  78,2,"About the Great Tiding,"
  78,3,"over which they differ."
  78,4,"But no, surely they will find out!"
  78,5,"Once again, no, surely they will find out!"
  78,6,"Did We not make the earth a resting place,"
  78,7,"and the mountains as pegs?"
  78,8,"And created you<sup>pl</sup> in pairs?"
  78,9,"And made your sleep for rest,"
  78,10,"and made the night a garment,"
  78,11,"and made the day for livelihood?"
  78,12,"And built above you seven strong ones,"
  78,13,"and made a glowing lamp?"
  78,14,"And brought down from the clouds pouring water,"
  78,15,"to bring out with it grains and plants"
  78,16,"and luxuriant gardens?"
  78,17,"Indeed, the Day of Decision has been appointed:"
  78,18,"the day when the Trumpet isblown, and you come in crowds,"
  78,19,"19 and the sky was<sup foot_note="366455">1</sup> <span class="h">opened<sup foot_note="366456">2</sup></span> up and became gateways,",footnotes:346918:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense, this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.|346919:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…the sky was opened up wide and…”</span>
  78,20,"20 and the mountains were set in motion and became a mirage."
  78,21,"21 Indeed, Hell has been lying in ambush—"
  78,22,"22 a destination for those who exceed all limits,"
  78,23,"23 where they <span class="h">remain<sup foot_note="366457">1</sup></span> for eons,",footnotes:346920:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza and Rouh read it as: “…they fixedly remain for eons,”</span>
  78,24,"24 tasting therein neither coolness nor drink,"
  78,25,"25 except scalding water and purulence—"
  78,26,"26 a fitting repayment,"
  78,27,"27 for they were not expecting any reckoning,"
  78,28,"28 and they disbelieved Our signs with utter disbelief."
  78,29,"29 But We have enumerated everything in writing."
  78,30,"30 So taste, for We will not increase you<sup>pl</sup> except in punishment!"
  78,31,"31 Indeed, for the mindfulpl (of God) there is triumph:"
  78,32,"32 Gardens (of Paradise) and vineyards;"
  78,33,"33 and high-class spouses, well-matched;"
  78,34,"34 and overflowing cups."
  78,35,"35 They hear therein neither idle talk nor lies—"
  78,36,"36 a repayment from yoursg Lord, a measured gift,"
  78,37,"37 (from) the <span class="h">Lord<sup foot_note="366458">1</sup></span> of the heavens and the earth and everything between them, (from) the All-Merciful. They have no authority from Him to speak",footnotes:346921:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn ‘Amer, Asem and Ya’qub read it as: “a measured gift,<sub> <small>37 </small></sub>37 (from) the Lord of the heavens and the earth and everything between them, (from) the All-Merciful.” Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu ‘Amr and Abu Ja’far read it as: “a measured gift. <sub><small>37 </small></sub>37 (He is) the Lord of the heavens and the earth and everything between them, the All-Merciful.” All others read it as: “a measured gift, <sub><small>37 </small></sub>37 (from) the Lord of the heavens and the earth and everything between them. (He is) the All-Merciful.”</span>
  78,38,"38 on the day when the Spirit and the angels line up in ranks, not speaking—except whomever the All-Merciful has permitted and who has said what is right."
  78,39,"39 That is the True Day. So whoever wills, let him take a route to return to his Lord."
  78,40,"40 Indeed, We have warned you<sup>pl</sup> of a near punishment—the day when a person looks at what his hands have put forth, and the denier says, “If only I were dust!”"
  79,1,"By those who snatch violently<sup foot_note="366459">1</sup> .",footnotes:346922:Al-Alousi and other exegetes mentioned that these are angels snatching the souls of the disbelievers.
  79,2,"By those who remove gently."
  79,3,"By those who glide smoothly,"
  79,4,"and by those who race swiftly,"
  79,5,"and by those who regulate matters—"
  79,6,"on the day when the Quake quakes"
  79,7,"and is followed by the Successor,"
  79,8,"hearts on that day are pounding,"
  79,9,"their sight<small>(s)</small> <small>(subdued)</small> in reverence."
  79,10,"They say, “Can it <span class="h">be<sup foot_note="366460">1</sup></span> that we will really be restored to the original condition?",footnotes:346923:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “‘Will we really be restored to the original condition?’”</span>
  79,11,"Can that <span class="h">be<sup foot_note="366461">1</sup></span> when we have become worn <span class="h">out<sup foot_note="366462">2</sup></span> bones?”",footnotes:346924:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn ‘Amer, Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “‘When we have become…’”</span>|346925:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Shu’ba, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Roways and Khalaf read it as: “…become hollow bones?”</span>
  79,12,"They said<sup foot_note="366463">1</sup>, “This is a losing return.”",footnotes:346926:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense, this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  79,13,"Yet, indeed, it is nothing but a single nudge,"
  79,14,"and they are all awake."
  79,15,"Has the story of Moses reached you<sup>sg</sup>?"
  79,16,"When His Lord called out to him in the sacred valley of Tuwa,"
  79,17,"“Go to Pharaoh—indeed, he has exceeded all limits—"
  79,18,"and say, 'Do you<sup>sg</sup> care to be purified?"
  79,19,"And I will guide you to your Lord, so you will be in awe.'”"
  79,20,"So he showed him the biggest sign,"
  79,21,"but he disbelieved and disobeyed,"
  79,22,"then retreated in haste"
  79,23,"and gathered and proclaimed."
  79,24,"He said, “I am your<sup>pl</sup> Lord, the most high.”"
  79,25,"So Allah seized him with an exemplary punishment, in the Last <small>(life)</small> and in the First."
  79,26,"Indeed, in this is a lesson for whoever fears."
  79,27,"Are you<sup>pl</sup> more difficult to create or the heaven? He constructed it:"
  79,28,"He raised its masses and proportioned it,"
  79,29,"and He dimmed its night and brought out its daylight."
  79,30,"And the earth, after that—He spread it out;"
  79,31,"from it He brought out its water and its pasture,"
  79,32,"and the mountains He anchored—"
  79,33,"a source of enjoyment for you<sup>pl</sup> and for your livestock."
  79,34,"So when the Biggest Catastrophe arrives—"
  79,35,"on the day when man reminds himself of what he has endeavored,"
  79,36,"and purgatory is displayed to whoever sees."
  79,37,"So as for the one who exceeded all"
  79,38,"limits and preferred the Earlier Life,"
  79,39,"then indeed, purgatory is the shelter."
  79,40,"But as for the one who feared standing before his Lord and forbade the self <small>(its)</small> whim,"
  79,41,"then indeed, the Garden <small>(of Paradise) </small>is the shelter."
  79,42,"They ask you<sup>sg</sup> about the Hour: “When will it take place?”"
  79,43,"What have you<sup>sg</sup> to do with mentioning it?"
  79,44,"To your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is its finality."
  79,45,"You are just a forewarner for whoever fears it."
  79,46,"On the day when they witness it, it will be as though they tarried <small>(in the world)</small> but the evening of one day or its morning."
  80,1,"He frowned and turned away"
  80,2,"when the blind man approached him."
  80,3,"But what could make you<sup>sg</sup> realize that perhaps he was seeking to purify himself,"
  80,4,"or to be reminded so <span class="h">that<sup foot_note="366464">1</sup></span> the reminder would benefit him?",footnotes:346927:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem read it as: “…or to be reminded and the reminder would benefit him?”</span>
  80,5,"But as for the one who thought himself self-sufficient,"
  80,6,"you<sup>sg</sup> give him your attention,"
  80,7,"though you are not liable if he never purifies himself."
  80,8,"Yet, as for the one who came to you rushing"
  80,9,"with fear <small>(of Allah)</small>,"
  80,10,"to him you are inattentive."
  80,11,"But no, indeed this is a Reminder."
  80,12,"So whoever wills shall remember it."
  80,13,"<small>(It is) </small>in honorable Scrolls,"
  80,14,"exalted and purified,"
  80,15,"borne by the hands of scribes,"
  80,16,"noble and devoted."
  80,17,"May man perish<sup foot_note="366465">1</sup> ! What a denier he is!",footnotes:346928:Literally ‘May the man be killed!’
  80,18,"From what did He create him?"
  80,19,"From a sperm drop He created him and enabled him,"
  80,20,"then He eased the way for him,"
  80,21,"then He put him to death and buried him,"
  80,22,"then, when He wills, He will resurrect him."
  80,23,"But no, he did not fulfill what He commanded him."
  80,24,"Let man look at his food:"
  80,25,"that <span class="h">We<sup foot_note="366466">1</sup></span> poured down water in abundance,",footnotes:346929:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Khalaf and Roways when he continued recitation without stopping at the end of sign 24 read it as: “…his food: <sub lang="en-US"><small>25 </small></sub>25 that We poured down…” All others including Roways when he stopped at the end of sign 24 read it as: “…his food: <sub><small>25 </small></sub>25 indeed, We poured down…”</span>
  80,26,"then We made the land vigorously rupture"
  80,27,"and germinated therein grains"
  80,28,"and grapes and herbs,"
  80,29,"and olives and dates,"
  80,30,"and luscious orchards,"
  80,31,"and fruit and fodder—"
  80,32,"an enjoyment for you and for your<sup>pl</sup> livestock."
  80,33,"But when the Deafening Noise comes to pass,"
  80,34,"on a day when a person flees from his brother"
  80,35,"and his mother and his father"
  80,36,"and his female companion and his children—"
  80,37,"every one of them on that day has enough to preoccupy him."
  80,38,"Some faces on that day are radiant,"
  80,39,"laughing and glad."
  80,40,"And some faces on that day are covered with dust,"
  80,41,"covered in darkness:"
  80,42,"those are the deniers, the vicious."
  81,1,"When the sun is rolled up,"
  81,2,"and when the stars are dimmed,"
  81,3,"and when the mountains are set in motion,"
  81,4,"and when pregnant camels are abandoned,"
  81,5,"and when the beasts are herded,"
  81,6,"and when the oceans are set aflame,"
  81,7,"and when the souls are paired,"
  81,8,"and when the baby girl that was buried alive is asked"
  81,9,"for what misdeed she was <span class="h">killed<sup foot_note="366467">1</sup></span>,",footnotes:346930:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…for what misdeed she was relentlessly killed,”</span>
  81,10,"and when the scrolls are made <span class="h">public<sup foot_note="366468">1</sup></span>,",footnotes:346931:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn ‘Amer, Asem, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…are made entirely public,”</span>
  81,11,"and when the sky is peeled away,"
  81,12,"and when purgatory is set fully <span class="h">ablaze<sup foot_note="366469">1</sup></span>,",footnotes:346932:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Zekwan, Hafs, Abu Ja’far and Roways read it as: “…is set ablaze,”</span>
  81,13,"and when the Garden <small>(of Paradise)</small> is brought near—"
  81,14,"each soul will know what it has brought forth."
  81,15,"So, no! I swear by those <small>(stars)</small> receding,"
  81,16,"running, sweeping."
  81,17,"By the night as its darkness comes and goes."
  81,18,"By the morn as it breathes—"
  81,19,"indeed, it is the word of a noble messenger<sup foot_note="366470">1</sup>,",footnotes:346933:The noble messenger referred to here is the angel Gabriel (<i>Jibreel</i>).
  81,20,"endowed with power, eminent with the Lord of the Throne,"
  81,21,"obeyed there and trustworthy."
  81,22,"Thus your<sup>pl</sup> fellow is not a madman,"
  81,23,"for he most surely saw him on the evident horizon,"
  81,24,"and he does not stingily <span class="h">withhold<sup foot_note="366471">1</sup></span><small>(knowledge of)</small> the hidden realm,",footnotes:346934:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu ‘Amr, Al-Kesa’i and Roways read it as: “…and he is not accused of withholding (knowledge of ) the hidden realm,”</span>
  81,25,"and it is not the word of an outcast Satan."
  81,26,"So where are you<sup>pl</sup> going?"
  81,27,"It is but a Reminder to <small>(all creatures of)</small> all realms,"
  81,28,"to whomever of you who wills to be upright."
  81,29,"But you<sup>pl</sup> cannot will unless Allah, the Lord of all realms, wills."
  82,1,"When the sky splits apart,"
  82,2,"and when the planets are scattered,"
  82,3,"and when the seas are made to burst,"
  82,4,"and when the tombs are strewn around—"
  82,5,"each self will know what it has put forth and what it has deferred."
  82,6,"O Man, what deceived you concerning your Noble Lord,"
  82,7,"who created you and formed you and <span class="h">proportioned<sup foot_note="366472">1</sup></span> you?",footnotes:346935:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…and perfectly proportioned you?”</span>
  82,8,"In whatever shape He willed, He assembled you."
  82,9,"But no, rather you<sup>pl</sup> <span class="h">disbelieve<sup foot_note="366473">1</sup></span> in the Recompense,",footnotes:346936:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…rather they disbelieve in…”</span>
  82,10,"while indeed, over you are preservers—"
  82,11,"honorable scribes—"
  82,12,"who know whatever you do."
  82,13,"Indeed, the virtuous are in bliss,"
  82,14,"while indeed, the wicked are in purgatory;"
  82,15,"they will roast in it on the Day of Recompense,"
  82,16,"and in no way will they be absent from it."
  82,17,"But what can make you<sup>sg</sup> realize what the Day of Recompense is?"
  82,18,"Again, what can make you<sup>sg</sup> realize what the Day of Recompense is?"
  82,19,"<small>(They will be recompensed on)</small> a <span class="h">day<sup foot_note="366474">1</sup></span> when no self is able to avail another self in anything, and the command on that day belongs to Allah.",footnotes:346937:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu ‘Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “(It is) a day when…”</span>
  83,1,"Woe to the defrauders:"
  83,2,"those who, when they take a measure from people, take in full;"
  83,3,"but when they measure or weigh to others, they give less than they should."
  83,4,"Do those not think that they will be resurrected"
  83,5,"on a great day,"
  83,6,"a day when mankind stands before the Lord of all realms?"
  83,7,"But no, indeed the record<sup foot_note="366475">1</sup> of the wicked is in Sijjeen<sup foot_note="366476">2</sup> .",footnotes:346938:Literally ‘scripture’.|346939:<i>Sijjeen</i> is derived from the word ‘<i>sijn</i>’ which means ‘prison’. Here, Allah is expressing the gravity of the matter and describing it as an eternal prison and a painful torment.
  83,8,"And what can make you<sup>sg</sup> realize what Sijjeen is?"
  83,9,"A written recorda."
  83,10,"Woe on that day to the disbelievers"
  83,11,"who disbelieve in the Day of Recompense,"
  83,12,"for none disbelieves in it except every sinful transgressor"
  83,13,"who, when Our signs<sup foot_note="366477">1</sup> are recited to him, says, “Legends of the ancients.”",footnotes:346940:The Arabic word used is ayat (singular ayah). Ayah means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Quran, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  83,14,"But no, rather, encrusted over their hearts is what they used to earn."
  83,15,"But no, indeed on that day they are sure to be screened off from their Lord."
  83,16,"Then indeed, they are sure to roast in purgatory."
  83,17,"Then it will be said, “This is what you used to disbelieve in.”"
  83,18,"But no, indeed the recorda of the virtuous is in Elliyyeen<sup foot_note="366478">1</sup> .",footnotes:346941:<i>Elliyyeen (Elliyyoon) </i>is derived from the word <i>‘uluw</i> which means highness.
  83,19,"And what can make you<sup>sg</sup> realize what Elliyyoond is?"
  83,20,"A written recorda,"
  83,21,"witnessed by those brought near."
  83,22,"Indeed, the virtuous are amid bliss,"
  83,23,"on couches, looking on."
  83,24,"You<sup>sg</sup> can <span class="h">recognize<sup foot_note="366479">1</sup></span> on their faces the radiance of bliss.",footnotes:346942:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “The radiance of bliss can be recognized on their faces.”</span>
  83,25,"They are given to drink of a sealed nectar,"
  83,26,"whose <span class="h">end<sup foot_note="366480">1</sup></span> is musk—and this is what competitors should compete for.",footnotes:346943:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Kesa’i read it as: “whose seal is musk—and this is…”</span>
  83,27,"And its mixture is of Tasneem,"
  83,28,"a spring from which those brought near drink."
  83,29,"Indeed, those who committed crimes used to laugh at those who had attained faith;"
  83,30,"and when they passed by them, they would wink at one another;"
  83,31,"and when they went back to their families, they would go back jesting;"
  83,32,"and when they saw them, they would say, “These people are most surely misguided.”"
  83,33,"Yet they were not sent as preservers over them."
  83,34,"So today<sup foot_note="366481">1</sup> those who have attained faith are laughing at the deniers,",footnotes:346944:Referring to the Day of Judgment.
  83,35,"on couches, looking on."
  83,36,"Have the deniers been recompensed for what they used to do?"
  84,1,"When the sky is ruptured"
  84,2,"and listens to its Lord as it rightly must,"
  84,3,"and when the earth is leveled out"
  84,4,"and casts out what is in it and becomes empty"
  84,5,"and listens to its Lord as it rightly must—"
  84,6,"O man, you are laboring towards your Lord laboriously, then you are bound to meet Him."
  84,7,"So as for the one who was brought his record<sup foot_note="366482">1</sup> in his right hand,",footnotes:346945:Literally ‘scripture’.
  84,8,"he will have an easy reckoning"
  84,9,"and will return to his family joyful."
  84,10,"But as for the one who was brought his recorda behind his back,"
  84,11,"he will call for demise"
  84,12,"and will <span class="h">roast<sup foot_note="366483">1</sup></span> at the Blaze.",footnotes:346946:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Ibn ‘Amer and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…and will continuously roast at the Blaze.”</span>
  84,13,"Indeed, he used to be joyful among his family;"
  84,14,"indeed, he thought he would never return."
  84,15,"Yes, surely his Lord has always been All-Seeing of him."
  84,16,"So, No! I swear by the twilight."
  84,17,"By the night and what it covers."
  84,18,"By the moon as it grows full—"
  84,19,"you<sup>pl</sup> <span class="h">will<sup foot_note="366484">1</sup></span> surely mount stage by stage.",footnotes:346947:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…you<sup lang="en-US"><small>sg</small></sup> will surely mount…”</span>
  84,20,"So what is the matter with them that they do not believe?"
  84,21,"And when the Recital<sup foot_note="366485">1</sup> is recited to them, they do not prostrate themselves?",footnotes:346948:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  84,22,"Rather, the deniers disbelieve,"
  84,23,"but Allah knows better what they hide inside."
  84,24,"So give them glad tidings<sup foot_note="366486">1</sup> of a painful punishment—",footnotes:346949:This is said in sarcasm.
  84,25,"except for those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds; for them is an unfailing reward."
  85,1,"By the sky full of constellations."
  85,2,"By the Promised Day."
  85,3,"By the witness and the witnessed—"
  85,4,"may they perish: the fellows of the Trench<sup foot_note="366487">1</sup>",footnotes:346950:Literally ‘The fellows of the Trench were killed’, which may either refer to what happened to the victims who were killed in the trench or be meant as a curse against their killers.
  85,5,"<small> (of) </small>the fire fed with fuel!"
  85,6,"Recall when they sat around it,"
  85,7,"witnessing what they were doing to the believers."
  85,8,"And they resented them only for believing in Allah the Almighty, the Praiseworthy,"
  85,9,"to Whom belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth. Yet Allah is Witness over everything."
  85,10,"Indeed, those who have persecuted the believing men and the believing women, then have not repented—for them is the punishment of Hell, and for them is the punishment of burning."
  85,11,"Indeed, those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—for them are Gardens beneath which rivers flow; that is the supreme triumph."
  85,12,"Indeed, the onslaught of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is surely severe."
  85,13,"Indeed, it is He who originates and reproduces,"
  85,14,"and He is the Oft-Forgiving, the Most Loving,"
  85,15,"Possessor of the Throne, the <span class="h">Glorious<sup foot_note="366488">1</sup></span>,",footnotes:346951:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…Possessor of the glorious Throne,”</span>
  85,16,"Doer of whatever He wants."
  85,17,"Has there come to you<sup>sg</sup> the story of the troops—"
  85,18,"<small>(that of)</small> Pharaoh and Thamûd<sup foot_note="366489">1</sup> ?",footnotes:346952:The pagan tribe of Prophet <i>Salih</i>.
  85,19,"Rather, the deniers are in <small>(a state of)</small> disbelief,"
  85,20,"while beyond them Allah is All-Encompassing."
  85,21,"Rather, it is a Glorious Recital<sup foot_note="366490">1</sup>,",footnotes:346953:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an </i>which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  85,22,"in a <span class="h">preserved<sup foot_note="366491">1</sup></span> Tablet.",footnotes:346954:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie read it as: “…preserved in a tablet.”</span>
  86,1,"By the sky and the pulsar."
  86,2,"But what can make you<sup>sg</sup> realize what the pulsar is?"
  86,3,"The Drilling Star."
  86,4,"There is no self but <span class="h">has<sup foot_note="366492">1</sup></span> a preserver over it.",footnotes:346955:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Ibn ‘Amer, Asem, Hamza and Abu Ja’far read it as: “Every self has a preserver over it.”</span>
  86,5,"Let man look at what he was created from."
  86,6,"He was created from an ejected fluid,"
  86,7,"coming out from between the backbone and the breastbones."
  86,8,"He is certainly able to return him"
  86,9,"on the day when the secrets are put on trial,"
  86,10,"then he will have neither strength nor helper."
  86,11,"By the sky that returns<sup foot_note="366493">1</sup> .",footnotes:346956:According to Al-Qurtubi, the majority of exegetes mentioned that it is the rain which returns the water in the form of recurring rain.
  86,12,"By the earth that cracks open—"
  86,13,"it is most surely a decisive word<sup foot_note="366494">1</sup>,",footnotes:346957:The Qur’an.
  86,14,"and it is no joke."
  86,15,"Indeed, they are plotting plots,"
  86,16,"but I plot plots <small>(as well)</small>."
  86,17,"So give<sup>sg</sup> the deniers respite; respite them briefly."
  87,1,"Highly exalt the Name of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord, the Most High,"
  87,2,"Who created and proportioned;"
  87,3,"and Who determined and guided;"
  87,4,"and Who brought out the pasture,"
  87,5,"then turned it into dark debris."
  87,6,"We shall make you<sup>sg</sup> recite such that you shall not forget—"
  87,7,"except what Allah wills; indeed, He knows whatever is said aloud and whatever is hidden."
  87,8,"And We shall ease you<sup>sg</sup> towards ease."
  87,9,"So remind<sup>sg</sup>, if reminding can be of benefit."
  87,10,"The God-fearing will constantly remember,"
  87,11,"but the wretched will avoid it—"
  87,12,"he who will roast in the Gigantic Fire,"
  87,13,"then he neither dies nor lives."
  87,14,"Surely, successful is the one who has purified himself"
  87,15,"and remembered the name of his Lord and prayed."
  87,16,"Rather, you<sup>pl</sup> <span class="h">prefer<sup foot_note="366495">1</sup></span> the Earlier Life,",footnotes:346958:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu ‘Amr read it as: “Rather, they prefer the Earlier Life,”</span>
  87,17,"though the Hereafter is better and more lasting."
  87,18,"Most surely, this is in the former scrolls—"
  87,19,"the Scrolls of Abraham and Moses."
  88,1,"Has there come to you<sup>sg</sup> the news of the Overwhelming <small>(event)</small><sup foot_note="366496">1</sup> ?",footnotes:346959:The Day of Judgment.
  88,2,"Some faces on that day are <small>(subdued)</small> in reverence,"
  88,3,"toiling, exhausted,"
  88,4,"<span class="h">roasting<sup foot_note="366497">1</sup></span> in a hot fire,",footnotes:346960:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu ‘Amr, Shu’ba and Ya’qub read it as: “…made to roast in a hot fire,”</span>
  88,5,"given to drink from a boiling spring."
  88,6,"They have no food except of a thorny bush"
  88,7,"which neither nourishes nor satisfies hunger."
  88,8,"Some faces on that day are blissful,"
  88,9,"well pleased with their endeavor,"
  88,10,"in a lofty Garden:"
  88,11,"in it you <span class="h">hear<sup foot_note="366498">1</sup></span> no nonsense;",footnotes:346961:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu ‘Amr and Roways read it as: “…no nonsense is heard in it;”</span>
  88,12,"in it is a flowing spring;"
  88,13,"in it are raised couches,"
  88,14,"and cups set in place,"
  88,15,"and cushions set in rows,"
  88,16,"and carpets spread around."
  88,17,"Do they not look at the camels—how they were created?"
  88,18,"And at the sky—how it was raised?"
  88,19,"And at the mountains—how they were firmly fixed?"
  88,20,"And at the earth—how it was spread out?"
  88,21,"So remind; you<sup>sg</sup> are only a reminder;"
  88,22,"you have no control over them."
  88,23,"But whoever turns away and denies,"
  88,24,"then Allah punishes him with the greatest punishment."
  88,25,"Indeed, to Us is their<sup foot_note="366499">1</sup> return,",footnotes:346962:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  88,26,"then upon Us is their reckoning."
  89,1,"By the dawn."
  89,2,"By the ten nights."
  89,3,"By the even and the odd."
  89,4,"By the night as it passes—"
  89,5,"is there in that a sworn oath for whoever has a mind<sup foot_note="366500">1</sup> ?",footnotes:346963:A rational person.
  89,6,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen what your Lord did to Ād<sup foot_note="366501">1</sup> —",footnotes:346964:The pagan tribe of Prophet Hûd.
  89,7,"Iram, <small>(the city)</small> of the pillars"
  89,8,"whose like has never been created in the lands;"
  89,9,"and Thamûd<sup foot_note="366502">1</sup>, who carved the rocks in the valley;",footnotes:346965:The pagan tribe of Prophet Salih.
  89,10,"and Pharaoh of the stakes?"
  89,11,"They <small>(all)</small> exceeded all limits in the lands"
  89,12,"and spread much corruption therein,"
  89,13,"so your<sup>sg</sup> Lord poured down upon them a scourge of punishment;"
  89,14,"indeed, your Lord is certainly ever-watchful."
  89,15,"So, as for man, whenever his Lord tries him through honoring and blessing him, he says, “My Lord has honored me.”"
  89,16,"But whenever He tries him through <span class="h">restricting<sup foot_note="366503">1</sup></span> his provision, he says, “My Lord has insulted me.”",footnotes:346966:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn ‘Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…through utterly restricting his provision,”</span>
  89,17,"But no! Rather, you<sup>pl</sup> do not <span class="h">honor<sup foot_note="366504">1</sup></span> the orphan,",footnotes:346967:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu ‘Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “Rather, they do not honor the orphan, <sub><small>18 </small></sub>18 and they do not urge (others) to (serve) food to the destitute<sup><small>sg</small></sup>, <sub><small>19</small></sub>19 and they devour inheritance (of the vulnerable) greedily, <sub><small>20</small></sub>20 and they love wealth immensely.”</span>
  89,18,"and you do not urge one <span class="h">another<sup foot_note="366505">1</sup></span> to <small>(serve)</small> food to the destitute<sup>sg</sup>,",footnotes:346968:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn Kathir and Ibn ‘Amer read it as: “…and you do not urge (others) to (serve) food…”</span>
  89,19,"and you devour inheritance <small>(of the vulnerable)</small> greedily,"
  89,20,"and you love wealth immensely."
  89,21,"But no! When the earth is pounded to dust, pounding after pounding;"
  89,22,"and your<sup>sg</sup> Lord comes with the angels, rank after rank;"
  89,23,"and on that day, Hell is made to come forward—on that day man reminds himself, but how will reminding avail him?"
  89,24,"He says, “If only I had put forth something <small>(good)</small> for my life.”"
  89,25,"On that day, none can punish as He <span class="h">punishes<sup foot_note="366506">1</sup></span>,",footnotes:346969:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Kesa’i and Ya’qub read it as: “On that day, none is punished as he is punished, <sub><small>26 </small></sub>26 and none is shackled as he is shackled.”</span>
  89,26,"and none can shackle as He shackles."
  89,27,"O you tranquil self,"
  89,28,"return to your Lord, well pleased and well pleasing;"
  89,29,"so enter among My servants,"
  89,30,"and enter My Garden."
  90,1,"No! I swear by this city,"
  90,2,"and you<sup>sg</sup> are free of restriction this city."
  90,3,"By the begetter and what he has begotten—"
  90,4,"We have certainly created man in distress."
  90,5,"Does he think that no one will be able to restrain him?"
  90,6,"He says, “I have consumed stacks <span class="h">of<sup foot_note="366507">1</sup></span> wealth.”",footnotes:346970:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “I have consumed piles of wealth.”</span>
  90,7,"Does he think that no one has seen him?"
  90,8,"Have We not made for him two eyes"
  90,9,"and a tongue and two lips,"
  90,10,"and showed him the two courses<sup foot_note="366508">1</sup> ?",footnotes:346971:Of good and evil.
  90,11,"But he did not brave the difficult route."
  90,12,"And what can make you realize what the difficult route is?"
  90,13,"<small>(It is)</small> the <span class="h">freeing<sup foot_note="366509">1</sup></span> of a neck <small>(from the yokes of slavery)</small>,",footnotes:346972:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu ‘Amr and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “(Nor) did he free a neck (from the yokes of slavery), <sub><small>14</small></sub>14 (nor) did he feed—on a day of starvation— <sub><small>15</small></sub>15 an orphaned relative …”</span>
  90,14,"14 or the feeding—on a day of starvation—of"
  90,15,"15 an orphaned relative"
  90,16,"or a destitute person in the dust<sup foot_note="366510">1</sup>,",footnotes:346973:A homeless person.
  90,17,"then becoming of those who attained faith and enjoined upon one another patience and enjoined upon one another compassion—"
  90,18,"those are the fellows of the rightness."
  90,19,"But those who denied Our revelations—those are the fellows of the ill-omened;"
  90,20,"over them is a fire with no exit."
  91,1,"By the sun and its morning shine,"
  91,2,"and the moon as it follows her,"
  91,3,"and the daytime as it reveals her,"
  91,4,"and the night as it conceals her."
  91,5,"By the sky and He Who built it."
  91,6,"By the land and He Who spread it."
  91,7,"By the <small>(inner)</small> self and He Who formed it"
  91,8,"then inspired it its own wickedness and its own mindfulness <small>(of God)</small>—"
  91,9,"surely, successful is the one who has purified it,"
  91,10,"and surely, failing is the one who has stunted it."
  91,11,"Exceeding all limits caused Thamûd<sup foot_note="366511">1</sup> to disbelieve,",footnotes:346974:The pagan tribe of Prophet Salih.
  91,12,"when the most wicked man among them was delegated."
  91,13,"Then the messenger of Allah<sup foot_note="366512">1</sup> said to them, “This is the she-camel of Allah, so let her drink.”",footnotes:346975:Prophet Salih.
  91,14,"So they disbelieved him and hamstrung her, so their Lord crushed them for their misdeed and leveled it<sup foot_note="366513">1</sup>,",footnotes:346976:Their dwelling.
  91,15,"<span class="h">and<sup foot_note="366514">1</sup></span> He does<sup foot_note="366515">2</sup> not fear its ultimate outcome.",footnotes:346977:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’, Ibn ‘Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…so He does not…”</span>|346978:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense.
  92,1,"By the night as it covers."
  92,2,"By the day as it reveals."
  92,3,"By the creation of the male and the female—"
  92,4,"indeed, your<sup>pl</sup> pursuits are diverse."
  92,5,"So as for the one who has given and has been mindful <small>(of God)</small>"
  92,6,"and has believed in ultimate goodness—"
  92,7,"We will ease his way towards ease."
  92,8,"But as for the one who has been stingy and complacent"
  92,9,"and has disbelieved in ultimate goodness—"
  92,10,"We will ease his way towards difficulty,"
  92,11,"and his money will not avail him when he plummets."
  92,12,"Indeed, guidance is upon Us,"
  92,13,"and indeed, unto Us belong the Last and the First <small>(life)</small>."
  92,14,"So I have warned you<sup>pl</sup> of a fierce fire,"
  92,15,"in which none roasts except the most wicked—"
  92,16,"the one who disbelieved and turned away."
  92,17,"But the most mindful<sup>sg</sup> <small>(of God)</small> will be kept away from it—"
  92,18,"the one who brings<sup foot_note="366516">1</sup> his wealth to purify himself,",footnotes:346979:The Quran always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.
  92,19,"and not in return for any favor to anyone,"
  92,20,"except for seeking the countenance of his Lord, the Most High."
  92,21,"And he will certainly be well pleased."
  93,1,"By the morning shine."
  93,2,"By the night as it settles—"
  93,3,"your Lord has not abandoned you<sup>sg</sup>, nor has He despised <small>(you)</small>."
  93,4,"And indeed the Last is better for you<sup>sg</sup> than the First,"
  93,5,"and your Lord will certainly give you so that you will be well pleased."
  93,6,"Did He not find you<sup>sg</sup> an orphan, so He sheltered <small>(you)</small>;"
  93,7,"and found you wandering, so He guided <small>(you)</small>;"
  93,8,"and found you in need, so He enriched <small>(you)</small>?"
  93,9,"So as for the orphan, do<sup>sg</sup> not subdue;"
  93,10,"and as for the asker, do not rebuke;"
  93,11,"and as for the blessing of your Lord, do talk about it."
  94,1,"Did We not expand your<sup>sg</sup> chest,"
  94,2,"and lift from you your burden"
  94,3,"which weighed down your back,"
  94,4,"and raised for you your remembrance<sup foot_note="366517">1</sup> ?",footnotes:346980:The Arabic word <i>zhikr</i> can be translated as ‘remembrance’, ‘mention’ or ‘reminder’.
  94,5,"So indeed, with hardship comes ease;"
  94,6,"indeed, with hardship comes ease."
  94,7,"So whenever you<sup>sg</sup> are done <small>(from work)</small>, stand up<sup foot_note="366518">1</sup>,",footnotes:346981:In adoration.
  94,8,"and to your Lord turn wishfully."
  95,1,"By the fig and the olive."
  95,2,"By Mount Tûr of Sinai."
  95,3,"By this safe city<sup foot_note="366519">1</sup> —",footnotes:346982:Makkah.
  95,4,"surely, We created man in the best state,"
  95,5,"then We returned him to the lowest of the low,"
  95,6,"except those who attained faith and did righteous deeds, for for them is an unfailing reward."
  95,7,"So what makes you<sup>sg</sup> still deny the recompense?"
  95,8,"Is Allah not the Wisest of judges?"
  96,1,"Recite: In the name of your<sup>sg</sup> Lord Who created—"
  96,2,"created man from a clinging form."
  96,3,"Recite: And your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is the Most Noble,"
  96,4,"the One Who taught by the pen—"
  96,5,"taught man what he never knew."
  96,6,"But no! Indeed, man surely exceeds all limits,"
  96,7,"for he sees himself self-sufficient."
  96,8,"Indeed, to your<sup>sg</sup> Lord is the ultimate return."
  96,9,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> seen the one who forbids"
  96,10,"a servant when he prays?"
  96,11,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> seen whether he was rightly guided"
  96,12,"or commanded to mindfulness <small>(of God)</small>?"
  96,13,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> seen whether he disbelieved and turned away?"
  96,14,"Has he not realized that Allah sees?"
  96,15,"But no! Surely, if he does not desist, We will drag <small>(him)</small> by the forelock—"
  96,16,"a lying, wrongful forelock."
  96,17,"Let him call on his gang;"
  96,18,"We will call the guards of Hell."
  96,19,"But no! Do not obey him, but prostrate yourself and draw near."
  97,1,"We sent it<sup foot_note="366520">1</sup> down on the Night of Determination.",footnotes:346983:The Qur’an.
  97,2,"But what can make you<sup>sg</sup> realize what the Night of Determination is?"
  97,3,"The Night of Determination is better than a thousand months—"
  97,4,"in it descend the angels, with the Spirit<sup foot_note="366521">1</sup> among them, by the leave of their Lord with every command.",footnotes:346984:Angel Gabriel (<i>Jibreel</i>).
  97,5,"Peace! It is until the <span class="h">rise<sup foot_note="366522">1</sup></span> of dawn.",footnotes:346985:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…until the point of the rise of dawn.”</span>
  98,1,"Those who have denied from among the People of the Scripture and the polytheists were not to be parted <small>(from disbelief)</small> until the evident proof came to them—"
  98,2,"a messenger from Allah reading purified Scrolls;"
  98,3,"in them are valuable scriptures."
  98,4,"Nor did those who were given the Scripture become divided except after the evident proof came to them."
  98,5,"And they were only commanded to worship Allah—devoting religion to Him, turning away from all that is false—and to establish the prayer and to bring<sup foot_note="366523">1</sup> the purifying charity<sup foot_note="366524">2</sup>, and that is the religion<sup foot_note="366525">3</sup> most upright.",footnotes:346986:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.|346987:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.|346988:The Arabic word used is deen which means ‘a way of life’, ‘religion’ or ‘recompense’.
  98,6,"Indeed, those who have denied among the People of the Scripture and the polytheists are in the fire of Hell, abiding therein; those are the worst of all beings."
  98,7,"Indeed, those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—those are the best of all beings."
  98,8,"Their repayment with their Lord: Gardens of Eternity beneath which rivers flow, abiding therein forever. Allah became well pleased with them and they became well pleased with Him. That is for whoever was in awe of his Lord."
  99,1,"When the earth is made to quake with its earthquake,"
  99,2,"and the earth brings out its heavy burdens,"
  99,3,"and man says, “What is the matter with it?”—"
  99,4,"On that day, it tells its tales,"
  99,5,"because your<sup>sg</sup> Lord has revealed to it."
  99,6,"On that day, mankind emerge in droves to be shown their deeds."
  99,7,"So whoever does an atom's weight of good sees it,"
  99,8,"and whoever does an atom's weight of evil sees it."
  100,1,"By those<sup foot_note="366526">1</sup> that run panting,",footnotes:346989:Horses.
  100,2,"then by those igniting sparks,"
  100,3,"then by those raiding at dawn,"
  100,4,"raising clouds of dust"
  100,5,"and storming into the midst of the crowd—"
  100,6,"indeed, man is certainly ungrateful to his Lord;"
  100,7,"and indeed, he certainly bears witness to that;"
  100,8,"and indeed, in his love for wealth he is certainly fierce."
  100,9,"Does he not know that when whatever lies within the graves is scattered around,"
  100,10,"and when whatever lies within the hearts is obtained—"
  100,11,"indeed, on that day, their Lord is most surely aware of them."
  101,1,"The Shocking Event!"
  101,2,"What is the Shocking Event?"
  101,3,"And what can make you<sup>sg</sup> realize what the Shocking Event is?"
  101,4,"A day when mankind become like scattered moths,"
  101,5,"and the mountains become like tufted wool."
  101,6,"So, as for the one whose scales were heavy<sup foot_note="366527">1</sup> —",footnotes:346990:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  101,7,"he is in a pleasant life."
  101,8,"But as for the one whose scales were lighta—"
  101,9,"his home<sup foot_note="366528">1</sup> is an Abyss.",footnotes:346991:The Arabic word used is <i>ummuhu</i> which literally means ‘his mother’. According to Al-Qurtubi, Hell was described as a mother because the disbeliever heads towards it like a baby heads towards its mother.
  101,10,"And what can make you<sup>sg</sup> realize what it is?"
  101,11,"A raging fire."
  102,1,"Vying for more distracted you<sup>pl</sup>"
  102,2,"until you visited the graves."
  102,3,"But no! You<sup>pl</sup> will come to know."
  102,4,"Once again: But no! You<sup>pl</sup> will come to know."
  102,5,"But no! If only you<sup>pl</sup> knew with the knowledge of certitude:"
  102,6,"you will certainly <span class="h">see<sup foot_note="366529">1</sup></span> purgatory.",footnotes:346992:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn ‘Amer and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “…you will certainly be shown purgatory.”</span>
  102,7,"Then you<sup>pl</sup> will certainly see it with the eye of certitude."
  102,8,"Then, on that day, you<sup>pl</sup> will certainly be asked about <small>(worldly)</small> bliss."
  103,1,"By Time—"
  103,2,"man is most surely in a continuous state of loss,"
  103,3,"except those who attained faith and did righteous deeds, and enjoined upon one another keeping to the truth, and enjoined upon one another patience."
  104,1,"Woe to every slandering backbiter,"
  104,2,"who <span class="h">hoarded<sup foot_note="366530">1</sup></span> wealth and counted it over,",footnotes:346993:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn ‘Amer, Hamza, Al-Kesa’i, Abu Ja’far, Rouh and Khalaf read it as: “…who kept hoarding wealth…”</span>
  104,3,"thinking that his wealth has made him immortal."
  104,4,"But no! He will surely be thrown into the Crusher."
  104,5,"And what can make you realize what the Crusher is?"
  104,6,"Allah's kindled Fire"
  104,7,"that mounts over burning hearts."
  104,8,"Indeed, it is over them with no exit,"
  104,9,"in extended columns."
  105,1,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> not seen how your Lord dealt with the fellows of the Elephant?"
  105,2,"Did He not make their plot go into great error?"
  105,3,"And He sent against them swarms of birds,"
  105,4,"throwing at them rocks of baked clay—"
  105,5,"thus He made them like eaten leaves"
  106,1,"for the lasting security of Quraysh<sup foot_note="366531">1</sup> —",footnotes:346994:The tribe of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him).
  106,2,"their lasting security during winter and summer journeys—"
  106,3,"so let them worship the Lord of this House,"
  106,4,"who has fed them to ward off hunger and has secured them to ward off fear."
  107,1,"Have you<sup>sg</sup> seen the one who denies the Recompense<sup foot_note="366532">1</sup> ?",footnotes:346995:The Arabic word used is deen which means ‘a way of life’, ‘religion’ or ‘recompense’.
  107,2,"It is the one who mistreats the orphan"
  107,3,"and does not urge <small>(others to serve)</small> food to the destitute<sup>sg</sup>."
  107,4,"So woe to the ones who pray—"
  107,5,"those who are heedless of their prayers,"
  107,6,"those who make show <small>(of their deeds)</small>"
  107,7,"yet withhold (little) kindnesses<small>(little)</small> kindnesses<sup foot_note="366533">1</sup> .",footnotes:346996:The Arabic word used is ; it denotes <i>ma’oun</i>small acts of help like lending house utensils, the withholding of which is a sign of stinginess.
  108,1,"Indeed, We have given you<sup>sg</sup> plenty<sup foot_note="366534">1</sup> .",footnotes:346997:The Arabic word used is <i>Al</i> <i>Kawthar</i>, which is also the name of a river in Paradise.
  108,2,"So pray to your<sup>sg</sup> Lord and sacrifice."
  108,3,"Indeed, it is the one who hates you<sup>sg</sup> who has been cut off."
  109,1,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “O deniers,"
  109,2,"I do not worship what you<sup>pl</sup> worship,"
  109,3,"nor do you worship what I worship,"
  109,4,"nor shall I ever worship what you worship,"
  109,5,"nor shall you ever worship what I worship—"
  109,6,"you have your religion, and I have my religion<sup foot_note="366535">1</sup> .”",footnotes:346998:The Arabic word used is <i>deen </i>which means ‘a way of life’, ‘religion’ or ‘recompense’.
  110,1,"When there comes Allah’s support and the conquest,"
  110,2,"and you<sup>sg</sup> see mankind entering Allah’s religion in crowds,"
  110,3,"then highly exalt your Lord with praise and seek His forgiveness; indeed, He has always been Granting and Accepting of repentance."
  111,1,"May the hands of Abi Lahab<sup foot_note="366536">1</sup> be ruined, and may he be ruined!",footnotes:346999:The uncle of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), and one of his fiercest enemies.
  111,2,"His wealth did<sup foot_note="366537">1</sup> not avail him, nor did what he earned.",footnotes:347000:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  111,3,"He will roast in a flaming fire,"
  111,4,"while his wife<sup foot_note="366538">1</sup>, that firewood <span class="h">carrier<sup foot_note="366539">2</sup></span>—",footnotes:347001:Abu Lahab’s wife who used to throw thorns in the way of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him).|347002:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Asem read it as: “…while his wife, the firewood carrier— <sub><small>5 </small></sub>5 around…”</span>
  111,5,"around her neck is a rope of palm fiber."
  112,1,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “He is Allah, the Uniquely One."
  112,2,"Allah, the Indivisible."
  112,3,"He begot no one nor was He begotten,"
  112,4,"and never has there been to Him anyone equivalent.”"
  113,1,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “I seek refuge with the Lord of daybreak"
  113,2,"from the evil of whatever He created,"
  113,3,"and from the evil of a dusky night when it darkens,"
  113,4,"and from the evil of sorceresses who blow upon knots,"
  113,5,"and from the evil of an envier when he envies.”"
  114,1,"Say<sup>sg</sup>, “I seek refuge with the Lord of mankind,"
  114,2,"the King of mankind,"
  114,3,"the God of mankind,"
  114,4,"from the evil of the sneaky whisperer"
  114,5,"who whispers into the chests of mankind—"
  114,6,"<small>(from the whisperers) </small>among the race of unseen beings<sup foot_note="366540">1</sup> and mankind.”",footnotes:347003:The Arabic word used is jinnah which is the race of unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.